const QUESTIONS = [{"id": "IP-001", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "An MRI system utilizes three distinct magnetic fields during image acquisition. Which of the following correctly identifies all three?", "options": ["Static field, gradient field, and shim field", "Static field, radiofrequency field, and shim field", "Static field, radiofrequency field, and gradient field", "Radiofrequency field, gradient field, and shim field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI systems employ three electromagnetic fields: the static (B0) field from the main magnet for proton alignment, the radiofrequency (B1) field for proton excitation, and gradient fields for spatial encoding. Shim coils correct B0 inhomogeneities but are not classified as a separate field type in the standard MRI framework.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 311"}, {"id": "IP-002", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which component of the MRI system is responsible for generating the B0 (static) magnetic field?", "options": ["Main magnet", "Radiofrequency transmitter", "Gradient coil assembly", "Shim coil system"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The main magnet—whether permanent, resistive, or superconducting—generates the static B0 field that aligns hydrogen proton spins. The RF transmitter produces B1, and gradient coils create temporary spatial field variations for encoding.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-003", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.d", "stem": "The B1 magnetic field, used to excite hydrogen protons into a higher energy state, is generated by the:", "options": ["Main magnet assembly", "Radiofrequency system", "Gradient coil assembly", "Shim coil system"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The B1 field is a secondary oscillating magnetic field produced by the RF system at the Larmor frequency to tip hydrogen protons out of equilibrium. The main magnet produces B0, and gradient coils produce spatially varying fields for localization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-004", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following is true regarding magnet types used in clinical MRI?", "options": ["Only superconducting magnets are currently used in clinical imaging", "Resistive magnets generate fields using permanent magnetic materials", "Permanent magnets require cryogenic cooling to maintain field strength", "Permanent, resistive, and superconducting designs have all been used in clinical MRI"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All three magnet types have seen clinical use, though superconducting designs dominate modern practice due to superior field strength and temporal stability. Resistive magnets use electromagnets (not permanent materials), and permanent magnets require no cryogenic cooling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315-318"}, {"id": "IP-005", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which MRI system component is responsible for aligning hydrogen proton spins along a single axis?", "options": ["Main magnet", "Radiofrequency system", "Gradient coil system", "Analog-to-digital converter"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The main magnet produces the strong static B0 field that causes hydrogen proton spins to preferentially align parallel or antiparallel to the field, creating net magnetization. The RF system excites protons, and gradient coils provide spatial encoding—neither causes alignment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-006", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.d", "stem": "Excitation of hydrogen protons from their equilibrium state is accomplished by the:", "options": ["Static magnetic field", "Radiofrequency system", "Gradient coil system", "Shim coil system"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The RF system transmits energy at the Larmor frequency to move hydrogen protons from equilibrium to a higher energy state. The static field maintains alignment and gradients provide spatial localization—neither can cause resonant excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-007", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Spatial encoding of the MR signal for image reconstruction is primarily performed by the:", "options": ["Main magnet", "Radiofrequency system", "Gradient system", "Shim coils"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The gradient system creates controlled, linear variations in the magnetic field along three orthogonal axes, enabling spatial encoding via slice selection, phase encoding, and frequency encoding. The main magnet and RF system cannot provide spatial localization by themselves.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128-129"}, {"id": "IP-008", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which cryogen is used in modern superconducting MRI systems to maintain the magnet coils at superconducting temperature?", "options": ["Liquid helium", "Liquid hydrogen", "Liquid nitrogen", "Liquid oxygen"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Liquid helium (boiling point ~4.2 K) cools superconducting coils to near absolute zero, where electrical resistance drops to zero and persistent current flows indefinitely. Liquid nitrogen (77 K) was historically used as an outer thermal shield but cannot achieve the temperatures required for superconductivity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-009", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In contemporary MRI systems that use a single cryogen to cool the superconducting coils, which substance is used?", "options": ["Nitrogen", "Hydrogen", "Helium", "Argon"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Modern superconducting MRI systems use sealed helium-only cooling systems to maintain superconducting temperatures. Earlier designs used both liquid nitrogen and liquid helium, but contemporary systems have eliminated the nitrogen stage through improved thermal insulation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-010", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "According to Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction, moving a conductor through a magnetic field generates:", "options": ["A static magnetic charge", "An electrical voltage", "A rotational torque", "Nuclear resonance"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Faraday's law states that a changing magnetic flux through a conductor induces an electromotive force (voltage). This principle underlies MR signal detection: precessing transverse magnetization induces a voltage in the receiver coil. A static charge or torque is not produced by electromagnetic induction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-011", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which equation represents Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction?", "options": ["ω₀ = γ × B₀", "SAR (W/kg)", "ΔB/ΔT = ΔV", "ppm = (Δf / f₀) × 10⁶"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction relates a changing magnetic field to the voltage it induces (change in B / change in T = change in V). The Larmor equation relates precessional frequency to field strength, and ppm describes chemical shift—neither represents induction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-012", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "According to Faraday's law, the magnitude of the voltage induced in a conductor moving through a magnetic field is directly proportional to the:", "options": ["Length of the conductor", "Strength of the magnetic field", "Electrical resistance of the conductor", "Duration of the field exposure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Per Faraday's law, the induced voltage is proportional to the rate of change of magnetic flux, which depends on field strength. A stronger magnetic field produces greater flux change, inducing a larger voltage in the receiver coil—this is why higher field strength MRI systems produce more signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-013", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In a cylindrical bore superconducting magnet, the main magnetic field (B0) is oriented in which direction?", "options": ["Vertical (floor to ceiling)", "Horizontal (head to foot along the bore)", "Perpendicular to the bore axis", "Circumferential around the bore"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a cylindrical bore superconducting magnet, B0 runs horizontally along the bore axis (head to foot in standard patient positioning). This horizontal orientation determines how RF coils must be configured to produce a B1 field perpendicular to B0, which is required for excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-014", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In an open-design permanent MRI magnet, the main magnetic field (B0) is typically oriented in which direction?", "options": ["Vertical (floor to ceiling)", "Horizontal (head to foot)", "Transverse to the patient axis", "Circumferential around the gap"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In open-design permanent magnets, B0 is oriented vertically between the two magnetic poles (floor to ceiling). This vertical field direction contrasts with the horizontal B0 of cylindrical bore systems and directly affects RF coil selection and design.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-015", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "A resistive MRI magnet generates its magnetic field by continuously applying which of the following to its electromagnet coils?", "options": ["Cryogenic coolant", "Thermal energy", "Electrical current", "Radiofrequency pulses"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Resistive magnets generate their magnetic field by continuously passing electrical current through electromagnetic coils. Unlike superconducting magnets, they have inherent electrical resistance, requiring ongoing power and generating heat that limits achievable field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-016", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "The conversion between Tesla (T) and Gauss (G) is defined as 1 Tesla equals:", "options": ["100 Gauss", "1,000 Gauss", "10,000 Gauss", "100,000 Gauss"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Tesla and Gauss are both units of magnetic field strength, related by the conversion 1 T = 10,000 G. This is a fundamental conversion factor used throughout MRI physics.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-017", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "A 1.5 Tesla MRI system operates at a magnetic field strength equivalent to:", "options": ["10,000 Gauss", "15,000 Gauss", "20,000 Gauss", "30,000 Gauss"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Using the conversion 1 T = 10,000 G, a 1.5 T system operates at 15,000 Gauss (1.5 x 10,000). This is approximately 30,000 times the strength of the Earth's magnetic field (~0.5 G).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-018", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "In a superconducting magnet, field strength is primarily increased during manufacturing by adding more:", "options": ["Liquid helium to the dewar", "Thermal insulation layers", "Internal pressure to the cryostat", "Turns of superconducting wire"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In a superconducting magnet, field strength is determined during manufacturing by the number of turns of superconducting wire in the solenoid coil. More turns produce a stronger field when current flows. Adding helium maintains temperature but does not increase field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-019", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In a solenoid-based superconducting magnet, reversing the direction of current flow through the coils would change the:", "options": ["Strength of the magnetic field", "Direction of the magnetic field", "Homogeneity of the magnetic field", "Temporal stability of the magnetic field"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a solenoid, the magnetic field direction is determined by the direction of current flow (right-hand rule). Reversing the current reverses the B0 field direction without changing its strength, homogeneity, or temporal stability.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-020", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.b", "stem": "When using a permanent magnet MRI system with a vertical main magnetic field, which surface coil design is most appropriate?", "options": ["Solenoid", "Butterfly", "Quadrature", "Flat plate"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A solenoid coil generates B1 along its axis. In a permanent magnet with vertical B0, a horizontally oriented solenoid surface coil produces B1 perpendicular to B0—the requirement for effective excitation. Butterfly and flat-plate designs generate B1 perpendicular to their surface, making them suited for horizontal B0 systems.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-021", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "The transmit bandwidth of an RF excitation pulse directly influences:", "options": ["Image contrast weighting", "Signal-to-noise ratio only", "Patient-specific absorption rate", "Slice thickness and spatial resolution"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The transmit bandwidth of an RF pulse, combined with the slice-select gradient amplitude, directly determines slice thickness. A narrower transmit bandwidth excites a thinner tissue slice, improving through-plane spatial resolution. SAR depends on pulse power and duty cycle, not bandwidth alone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-022", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "Which combination of adjustments will produce a thinner slice thickness?", "options": ["Decreased gradient amplitude with wider transmit bandwidth", "Increased receiver bandwidth with lower gradient amplitude", "Steeper slice-select gradient with narrower transmit bandwidth", "Wider transmit bandwidth with decreased gradient steepness"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Slice thickness is inversely proportional to slice-select gradient amplitude and directly proportional to transmit bandwidth. Combining a steeper gradient with a narrower bandwidth produces the thinnest possible slices. Decreasing gradient amplitude or widening bandwidth both increase slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-023", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "The receiver bandwidth setting directly affects which of the following image characteristics?", "options": ["Slice thickness and spatial resolution", "Repetition time and echo spacing", "Matrix size and field of view", "Chemical shift artifact and signal-to-noise ratio"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Receiver bandwidth directly affects chemical shift artifact magnitude (wider bandwidth reduces fat-water pixel displacement) and SNR (wider bandwidth samples more noise, reducing SNR). Slice thickness depends on transmit bandwidth and gradient amplitude, not receiver bandwidth.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-024", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "An MRI technologist notices poor image quality and discovers the receive coil was not properly tuned before scanning. This error most directly results in:", "options": ["Decreased signal-to-noise ratio", "Improved spatial resolution", "Radiofrequency burn injury", "Gradient-related artifacts"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A receive coil must be properly tuned to the Larmor frequency and impedance-matched to the receiver electronics to efficiently capture the MR signal. An improperly tuned coil collects less signal, directly reducing SNR. This error does not cause RF burns or gradient-related artifacts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-025", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "During MRI data acquisition, the gradient magnetic fields function by being:", "options": ["Activated independently of the static field", "Superimposed onto the main magnetic field", "Used to control tissue contrast weighting", "Modulated by radiofrequency pulse timing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient fields are superimposed onto B0 to create controlled, linear spatial variations in total field strength. This superposition causes protons at different locations to precess at slightly different frequencies, enabling spatial encoding. Gradients do not function independently of the static field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 129"}, {"id": "IP-026", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "The timing of radiofrequency pulses within a pulse sequence primarily determines:", "options": ["Image contrast weighting", "Spatial encoding of the MR signal", "Static field homogeneity", "Receiver coil sensitivity"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The timing of RF pulses (TR, TE, TI) within a pulse sequence controls how much T1 recovery and T2 decay occur between excitations and signal readout, directly determining image contrast weighting. Spatial encoding is performed by gradients, not RF pulse timing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 22"}, {"id": "IP-027", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.d", "stem": "The oscillating B1 field used to tip the net magnetization vector away from equilibrium is produced by the:", "options": ["Gradient coil", "Shim coil", "Radiofrequency coil", "Superconducting magnet coil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The B1 field is an oscillating magnetic field produced by the RF transmit coil at the Larmor frequency to tip the net magnetization vector away from its equilibrium alignment along B0. Gradient coils create spatial field variations and shim coils correct B0 inhomogeneity—neither produces B1.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-028", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.c", "stem": "Active shimming in an MRI system improves B0 homogeneity by:", "options": ["Adjusting current through the shim coils", "Repositioning metallic shim plates within the bore", "Increasing current to the gradient coils", "Rapidly cycling the shim coils on and off"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Active shimming corrects B0 inhomogeneities by adjusting electrical current through dedicated shim coils to produce compensating magnetic fields. Passive shimming uses repositioning of metallic plates; rapidly cycling shim coils is not a recognized shimming technique.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-029", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.c", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a recognized method for shimming an MRI system?", "options": ["Adjusting electrical current through dedicated shim coils", "Placing metallic shim plates at specific locations within the bore", "Using gradient offsets to compensate for field inhomogeneity", "Rapidly pulsing the shim coils on and off"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Recognized shimming methods include active shimming (adjusting current through shim coils), passive shimming (placing metallic plates), and gradient offset shimming. Rapidly pulsing shim coils on and off is not a valid technique—shim corrections require steady-state adjustments.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-030", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Gradient amplitude (field strength per unit distance) is measured in which units?", "options": ["mT/m or G/cm", "T/m/s", "Microseconds (µs)", "Percentage (%)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient amplitude measures the change in magnetic field strength per unit distance and is expressed in milliTesla per meter (mT/m) or Gauss per centimeter (G/cm). T/m/s is the unit for slew rate, and microseconds measure rise time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-031", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.c", "stem": "Gradient rise time — the interval required for a gradient to reach its target amplitude — is measured in which units?", "options": ["mT/m", "T/m/s", "Percentage (%)", "Microseconds (µs)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gradient rise time is the interval for a gradient to ramp from zero to its target amplitude, measured in microseconds. Shorter rise times enable faster pulse sequences and shorter minimum TE values. mT/m measures amplitude and T/m/s measures slew rate.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-032", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.b", "stem": "Slew rate — the gradient performance metric that combines both amplitude and rise time — is expressed in which units?", "options": ["mT/m", "Microseconds (µs)", "T/m/s", "Percentage (%)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Slew rate equals gradient amplitude divided by rise time, expressed in Tesla per meter per second (T/m/s). Higher slew rates indicate faster gradient switching, enabling shorter echo times and faster sequences. mT/m measures amplitude alone, and microseconds measure time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-033", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.d", "stem": "Gradient duty cycle — the proportion of time a gradient can remain active within a given period — is expressed in which units?", "options": ["mT/m", "T/m/s", "Microseconds (µs)", "Percentage (%)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Duty cycle is the proportion of time a gradient coil can remain active within a repetition period, expressed as a percentage. It reflects the thermal limits of the gradient system—exceeding duty cycle limits risks overheating the gradient coils.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-034", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Which gradient characteristic describes the maximum field strength a gradient coil can produce?", "options": ["Amplitude", "Slew rate", "Duty cycle", "Rise time"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient amplitude describes the maximum field strength a gradient coil can produce, measured in mT/m. It determines how steeply the magnetic field varies across the imaging volume. Slew rate combines amplitude with rise time, and duty cycle reflects thermal operating limits.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-035", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.b", "stem": "Which gradient specification combines both amplitude and rise time into a single performance metric?", "options": ["Amplitude", "Slew rate", "Duty cycle", "Bandwidth"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slew rate (T/m/s) is calculated by dividing gradient amplitude by rise time, making it a composite metric of gradient switching performance. Higher slew rates enable shorter TE, faster EPI, and more efficient diffusion sequences. Amplitude and rise time are individual components, not combined metrics.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-036", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.d", "stem": "The percentage of time that a gradient coil is permitted to operate during a pulse sequence is defined by the:", "options": ["Amplitude", "Slew rate", "Duty cycle", "Rise time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Duty cycle defines the maximum percentage of time a gradient may be active during a pulse sequence before thermal limits are reached. Exceeding the duty cycle causes the system to pause scanning or reduce gradient performance to prevent overheating.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-037", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.c", "stem": "The time interval required for a gradient to ramp from zero to its maximum amplitude is known as the:", "options": ["Gradient amplitude", "Slew rate", "Duty cycle", "Rise time"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Rise time is the interval required for a gradient to ramp from zero to its maximum specified amplitude. Shorter rise times improve gradient switching speed and are essential for sequences requiring rapid gradient changes such as EPI and diffusion imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-038", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "Which of the following is true regarding RF coil configurations used in MRI?", "options": ["Only linear and quadrature designs are used in clinical practice", "Phased array coils have been replaced entirely by multichannel designs", "Helmholtz coil pairs are used exclusively in permanent magnet systems", "Linear, quadrature, phased array, Helmholtz, and multichannel are all recognized RF coil configurations"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All five coil designs have clinical applications: linear (simple, lower SNR), quadrature (sqrt-2 SNR improvement), phased array (extended coverage), Helmholtz (paired elements for uniform field), and multichannel (parallel imaging capability). No single design has replaced all others.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-039", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.c", "stem": "A Helmholtz coil pair is distinguished from phased array and multichannel coils primarily because it:", "options": ["Uses a single coil element with one receiver channel", "Requires parallel imaging reconstruction", "Contains multiple independent receiver channels", "Uses paired coil elements connected to a single receiver channel"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A Helmholtz coil pair consists of two coil elements separated by a specific distance and connected to a single receiver channel, producing a relatively uniform B1 field between them. Phased array and multichannel coils differ by having multiple independent receiver channels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-040", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.c", "stem": "Which RF coil configurations utilize multiple coil elements with independent receiver channels?", "options": ["Linear and quadrature only", "Helmholtz pair only", "Phased array and multichannel", "Quadrature and Helmholtz only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Phased array and multichannel coils both use multiple coil elements with independent receiver channels, enabling extended anatomic coverage, improved SNR, and parallel imaging capability. Linear coils use a single element, and Helmholtz pairs share a single channel.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-041", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "Which type of RF polarization is considered the modern standard for clinical MRI because it creates a rotating magnetic field that matches nuclear precession?", "options": ["Linear polarization", "Quadrature (circular) polarization", "Vertical polarization", "Parallel polarization"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Quadrature polarization produces a rotating B1 field that matches the circular precession of nuclear spins, delivering RF energy more efficiently and improving SNR by up to sqrt-2 compared to linear polarization. Linear polarization wastes approximately half its energy because only the rotating component matching precession direction contributes to excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-042", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "An RF coil designed with two sets of conductors oriented perpendicular to each other — enabling detection of signal from two orthogonal planes — is classified as a:", "options": ["Linear coil", "Quadrature coil", "Phased array coil", "Helmholtz coil"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A quadrature coil uses two conductor sets oriented 90 degrees apart to detect signal from two orthogonal planes simultaneously, providing a sqrt-2 improvement in SNR over a linear coil. A phased array uses multiple separate elements rather than two perpendicular conductors in a single housing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-043", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "In the Larmor equation (ω₀ = γ × B₀), the variable B₀ represents:", "options": ["Static magnetic field strength", "Precessional frequency", "Gyromagnetic ratio", "Induced voltage"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In the Larmor equation, B0 represents the external static magnetic field strength in Tesla. The precessional frequency is directly proportional to B0—doubling the field strength doubles the Larmor frequency.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-044", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "In the Larmor equation (ω₀ = γ × B₀), the variable ω₀ represents:", "options": ["Static magnetic field strength", "Precessional (Larmor) frequency", "Gyromagnetic ratio", "Induced voltage"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Omega-zero represents the precessional or Larmor frequency—the rate at which hydrogen protons precess around the axis of B0. At 1.5 T, this frequency is approximately 63.86 MHz for hydrogen. The gyromagnetic ratio is a constant specific to each nucleus.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-045", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "In the Larmor equation (ω₀ = γ × B₀), the variable γ (gamma) represents:", "options": ["Static magnetic field strength", "Precessional frequency", "Gyromagnetic ratio", "Induced voltage"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gamma is the gyromagnetic ratio, a constant unique to each MR-active nucleus that relates its precessional frequency to the applied field strength. For hydrogen, gamma = 42.57 MHz/T. B0 is field strength and omega-zero is the resulting frequency.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-046", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "A 0.5 Tesla MRI system operates at a magnetic field strength equivalent to:", "options": ["500 Gauss", "5,000 Gauss", "10,000 Gauss", "15,000 Gauss"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Using the conversion 1 T = 10,000 G, a 0.5 T system operates at 5,000 Gauss (0.5 x 10,000). This field strength is typical of older open-design permanent or resistive MRI systems.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-047", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "When hydrogen protons are placed in an external magnetic field and a slight majority of spins align parallel to B₀, this baseline condition is known as:", "options": ["Low energy absorption", "High energy saturation", "Thermal equilibrium", "Excitation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When placed in B0, hydrogen protons distribute between parallel and antiparallel energy states with a slight majority in the lower energy (parallel) state. This stable baseline condition is called thermal equilibrium and produces the net magnetization vector (NMV) aligned with B0.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-048", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "At thermal equilibrium within an external magnetic field, the distribution of hydrogen proton spins is characterized by:", "options": ["A slight excess of spins in the low energy (parallel) state", "A slight excess of spins in the high energy (anti-parallel) state", "An equal number of spins in the low and high energy states", "Fewer spins in the low energy state than the high energy state"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "At thermal equilibrium, slightly more proton spins occupy the lower energy parallel state than the higher energy antiparallel state, creating a net magnetization vector along B0. This spin excess is very small (only a few per million) but sufficient to generate detectable MR signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-049", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "Hydrogen proton spins that are aligned parallel to the B₀ field are described by all of the following terms EXCEPT:", "options": ["Spin-up", "Parallel", "Low energy state", "High energy state"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Proton spins aligned parallel to B0 are described as spin-up, parallel, and in the low energy state. The high energy state describes antiparallel (spin-down) alignment. This energy difference between states is what allows RF energy at the Larmor frequency to cause transitions (excitation).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-050", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "The tiny magnetic field generated by an individual precessing hydrogen proton is referred to as the:", "options": ["Free induction decay (FID)", "Magnetic moment (μ)", "Spin echo (SE)", "Net magnetization vector (NMV)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Each precessing hydrogen proton generates a tiny magnetic field called a magnetic moment. The vector sum of all individual magnetic moments in a voxel produces the net magnetization vector (NMV). The FID is the signal detected after excitation, not a property of individual protons.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-051", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "The vector sum of all hydrogen proton magnetic moments at thermal equilibrium — representing the slight spin excess in the parallel direction — is called the:", "options": ["Free induction decay (FID)", "Net magnetization vector (NMV)", "Spin echo (SE)", "Magnetic moment (μ)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The NMV is the vector sum of all individual hydrogen proton magnetic moments at thermal equilibrium. Because slightly more spins align parallel than antiparallel to B0, the NMV points along B0. The magnetic moment describes an individual proton, not the collective vector.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-052", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.d", "stem": "Applying a radiofrequency pulse at the Larmor frequency to a spin system at equilibrium produces a condition known as:", "options": ["Thermal equilibrium", "Excitation", "Relaxation", "Saturation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Applying an RF pulse at the Larmor frequency transfers energy to the spin system, tipping the NMV away from equilibrium into the transverse plane. This energy absorption is called excitation. Saturation occurs when equal numbers of spins occupy both energy states, eliminating net magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-053", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "Which of the following events occurs during relaxation rather than excitation?", "options": ["Low energy proton spins absorb energy and transition to the high energy state", "Proton spins achieve phase coherence", "Net magnetization tips into the transverse plane", "High energy proton spins release energy and return to the low energy state"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "During relaxation, proton spins that were excited to the high energy (antiparallel) state release energy and return to the low energy (parallel) state, recovering longitudinal magnetization. The other three options—energy absorption, phase coherence, and transverse tipping—all describe excitation events.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-054", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following events occurs during excitation rather than relaxation?", "options": ["Low energy proton spins absorb RF energy and transition to the high energy state", "Anti-parallel spins release energy and return to the parallel orientation", "Proton spins lose phase coherence (dephasing)", "Longitudinal magnetization recovers toward its equilibrium value"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "During excitation, protons in the low energy (parallel) state absorb RF energy at the Larmor frequency and transition to the high energy (antiparallel) state. The remaining options—energy release, dephasing, and longitudinal recovery—all describe relaxation processes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-055", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following terms describes T2 relaxation rather than T1 relaxation?", "options": ["T1 recovery", "Spin-lattice relaxation", "Longitudinal recovery", "Spin-spin relaxation"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2 relaxation (transverse decay) is also called spin-spin relaxation because it results from interactions between neighboring proton spins causing loss of phase coherence. T1 relaxation is called spin-lattice relaxation because energy is transferred from the spin system to the surrounding molecular lattice.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-056", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "Transverse relaxation — the process by which proton spins lose phase coherence after excitation — is also referred to as:", "options": ["T1 recovery", "Spin-lattice relaxation", "Longitudinal relaxation", "Spin-spin relaxation"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Transverse relaxation describes the loss of phase coherence among precessing protons after excitation, resulting in decay of the transverse magnetization signal. This process is driven by spin-spin interactions—local magnetic field variations from neighboring nuclei—and is independent of energy transfer to the lattice.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-057", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "Which of the following terms is associated with T1 relaxation rather than T2 relaxation?", "options": ["T2 decay", "Spin-lattice", "Spin-spin", "Transverse relaxation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T1 relaxation involves the transfer of energy from excited proton spins to the surrounding molecular lattice, allowing longitudinal magnetization to recover. The term spin-lattice distinguishes this energy exchange mechanism from T2 (spin-spin) relaxation, which involves dephasing without energy transfer.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 26"}, {"id": "IP-058", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "The T1 relaxation time of a tissue is defined as the time required for:", "options": ["37% of the longitudinal magnetization to recover after excitation", "63% of the longitudinal magnetization to recover after excitation", "63% of the transverse magnetization to recover after excitation", "76% of the longitudinal magnetization to recover after excitation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T1 is defined as the time constant at which 63% of longitudinal magnetization has recovered toward its equilibrium value following excitation. This follows an exponential recovery curve. The 37% value describes the amount still unrecovered at one T1 time constant.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 26"}, {"id": "IP-059", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "The T2 relaxation time of a tissue is defined as the time required for:", "options": ["37% of the transverse magnetization to decay after excitation", "63% of the longitudinal magnetization to decay after excitation", "63% of the transverse magnetization to decay after excitation", "76% of the transverse magnetization to decay after excitation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "T2 is defined as the time constant at which transverse magnetization has decayed to 37% of its initial value—equivalently, 63% of the signal has been lost. This exponential decay is driven by spin-spin interactions causing progressive dephasing of precessing protons.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-060", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A spin echo pulse sequence programmed with a short TR and a short TE produces images that are primarily:", "options": ["T1 weighted", "T2 weighted", "Proton density weighted", "Diffusion weighted"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Short TR maximizes T1 contrast by sampling tissues before full longitudinal recovery, so tissues with short T1 (like fat) appear bright. Short TE minimizes T2 contrast by sampling before significant transverse decay. The combination produces T1-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-061", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "A spin echo pulse sequence programmed with a long TR and a long TE produces images that are primarily:", "options": ["T1 weighted", "T2 weighted", "Proton density weighted", "Diffusion weighted"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Long TR allows nearly complete longitudinal recovery in all tissues, minimizing T1 contrast. Long TE allows substantial transverse decay, maximizing T2 contrast so that tissues with long T2 (like fluid) appear bright. The combination produces T2-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-062", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "A spin echo pulse sequence programmed with a long TR and a short TE produces images that are primarily:", "options": ["T1 weighted", "T2 weighted", "Proton density weighted", "Diffusion weighted"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Long TR minimizes T1 contrast and short TE minimizes T2 contrast, leaving signal intensity primarily dependent on the number of mobile hydrogen protons (proton density) in each tissue. Tissues with higher hydrogen concentration appear brighter on PD-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-063", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "In MRI, the term \"spin density\" is used interchangeably with:", "options": ["Nuclear density", "Hydrogen concentration", "Proton density", "Electron density"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Spin density and proton density are interchangeable terms describing the concentration of mobile hydrogen nuclei in a tissue that can contribute to the MR signal. Nuclear density and electron density are not synonymous with spin density in MRI terminology.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-064", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "Proton (spin) density in a tissue is fundamentally determined by the:", "options": ["Concentration of hydrogen nuclei available to contribute to the MR signal", "Amount of transverse magnetization at the time the echo is sampled", "Ratio of T1 to T2 relaxation times", "Number of anti-parallel spins at thermal equilibrium"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Proton density is an intrinsic tissue property determined by the concentration of mobile hydrogen nuclei. Tightly bound hydrogen (as in cortical bone) does not contribute significant signal. The amount of transverse magnetization at echo sampling is influenced by both PD and T2, not PD alone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-065", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.4", "stem": "A steady-state gradient echo sequence using a short TR, a low flip angle, and a moderately long TE produces images with predominant:", "options": ["T1 weighting", "T2 weighting", "Proton density weighting", "T2* weighting"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In gradient echo sequences, the absence of a 180-degree refocusing pulse means the echo contains T2* decay (true T2 plus field inhomogeneity effects). A low flip angle with long TE in a steady-state GRE maximizes T2* contrast. T2 weighting requires spin echo refocusing to eliminate inhomogeneity effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-066", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "The combined effect of true T2 relaxation and additional dephasing from local field inhomogeneities (T2') results in a shorter effective decay constant known as:", "options": ["T1", "T2", "Proton density", "T2*"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2* represents the observed transverse decay rate, combining true T2 relaxation (spin-spin interactions) with additional dephasing from local magnetic field inhomogeneities (T2-prime). T2* is always shorter than T2 because inhomogeneity effects accelerate signal loss. Spin echo sequences compensate for T2-prime using 180-degree refocusing pulses.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-067", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "When prescribing an axial image, the logical gradient assigned to perform slice selection is the:", "options": ["X gradient", "Y gradient", "Z gradient", "A combination of X, Y, and Z gradients"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "For axial images, the slice-select gradient must vary the field along the superior-inferior axis to separate individual axial slices. In a horizontal bore system, this is the Z gradient (along the bore). The X and Y gradients are then available for frequency and phase encoding within the axial plane.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-068", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) MRI system, the physical gradient coil responsible for selecting an axial slice is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "A combination of gradient coils"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a superconducting horizontal bore magnet, the Z gradient coil varies the field along the bore axis (superior-inferior). When activated simultaneously with a frequency-selective RF pulse, it excites only the protons within a specific axial slice. The X (left-right) and Y (anterior-posterior) gradients handle in-plane encoding.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-069", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "When prescribing a sagittal image, the logical gradient assigned to perform slice selection is the:", "options": ["X gradient", "Y gradient", "Z gradient", "A combination of X, Y, and Z gradients"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "For sagittal images, slices are separated in the left-right direction. The X gradient varies the field along the left-right axis, so when applied with a frequency-selective RF pulse, it selects a specific sagittal slice. The Z gradient (superior-inferior) is used for axial slice selection, not sagittal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-070", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) MRI system, the physical gradient coil responsible for selecting a sagittal slice is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "A combination of gradient coils"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a horizontal bore system, sagittal slices are separated in the left-right direction. The X gradient coil varies the field along this axis, so when applied with a frequency-selective RF pulse, it excites only protons within a specific sagittal slice. The Z gradient (bore axis) handles axial selection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-071", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "When acquiring an axial image of the abdomen, the logical gradient assigned to perform phase encoding is the:", "options": ["X gradient", "Y gradient", "Z gradient", "A combination of X, Y, and Z gradients"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "For axial abdominal imaging, phase encoding is conventionally assigned to the anterior-posterior direction (Y gradient) because this is typically the shorter anatomic dimension, reducing scan time. The Z gradient handles slice selection, and X handles frequency encoding in this configuration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-072", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "When acquiring an axial image of the head, the logical gradient assigned to perform phase encoding is the:", "options": ["X gradient", "Y gradient", "Z gradient", "A combination of X, Y, and Z gradients"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "For standard axial head imaging, phase encoding is typically assigned to the anterior-posterior axis (Y gradient). This convention helps direct motion and flow artifacts from pulsating vessels away from critical brain structures. The phase direction can be swapped by the technologist as needed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-073", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient coil used for phase encoding during an axial abdomen acquisition (with phase set anterior-posterior) is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "A combination of gradient coils"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When phase encoding is set anterior-posterior for an axial acquisition, the Y gradient coil performs phase encoding. Each phase-encoding step applies a different Y gradient amplitude to impart unique phase shifts across the AP dimension of the imaging volume.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-074", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient coil used for phase encoding during an axial head acquisition (with phase set left-right) is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "A combination of gradient coils"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When phase encoding is set left-right for an axial head acquisition, the X gradient coil performs phase encoding. This swap from the conventional AP direction may be chosen to redirect flow artifacts from the carotid and vertebral arteries away from the region of interest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-075", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The receive bandwidth is directly related to the amplitude (slope) of which gradient?", "options": ["Frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Phase-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Shim gradient"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Receiver bandwidth defines the range of frequencies sampled during signal readout and is directly related to the amplitude of the frequency-encoding gradient. A steeper readout gradient spreads frequencies across a wider bandwidth. The phase-encoding and slice-select gradients operate at different points in the sequence and do not determine receiver bandwidth.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-076", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.i", "stem": "The MR signal generated immediately after a 90° excitation pulse — before any refocusing pulse is applied — is called the:", "options": ["Spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Free induction decay (FID)", "Stimulated echo"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FID is the signal generated immediately after an excitation pulse as transverse magnetization precesses and induces a voltage in the receiver coil. It decays rapidly due to T2* effects. A spin echo requires a subsequent refocusing pulse, and a gradient echo requires a gradient reversal—neither occurs immediately after excitation alone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 20"}, {"id": "IP-077", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "T2* dephasing results from a tissue's intrinsic T2 decay combined with additional signal loss from:", "options": ["T1 recovery processes", "Magnetic susceptibility differences, field inhomogeneities, and chemical shift", "Molecular weight of the tissue", "Proton density variations"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T2* dephasing combines intrinsic T2 decay with additional signal loss from extrinsic sources: local magnetic susceptibility differences between tissues, static field inhomogeneities, and chemical shift effects. These extrinsic factors (collectively called T2-prime) are reversible by a 180-degree refocusing pulse in spin echo sequences but not in gradient echo sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-078", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "The maximum amplitude of a spin echo is always lower than the initial FID signal because of irreversible signal loss caused by:", "options": ["T1 recovery", "T2* dephasing", "Changes in proton density", "T2 relaxation"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A 180-degree refocusing pulse rephases dephasing caused by static field inhomogeneities (T2-prime), but it cannot recover signal lost to true T2 (spin-spin) relaxation. Therefore, spin echo amplitude is always lower than the initial FID because irreversible T2 decay has occurred during the interval between excitation and echo formation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-079", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "Which of the following is an example of a magnetic dipole?", "options": ["A hydrogen nucleus only", "A bar magnet only", "The earth only", "A hydrogen nucleus, a bar magnet, and the earth are all magnetic dipoles"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A magnetic dipole is any entity with distinct north and south magnetic poles. Hydrogen nuclei (due to spin), bar magnets, and the Earth all exhibit dipole behavior. This concept is fundamental to understanding why hydrogen protons align in an external magnetic field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-080", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.a", "stem": "In MRI physics, a vector quantity is defined as having both direction and:", "options": ["Polarity", "Current", "Magnitude", "Frequency"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A vector quantity is defined by both its direction and magnitude. In MRI, the net magnetization vector has both a direction (along B0 at equilibrium) and a magnitude (determined by the spin excess). Scalar quantities have magnitude only, without direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-081", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "Hydrogen nuclei exhibit a magnetic moment because they possess an intrinsic quantum mechanical property known as:", "options": ["Inversion", "Magnetic flux", "Spin angular momentum", "Resonance"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Hydrogen nuclei possess an intrinsic quantum mechanical property called spin angular momentum, which gives rise to their magnetic moment. Because the hydrogen nucleus (a single proton) has an odd mass number, it has a net spin and behaves as a tiny magnetic dipole when placed in an external field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-082", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "When hydrogen protons are placed in an external static magnetic field, they:", "options": ["All align in the same direction as B₀", "Distribute between parallel and anti-parallel energy states", "Oscillate randomly without preferred orientation", "Immediately undergo relaxation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When placed in B0, hydrogen protons distribute between parallel (low energy) and antiparallel (high energy) states according to the Boltzmann distribution. They do not all align in one direction—only a slight excess favors the parallel state, which is sufficient to produce net magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-083", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "Hydrogen proton spins oriented anti-parallel to the static magnetic field (B₀) occupy:", "options": ["A metastable energy state", "A resonant condition", "The high-energy state", "A state of thermal equilibrium"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton spins oriented antiparallel (opposed) to B0 occupy the high-energy state because this alignment opposes the external field. Transitioning from parallel to antiparallel requires energy absorption (provided by an RF pulse at the Larmor frequency). The energy difference between states is proportional to field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-084", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "At thermal equilibrium, the cumulative effect of the slight excess of parallel-aligned proton spins produces:", "options": ["A rotating magnetic field", "An oscillating signal", "A transverse magnetization component", "A net magnetization vector (NMV) aligned with B₀"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The slight excess of parallel-aligned protons at thermal equilibrium produces a measurable net magnetization vector that points along B0. This NMV is the starting point for all MRI signal generation. A rotating field or transverse component does not exist at equilibrium—these only appear after an RF excitation pulse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-085", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "The mathematical relationship that defines how precessional frequency depends on static magnetic field strength is expressed by the:", "options": ["Helmholtz equation", "Nyquist theorem", "Larmor equation", "Bloch equation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Larmor equation defines the linear relationship between precessional frequency and magnetic field strength. The Nyquist theorem relates to sampling frequency requirements, the Helmholtz equation describes electromagnetic wave propagation, and the Bloch equations describe the time evolution of magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-086", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "In the Larmor equation, the constant that is multiplied by field strength to determine precessional frequency is the:", "options": ["Gyromagnetic ratio (γ)", "Boltzmann constant", "Planck constant", "Linear attenuation coefficient"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The gyromagnetic ratio (gamma) is a nucleus-specific constant that relates precessional frequency to field strength in the Larmor equation. For hydrogen, gamma = 42.58 MHz/T. The Boltzmann and Planck constants relate to energy distributions and quantum mechanics respectively but do not appear in the Larmor equation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-087", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "Within seconds of being placed in an external magnetic field, hydrogen protons establish a baseline state known as:", "options": ["Resonance", "Free induction decay", "Phase coherence", "Thermal equilibrium"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Within seconds of being placed in an external magnetic field, hydrogen protons establish thermal equilibrium—a stable state where a slight excess of spins aligns parallel to B0, producing the NMV. Resonance requires an applied RF pulse, the FID occurs after excitation, and phase coherence only exists transiently after an RF pulse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-088", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.h", "stem": "At thermal equilibrium in a uniform magnetic field, individual hydrogen protons precess at the Larmor frequency but are:", "options": ["All in phase with one another", "Stationary and not precessing", "Out of phase (random phase positions)", "Precessing at different frequencies"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At thermal equilibrium, all protons precess at the Larmor frequency, but each has a random phase position relative to the others. No net transverse magnetization exists because individual transverse components cancel. An RF pulse at the Larmor frequency is required to establish phase coherence.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-089", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.d", "stem": "Efficient energy transfer between a radiofrequency pulse and precessing hydrogen protons requires that both systems share the same:", "options": ["Phase position", "Energy level", "Mass", "Resonant frequency"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Resonance occurs when the RF pulse frequency matches the Larmor (precessional) frequency of the hydrogen protons. This frequency match enables efficient energy transfer from the RF field to the spin system, causing excitation. If frequencies do not match, energy transfer is negligible and excitation does not occur.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-090", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "Assuming complete longitudinal recovery before each excitation, the maximum MR signal is induced in the receiver coil when the net magnetization vector is tipped:", "options": ["180° (full inversion)", "90° (fully into the transverse plane)", "45° (partially toward the transverse plane)", "270° (past the transverse plane)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A 90-degree pulse tips the entire NMV into the transverse plane, maximizing the component that precesses and induces signal in the receiver coil. A 180-degree pulse inverts magnetization but produces no transverse component (no signal). Flip angles less than 90 degrees leave some magnetization longitudinal, producing less transverse signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-091", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "The B1 (radiofrequency) field is applied in an orientation that is _____ to the static magnetic field (B₀):", "options": ["Parallel (0°)", "Perpendicular (90°)", "Anti-parallel (180°)", "Oblique (45°)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The B1 (RF) field must be applied perpendicular to B0 to effectively tip the NMV away from its equilibrium alignment. A parallel B1 field would not exert the rotational torque needed to flip magnetization into the transverse plane. This perpendicular orientation is fundamental to the excitation process.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-092", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "Radiofrequency energy used in MRI is classified on the electromagnetic spectrum as:", "options": ["Non-ionizing electromagnetic radiation", "Ionizing radiation", "Particulate radiation", "Acoustic energy"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Radiofrequency energy used in MRI falls in the megahertz range of the electromagnetic spectrum, well below the energy threshold for ionization. This non-ionizing nature is a key safety advantage of MRI over modalities that use ionizing radiation (X-ray, CT, nuclear medicine). RF energy can cause tissue heating but cannot remove electrons from atoms.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-093", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.h", "stem": "The immediate effect of applying a 90° RF pulse on precessing hydrogen protons is that they:", "options": ["All transition to the anti-parallel (high energy) state", "Undergo T2 relaxation", "Achieve phase coherence (begin precessing in phase)", "Emit a spin echo signal"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A 90-degree RF pulse forces all hydrogen protons to precess together in phase (phase coherence), creating measurable transverse magnetization. At equilibrium, protons precess at random phase positions with no net transverse signal. Not all protons transition to the antiparallel state—only enough to eliminate the longitudinal magnetization component.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-094", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.i", "stem": "The MR signal detected by the receiver coil is generated by magnetization that is:", "options": ["Out of phase in the longitudinal plane", "Aligned along the longitudinal (z) axis", "Fully decayed", "Rotating in the transverse (x-y) plane"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The MR signal is generated by transverse magnetization rotating in the x-y plane at the Larmor frequency. This rotating magnetic field induces a voltage in the receiver coil via Faraday's law. Longitudinal magnetization (along z) does not rotate relative to B0 and therefore does not induce a detectable signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-095", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "In MRI physics, frequency is defined as the:", "options": ["Rate of phase change per unit time", "Total accumulated phase divided by two", "Output of a Fourier transform", "Peak amplitude of the MR signal"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Frequency describes how rapidly phase accumulates over time—essentially how many complete precessional cycles occur per second (measured in Hz or MHz). This relationship between frequency and phase is fundamental to spatial encoding, where gradients cause location-dependent frequency and phase differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-096", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "The primary purpose of gradient magnetic fields in MRI is to:", "options": ["Increase the signal-to-noise ratio", "Spatially encode the MR data", "Generate the radiofrequency excitation pulse", "Directly control image contrast weighting"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient magnetic fields create linear spatial variations in the magnetic field, causing protons at different locations to precess at different frequencies. This frequency variation enables spatial encoding through slice selection, phase encoding, and frequency encoding. Gradients do not directly affect SNR, generate RF pulses, or control image contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-097", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In MRI, slice thickness is primarily determined by the:", "options": ["Physical length of the gradient coil", "Slope (amplitude) of the slice-select gradient and the transmit bandwidth", "Receiver bandwidth setting", "Number of phase-encoding steps"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slice thickness is determined by two factors acting together: the amplitude (steepness) of the slice-select gradient and the transmit bandwidth of the RF pulse. A steeper gradient or narrower bandwidth produces a thinner slice. Receiver bandwidth, phase-encoding steps, and coil dimensions do not determine slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-098", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) MRI system, the physical gradient coil oriented along the bore axis (superior-inferior) is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "A combination of X and Y gradients", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In a horizontal bore superconducting magnet, the Z gradient coil is oriented along the bore axis, varying the field in the superior-inferior direction. By convention: X = left-right, Y = anterior-posterior, Z = superior-inferior (along the bore). This Z gradient is the same one used for axial slice selection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-099", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient coil activated during the excitation pulse to select a sagittal slice is the:", "options": ["Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "X gradient (left-right)", "A combination of Z and Y gradients"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Sagittal slices separate anatomy in the left-right direction. In a horizontal bore system, the X gradient coil varies the field along the left-right axis. When applied simultaneously with a frequency-selective RF pulse, it excites only protons within a specific sagittal slice location.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-100", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "The gyromagnetic ratio (γ) for hydrogen is approximately:", "options": ["63.86 MHz/T", "42.58 MHz/T", "1 G/cm", "4 W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The gyromagnetic ratio of hydrogen is approximately 42.58 MHz/T. A common misconception is confusing this constant with the Larmor frequency at 1.5 T (approximately 63.86 MHz), which is the product of gamma times field strength, not gamma itself. The other options represent unrelated units (gradient amplitude and SAR).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-101", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "At a static field strength of 0.5 Tesla, the precessional (Larmor) frequency of hydrogen is approximately:", "options": ["63.86 MHz", "42.58 MHz", "21.29 MHz", "10.65 MHz"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Larmor frequency equals the gyromagnetic ratio times field strength: 42.58 MHz/T x 0.5 T = 21.29 MHz. A common error is selecting 42.58 MHz (the gyromagnetic ratio itself) or 63.86 MHz (the frequency at 1.5 T, not 0.5 T).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-102", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "The flip angle achieved by an RF excitation pulse is determined by all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["The RF coil configuration being used", "The amplitude and duration of the RF pulse", "The strength of the static magnetic field", "The receiver bandwidth setting"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Flip angle is determined by the amplitude and duration of the RF pulse, the coil configuration (which affects B1 delivery efficiency), and the static field strength. Receiver bandwidth affects the frequency range sampled during readout but has no role in determining the excitation flip angle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-103", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "Which gradient changes its amplitude with each repetition (TR) to fill successive lines of k-space?", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Shim gradient"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The phase-encoding gradient is applied at a different amplitude for each TR interval, imparting a unique phase shift to fill successive lines of k-space. The frequency-encoding and slice-select gradients maintain consistent amplitude across repetitions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-104", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "During echo sampling (data readout), the gradient that remains active to encode spatial position along one axis is the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Spoiler gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding (readout) gradient remains active during echo sampling, causing protons at different positions along one axis to precess at slightly different frequencies. This frequency variation allows spatial position to be decoded from the sampled signal via Fourier transform.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-105", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "In MRI, k-space represents:", "options": ["The final reconstructed image in spatial domain", "A negative (inverted) version of the MR image", "The raw frequency-domain data from which an MR image is reconstructed", "The storage format used by PACS systems"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "k-space is a matrix of raw data in the spatial frequency domain, not a direct image. Each line contains frequency and phase information that must be converted to a spatial image via Fourier transformation. It is not a negative of the image, nor is it related to PACS storage formats.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-106", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.c", "stem": "An RF coil system that combines multiple independent coil elements, each connected to its own receiver channel, is classified as a:", "options": ["Quadrature coil", "Surface coil", "Linear coil", "Phased array coil"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A phased array coil combines multiple independent coil elements, each connected to its own receiver channel. This design provides extended anatomic coverage while maintaining the high SNR of small surface coils, and enables parallel imaging techniques like GRAPPA and SENSE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-107", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "When a large FOV is selected, small structures within the imaging volume may be averaged together within a single voxel. This effect is known as:", "options": ["Wrap-around artifact", "Fold-over artifact", "Aliasing", "Partial volume averaging"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Partial volume averaging occurs when a voxel contains more than one tissue type, and the signal from each tissue is averaged into a single pixel value. Larger voxels (from large FOV, thick slices, or low matrix) increase partial volume effects. This is distinct from aliasing, which involves spatial mismapping of signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-108", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Signal from anatomy outside a small FOV can fold back into the image. This artifact is described by all of the following terms EXCEPT:", "options": ["Wrap-around", "Fold-over", "Aliasing", "Partial volume averaging"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Wrap-around, fold-over, and aliasing are all terms describing the same artifact: signal from outside the FOV being mismapped to the wrong location in the image. Partial volume averaging is a completely different phenomenon involving the averaging of multiple tissue types within a single voxel.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-109", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Motion-related ghosting artifact propagates as signal replicas across the image in the:", "options": ["Frequency-encoding direction", "Phase-encoding direction", "Slice-selection direction", "Readout direction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Motion-related ghosting propagates along the phase-encoding direction because phase encoding occurs over many TR intervals (the slowest encoding step). Any periodic motion (cardiac, respiratory, vascular pulsation) during this time produces phase errors that manifest as replicated signal ghosts in the phase direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-110", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Aliasing (wrap-around) artifact occurs because anatomy extending beyond the selected FOV is:", "options": ["Undersampled relative to the Nyquist criterion", "Oversampled by the frequency-encoding gradient", "Completely excluded from signal detection", "Positioned too far from the receiver coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Aliasing occurs when the FOV is too small to contain all signal-producing anatomy, violating the Nyquist sampling criterion in the phase-encoding direction. Frequencies exceeding half the sampling rate are misinterpreted as lower frequencies, causing the signal to wrap into the opposite side of the image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-111", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Which of the following strategies can be used to compensate for aliasing artifact?", "options": ["Shortening the overall scan time", "Decreasing the number of signal averages (NSA)", "Reducing the receiver bandwidth", "Enlarging the FOV or applying oversampling in the phase-encoding direction"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Aliasing is corrected by ensuring the FOV fully covers the anatomy (eliminating signal outside the sampled range) or by applying phase oversampling, which doubles the sampling without increasing displayed FOV. Reducing scan time, decreasing NSA, or narrowing receiver bandwidth do not address the spatial undersampling that causes aliasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-112", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact typically appears as:", "options": ["Tissue superimposition resembling aliasing", "A single bright pixel at the image center", "Dark lines at fat-water interfaces (chemical shift)", "Alternating high and low signal intensity bands near sharp contrast boundaries"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact appears as alternating bright and dark lines parallel to high-contrast interfaces (e.g., CSF-cord boundary). It results from the finite number of Fourier harmonics used to represent abrupt signal transitions—the Fourier series rings at sharp edges when truncated.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-113", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "The most effective method to reduce Gibbs (truncation) artifact is to:", "options": ["Decrease the number of phase-encoding steps", "Increase the number of phase-encoding steps (increase matrix)", "Increase the field of view", "Decrease the echo time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the acquisition matrix adds more Fourier harmonics to the reconstruction, more accurately representing sharp tissue boundaries and reducing truncation ringing. Decreasing phase-encoding steps worsens the artifact. FOV and TE changes do not address the fundamental sampling limitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-114", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Chemical shift artifact occurs because:", "options": ["The system undersamples fat and water molecules", "The signal-to-noise ratio is insufficient", "Fat and water protons precess at slightly different frequencies", "The frequency-encoding gradient is applied too quickly"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Fat protons are shielded by surrounding electron clouds and precess at a slightly lower frequency than water protons (~3.5 ppm difference). The frequency-encoding gradient misregisters fat and water signal by a number of pixels proportional to this frequency offset, creating a bright/dark band at fat-water interfaces.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-115", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Chemical shift artifact becomes more conspicuous when the:", "options": ["Transmit bandwidth is widened", "Receiver bandwidth is narrowed", "Receiver bandwidth is widened", "Static magnetic field strength is decreased"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "With a narrower receiver bandwidth, each pixel represents a smaller frequency range (Hz/pixel). Since the fat-water frequency difference is fixed (~220 Hz at 1.5 T), fewer Hz per pixel means the fat signal shifts across more pixels, making chemical shift artifact more conspicuous. Widening the bandwidth reduces the effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-116", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.5", "stem": "Magnetic susceptibility artifact is most prominent when using:", "options": ["Gradient echo (GRE) sequences", "Conventional spin echo (SE) sequences", "Fast spin echo (FSE/TSE) sequences", "Inversion recovery (IR) sequences"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "GRE sequences lack a 180-degree refocusing pulse, so they cannot compensate for dephasing caused by local magnetic field inhomogeneities at tissue interfaces. This makes susceptibility artifact most prominent on GRE images, especially at long TE. Spin echo and FSE sequences use refocusing pulses that partially correct susceptibility-related dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-117", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.5", "stem": "Magnetic susceptibility artifact is least prominent when using:", "options": ["Gradient echo (GRE) sequences", "Conventional spin echo (SE) sequences", "Fast spin echo (FSE/TSE) sequences", "Echo planar imaging (EPI) sequences"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "FSE sequences use multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses per TR (the echo train), which repeatedly rephase susceptibility-induced dephasing. This makes FSE the most resistant sequence to susceptibility artifact. GRE and especially EPI are the most susceptibility-sensitive because they lack refocusing pulses.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-118", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.5", "stem": "Which of the following parameter adjustments helps reduce magnetic susceptibility artifact?", "options": ["Increasing the TR", "Increasing the TE", "Increasing the slice thickness", "Decreasing the TE and using a smaller voxel size"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Shorter TE limits the time available for susceptibility-induced dephasing to accumulate. Smaller voxels reduce the range of field variation within each voxel, decreasing intravoxel dephasing. Increasing TE or slice thickness both worsen susceptibility artifact by amplifying these effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-119", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.6", "stem": "A breach in the radiofrequency shielding of the scan room can produce:", "options": ["A bright spot at the center of the image", "A \"zipper\" artifact oriented along the frequency-encoding direction", "A uniform signal loss across the entire image", "Ghosting along the phase-encoding direction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A breach in the RF shielding (Faraday cage) allows external RF interference to enter the scan room. This extraneous signal is detected at a specific frequency and appears as a discrete line (zipper) in the frequency-encoding direction of the image. The artifact persists until the shielding breach is repaired.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 275"}, {"id": "IP-120", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a recognized technique for reducing flow-related artifact?", "options": ["Applying gradient moment nulling (flow compensation)", "Placing spatial presaturation bands over vessels", "Shortening the echo time", "Increasing the number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Flow compensation (GMN), spatial presaturation bands, and shorter TE are all established techniques for reducing flow artifact. Increasing NSA averages random noise but does not specifically compensate for the phase errors caused by flowing blood, making it ineffective for flow artifact reduction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-121", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Decreasing voxel volume (by increasing matrix or reducing slice thickness) leads to a decrease in:", "options": ["Aliasing artifact only", "Ghosting artifact only", "Signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) only", "Both chemical shift artifact and partial volume averaging"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Smaller voxels reduce partial volume averaging (less tissue averaging per voxel) and can reduce chemical shift artifact (smaller pixel size at a given bandwidth means fewer pixels of fat-water displacement). However, smaller voxels also decrease SNR because less signal-producing tissue is sampled per voxel.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-122", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "If the field of view (FOV) is increased while the matrix size remains constant, partial volume averaging will:", "options": ["Increase (larger voxels average more tissue)", "Decrease", "Remain unchanged", "Not be affected by FOV changes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "If FOV increases while matrix stays constant, each pixel covers a larger area and each voxel contains more tissue volume. More tissue types may be averaged within a single voxel, increasing partial volume effects and reducing the ability to resolve small structures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-123", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "If slice thickness is increased while all other parameters remain constant, partial volume averaging will:", "options": ["Increase (larger voxel volume averages more tissue types)", "Decrease", "Remain unchanged", "Not be affected by slice thickness changes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Thicker slices increase voxel volume in the through-plane direction, making it more likely that multiple tissue types will be included in a single voxel. This increases partial volume averaging and can obscure small lesions or thin anatomic structures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-124", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "If the acquisition matrix is increased while FOV and slice thickness remain constant, partial volume averaging will:", "options": ["Increase", "Decrease (smaller voxels resolve finer detail)", "Remain unchanged", "Not be affected by matrix changes"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the acquisition matrix while holding FOV and slice thickness constant reduces in-plane pixel dimensions, creating smaller voxels. Smaller voxels are less likely to contain mixed tissue types, reducing partial volume averaging and improving spatial resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-125", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "If the repetition time (TR) is increased while all spatial parameters remain constant, partial volume averaging will:", "options": ["Increase", "Decrease", "Change unpredictably", "Not be affected (TR does not influence voxel dimensions)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "TR controls the time between successive excitations and affects T1 contrast weighting and scan time, but it has no effect on voxel dimensions (FOV, matrix, and slice thickness). Since partial volume averaging depends entirely on voxel size, changing TR alone does not alter partial volume effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-126", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT an effective technique for reducing respiratory motion artifact?", "options": ["Respiratory gating", "Respiratory triggering", "Increasing the number of signal averages (NSA)", "Widening the receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Respiratory gating, triggering, and increasing NSA (which averages out random motion effects) all help reduce respiratory motion artifact. Widening receiver bandwidth affects chemical shift artifact and SNR but does not compensate for the phase errors caused by respiratory motion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-127", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Respiratory motion during an MRI examination is classified as:", "options": ["Periodic motion", "Aperiodic motion", "Random motion", "Involuntary motion"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Respiratory motion follows a regular, cyclical pattern (inspiration-expiration), making it periodic. Periodic motion produces discrete ghost images along the phase-encoding direction at predictable intervals. Aperiodic motion produces diffuse blurring rather than discrete ghosts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-128", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Cardiac motion during an MRI examination is classified as:", "options": ["Periodic motion", "Aperiodic motion", "Random motion", "Involuntary motion"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Cardiac motion is periodic because the heart contracts in a regular, repeating cycle. Like respiratory motion, cardiac pulsation produces discrete ghosting artifacts in the phase-encoding direction. ECG gating and triggering are used to synchronize data acquisition to the cardiac cycle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-129", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Unpredictable patient movement (e.g., shifting position on the table) during an MRI scan is classified as:", "options": ["Periodic motion", "Aperiodic motion", "Pulsatile motion", "Physiologic motion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Unpredictable patient movement (shifting, coughing, swallowing) has no regular timing pattern, classifying it as aperiodic motion. Aperiodic motion produces diffuse image blurring and smearing rather than the discrete ghost artifacts seen with periodic motion. Gating techniques are ineffective against aperiodic motion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-130", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Peristaltic motion of the bowel during an abdominal MRI is classified as:", "options": ["Periodic motion", "Aperiodic motion", "Pulsatile motion", "Cardiac-gated motion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Bowel peristalsis is irregular and unpredictable in timing, making it aperiodic. Unlike cardiac or respiratory motion, peristalsis cannot be effectively gated because it lacks a consistent cyclical pattern. Strategies like glucagon administration or shorter scan times are used instead.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-131", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "A technologist reduces slice thickness by half. To restore the original SNR (all other parameters unchanged), the number of signal averages (NSA) must be increased by a factor of:", "options": ["8", "2", "4", "1.41"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "SNR is directly proportional to slice thickness and proportional to the square root of NSA. Halving slice thickness halves the SNR. To restore the original SNR, NSA must increase by a factor of 4 (since SNR scales with sqrt-NSA: sqrt-4 = 2, compensating for the 2x loss from halving thickness).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-132", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Doubling the slice thickness from 5 mm to 10 mm (all other parameters unchanged) will change the SNR by:", "options": ["Increasing by a factor of √2 (1.41)", "Increasing by a factor of 2", "Decreasing by a factor of 2", "Decreasing by a factor of √2 (1.41)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SNR is directly proportional to slice thickness (linear relationship). Doubling slice thickness from 5 mm to 10 mm doubles the voxel volume in the through-plane direction, doubling the amount of signal-producing tissue per voxel and thus doubling the SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-133", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Increasing slice thickness (all other parameters unchanged) will cause the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) to:", "options": ["Increase", "Decrease", "Remain unchanged", "Fluctuate unpredictably"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Thicker slices contain more hydrogen protons per voxel, producing more MR signal. Since noise remains relatively constant, the increased signal raises the SNR. This is a direct, linear relationship—doubling slice thickness approximately doubles SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-134", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Increasing slice thickness (all other parameters unchanged) will cause spatial resolution to:", "options": ["Increase", "Decrease (larger voxels average more tissue in the slice direction)", "Remain unchanged", "Not be affected by slice thickness"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spatial resolution depends on voxel size—smaller voxels resolve finer detail. Increasing slice thickness enlarges the voxel in the through-plane direction, averaging more tissue per voxel and reducing the ability to distinguish small structures. This is the classic SNR vs. resolution trade-off.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-135", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Altering the voxel dimension in the frequency-encoding direction (by changing the frequency matrix or FOV) will affect scan time by:", "options": ["Doubling the scan time", "Decreasing the scan time", "Having no effect on scan time", "Increasing the scan time by a factor of 1.5"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Scan time in conventional imaging is determined by TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA. Changes to the frequency matrix or FOV in the frequency direction alter voxel size and SNR but do not change the number of TRs required, so scan time is unaffected.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-136", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "All of the following parameters directly influence image contrast EXCEPT:", "options": ["Repetition time (TR)", "Echo time (TE)", "Flip angle", "Acquisition matrix size"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Image contrast is primarily determined by TR (T1 weighting), TE (T2 weighting), and flip angle. Matrix size affects spatial resolution and SNR but does not directly influence the T1, T2, or proton density contrast between tissues.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-137", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) in MRI is:", "options": ["A quantitative metric that can be directly measured from an image", "A qualitative assessment that can only be estimated visually", "A calculated value that requires knowledge of T1 and T2 times", "A parameter set by the technologist before scanning"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SNR can be measured directly from an MR image by dividing the mean signal intensity in a tissue region of interest by the standard deviation of signal in a background (noise-only) region. This quantitative measurement is essential for quality control testing and protocol optimization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-138", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "Contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR) in MRI is:", "options": ["Directly measured from a single tissue region on the image", "A calculated value derived from the SNR difference between two tissues", "A parameter that is preset on the scanner console", "Determined solely by the magnetic field strength"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "CNR is calculated by subtracting the SNR of one tissue from the SNR of another (or equivalently, the signal difference divided by noise). It quantifies how well two adjacent tissues can be distinguished and is influenced by both intrinsic tissue properties and imaging parameters.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-139", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "All of the following parameters directly affect spatial resolution EXCEPT:", "options": ["Field of view (FOV)", "Slice thickness", "Flip angle", "Acquisition matrix size"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Spatial resolution is determined by voxel dimensions: FOV, matrix size, and slice thickness. Flip angle influences image contrast and SNR but does not change the physical size of the voxels, so it has no direct effect on spatial resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-140", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "All of the following parameters directly affect the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) EXCEPT:", "options": ["Repetition time (TR)", "Static magnetic field strength", "Field of view (FOV)", "Time of day the scan is performed"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "SNR is influenced by field strength (stronger field = more signal), FOV (larger FOV = larger voxels = more signal), TR (longer TR = more longitudinal recovery), and many other scan parameters. The time of day has no effect on the physics of signal generation or noise levels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-141", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.5", "stem": "The center frequency calibration on an MRI system determines:", "options": ["Only the frequency of the RF excitation pulse", "Only the frequency used for signal reception", "The amplitude and duration of the RF pulse", "The frequency of RF used for both excitation and signal detection"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Center frequency calibration (performed during prescan) determines the precise Larmor frequency for the specific patient in the magnet. This frequency is used for both the RF excitation pulse and the receiver tuning, ensuring accurate resonance and proper signal detection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-142", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.6", "stem": "The transmit gain (or transmit attenuation) calibration on an MRI system determines:", "options": ["The frequency of the RF excitation pulse", "The frequency used for signal reception", "The static magnetic field homogeneity", "The amplitude and/or duration of the RF pulse (which controls flip angle)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Transmit gain (or transmit attenuation) calibration adjusts the power of the RF pulse to achieve the prescribed flip angle for a specific patient. Patient size, body composition, and coil loading all affect how much RF power is needed. This calibration occurs during prescan.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-143", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.7", "stem": "The accuracy of spatial measurements (geometric accuracy) on an MR image is primarily determined by the performance of the:", "options": ["Radiofrequency system", "Shim coil system", "Gradient coil system", "Superconducting magnet"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Geometric accuracy—how faithfully spatial dimensions in the image correspond to actual anatomy—depends primarily on gradient linearity and calibration. Nonlinear gradients cause spatial distortion (objects appear stretched or compressed). Gradient QC testing verifies that measured distances match known phantom dimensions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-144", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.8", "stem": "Prior to performing an MRI examination, which components should be inspected to ensure proper function?", "options": ["RF coils only", "Cables and connectors only", "RF door seal only", "RF coils, cables, connectors, and RF door seals should all be inspected"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A thorough pre-scan equipment inspection includes checking RF coils for damage, cables and connectors for wear or breaks, and the RF door seal for gaps that could compromise shielding. Failure in any component can cause artifacts, signal loss, or safety issues. Inspecting only one component is insufficient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-145", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Halving the slice thickness (all other parameters unchanged) will reduce the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) by a factor of:", "options": ["2", "√2 (1.41)", "4", "√2/2 (0.71)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SNR is directly proportional to slice thickness (linear relationship). Halving the slice thickness halves the voxel volume in the through-plane direction, reducing the number of signal-producing protons per voxel by half and thus reducing SNR by a factor of 2.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-146", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.c", "stem": "The two recognized methods for shimming the main magnetic field of an MRI system are:", "options": ["Retroactive shimming and active shimming", "Active shimming and gradient shimming", "Passive shimming and retroactive shimming", "Active shimming and passive shimming"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The two recognized shimming methods are active shimming (adjusting current through dedicated shim coils) and passive shimming (placing ferromagnetic metal plates at specific locations). Retroactive shimming and gradient shimming are not standard terminology for the two primary shimming categories.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-147", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.c", "stem": "The primary purpose of shimming an MRI magnet is to:", "options": ["Maximize B1 field homogeneity", "Maximize B0 (static magnetic) field homogeneity", "Reduce overall scan acquisition time", "Compensate for gradient coil nonlinearity"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Shimming corrects spatial variations in the static magnetic field (B0) to achieve the most uniform field possible across the imaging volume. Good B0 homogeneity is essential for accurate frequency encoding, effective fat suppression, and minimizing susceptibility artifacts. B1 homogeneity is a separate concern related to RF coil design.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-148", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.8", "stem": "The smallest discrete unit of a two-dimensional digital MR image is known as a:", "options": ["Voxel", "Matrix element", "Pixel (picture element)", "Data point"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A pixel is the smallest discrete unit of a two-dimensional digital image, representing a single point of signal intensity. A voxel extends the pixel concept into three dimensions by incorporating slice thickness. The acquisition matrix defines the total number of pixels in the image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-149", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "The field of view (FOV) in an MR image is subdivided into discrete units called:", "options": ["Encoding zones", "Pixels", "Frequency codes", "Data spaces"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The field of view is divided into a grid of pixels determined by the acquisition matrix. For example, a 256 x 256 matrix divides the FOV into 65,536 individual pixels, each representing a small area of anatomy whose signal intensity is displayed as a shade of gray.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-150", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "The imaging parameter that defines the total area of anatomy displayed in a single MR image is the:", "options": ["Acquisition matrix", "Field of view (FOV)", "Number of phase-encoding steps", "Slice thickness"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The FOV defines the total anatomic area covered by the image, measured in centimeters or millimeters. It is selected by the technologist based on the anatomy of interest. The matrix subdivides the FOV into pixels, and slice thickness extends into the third dimension, but neither defines the total area displayed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-151", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "Which logical gradient is responsible for encoding spatial position along the short axis of the anatomy?", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Radiofrequency (B1) field"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "By convention, the phase-encoding gradient is assigned to the shorter anatomical dimension to minimize the number of phase-encoding steps required, reducing scan time. The frequency-encoding gradient is assigned to the longer dimension because additional frequency samples do not add scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-152", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The mathematical process that converts raw k-space data into a viewable MR image is known as the:", "options": ["Larmor equation", "Fast Fourier Transform (FFT)", "Bloch equation", "Faraday's law of induction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The FFT is the mathematical algorithm that converts raw frequency-domain data stored in k-space into a spatial-domain image. It decodes the frequency and phase information from each line of k-space into pixel-by-pixel signal intensities. The Larmor equation relates frequency to field strength, and Faraday's law describes signal induction—neither performs image reconstruction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-153", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "To produce a large phase difference between adjacent voxels, the phase-encoding gradient must have a:", "options": ["Shallow (low amplitude) slope", "Steep (high amplitude) slope", "Zero amplitude (no gradient applied)", "Reversed polarity slope"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A steeper (higher amplitude) phase-encoding gradient creates a greater range of phase shifts across the imaging volume, producing larger phase differences between adjacent voxels. This corresponds to filling the outer lines of k-space, which encode fine spatial detail. A shallow gradient fills central k-space lines (bulk contrast information).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-154", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "If a 512 × 512 acquisition matrix is selected, the minimum number of phase-encoding steps (lines of k-space) required is:", "options": ["128", "256", "512", "1024"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a 512 x 512 matrix, 512 unique phase-encoding steps are required to fill 512 lines of k-space (one line per TR). The phase matrix dimension directly determines the number of k-space lines. Partial Fourier techniques can reduce this, but the minimum without acceleration equals the phase matrix.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-155", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "If a 256 × 256 acquisition matrix is selected, the minimum number of lines of k-space that must be filled is:", "options": ["128", "256", "512", "1024"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A 256 x 256 matrix requires 256 phase-encoding steps, each filling one line of k-space. The number of k-space lines equals the phase matrix dimension. The frequency matrix determines data points sampled along each line but does not affect the number of lines.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-156", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "The total number of lines filled in k-space during an acquisition is determined by the number of:", "options": ["Slice-select gradient applications", "Phase-encoding steps", "Frequency-encoding samples per readout", "Signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Each phase-encoding step fills one line of k-space. The total number of k-space lines equals the number of phase-encoding steps selected (the phase matrix dimension). Frequency-encoding samples determine data points per line, and slice-select gradient applications determine the number of slices—neither controls the number of k-space lines.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-157", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "To fill successive lines of k-space, the amplitude of the phase-encoding gradient is incremented with each:", "options": ["Echo time (TE)", "Signal average", "Repetition time (TR)", "Slice acquisition"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The phase-encoding gradient amplitude changes with each TR to fill a different line of k-space. After one complete set of phase-encoding steps (one per TR), k-space is fully populated and the image can be reconstructed. This is why scan time = TR x phase steps x NSA.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-158", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "The specific line of k-space filled during each TR is determined by the amplitude of the:", "options": ["Slice-select gradient", "Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Shim gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The amplitude of the phase-encoding gradient applied during each TR determines which line of k-space is filled. Maximum positive amplitude fills the outermost line, zero amplitude fills the center line, and maximum negative amplitude fills the opposite outermost line. The frequency-encoding and slice-select gradients maintain fixed amplitudes across TRs.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-159", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The slope of the frequency-encoding gradient — and therefore the range of frequency shifts across the image — is determined by the:", "options": ["Acquisition matrix size", "Slice thickness", "Field of view (FOV)", "Repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The slope of the frequency-encoding gradient is set to spread the total receiver bandwidth across the selected FOV. A smaller FOV requires a steeper gradient to create the same frequency range over a shorter distance, while a larger FOV uses a shallower gradient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-160", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The magnitude of the frequency shift imposed on spins at different positions along the readout direction is determined by the:", "options": ["Amplitude of the phase-encoding gradient", "Amplitude of the frequency-encoding gradient", "Amplitude of the slice-select gradient", "Size of the acquisition matrix"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding gradient creates a linear variation in magnetic field strength along the readout direction. The amplitude of this gradient determines how much the precessional frequency differs between positions—steeper gradients create larger frequency differences per unit distance, enabling finer spatial discrimination.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-161", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "During each repetition time (TR), the MR signal from every excited slice undergoes:", "options": ["Only frequency encoding", "Both phase and frequency encoding", "Only phase encoding", "Slice selection without spatial encoding"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "During each TR, every excited slice undergoes both phase encoding (applied before readout) and frequency encoding (applied during readout). Phase encoding assigns a unique phase shift to fill one k-space line, while frequency encoding maps spatial position to frequency along the readout direction. Both are required for complete 2D spatial localization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 152"}, {"id": "IP-162", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "In the standard k-space diagram, the frequency-encoding axis is oriented:", "options": ["Horizontally, running through the center", "Vertically, along the outer edges", "Vertically, through the center and perpendicular to the phase-encoding lines", "Horizontally, along the outer edges"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In the standard k-space diagram, the frequency-encoding axis runs vertically through the center, perpendicular to the horizontally oriented phase-encoding lines. Each horizontal line represents the frequency data collected during one phase-encoding step, and the frequency axis tracks data points within each line from top to bottom of k-space.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-163", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "In the standard k-space diagram, the phase-encoding axis is oriented:", "options": ["Horizontally, with lines running through the center", "Vertically, along the outer edges", "Vertically, through the center", "Horizontally, along the outer edges"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The phase-encoding axis in k-space runs horizontally, with each line representing the data acquired during one unique phase-encoding step. The center lines (acquired with the lowest phase gradient amplitudes) contain the bulk contrast information, while the outer lines encode fine spatial detail.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-164", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "Spatially encoded MR signal data is stored in a temporary data matrix known as:", "options": ["Image space", "K-space (raw data space)", "Frequency cycles", "Phase maps"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "K-space is the temporary data matrix where spatially encoded MR signal data is stored before image reconstruction. It contains frequency-domain information that requires Fourier transformation to produce a viewable image. Image space is the result after FFT, not the storage format for raw data.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-165", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In standard orthogonal imaging, spatial encoding along the shorter anatomical dimension is performed by the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Spoiler gradient"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Phase encoding is conventionally assigned to the shorter anatomical axis to minimize the number of phase-encoding steps and thus reduce scan time. Since each phase-encoding step requires one TR, fewer steps along the short axis means fewer TRs and a shorter total acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-166", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "In standard orthogonal imaging, spatial encoding along the longer anatomical dimension is performed by the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Shim gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Frequency encoding is assigned to the longer anatomical axis because adding more frequency samples does not increase scan time—they are all collected during a single readout period within each TR. This allows high resolution along the long axis without a time penalty.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-167", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "The gradient responsible for exciting a specific slice of tissue at the prescribed location is the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Readout gradient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The slice-select gradient creates a linear field variation across the imaging volume so that only protons at a specific location precess at the exact Larmor frequency of the RF pulse. This selective excitation confines signal to a defined slice of tissue at the prescribed location.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-168", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) MRI system, which physical gradient axis is used for frequency encoding in both sagittal and coronal acquisitions?", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In both sagittal and coronal acquisitions, the long anatomical axis runs superior-to-inferior (head-to-foot). Since frequency encoding is assigned to the long axis by convention, the Z gradient (along the bore) performs frequency encoding for both planes. The X or Y gradient handles slice selection depending on the plane.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-169", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis used for frequency encoding during an axial head acquisition (with frequency set anterior-posterior) is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When frequency encoding is set anterior-posterior for an axial head acquisition, the Y gradient (which varies the field along the AP axis) performs the readout. This assignment means the phase-encoding gradient must be X (left-right), directing motion ghosts in the L-R direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-170", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis used for frequency encoding during an axial body acquisition (with frequency set left-right) is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When frequency encoding is set left-right for an axial body acquisition, the X gradient performs the readout. With frequency assigned to L-R, phase encoding runs A-P (Y gradient), which may place respiratory ghosting in the AP direction over the anatomy of interest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-171", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis used for phase encoding during axial head (phase left-right) or coronal (phase left-right) acquisitions is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When phase encoding is assigned to the left-right direction (as in axial head with phase L-R, or coronal with phase L-R), the X gradient performs phase encoding. This assignment is chosen to redirect flow or motion ghosts away from the anatomy of interest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-172", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis used for phase encoding during sagittal (phase anterior-posterior) or axial body (phase anterior-posterior) acquisitions is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When phase encoding is set anterior-posterior (as in sagittal with phase AP, or axial body with phase AP), the Y gradient performs phase encoding. The AP phase direction is standard for abdominal imaging where the shorter anatomic dimension runs front-to-back.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-173", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis activated for coronal slice selection is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Coronal slices separate anatomy in the anterior-posterior direction. In a horizontal bore system, the Y gradient varies the field along the AP axis, so it selects coronal slices when activated simultaneously with a frequency-selective RF pulse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-174", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis activated for axial slice selection (head or body) is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Axial slices separate anatomy in the superior-inferior direction. The Z gradient (along the bore axis) varies the field along this axis, selecting specific axial slice locations when combined with a frequency-selective RF pulse. This applies to both head and body axial imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-175", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) system, the physical gradient axis activated for sagittal slice selection is the:", "options": ["X gradient (left-right)", "Y gradient (anterior-posterior)", "Z gradient (superior-inferior)", "Isocenter reference point"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Sagittal slices separate anatomy in the left-right direction. The X gradient varies the field along the L-R axis in a horizontal bore system. When activated with a frequency-selective RF pulse, it excites only protons within a specific sagittal slice location.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-176", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.4", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence is programmed with a short TR, long TE, and small flip angle. What type of image weighting will result?", "options": ["T1 weighted", "T2 weighted", "Proton density weighted", "T2* weighted"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In GRE sequences, long TE allows T2* dephasing to accumulate, and a small flip angle minimizes T1 contrast, producing T2* weighting. Unlike spin echo, GRE has no 180-degree refocusing pulse, so the echo contains T2* (not pure T2) decay. Short TR maintains the steady state.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-177", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "When performing a gradient echo acquisition with a relatively short TR, short TE, and small flip angle, which type of image contrast is produced?", "options": ["T1 weighted", "T2* weighted", "Proton density weighted", "T2 weighted"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A small flip angle in GRE minimizes T1 saturation effects (reducing T1 contrast), and short TE minimizes T2* decay (reducing T2* contrast). With both T1 and T2* contrast minimized, signal intensity primarily reflects the proton density of each tissue.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-178", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A technologist selects a short TR, short TE, and large flip angle for a gradient echo sequence. What image weighting will this combination produce?", "options": ["T1 weighted", "T2* weighted", "Proton density weighted", "T2 weighted"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A large flip angle combined with short TR creates T1 saturation differences between tissues (short T1 tissues recover more signal between pulses). Short TE minimizes T2* effects. This combination produces T1-weighted contrast in gradient echo imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-179", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which parameters primarily determine the degree of T2* weighting in a gradient echo sequence?", "options": ["FOV and matrix", "TE and flip angle", "TR and TE", "TR and flip angle"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In GRE sequences, TE controls how much T2* dephasing accumulates (longer TE = more T2* weighting), and flip angle determines the degree of T1 saturation. Together, these two parameters primarily control the balance between T1 and T2* contrast in the image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-180", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "Which of the following is a recognized limitation of gradient echo sequences compared to spin echo sequences?", "options": ["Longer acquisition times", "Requirement for large fields of view", "Lack of compensation for magnetic field inhomogeneities", "Requirement for very long echo times"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "GRE sequences form echoes by gradient reversal rather than a 180-degree RF refocusing pulse. This means field inhomogeneity effects (T2-prime) are not corrected, resulting in greater susceptibility artifact and signal loss near metal or air-tissue interfaces compared to spin echo sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-181", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "Compared to conventional spin echo sequences, how is the scan time typically affected when using gradient echo sequences?", "options": ["Scan time is shorter", "Scan time is longer", "Scan time remains unchanged", "Scan time depends solely on the number of slices"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "GRE sequences can use very short TR values (often under 50 ms) because they employ small flip angles that leave substantial longitudinal magnetization, eliminating the need for long recovery periods. This dramatically reduces scan time compared to conventional SE sequences that require TR values of several hundred milliseconds or more.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-182", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "How do the TR and TE values in a gradient echo sequence typically compare to those used in a conventional spin echo sequence?", "options": ["Both TR and TE can be significantly shorter", "Both TR and TE are typically longer", "TR is shorter but TE must remain the same", "TR and TE values are equivalent between the two sequences"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "GRE sequences achieve shorter TR by using small flip angles and shorter TE by eliminating the 180-degree refocusing pulse. The gradient reversal that forms the GRE echo is faster than waiting for an RF refocusing pulse, enabling minimum TE values well below those achievable with SE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-183", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "When hydrogen protons experience a stronger magnetic field, what happens to their precessional frequency?", "options": ["It increases", "It decreases", "It remains unchanged", "It oscillates unpredictably"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Per the Larmor equation, precessional frequency is directly proportional to magnetic field strength. A stronger B0 field increases the energy difference between parallel and antiparallel states, causing protons to precess faster. This is why the Larmor frequency at 3 T (127.7 MHz) is double that at 1.5 T (63.9 MHz).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-184", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "When a gradient is applied along the bore (z-axis) of the magnet, the magnetic field strength varies along the gradient axis in which manner?", "options": ["Exponential", "Linear", "Logarithmic", "Inversely proportional"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient coils are designed to produce a linear variation in magnetic field strength along their axis. This linearity is essential for accurate spatial encoding—if the field varied nonlinearly, the frequency-to-position mapping would be distorted, producing geometric inaccuracies in the reconstructed image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 129"}, {"id": "IP-185", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "The precise geometric center of the magnet bore, where the magnetic field is most homogeneous, is known as the:", "options": ["Z-axis origin", "Gradient null point", "Fringe field boundary", "Isocenter"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The isocenter is the precise geometric center of the magnet bore where B0 is most homogeneous and all three gradient axes intersect at zero amplitude. Patient anatomy is positioned at isocenter for optimal image quality, field uniformity, and gradient linearity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-186", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "The rated field strength of a superconducting MRI system (such as 1.5 T or 3.0 T) is specified at which location?", "options": ["The bore entrance", "The far end of the bore", "The center of the bore along the magnet axis", "Uniformly along the entire length of the bore"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The rated field strength (1.5 T, 3.0 T, etc.) is specified at isocenter—the geometric center of the bore along the magnet axis—where the field is most uniform. Field strength decreases with distance from isocenter in all directions, which is why patient positioning at isocenter is critical.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-187", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Magnetic field gradients used for spatial encoding in MRI are produced by:", "options": ["Coils of wire positioned within the bore of the magnet", "Radiofrequency pulses delivered at specific intervals", "Surface coils placed on the patient", "Coils of wire located outside the bore of the magnet"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient coils are sets of wire coils mounted inside the magnet bore (between the main magnet and the patient). When current flows through them, they produce controlled linear magnetic field variations. They are distinct from RF coils and are located inside, not outside, the bore.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-188", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "In spin echo imaging, how is the signal loss from dephasing caused by magnetic field inhomogeneities corrected?", "options": ["Increasing the field of view", "Decreasing the field of view", "Applying a 180-degree refocusing RF pulse", "Reducing the acquisition matrix"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In spin echo imaging, a 180-degree RF pulse is applied after excitation to rephase proton spins that have dephased due to static field inhomogeneities (T2-prime effects). This refocusing produces an echo with only true T2 decay, eliminating the reversible component of signal loss. Changing FOV or matrix does not address dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-189", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "How does the rate of T2* decay compare to T2 decay?", "options": ["T2* decay is slower than T2 decay", "T2* decay is faster than T2 decay", "T2* and T2 decay occur at the same rate", "The comparison depends on the pulse sequence used"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T2* includes both intrinsic T2 relaxation and additional dephasing from field inhomogeneities (T2-prime). Since T2-prime adds to the decay rate, T2* is always shorter (faster decay) than T2. The relationship is: 1/T2* = 1/T2 + 1/T2-prime.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-190", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Which of the following is an example of a patient-dependent or tissue-dependent artifact?", "options": ["Metallic susceptibility artifact", "Gibbs ringing", "Truncation artifact", "Aliasing"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Magnetic susceptibility artifact depends on the magnetic properties of the patient's tissues and any implanted or retained materials, making it patient-dependent. Gibbs ringing, truncation, and aliasing are all system- or parameter-dependent artifacts that occur regardless of patient tissue composition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-191", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.12", "stem": "In parallel imaging techniques such as SENSE, a characteristic artifact pattern may appear as a non-uniform distribution of image noise, predominantly affecting the center of the image. This artifact is commonly referred to as:", "options": ["Zipper artifact", "Starry-sky (salt-and-pepper) artifact", "Moiré pattern", "Gibbs ringing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In parallel imaging techniques like SENSE, undersampling of k-space combined with coil sensitivity map inaccuracies can produce spatially non-uniform noise amplification, creating a salt-and-pepper or starry-sky appearance centrally. This artifact worsens at higher acceleration factors where more k-space lines are skipped.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-192", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.10", "stem": "An artifact caused by contamination of the MR signal with transient signal from tissues located outside the intended imaging slice is called:", "options": ["Cross-excitation", "Gibbs ringing", "Aliasing", "Zipper artifact"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Cross-excitation occurs when RF pulses intended for one slice inadvertently excite protons in adjacent slices due to imperfect slice profiles. This contaminates the signal with information from neighboring tissue, reducing contrast. Interleaving slice acquisition order and adding gaps between slices help reduce cross-excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-193", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "An artifact that appears as slightly curved, concentric lines of alternating high and low signal intensity near sharp tissue boundaries is known as:", "options": ["Cross-talk", "Truncation (Gibbs) artifact", "Aliasing", "Partial volume averaging"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Truncation artifact appears as concentric alternating bright and dark lines near sharp high-contrast tissue boundaries (e.g., CSF-spinal cord). It results from the finite number of data points used in Fourier reconstruction—the abrupt signal transition cannot be perfectly represented with a limited number of harmonics.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-194", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.9", "stem": "Which artifact results from the partial excitation of adjacent tissue slices during simultaneous multislice acquisition?", "options": ["Cross-talk", "Truncation", "Aliasing", "Partial volume averaging"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Cross-talk occurs during simultaneous multislice acquisition when the imperfect RF pulse profile partially excites tissue in neighboring slices, saturating those spins and reducing their signal on subsequent excitations. Interleaving slice order and using slice gaps are standard strategies to minimize cross-talk.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-195", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "When a structure is equal to or smaller than the voxel dimensions, which artifact is most likely to occur?", "options": ["Wrap-around", "Truncation", "Chemical shift", "Partial volume averaging"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "When a structure is equal to or smaller than the voxel dimensions, its signal is averaged with surrounding tissues within the same voxel, potentially obscuring or misrepresenting the structure. This is partial volume averaging—the fundamental spatial resolution limitation in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-196", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Which of the following is an effective method for correcting aliasing artifact?", "options": ["Restraining the patient to prevent motion", "Improving RF shielding of the scan room", "Increasing the field of view", "Widening the receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing the FOV ensures that all signal-producing anatomy falls within the sampled area, eliminating the undersampling that causes aliasing. Restraining the patient addresses motion artifact, RF shielding fixes zipper artifact, and widening bandwidth affects chemical shift and SNR but not aliasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-197", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "What is the primary cause of aliasing (wrap-around) artifact in MRI?", "options": ["Patient movement during acquisition", "RF energy leaking into the scan room", "Differences in chemical composition of adjacent tissues", "Undersampling of the anatomy within the field of view"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Aliasing occurs when the selected FOV is smaller than the anatomy producing signal, causing frequencies from outside the FOV to be sampled below the Nyquist rate. These undersampled frequencies are misinterpreted and mapped to incorrect positions, wrapping signal from one side of the image to the other.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-198", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Aliasing artifact is most likely to occur when:", "options": ["A fat-water interface is present", "The selected field of view does not fully encompass the anatomy being imaged", "The patient moves during the scan", "There is a breach in the RF shielding"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Aliasing is directly caused by the FOV being too small for the anatomy. Signal from tissue outside the FOV still reaches the receiver coil and is detected, but it is spatially misencoded and wrapped into the opposite side of the image. Fat-water interfaces cause chemical shift artifact, not aliasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-199", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Which of the following quality control tests is classified as a magnetic resonance measurement?", "options": ["Signal-to-noise ratio", "RF pulse profile assessment", "Gradient pulse shape verification", "Flip angle accuracy"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Flip angle accuracy is classified as a magnetic resonance measurement because it evaluates the RF system's ability to produce the prescribed excitation angle—a fundamental MR physics parameter. SNR measurement, while using MR images, is classified as a general imaging measurement that assesses overall system performance.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-200", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.7", "stem": "Which of the following quality control tests is classified as a general imaging measurement?", "options": ["Signal-to-noise ratio", "RF pulse profile assessment", "Gradient pulse shape verification", "Flip angle accuracy"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SNR measurement is classified as a general imaging measurement because it evaluates overall image quality rather than a specific MR physics component. It reflects the combined performance of the magnet, gradients, RF system, and receiver electronics. RF pulse profile and gradient pulse shape are classified as MR-specific measurements.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-201", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a recognized category of quality assurance testing for an MRI system?", "options": ["General imaging measurements", "Electronic measurements", "Magnetic resonance measurements", "Focal spot size testing"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "MRI QA testing includes general imaging measurements (SNR, uniformity), electronic measurements (system performance), and magnetic resonance measurements (relaxation times, spectral quality). Focal spot size testing is an X-ray tube QC measure used in radiography and fluoroscopy, not MRI. A student might confuse electronic measurements as non-MRI, but these are standard scanner hardware tests.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-202", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Errors in data processing hardware are most likely to produce which type of image artifact?", "options": ["Intermittent signal flickering", "Herringbone (corduroy) pattern", "Focal signal void", "Wrap-around of anatomy"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Herringbone (corduroy) artifact results from errors in data processing hardware or the reconstruction algorithm, producing a characteristic crisscross pattern when individual k-space data points are corrupted. Intermittent signal flickering suggests RF interference, not hardware processing errors.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-203", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.8", "stem": "When an image quality problem is identified during an MRI examination, the most important immediate action is to:", "options": ["Preserve the raw (k-space) data from the affected scan", "Save multiple images at different window and level settings", "Perform an emergency ramp-down of the magnet", "Power cycle the scanner and repeat the sequence"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Preserving raw (k-space) data is critical when an image quality problem occurs because it allows retrospective analysis and reprocessing to diagnose the cause. Once raw data is overwritten by subsequent acquisitions, the opportunity to troubleshoot is lost. Saving images at different window/level settings preserves display information but not the underlying diagnostic data.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-204", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "How does increasing gradient strength affect the acoustic noise generated during an MRI scan?", "options": ["Acoustic noise decreases", "Acoustic noise increases", "Acoustic noise is unaffected by gradient strength", "Acoustic noise increases only at field strengths above 1.5 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient coils produce acoustic noise because rapid current switching in the static magnetic field causes Lorentz forces that vibrate coil windings. Stronger gradients require larger current amplitudes, producing greater forces and louder noise. The claim that noise is unaffected contradicts the direct relationship between current amplitude and Lorentz force.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-205", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "What potential imaging consequence can result from the mechanical vibrations produced by strong gradient pulses?", "options": ["Chemical shift artifact", "Aliasing artifact", "Motion artifact", "Susceptibility artifact"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Rapid gradient switching generates mechanical vibrations that can physically vibrate the patient, table, or coil hardware, introducing motion during data acquisition that results in motion artifact (ghosting or blurring). Chemical shift artifact is caused by the fat-water frequency difference, not mechanical vibration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330; Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-206", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "On modern high-performance clinical MRI systems, the maximum gradient amplitude is approximately:", "options": ["20 mT/m", "40 mT/m", "60 mT/m", "80 mT/m"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Modern high-performance clinical MRI systems achieve maximum gradient amplitudes of approximately 80 mT/m, with some systems reaching even higher values. These high gradient strengths enable faster imaging, thinner slices, and higher spatial resolution. Older systems typically operated at 20-40 mT/m.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-207", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "If the field of view is reduced from 24 cm to 12 cm while maintaining the same matrix size and all other parameters, what happens to the signal-to-noise ratio?", "options": ["SNR decreases to one-quarter of its original value", "SNR decreases to one-half of its original value", "SNR doubles", "SNR increases by a factor of four"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SNR is proportional to FOV squared when matrix size is held constant, because halving the FOV reduces pixel area by a factor of 4 (half in each dimension), reducing voxel volume to one-quarter. A common misconception is that halving FOV halves SNR, but this ignores the two-dimensional nature of the pixel area reduction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-208", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "When spatial resolution is improved by reducing the voxel volume, what is the expected effect on the signal-to-noise ratio?", "options": ["SNR increases", "SNR decreases", "SNR is unaffected", "SNR improves only if NEX is simultaneously increased"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Reducing voxel volume to improve spatial resolution means fewer hydrogen protons contribute signal per voxel, directly reducing SNR. This is a fundamental trade-off in MRI: higher resolution requires smaller voxels with less signal. The misconception that SNR increases with better resolution confuses image sharpness with signal strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210, 232"}, {"id": "IP-209", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Which of the following factors directly influences the signal-to-noise ratio in MRI?", "options": ["Voxel volume", "Number of signal averages (NSA/NEX)", "Both voxel volume and number of signal averages", "Neither voxel volume nor number of signal averages"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Both voxel volume and the number of signal averages (NSA/NEX) are primary determinants of SNR. Larger voxels contain more protons and produce more signal, while increasing NSA improves SNR by a factor of the square root of the number of averages. Claiming that neither affects SNR contradicts the fundamental MRI signal equation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-210", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "What is the primary advantage of acquiring isotropic 3D MRI data?", "options": ["Thinner contiguous slices with minimal cross-talk between slices", "The ability to reconstruct images in any arbitrary plane without loss of spatial resolution", "Faster acquisition times compared to 2D multislice techniques", "Improved signal-to-noise ratio at all slice locations"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Isotropic 3D acquisitions produce voxels with equal dimensions in all three spatial directions, allowing multiplanar reconstructions (MPR) in any orientation without degradation of spatial resolution. This is the key advantage over 2D multislice imaging, where through-plane resolution is limited by slice thickness. While 3D imaging does reduce cross-talk, the ability to reformat in any plane is the primary clinical advantage.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232; Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-211", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "A 2D Fourier transform spin echo sequence is acquired with the following parameters: TR = 1000 ms, TE = 30 ms, FOV = 24 cm, phase-encoding matrix = 128, and NSA = 2. What is the approximate total scan time?", "options": ["2.4 minutes", "3.6 minutes", "4.3 minutes", "5.4 minutes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Scan time for a 2D spin echo sequence = TR x phase-encoding steps x NSA. Here: 1000 ms x 128 x 2 = 256,000 ms = 256 seconds, which is approximately 4.3 minutes. A common error is forgetting to multiply by NSA or incorrectly converting milliseconds to minutes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-212", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "The central lines of k-space primarily contribute to which aspect of the final MR image?", "options": ["Image contrast", "Spatial resolution", "Number of slices", "Slice thickness"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The central lines of k-space contain low spatial frequency data, which determines overall signal intensity and contrast between tissues. These lines carry the bulk of the signal amplitude and establish brightness relationships. The peripheral lines contain high spatial frequency data that contributes to edge detail and spatial resolution, not contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-213", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "The total extent (area) of k-space that is sampled during an acquisition determines the achievable:", "options": ["Number of slices", "Field of view", "Spatial resolution", "Matrix size"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The total extent (coverage) of k-space sampled determines achievable spatial resolution because sampling more of the outer periphery captures higher spatial frequencies, producing finer detail in the image. The spacing between k-space lines determines the FOV, not the total extent. Students often confuse these two relationships.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-214", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "The mathematical domain where raw MRI data is collected before image reconstruction is referred to as:", "options": ["Nyquist space", "Gradient domain", "k-space", "Gamma field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "k-space is the spatial frequency domain where raw MRI data is collected as a matrix of complex numbers before Fourier transformation converts it into the final image. It is named for the spatial frequency variable k. Nyquist space is not a standard MRI term; Nyquist relates to sampling theory but does not name the data collection domain.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 159"}, {"id": "IP-215", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "Which of the following methods will reduce the slice thickness in MRI?", "options": ["Decreasing gradient strength or increasing RF bandwidth", "Decreasing the field of view", "Increasing the interslice gap", "Increasing gradient strength or decreasing RF bandwidth"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Slice thickness depends on slice-select gradient strength and RF transmit bandwidth. Increasing gradient steepness spreads frequencies across a narrower physical distance, producing thinner slices. Narrowing RF bandwidth selects fewer frequencies, also producing thinner slices. Decreasing gradient strength would increase slice thickness, not reduce it.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-216", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "After raw data collection is complete, which mathematical process is applied to convert the k-space data into an MR image?", "options": ["Ohm's law calculation", "Faraday's law application", "Larmor equation", "Fourier transform"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The Fourier transform (specifically the fast Fourier transform, FFT) converts k-space raw data from the spatial frequency domain into the spatial domain, producing the viewable MR image. The Larmor equation relates precessional frequency to field strength but is not a data reconstruction algorithm.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-217", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "In MRI, which hardware component is used to intentionally vary the magnetic field strength across a specified spatial direction?", "options": ["Field of view selection", "Acquisition matrix", "180-degree RF pulse", "Gradient coil"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gradient coils are electromagnetic coils designed to produce a linear variation in magnetic field strength along a specific spatial direction (x, y, or z). This intentional field variation is fundamental to spatial encoding in MRI. A 180-degree RF pulse is used for spin refocusing, not spatial field variation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 129; Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-218", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "In a spin echo pulse sequence, which mechanism corrects the loss of phase coherence caused by static magnetic field inhomogeneities?", "options": ["A presaturation RF pulse", "A reduced field of view", "A larger acquisition matrix", "A 180-degree refocusing RF pulse"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In a spin echo sequence, the 180-degree refocusing RF pulse reverses phase dispersion caused by static magnetic field inhomogeneities, rephasing transverse magnetization to form an echo. This is the defining feature of spin echo sequences and their primary advantage over gradient echo. A presaturation pulse eliminates signal from a region but does not rephase dephased spins.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-219", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "The accelerated decay of transverse magnetization that occurs because protons experience slightly different local magnetic fields is described by which relaxation parameter?", "options": ["T1", "T2", "T2*", "Proton density"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "T2* (T2 star) describes the actual observed rate of transverse magnetization decay, which is faster than true T2 because it includes dephasing from both intrinsic spin-spin interactions (T2) and static field inhomogeneities (T2-prime). The relationship is 1/T2* = 1/T2 + 1/T2-prime. T2 alone describes only the intrinsic tissue-related decay without external field effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51; Ch. 1, p. 20"}, {"id": "IP-220", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "Which spin echo parameter combination would produce a proton density-weighted image?", "options": ["TR 500 ms / TE 20 ms", "TR 1000 ms / TE 70 ms", "TR 2000 ms / TE 30 ms", "TR 2500 ms / TE 80 ms"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton density weighting requires a long TR (to minimize T1 contrast by allowing full longitudinal recovery) and a short TE (to minimize T2 contrast by sampling before significant transverse decay). TR 2000 ms/TE 30 ms meets both criteria. TR 2500/TE 80 would produce T2-weighting because the long TE allows significant T2 decay to influence contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-221", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Which spin echo parameter combination would produce a T2-weighted image?", "options": ["TR 500 ms / TE 20 ms", "TR 1000 ms / TE 70 ms", "TR 2000 ms / TE 30 ms", "TR 2500 ms / TE 80 ms"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2-weighting requires a long TR (to minimize T1 contrast) and a long TE (to maximize T2 contrast by allowing tissues with different T2 values to produce different signal intensities at echo sampling). TR 2500 ms/TE 80 ms achieves this. TR 2000/TE 30 would produce PD-weighting because the short TE does not allow sufficient T2 decay.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-222", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which spin echo parameter combination would produce a T1-weighted image?", "options": ["TR 500 ms / TE 20 ms", "TR 1000 ms / TE 70 ms", "TR 2000 ms / TE 30 ms", "TR 2500 ms / TE 80 ms"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1-weighting requires a short TR (to maximize T1 contrast by sampling before all tissues fully recover) and a short TE (to minimize T2 contrast). TR 500 ms/TE 20 ms satisfies both conditions. Longer TR values like 1000 ms or above begin to reduce T1 contrast as more tissues approach full recovery.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-223", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "To achieve proton density-weighted contrast, the imaging parameters should be selected to:", "options": ["Emphasize T1 differences and minimize T2 effects", "Emphasize T2 differences and minimize T1 effects", "Eliminate T1 and demonstrate only T2 contrast", "Minimize both T1 and T2 contributions to the image"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Proton density-weighted images aim to reflect primarily the hydrogen proton concentration in tissues. To achieve this, both T1 and T2 contributions must be minimized: long TR eliminates T1 differences, and short TE eliminates T2 differences. The common misconception is that PD weighting emphasizes T1 differences, but this would create T1 contrast instead.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-224", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "Which TR and TE combination is appropriate for producing a proton density-weighted spin echo image?", "options": ["Short TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Long TR and long TE"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton density weighting uses a long TR to minimize T1 contrast (allowing nearly complete longitudinal recovery of all tissues) and a short TE to minimize T2 contrast (sampling before significant transverse decay). Long TR with long TE would produce T2-weighting because the long TE introduces T2 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-225", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Which TR and TE combination is appropriate for producing a T2-weighted spin echo image?", "options": ["Short TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Long TR and long TE"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2-weighting requires both a long TR (to eliminate T1 contrast) and a long TE (to maximize T2 contrast). The long TE allows tissues with different T2 relaxation times to produce different signal intensities at echo sampling. Short TR with long TE would introduce mixed T1 and T2 contrast, which is not a standard clinical weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-226", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which TR and TE combination is appropriate for producing a T1-weighted spin echo image?", "options": ["Short TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Long TR and long TE"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1-weighting requires a short TR (to maximize differences in longitudinal recovery between tissues) and a short TE (to minimize T2 contrast). Short TR/short TE allows tissues with short T1 values (like fat) to appear bright while tissues with long T1 (like CSF) remain dark. Long TR would allow most tissues to fully recover, eliminating T1 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-227", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "To produce a T2-weighted image, the imaging parameters should be chosen to:", "options": ["Emphasize T1 differences and minimize T2 effects", "Emphasize T2 differences and minimize T1 effects", "Eliminate T1 and demonstrate only T2 contrast", "Eliminate T2 and demonstrate only T1 contrast"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T2-weighted images are designed to emphasize differences in T2 relaxation between tissues while minimizing T1 effects. This is achieved with a long TR (to allow full T1 recovery, removing T1 contrast) and a long TE (to allow T2 differences to manifest). Eliminating T1 to show only T2 is incorrect because some residual T1 influence always exists; the goal is to minimize, not eliminate.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-228", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "To produce a T1-weighted image, the imaging parameters should be chosen to:", "options": ["Emphasize T1 differences and minimize T2 effects", "Emphasize T2 differences and minimize T1 effects", "Eliminate T1 and demonstrate only T2 contrast", "Eliminate T2 and demonstrate only T1 contrast"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1-weighted images emphasize T1 relaxation differences between tissues while minimizing T2 effects. Short TR maximizes T1 contrast by sampling before full recovery; short TE minimizes T2 decay influence. The goal is to emphasize T1 differences, not eliminate T2 entirely, since some T2 effect is always present.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-229", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Regarding tissue contrast mechanisms in MRI, which statement is correct?", "options": ["PD, T1, and T2 contrast all contribute simultaneously to every MR image", "Only one contrast mechanism is active at a time, determined by the selected parameters", "T1 and T2 contribute simultaneously, but PD has no effect on image contrast", "Contrast mechanisms are only active during gradient echo sequences"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "All three intrinsic tissue contrast mechanisms — proton density, T1, and T2 — contribute simultaneously to every MR image. The operator controls which mechanism dominates by selecting appropriate TR and TE values, but the other mechanisms are never completely absent. The misconception that only one mechanism is active ignores that tissues always possess all three properties simultaneously.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 31"}, {"id": "IP-230", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Which statement correctly describes how T2-weighted contrast is controlled in a spin echo sequence?", "options": ["TR is the primary parameter controlling the degree of T2 weighting", "TE is the primary parameter controlling T2 weighting — a longer TE increases T2 contrast", "The field of view must be large to achieve adequate T2 weighting", "T2 weighting is determined solely by the flip angle"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a spin echo sequence, TE is the primary parameter controlling T2 weighting. A longer TE allows more time for transverse magnetization to decay, increasing the signal difference between tissues with different T2 values. TR controls T1 weighting, not T2. FOV and flip angle do not control image contrast weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-231", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which statement correctly describes how T1-weighted contrast is controlled in a spin echo sequence?", "options": ["TR is the primary parameter controlling the degree of T1 weighting", "TE is the primary parameter controlling T1 weighting", "A long TE is necessary for T1 weighting", "T1 weighting requires a large field of view"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR is the primary parameter controlling T1 weighting in a spin echo sequence. A short TR ensures that tissues with different T1 values have not fully recovered their longitudinal magnetization, maximizing T1 contrast between them. TE controls T2 weighting, not T1. FOV has no effect on contrast weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-232", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "On a T2-weighted spin echo image, how do fat and water typically appear?", "options": ["Both fat and water are dark (low signal)", "Both fat and water are bright (high signal)", "Fat is dark and water is bright", "Fat is bright and water is dark"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "On T2-weighted images, water-based tissues (like CSF, edema, cysts) appear bright because water has a long T2 and retains transverse magnetization longer. Fat appears relatively dark on T2-weighted SE images because fat has a short T2 and loses transverse signal quickly. The misconception that both are bright confuses T2 behavior with proton density effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-233", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Fat is known for recovering longitudinal magnetization quickly after an RF pulse. Which statement correctly describes fat's relaxation times?", "options": ["Fat has a short T1 and a long T2", "Fat has a long T1 and a short T2", "Fat has a short T1 and a short T2", "Fat has a long T1 and a long T2"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Fat has both a short T1 (recovers longitudinal magnetization quickly) and a short T2 (loses transverse magnetization quickly). The short T1 is due to efficient energy transfer between fat molecules and the lattice at the Larmor frequency. The short T2 reflects rapid dephasing among closely packed fat protons. A common error is assuming long T2 because fat appears bright on some sequences, but that brightness is from short T1 on T1W images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-234", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "Fat demonstrates rapid loss of transverse magnetization. Which statement correctly describes fat's relaxation times?", "options": ["Fat has a short T1 and a long T2", "Fat has a long T1 and a short T2", "Fat has a short T1 and a short T2", "Fat has a long T1 and a long T2"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Fat demonstrates rapid transverse magnetization loss (short T2) because its large molecular structure promotes efficient spin-spin interactions that cause rapid dephasing. Fat also has a short T1 due to efficient spin-lattice relaxation. The combination of short T1 and short T2 is characteristic of fat tissue.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-235", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "Which of the following tissues has the lowest proton density and therefore produces the least MR signal?", "options": ["White matter", "Gray matter", "Liver", "Cortical bone"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Cortical bone has the lowest proton density of the listed tissues because it contains very few mobile hydrogen protons — its hydrogen is bound in rigid crystalline structures and does not produce MR signal. This is why cortical bone appears as a signal void on all MRI pulse sequences. White matter, gray matter, and liver all contain abundant mobile hydrogen and produce measurable signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-236", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Data collected in the center of k-space is primarily responsible for determining the image's:", "options": ["Contrast", "Spatial resolution", "Number of slices acquired", "Slice thickness"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The center of k-space contains low spatial frequency data that determines overall image contrast — the brightness relationships between different tissues. These central lines carry the majority of signal amplitude. Peripheral k-space data contributes to spatial resolution (edge detail), not contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-237", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "The overall dimensions of the sampled region in k-space directly determine the:", "options": ["Number of slices", "Field of view", "Spatial resolution of the image", "Matrix size"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The overall dimensions (total extent) of the sampled k-space region determine the achievable spatial resolution of the image. Sampling further into the k-space periphery captures higher spatial frequencies, producing finer detail. The spacing between adjacent k-space lines determines the FOV. Students frequently confuse extent (resolution) with spacing (FOV).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-238", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "Prior to Fourier transformation, the collected MRI signal data resides in a domain known as:", "options": ["Nyquist space", "Gradient domain", "k-space", "Gamma field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "k-space is the spatial frequency domain where raw MRI signal data is stored prior to Fourier transformation into the final image. Each point in k-space represents a specific combination of spatial frequencies. Nyquist space is not an accepted MRI term; the Nyquist theorem relates to sampling requirements but does not name a data domain.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 159"}, {"id": "IP-239", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "A technologist needs to acquire thinner slices. Which parameter adjustment will accomplish this?", "options": ["Decreasing the slice-select gradient amplitude or widening the RF bandwidth", "Reducing the field of view", "Widening the interslice gap", "Increasing the slice-select gradient amplitude or narrowing the RF bandwidth"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Thinner slices are achieved by increasing the slice-select gradient amplitude (steeper gradient spreads the Larmor frequency range across a narrower physical distance) or by narrowing the RF transmit bandwidth (selecting a smaller range of frequencies). Decreasing gradient amplitude or widening bandwidth would produce thicker slices, not thinner ones.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-240", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "Once k-space data collection is finished, which mathematical operation separates the individual frequency components to generate the MR image?", "options": ["Ohm's law", "Faraday's law", "Larmor equation", "Fourier transform"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The Fourier transform separates the composite MR signal into its individual frequency components, mapping each to a spatial location to generate the final image. This mathematical operation converts data from the spatial frequency domain (k-space) to the spatial domain (image). The Larmor equation calculates precessional frequency but is not used for image reconstruction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-241", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "To create a controlled, predictable variation in the static magnetic field along a specific axis, MRI systems use:", "options": ["Adjustments to the field of view", "Changes to the acquisition matrix", "A 180-degree RF pulse", "Gradient coils"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gradient coils produce a controlled, linear variation in the static magnetic field along a specific axis, which is essential for spatial encoding in MRI. Each gradient coil (x, y, z) creates a predictable field change along its axis. A 180-degree RF pulse refocuses dephased spins but does not create spatial field variation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 129; Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-242", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "What corrects the dephasing from static field inhomogeneities in a spin echo sequence, allowing a true T2-weighted signal to be recovered?", "options": ["A presaturation RF pulse", "A smaller field of view", "A larger acquisition matrix", "A 180-degree refocusing RF pulse"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The 180-degree refocusing RF pulse in a spin echo sequence corrects dephasing caused by static field inhomogeneities by reversing the phase accumulation of protons, producing a true T2-weighted echo. This is the fundamental mechanism that distinguishes spin echo from gradient echo sequences. A presaturation pulse suppresses signal from a specific region but does not rephase dephased magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-243", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "When transverse magnetization decays more rapidly than predicted by true T2 relaxation due to local field variations, this faster decay rate is characterized as:", "options": ["T1", "T2", "T2*", "Proton density"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "T2* (T2 star) characterizes the observed transverse decay rate that is faster than true T2 because it includes both intrinsic spin-spin relaxation (T2) and additional dephasing from local magnetic field inhomogeneities (T2-prime). The relationship is 1/T2* = 1/T2 + 1/T2-prime. T2 alone does not account for inhomogeneity-driven dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51; Ch. 1, p. 20"}, {"id": "IP-244", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "A technologist wants to produce a proton density-weighted spin echo image. Which set of parameters is most appropriate?", "options": ["TR 500 ms / TE 20 ms", "TR 1000 ms / TE 70 ms", "TR 2000 ms / TE 30 ms", "TR 2500 ms / TE 80 ms"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton density weighting requires a long TR (to minimize T1 contrast) and a short TE (to minimize T2 contrast), allowing the image to primarily reflect hydrogen proton concentration. TR 2000/TE 30 meets these criteria. TR 2500/TE 80 would produce T2-weighting due to the long TE allowing significant transverse decay differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-245", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "To maximize T2-weighted contrast on a spin echo sequence, which parameter set should the technologist select?", "options": ["TR 500 ms / TE 20 ms", "TR 1000 ms / TE 70 ms", "TR 2000 ms / TE 30 ms", "TR 2500 ms / TE 80 ms"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2-weighted contrast requires a long TR (to minimize T1 influence) and a long TE (to maximize T2 contrast). TR 2500/TE 80 provides both. TR 2000/TE 30 would produce PD-weighting because the short TE prevents significant T2 decay from influencing contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-246", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which set of spin echo parameters would best demonstrate T1-weighted tissue contrast?", "options": ["TR 500 ms / TE 20 ms", "TR 1000 ms / TE 70 ms", "TR 2000 ms / TE 30 ms", "TR 2500 ms / TE 80 ms"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1-weighted contrast requires a short TR (to maximize T1 differences between tissues) and a short TE (to minimize T2 effects). TR 500/TE 20 satisfies both. Longer TR values (1000+ ms) progressively reduce T1 contrast as tissues approach complete longitudinal recovery.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-247", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "When selecting parameters for proton density weighting, the technologist's goal is to:", "options": ["Maximize T1 contrast differences while suppressing T2 effects", "Maximize T2 contrast differences while suppressing T1 effects", "Eliminate T1 contrast to show only T2", "Minimize the influence of both T1 and T2 on the image"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Proton density weighting aims to make the image primarily reflect hydrogen concentration in tissues. To achieve this, the technologist must minimize both T1 and T2 contributions: a long TR reduces T1 differences (full recovery for all tissues), and a short TE reduces T2 differences (minimal transverse decay). Maximizing either T1 or T2 contrast would produce T1W or T2W images instead.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-248", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "The concentration of mobile hydrogen nuclei per unit volume of tissue is the definition of:", "options": ["T1 relaxation time", "T2 relaxation time", "Proton density", "Inversion time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton density is defined as the concentration of mobile hydrogen nuclei per unit volume of tissue. It is an intrinsic tissue property that determines the maximum possible signal from that tissue. T1 and T2 relaxation times describe how quickly magnetization recovers or decays, not the quantity of hydrogen present.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-249", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "Compared to most other body tissues, the T2 relaxation time of water (such as CSF) is:", "options": ["Short", "Long", "Intermediate (similar to soft tissue)", "Negligible due to low proton density"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Water (including CSF) has a long T2 relaxation time because its small, rapidly tumbling molecules are inefficient at spin-spin energy exchange, resulting in slow transverse magnetization decay. This is why water-based fluids appear bright on T2-weighted images. The claim that water has a short T2 confuses it with fat, which has rapid spin-spin interactions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-250", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "Compared to water-based tissues, the T2 relaxation time of fat is:", "options": ["Short", "Long", "Intermediate (similar to muscle)", "Dependent on the external magnetic field strength"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat has a short T2 compared to water-based tissues because fat's large molecular structure promotes efficient spin-spin interactions that cause rapid dephasing of transverse magnetization. This is why fat appears relatively dark on T2-weighted images. The misconception that fat has a long T2 may arise from confusing fat's bright appearance on T1W images (due to short T1) with T2 behavior.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-251", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Due to the high molecular mobility of free water, the T1 relaxation time of cerebrospinal fluid is:", "options": ["Short", "Long", "Equivalent to that of gray matter", "Unaffected by molecular motion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "CSF (free water) has a long T1 because its small, rapidly tumbling molecules are inefficient at transferring energy to the surrounding lattice at the Larmor frequency. Efficient spin-lattice relaxation requires molecular motion near the Larmor frequency, which water molecules exceed due to their high mobility. This is why CSF appears dark on T1-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 26"}, {"id": "IP-252", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Relative to water-based tissues, the T1 relaxation time of fat is:", "options": ["Short", "Long", "Equivalent to that of muscle", "Dependent on the echo time selected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat has a short T1 relative to water-based tissues because fat molecules tumble at frequencies close to the Larmor frequency, enabling highly efficient spin-lattice energy transfer. This rapid longitudinal recovery is why fat appears bright on T1-weighted images. Water-based tissues have longer T1 values because their molecular tumbling rates do not match the Larmor frequency as efficiently.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-253", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "The resonant (precessional) frequency of water protons compared to fat protons is:", "options": ["Higher", "Lower", "Identical", "Variable depending on the TR selected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Water protons precess at a slightly higher frequency than fat protons because water protons experience a slightly stronger local magnetic field. Fat protons are shielded by the surrounding electron cloud of the fat molecule, reducing the effective field they experience. This frequency difference (approximately 3.5 ppm) is the basis of chemical shift artifact and fat suppression techniques.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-254", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "In MRI, which two tissue types represent the greatest extremes of signal contrast?", "options": ["Fat and muscle", "Muscle and liver", "Cortical bone and bone marrow", "Water and fat"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Water and fat represent the greatest signal contrast extremes in MRI because they have the most divergent relaxation properties: fat has a short T1/short T2 while water has a long T1/long T2. Their signal behaviors reverse between T1W and T2W images. Cortical bone produces no signal, so it cannot contribute to contrast differences in the same way.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-255", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "A tissue with a large transverse magnetization component at the time of signal readout will appear on the MR image with:", "options": ["High signal intensity", "Low signal intensity", "The same signal intensity as surrounding tissues", "Signal intensity determined solely by T1"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Signal intensity in MRI is directly related to the magnitude of transverse magnetization at the time of echo sampling. A tissue with large transverse magnetization produces a strong signal that appears bright (high signal intensity) on the image. Low transverse magnetization at readout produces dark signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-256", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "On a T1-weighted image, a tissue that recovers longitudinal magnetization quickly (short T1) will demonstrate:", "options": ["Intermediate (gray) signal", "Low (dark) signal", "High (bright) signal", "No signal"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "On a T1-weighted image, tissues with short T1 values recover longitudinal magnetization quickly between TR intervals, making more magnetization available for the next excitation pulse. This results in a larger transverse component after the next RF pulse and therefore bright (high) signal. Tissues with long T1 (like CSF) have not fully recovered and appear dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-257", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "When describing MR images, regions that appear bright are also referred to as areas of:", "options": ["Bright signal", "High signal intensity", "Large field of view", "Signal suppression"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In MRI terminology, bright areas on an image are properly described as regions of high signal intensity. This standardized language avoids ambiguity. 'Bright signal' is informal but less precise than 'high signal intensity,' which is the accepted radiological description. Signal suppression refers to techniques that eliminate signal, not bright regions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-258", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The shielding method that uses additional superconducting coils wound in the opposite direction around the main magnet to contain the fringe field is called:", "options": ["Passive shielding", "Active shielding", "Resistive shielding", "Second-order shielding"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Active shielding uses additional superconducting coils wound in the opposite direction around the main magnet windings to generate a counter-field that contains the fringe field. This reduces the 5-gauss line footprint significantly. Passive shielding uses ferromagnetic materials (steel plates) placed around the magnet room rather than additional coils.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 326"}, {"id": "IP-259", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The two general methods used to contain the fringe field of a superconducting MRI magnet are:", "options": ["First-order and second-order shielding", "Internal and external shielding", "Passive and active shielding", "Resistive and permanent shielding"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The two general methods for containing the fringe field of a superconducting magnet are passive shielding (ferromagnetic materials like steel in walls/floor/ceiling) and active shielding (counter-wound superconducting coils). Most modern systems use active shielding because it reduces the magnet footprint without requiring heavy structural materials.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 326"}, {"id": "IP-260", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "When viewing a cross-section through an MRI magnet bore, which coil set is positioned closest to the patient (innermost)?", "options": ["Gradient coils", "Shim coils", "RF body coil", "Main magnet coils"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When viewed in cross-section from the bore opening inward, the RF body coil is positioned closest to the patient (innermost). The typical arrangement from outside in is: main magnet coils, shim coils, gradient coils, then RF body coil. Local receive coils placed on the patient are even closer but are removable accessories, not permanent bore components.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-261", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.b", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT classified as a surface coil?", "options": ["Cervical spine coil", "Lumbar spine coil", "Breast coil", "Body coil"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The body coil is a large-volume transmit/receive coil built into the bore of the scanner, not a surface coil. Surface coils are smaller receiver coils placed directly on or near the anatomy of interest to improve SNR. Cervical spine, lumbar spine, and breast coils are all examples of surface coils (or phased-array surface coil assemblies) designed for specific anatomy.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-262", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "An inversion recovery pulse sequence begins with which RF pulse combination?", "options": ["A 90-degree RF pulse only", "A 180-degree inversion pulse followed by a 90-degree excitation pulse (and then a 180-degree refocusing pulse)", "A 25-degree RF pulse", "A 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An inversion recovery sequence begins with a 180-degree inversion pulse that flips longitudinal magnetization completely, followed after TI by a 90-degree excitation pulse (and then a 180-degree refocusing pulse for signal recovery). The initial 180-degree inversion is the defining feature that distinguishes IR from standard spin echo sequences. A standard SE begins with 90 degrees, not 180.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-263", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A conventional spin echo pulse sequence consists of which RF pulse combination?", "options": ["A 90-degree RF pulse only", "A 180-degree pulse followed by a 90-degree pulse", "A small flip angle RF pulse", "A 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A conventional spin echo sequence consists of a 90-degree excitation pulse that tips longitudinal magnetization into the transverse plane, followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse that corrects for dephasing from static field inhomogeneities to produce a spin echo. The 90-180 combination is the hallmark of spin echo imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-264", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "At 1.0 T field strength, the approximate T2 relaxation time of cerebral white matter is:", "options": ["40 ms", "80 ms", "480 ms", "2000 ms"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "At 1.0 T, cerebral white matter has a T2 relaxation time of approximately 80 ms. White matter has a shorter T2 than gray matter due to its higher lipid content from myelin, which promotes more efficient spin-spin relaxation. T2 values of 2000 ms are characteristic of free water (CSF), not white matter.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-265", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "At 1.0 T field strength, the approximate T1 relaxation time of cerebrospinal fluid is:", "options": ["120 ms", "480 ms", "2000 ms", "2500 ms"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At 1.0 T, CSF has a T1 relaxation time of approximately 2000 ms. The long T1 of CSF reflects the inefficient spin-lattice energy exchange in free water, whose rapid molecular tumbling exceeds the Larmor frequency. Fat has a T1 of approximately 180 ms at 1.0 T, far shorter than CSF.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-266", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "At 1.0 T field strength, the approximate T2 relaxation time of water (CSF) is:", "options": ["120 ms", "480 ms", "2000 ms", "2500 ms"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "At 1.0 T, CSF (free water) has a T2 of approximately 2500 ms — the longest T2 of common body tissues. This is because water molecules tumble too rapidly for efficient spin-spin dephasing. A T2 of 80 ms is typical of white matter, not free water.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-267", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "At 1.0 T field strength, the approximate T1 relaxation time of fat is:", "options": ["120 ms", "180 ms", "480 ms", "2000 ms"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "At 1.0 T, fat has a T1 of approximately 180 ms, which is among the shortest T1 values of soft tissues. Fat's molecular tumbling rate closely matches the Larmor frequency, enabling highly efficient spin-lattice relaxation. A T1 of 2000 ms is characteristic of CSF, not fat.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-268", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A tissue with a short T1 value will appear on a T1-weighted image as:", "options": ["Gray (intermediate signal)", "Dark (low signal)", "Bright (high signal)", "Signal void"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Tissues with short T1 values recover longitudinal magnetization rapidly between TR intervals, so they have more magnetization available for the next excitation pulse. This produces a larger transverse component and therefore bright (high) signal on T1-weighted images. Tissues with long T1 (like CSF) appear dark because they have not fully recovered.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-269", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "As nuclear spins return to their equilibrium alignment after RF excitation, they emit:", "options": ["An NMR signal", "Photons", "Nuclear particles", "Free hydrogen atoms"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "As nuclear spins relax back to their equilibrium alignment after RF excitation, the changing transverse magnetization induces a voltage in the receiver coil — this is the NMR (nuclear magnetic resonance) signal, also called the FID or echo signal. Spins do not emit photons, nuclear particles, or free atoms during relaxation in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-270", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "At thermal equilibrium within an external magnetic field, the majority of hydrogen nuclear spins are:", "options": ["Aligned parallel (with) the magnetic field", "Aligned antiparallel (against) the field", "Randomly oriented with no net preference", "Equally split between parallel and antiparallel"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "At thermal equilibrium in an external magnetic field, a slight excess of hydrogen spins align parallel (with) the field because this is the lower energy state. The excess is very small (only a few per million) but creates a measurable net magnetization vector in the direction of B0. The claim that spins are equally split ignores this critical energy state difference.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-271", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact is most directly caused by:", "options": ["Insufficient sampling of high spatial frequency data", "Using an excessively large FOV", "Scanning a patient who exceeds the bore diameter", "Using an oversized RF coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact results from insufficient sampling of high spatial frequency data — when the acquisition matrix is too small to capture the sharp signal transitions at tissue boundaries. This causes ringing lines parallel to high-contrast interfaces. Increasing the matrix size samples more high-frequency data and reduces this artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-272", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Which of the following techniques can help reduce motion ghosting artifact?", "options": ["Swapping the phase-encoding direction", "Applying a presaturation band", "Using respiratory compensation or breath-hold techniques", "All of these strategies are effective"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All listed strategies are effective for reducing motion ghosting: swapping phase-encoding direction moves ghost location away from the anatomy of interest, presaturation bands suppress signal from moving tissues before they enter the imaging slice, and respiratory compensation or breath-hold techniques directly reduce the motion itself. Using multiple approaches together provides the best results.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-273", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Motion-related ghosting artifacts propagate along which encoding direction?", "options": ["Phase-encoding direction", "Frequency-encoding direction", "Slice-select direction", "All three encoding directions equally"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Motion-related ghosting artifacts propagate along the phase-encoding direction because phase encoding is sampled over many TR intervals (the slow encoding direction). Any motion between TR intervals causes inconsistent phase data, producing ghost replicas displaced along the phase axis. Frequency encoding occurs within a single readout and is far less susceptible to motion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-274", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "To acquire an oblique imaging plane, the MRI system activates:", "options": ["Only the X gradient", "Only the Y gradient", "Only the Z gradient", "A combination of two or more gradients simultaneously"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Oblique imaging planes are acquired by simultaneously activating two or more gradient coils to create a composite gradient oriented at an angle between standard planes. For example, combining X and Z gradients produces an oblique plane between sagittal and axial. Using only a single gradient produces only the three standard orthogonal planes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-275", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "In a standard supine, head-first patient orientation, the X gradient runs left to right and is used as the slice-select gradient for which imaging plane?", "options": ["Sagittal", "Coronal", "Axial", "Oblique"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a standard supine, head-first orientation, the X gradient runs left-to-right. The slice-select gradient for a sagittal plane must vary the field from left to right to select a slice at a specific lateral position. Therefore, the X gradient serves as the slice-select gradient for sagittal images. The Z gradient (head-foot) selects axial slices, and the Y gradient (anterior-posterior) selects coronal slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-276", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "In standard axial imaging of a supine patient, the Y gradient (anterior-to-posterior) typically serves as the:", "options": ["Frequency-encoding gradient", "Phase-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Readout gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In standard axial imaging, the Z gradient (head-foot) is the slice-select gradient, the X gradient (left-right) is typically the frequency-encoding gradient, and the Y gradient (anterior-posterior) serves as the phase-encoding gradient. The phase-encoding gradient is applied along the shorter anatomic axis to minimize scan time when rectangular FOV is used.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-277", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "To optimize both SNR and spatial resolution for a specific anatomic region, the technologist should select:", "options": ["A small surface coil matched to the anatomy of interest", "The largest available coil", "Fewer signal averages (NSA)", "A coil with the widest possible coverage area"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A small surface coil matched to the anatomy of interest optimizes both SNR and spatial resolution because it receives signal only from nearby tissue, maximizing the signal-to-noise ratio for that region. Larger coils receive signal from a greater volume but also collect more noise from tissues outside the area of interest, reducing SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337; Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-278", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "Which of the following is a type of RF receiver coil used in MRI?", "options": ["Solenoidal coil", "Birdcage (volume) coil", "Helmholtz pair coil", "All of these are receiver coil designs"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Solenoidal coils, birdcage (volume) coils, and Helmholtz pair coils are all valid RF receiver coil designs used in MRI. Solenoidal coils wrap around the anatomy, birdcage coils are cylindrical volume coils (often used as head or body coils), and Helmholtz pairs use two parallel loops to create a uniform field. Each design is optimized for different anatomic applications.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-279", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.d", "stem": "Which of the following can function as an RF transmit coil?", "options": ["Body coil", "Head coil", "Volume coil", "All of these can transmit RF energy"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The body coil, head coil, and other volume coils can all function as RF transmit coils because they are designed to produce a uniform B1 field across a large volume. Many modern systems use the body coil as the primary transmitter with local coils as receive-only, but dedicated transmit head coils and volume coils are also used. Surface coils are typically receive-only.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-280", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Modern superconducting MRI magnets maintain their coils at near absolute zero temperature using:", "options": ["Liquid oxygen", "Liquid hydrogen", "Liquid mercury", "Liquid helium"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Superconducting magnets use liquid helium to cool the coil windings to approximately 4 Kelvin (near absolute zero), where the wire achieves zero electrical resistance and current flows indefinitely without power input. Modern systems use sealed helium cooling systems. Liquid oxygen, hydrogen, and mercury are not used as MRI cryogens.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-281", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.c", "stem": "The process of shimming an MRI magnet involves:", "options": ["Removing the outermost imaging slices from a multislice acquisition", "Centering the laser alignment on a bony landmark", "Adjusting the magnetic field to achieve maximum homogeneity across the imaging volume", "De-energizing the magnet for routine maintenance"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Shimming adjusts the magnetic field to achieve maximum homogeneity across the imaging volume. This can be done passively (placing small ferromagnetic pieces at specific locations) or actively (adjusting current through dedicated shim coils). Good field homogeneity is essential for accurate spatial encoding, fat suppression, and minimizing artifacts. Shimming has nothing to do with removing slices or centering lasers.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-282", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Clinical MRI systems operating at 1.0 T or 1.5 T field strength use which type of magnet?", "options": ["Permanent", "Resistive", "Superconducting", "Hybrid"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Clinical MRI systems operating at 1.0 T and above use superconducting magnets because only superconducting technology can generate and maintain the strong, stable, homogeneous fields required at these strengths. Permanent magnets are limited to low field strengths (typically 0.2-0.35 T), and resistive magnets cannot sustain fields above about 0.3 T without excessive power consumption and heat generation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-283", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The three basic categories of magnets used in MRI systems are:", "options": ["Permanent and resistive only", "Permanent, resistive, and superconducting", "Permanent and superconducting only", "Superconducting and passive only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The three basic categories of magnets used in MRI are permanent, resistive, and superconducting. Permanent magnets use inherently magnetized materials, resistive magnets use conventional electromagnets requiring continuous power, and superconducting magnets use cryogenically cooled coils with zero resistance. Each has distinct advantages in cost, field strength, and maintenance.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-284", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "What is the relationship between k-space data and the final MR image?", "options": ["k-space is a direct spatial map of the image", "k-space contains frequency and phase data that must be Fourier transformed to produce the image", "k-space and the image are identical representations", "k-space only stores contrast information"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "k-space contains raw frequency and phase-encoded data that must be mathematically transformed (via Fourier transform) to produce the final MR image. k-space is not a direct spatial map of the image; each point in k-space contributes information to the entire image. The common misconception that k-space and the image are identical ignores the frequency-domain nature of the raw data.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 159"}, {"id": "IP-285", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "A 3D volume acquisition allows image reformatting in:", "options": ["Only the plane that was originally acquired", "Any arbitrary plane, including oblique orientations", "Only the three standard orthogonal planes", "Only planes perpendicular to the acquisition plane"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A 3D volume acquisition collects data from an entire slab, allowing image reformatting in any arbitrary plane including oblique orientations. This is because the data is encoded in all three spatial dimensions, unlike 2D acquisitions where through-plane information is limited to slice thickness. The ability to reformat in any plane is a primary advantage of 3D imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232; Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-286", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "For optimal multiplanar reformatting from a 3D volume acquisition, the voxel shape should ideally be:", "options": ["Rectangular (anisotropic) to maximize coverage", "Isotropic (equal dimensions in all three axes)", "Elongated along the slice-select direction", "Flat (thin in one dimension) to improve through-plane resolution"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Isotropic voxels (equal dimensions in all three axes) are ideal for multiplanar reformatting because they provide equal spatial resolution regardless of the reformatted plane orientation. Anisotropic voxels would produce degraded resolution in planes that cut through the elongated voxel dimension, resulting in blurry reformatted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-287", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "What effect does doubling the slice thickness have on the signal-to-noise ratio, assuming all other parameters remain constant?", "options": ["SNR approximately doubles", "SNR approximately quadruples", "SNR is reduced by half", "SNR is unaffected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Doubling slice thickness doubles the voxel volume (assuming pixel dimensions remain constant), which approximately doubles the number of protons contributing signal per voxel. Since SNR is directly proportional to voxel volume, doubling slice thickness approximately doubles SNR. The trade-off is increased partial volume averaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-288", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.9", "stem": "A voxel in MRI represents:", "options": ["A three-dimensional volume of tissue defined by the pixel area and slice thickness", "A two-dimensional unit of the displayed image", "The total imaging volume within the FOV", "The gap between adjacent slices"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A voxel (volume element) represents a three-dimensional volume of tissue defined by the pixel area (determined by FOV and matrix) multiplied by the slice thickness. Each voxel contributes one signal intensity value that is displayed as a pixel on the 2D image. A pixel is the 2D display unit, while a voxel is its 3D tissue counterpart.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-289", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "In MRI, adjusting one acquisition parameter often affects other image characteristics. This principle is best described as:", "options": ["Parameter interdependence — trade-offs are inherent in MRI protocol design", "Parameters are independent and can be adjusted without affecting other factors", "Trade-offs only occur when changing the field of view", "Parameter interactions are limited to gradient echo sequences"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "MRI acquisition parameters are fundamentally interdependent — changing one parameter typically affects other image characteristics such as SNR, spatial resolution, scan time, and contrast. For example, increasing matrix improves resolution but decreases SNR and increases scan time. Understanding these trade-offs is essential for effective protocol optimization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 238"}, {"id": "IP-290", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.13", "stem": "Which statement is correct regarding eddy currents in MRI?", "options": ["Eddy currents cannot be reduced by any shielding method", "Eddy currents only occur in permanent magnet systems", "Active gradient shielding is an effective method for minimizing eddy currents", "Eddy currents have no measurable effect on image quality"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Active gradient shielding is an effective method for minimizing eddy currents. Eddy currents are induced in nearby conductive structures (such as the magnet cryostat) by the rapidly switching gradient fields. Active shielding uses a secondary set of gradient coils wound in the opposite sense to cancel the stray fields that would otherwise induce eddy currents. Without mitigation, eddy currents degrade field homogeneity and cause image artifacts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-291", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.13", "stem": "What effect can eddy currents have on the MRI magnetic field?", "options": ["They generate small parasitic magnetic fields that degrade field homogeneity", "They strengthen the main magnetic field uniformly", "They only affect the RF coil performance", "They improve gradient linearity"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Eddy currents generate small parasitic magnetic fields that oppose the intended gradient field changes, degrading magnetic field homogeneity. These unwanted fields cause spatial encoding errors, image distortion, and artifacts. Eddy currents do not strengthen the main field, improve gradient linearity, or only affect the RF coil.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-292", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "How does the minimum achievable TE in a gradient echo sequence compare to that of a conventional spin echo sequence?", "options": ["Gradient echo allows a shorter TE because no 180-degree refocusing pulse is required", "Gradient echo requires a longer TE due to gradient reversal timing", "Both sequences achieve the same minimum TE", "The minimum TE depends solely on the matrix size"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences achieve shorter minimum TE than spin echo because they do not require a 180-degree refocusing pulse between excitation and echo formation. In GRE, the echo is formed by gradient reversal alone, which can be executed much faster. The 180-degree pulse in SE adds time for pulse application and associated gradient spoiling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-293", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "The number of lines filled in k-space during a standard acquisition is directly determined by the:", "options": ["Number of phase-encoding steps", "Number of frequency-encoding samples", "Slice thickness", "Receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The number of lines filled in k-space equals the number of phase-encoding steps. Each TR interval applies a unique phase-encoding gradient amplitude that fills one line of k-space. The frequency-encoding samples determine the number of data points along each line (columns), not the number of lines.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-294", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "T1 relaxation is also known as:", "options": ["Spin-spin relaxation", "Transverse relaxation", "Spin-lattice relaxation", "Free induction decay"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "T1 relaxation is also called spin-lattice relaxation because it describes the process by which excited spins transfer energy to the surrounding molecular lattice (environment) as they recover longitudinal magnetization. Spin-spin relaxation is T2 (transverse decay). Free induction decay describes the signal after excitation, not the relaxation mechanism.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 26"}, {"id": "IP-295", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Aliasing (wrap-around) artifact can occur along:", "options": ["Both the phase-encoding and frequency-encoding axes", "Only the phase-encoding axis", "Only the frequency-encoding axis", "Only the slice-select axis"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Aliasing can occur along both the phase-encoding and frequency-encoding axes when anatomy extends beyond the FOV in either direction. Along the frequency axis, oversampling (digital filtering) is routinely applied to prevent aliasing at no time cost. Along the phase axis, aliasing must be corrected with phase oversampling or increased FOV, which may add scan time. Students often think aliasing only occurs in phase, but it can occur in both.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-296", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "To achieve thin slices in MRI, which combination of parameters is used?", "options": ["A steep slice-select gradient and/or a narrow RF transmit bandwidth", "A shallow gradient and wide bandwidth", "Thin slices are controlled only by the matrix size", "Slice thickness cannot be adjusted after calibration"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Thin slices require a steep (strong) slice-select gradient that spreads the Larmor frequency range across a narrow spatial distance, and/or a narrow RF transmit bandwidth that excites a smaller frequency range. A shallow gradient or wide bandwidth produces thicker slices. Matrix size affects in-plane resolution, not slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-297", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.d", "stem": "Which coils within an MRI system are responsible for transmitting RF energy to the patient?", "options": ["Shim coils and tune coils", "The body coil and, when applicable, a local transmit coil", "Gradient coils", "Receiver-only surface coils"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The body coil and, when applicable, local transmit coils are responsible for transmitting RF energy to excite hydrogen protons. The body coil is the most common transmitter in clinical systems, producing a uniform B1 field. Gradient coils create spatial encoding fields, not RF excitation. Shim coils adjust static field homogeneity. Receiver-only surface coils detect signal but do not transmit.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-298", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "What is the primary advantage of a quadrature coil design compared to a linear coil?", "options": ["Lower SNR but faster imaging", "Reduced RF heating", "Approximately 41% improvement in SNR", "Elimination of aliasing artifact"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A quadrature coil detects signal from two orthogonal channels simultaneously, providing approximately a 41% (square root of 2) improvement in SNR compared to a linear coil. This is because the two channels capture independent signal components while their noise is uncorrelated. The SNR gain comes from signal combination, not from reduced RF heating or faster imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-299", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "The frequency of RF energy required to produce resonance in hydrogen nuclei is calculated using:", "options": ["Faraday's equation", "The Larmor equation", "Ohm's law", "The Nyquist theorem"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Larmor equation (omega = gamma x B0) calculates the precessional frequency of hydrogen nuclei and therefore the RF frequency needed to produce resonance. It relates the gyromagnetic ratio of the nucleus to the external magnetic field strength. Faraday's equation describes electromagnetic induction, Ohm's law relates voltage to current, and the Nyquist theorem addresses sampling requirements.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-300", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Regarding the economics of MRI operations, which statement is correct?", "options": ["Operating costs are negligible for all magnet types", "Only the purchase price matters; ongoing costs are minimal", "Both startup and ongoing operating costs are significant factors in MRI", "Costs only apply to low-field systems"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Both startup (purchase/installation) and ongoing operating costs (cryogen replenishment, power, maintenance contracts, facility requirements) are significant factors in MRI operations. Superconducting systems have high purchase costs but moderate operating costs; resistive systems have lower purchase costs but high power consumption. The claim that costs are negligible or only apply to low-field systems is incorrect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-301", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Faraday's Law of electromagnetic induction describes:", "options": ["The generation of an electrical current by a changing magnetic field", "The relationship between precessional frequency and field strength", "The thermal effects of RF energy on tissue", "The behavior of cryogens at low temperatures"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Faraday's Law states that a changing magnetic field induces an electrical current (voltage) in a nearby conductor. In MRI, this principle underlies signal detection: the precessing transverse magnetization creates a changing magnetic field that induces a current in the receiver coil. The Larmor equation (not Faraday's Law) relates frequency to field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-302", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Compared to permanent and resistive magnets, the initial installation cost of a superconducting MRI system is:", "options": ["Significantly higher", "Significantly lower", "Approximately the same", "Lower due to simpler cooling requirements"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Superconducting MRI systems have significantly higher initial installation costs than permanent or resistive systems due to the expense of superconducting wire, cryogenic cooling systems, and specialized site preparation (RF shielding, floor reinforcement). However, their operating costs are lower than resistive magnets because no continuous electrical power is needed to maintain the magnetic field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-303", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Compared to permanent and resistive magnet designs, superconducting magnets offer:", "options": ["Superior magnetic field homogeneity", "Inferior field homogeneity but lower cost", "Equivalent homogeneity at all field strengths", "Homogeneity that degrades rapidly over time"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Superconducting magnets provide superior magnetic field homogeneity compared to permanent and resistive designs. The persistent current in superconducting coils produces an extremely stable, uniform field essential for high-quality imaging. Permanent magnets struggle with homogeneity at higher field strengths, and resistive magnets suffer from thermal instability affecting field uniformity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-304", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "The precessional (Larmor) frequency of hydrogen at 1.5 T is approximately:", "options": ["21 MHz", "63.86 MHz", "68 MHz", "128 MHz"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Using the Larmor equation (frequency = gyromagnetic ratio x field strength): 42.57 MHz/T x 1.5 T = 63.86 MHz. This is the precessional frequency of hydrogen protons at 1.5 T and the RF frequency required for resonance. At 3.0 T, the frequency doubles to approximately 128 MHz. The value of 21 MHz corresponds to a much lower field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-305", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "How does signal refocusing in a gradient echo sequence differ from a spin echo sequence?", "options": ["GRE uses a 90-degree pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse", "GRE uses only 180-degree pulses", "GRE uses gradient reversal rather than a 180-degree RF refocusing pulse", "There is no difference in refocusing mechanism"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In gradient echo sequences, the echo is formed by reversing the polarity of the frequency-encoding gradient (gradient reversal) rather than using a 180-degree RF refocusing pulse. This allows shorter TE and faster imaging but does not compensate for static field inhomogeneities, making GRE sequences sensitive to T2* effects. Spin echo uses the 180-degree pulse to correct for these inhomogeneities.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-306", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Which statement accurately describes the relaxation properties of fat?", "options": ["Fat has a short T1 and a short T2", "Fat has a long T1 and a long T2", "Fat has a short T1 and a long T2", "Fat has a long T1 and a short T2"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat has a short T1 (efficient spin-lattice relaxation due to molecular tumbling near the Larmor frequency) and a short T2 (rapid spin-spin dephasing due to closely packed protons). This combination explains why fat is bright on T1W images (short T1 = fast recovery) and relatively dark on T2W images (short T2 = rapid signal decay).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-307", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In a low-field permanent magnet MRI system, the orientation of the main magnetic field (B0) is typically:", "options": ["Vertical (inferior to superior)", "Horizontal (head to foot along the bore)", "Transverse (left to right)", "Variable depending on patient position"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In permanent magnet systems (typically open or C-arm designs), the main magnetic field B0 is oriented vertically (inferior to superior). This contrasts with superconducting cylindrical bore magnets where B0 runs horizontally along the bore axis (head to foot). This orientation difference affects coil design and gradient configurations.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-309", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Because fat molecules have slow molecular tumbling rates, which of the following is true?", "options": ["Fat has a short T1 relaxation time", "Fat has a long T2 relaxation time", "Fat's net magnetization realigns slowly with B0", "Fat produces no measurable MR signal"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat molecules tumble at frequencies close to the Larmor frequency, which makes spin-lattice energy transfer highly efficient, resulting in a short T1 relaxation time. This is why fat recovers longitudinal magnetization quickly and appears bright on T1-weighted images. The misconception that slow tumbling means slow T1 recovery confuses molecular motion rate with energy transfer efficiency.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-310", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.g", "stem": "The relationship linking sampling time, sampling rate, and receiver bandwidth is described by the:", "options": ["Larmor equation", "Fourier transform", "Nyquist theorem", "Law of electromagnetic induction"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Nyquist theorem establishes the relationship between sampling time, sampling rate, and receiver bandwidth. It states that the sampling rate must be at least twice the highest frequency present in the signal to avoid aliasing. In MRI, this means the receiver bandwidth must be at least twice the maximum frequency offset in the readout direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-311", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.f", "stem": "A nonselective (block) RF pulse is characterized by:", "options": ["A narrow frequency bandwidth that excites only a single slice", "A wide frequency bandwidth, constant amplitude and frequency, that excites the entire sample", "A shaped (sinc) waveform that targets a specific slice location", "A pulse that only affects protons at the isocenter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A nonselective (block) RF pulse has a wide frequency bandwidth with constant amplitude, exciting all protons in the sample regardless of their spatial location. It does not use the slice-select gradient because there is no need to limit excitation to a single slice. Selective (sinc-shaped) pulses have narrow bandwidths designed to excite only a specific slice.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-312", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.f", "stem": "A selective RF pulse is characterized by:", "options": ["A narrow frequency bandwidth that excites only a specific slice of tissue", "A wide frequency bandwidth that excites the entire imaging volume", "Constant amplitude and frequency throughout its duration", "No dependence on the slice-select gradient"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A selective RF pulse has a narrow frequency bandwidth (typically a sinc-shaped waveform) that excites only protons within a specific slice of tissue when applied simultaneously with the slice-select gradient. The gradient creates a frequency distribution across the anatomy, and the narrow-bandwidth pulse excites only the frequencies corresponding to the desired slice location.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135; Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-313", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "During a conventional spin echo sequence, the frequency-encoding gradient:", "options": ["Applies a single, constant value for each phase-encoding step during echo readout", "Varies in amplitude with each TR to encode different spatial frequencies", "Is applied simultaneously with the slice-select gradient", "Changes polarity between the 90-degree and 180-degree pulses"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "During a spin echo sequence, the frequency-encoding (readout) gradient applies a single, constant value during each echo readout. Its amplitude and polarity remain the same for every TR interval because it encodes spatial position along the frequency axis by assigning unique frequencies to each column of tissue. The phase-encoding gradient, not the frequency gradient, changes amplitude with each TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-314", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "At the geometric center of the frequency-encoding gradient, the tissue at that location experiences:", "options": ["Maximum positive gradient field strength", "Maximum negative gradient field strength", "No additional gradient field — only the main B0 field", "An intermediate gradient field strength"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At the geometric center (isocenter) of the frequency-encoding gradient, the gradient contributes zero additional field — protons there experience only the main B0 field and precess at the center frequency. The gradient adds field on one side and subtracts field on the other side of center, creating a linear frequency distribution used for spatial encoding.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-315", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a spin echo sequence, the phase-encoding gradient is applied:", "options": ["During all RF pulses", "Only during the acquisition of the echo", "Between the 90-degree excitation and the 180-degree refocusing pulses", "Only during slice selection"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a spin echo sequence, the phase-encoding gradient is applied between the 90-degree excitation pulse and the 180-degree refocusing pulse. This timing allows phase differences to be introduced after excitation but before the refocusing pulse. Its amplitude changes with each TR to fill a different line of k-space. It is not applied during RF pulses or during the echo readout.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-316", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The frequency-encoding (readout) gradient in a spin echo sequence is applied:", "options": ["During all RF pulses", "During the acquisition (readout) of the echo signal", "Only during the 180-degree refocusing pulse", "Only during the slice-selection process"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding (readout) gradient is applied during the acquisition of the echo signal, assigning unique precessional frequencies to protons at different positions along the readout axis. The receiver is open during this gradient application to collect the frequency-encoded signal. It is not applied during RF pulses or slice selection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-317", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "Which parameter adjustment will produce thinner imaging slices?", "options": ["Decreasing the transmit RF bandwidth", "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth", "Increasing the slice-select gradient amplitude", "Both decreasing the RF bandwidth and increasing the gradient amplitude"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Thinner slices are achieved by both decreasing the RF transmit bandwidth (narrower frequency range excites a thinner tissue section) and increasing the slice-select gradient amplitude (steeper gradient spreads frequencies across a narrower spatial distance). Either method alone works, but combining both provides the thinnest possible slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-318", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Which factors influence the magnitude of chemical shift artifact?", "options": ["Field strength", "Field of view", "Receiver bandwidth", "All of these factors influence chemical shift artifact"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifact magnitude is influenced by all listed factors. Higher field strength increases the absolute frequency difference between fat and water. Smaller FOV concentrates the pixel bandwidth, increasing the pixel shift. Lower receiver bandwidth reduces the frequency range per pixel, also increasing the artifact. Understanding these interactions is essential for protocol optimization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-319", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "When imaging the thoracic spine, phase ghosting can result from:", "options": ["CSF pulsation and cardiac motion only", "CSF pulsation and respiratory motion only", "Cardiac and respiratory motion only", "CSF pulsation, cardiac motion, and respiratory motion"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The thoracic spine is uniquely affected by all three sources of periodic motion: CSF pulsation (driven by cardiac cycle), direct cardiac motion from the adjacent heart, and respiratory motion from chest wall movement. All three contribute phase-encoding inconsistencies that manifest as ghosting artifacts in thoracic spine images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-320", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Which techniques help minimize motion ghosting artifacts?", "options": ["Swapping the phase-encoding direction", "Applying presaturation bands", "Using respiratory compensation", "All of these techniques reduce ghosting"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All listed techniques effectively reduce motion ghosting: swapping phase-encoding direction redirects ghosts away from the anatomy of interest, presaturation bands suppress signal from moving tissues, and respiratory compensation synchronizes data acquisition with the breathing cycle. Using multiple techniques together provides the best results.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-321", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "When anatomy moves along a gradient during the pulse sequence, the resulting artifact is called:", "options": ["Chemical shift", "Truncation", "Aliasing", "Phase mis-mapping (motion ghosting)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "When anatomy moves along a gradient during the pulse sequence, the motion causes phase inconsistencies between successive TR intervals, resulting in phase mis-mapping (motion ghosting). Ghost replicas of the moving anatomy appear displaced along the phase-encoding direction. Chemical shift is caused by fat-water frequency differences, not motion. Truncation results from insufficient matrix sampling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-322", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When anatomy located outside the selected field of view is incorrectly mapped into the image, the resulting artifact is:", "options": ["Chemical shift", "Truncation", "Aliasing (wrap-around)", "Phase mis-mapping"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Aliasing (wrap-around) artifact occurs when anatomy extending beyond the selected FOV is incorrectly mapped to the opposite side of the image. This happens because frequencies outside the sampled range are misinterpreted as lower frequencies within the FOV. Chemical shift involves fat-water frequency displacement, and truncation involves ringing at high-contrast boundaries.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-323", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Spatial resolution (smaller voxel size) can be improved by:", "options": ["Selecting a thinner slice", "Choosing a finer matrix while maintaining FOV", "Reducing the FOV while maintaining matrix size", "All of these methods reduce voxel size"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Spatial resolution improves (smaller voxels) with thinner slices (reduces through-plane voxel dimension), finer matrix at same FOV (reduces in-plane pixel size), or reduced FOV at same matrix (also reduces pixel size). All three methods decrease voxel volume and improve the ability to resolve small structures, but each also reduces SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-324", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "What are the consequences of doubling the number of signal averages (NEX)?", "options": ["Scan time doubles and SNR increases by approximately 41%", "Scan time doubles and spatial resolution improves", "SNR increases by 41% without affecting scan time", "Both scan time and spatial resolution double"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Doubling NEX doubles the scan time (twice as many signal acquisitions) and increases SNR by approximately 41% (the square root of 2, or 1.41). SNR improves proportionally to the square root of NEX, not linearly. NEX does not affect spatial resolution — resolution is determined by voxel dimensions (matrix, FOV, slice thickness).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-325", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which parameter defines the time interval for each repetition of the pulse sequence?", "options": ["Repetition time (TR)", "Echo time (TE)", "Phase encoding", "Number of excitations (NEX)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Repetition time (TR) is the time interval between successive applications of the excitation pulse — one complete cycle of the pulse sequence. It determines how much T1 recovery occurs between excitations and is a primary factor controlling T1 contrast, scan time, and the number of slices. TE is the time to echo, not the repetition interval.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 22"}, {"id": "IP-326", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Which of the following will increase the signal-to-noise ratio?", "options": ["Using a spin echo sequence instead of gradient echo", "Selecting a short TR with a long TE", "Choosing a fine acquisition matrix", "Reducing the number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Spin echo sequences collect signal as true T2-weighted echoes using 180-degree refocusing pulses, which produce inherently higher SNR than gradient echo sequences that are T2*-weighted and lose signal to field inhomogeneities. Short TR with long TE reduces SNR (less recovery, more decay), fine matrices reduce voxel size (less signal), and reducing NSA removes averaging benefit.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-327", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "What are the effects of halving the receiver bandwidth?", "options": ["SNR increases by approximately 41%", "The minimum achievable TE increases", "Chemical shift artifact increases", "All of these effects occur when receiver bandwidth is halved"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Halving the receiver bandwidth has three simultaneous effects: SNR increases by approximately 41% (square root of 2) because less noise is sampled, the minimum achievable TE increases because the readout takes longer, and chemical shift artifact increases because the frequency range per pixel decreases, causing fat-water misregistration to span more pixels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210; Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-328", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is performed with TR 250 ms and TE 25 ms. What type of image contrast will this produce?", "options": ["Predominantly T1-weighted", "Predominantly T2-weighted", "Predominantly proton density", "Predominantly T2 and PD mixed"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR 250 ms is a short TR that maximizes T1 contrast by not allowing complete longitudinal recovery. TE 25 ms is a short TE that minimizes T2 contrast. This combination (short TR/short TE) produces predominantly T1-weighted contrast, where fat appears bright and fluid appears dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-329", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is performed with TR 2000 ms and TE 75 ms. What type of image contrast will this produce?", "options": ["Predominantly T1-weighted", "Predominantly T2-weighted", "Predominantly T2*-weighted", "Predominantly proton density"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "TR 2000 ms is a long TR that minimizes T1 contrast, and TE 75 ms is a long TE that maximizes T2 contrast. This combination (long TR/long TE) produces predominantly T2-weighted images where fluid appears bright and fat appears relatively dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-330", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence uses TR 30 ms, TE 5 ms, and flip angle 20 degrees. What contrast weighting will this produce?", "options": ["Predominantly T1-weighted", "Predominantly T2-weighted", "Predominantly T2*-weighted", "Predominantly proton density"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In this GRE sequence, a small flip angle (20 degrees) minimizes T1 dependence because it does not significantly deplete longitudinal magnetization, so T1 recovery differences between tissues are minimal. The short TE (5 ms) minimizes T2* contrast. With both T1 and T2* influences minimized, the image primarily reflects proton density differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-331", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.4", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence uses TR 30 ms, TE 25 ms, and flip angle 20 degrees. What contrast weighting will this produce?", "options": ["Predominantly T1-weighted", "Predominantly T2-weighted", "Predominantly T2*-weighted", "Predominantly proton density"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "This GRE sequence uses a small flip angle (20 degrees, minimizing T1 contrast) but a long TE (25 ms, maximizing T2* dephasing effects). Since gradient echo does not use a 180-degree refocusing pulse, the long TE allows significant T2* decay, making the image predominantly T2*-weighted. Tissues with short T2* (like blood products) appear dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-332", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is performed with TR 300 ms and TE 10 ms. What type of image contrast will this produce?", "options": ["Predominantly T1-weighted", "Predominantly T2-weighted", "Predominantly T2*-weighted", "Predominantly proton density"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR 300 ms is a short TR that maximizes T1 differences between tissues, and TE 10 ms is a short TE that minimizes T2 contrast. This short TR/short TE combination produces predominantly T1-weighted contrast. These parameters are typical for T1W conventional spin echo imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-333", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "Listed from closest to the patient (innermost) to farthest, what is the correct order of coil layers within an MRI bore?", "options": ["RF coil, gradient coils, shim coils", "Gradient coils, RF coil, shim coils", "RF coil, shim coils, gradient coils", "Shim coils, RF coil, gradient coils"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "From innermost (closest to patient) to outermost, the coil layers within the MRI bore are: RF coil (body coil), gradient coils, then shim coils. The RF coil must be closest to the patient to efficiently transmit and receive RF energy. Gradient coils are next, and shim coils are between the gradients and the main magnet windings.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-334", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which type of MRI magnet does NOT utilize shim coils for field homogeneity adjustment?", "options": ["Permanent", "Resistive", "Superconducting", "All magnet types use shim coils"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Permanent magnets do not use shim coils for field homogeneity adjustment. Instead, permanent magnets rely on passive shimming using small ferromagnetic pieces placed strategically to correct field imperfections. Resistive and superconducting magnets can use both active shim coils (carrying adjustable currents) and passive shimming.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-335", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The principle that a changing magnetic field induces an electrical current in a conductor is described by:", "options": ["Faraday's law", "Maxwell's law", "Planck's law", "Fourier's law"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Faraday's law describes the principle that a changing magnetic field induces an electrical current (or voltage) in a nearby conductor. This is the fundamental principle underlying MR signal detection: the precessing transverse magnetization creates a changing magnetic field that induces a measurable voltage in the receiver coil.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-336", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "How does ECG gating function in cardiac MRI?", "options": ["RF excitation pulses are synchronized to the same phase of the cardiac cycle using the ECG signal", "The ECG signal is used to adjust the flip angle in real time", "ECG gating eliminates the need for breath-holding", "The gradient timing is modified based on heart rate variability"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "ECG gating synchronizes RF excitation pulses to the same phase of the cardiac cycle using the patient's ECG signal as a timing reference. Data is acquired at the same point in each heartbeat, ensuring consistent cardiac anatomy position across k-space lines. This reduces cardiac motion artifact. ECG gating does not adjust flip angle or eliminate the need for breath-holding.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-337", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.3", "stem": "When performing MR angiography, which techniques help suppress stationary background tissue?", "options": ["Decreased TR only", "Presaturation pulses only", "Increased flip angle only", "Decreased TR, presaturation pulses, and increased flip angle are all effective"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In MR angiography, stationary background tissue suppression is achieved through multiple complementary techniques: decreased TR reduces signal from stationary tissue with long T1, presaturation pulses null signal from specified regions, and increased flip angle enhances the saturation of stationary spins. All three work together to maximize vessel-to-background contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-338", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.4", "stem": "When performing MR angiography, which of the following techniques reduce intravoxel dephasing?", "options": ["Reducing slice thickness only", "Reducing TE only", "Reducing slice thickness and TE, but not FOV", "Reducing slice thickness, reducing FOV, and reducing TE"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Intravoxel dephasing in MRA occurs when spins within a single voxel have different velocities and phases, causing signal cancellation. Reducing slice thickness, FOV, and TE all help: thinner slices and smaller FOV reduce voxel size (fewer velocity variants per voxel), and shorter TE reduces the time available for phase dispersion. All three are effective.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-339", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Which factors affect contrast in phase contrast MRA?", "options": ["Flow velocity", "Flow direction", "Velocity aliasing", "All of these factors influence phase contrast MRA contrast"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Phase contrast MRA contrast is influenced by flow velocity (determines signal intensity), flow direction (can be encoded in any direction), and velocity aliasing (occurs when the VENC is set too low for the actual flow velocity, causing signal wrap). All three must be considered when optimizing PC-MRA protocols.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-340", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.a", "stem": "The postprocessing algorithm that creates a 2D projection image from a 3D volumetric dataset is called:", "options": ["Fast Fourier transform", "Cardiac gating", "Maximum intensity projection (MIP)", "Phase contrast"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Maximum intensity projection (MIP) is a postprocessing algorithm that projects the brightest voxel along each ray through a 3D dataset onto a 2D plane. It is the standard postprocessing technique for MRA, displaying bright vessels against a suppressed background. FFT is for image reconstruction, not postprocessing visualization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-341", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "How does the SNR of fast spin echo (FSE/TSE) sequences compare to conventional spin echo?", "options": ["FSE has inherently lower SNR than conventional SE", "FSE typically has equal or higher SNR compared to conventional SE", "SNR is identical between FSE and SE at all echo train lengths", "FSE SNR depends solely on the number of echoes collected"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Fast spin echo (FSE/TSE) typically has equal or higher SNR compared to conventional SE because multiple echoes are collected per TR, effectively sampling more signal. The multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses also maintain magnetization transfer effects. The misconception that FSE has lower SNR may arise from confusing blurring (a resolution effect) with signal loss.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-342", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "How does respiratory compensation reduce motion artifacts?", "options": ["By timing RF excitation pulses to a specific phase of respiration", "By reordering k-space data acquisition based on the respiratory cycle", "By eliminating respiratory motion entirely through sedation", "By increasing the TR to match the respiratory rate"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Respiratory compensation reduces motion artifacts by reordering k-space data acquisition based on the respiratory cycle, placing data acquired during similar respiratory phases in adjacent k-space lines. This smooths the phase errors rather than eliminating motion entirely. It does not time RF excitation to respiration (that would be respiratory triggering) and does not require sedation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-343", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The fast Fourier transform (FFT) converts:", "options": ["Signal into a unit of time", "A unit of time into a signal", "Signal intensity from the frequency domain into the time domain", "Signal intensity from the time domain into the frequency domain"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The fast Fourier transform converts signal intensity from the time domain (raw acquired signal as a function of time) into the frequency domain (signal decomposed into component frequencies). In MRI, this operation is applied to k-space data to produce the final spatial-domain image. The conversion from frequency to time would be the inverse FFT.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-344", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "When evaluating the carotid arteries with 2D time-of-flight MRA, a presaturation pulse should be applied:", "options": ["Superior to the imaging volume", "Inferior to the imaging volume", "Lateral to the imaging volume", "Medial to the imaging volume"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In 2D TOF MRA of the carotid arteries, a presaturation pulse is applied superior to the imaging volume to suppress venous blood flowing downward (from the brain). This eliminates jugular venous signal that would otherwise overlap with the arterial signal. Arterial blood flowing upward from the heart enters unsaturated and produces bright signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-345", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.4", "stem": "What is the primary function of gradient moment nulling (flow compensation) in an MRI pulse sequence?", "options": ["To rephase moving spins that have been dephased by imaging gradients", "To suppress signal from stationary tissue", "To increase the speed of gradient switching", "To reduce the flip angle of the excitation pulse"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient moment nulling (flow compensation) rephases moving spins that have been dephased by imaging gradients. Additional gradient lobes are applied to null the first moment of the gradient waveform, correcting for constant velocity motion. This reduces flow-related signal loss and phase ghosting from vessels and CSF. It does not suppress stationary tissue or change the flip angle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-346", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "Which of the following best describes a CINE MRI examination?", "options": ["A series of rapidly acquired images displayed in a dynamic loop to visualize motion", "A single static image acquired with cardiac gating to freeze motion", "A maximum intensity projection created from a 3D dataset", "A subtracted image set used to visualize contrast enhancement over time"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "CINE MRI acquires a series of images at multiple time points throughout the cardiac cycle, which are then displayed in a dynamic loop to visualize cardiac wall motion, valve function, and blood flow. This requires rapid acquisition, typically using gradient echo sequences with ECG gating. It is not a single static image or a postprocessing projection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-347", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "Which set of parameters is most appropriate for a cardiac CINE examination?", "options": ["Long TR, conventional spin echo sequence, large flip angle", "Short TR, coherent gradient echo sequence, small flip angle", "Long TR, fast spin echo sequence, large flip angle", "Short TR, inversion recovery sequence, small flip angle"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cardiac CINE requires rapid acquisition to capture multiple cardiac phases within a single heartbeat. A short TR coherent (balanced) gradient echo sequence with a small flip angle provides the speed needed while maintaining good blood-myocardium contrast. Conventional spin echo with long TR would be far too slow for dynamic cardiac imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-348", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "In a gradient echo sequence, what are the effects of increasing the flip angle?", "options": ["Increased T1 dependence, decreased signal-to-noise ratio, and an effect similar to decreasing TR in spin echo", "Increased T1 dependence and decreased signal-to-noise ratio, but no similarity to TR changes in spin echo", "Decreased T1 dependence and increased signal-to-noise ratio", "Increased T2* dependence with no change in signal-to-noise ratio"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In GRE, increasing the flip angle increases T1 dependence because larger flip angles deplete more longitudinal magnetization, making T1 recovery differences more apparent. This is similar to decreasing TR in spin echo (both reduce available longitudinal magnetization). SNR may decrease at very large flip angles because the steady-state signal is reduced when longitudinal recovery between TRs is insufficient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-349", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "Which of the following are effects of increasing the echo train length in a fast spin echo sequence?", "options": ["Increased scan time and increased image blurring", "Increased image blurring and a possible reduction in signal-to-noise ratio", "Decreased scan time and increased spatial resolution", "Increased scan time, increased image blurring, and possible reduction in signal-to-noise ratio"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the echo train length (ETL) in FSE decreases scan time (more k-space lines per TR) but increases image blurring (later echoes have T2 decay affecting edge detail) and may reduce SNR (later echoes contribute weaker signal). The blurring occurs because peripheral k-space lines are filled with echoes at different TEs. Scan time decreases, not increases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-350", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.14", "stem": "A fast spin echo sequence is prescribed with echo times of 20, 40, 60, 80, and 100 ms. What is the effective echo time for this sequence?", "options": ["20 ms", "40 ms", "60 ms", "100 ms"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The effective TE in an FSE sequence is the echo time assigned to fill the center of k-space, which determines the image contrast. With echo times of 20, 40, 60, 80, and 100 ms (ETL=5), the middle echo (60 ms) is typically assigned to fill the central k-space lines, making 60 ms the effective TE. The first and last echoes fill the periphery of k-space.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-351", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.4", "stem": "What is the primary clinical benefit of applying gradient moment nulling to an MRI pulse sequence?", "options": ["Reduction of artifacts caused by flowing or pulsating structures", "Suppression of fat signal throughout the image", "Elimination of the MR signal from a selected spatial region", "Improvement of T2 contrast between adjacent tissues"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient moment nulling (flow compensation) reduces artifacts caused by flowing or pulsating structures (blood vessels, CSF) by adding extra gradient lobes that null the first moment of the gradient waveform, rephasing spins moving at constant velocity. This reduces flow voids and ghosting from vascular pulsation. It does not suppress fat or eliminate signal from a spatial region.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-352", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Which of the following acquisition matrices would produce the highest spatial resolution?", "options": ["128 × 128", "192 × 256", "256 × 256", "512 × 512"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A 512 x 512 matrix produces the highest spatial resolution because it divides the FOV into the largest number of pixels, creating the smallest pixel dimensions. For a given FOV, doubling the matrix from 256 to 512 halves the pixel size and doubles the spatial resolution in each dimension. The trade-off is reduced SNR and longer scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-353", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following imaging parameters influence both image contrast and signal-to-noise ratio?", "options": ["TR and TE only", "TR and flip angle only", "TE and flip angle only", "TR, TE, and flip angle"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "TR, TE, and flip angle all influence both image contrast and SNR. TR controls T1 recovery time (contrast) and signal available per repetition (SNR). TE controls T2/T2* decay (contrast) and signal amplitude at readout (SNR). Flip angle controls the proportion of longitudinal magnetization converted to transverse (both contrast weighting and signal strength).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210; Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-354", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Reducing the receiver bandwidth by half will result in which combination of effects?", "options": ["Increased SNR, decreased minimum TE, and decreased chemical shift artifact", "Increased SNR, increased minimum TE, and increased chemical shift artifact", "Decreased SNR, decreased minimum TE, and increased chemical shift artifact", "Increased SNR, increased minimum TE, and no change in chemical shift artifact"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Halving the receiver bandwidth increases SNR by approximately 41% (less noise sampled), increases the minimum achievable TE (longer readout time required), and increases chemical shift artifact (fewer Hz per pixel means the fat-water frequency difference spans more pixels). These three effects always occur together when bandwidth is reduced.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210; Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-355", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Which of the following techniques will increase the signal-to-noise ratio of an MR image?", "options": ["Using a spin echo sequence instead of a gradient echo sequence", "Selecting a short TR and long TE", "Selecting a finer acquisition matrix", "Decreasing the number of signal averages"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Spin echo sequences inherently produce higher SNR than gradient echo sequences because the 180-degree refocusing pulse recovers signal lost to static field inhomogeneities, generating a true T2-weighted echo rather than a T2*-weighted signal. Short TR/long TE reduces SNR, finer matrices reduce voxel size (less signal), and decreasing NSA reduces averaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-356", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which timing parameter defines the interval between successive excitation pulses in an MRI pulse sequence?", "options": ["Repetition time (TR)", "Echo time (TE)", "Inversion time (TI)", "Number of signal averages (NEX)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Repetition time (TR) defines the interval between successive excitation pulses in a pulse sequence. It determines how much time is available for longitudinal (T1) recovery between excitations. TE measures the time from excitation to echo formation, TI is the inversion delay, and NEX is the number of signal averages — none of these define the repetition interval.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 22"}, {"id": "IP-357", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "What are the effects of doubling the number of signal averages (NEX)?", "options": ["Scan time is doubled and SNR increases by approximately 41%", "Scan time is doubled, SNR increases by 41%, and spatial resolution improves", "SNR increases by 41% and spatial resolution improves, with no change in scan time", "Scan time is doubled and SNR is doubled"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Doubling NEX doubles scan time (twice as many signal acquisitions to average) and increases SNR by the square root of 2, approximately 41%. SNR improves as the square root of NEX, not linearly. NEX does not affect spatial resolution, which depends on voxel dimensions (matrix, FOV, slice thickness).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-358", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Which of the following strategies will improve spatial resolution in MRI?", "options": ["Selecting a thinner slice, using a finer matrix, and reducing the field of view", "Selecting a thicker slice and increasing the number of signal averages", "Increasing the field of view while maintaining the matrix size", "Using a coarser matrix while reducing the field of view"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Spatial resolution improves (voxel volume decreases) by selecting thinner slices (reduces through-plane dimension), using a finer matrix at the same FOV (reduces in-plane pixel size), or reducing the FOV at the same matrix (also reduces pixel size). All three decrease voxel volume. Thicker slices and larger FOV increase voxel size and worsen resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-359", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The gradient applied during signal reception is referred to as the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Shim gradient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding (readout) gradient is the gradient applied during signal reception (echo readout). It assigns unique precessional frequencies to protons at different positions along the readout axis, allowing spatial localization in that direction. The phase-encoding gradient is applied before readout, and the slice-select gradient is applied during RF excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-360", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "In a superconducting MRI system with the bore oriented along the z-axis, the frequency-encoding gradient is applied along the x-axis for an axial acquisition. The amplitude of this gradient primarily determines the:", "options": ["Size of the anatomical area covered in the frequency-encoding direction", "Thickness of the selected slice", "Homogeneity of the magnetic field at isocenter", "Number of phase-encoding steps applied per TR"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding gradient amplitude determines the frequency range spread across the FOV in the readout direction, which directly relates to the anatomical area covered (FOV) in the frequency-encoding direction. A steeper gradient covers less anatomy (smaller FOV) with higher resolution. The slice-select gradient controls slice thickness, not the readout gradient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-361", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "To select thinner slices during an MRI acquisition, the technologist can:", "options": ["Apply a steeper slice-select gradient and/or use a narrower RF transmit bandwidth", "Apply a steeper slice-select gradient and/or use a broader RF transmit bandwidth", "Apply a shallower slice-select gradient and/or use a narrower RF transmit bandwidth", "Apply a shallower slice-select gradient and/or use a broader RF transmit bandwidth"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Thinner slices are achieved by increasing the steepness of the slice-select gradient (spreads the Larmor frequency range across a narrower spatial distance) and/or using a narrower RF transmit bandwidth (excites a smaller range of frequencies). A shallower gradient or broader bandwidth produces thicker slices. This is a fundamental spatial encoding relationship.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-362", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "The most commonly adjusted parameter for changing slice thickness on an MRI scanner is the:", "options": ["Field of view", "Amplitude of the slice-select gradient", "Receiver bandwidth", "Number of signal averages"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The amplitude of the slice-select gradient is the most commonly adjusted parameter for changing slice thickness on clinical MRI scanners. Although RF bandwidth also affects slice thickness, gradient amplitude is the standard user-adjustable parameter. FOV affects in-plane resolution, receiver bandwidth affects SNR and readout characteristics, and NSA affects signal averaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-363", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which of the following are intrinsic tissue properties that serve as mechanisms of contrast in MRI?", "options": ["T1 relaxation time only", "T1 and T2 relaxation times only", "T2 relaxation time and proton density only", "T1 relaxation time, T2 relaxation time, and proton density"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T1 relaxation time, T2 relaxation time, and proton density are all intrinsic tissue properties that serve as contrast mechanisms in MRI. Every tissue has characteristic values of all three, and all contribute to the final image signal intensity. The operator controls which mechanism dominates through parameter selection (TR, TE, flip angle), but all three are always present.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 31"}, {"id": "IP-364", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is prescribed with a short TR and a short TE. What type of image contrast will predominantly result?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "Proton density-weighted", "T2*-weighted"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Short TR maximizes T1 contrast by sampling before full longitudinal recovery, and short TE minimizes T2 contrast by sampling before significant transverse decay. This short TR/short TE combination produces predominantly T1-weighted contrast where tissues with short T1 (fat) appear bright and tissues with long T1 (CSF) appear dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-365", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A conventional dual-echo spin echo sequence is performed using a long TR. Which types of image contrast are produced from the two echoes?", "options": ["T1-weighted from both echoes", "T1-weighted and T2-weighted", "T2-weighted and proton density-weighted", "T1-weighted and proton density-weighted"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A dual-echo spin echo with long TR produces two images: the first echo (short TE) is proton density-weighted (long TR minimizes T1, short TE minimizes T2), and the second echo (long TE) is T2-weighted (long TR minimizes T1, long TE maximizes T2). Neither echo is T1-weighted because the long TR eliminates T1 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-366", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "Compared to conventional spin echo sequences, gradient echo sequences are typically characterized by:", "options": ["Shorter scan times due to the use of reduced flip angles and shorter TR values", "Longer scan times due to the need for 180-degree refocusing pulses", "Similar scan times when the same TR and TE are used", "Longer scan times because gradient reversals require more processing time"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences use reduced flip angles (less than 90 degrees) and shorter TR values than conventional spin echo, resulting in significantly shorter scan times. GRE does not use a 180-degree refocusing pulse, which further reduces the minimum TE and TR. The trade-off is sensitivity to T2* effects and magnetic susceptibility artifacts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-367", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "How does the 180-degree refocusing pulse in a conventional spin echo sequence affect magnetic field inhomogeneities?", "options": ["It has no effect on signal loss caused by field inhomogeneities", "It compensates for static field inhomogeneities by refocusing dephased spins", "It amplifies the effects of field inhomogeneities to improve T2* contrast", "It eliminates field inhomogeneities by adjusting the shim coil settings"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 180-degree refocusing pulse in conventional spin echo compensates for static field inhomogeneities by reversing the phase dispersion that accumulates after the 90-degree excitation pulse. This refocusing produces a true T2 echo, removing T2-prime effects. This is the defining advantage of spin echo over gradient echo sequences, which are sensitive to T2* decay.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-368", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "In a gradient echo sequence, which parameters can be adjusted to control the degree of T1-weighted contrast?", "options": ["Repetition time (TR) only", "Repetition time (TR) and flip angle", "Echo time (TE) and flip angle", "Flip angle and inversion time (TI)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In gradient echo sequences, both TR and flip angle control T1 weighting. A shorter TR reduces the time for T1 recovery (increasing T1 contrast), and a larger flip angle depletes more longitudinal magnetization (also increasing T1 dependence). Together they control how much T1 information is present in the image. TE controls T2* weighting, and TI is used in inversion recovery, not standard GRE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-369", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is performed with TR 300 ms, TE 10 ms, and a 90-degree excitation pulse. What type of contrast will this sequence predominantly produce?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "T2*-weighted", "Proton density-weighted"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR 300 ms (short TR) maximizes T1 contrast, and TE 10 ms (short TE) minimizes T2 contrast. The 90-degree excitation is standard for spin echo. This combination produces predominantly T1-weighted contrast. These parameters are typical clinical T1W SE settings.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-370", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.4", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence is prescribed with TR 30 ms, TE 25 ms, and a 20-degree flip angle. What type of contrast will this sequence predominantly produce?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "T2*-weighted", "Proton density-weighted"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "With a 20-degree flip angle (small, minimizing T1 contrast) and TE 25 ms (long for GRE, maximizing T2* dephasing), this sequence produces predominantly T2*-weighted contrast. The small flip angle ensures minimal T1 dependence, and the long TE allows significant dephasing from field inhomogeneities to accumulate.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-371", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence is prescribed with TR 30 ms, TE 5 ms, and a 20-degree flip angle. What type of contrast will this sequence predominantly produce?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "T2*-weighted", "Proton density-weighted"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A 20-degree flip angle (small) minimizes T1 contrast, and TE 5 ms (short for GRE) minimizes T2* contrast. With both T1 and T2* influences minimized, the image primarily reflects proton density differences between tissues. This is the GRE equivalent of a long TR/short TE spin echo sequence.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-372", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is performed with TR 2000 ms, TE 75 ms, and a 90-degree excitation pulse. What type of contrast will this sequence predominantly produce?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "T2*-weighted", "Proton density-weighted"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "TR 2000 ms (long) minimizes T1 contrast by allowing nearly complete longitudinal recovery, and TE 75 ms (long) maximizes T2 contrast by allowing significant transverse decay differences between tissues. This long TR/long TE combination produces predominantly T2-weighted images where fluid appears bright.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-373", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence is prescribed with TR 250 ms, TE 25 ms, and a 90-degree excitation pulse. What type of contrast will this sequence predominantly display?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "Proton density-weighted", "Mixed T2 and proton density-weighted"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR 250 ms (short) maximizes T1 differences by sampling before full longitudinal recovery, and TE 25 ms (short) minimizes T2 effects. This short TR/short TE combination produces predominantly T1-weighted contrast. These are standard T1W spin echo parameters.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-374", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "In an inversion recovery pulse sequence, a short inversion time (TI) is selected primarily to:", "options": ["Suppress signal from fat tissue", "Maximize T2 contrast between gray and white matter", "Collect the MR signal immediately after the inversion pulse", "Suppress signal from cerebrospinal fluid"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A short TI in an inversion recovery sequence is used in STIR (Short TI Inversion Recovery) to suppress fat signal. The TI is chosen to match the null point of fat (approximately 150 ms at 1.5 T), where fat's longitudinal magnetization crosses zero during recovery from the 180-degree inversion pulse. At this point, fat produces no signal. A long TI (approximately 2200 ms at 1.5 T) would suppress CSF instead (FLAIR).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-375", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "In a fast spin echo sequence, the echo train length (ETL) refers to the:", "options": ["Number of 180-degree refocusing pulses applied per repetition time", "Time interval between the first and last echo in the echo train", "Total number of slices acquired during one TR period", "Duration of the slice-select gradient application"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Echo train length (ETL) in fast spin echo refers to the number of 180-degree refocusing pulses applied per TR interval, each generating a separate echo that fills one line of k-space. A longer ETL means more k-space lines per TR, reducing scan time proportionally. The trade-off is increased image blurring from T2 decay across the echo train.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-376", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "A fast spin echo sequence uses an echo train length of 3, with echo times at 25, 50, and 75 ms. What is the echo train spacing?", "options": ["25 ms", "50 ms", "75 ms", "100 ms"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Echo train spacing (ETS) is the time interval between successive echoes in an FSE echo train. With echoes at 25, 50, and 75 ms, the spacing between each is 25 ms. ETS is determined by the time needed to apply the 180-degree refocusing pulse, phase-encoding gradient, and readout for each echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-377", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.14", "stem": "The effective echo time in a fast spin echo sequence is best described as the:", "options": ["Echo time at which the center of k-space is filled, determining the dominant image contrast", "Shortest echo time in the echo train", "Average of all echo times in the echo train", "Echo time at which the periphery of k-space is sampled"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The effective TE in an FSE sequence is the echo time at which the center of k-space is filled, because the central k-space lines determine the dominant image contrast. The technologist selects this effective TE, and the system assigns it to fill the central k-space lines. Peripheral k-space lines are filled by earlier or later echoes in the train.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-378", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "Which of the following is an advantage of 3D volumetric acquisition over 2D multislice imaging?", "options": ["Shorter echo times are achievable because TE is independent of slice thickness", "Slice thickness is limited by maximum gradient amplitude", "Thinner slices can be achieved because slice thickness is determined by the secondary phase-encoding partition, not gradient amplitude alone", "Only a small number of slices can be acquired per TR period"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In 3D volumetric acquisition, slice thickness is determined by the secondary phase-encoding partition (slab divided into partitions), not by gradient amplitude alone. This allows thinner contiguous slices than 2D multislice, where slice thickness is limited by the slice-select gradient and RF bandwidth. 3D also provides isotropic voxels for multiplanar reformatting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-379", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.4", "stem": "Gradient moment nulling works by:", "options": ["Applying additional gradient lobes that rephase spins dephased by motion through imaging gradients", "Applying an RF saturation pulse to eliminate signal from flowing blood", "Reversing the polarity of the readout gradient to cancel all signal", "Reducing the flip angle to minimize the effect of motion on signal intensity"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient moment nulling applies additional gradient lobes to the slice-select, phase-encoding, or frequency-encoding gradient waveforms to rephase spins that have been dephased by motion through those gradients. By nulling the first moment of the gradient, constant-velocity motion is compensated, reducing flow voids and ghosting from vascular and CSF pulsation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-380", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "What is a primary advantage of gradient echo sequences compared to conventional spin echo sequences?", "options": ["Faster acquisition times", "Greater RF power deposition", "Superior T2 contrast", "Complete elimination of susceptibility artifacts"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences provide faster acquisition times than conventional spin echo because they use reduced flip angles (less than 90 degrees) and shorter TR values, and they do not require a time-consuming 180-degree refocusing pulse. GRE actually deposits less RF power than SE (lower SAR), has inferior T2 contrast (T2* instead), and is more susceptible to artifacts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-381", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "What is the difference between signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR)?", "options": ["There is no difference; the terms are interchangeable", "SNR measures overall signal relative to background noise, while CNR measures the signal difference between two tissues relative to noise", "SNR measures the difference between two tissues, while CNR measures signal relative to noise", "SNR applies only to T1-weighted images, while CNR applies only to T2-weighted images"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SNR measures the overall signal from a tissue relative to background noise, while CNR measures the signal difference between two specific tissues relative to noise. CNR determines whether two adjacent structures can be visually distinguished. High SNR does not guarantee high CNR if both tissues have similar signal intensities. They are distinct measurements with different clinical implications.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-382", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "Which of the following statements about SNR and CNR is correct?", "options": ["Both SNR and CNR are influenced by the same imaging parameters, including TR, TE, flip angle, bandwidth, and voxel size", "SNR is affected by imaging parameters, but CNR is determined solely by intrinsic tissue properties", "CNR is affected by imaging parameters, but SNR is determined solely by coil selection", "SNR and CNR are controlled by completely independent sets of factors"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Both SNR and CNR are influenced by the same set of imaging parameters, including TR, TE, flip angle, bandwidth, and voxel size. These parameters affect signal intensity of all tissues and noise levels simultaneously. CNR additionally depends on intrinsic tissue contrast differences (T1, T2, PD), but the imaging parameters that control SNR also directly influence CNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-383", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "Which of the following best describes the mechanism of respiratory gating?", "options": ["Data acquisition is completed more quickly than with ungated techniques", "The patient is asked to hold their breath throughout the entire scan", "Data acquisition is synchronized to the respiratory cycle so that imaging occurs during a consistent phase of breathing", "Image contrast is unaffected because gating only changes the timing of acquisition"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Respiratory gating synchronizes data acquisition to the respiratory cycle so that imaging occurs during a consistent phase of breathing (typically end-expiration when the diaphragm is most stable). This reduces ghosting from respiratory motion. It does not speed up acquisition (it often lengthens scan time) and is different from breath-holding, which eliminates respiratory motion entirely.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-384", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.c", "stem": "The limited field of view coverage of individual surface coils has been overcome by the development of:", "options": ["Stronger main magnets", "Higher bandwidth receivers", "Phased array coil systems", "Linear gradient amplifiers"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Phased array coil systems overcome the limited FOV coverage of individual surface coils by combining multiple small coils, each with high local SNR, into an array that covers a larger anatomical region. Each coil element receives signal independently, and the signals are combined to produce a composite image with both high SNR and wide coverage.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-385", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.f", "stem": "Given a fixed slice-select gradient amplitude, which RF transmit pulse would produce the thinnest slice?", "options": ["42.6 MHz ± 0.1 MHz", "42.6 MHz ± 0.2 MHz", "42.6 MHz ± 0.3 MHz", "42.6 MHz ± 0.4 MHz"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "For a fixed slice-select gradient amplitude, a narrower RF transmit bandwidth excites a smaller range of frequencies, corresponding to a thinner slice. The pulse at 42.6 MHz +/- 0.1 MHz has the narrowest bandwidth (0.2 MHz total), producing the thinnest slice. Wider bandwidths (+/- 0.4 MHz = 0.8 MHz total) excite four times the frequency range, producing thicker slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-386", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Which of the following are functions performed by gradient coils in an MRI system?", "options": ["Slice selection and frequency encoding only", "Phase encoding and frequency encoding only", "Slice selection, frequency encoding, and phase encoding", "Slice selection and shimming only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gradient coils perform all three spatial encoding functions in MRI: slice selection (selects the imaging plane), frequency encoding (encodes position along the readout axis), and phase encoding (encodes position along the phase axis). Each function uses a gradient along a specific physical axis (x, y, or z), and the assignment depends on the selected imaging plane.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-387", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following are true regarding permanent magnets used in MRI?", "options": ["They are used in low-field systems, the B0 field is oriented perpendicular to the long axis of the patient, and they have minimal maintenance requirements", "They generate field strengths above 1.5T and require cryogenic cooling", "They are used only in low-field systems and have high maintenance requirements", "Their B0 field is oriented parallel to the long axis of the patient, similar to superconducting systems"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Permanent magnets are used in low-field MRI systems (typically 0.2-0.35 T), generate a vertical B0 field (perpendicular to the patient's long axis), and have minimal maintenance requirements because they need no electricity or cryogens to maintain the field. They cannot achieve field strengths above about 0.5 T and do not require cryogenic cooling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-388", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following is a characteristic of superconducting MRI magnets?", "options": ["They can generate high magnetic field strengths, typically 1.5T and above", "They are limited to low-field applications below 0.5T", "Their main magnetic field (B0) is oriented perpendicular to the long axis of the patient", "They do not require any cryogenic cooling to maintain superconductivity"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Superconducting MRI magnets can generate high field strengths (typically 1.5 T and above, up to 7 T for clinical use). They use superconducting wire cooled to near absolute zero with liquid helium, where electrical resistance drops to zero. The B0 field runs horizontally along the bore axis (parallel to patient), not perpendicular.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-389", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "What is the purpose of tuning and matching an RF coil before an MRI examination?", "options": ["To make the patient more comfortable by reducing acoustic noise", "To adjust the coil so it operates at the system's center frequency", "To ensure the coil resonates at the Larmor frequency and achieves optimal energy transfer between the coil and the patient", "To increase the static magnetic field strength within the bore"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Tuning and matching an RF coil ensures it resonates at the Larmor frequency and achieves optimal energy transfer between the coil and the patient. Tuning adjusts the coil's resonant frequency to match the system center frequency, while matching optimizes impedance for maximum power transfer. An improperly tuned coil results in poor SNR and image quality.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-390", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following statements about superconducting MRI magnets is correct?", "options": ["They require liquid helium to maintain the superconducting coils at cryogenic temperatures", "They are less expensive to operate than permanent magnets", "Their main magnetic field runs perpendicular to the patient's long axis", "They use the same coil design as permanent magnet systems"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Superconducting magnets require liquid helium to maintain the coil windings at cryogenic temperatures (approximately 4 K) where electrical resistance is zero. Modern sealed-helium systems minimize helium loss through recondensing technology. Superconducting magnets have higher operating costs than permanent magnets, and their B0 field runs parallel (not perpendicular) to the patient axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-391", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.c", "stem": "The rise time of a gradient coil refers to the:", "options": ["Total duration that the gradient remains at its maximum amplitude", "Time required for the gradient to ramp from zero to its specified amplitude", "Interval between successive gradient pulses within a sequence", "Maximum duration a gradient can operate before the coil overheats"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rise time is the time required for a gradient coil to ramp from zero to its specified maximum amplitude. Shorter rise times allow faster gradient switching, enabling shorter TE and faster pulse sequences. Rise time is a key performance specification for gradient coils and is related to slew rate (slew rate = maximum gradient amplitude / rise time).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-392", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "The amplitude of a magnetic field gradient is determined by the:", "options": ["Amount of electrical current applied to the gradient coil", "Strength of the static magnetic field", "Receiver bandwidth selected for the acquisition", "Current applied to the radiofrequency coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The amplitude of a magnetic field gradient is directly determined by the amount of electrical current applied to the gradient coil. Higher current produces a steeper gradient (larger field variation per unit distance). The static field strength, receiver bandwidth, and RF coil current do not control gradient amplitude.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-393", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.f", "stem": "A selective RF pulse is characterized by:", "options": ["A narrow frequency bandwidth that excites only a specific range of frequencies corresponding to a defined slice", "A wide frequency bandwidth that excites the entire imaging volume simultaneously", "Constant frequency and amplitude throughout the duration of the pulse", "The inability to be used with slice-select gradients"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A selective RF pulse has a narrow frequency bandwidth (typically sinc-shaped) that excites only protons precessing within a specific frequency range. When applied simultaneously with a slice-select gradient, this narrow bandwidth corresponds to a defined spatial slice. The pulse shape (usually sinc) determines the slice profile quality.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135; Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-394", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.f", "stem": "Which of the following describes a nonselective (hard) RF pulse?", "options": ["It has a narrow frequency bandwidth and excites a thin slice", "It is also called a sinc pulse and is used for slice selection", "It requires a simultaneous slice-select gradient to function", "It has a wide frequency bandwidth, constant amplitude, and excites the entire sample — also known as a block pulse"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A nonselective (hard/block) RF pulse has a wide frequency bandwidth, constant amplitude throughout its duration, and excites all protons in the sample regardless of position. It does not use a slice-select gradient because no spatial selectivity is intended. A sinc pulse is selective, not nonselective.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-395", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.g", "stem": "The relationship between sampling time, sampling rate, and receive bandwidth in MRI is governed by the:", "options": ["Larmor equation", "Fourier transform", "Nyquist theorem", "Bloch equations"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Nyquist theorem governs the relationship between sampling time, sampling rate, and receive bandwidth. It states that the sampling rate must be at least twice the highest frequency in the signal to accurately represent it without aliasing. In MRI, this determines how the receiver bandwidth, sampling frequency, and readout duration are interrelated.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-396", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Because fat molecules have slow molecular tumbling rates, fat tissue characteristically has:", "options": ["A short T1 relaxation time", "A long T2 relaxation time", "A slow rate of longitudinal magnetization recovery", "A very low proton density"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat molecules have tumbling rates near the Larmor frequency, which makes spin-lattice energy transfer highly efficient, resulting in a characteristically short T1 relaxation time. This rapid longitudinal recovery is why fat appears bright on T1-weighted images. The common misconception that slow tumbling means slow recovery confuses molecular motion rate with resonance matching efficiency.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-397", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "Which of the following statements regarding proton (spin) density in MRI are correct?", "options": ["Bone produces low MR signal due to its low hydrogen content, and muscle produces relatively high signal due to abundant hydrogen", "Cortical bone and lungs produce low signal, but air-filled sinuses produce high signal", "Fat produces low MR signal because it has few mobile hydrogen atoms", "Bone, cortical bone, lungs, and air all produce low MR signal due to limited hydrogen content, while muscle, white matter, and fat produce relatively high signal"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All listed statements are correct: cortical bone, lungs, and air produce low MR signal due to very few mobile hydrogen atoms, while muscle, white matter, and fat produce relatively high signal due to abundant mobile hydrogen. Proton density determines the maximum available signal from any tissue. The claim that fat has few mobile hydrogen is incorrect — fat has high proton density.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-398", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "Which of the following statements about k-space is correct?", "options": ["k-space represents the spatial frequency data of the MR signal before image reconstruction", "The center of k-space contributes primarily to fine image detail and edge definition", "The periphery of k-space contributes primarily to overall image contrast and signal intensity", "Data in k-space is stored as a fully reconstructed image ready for display"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "k-space represents the spatial frequency data of the MR signal before image reconstruction. Each point in k-space contains frequency and phase information that contributes to the entire image, not just one location. The center of k-space contributes to overall contrast (not fine detail), and the periphery contributes to edge definition (not contrast). k-space is not a ready-to-display image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 159"}, {"id": "IP-399", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Motion artifacts in MRI, such as ghosting from respiratory or cardiac motion, propagate primarily in the:", "options": ["Frequency-encoding direction", "Phase-encoding direction", "Slice-selection direction", "All three gradient directions equally"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Motion artifacts (ghosting) propagate primarily in the phase-encoding direction because phase encoding is sampled over many TR intervals. Any motion between TRs creates inconsistent phase information, producing ghost replicas displaced along the phase axis. Frequency encoding occurs within a single readout (too fast for most motion to affect), so ghosts do not propagate in the frequency direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-400", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.e", "stem": "Under normal physiologic conditions, blood flow within most vessels is characterized as:", "options": ["Plug flow", "Turbulent flow", "Laminar flow", "Stagnant flow"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Under normal physiologic conditions, blood flow is laminar — characterized by a parabolic velocity profile where blood flows fastest at the center of the vessel and slowest near the walls. Turbulent flow occurs in pathologic conditions (stenosis, aneurysm) or at vessel bifurcations. Plug flow (uniform velocity across the vessel lumen) occurs only in very small capillaries.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-401", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.e", "stem": "Time-of-flight effects in MRI can result in:", "options": ["Signal loss only, due to outflow of excited spins from the imaging slice", "Signal gain only, due to inflow of fully magnetized unsaturated spins", "Either signal loss or signal gain, depending on the flow velocity and sequence parameters", "No change in signal intensity, because flow does not affect MR signal"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Time-of-flight effects can produce either signal loss or signal gain depending on flow parameters and sequence design. Outflow effects occur when excited spins leave the slice before echo readout, causing signal loss. Inflow effects occur when fully magnetized unsaturated spins enter the slice, producing bright signal (flow-related enhancement). The balance depends on velocity, TR, and slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-402", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "The artifact that results from the difference in precessional frequency between fat and water protons is called:", "options": ["Chemical shift artifact", "Truncation artifact", "Aliasing artifact", "Phase mismapping artifact"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifact results from the precessional frequency difference between fat and water protons (approximately 3.5 ppm, or about 220 Hz at 1.5 T). This frequency difference causes fat and water signals from the same location to be mapped to slightly different pixel positions in the frequency-encoding direction. Truncation is caused by matrix undersampling, not frequency differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-403", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Truncation (Gibbs) artifact is caused by:", "options": ["Differences in precessional frequency between fat and water", "Undersampling of data at sharp signal intensity boundaries, producing alternating bright and dark bands", "Anatomy outside the field of view being mismapped into the image", "Patient motion during the phase-encoding steps of acquisition"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Truncation (Gibbs) artifact is caused by undersampling of data at sharp signal intensity boundaries (high contrast interfaces). When the acquisition matrix is insufficient to represent these abrupt transitions, the Fourier transform produces alternating bright and dark bands (ringing) parallel to the interface. Increasing the matrix size reduces this artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-404", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When anatomy located outside the prescribed field of view is mismapped to the opposite side of the image, the resulting artifact is called:", "options": ["Chemical shift", "Truncation", "Aliasing (wraparound)", "Phase mismapping (ghosting)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Aliasing (wraparound) occurs when anatomy outside the prescribed FOV is mismapped to the opposite side of the image. This happens because frequencies from outside the sampled range are misinterpreted as frequencies within the FOV due to undersampling. It is corrected by increasing the FOV, applying oversampling, or using presaturation bands.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-405", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "When anatomy moves along a gradient during the MRI pulse sequence, the resulting artifact is called:", "options": ["Chemical shift", "Truncation", "Aliasing", "Phase mismapping (ghosting)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Phase mismapping (ghosting) occurs when anatomy moves along a gradient during the pulse sequence, causing inconsistent phase data between successive TR intervals. Ghost replicas of the moving structure appear displaced along the phase-encoding direction. Chemical shift is caused by fat-water frequency differences, truncation by matrix undersampling, and aliasing by FOV limitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-406", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Which of the following techniques can be used to reduce phase mismapping (ghosting) artifacts?", "options": ["Increasing the receiver bandwidth", "Reducing the echo train length", "Using a larger acquisition matrix", "Swapping the phase-encoding direction, applying presaturation bands, and using respiratory compensation"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Effective strategies to reduce ghosting include swapping the phase-encoding direction (moves ghosts away from the anatomy of interest), applying presaturation bands (suppress signal from moving structures), and respiratory compensation (synchronizes acquisition to breathing). Increasing bandwidth, reducing ETL, or using a larger matrix may help indirectly but are not the primary motion-reduction techniques.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-407", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "When imaging the thoracic spine, phase ghosting artifacts may result from:", "options": ["CSF pulsation and cardiac motion only", "CSF pulsation and respiratory motion only", "Cardiac motion and respiratory motion only", "CSF pulsation, cardiac motion, and respiratory motion"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The thoracic spine is uniquely affected by all three sources of periodic motion: CSF pulsation (cardiac-driven), direct cardiac motion from the adjacent heart, and respiratory motion from chest wall expansion. All three generate phase inconsistencies that produce ghosting in thoracic spine images. This makes thoracic spine imaging particularly challenging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-408", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "The severity of chemical shift artifact is influenced by which combination of factors?", "options": ["Field strength and echo time only", "Matrix size and number of signal averages only", "Field strength, field of view, and receiver bandwidth", "Flip angle and repetition time only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifact severity is influenced by field strength (higher field = larger absolute frequency difference), FOV (smaller FOV = fewer Hz per pixel = more pixel shift), and receiver bandwidth (lower bandwidth = fewer Hz per pixel = more pixel shift). Matrix size and NSA do not directly affect the magnitude of chemical shift misregistration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-409", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "Which of the following statements about the precessional frequency of hydrogen protons is correct?", "options": ["Hydrogen is the only nucleus that possesses a gyromagnetic ratio", "The precessional frequency is the same regardless of the external magnetic field strength", "The precessional frequency of hydrogen protons is higher at 1.5T than at 1.0T", "The gyromagnetic ratio changes depending on the external field strength"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The precessional frequency of hydrogen protons is directly proportional to the external magnetic field strength (Larmor equation: f = gamma x B0). At 1.5 T, hydrogen precesses at approximately 63.86 MHz; at 1.0 T, approximately 42.57 MHz. The gyromagnetic ratio (gamma) is a fixed constant for each nuclear species and does not change with field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-410", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.d", "stem": "Nuclei that are MR-visible share the common characteristic of having:", "options": ["An odd number of protons and/or neutrons, resulting in a net nuclear spin", "An even atomic mass number with paired nuclear particles", "Unpaired electrons in their outer orbital shells", "Only unpaired protons in the nucleus, with no contribution from neutrons"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "MR-visible nuclei have an odd number of protons and/or neutrons, which gives them a net nuclear spin (non-zero magnetic moment). This includes hydrogen-1 (1 proton), carbon-13 (6 protons, 7 neutrons), sodium-23, and phosphorus-31. Nuclei with even numbers of both protons and neutrons (like carbon-12) have no net spin and are MR-invisible.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-411", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "The electromagnetic radiation used for excitation in clinical MRI systems operates within the frequency range of:", "options": ["X-rays and gamma rays", "Microwaves", "Radiofrequency waves", "Visible light"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Clinical MRI uses radiofrequency (RF) waves for excitation, operating in the megahertz range (approximately 42-128 MHz for hydrogen at 1.0-3.0 T). RF waves are non-ionizing electromagnetic radiation, unlike X-rays and gamma rays which are ionizing. Microwaves have higher frequencies and shorter wavelengths than the RF range used in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-412", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.d", "stem": "The condition of resonance in MRI is achieved when:", "options": ["A sample is simply placed within a strong static magnetic field", "Radiofrequency energy of any frequency is applied to the sample", "Adjacent nuclei interact with each other through dipole-dipole coupling", "Radiofrequency energy at the Larmor frequency is applied to a sample within a static magnetic field"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Resonance in MRI is achieved when radiofrequency energy at exactly the Larmor frequency is applied to a sample already placed within a static magnetic field. Both conditions must be met: the static field establishes precessional frequencies, and the RF pulse at the matching frequency enables efficient energy transfer. Simply placing a sample in the field or applying off-resonance RF does not produce resonance.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-413", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "In a 3D volumetric acquisition, what is an advantage over conventional 2D multislice imaging?", "options": ["Echo time is independent of the slice-select gradient amplitude", "Only a limited number of slices can be acquired per excitation", "Very thin contiguous slices can be obtained because slice thickness is controlled by a secondary phase-encoding partition", "Scan time is always shorter than an equivalent 2D acquisition"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In 3D volumetric acquisition, slice thickness is controlled by a secondary phase-encoding partition that divides the excited slab into thin contiguous sections. This allows much thinner slices than conventional 2D, where slice thickness is limited by the slice-select gradient and RF bandwidth. 3D acquisition does not guarantee shorter scan times — it often takes longer but provides isotropic resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-414", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "The gyromagnetic ratio of a nucleus represents the:", "options": ["Ratio of the precessional frequency to the external magnetic field strength", "Total number of protons present in the nucleus", "Magnitude of the net magnetization vector at equilibrium", "Ratio of unpaired protons to unpaired neutrons in the nucleus"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The gyromagnetic ratio is the ratio of the precessional frequency to the external magnetic field strength, expressed in MHz/T. For hydrogen, gamma = 42.57 MHz/T. It is an intrinsic property of each nuclear species and determines how fast the nucleus precesses at a given field strength. It does not represent proton count or magnetization magnitude.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-415", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "Which of the following factors influence the size of the equilibrium magnetization vector?", "options": ["The strength of the static magnetic field only", "The strength of the static magnetic field and the maximum MR signal that can be collected", "The strength of the static magnetic field, the number of nuclei in the sample, and the temperature of the sample", "The strength of the static magnetic field, the maximum collectible MR signal, the number of nuclei in the sample, and the sample temperature"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The equilibrium magnetization vector size is influenced by the static field strength (stronger field = greater energy state separation = larger spin excess), the number of nuclei in the sample (more protons = more contributors), the sample temperature (lower temperature = larger spin excess), and these factors collectively determine the maximum MR signal. All four factors are correct.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-416", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following statements about the relationships between T1, T2, and T2* relaxation times are correct?", "options": ["T1 values are always greater than T2 values", "T2 values are always greater than T2* values", "T1 is generally 5 to 10 times longer than T2", "All of the above: T1 > T2, T2 > T2*, and T1 is generally 5–10 times longer than T2"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All three statements are correct: T1 is always longer than T2 (longitudinal recovery is slower than transverse decay), T2 is always longer than T2* (T2* includes additional dephasing from field inhomogeneities), and T1 is generally 5-10 times longer than T2 in biological tissues. These hierarchical relationships are fundamental to understanding relaxation in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-417", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "As the strength of the main magnetic field (B0) increases, the T1 relaxation time of hydrogen protons:", "options": ["Increases", "Decreases", "Remains unchanged", "Becomes shorter than the T2 relaxation time"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1 relaxation time increases as B0 field strength increases because the Larmor frequency increases, moving further from the optimal molecular tumbling rates of most biological tissues. Since spin-lattice relaxation is most efficient when molecular tumbling matches the Larmor frequency, higher fields reduce this efficiency, prolonging T1. This is why T1 contrast differences change between 1.5 T and 3.0 T.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 26"}, {"id": "IP-418", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "As the strength of the main magnetic field (B0) increases, the T2 relaxation time of hydrogen protons:", "options": ["Increases", "Decreases slightly", "Remains unchanged", "Becomes shorter than T2*"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T2 relaxation time decreases slightly as B0 increases because higher field strengths amplify local field variations caused by magnetic susceptibility differences between tissues, leading to more efficient spin-spin dephasing. However, the change in T2 with field strength is much less dramatic than the change in T1. T2 is always longer than T2*.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-419", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "Thinner slices can be achieved by:", "options": ["Decreasing the bandwidth of the RF transmit pulse and/or increasing the slice-select gradient amplitude", "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth", "Increasing the bandwidth of the RF transmit pulse", "Decreasing the slice-select gradient amplitude"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Thinner slices are achieved by decreasing the RF transmit bandwidth (exciting a narrower frequency range) and/or increasing the slice-select gradient amplitude (spreading frequencies across a narrower physical distance). Decreasing the receiver bandwidth affects readout characteristics, not slice thickness. Increasing RF bandwidth or decreasing gradient amplitude would produce thicker slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-420", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "During an MRI pulse sequence, the frequency-encoding gradient is applied:", "options": ["Throughout all RF pulse transmissions", "Only during the acquisition (readout) of the echo signal", "Only during the 180-degree refocusing pulse", "Only during the slice-selection process"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding gradient is applied during the acquisition (readout) of the echo signal. It creates a linear frequency variation along the readout axis, allowing spatial position to be encoded by frequency. The receiver is open during this gradient application to collect the spatially encoded signal. It is not applied during RF pulse transmission or slice selection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-421", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a conventional spin echo sequence, the phase-encoding gradient is applied:", "options": ["During all RF pulse transmissions", "Only during the acquisition of the echo signal", "Between the excitation pulse and the refocusing pulse, or between the refocusing pulse and the echo", "Only during the slice-selection process"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a conventional spin echo sequence, the phase-encoding gradient is applied between the excitation pulse and the refocusing pulse, or between the refocusing pulse and the echo readout. Its amplitude changes with each TR to encode spatial information along the phase axis. One unique phase-encoding step is applied per TR period in conventional SE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-422", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "At the center of the frequency-encoding gradient (isocenter), the tissue experiences:", "options": ["The maximum positive gradient field strength", "The maximum negative gradient field strength", "No additional gradient field — only the static B0 field", "An intermediate gradient field strength between maximum and minimum"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At the isocenter of the frequency-encoding gradient, the gradient field contribution is zero — tissue there experiences only the static B0 field and precesses at the center (Larmor) frequency. The gradient adds field strength on one side of isocenter and subtracts on the other, creating the linear frequency distribution used for spatial encoding along the readout axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-423", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a conventional spin echo sequence, how many phase-encoding steps are applied per repetition time (TR)?", "options": ["One unique phase-encoding gradient amplitude is applied per TR period", "Multiple phase-encoding gradient amplitudes are applied within a single TR period", "The phase-encoding gradient remains at a constant amplitude throughout the entire acquisition", "No phase-encoding gradient is used; spatial encoding relies only on frequency encoding"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In conventional spin echo, one unique phase-encoding gradient amplitude is applied per TR period, filling one line of k-space. The amplitude changes with each successive TR to sample a different spatial frequency. This is why scan time equals TR x phase-encoding steps x NSA. In fast spin echo, multiple phase-encoding steps occur per TR (equal to the ETL).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-424", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Chemical shift artifact is most prominently displayed in the:", "options": ["Frequency-encoding direction", "Phase-encoding direction", "Slice-selection direction", "Equally in all three gradient directions"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifact appears most prominently in the frequency-encoding direction because the frequency difference between fat and water protons causes them to be mapped to different pixel positions along the readout axis. The readout gradient assigns spatial position by frequency, so any inherent frequency difference between tissues results in spatial misregistration along this axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-425", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.4", "stem": "Chemical misregistration occurs because the slice-select gradient assigns slightly different physical slice locations to fat and water protons due to their precessional frequency difference. This artifact is therefore seen in the:", "options": ["Frequency-encoding direction", "Slice-selection direction", "Phase-encoding direction", "Equally in all directions"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Chemical misregistration occurs in the slice-selection direction because the slice-select gradient assigns slice position based on precessional frequency. Since fat and water protons precess at slightly different frequencies, they are excited at slightly different physical locations, causing the fat and water slices to be offset from each other in the through-plane direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 265"}, {"id": "IP-426", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Which techniques can be used to minimize chemical shift artifact?", "options": ["Using a smaller field of view", "Using a narrower receiver bandwidth", "Using a wider receiver bandwidth and/or applying chemical (fat) saturation", "Decreasing the matrix size"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifact is minimized by using a wider receiver bandwidth (more Hz per pixel reduces the number of pixels the fat-water frequency difference spans) and/or applying chemical fat saturation (eliminates the fat signal entirely). A narrower bandwidth worsens chemical shift. Smaller FOV and decreased matrix do not directly reduce this artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-427", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Aliasing (wraparound) artifact occurs when:", "options": ["The prescribed field of view is larger than the anatomy being imaged", "The anatomy extends beyond the prescribed field of view", "The sampling frequency exceeds the Nyquist limit", "The receiver bandwidth is too wide for the selected matrix"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Aliasing occurs when anatomy extends beyond the prescribed FOV. Frequencies from these outer tissues exceed the sampled range and are misinterpreted as lower frequencies, mapping them to the opposite side of the image. If the FOV is larger than the anatomy, there is no aliasing. The Nyquist limit relates to undersampling, which is the underlying cause.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-428", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.9", "stem": "To minimize aliasing in the frequency-encoding direction, the most effective technique is:", "options": ["Increasing the field of view in the phase direction", "Increasing the number of phase-encoding steps", "Applying a low-pass filter to remove signals outside the selected field of view", "Using a smaller acquisition matrix"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In the frequency-encoding direction, aliasing is prevented by applying a low-pass (anti-aliasing) filter that removes signal frequencies outside the selected FOV before digitization. This digital oversampling technique adds no scan time. Phase-direction aliasing requires different solutions (increased FOV or phase oversampling) because filtering cannot be applied in the phase direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-429", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.9", "stem": "To minimize aliasing in the phase-encoding direction, the technologist can:", "options": ["Increase the field of view in the phase direction and/or increase the number of phase-encoding steps (oversampling)", "Apply a low-pass filter to the phase-encoding data", "Decrease the receiver bandwidth", "Reduce the number of signal averages"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Phase-direction aliasing is minimized by increasing the FOV in the phase direction (to encompass all anatomy) and/or increasing the number of phase-encoding steps (phase oversampling). Unlike frequency-direction aliasing, a simple digital filter cannot prevent phase aliasing because phase encoding occurs over multiple TR intervals. Reducing bandwidth and NSA do not address phase aliasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-430", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Truncation (Gibbs ringing) artifact becomes more pronounced when:", "options": ["A small (coarse) acquisition matrix is used", "A large (fine) acquisition matrix is used", "A large field of view is selected", "A narrow receiver bandwidth is chosen"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Truncation (Gibbs ringing) artifact is more pronounced with a small (coarse) acquisition matrix because fewer data points are available to represent sharp signal intensity transitions at tissue boundaries. The Fourier transform of truncated data produces ringing. A larger matrix samples more high-frequency data, better representing sharp edges and reducing the artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-431", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "The most effective way to reduce truncation (Gibbs ringing) artifact is to:", "options": ["Increase the acquisition matrix size", "Decrease the acquisition matrix size", "Increase the field of view", "Decrease the field of view"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the acquisition matrix size is the most effective way to reduce truncation artifact because it provides more data points to represent sharp signal transitions, reducing the Fourier truncation effect. A finer matrix captures higher spatial frequencies that more accurately represent abrupt intensity changes at tissue boundaries.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-432", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.5", "stem": "Magnetic susceptibility artifact is more pronounced when using:", "options": ["Spin echo sequences with short TE", "Gradient echo sequences", "Small fields of view", "Wide receiver bandwidths"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magnetic susceptibility artifact is more pronounced with gradient echo sequences because they lack the 180-degree refocusing pulse that corrects for dephasing caused by local field inhomogeneities. GRE sequences produce T2*-weighted images that include susceptibility-related signal loss. Spin echo sequences compensate for these effects through refocusing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-433", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.5", "stem": "Magnetic susceptibility artifact can be minimized by:", "options": ["Using a spin echo sequence, selecting a shorter TE, and widening the receiver bandwidth", "Using a gradient echo sequence with a long TE", "Narrowing the receiver bandwidth", "Increasing the echo train length"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Susceptibility artifact is minimized by using a spin echo sequence (refocusing pulse corrects static field dephasing), selecting a shorter TE (less time for dephasing to accumulate), and widening the receiver bandwidth (reduces the effect of frequency shifts per pixel). GRE with long TE would maximize susceptibility effects. Narrowing bandwidth worsens the artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-434", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.10", "stem": "Cross-excitation artifact is most likely to occur when:", "options": ["The field of view is larger than the anatomy being imaged", "The receiver bandwidth is too narrow", "The interslice gap is too small and the RF excitation pulse profile is imperfect", "The echo train length is too long"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Cross-excitation occurs when adjacent slices receive unintended RF energy due to imperfect slice profiles (the RF pulse excites slightly beyond the intended slice boundaries). When the interslice gap is too small, these overlapping excitation profiles affect neighboring slices, reducing their signal. The imperfect RF pulse profile is the root cause.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-435", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.10", "stem": "Which of the following techniques help minimize cross-excitation artifact?", "options": ["Using a larger field of view", "Increasing the receiver bandwidth", "Increasing the interslice gap and/or using interleaved slice acquisition order", "Decreasing the echo train length"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Cross-excitation is minimized by increasing the interslice gap (provides physical separation so imperfect slice profiles do not overlap) and/or using interleaved slice acquisition order (alternating slice excitation allows adjacent slices time to recover before being excited). Larger FOV, increased bandwidth, and decreased ETL do not address cross-excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-436", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.6", "stem": "Zipper artifact in MRI is most commonly caused by:", "options": ["Radiofrequency leakage into the scan room from external sources", "Magnetic susceptibility differences at tissue interfaces", "Anatomy wrapping around from outside the field of view", "Patient motion during data acquisition"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Zipper artifact is caused by radiofrequency leakage into the scan room from external sources. When the RF shielding (Faraday cage) is compromised — by a door left ajar, a damaged seal, or unauthorized electronic devices — external RF signals at or near the Larmor frequency contaminate the MR signal, producing a characteristic line or band across the image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 275"}, {"id": "IP-437", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.6", "stem": "To minimize zipper artifact, the technologist should:", "options": ["Increase the receiver bandwidth", "Apply presaturation bands in the phase-encoding direction", "Verify the integrity of the RF shielding (Faraday cage) and remove any unauthorized electronic devices from the scan room", "Increase the number of signal averages"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Zipper artifact is corrected by verifying the integrity of the RF shielding (Faraday cage) and removing unauthorized electronic devices from the scan room. Common culprits include cell phones, monitoring equipment, or damaged door seals. Increasing bandwidth, presaturation, or NSA do not address the root cause of external RF contamination.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 275"}, {"id": "IP-438", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.14", "stem": "Shading artifact (signal intensity variation across the image) is most commonly caused by:", "options": ["Non-uniformity of the radiofrequency (B1) field, also known as the dielectric effect", "Non-uniformity of the static magnetic field", "Aliasing of anatomy from outside the field of view", "Patient motion during data acquisition"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Shading artifact (signal intensity variation across the image) is most commonly caused by non-uniformity of the radiofrequency (B1) field, also known as the dielectric effect. At higher field strengths (3T and above), RF wavelengths become comparable to body dimensions, causing constructive and destructive interference patterns that create uneven signal intensity. This is distinct from B0 inhomogeneity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 276"}, {"id": "IP-439", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Image contrast in MRI is primarily determined by:", "options": ["The number of phase-encoding steps in the acquisition", "The timing parameters of the pulse sequence, including TR, TE, and TI", "The amplitude of the frequency-encoding gradient", "The size of the field of view"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Image contrast in MRI is primarily determined by the timing parameters of the pulse sequence: TR controls T1 weighting, TE controls T2/T2* weighting, and TI controls inversion-based tissue suppression. These parameters determine which intrinsic tissue properties dominate the image signal. Phase-encoding steps, gradient amplitude, and FOV affect resolution and coverage, not contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-440", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "To produce a T1-weighted image using a conventional spin echo sequence, the technologist would select:", "options": ["Long TR and long TE", "Short TR and short TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T1-weighted spin echo images require short TR (to maximize T1 contrast by sampling before full longitudinal recovery) and short TE (to minimize T2 effects). Tissues with short T1 (fat) recover quickly and appear bright; tissues with long T1 (CSF) remain dark. Long TR would eliminate T1 contrast by allowing all tissues to fully recover.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-441", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "To produce a T2-weighted image using a conventional spin echo sequence, the technologist would select:", "options": ["Long TR and long TE", "Short TR and short TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T2-weighted spin echo images require long TR (to minimize T1 contrast) and long TE (to maximize T2 contrast). The long TE allows tissues with different T2 values to show maximum signal differences at readout. Water/CSF (long T2) retains signal and appears bright; fat and solid tissues (short T2) lose signal and appear relatively dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-442", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "Proton density-weighted contrast in a conventional spin echo sequence is achieved by selecting:", "options": ["Short TR and short TE", "Long TR and long TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton density weighting requires long TR (minimizes T1 contrast by allowing nearly complete recovery) and short TE (minimizes T2 contrast by sampling before significant decay). This combination makes the image primarily reflect hydrogen proton concentration. Long TR/long TE produces T2W, and short TR/short TE produces T1W.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-443", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "In an inversion recovery pulse sequence, the inversion time (TI) is defined as the interval between:", "options": ["The 90-degree excitation pulse and the 180-degree refocusing pulse", "The initial 180-degree inversion pulse and the subsequent 90-degree excitation pulse", "The 90-degree excitation pulse and the echo collection", "Two consecutive 90-degree excitation pulses"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In inversion recovery, the inversion time (TI) is the interval between the initial 180-degree inversion pulse and the subsequent 90-degree excitation pulse. During TI, longitudinal magnetization recovers from its inverted state. The choice of TI determines which tissue's magnetization passes through zero (null point), enabling selective tissue suppression (e.g., fat in STIR, CSF in FLAIR).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-444", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.5", "stem": "A STIR (Short Tau Inversion Recovery) sequence is primarily used to suppress signal from:", "options": ["Water", "Fat", "Cerebrospinal fluid", "Blood"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "STIR (Short Tau Inversion Recovery) uses a short TI (approximately 150 ms at 1.5 T) timed to the null point of fat, where fat's longitudinal magnetization crosses zero during recovery from inversion. At this point, fat contributes no signal to the image. STIR provides uniform fat suppression regardless of field homogeneity, making it useful when frequency-selective fat saturation fails.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-445", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.5", "stem": "A FLAIR (Fluid-Attenuated Inversion Recovery) sequence is primarily used to suppress signal from:", "options": ["Fat", "Bone marrow", "Cerebrospinal fluid", "Muscle"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "FLAIR (Fluid-Attenuated Inversion Recovery) uses a long TI (approximately 2200 ms at 1.5 T) timed to the null point of CSF, suppressing its bright signal on T2-weighted images. This allows periventricular and cortical lesions that would otherwise be obscured by adjacent bright CSF to become visible. FLAIR does not suppress fat (that's STIR).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-446", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "The specific absorption rate (SAR) in MRI is most directly affected by:", "options": ["The strength of the static magnetic field", "The amplitude of the gradient fields", "The RF power deposited and the flip angle used", "The size of the field of view"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Specific absorption rate (SAR) is most directly affected by the RF power deposited and the flip angle used. SAR increases with the square of the flip angle and is proportional to the RF energy absorbed by the patient per unit mass. Higher flip angles (especially 90 and 180 degrees in SE) deposit significantly more energy than low flip angles in GRE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "IP-447", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence differs from a spin echo sequence primarily because it:", "options": ["Uses a 180-degree refocusing pulse to generate the echo", "Uses a gradient reversal rather than an RF refocusing pulse to form the echo", "Always requires longer scan times", "Does not use any RF excitation pulses"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences differ from spin echo primarily because they use gradient reversal (reversing the polarity of the frequency-encoding gradient) rather than a 180-degree RF refocusing pulse to form the echo. This allows shorter TE and faster imaging but does not correct for static field inhomogeneities, making GRE sensitive to T2* rather than true T2.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-448", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "In fast gradient echo imaging, a steady-state condition is achieved when:", "options": ["The TR is shorter than both the T1 and T2 relaxation times of the tissue", "The patient remains completely motionless throughout the scan", "All gradient coils are deactivated between excitation pulses", "The flip angle is set to exactly 90 degrees"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In fast gradient echo imaging, a steady-state condition is achieved when the TR is shorter than both the T1 and T2 relaxation times of the tissue. Under these conditions, neither longitudinal nor transverse magnetization fully recovers or decays between excitations, creating a dynamic equilibrium. The resulting signal depends on the T1/T2 ratio and flip angle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-449", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Magic angle artifact occurs in tissues containing highly ordered collagen fibers (such as tendons and ligaments) when these structures are oriented at approximately what angle to the main magnetic field (B0)?", "options": ["45 degrees", "55 degrees", "90 degrees", "180 degrees"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magic angle artifact occurs when highly ordered collagen fibers (tendons, ligaments) are oriented at approximately 55 degrees (the magic angle) to B0. At this angle, dipole-dipole interactions that normally cause rapid T2 decay in collagen are minimized, artificially prolonging T2 and causing these structures to appear bright on short-TE sequences, potentially mimicking pathology.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 279"}, {"id": "IP-450", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Increasing the number of excitations (NEX/NSA) directly affects:", "options": ["Both scan time and signal-to-noise ratio", "Spatial resolution only", "Scan time only, with no effect on image quality", "Contrast resolution only"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing NEX/NSA directly affects both scan time (doubles with each doubling of NEX) and signal-to-noise ratio (increases by the square root of NEX). Doubling NEX increases SNR by approximately 41%. NEX does not affect spatial resolution, which depends on matrix, FOV, and slice thickness. It does not affect contrast resolution independently.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-451", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Doubling the number of signal averages (NEX) increases the signal-to-noise ratio by a factor of approximately:", "options": ["1.41 (the square root of 2)", "2.0", "4.0", "0.10 (10%)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SNR increases by the square root of NEX. Doubling NEX: sqrt(2) = approximately 1.41, or a 41% increase. This sublinear relationship means diminishing returns from additional averages. Quadrupling NEX would be needed to double SNR. The 41% improvement must be weighed against the doubled scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-452", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following parameter changes will decrease scan time?", "options": ["Increasing the repetition time", "Increasing the number of signal averages", "Decreasing the number of phase-encoding steps", "Decreasing the field of view without changing the matrix"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Scan time = TR x phase-encoding steps x NSA. Decreasing the number of phase-encoding steps directly reduces scan time proportionally. Increasing TR lengthens scan time, increasing NSA lengthens it, and decreasing FOV alone (without changing matrix) does not affect scan time because the number of phase steps remains the same.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-453", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Which of the following adjustments would increase the spatial resolution of an MR image?", "options": ["Increasing the slice thickness", "Increasing the acquisition matrix size", "Decreasing the number of phase-encoding steps", "Increasing the field of view"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the acquisition matrix size increases spatial resolution by dividing the FOV into more pixels, creating smaller pixel dimensions that can resolve finer anatomic detail. Increasing slice thickness reduces through-plane resolution, decreasing phase steps reduces resolution in that direction, and increasing FOV increases pixel size and reduces resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-454", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.8", "stem": "If the field of view is reduced by half while the matrix size remains unchanged, the pixel size will:", "options": ["Double", "Quadruple", "Decrease by half", "Remain the same"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Pixel size equals FOV divided by matrix size. If the FOV is halved while the matrix stays the same, pixel size decreases by half. Smaller pixels mean better spatial resolution but reduced SNR (smaller voxels contain fewer signal-producing protons). This is a common method for improving resolution when the anatomy permits a smaller FOV.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-455", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Decreasing the voxel size in an MRI acquisition will result in:", "options": ["Higher signal-to-noise ratio", "Lower signal-to-noise ratio", "No change in signal-to-noise ratio", "Faster scan time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Decreasing voxel size reduces SNR because smaller voxels contain fewer hydrogen protons to produce signal. SNR is directly proportional to voxel volume. This is the fundamental resolution-SNR trade-off in MRI: higher resolution requires smaller voxels with inherently less signal. Compensation strategies include increasing NEX or using a surface coil.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-456", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "The receive bandwidth in MRI refers to the:", "options": ["Range of frequencies sampled during echo acquisition", "Strength of the static magnetic field", "Speed at which gradients are switched", "Thickness of the selected imaging slice"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Receive (receiver) bandwidth refers to the range of frequencies sampled during echo acquisition — the total frequency window the receiver is tuned to detect. It determines the frequency range assigned to each pixel along the readout direction. It does not relate to field strength, gradient speed, or slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-457", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "Increasing the gap between adjacent slices helps prevent which artifact?", "options": ["Aliasing", "Cross-talk", "Truncation", "Chemical shift"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the gap between adjacent slices helps prevent cross-talk artifact. Cross-talk occurs when imperfect RF pulse profiles cause excitation to extend slightly beyond the intended slice boundaries, partially saturating adjacent slices. A wider gap ensures that the overlap regions do not affect neighboring slices. This is unrelated to aliasing, truncation, or chemical shift.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-458", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.8", "stem": "A rectangular (asymmetric) field of view is most useful when imaging anatomy that is:", "options": ["Perfectly circular in cross-section", "Significantly longer in one dimension than the other, such as the spine", "Very small and requires maximum resolution", "In constant rapid motion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A rectangular (asymmetric) FOV is most useful when the anatomy is significantly longer in one dimension than the other, such as the spine. By reducing the FOV in the shorter dimension (typically the phase direction), scan time decreases (fewer phase-encoding steps needed) while spatial resolution is maintained. This also reduces phase-direction aliasing for elongated anatomy.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-474", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "In a gradient echo pulse sequence, the slice-select gradient is activated:", "options": ["During the RF excitation pulse", "During the gradient reversal that forms the echo", "Between successive RF excitation pulses only", "Continuously throughout the entire TR period"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a gradient echo sequence, the slice-select gradient is activated during the RF excitation pulse, just as in spin echo. The gradient creates a frequency distribution across the anatomy so that the RF pulse (at a specific frequency band) excites only the desired slice. The gradient reversal that forms the echo involves the frequency-encoding gradient, not the slice-select gradient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-475", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "Proton density-weighted images display contrast based on:", "options": ["The relative hydrogen content of tissues — structures with more mobile hydrogen protons appear brighter, while those with fewer appear darker", "Differences in T1 relaxation times between tissues", "Differences in T2 decay rates between tissues", "The magnetic susceptibility of tissues"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Proton density-weighted images display contrast based on the relative hydrogen content of tissues. Structures with more mobile hydrogen protons (like muscle, fat, and brain parenchyma) appear brighter, while those with fewer (like cortical bone and air) appear darker. PD weighting minimizes both T1 and T2 contributions using long TR and short TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-476", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "Which of the following statements about T2* decay are correct?", "options": ["T2* results from T2 relaxation only", "T2* is always longer than T2", "T2* is caused by magnetic field inhomogeneities but is unrelated to T2", "T2* decay includes contributions from both inherent T2 relaxation and local magnetic field inhomogeneities, and is always shorter than T2"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2* decay combines the effects of true T2 (spin-spin) relaxation with additional dephasing caused by local magnetic field inhomogeneities. Because these inhomogeneity effects add to the inherent T2 decay, T2* is always shorter than T2. Option a is incorrect because T2* includes both T2 and inhomogeneity effects, not T2 alone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-477", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "Which of the following is true regarding gradient echo pulse sequences?", "options": ["They fully compensate for magnetic field inhomogeneities", "Susceptibility artifacts are never a concern", "T2* effects cannot be eliminated because no 180-degree refocusing pulse is used", "They produce pure T2-weighted contrast identical to spin echo"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences use gradient reversals rather than 180-degree RF refocusing pulses to form echoes. Without RF refocusing, static field inhomogeneities are not compensated, so the signal reflects T2* rather than true T2 decay. Option a is incorrect because GRE sequences do not compensate for field inhomogeneities.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-478", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A primary disadvantage of conventional spin echo imaging compared to fast imaging techniques is:", "options": ["Relatively long scan times", "Inferior image quality compared to gradient echo", "Reduced susceptibility artifact", "Inability to produce T1-weighted contrast"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Conventional spin echo acquires only one line of k-space per TR, resulting in relatively long scan times compared to fast imaging techniques like FSE or GRE. Option b is incorrect because conventional SE generally produces excellent image quality with high SNR and true T2 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-479", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "Known disadvantages of fast spin echo (FSE) imaging include:", "options": ["Longer scan times than conventional spin echo", "Bright fat signal on T2-weighted images, image blurring, and flow-related artifacts", "Inability to produce T2-weighted contrast", "Complete loss of signal from cerebrospinal fluid"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "FSE produces characteristically bright fat on T2-weighted images due to J-coupling effects and reduced magnetization transfer, which can obscure pathology. Multiple refocusing pulses can also cause blurring and flow-related artifacts from stimulated echoes. Option a is incorrect because FSE is faster than conventional SE, not slower.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-480", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "Which pulse sequence type is preferred when using respiratory compensation techniques?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Fast spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Inversion recovery"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences are preferred with respiratory compensation techniques because their shorter TR allows more efficient data collection within the respiratory cycle. The rapid acquisition of GRE sequences makes them well-suited for breath-hold and respiratory-triggered imaging. Option a (conventional SE) is incorrect because its long scan times make respiratory compensation less efficient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89; Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-481", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "Which of the following pulse sequence types is known for providing very high signal-to-noise ratio?", "options": ["Inversion recovery", "2D coherent gradient echo", "2D spoiled gradient echo", "Echo planar imaging"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Inversion recovery sequences provide very high SNR because the 180-degree inversion pulse allows full longitudinal magnetization recovery before excitation, maximizing the available signal. The additional RF pulse and long TR contribute to robust signal. Option d (EPI) is incorrect because EPI sacrifices SNR for speed due to rapid gradient switching and T2* decay.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-482", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Which pulse sequence type offers fast acquisition, sensitivity to flow, the ability to acquire 3D volumes, but produces significant acoustic noise?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Fast spin echo", "Inversion recovery", "Coherent gradient echo"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Coherent (rewound) gradient echo sequences offer fast acquisition times, inherent sensitivity to flowing blood, and efficient 3D volume acquisition. The rapid gradient switching required generates significant acoustic noise. Option a (conventional SE) is incorrect because it is slow and impractical for 3D volumes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106; Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-483", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A T1-weighted conventional spin echo sequence is produced using:", "options": ["Long TR and long TE", "Short TR and short TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T1-weighted spin echo images require a short TR to maximize T1 contrast differences between tissues and a short TE to minimize T2 contributions. Typical values are TR 300-700 ms and TE 10-25 ms. Option a (long TR, long TE) would produce T2-weighted contrast instead.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-484", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "A T2-weighted conventional spin echo sequence is produced using:", "options": ["Long TR and long TE", "Short TR and short TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T2-weighted spin echo images require a long TR to minimize T1 contrast and a long TE to maximize T2 contrast differences as tissues decay at different rates. Typical values are TR 2000+ ms and TE 80+ ms. Option b (short TR, short TE) would produce T1-weighted contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-485", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "A proton density-weighted conventional spin echo sequence is produced using:", "options": ["Short TR and short TE", "Long TR and long TE", "Long TR and short TE", "Short TR and long TE"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Proton density weighting requires a long TR to minimize T1 contrast and a short TE to minimize T2 contrast, leaving image contrast predominantly determined by the hydrogen proton density of tissues. Option a (short TR, short TE) would produce T1 weighting due to the short TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-486", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Which of the following are characteristics of partial (fractional) Fourier imaging?", "options": ["It acquires the full k-space dataset and doubles the acquisition time", "It acquires slightly more than half of k-space and uses symmetry properties to estimate the remainder, reducing scan time", "It fills the center of k-space only and discards all peripheral data", "It requires a 3D acquisition volume to function"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Partial Fourier imaging exploits the conjugate symmetry of k-space data, where one half is theoretically a mirror image of the other. By acquiring just over half the k-space lines, the remaining data can be mathematically estimated, significantly reducing scan time. Option c is incorrect because partial Fourier acquires slightly more than half of k-space, not just the center.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-487", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "Which of the following are true regarding conventional spin echo sequences?", "options": ["They use a 90-degree excitation pulse followed by one or more 180-degree refocusing pulses, and they compensate for static field inhomogeneities", "They use gradient reversals instead of RF refocusing pulses", "They always produce T2*-weighted contrast", "They require flip angles less than 90 degrees"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Conventional spin echo uses a 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse that rephases dephasing caused by static magnetic field inhomogeneities, producing true T2-weighted contrast. Option b is incorrect because gradient reversals characterize gradient echo sequences, not spin echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-488", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) in MRI converts:", "options": ["Signal amplitude into spatial coordinates", "Frequency-domain data into the time domain", "Image data into k-space", "Time-domain (k-space) data into frequency-domain (image) data"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The Fast Fourier Transform converts the raw time-domain data stored in k-space into frequency-domain information that forms the spatial image. This mathematical operation is essential for reconstructing MR images from the acquired signal data. Option c is incorrect because the FFT converts k-space into images, not the reverse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-489", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "Which of the following best describes respiratory compensation in MRI?", "options": ["A technique that reorders phase-encoding steps to match the respiratory cycle, reducing motion artifacts", "A technique that requires the patient to hold their breath for the entire scan duration", "A post-processing algorithm applied after data acquisition to remove motion blur", "A gradient modification that eliminates all respiratory motion from the image"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Respiratory compensation works by monitoring the respiratory cycle and reordering the phase-encoding gradient steps so that adjacent lines of k-space are acquired at similar points in the breathing cycle, reducing phase mismapping artifacts. Option b is incorrect because respiratory compensation does not require breath-holding.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-490", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Compared to conventional spin echo, fast spin echo (FSE/RARE) sequences:", "options": ["Always produce lower SNR and poorer contrast", "Can achieve comparable or even higher SNR due to more efficient data collection, though contrast characteristics may differ", "Cannot produce T2-weighted images", "Require longer scan times to achieve the same number of slices"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "FSE sequences collect multiple k-space lines per TR using an echo train, which can result in comparable or higher SNR than conventional SE while dramatically reducing scan time. However, contrast characteristics differ due to the multiple refocusing pulses affecting magnetization transfer and J-coupling. Option a is incorrect because FSE generally produces equal or higher SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-491", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.a", "stem": "The post-processing algorithm that creates a two-dimensional projection image from a three-dimensional dataset by selecting the brightest voxel along each viewing ray is called:", "options": ["Fast Fourier Transform (FFT)", "Physiologic gating", "Maximum Intensity Projection (MIP)", "Phase contrast"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Maximum Intensity Projection (MIP) is a post-processing algorithm that projects a 3D dataset onto a 2D plane by selecting the brightest voxel along each ray through the volume. It is widely used in MRA to display bright-blood vessels. Option a (FFT) is incorrect because the Fourier Transform converts k-space to image data, not 3D to 2D projections.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-492", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In phase-contrast MRA, which of the following factors affect the resulting image contrast?", "options": ["Flow velocity only", "Flow direction only", "Velocity aliasing only", "Flow velocity, flow direction, and velocity aliasing"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Phase-contrast MRA derives contrast from phase shifts imparted to moving protons by bipolar gradients. The resulting images are sensitive to flow velocity, flow direction (determined by the gradient axis), and velocity aliasing (which occurs when velocities exceed the selected VENC). Option a is incorrect because flow direction and aliasing also significantly affect image contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-493", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "MRI uses which type of nonionizing electromagnetic radiation to excite hydrogen protons?", "options": ["X-rays", "Gamma rays", "Radiofrequency energy", "Alpha particles"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI uses radiofrequency (RF) energy in the electromagnetic spectrum to excite hydrogen protons into resonance. RF energy is nonionizing, which is a key safety advantage of MRI. Options a and b (X-rays and gamma rays) are incorrect because these are ionizing forms of radiation used in CT and nuclear medicine.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-494", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "Which of the following are advantages of MRI compared to other imaging modalities?", "options": ["The ability to acquire images in multiple planes without repositioning the patient, and superior contrast resolution", "The ability to acquire images in multiple planes without repositioning, and the use of no ionizing radiation", "Superior contrast resolution and the use of no ionizing radiation", "The ability to acquire images in multiple planes without repositioning, superior contrast resolution, and the use of no ionizing radiation"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "MRI offers multiplanar imaging capability by manipulating gradient directions electronically, superior soft tissue contrast resolution compared to CT and ultrasound, and uses no ionizing radiation. All three together represent the major advantages of MRI. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete, listing only two of the three advantages.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 1; Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-495", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which MRI system designs are suitable for accommodating large or claustrophobic patients?", "options": ["Short-bore and open-bore systems only", "Short-bore and high-field systems only", "Open-bore and high-field systems only", "Short-bore, open-bore, and high-field (wide-bore) systems"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Short-bore systems reduce claustrophobia by shortening the bore length, open-bore systems eliminate the cylindrical enclosure, and wide-bore high-field systems provide a larger diameter opening. All three designs address the needs of large or claustrophobic patients. Options a, b, and c each list only two of the three appropriate designs.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-496", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following is a characteristic of superconducting MRI magnets?", "options": ["They use liquid helium to cool the magnet coils and reduce electrical resistance to zero", "Electrical current flows through the coils without resistance once superconductivity is achieved", "They represent a significant capital investment", "Field strengths are capable of exceeding 2T"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Superconducting magnets are the only magnet type capable of producing field strengths above 2T, with clinical systems operating at 1.5T and 3T and research systems reaching 7T and higher. While all listed options are true characteristics, the ability to achieve very high field strengths is a defining advantage over permanent and resistive magnets.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-497", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following correctly orders magnet types from weakest to strongest typical field strength?", "options": ["Superconducting, permanent, resistive", "Resistive, permanent, superconducting", "Permanent, superconducting, resistive", "Resistive, superconducting, permanent"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Resistive magnets typically produce the weakest fields (up to about 0.3T), permanent magnets operate in the low-to-mid range (up to about 0.3-0.5T), and superconducting magnets produce the strongest fields (1.5T, 3T, and higher). Option a reverses the order, placing superconducting first, which is incorrect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-500", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "An imaging plane that divides the body into anterior and posterior halves is called a:", "options": ["Sagittal plane", "Coronal plane", "Axial plane", "Oblique plane"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The coronal plane divides the body into anterior (front) and posterior (back) portions. In a superconducting MRI system, coronal slices are selected by the Y gradient. Option a (sagittal) is incorrect because the sagittal plane divides the body into left and right halves.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-501", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.14", "stem": "Sir Peter Mansfield and Paul Lauterbur received the 2003 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for contributions to the development of:", "options": ["Computed tomography", "Positron emission tomography", "Magnetic resonance imaging", "Ultrasound imaging"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Sir Peter Mansfield and Paul Lauterbur shared the 2003 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries concerning magnetic resonance imaging. Mansfield developed mathematical methods for rapid MRI acquisition, while Lauterbur introduced magnetic field gradients for spatial encoding. Option a (CT) is incorrect -- Hounsfield and Cormack received the 1979 Nobel Prize for CT.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 1"}, {"id": "IP-502", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Regarding a superconducting MRI system under normal operating conditions, which statement is correct?", "options": ["The static magnetic field is always on, even when no patients are being scanned", "The magnetic field is only activated when the technologist initiates a scan", "The magnetic field is turned off at the end of each workday", "The magnetic field strength fluctuates with patient size"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a superconducting MRI system, electrical current flows perpetually through the cooled superconducting coils with zero resistance, maintaining the magnetic field 24/7 regardless of whether patients are being scanned. Option b is incorrect because the field cannot be turned on and off for each scan -- it requires a controlled ramp-up procedure.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-503", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "When hydrogen protons spin, they:", "options": ["Create a small magnetic field and a magnetic moment", "Create a small magnetic field and lose their electrical charge", "Lose their electrical charge and generate a magnetic moment", "Create a magnetic field, a magnetic moment, and lose their charge"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The spinning motion of a charged hydrogen proton generates a small magnetic field around it and creates a magnetic moment representing the strength and direction of the tiny magnet. Protons do not lose their electrical charge during this process. Option c is incorrect because protons retain their charge.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-504", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The process of producing voltage using magnetic fields is described by:", "options": ["Electromagnetic induction and the Larmor equation", "Electromagnetic induction and Faraday's law", "The Larmor equation and Faraday's law", "Electromagnetic induction, the Larmor equation, and Faraday's law"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction describes the principle by which a changing magnetic field induces a voltage in a conductor. This is the fundamental principle behind MR signal detection in the receiver coil. Option a is incorrect because the Larmor equation describes precessional frequency, not voltage generation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-505", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "Hydrogen protons are used to create MR images because they:", "options": ["Have an odd number of nucleons (giving them net spin) and are abundant in the human body", "Have an odd number of nucleons and carry a negative charge", "Are abundant in the body and carry a negative charge", "Have an odd number of nucleons, are abundant in the body, and are negatively charged"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Hydrogen has a single proton (odd number of nucleons), which gives it a net nuclear spin and makes it MR-active. Hydrogen is also the most abundant element in the body due to the high water and fat content of tissues. Option b is incorrect because hydrogen protons carry a positive charge, not negative.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4"}, {"id": "IP-506", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "In the presence of the main magnetic field, the majority of hydrogen protons align parallel to B0 in the:", "options": ["Low-energy state", "Medium-energy state", "Average-energy state", "High-energy state"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When placed in the main magnetic field, the majority of hydrogen protons align parallel to B0 in the lower-energy state. A smaller number align antiparallel in the higher-energy state. The slight excess of parallel protons creates the net magnetization vector. Option d is incorrect because the high-energy state corresponds to antiparallel alignment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-507", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "Net magnetization in MRI represents:", "options": ["The magnetic moment of unpaired nuclei only", "The measurable total magnetization only", "The balance between spin-up and spin-down nuclei only", "The measurable total magnetization that results from the slight excess of spin-up over spin-down nuclei"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Net magnetization is the vector sum of all individual magnetic moments in a sample. It is measurable because a slight excess of protons align parallel (spin-up) versus antiparallel (spin-down) to B0, creating a small but detectable net magnetic vector. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete descriptions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-508", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "The abbreviation B0 in MRI refers to the:", "options": ["Radiofrequency (B1) field used for excitation", "Static main magnetic field", "Gradient magnetic field", "Net magnetization vector"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "B0 refers to the static main magnetic field produced by the MRI magnet, distinguished from B1 (the radiofrequency excitation field) and the gradient magnetic fields. Option a is incorrect because the RF field is designated B1, not B0.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-509", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.5", "stem": "Magnetic field homogeneity is measured in units of:", "options": ["Line pairs per millimeter (lp/mm)", "Parts per million (ppm)", "Megahertz (MHz)", "Gauss (G)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magnetic field homogeneity is expressed in parts per million (ppm), quantifying how uniformly the field strength is distributed across the imaging volume. A typical clinical MRI requires homogeneity better than 1 ppm. Option a (lp/mm) is incorrect because that measures spatial resolution, not field uniformity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-510", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "The wobbling motion of hydrogen protons around the axis of the main magnetic field is called:", "options": ["Precession", "Magnetization", "Vectoring", "Magnetic moment"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Precession is the wobbling or gyroscopic motion of hydrogen protons around the axis of the main magnetic field (B0), similar to the wobble of a spinning top. The frequency of this motion is described by the Larmor equation. Option b (magnetization) is incorrect because magnetization refers to the magnetic property, not the motion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-511", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "The precessional frequency of hydrogen protons:", "options": ["Is dependent on B0 strength and is the rate of the magnetization wobble, but is not called the Larmor frequency", "Is called the Larmor frequency but is independent of B0 strength", "Depends on B0, is the rate of magnetization wobble, but is measured in Tesla", "Is dependent on B0 strength, represents the rate of magnetization wobble, and is called the Larmor frequency"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The precessional frequency (Larmor frequency) is directly proportional to the external magnetic field strength (B0) as described by the Larmor equation. It represents the rate at which protons wobble around B0. Options a, b, and c are each missing one or more correct attributes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-512", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a requirement for resonance to occur in MRI?", "options": ["Magnetic moments must be precessing around B0", "The applied RF energy must match the Larmor frequency", "The RF energy must disturb the alignment of net magnetization", "The main magnetic field strength must exceed 0.2 Tesla"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Resonance occurs when RF energy at the Larmor frequency is applied to protons precessing in any external magnetic field -- there is no minimum field strength threshold. MRI can be performed at field strengths below 0.2T. Option d states a nonexistent requirement, making it the correct answer to this NOT question.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-513", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "Transverse magnetization in MRI is oriented:", "options": ["Parallel to the main magnetic field (B0)", "Perpendicular to the main magnetic field (B0)", "At a 45-degree angle to B0", "In a random direction relative to B0"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Transverse magnetization lies in the plane perpendicular (90 degrees) to B0. It is created when an RF pulse tips the net magnetization vector away from the longitudinal axis into the transverse plane, where it can induce a signal in the receiver coil. Option a is incorrect because magnetization parallel to B0 is longitudinal magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-514", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The direction parallel to the main magnetic field (B0) in a superconducting MRI system is referred to as the:", "options": ["Longitudinal direction and the transverse plane", "Longitudinal direction and the Z-axis", "Transverse plane and the Z-axis", "Longitudinal direction, the transverse plane, and the Z-axis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) MRI system, the direction parallel to B0 runs along the length of the bore and is designated as both the longitudinal direction and the Z-axis. The transverse plane is perpendicular to this axis. Option a is incorrect because the transverse plane is not parallel to B0.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-515", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "T1 and T2 relaxation processes begin:", "options": ["As excess RF energy is released from the spin system and the RF excitation pulse is discontinued", "As excess RF energy is released and at fixed 10-second intervals", "At fixed 10-second intervals and when the RF pulse is stopped", "As excess RF energy is released, when RF is stopped, and at 10-second intervals"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1 and T2 relaxation processes begin immediately after the RF excitation pulse is turned off and the spin system begins releasing absorbed energy. T1 recovery and T2 decay occur simultaneously but at different rates. Option b is incorrect because relaxation is a continuous process, not occurring at fixed intervals.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-516", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Compared to PET fused with computed tomography, PET fused with MR imaging offers improved:", "options": ["Functional metabolic detail", "Soft-tissue contrast", "Structural bone data", "Patient throughput times"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "PET fused with MRI offers superior soft-tissue contrast compared to PET-CT because MRI inherently provides excellent soft-tissue differentiation. This is particularly advantageous for brain, pelvis, and abdominal imaging. Option a is incorrect because PET provides the metabolic detail in both PET-CT and PET-MR systems.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-517", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.i", "stem": "Which of the following statements about T2 relaxation is correct?", "options": ["T2 relaxation occurs simultaneously with T1 relaxation following the RF excitation pulse", "T2 relaxation measures the time for 63% of longitudinal magnetization to recover", "T2 relaxation is synonymous with spin-lattice relaxation", "T2 relaxation refers exclusively to the free induction decay signal"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "After the RF pulse is discontinued, both T1 recovery (longitudinal regrowth) and T2 decay (transverse dephasing) begin simultaneously but proceed at different rates determined by tissue properties. T2 is always shorter than or equal to T1. Option b is incorrect because 63% recovery describes T1, not T2.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-518", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "Inside the MRI magnet bore, the coil located closest to the patient is the:", "options": ["Shim coil", "Radiofrequency (RF) coil", "Gradient coil", "Superconducting magnet coil"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The RF coil is positioned closest to the patient inside the bore to maximize signal detection sensitivity. Moving outward: RF coil, gradient coils, shim coils, superconducting magnet coils. Option c (gradient coil) is incorrect because gradient coils are located between the RF coil and magnet housing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-519", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The circular opening (aperture) of an MRI gantry is defined by the:", "options": ["Physical size of the magnet", "Strength of the magnetic field", "Dimensions of the x-z plane", "Dimensions of the x-y plane"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The circular aperture of the MRI gantry is defined by the dimensions in the x-y plane, the transverse plane perpendicular to the bore axis (z-axis). The diameter of this opening determines the patient space available. Option a is incorrect because the physical size of the magnet refers to overall external dimensions, not specifically the aperture.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-520", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Short-bore MRI systems typically have a magnet bore length of approximately:", "options": ["75 cm", "100 cm", "125 cm", "175 cm"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Short-bore MRI systems have a typical bore length of approximately 125 cm, significantly shorter than the traditional 160+ cm of early superconducting systems. The reduced length helps decrease claustrophobia and improve patient compliance. Option d (175 cm) is incorrect because that would be closer to a standard-length bore.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-521", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.j", "stem": "Which of the following statements about magnetic susceptibility is correct?", "options": ["Most biological substances exhibit no magnetism whatsoever", "Diamagnetic substances have unpaired orbital electrons", "Diamagnetic substances are slightly repelled by an external magnetic field", "Tungsten, platinum, and gadolinium are examples of diamagnetic substances"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Diamagnetic substances have all paired orbital electrons and exhibit a very small negative magnetic susceptibility, causing them to be slightly repelled by an external magnetic field. Most biological tissues are diamagnetic. Option b is incorrect because diamagnetic substances have paired (not unpaired) electrons -- unpaired electrons characterize paramagnetic substances.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-522", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "When exposed to an external magnetic field, paramagnetic substances demonstrate:", "options": ["A small positive magnetic susceptibility", "A large positive magnetic susceptibility greater than 1", "No magnetic susceptibility", "Permanent magnetization that persists after the field is removed"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Paramagnetic substances have unpaired orbital electrons that create a small positive magnetic susceptibility, causing them to be weakly attracted to an external magnetic field. Examples include gadolinium, platinum, and tungsten. Option b is incorrect because a large positive susceptibility greater than 1 describes ferromagnetic materials.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-523", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.j", "stem": "Which substance is ferromagnetic and would be strongly attracted to the MRI magnet?", "options": ["Platinum", "Copper", "Gadolinium", "Steel"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Steel (an iron alloy) is ferromagnetic and would be strongly attracted to the MRI magnet. Ferromagnetic substances have very large positive magnetic susceptibility and can become permanently magnetized. Options a (platinum) and b (copper) are incorrect -- platinum is paramagnetic and copper is diamagnetic.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-524", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "One Tesla is equivalent to how many gauss?", "options": ["100", "1,000", "10,000", "100,000"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "One Tesla equals 10,000 gauss. A 1.5T clinical MRI system has a field strength of 15,000 gauss, and a 3T system equals 30,000 gauss. This conversion is commonly tested on MRI certification exams. Option b (1,000) is incorrect by a factor of 10.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-525", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "According to U.S. FDA guidelines, the maximum magnetic field strength approved for MRI use in neonates less than 1 month old is:", "options": ["4 Tesla", "3 Tesla", "1.5 Tesla", "8 Tesla"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The U.S. FDA has established 4 Tesla as the maximum field strength for MRI use in neonates less than 1 month old. The lower limit reflects additional caution for the developing neonatal physiology. Option d (8 Tesla) is incorrect because 8T is the FDA upper limit for adults and older children, not neonates.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 346"}, {"id": "IP-526", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Which of the following statements about ultra-high field MRI systems is NOT true?", "options": ["They typically have a closed, cylindrical magnet design", "They are widely used in routine clinical applications", "They provide improved signal-to-noise ratios", "Chemical shift artifact is increased at higher field strengths"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Ultra-high field MRI systems (7T and above) are primarily used in research settings and are not yet widely used for routine clinical applications due to increased artifacts, SAR concerns, and regulatory limitations. They do provide improved SNR but also increase chemical shift artifacts. Option d is actually a true statement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-527", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "To reduce the specific absorption rate (SAR) during an MRI examination, the technologist can:", "options": ["Increase TR and decrease flip angle only", "Increase TR and reduce echo train length only", "Decrease flip angle and reduce echo train length only", "Increase TR, decrease flip angle, and reduce echo train length"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "SAR is proportional to flip angle squared, the number of RF pulses per unit time, and duty cycle. Increasing TR reduces RF pulses per time, decreasing flip angle reduces RF power per pulse, and reducing ETL decreases refocusing pulses per TR. All three together effectively lower SAR. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "IP-528", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.14", "stem": "The shading artifact caused by the dielectric effect at high field strengths is most pronounced in:", "options": ["Tissues with high water content, such as muscle", "Fatty tissue", "Cortical bone", "Blood vessels"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The dielectric effect occurs when the RF wavelength approaches body dimensions at high field strengths. Tissues with high water content like muscle are most affected because water has a high dielectric constant, leading to nonuniform B1 distribution and signal shading. Option b (fatty tissue) is incorrect because fat has a lower dielectric constant.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 276"}, {"id": "IP-529", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "High-field MRI systems (1.5T and above) account for approximately what percentage of the clinical MRI market?", "options": ["30%", "50%", "70%", "90%"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "High-field MRI systems (1.5T and above) account for approximately 70% of the clinical MRI market, reflecting their superior image quality and versatility. The remaining market includes mid-field and low-field systems for extremity or open-bore applications. Option d (90%) overstates the high-field market share.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-530", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Regarding low-field MRI systems, which statement is most accurate?", "options": ["They provide resolution comparable to high-field systems for all clinical applications", "They have limitations in resolution that make them less suitable for some orthopedic and neurovascular studies", "They are the preferred choice for all neurological imaging", "They produce higher SNR than high-field systems"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Low-field MRI systems have inherently lower SNR due to reduced field strength, which limits spatial resolution. This makes them less suitable for applications requiring fine anatomic detail such as certain orthopedic and neurovascular studies. Option a is incorrect because low-field systems cannot match high-field resolution for all applications.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-531", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Permanent MRI magnets are typically constructed from a magnetized alloy containing aluminum along with:", "options": ["Steel and nickel", "Nickel and cobalt", "Cobalt and tungsten", "Tungsten and nickel"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Permanent MRI magnets are typically constructed from an alloy of aluminum, nickel, and cobalt (known as Alnico). This alloy retains strong permanent magnetism once magnetized. Option a (steel and nickel) is incorrect because the standard permanent magnet alloy uses cobalt rather than steel.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-532", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The static magnetic field (B0) of a permanent MRI magnet is oriented:", "options": ["Horizontally from the bore entrance to the back wall", "Horizontally along the long axis of the patient's body", "In a straight line from the magnet bore to the edge of the room", "Vertically, running from ceiling to floor"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Permanent MRI magnets typically have an open design with the magnetic field oriented vertically (from floor to ceiling or vice versa), perpendicular to the patient's long axis. This contrasts with superconducting magnets where B0 runs horizontally along the bore. Option b is incorrect because horizontal orientation describes the superconducting configuration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-533", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following is a characteristic of resistive MRI magnets?", "options": ["They tend to be expensive to operate", "They can be easily turned off by discontinuing the electrical power supply", "They generally have open configurations", "They have high field strengths but low fringe fields"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Resistive magnets generate their field by passing electric current through resistive wire coils. When the power supply is disconnected, the magnetic field immediately dissipates, making them easy to shut down -- an advantage over superconducting magnets. Option a is partially true regarding operating costs but the defining characteristic is the ability to easily turn them off.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-534", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The superconducting coils in an MRI magnet are maintained at cryogenic temperatures using:", "options": ["Specialized electrical cooling systems", "Solid cryogenic materials", "Liquid cryogens, primarily liquid helium", "Synthetic chemical coolants"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Superconducting MRI magnets are cooled using liquid helium to maintain temperatures near absolute zero (approximately 4 Kelvin), at which the coils achieve superconductivity with zero electrical resistance. Modern sealed helium systems minimize helium loss. Option a is incorrect because the primary cooling medium is liquid helium, not electrical systems.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-536", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The static magnetic field (B0) of a superconducting MRI magnet is oriented:", "options": ["Horizontally from the bore entrance to the back wall", "Horizontally along the long axis of the patient's body (the Z-axis)", "In a straight line from the magnet bore to the edge of the room", "Vertically, running from ceiling to floor"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a superconducting (horizontal bore) MRI system, B0 is oriented horizontally along the bore from head to foot, corresponding to the Z-axis. This is a fundamental distinction from permanent magnets where B0 is vertical. Option d is incorrect because vertical B0 orientation is characteristic of permanent open magnets.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318; Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-538", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The seamless conductive enclosure surrounding the MRI scan room that prevents external radiofrequency interference is called a:", "options": ["Fringe shield", "Birdcage coil", "Faraday cage", "Active shield"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Faraday cage is a continuous conductive enclosure (typically copper or aluminum) surrounding the MRI scan room that prevents external RF signals from entering and contaminating the MR signal. Without it, zipper artifacts and other RF interference would degrade image quality. Option d (active shield) is incorrect because active shielding refers to gradient or main field containment, not RF isolation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337; Ch. 8, p. 275"}, {"id": "IP-540", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "The state in which a slight majority of nuclei align parallel to B0 in the low-energy state, while a smaller number align antiparallel in the high-energy state, is called:", "options": ["Equilibrium magnetization", "Net magnetization factor", "Magnetic moment", "Magnitude"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Equilibrium magnetization describes the state in which the slight excess of protons aligned parallel to B0 in the low-energy state creates a net magnetization vector along the longitudinal axis, existing before any RF excitation is applied. Option c (magnetic moment) is incorrect because that refers to the individual property of a single proton, not the collective alignment state.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-541", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "The precessional frequency of hydrogen protons is calculated using the:", "options": ["Faraday equation", "Larmor equation", "Precessional equation", "Magnetic frequency equation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Larmor equation calculates the precessional frequency of hydrogen protons based on the gyromagnetic ratio and external magnetic field strength. For hydrogen at 1.5T, the Larmor frequency is approximately 63.86 MHz. Option a (Faraday equation) is incorrect because Faraday's law describes electromagnetic induction, not precessional frequency.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-542", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "The process of adding electromagnetic coils within the magnet cryostat to improve magnetic field homogeneity is called:", "options": ["Active shimming", "Passive shimming", "Gross field adjustment", "Active shielding"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Active shimming uses electromagnetic coils within the magnet cryostat that carry adjustable currents to fine-tune magnetic field homogeneity. These coils can be calibrated for each patient to optimize uniformity across the imaging volume. Option b (passive shimming) is incorrect because passive shimming uses fixed metal plates rather than electromagnetic coils.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 328"}, {"id": "IP-543", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "The ability to localize MR signals to specific spatial locations within the body was made possible by the introduction of:", "options": ["Contrast agents", "Computer reconstruction algorithms", "Magnetic field gradients", "Scout (localizer) images"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The introduction of magnetic field gradients by Paul Lauterbur was the key innovation that made spatial localization of MR signals possible. Gradients create a linear variation in field strength, allowing signals from different locations to be distinguished by their unique frequencies and phases. Option b is incorrect because reconstruction algorithms alone cannot localize signals without gradients.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-544", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "The cumulative change in magnetic field strength across the bore that forms a straight line from one end to the other is described as the gradient:", "options": ["Angle", "Slope", "k-space trajectory", "Z-space"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The gradient slope describes the cumulative change in magnetic field strength across the bore, forming a straight-line relationship from one end of the gradient to the other. A steeper slope provides faster spatial encoding and thinner slice selection. Option a (angle) is incorrect terminology in gradient field characterization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 129"}, {"id": "IP-545", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "Which of the following statements about the magnetic isocenter is NOT true?", "options": ["The isocenter is the point where the x, y, and z coordinates all equal zero", "The field strength at the isocenter equals that of the main magnetic field (B0)", "Gradient polarity depends on the direction of current through the gradient coil", "The magnetic field strength always decreases regardless of direction from isocenter"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "When a gradient is applied, the field strength increases on one side of isocenter and decreases on the other -- it does not always decrease. The gradient creates a linear field variation with isocenter as the reference point where gradient contribution is zero. Options a, b, and c are all true statements about the isocenter.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 129"}, {"id": "IP-546", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.c", "stem": "The time required for a gradient to ramp from zero to its maximum specified amplitude is known as:", "options": ["Echo time", "Rise time", "Peak strength duration", "Maximum gradient time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rise time is the time required for a gradient to ramp from zero to its maximum amplitude. Shorter rise times enable faster pulse sequences and shorter echo times. Rise time is inversely related to slew rate (slew rate = gradient amplitude / rise time). Option a (echo time) is incorrect because TE is the time from excitation to signal sampling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-547", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Gradient coils used in MRI are typically:", "options": ["Asymmetrical with a 3-terminal configuration", "Asymmetrical with a 2-terminal configuration", "Symmetrical with a 3-terminal configuration", "Symmetrical with a 2-terminal configuration"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI gradient coils are symmetrical and use a 3-terminal configuration: the center tap provides the reference point (isocenter), while the two outer terminals carry current in opposite directions to create the linear field variation. Option d is incorrect because 2-terminal configurations lack the center reference point.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-548", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "In a typical MRI gradient coil, the electrical current:", "options": ["Flows in a single direction through all coil windings", "Alternates direction continuously during the pulse sequence", "Flows in opposite directions in the two halves of the coil to create a linear field variation", "Only flows when the RF pulse is applied"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a gradient coil, electrical current flows in one direction in one half and the opposite direction in the other half. This bidirectional flow creates a linear magnetic field variation across the imaging volume, with the field increasing on one side of isocenter and decreasing on the other. Option a is incorrect because unidirectional current would create a uniform field, not a gradient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-549", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "The three spatial encoding functions performed by gradients in an MRI pulse sequence are:", "options": ["Slice selection and phase encoding only", "Slice selection and frequency encoding only", "Phase encoding and frequency encoding only", "Slice selection, phase encoding, and frequency encoding"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "MRI uses three gradient functions for spatial encoding: slice-select determines which slice is excited, phase-encoding assigns unique phase shifts to rows, and frequency-encoding assigns unique frequencies to columns. All three are required for a complete 2D image. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-550", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "For an axial image of the head in a superconducting MRI system, which gradient axis assignment is correct?", "options": ["X-axis for slice selection, Y-axis for phase encoding, Z-axis for frequency encoding", "Z-axis for slice selection, X-axis for phase encoding, Y-axis for frequency encoding", "Z-axis for slice selection, Y-axis for phase encoding, X-axis for frequency encoding", "Y-axis for slice selection, X-axis for phase encoding, Z-axis for frequency encoding"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "For axial images of the head in a superconducting system, the Z gradient selects the axial slice (along the bore). Conventionally, phase encoding is assigned to the shorter axis (left-right = X) and frequency encoding to the longer axis (anterior-posterior = Y) to reduce scan time and motion artifacts. Option a is incorrect because X cannot select axial slices in a horizontal bore.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-551", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "The use of oblique (combined) gradients in MRI is advantageous because it allows:", "options": ["More complex geometric calculations", "Shorter scan times for all sequences", "Imaging of virtually any body part in any orientation", "Creation of perfectly parallel slices only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Oblique (combined) gradients use two or more physical gradient axes simultaneously, allowing imaging of virtually any body part in any arbitrary orientation. This flexibility is essential for imaging structures that do not align with the standard axial, coronal, or sagittal planes. Option b is incorrect because oblique gradients do not inherently shorten scan times.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-552", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "The phase-encoding gradient is typically applied along the:", "options": ["Longest dimension of the anatomy being imaged", "Shortest dimension of the anatomy being imaged", "Right-to-left direction exclusively", "Superior-to-inferior direction exclusively"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The phase-encoding gradient is typically assigned to the shortest dimension of the anatomy to minimize scan time, since the number of phase-encoding steps directly determines acquisition duration. Fewer phase-encoding steps along the shorter axis means fewer TR repetitions needed. Option a is incorrect because the frequency-encoding direction is usually along the longest dimension.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-553", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The gradient that is activated during signal acquisition and is also known as the readout gradient is the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Slice-selection gradient", "RF gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding gradient is activated during signal acquisition (readout) and encodes spatial information by assigning unique frequencies to different positions along one axis. It is also called the readout gradient because it operates while the echo signal is being sampled. Option a (phase-encoding) is incorrect because that gradient is applied briefly before readout.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-554", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Higher maximum gradient amplitudes allow the technologist to achieve:", "options": ["Thicker slices or lower signal-to-noise ratios", "Thinner slices or lower signal-to-noise ratios", "Thicker slices or smaller fields of view", "Thinner slices or smaller fields of view"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Higher maximum gradient amplitudes allow for thinner slices (because a steeper gradient maps fewer frequencies across a given bandwidth to a narrower slice) and smaller fields of view (because a steeper gradient provides higher spatial resolution per unit distance). Option a is incorrect because higher gradients produce thinner, not thicker, slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330; Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-555", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.d", "stem": "Which gradient system specification describes the fraction of one repetition time (TR) during which the gradient operates at peak amplitude?", "options": ["Slew rate", "Rise time", "Duty cycle", "Echo spacing"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Duty cycle describes the fraction of the repetition time (TR) during which the gradient operates at its peak amplitude. A high duty cycle means the gradient is at maximum power for a larger proportion of each TR, which is important for fast sequences. Option a (slew rate) is incorrect because slew rate describes the speed of gradient switching, not the duration of peak operation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-556", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.13", "stem": "Which pulse sequence is most susceptible to geometric distortion caused by eddy currents?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Fast spin echo", "Echo planar imaging", "Spoiled gradient echo"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Echo planar imaging (EPI) is most susceptible to eddy current-induced geometric distortion because it uses extremely rapid and repeated gradient switching. The fast gradient changes induce eddy currents in nearby conductive structures, causing field perturbations that distort the image. Option a (conventional SE) is incorrect because its slower gradient switching produces minimal eddy currents.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 242; Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-558", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "At clinical field strengths, the radiofrequency (RF) energy used to excite hydrogen protons falls within which region of the electromagnetic spectrum?", "options": ["Infrared", "Microwave", "Radiofrequency (megahertz range)", "Extremely low frequency"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At clinical field strengths, the RF energy used to excite hydrogen protons falls in the radiofrequency (megahertz) range of the electromagnetic spectrum. At 1.5T the Larmor frequency is approximately 63.86 MHz, and at 3T approximately 127.72 MHz. Option a (infrared) is incorrect because infrared radiation has much higher frequencies than those used in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-559", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.i", "stem": "Immediately after the initial 90° excitation pulse in a spin-echo sequence, the MR signal:", "options": ["Gradually increases as longitudinal magnetization recovers", "Decays rapidly due to T2* effects", "Remains stable until the 180° refocusing pulse arrives", "Automatically rephases without further RF input"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Immediately after the 90-degree excitation pulse, the MR signal (free induction decay) begins to decay rapidly due to T2* effects -- the combination of true T2 relaxation and local magnetic field inhomogeneities causes rapid dephasing of transverse magnetization. Option a is incorrect because longitudinal recovery occurs simultaneously but does not produce the initial signal behavior.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 20"}, {"id": "IP-560", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.9", "stem": "When phase oversampling is applied to eliminate aliasing in the phase-encoding direction, the primary trade-off is:", "options": ["Decreased spatial resolution", "Increased acquisition time", "Reduced signal-to-noise ratio", "Loss of contrast between tissues"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Phase oversampling eliminates aliasing by acquiring additional phase-encoding steps beyond the prescribed FOV, but the trade-off is increased acquisition time because more TR cycles are needed. SNR is maintained or slightly improved. Option a is incorrect because spatial resolution is preserved -- only acquisition time increases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-561", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.b", "stem": "Which of the following RF coil types functions exclusively as a receive-only coil?", "options": ["Birdcage coil", "Body coil", "Surface coil", "Quadrature volume coil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Surface coils function exclusively as receive-only coils because their small size and proximity to the anatomy provide excellent sensitivity for signal reception but cannot produce a uniform transmit field. The body coil or a dedicated transmit coil provides the RF excitation. Option a (birdcage coil) is incorrect because birdcage coils can function as both transmit and receive.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-562", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "A linearly polarized RF coil is best suited for imaging:", "options": ["Only the head", "Any regularly shaped body region", "Specific, irregularly shaped anatomical regions", "Only lower extremity joints"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A linearly polarized RF coil transmits and receives along a single axis and is suited for imaging specific, irregularly shaped anatomical regions where its directional sensitivity can be positioned optimally. Option b is incorrect because regularly shaped body regions typically benefit more from quadrature coils, which provide better SNR uniformity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-563", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.c", "stem": "Which statement accurately describes a phased-array coil?", "options": ["It consists of a single large receiver element", "It sacrifices signal-to-noise ratio compared to a single surface coil", "It combines multiple receiver elements to improve SNR and anatomical coverage", "It images less anatomy than a comparable single-element coil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A phased-array coil combines multiple small receiver elements, each providing the high SNR of a surface coil over its local area. The signals from all elements are combined to produce an image with both high SNR and wide anatomical coverage. Option b is incorrect because phased arrays improve SNR compared to a single large coil.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-564", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "A coil design consisting of two flat coil elements positioned parallel to each other on opposite sides of the anatomy is known as a:", "options": ["Phased-array coil", "Helmholtz coil", "Birdcage coil", "Solenoid coil"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A Helmholtz coil consists of two flat, parallel coil elements positioned on opposite sides of the anatomy. This configuration provides a relatively uniform magnetic field between the two elements and is commonly used for imaging structures like the knee or temporomandibular joints. Option a (phased array) is incorrect because phased arrays typically use many small overlapping elements.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-565", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "The proportionality constant that relates a nucleus's angular momentum to its magnetic moment is called the:", "options": ["Faraday constant", "Larmor frequency", "Gyromagnetic ratio", "Signal-to-noise ratio"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The gyromagnetic ratio is the proportionality constant that relates a nucleus's angular momentum to its magnetic moment, and it determines how fast the nucleus precesses in a given magnetic field. For hydrogen, the gyromagnetic ratio is 42.57 MHz/T. Option b (Larmor frequency) is incorrect because the Larmor frequency is the result of applying the gyromagnetic ratio, not the constant itself.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-566", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a reason hydrogen is the primary nucleus used in clinical MRI?", "options": ["It is the most abundant element in the human body", "It has a mass number of 1, giving it a net nuclear spin", "Its signal is easily detectable at clinical field strengths", "It has a very small magnetic moment"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Hydrogen actually has a relatively large magnetic moment for its size, which makes it easily detectable -- a small magnetic moment would make detection more difficult, not easier. The correct reasons for using hydrogen include its abundance in the body, its odd mass number providing net spin, and its strong detectable signal. Option d correctly identifies the false statement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4"}, {"id": "IP-567", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "In a gradient-echo sequence, the flip angle is determined by:", "options": ["The amplitude and duration of the RF pulse", "The amplitude of the RF pulse and the relaxation period", "The duration of the RF pulse and the relaxation period", "The amplitude of the RF pulse, its duration, and the relaxation period"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The flip angle in a gradient-echo sequence is determined by the amplitude (power) and duration of the RF excitation pulse. A stronger or longer RF pulse tips the net magnetization vector through a larger angle. Option b is incorrect because the relaxation period occurs after the RF pulse and does not determine the flip angle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-568", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "The type of tissue contrast displayed on an MRI image is primarily determined by:", "options": ["T1 relaxation time of the tissue", "T2 relaxation time of the tissue", "Proton density of the tissue", "The operator-selected imaging parameters (TR, TE, TI)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The type of tissue contrast (T1, T2, PD weighting) on an MRI image is primarily determined by the operator-selected imaging parameters such as TR, TE, and TI, which control how much each tissue property influences the final signal intensity. While T1, T2, and proton density are intrinsic tissue properties, the operator controls which property dominates. Options a, b, and c each describe only one tissue property.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-569", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "T1 relaxation time is defined as the time required for:", "options": ["63% of longitudinal magnetization to recover following an RF excitation pulse", "Transverse magnetization to lose 63% of its initial amplitude", "Complete recovery of longitudinal magnetization to equilibrium", "The echo to form after the 180° refocusing pulse"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1 relaxation time is defined as the time required for 63% of the longitudinal magnetization to recover following an RF excitation pulse. This represents one time constant in the exponential recovery curve of longitudinal magnetization toward its equilibrium value. Option b is incorrect because 63% signal loss describes T2 decay (transverse), not T1 recovery.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 26"}, {"id": "IP-570", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "The longitudinal plane in MRI is defined as the direction of:", "options": ["The main magnetic field and the net magnetization vector after a 90° excitation pulse", "The main magnetic field and the net magnetization vector before a 90° excitation pulse", "The plane perpendicular to the main magnetic field", "The main magnetic field, and the net magnetization vector both before and after the 90° excitation pulse"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The longitudinal plane is defined by the direction of the main magnetic field (B0). Before a 90-degree excitation pulse, the net magnetization vector (NMV) is aligned along B0 in the longitudinal direction. After a 90-degree pulse, the NMV is tipped into the transverse plane. Option a is incorrect because after the 90-degree pulse the NMV is in the transverse plane, not longitudinal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-573", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which statement regarding T1-weighted image contrast is FALSE?", "options": ["Fat recovers longitudinal magnetization quickly and produces high signal intensity", "Fat appears bright on T1-weighted images", "Cerebrospinal fluid recovers longitudinal magnetization slowly and produces high signal intensity", "Cerebrospinal fluid appears dark on T1-weighted images"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "CSF has a very long T1 relaxation time and recovers longitudinal magnetization slowly, resulting in LOW signal intensity (appearing dark) on T1-weighted images, not high signal. The statement that CSF produces high signal intensity on T1-weighted images is therefore false. Option a is a true statement because fat has a short T1 and appears bright.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-574", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which imaging parameter primarily controls the degree of T1 weighting in a spin-echo image?", "options": ["Inversion time (TI)", "Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "TR primarily controls the degree of T1 weighting by determining how much longitudinal magnetization recovery occurs between excitation pulses. A shorter TR increases T1 contrast because tissues with different T1 values will have recovered different amounts. Option b (TE) is incorrect because TE primarily controls T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-575", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "If the repetition time (TR) in a spin-echo sequence is shortened from 1,000 ms to 500 ms, the resulting image will primarily demonstrate:", "options": ["Enhanced T2 contrast due to increased spin-spin interactions", "Reduced contrast because tissues have insufficient time for transverse decay", "Signal loss in tissues with short T2 relaxation times", "Enhanced T1 contrast due to differences in spin-lattice energy transfer between tissues"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Shortening TR from 1000 ms to 500 ms enhances T1 contrast because less time is available for longitudinal recovery between pulses, amplifying the signal differences between tissues with different T1 relaxation times. Tissues with short T1 (like fat) recover more magnetization than tissues with long T1 (like CSF). Option a is incorrect because T2 contrast is controlled by TE, not TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-576", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "T2* signal decay caused by magnetic field inhomogeneities is most prominently demonstrated on which type of pulse sequence?", "options": ["Spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Inversion recovery", "Fast spin echo"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences are most sensitive to T2* decay because they lack the 180-degree refocusing pulse that compensates for static field inhomogeneities. The signal in GRE reflects T2* rather than true T2. Option a (spin echo) is incorrect because the 180-degree refocusing pulse in SE compensates for inhomogeneity-related dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-577", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "If the echo time (TE) in a spin-echo sequence is increased from 60 ms to 120 ms, the resulting image will primarily demonstrate:", "options": ["Reduced spin-spin interactions between protons", "Enhanced T2 contrast due to greater differences in spin-spin relaxation between tissues", "Darker signal from tissues with long T2 relaxation times", "Enhanced T1 contrast due to differences in spin-lattice energy transfer"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing TE from 60 to 120 ms allows more time for transverse magnetization to decay, amplifying the signal differences between tissues with different T2 relaxation times. Tissues with long T2 (like CSF) retain signal while short-T2 tissues lose signal. Option a is incorrect because longer TE actually reveals more spin-spin interaction differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-578", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which operator-controlled parameter is primarily adjusted to increase the degree of T2 weighting in an image?", "options": ["Flip angle", "Inversion time (TI)", "Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Echo time (TE) is the primary parameter adjusted to increase T2 weighting. A longer TE allows more time for T2 decay differences between tissues to manifest in the image contrast. Option d (TR) is incorrect because TR primarily controls T1 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-579", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "The process in which a hydrogen proton transfers energy to a neighboring proton, contributing to signal decay in the transverse plane, is known as:", "options": ["Spin-lattice relaxation", "T1 recovery", "Spin-spin interaction", "Free induction decay"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Spin-spin interaction (T2 relaxation) occurs when a hydrogen proton transfers energy to a neighboring proton, causing both to change their precessional frequencies slightly. This energy exchange leads to progressive dephasing of transverse magnetization. Option a (spin-lattice) is incorrect because spin-lattice relaxation involves energy transfer to the surrounding lattice, not between protons.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-580", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "T1 (spin-lattice) relaxation and T2 (spin-spin) relaxation are processes that:", "options": ["Occur sequentially, with T1 completing before T2 begins", "Are dependent on one another, with T2 driving T1 recovery", "Occur simultaneously but independently of one another", "Only occur simultaneously in gradient-echo sequences"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "T1 and T2 relaxation occur simultaneously but independently after the RF excitation pulse is discontinued. T1 recovery (longitudinal regrowth) and T2 decay (transverse dephasing) proceed at their own rates governed by different physical mechanisms. Option a is incorrect because the two processes occur at the same time, not sequentially.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-581", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.c", "stem": "T2* signal decay results from the combined effects of:", "options": ["Spin-spin interactions and magnetic field inhomogeneities only", "Spin-spin interactions and magnetic susceptibility differences only", "Magnetic field inhomogeneities and magnetic susceptibility differences only", "Spin-spin interactions, magnetic field inhomogeneities, and magnetic susceptibility differences"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2* decay results from the combined effects of true spin-spin interactions (T2), static magnetic field inhomogeneities, and magnetic susceptibility differences between adjacent tissues. All three contribute to the accelerated dephasing seen in gradient echo images. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete, listing only two of the three contributors.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-582", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.i", "stem": "The initial MR signal generated immediately after a 90° excitation pulse, which decays rapidly due to T2* effects, is called the:", "options": ["Spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Free induction decay (FID)", "Net magnetization vector"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The free induction decay (FID) is the initial MR signal generated immediately after a 90-degree excitation pulse. It decays rapidly due to T2* effects as protons lose phase coherence from both inherent T2 relaxation and field inhomogeneities. Option a (spin echo) is incorrect because a spin echo requires a subsequent 180-degree refocusing pulse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 20"}, {"id": "IP-583", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "In a spin-echo pulse sequence, the interval measured from one 90° excitation pulse to the next successive 90° excitation pulse defines the:", "options": ["Inversion time (TI)", "Echo time (TE)", "Echo train length (ETL)", "Repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Repetition time (TR) is defined as the interval from one 90-degree excitation pulse to the next in a spin-echo sequence. It determines how much T1 recovery occurs between excitations and directly affects scan time and T1 weighting. Option b (TE) is incorrect because TE measures from excitation to echo sampling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-584", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "The term proton density (spin density) refers to:", "options": ["The degree of signal void visible on the image", "The rate at which protons lose transverse magnetization", "The number of protons that contribute to hypointense signal in a tissue volume", "The total number of hydrogen protons present within a given volume of tissue"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Proton density (spin density) refers to the total number of mobile hydrogen protons present within a given volume of tissue. Tissues with high proton density (such as CSF) have more hydrogen nuclei available to contribute to the MR signal. Option c is incorrect because proton density counts the protons that can contribute signal, not those producing hypointense signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-585", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "Which RF flip angle is used to rotate the net magnetization vector entirely from the longitudinal plane into the transverse plane?", "options": ["45°", "180°", "90°", "10°"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A 90-degree RF pulse rotates the net magnetization vector entirely from the longitudinal plane into the transverse plane. This maximizes the transverse magnetization component, which is the source of the detectable MR signal. Option b (180 degrees) is incorrect because a 180-degree pulse inverts longitudinal magnetization rather than creating transverse magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18"}, {"id": "IP-586", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "A pulse sequence that begins with a 90° excitation pulse followed by a series of five successive 180° refocusing pulses to generate multiple echoes within a single TR is known as:", "options": ["Gradient echo", "Inversion recovery", "Fast spin echo (turbo spin echo)", "Conventional spin echo"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Fast spin echo (FSE/turbo spin echo) uses a 90-degree excitation pulse followed by multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses within a single TR to collect multiple echoes (k-space lines) per excitation. With five refocusing pulses, five echoes are collected per TR, dramatically reducing scan time. Option d (conventional SE) is incorrect because it uses only one 180-degree refocusing pulse per TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-587", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "In a fast spin-echo sequence, the initial 90° excitation pulse is followed by five 180° refocusing pulses before the next 90° excitation pulse. How many echoes are collected during each repetition?", "options": ["1", "5", "6", "Depends on the frequency matrix size"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "With five 180-degree refocusing pulses following each 90-degree excitation pulse, five separate echoes are generated and collected within each TR. The echo train length (ETL) equals 5 in this example. Option a is incorrect because conventional SE produces one echo per TR, not FSE with multiple refocusing pulses.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-588", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "In a gradient-echo pulse sequence, the echo is formed by rephasing transverse magnetization using:", "options": ["A 90° RF excitation pulse", "A 180° RF refocusing pulse", "A variable flip angle technique", "Gradient reversal"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In a gradient-echo sequence, the echo is formed by reversing the polarity of the readout gradient, which rephases the transverse magnetization that was previously dephased. Unlike spin echo, no 180-degree RF refocusing pulse is used, so static field inhomogeneities are not compensated. Option b is incorrect because 180-degree RF pulses are used in spin echo, not gradient echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-589", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "A pulse sequence that begins with a 180° inversion pulse, followed by a 90° excitation pulse, and then a 180° refocusing pulse to suppress specific tissue types and enhance contrast is called:", "options": ["Steady-state gradient echo", "Spoiled gradient echo", "Fast spin echo", "Inversion recovery"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Inversion recovery sequences begin with a 180-degree inversion pulse that flips longitudinal magnetization, followed by a delay (TI) allowing selective tissue nulling, then a 90-degree excitation pulse and 180-degree refocusing pulse to form the echo. STIR and FLAIR are common IR variants. Option c (FSE) is incorrect because FSE does not begin with an inversion pulse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-590", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "To obtain T1-weighted contrast on a gradient-echo sequence, the technologist should select:", "options": ["A small flip angle, short TE, and short TR", "A large flip angle, short TE, and short TR", "A small flip angle, long TE, and long TR", "A large flip angle, long TE, and long TR"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T1-weighted contrast on a gradient-echo sequence requires a large flip angle (to create substantial T1 contrast), short TE (to minimize T2* effects), and short TR (to maximize T1 differences between tissues). Option a is incorrect because a small flip angle reduces T1 weighting and moves toward proton density or T2* contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-591", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of steady-state free precession (SSFP) imaging?", "options": ["Flip angles of approximately 30° to 45°", "Very short repetition times (TR)", "Long repetition times exceeding 50 ms", "Rapid image acquisition"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "SSFP sequences are characterized by very short TR (typically less than 10 ms), moderate flip angles (30-45 degrees), and rapid image acquisition. Long TR exceeding 50 ms is NOT characteristic of SSFP -- in fact, maintaining a very short TR is essential for establishing the steady state. Option c correctly identifies the false statement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-592", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.4", "stem": "To produce a gradient-echo image with T2*-weighted contrast, the technologist should adjust which of the following parameters?", "options": ["Only the flip angle", "Only the echo time (TE)", "Only the proton density", "Both the flip angle and echo time (TE)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2*-weighted gradient echo contrast requires both a small flip angle (to reduce T1 weighting) and a long TE (to allow T2* decay differences to manifest). Adjusting both parameters together produces the desired susceptibility-sensitive contrast. Option a is incorrect because flip angle alone does not create T2* weighting without an appropriately long TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-593", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "The primary advantage of selecting a gradient-echo sequence over a conventional spin-echo sequence is:", "options": ["Superior image quality", "Fewer imaging artifacts", "Faster image acquisition time", "Ability to produce true T2-weighted images"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The primary advantage of gradient echo over conventional spin echo is faster image acquisition time. GRE sequences use smaller flip angles and shorter TR values, allowing rapid data collection. This speed advantage makes GRE essential for breath-hold imaging, dynamic contrast studies, and 3D acquisitions. Option a is incorrect because SE generally produces superior image quality with fewer artifacts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-594", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "Which statement about hydrogen nuclei is NOT true?", "options": ["In the absence of an external magnetic field, they spin randomly at different speeds and orientations", "They possess angular momentum (spin) about their axes", "They naturally produce a net magnetization without an external magnetic field", "They precess when placed within an external magnetic field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Without an external magnetic field, hydrogen nuclei spin and precess randomly but do not produce a net magnetization -- the random orientations cancel each other out. A net magnetization vector only forms when an external field (B0) causes a slight preferential alignment. Option c correctly identifies the false statement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-595", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "Net magnetization in MRI is created when:", "options": ["Hydrogen protons align in the high-energy (anti-parallel) state only", "Equal numbers of low-energy and high-energy protons cancel each other out", "Paired low-energy and high-energy nuclei sum to produce signal", "A slight excess of hydrogen protons align parallel to the external magnetic field (B0)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Net magnetization is created when a slight excess of hydrogen protons align parallel (spin-up, low-energy state) to B0 compared to those aligned antiparallel (spin-down, high-energy state). This small population difference produces the measurable net magnetization vector. Option a is incorrect because anti-parallel alignment alone would not create net magnetization in the B0 direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-596", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "Which statement correctly describes the Larmor equation?", "options": ["The precessional rate is a fixed constant regardless of field strength", "Precessional frequency equals the gyromagnetic ratio of hydrogen multiplied by the magnetic field strength", "The gyromagnetic ratio varies in proportion to the magnetic field strength", "Precessional frequency is measured in kilohertz (kHz)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Larmor equation states that the precessional frequency equals the gyromagnetic ratio multiplied by the magnetic field strength (omega = gamma x B0). This relationship shows that frequency increases linearly with field strength. Option a is incorrect because precessional rate changes with field strength -- it is not a fixed constant.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-597", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "At clinical MRI field strengths (0.2T to 3.0T), the Larmor frequency of hydrogen falls approximately within which range?", "options": ["1 to 20 MHz", "20 to 40 MHz", "8 to 128 MHz", "200 to 400 MHz"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At 0.2T, the Larmor frequency of hydrogen is approximately 8.5 MHz, and at 3.0T it is approximately 127.7 MHz, placing the clinical range at approximately 8 to 128 MHz. Option a (1-20 MHz) is too narrow and misses the high end, while option d (200-400 MHz) is far above clinical frequencies.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-598", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which operator-selected parameter primarily controls the amount of T1 weighting in a spin-echo image?", "options": ["Inversion time (TI)", "Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "TR primarily controls T1 weighting by determining how much longitudinal magnetization recovery occurs between excitation pulses. A shorter TR increases T1 contrast because tissues with different T1 values have recovered different amounts. Option b (TE) is incorrect because TE primarily controls T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-599", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Repetition time (TR) and echo time (TE) are measured in which unit?", "options": ["Megahertz (MHz)", "Minutes (min)", "Milliseconds (ms)", "Milliampere-seconds (mAs)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "TR and TE are measured in milliseconds (ms). Typical clinical values range from 300-8000+ ms for TR and 10-200+ ms for TE. Option a (MHz) is incorrect because megahertz measures frequency, such as the Larmor frequency, not timing parameters.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-600", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "For a T2-weighted spin-echo image, which echo time (TE) value would be most appropriate?", "options": ["Greater than 2,000 ms", "Approximately 1,000 ms", "100 to 500 ms", "80 to 90 ms"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "For T2-weighted spin echo imaging, appropriate TE values are typically 80-120 ms or longer. A TE of 80-90 ms provides sufficient time for T2 decay differences between tissues to generate T2 contrast while maintaining adequate signal. Option a (>2000 ms) is incorrect because that value is appropriate for TR in T2-weighted imaging, not TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-601", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "On a proton density-weighted spin-echo image (long TR, short TE), which of the following tissue signal characteristics is expected?", "options": ["CSF appears dark and fat appears bright", "CSF appears bright and fat appears dark", "Both CSF and fat appear bright", "Both CSF and fat appear dark"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "On a PD-weighted image (long TR, short TE), CSF appears relatively dark because PD weighting minimizes T2 contributions (short TE), and CSF's signal is primarily T2-dependent. Fat appears bright because it has high proton density. Option c is incorrect because CSF does not appear bright on PD-weighted images with short TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-602", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "1.B.3.d", "stem": "The specific hydrogen protons that are excited during an MRI scan are selected by:", "options": ["Using different RF frequencies for each anatomical region", "Applying a magnetic field gradient to create spatially varying resonant frequencies", "Ensuring the anatomy is centered within the magnet bore", "Selecting the body part on the scanner console"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A magnetic field gradient creates a linear variation in field strength across the body, causing hydrogen protons at different locations to precess at different frequencies. By tuning the RF pulse to a specific frequency band, only protons within a corresponding slice are excited. Option a is incorrect because different RF frequencies select different slice positions via the gradient, not different anatomical regions independently.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-603", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "Which statement about phase encoding is NOT true?", "options": ["Applying a phase-encoding gradient helps spatially locate each pixel along one axis", "The phase-encoding gradient is applied after the slice-selection gradient", "The phase-encoding gradient is applied before slice selection", "The number of phase-encoding steps directly affects spatial resolution"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The phase-encoding gradient is applied AFTER slice selection (not before). The correct sequence is: slice-selection gradient during RF excitation, then phase-encoding gradient to impart position-dependent phase shifts, then frequency-encoding gradient during readout. Option c correctly identifies the false statement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-604", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.12", "stem": "The total number of repetitions (TR cycles) required to complete a pulse sequence is determined by the:", "options": ["Dimensions of k-space", "Fourier transform algorithm", "Frequency matrix size", "Phase matrix size"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The phase matrix size determines the total number of TR cycles required to complete a pulse sequence. Each TR cycle acquires one line of k-space (in conventional sequences), and the number of phase-encoding lines equals the phase matrix dimension. Option c (frequency matrix) is incorrect because frequency encoding occurs within each readout and does not add TR cycles.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-605", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "If an image were reconstructed using only data from the center of k-space, the result would demonstrate:", "options": ["Excellent contrast but poor spatial resolution", "Excellent contrast and prolonged scan times", "Poor spatial resolution and prolonged scan times", "Excellent contrast, poor spatial resolution, and prolonged scan times"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The center of k-space contains low spatial frequency data that determines overall image contrast and signal intensity, while peripheral k-space contains high-frequency data that defines edges and fine detail. Reconstructing from center-only data yields good contrast but poor spatial resolution. Option b is incorrect because using less data actually reduces scan time, not prolongs it.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-606", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Centric k-space filling, which acquires lines beginning at the center of k-space with the shallowest phase-encoding gradients first, primarily improves:", "options": ["Spatial resolution", "Echo spacing", "Signal-to-noise ratio", "Image contrast"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Centric k-space filling acquires the contrast-determining central lines first, when the magnetization preparation (such as contrast agent bolus or inversion recovery) has maximum effect. This timing optimizes the capture of contrast information. Option a (spatial resolution) is incorrect because resolution depends on peripheral k-space data.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-607", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "Which statement accurately describes the effect of increasing the number of signal averages (NSA/NEX)?", "options": ["Scan time increases proportionally", "Signal-to-noise ratio decreases", "NSA is the same as NEF (number of frequencies)", "Increasing NSA is the primary cause of motion artifacts"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing NSA/NEX increases scan time proportionally -- doubling NSA doubles acquisition time. SNR increases by the square root of NSA, not proportionally. Option b is incorrect because increasing NSA increases SNR (by square root of NSA), it does not decrease it.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-608", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.b", "stem": "Which of the following accurately describes gradient slew rate?", "options": ["It is measured in mT/m/ms and calculated from the gradient amplitude divided by rise time", "It is calculated from rise time and is a measure of spatial resolution", "It is measured in mT/m/ms and is a measure of spatial resolution", "It is measured in mT/m/ms, calculated from amplitude and rise time, and is a measure of spatial resolution"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient slew rate is measured in mT/m/ms (or T/m/s) and is calculated by dividing the maximum gradient amplitude by the rise time. It describes how quickly a gradient can reach its peak strength. Option b is incorrect because slew rate is not a direct measure of spatial resolution, though faster slew rates enable sequences that can achieve better resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-609", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "Which of the following is a direct result of increasing the field of view (FOV) while maintaining the same matrix size?", "options": ["Increased signal-to-noise ratio", "Improved spatial resolution", "Decreased voxel size", "Decreased signal-to-noise ratio"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the FOV while maintaining the same matrix size increases the voxel volume (larger pixels), which captures more signal per voxel and directly increases SNR. Option b is incorrect because spatial resolution actually decreases with larger FOV at the same matrix, as pixel size increases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-610", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Increasing the receiver bandwidth of a pulse sequence from 16 kHz to 32 kHz will:", "options": ["Increase echo spacing", "Increase gradient application time", "Decrease signal-to-noise ratio", "Increase total scan time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Doubling the receiver bandwidth from 16 to 32 kHz decreases SNR because a wider bandwidth samples more noise along with the signal. SNR is inversely proportional to the square root of bandwidth. Option a is incorrect because increasing bandwidth actually decreases echo spacing (shorter sampling time), not increases it.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-611", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "In a conventional dual-echo spin-echo acquisition, a single excitation produces images at two different echo times, typically yielding:", "options": ["A proton density-weighted image and a T2-weighted image from the same slice", "Two T1-weighted images at different slice locations", "A T1-weighted image and a T2-weighted image from different slices", "Two identical images used for signal averaging"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a dual-echo spin echo acquisition, a single 90-degree excitation is followed by two 180-degree refocusing pulses at different times, producing two echoes. The short-TE echo yields a PD-weighted image and the long-TE echo yields a T2-weighted image, both from the same slice location. Option b is incorrect because both images are from the same slice.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-612", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "In fast spin-echo imaging, the series of successive 180° refocusing pulses applied within a single TR period is referred to as the:", "options": ["Echo chain", "Echo train length", "Gradient gain", "Refocusing interval"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The echo train length (ETL) refers to the number of successive 180-degree refocusing pulses and corresponding echoes collected within a single TR in a fast spin echo sequence. Each echo fills a different line of k-space. Option a (echo chain) is not standard MRI terminology.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-613", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "Increasing the echo train length (ETL) in a fast spin-echo sequence from 4 to 10, without compensation, will result in:", "options": ["Increased T2 weighting and blurred edges only", "Increased T2 weighting and reduced scan time only", "Blurred edges and reduced scan time only", "Increased T2 weighting, blurred edges, and reduced scan time"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Increasing ETL from 4 to 10 means more echoes per TR: scan time decreases (more k-space lines per TR), T2 weighting increases (later echoes have more T2 decay), and edge blurring increases (later echoes with reduced signal fill peripheral k-space). Options a, b, and c each list only two of the three effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-615", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.B.4", "stem": "T2*-weighted image contrast is produced using which type of pulse sequence?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Inversion recovery", "Fast spin echo"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T2*-weighted contrast is produced using gradient echo sequences because they lack the 180-degree refocusing pulse that would compensate for field inhomogeneities. The resulting signal decay reflects T2* rather than true T2. Option a (conventional SE) is incorrect because SE produces true T2 contrast by rephasing inhomogeneity effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-616", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "3.A.4", "stem": "Which statement about echo planar imaging (EPI) is NOT true?", "options": ["Multiple lines of k-space are filled per TR", "It is highly sensitive to magnetic susceptibility artifacts", "It uses an echo train of multiple 180 degree RF refocusing pulses", "It is one of the fastest pulse sequences available"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "EPI fills multiple k-space lines per TR using rapid gradient switching, not multiple 180-degree RF refocusing pulses. That is the defining difference between EPI (gradient-based echo train) and FSE (RF-based echo train). EPI is extremely fast and sensitive to susceptibility, but uses gradient reversals. Option c correctly identifies the false statement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-617", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.4", "stem": "Which pulse sequence is particularly well-suited for cardiac imaging due to its extremely fast acquisition speed?", "options": ["Echo planar imaging (EPI)", "Fast spin echo", "Conventional gradient echo", "Contrast-enhanced conventional spin echo"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Echo planar imaging (EPI) is particularly well-suited for cardiac imaging because it can acquire complete images in as little as 50-100 ms, effectively freezing cardiac motion. This extreme speed also makes EPI valuable for diffusion-weighted imaging and functional MRI. Option b (FSE) is incorrect because while faster than conventional SE, FSE is not fast enough for real-time cardiac imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-618", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.5", "stem": "On a diffusion-weighted image (DWI), a focus of high signal intensity (bright) in the brain most likely represents:", "options": ["Rapidly flowing arterial blood", "Restricted diffusion consistent with an acute infarct", "Subcutaneous fat", "A ferromagnetic implant"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "On diffusion-weighted imaging, high signal intensity (bright) indicates restricted water diffusion, which in the brain is characteristic of acute cerebral infarction (stroke). Cytotoxic edema from cellular injury restricts the normal random motion of water molecules. Option a is incorrect because rapidly flowing blood typically appears dark on DWI due to signal loss from phase dispersion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-620", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "Which of the following are operator-adjustable (extrinsic) parameters that a technologist can modify to improve MRI image quality?", "options": ["T1 and T2 relaxation times", "T1 relaxation time and field of view", "Field of view and matrix size", "T1 and T2 relaxation times, field of view, and matrix size"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Field of view and matrix size are operator-adjustable (extrinsic) parameters that directly affect image quality. T1 and T2 relaxation times are intrinsic tissue properties that cannot be changed by the technologist. Option d is incorrect because T1 and T2 are tissue properties, not operator-controlled parameters.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 209"}, {"id": "IP-621", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Which of the following does NOT directly affect spatial resolution in MRI?", "options": ["Field of view", "Spatial saturation pulse", "Slice thickness", "Matrix size"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spatial saturation pulses suppress signal from specific regions but do not directly affect spatial resolution. Resolution is determined by FOV, matrix size, and slice thickness. Option b correctly identifies the parameter that does NOT directly affect spatial resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-622", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "Which of the following parameters does NOT directly control image contrast in MRI?", "options": ["Repetition time (TR)", "Echo time (TE)", "Flip angle", "Receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Receiver bandwidth affects the sampling rate and SNR but does not directly control image contrast (T1, T2, or PD weighting). TR, TE, and flip angle all directly determine the type and degree of tissue contrast. Option d correctly identifies the parameter that does not control contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-623", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "The chemical shift artifact in MRI occurs because fat and water protons resonate at slightly different frequencies. Signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) is a separate image quality metric that measures:", "options": ["The difference in resonant frequency between fat and water", "The ratio of desired signal amplitude to background noise in an image", "The spatial separation of fat and water signals along the frequency-encoding axis", "The number of protons contributing to signal within a voxel"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) measures the ratio of desired MR signal amplitude to background noise in an image. Higher SNR produces cleaner images with less graininess. Option a is incorrect because the frequency difference between fat and water describes chemical shift, which is a separate phenomenon from SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-624", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Which of the following techniques can reduce aliasing (wrap-around) artifacts?", "options": ["Increasing the field of view and applying oversampling", "Increasing the field of view and decreasing the magnetic field strength", "Applying oversampling and decreasing the magnetic field strength", "Increasing the field of view, applying oversampling, and decreasing the magnetic field strength"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the FOV ensures anatomy fits within the sampled area (eliminating wrap-around), and oversampling acquires additional data beyond the prescribed FOV to prevent aliased signal from appearing in the image. Together these are the primary techniques for reducing aliasing. Option b is incorrect because decreasing field strength does not address aliasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-625", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.b", "stem": "Which of the following statements about the main magnetic field (B0) are true?", "options": ["It is the primary static field, and increasing B0 increases SNR", "It is the primary static field only", "Increasing B0 increases SNR only", "It is the primary static magnetic field, it is referred to as the static field, and increasing B0 increases SNR"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "B0 is the primary static magnetic field produced by the MRI magnet, commonly referred to as the static field. Increasing B0 directly increases SNR because a stronger field creates a larger spin excess and higher Larmor frequency, both contributing to greater signal. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318; Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-626", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Which statement about the effects of increasing magnetic field strength (B0) is NOT true?", "options": ["Magnetic susceptibility artifacts increase", "Chemical shift artifacts decrease", "T1 relaxation times increase (lengthen)", "T2 relaxation times decrease (shorten)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifacts increase (not decrease) at higher field strengths because the frequency difference between fat and water scales linearly with B0. At 3.0T the frequency separation doubles to ~440 Hz, producing twice the pixel displacement. T1 values lengthen, susceptibility artifacts increase, and T2 values shorten slightly—all true effects of higher B0.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51; Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-627", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.5", "stem": "When imaging a patient with titanium hardware in the region of interest, which combination of parameters helps reduce magnetic susceptibility artifacts?", "options": ["Spin-echo sequence with a shorter echo time", "Spin-echo sequence with a larger voxel size", "Gradient-echo sequence with a shorter echo time", "Spin-echo sequence, larger voxel size, and shorter echo time"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Spin-echo sequences use a 180-degree refocusing pulse that compensates for static field inhomogeneities caused by metal hardware, and a shorter TE limits the time available for susceptibility-induced dephasing. Gradient-echo sequences lack the refocusing pulse, making them highly susceptible to metal artifacts. Larger voxels would worsen, not improve, susceptibility artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-628", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.d", "stem": "An RF coil that functions as both a transmitter and receiver of radiofrequency energy is called a:", "options": ["Receive-only coil", "Transmit-only coil", "Transceiver coil", "Surface coil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A transceiver coil is designed to perform both the transmit (excitation) and receive (signal detection) functions. Receive-only coils detect signal but rely on a separate body coil for excitation. Surface coils are typically receive-only and placed close to the anatomy of interest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-629", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "When the imaging matrix size is increased while field of view remains constant:", "options": ["Pixel size increases and spatial resolution decreases", "Spatial resolution increases and signal-to-noise ratio decreases", "Pixel size increases and signal-to-noise ratio increases", "Spatial resolution increases, pixel size increases, and signal-to-noise ratio decreases"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the matrix while maintaining a constant FOV reduces pixel and voxel size, which improves spatial resolution but decreases the volume of tissue contributing signal per voxel, reducing SNR. Larger pixels would have the opposite effect—lower resolution but higher SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-630", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "A matrix of 192 x 256, where the phase and frequency dimensions differ, is described as:", "options": ["A 3D isotropic matrix", "A 2D non-isotropic (asymmetric) matrix", "A square matrix", "A volume-averaged matrix"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A matrix where the phase and frequency dimensions differ (e.g., 192 × 256) is described as asymmetric or non-isotropic. A square matrix would have equal dimensions (e.g., 256 × 256). Asymmetric matrices save scan time by reducing the number of phase-encoding steps.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-631", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "In a 192 x 256 imaging matrix, the larger value (256) by convention represents the number of data points along which axis?", "options": ["Frequency-encoding axis", "Phase-encoding axis", "Slice-selection axis", "Through-plane axis"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "By convention, the larger matrix value (256) represents the frequency-encoding axis, while the smaller value (192) represents the phase-encoding axis. The frequency matrix does not affect scan time, while fewer phase-encoding steps reduce total acquisition time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142; Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-632", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "Partial volume averaging is worsened by all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Increased voxel size", "Increased slice thickness", "Increased field of view (with constant matrix)", "Increased source-to-image distance"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Source-to-image distance is a radiography/CT concept with no relevance to MRI partial volume averaging. Partial volume averaging worsens when voxel dimensions are large—caused by increased slice thickness, increased FOV with constant matrix, or inherently large voxel sizes—because different tissue types are averaged within a single voxel.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-633", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Increasing the imaging matrix size (with a fixed field of view) primarily results in:", "options": ["Higher contrast-to-noise ratio", "Higher spatial resolution", "Higher signal-to-noise ratio", "Shorter scan times"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the matrix with a fixed FOV directly reduces pixel size, improving spatial resolution. However, smaller voxels contain fewer hydrogen protons, reducing SNR. Scan time also increases because more phase-encoding steps are required.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-634", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "Increasing the number of signal averages (NSA/NEX) results in:", "options": ["Increased phase-encoding ghosting artifacts", "Increased signal-to-noise ratio", "Decreased acquisition time", "Decreased magnetic field homogeneity"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing NSA/NEX improves SNR because coherent signal is additive while random noise partially cancels with averaging. SNR increases by the square root of the NSA factor (doubling NSA increases SNR by approximately 1.4×). The trade-off is proportionally longer scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-635", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Which statement about receiver bandwidth in MRI is NOT true?", "options": ["Bandwidth represents the range of frequencies sampled during the readout", "A wider bandwidth decreases the minimum TE and reduces chemical shift artifact", "A narrower bandwidth increases SNR but also increases chemical shift artifact", "A narrower bandwidth is generally preferred at higher field strengths"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "At higher field strengths, wider (not narrower) bandwidth is preferred to compensate for the proportionally larger chemical shift artifact. Narrower bandwidth increases SNR but also increases chemical shift displacement and minimum TE. Wider bandwidth reduces SNR but decreases chemical shift artifact and allows shorter TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210; Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-636", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Image quality characteristics such as spatial resolution, contrast, and slice profile in MRI are determined by the gradient pulses:", "options": ["Order and timing only", "Order and amplitude only", "Timing and amplitude only", "Order, timing, and amplitude"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gradient pulses are characterized by their order (which determines whether they perform slice selection, phase encoding, or frequency encoding), their timing (which influences TE, TR, and echo formation), and their amplitude (which determines spatial resolution, FOV, and slice thickness). All three attributes are essential for image quality.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-637", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "Which pulse sequence uses a 180 degree radiofrequency refocusing pulse to rephase transverse magnetization and form a spin echo?", "options": ["Echo planar imaging", "Spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Steady-state free precession"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The spin-echo sequence applies a 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse. The 180-degree pulse rephases dephased transverse magnetization, compensating for static field inhomogeneities and producing a true T2-weighted echo. Gradient-echo sequences use gradient reversal instead and cannot compensate for these inhomogeneities.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-638", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Selecting a long repetition time (TR) and a long echo time (TE) in a spin-echo sequence will:", "options": ["Minimize T1 weighting and maximize T2 weighting", "Maximize T1 weighting and minimize T2 weighting", "Minimize both T1 and T2 weighting", "Maximize both T1 and T2 weighting"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A long TR allows all tissues to fully recover longitudinal magnetization, minimizing T1-based contrast differences. A long TE permits differential T2 decay, maximizing T2 contrast. This combination (long TR/long TE) is the classic T2-weighted spin-echo protocol.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-639", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Temporal resolution in MRI refers to:", "options": ["The shortest time interval between sequential image acquisitions that can be achieved", "The spatial detail visible in the frequency-encoding direction", "The signal-to-noise ratio achieved per unit time", "The total scan duration for a complete examination"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Temporal resolution describes the shortest achievable time interval between successive image acquisitions, which determines the ability to capture rapidly changing physiological events such as cardiac motion or contrast bolus dynamics. It is distinct from spatial resolution, which describes the ability to distinguish small structures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-640", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Repetition time (TR) is the primary operator-controlled parameter that determines the degree of:", "options": ["T1 weighting in the image", "T2 weighting in the image", "Temporal resolution", "Flip angle"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR controls T1 weighting because it determines how much longitudinal magnetization recovery occurs between successive excitation pulses. Short TR accentuates T1 differences between tissues; long TR allows full recovery and minimizes T1 contrast. TE controls T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-641", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "In an inversion recovery pulse sequence, the time interval between the 180 degree inversion pulse and the subsequent 90 degree excitation pulse is called the:", "options": ["Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Inversion time (TI)", "Delay time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The inversion time (TI) is the interval between the 180-degree inversion pulse and the 90-degree excitation pulse in an inversion recovery sequence. TI determines which tissue's longitudinal magnetization crosses the null point and is suppressed. TE measures time to the echo; TR is the total repetition interval.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-642", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "An inversion recovery sequence with a long inversion time (TI) of approximately 2,000 ms at 1.5T is used to null the signal from:", "options": ["Fat tissue (STIR)", "Cerebrospinal fluid (FLAIR)", "Muscle tissue", "Gadolinium-enhanced blood"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "FLAIR uses a long TI (~2,000 ms at 1.5T) matched to the T1 recovery time of CSF, nulling its signal. This makes periventricular and cortical lesions more conspicuous. STIR uses a short TI (~150 ms at 1.5T) to null fat. The TI value determines which tissue is suppressed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-643", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "Which statement about flip angle in gradient-echo imaging is NOT true?", "options": ["Flip angle is an adjustable parameter in gradient-echo sequences", "Flip angle selection affects image contrast", "Larger flip angles increase T1 weighting", "Larger flip angles always increase overall image brightness"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Larger flip angles do not always increase overall image brightness. Beyond the Ernst angle (the optimal flip angle for maximum signal at a given TR and T1), further increases in flip angle can saturate the longitudinal magnetization and reduce overall signal. Flip angle selection affects both contrast and signal intensity in gradient-echo imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-644", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents produce bright signal on T1-weighted images primarily because they:", "options": ["Attenuate the radiofrequency signal", "Shorten T1 relaxation times of nearby tissues", "Increase blood flow velocity in vessels", "Bind directly to water molecules and increase their proton density"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium is paramagnetic and shortens the T1 relaxation time of nearby water protons, causing tissues that have taken up contrast to recover longitudinal magnetization faster. This results in higher signal intensity on T1-weighted images. Gadolinium does not directly increase proton density or attenuate RF signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-645", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "The two theoretical frameworks used to explain the fundamental principles of MRI are:", "options": ["Classical physics and fluid mechanics", "Relativity and string theory", "Classical physics and quantum mechanics", "Quantum mechanics and string theory"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI principles are explained using two complementary frameworks: classical physics (which describes the behavior of net magnetization vectors) and quantum mechanics (which describes individual spin energy state transitions). Fluid mechanics and string theory are unrelated to MRI physics.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 1"}, {"id": "IP-646", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "The fundamental building blocks of all matter, including the human body, are:", "options": ["Carbon molecules", "Atoms", "Oxygen molecules", "Ions"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Atoms are the fundamental building blocks of all matter, including the human body. In MRI, the hydrogen atom is of primary importance because of its abundance in biological tissues and its strong magnetic moment due to its single unpaired proton.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-647", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "The types of motion present within an atom include:", "options": ["The nucleus spinning on its own axis and electrons orbiting the nucleus only", "Electrons orbiting the nucleus and electrons spinning on their own axes only", "The nucleus spinning on its own axis and electrons spinning on their own axes only", "The nucleus spinning on its own axis, electrons orbiting the nucleus, and electrons spinning on their own axes"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Three types of motion exist within an atom: the nucleus spinning on its own axis (nuclear spin), electrons orbiting the nucleus, and electrons spinning on their own axes (electron spin). Nuclear spin is the basis for the magnetic resonance phenomenon used in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 2"}, {"id": "IP-648", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.d", "stem": "MR-active nuclei are characterized by their tendency to align their axis of rotation with an applied:", "options": ["Magnetic moment", "External magnetic field", "Angular momentum vector", "Gravitational field"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MR-active nuclei possess a magnetic moment that aligns with an externally applied magnetic field (B0). This alignment creates a net magnetization vector that can be manipulated with radiofrequency pulses to generate the MR signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4"}, {"id": "IP-649", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "An MR-active nucleus that possesses a net charge and angular momentum (spin) automatically acquires a:", "options": ["Magnetic moment", "Static electrical charge", "Gravitational field", "Covalent bond"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A spinning charged nucleus automatically generates a small magnetic field called a magnetic moment. This magnetic moment is what makes the nucleus 'MR-active' and capable of interacting with external magnetic fields and RF energy in the MRI scanner.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 5"}, {"id": "IP-650", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.b", "stem": "The specific isotope of hydrogen used in clinical MRI, consisting of a single proton and no neutrons, is called:", "options": ["Deuterium", "Tritium", "Helium-3", "Protium"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Protium (hydrogen-1) consists of a single proton with no neutrons and is the isotope used in clinical MRI due to its high natural abundance and strong magnetic moment. Deuterium has one neutron, tritium has two, and helium-3 has two protons and one neutron.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 5"}, {"id": "IP-651", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.g", "stem": "The quantum mechanical effect that causes hydrogen nuclei to continuously transition between low-energy (parallel) and high-energy (anti-parallel) states within an external magnetic field is called the:", "options": ["Larmor equation", "Zeeman interaction", "Faraday's law", "Lenz's law"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Zeeman interaction describes how nuclear energy levels split into discrete parallel (low-energy) and anti-parallel (high-energy) states when placed in an external magnetic field. This quantum mechanical effect is fundamental to understanding how nuclei absorb and emit RF energy during MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 6"}, {"id": "IP-652", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "The constant that expresses the relationship between the angular momentum and the magnetic moment of an MR-active nucleus is the:", "options": ["Gyromagnetic ratio", "Larmor frequency", "Zeeman interaction", "Boltzmann distribution"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The gyromagnetic ratio is a nucleus-specific constant that relates the magnetic moment to the angular momentum. For hydrogen, it is 42.57 MHz/T, meaning the precessional frequency is directly proportional to field strength via this constant (Larmor equation).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 10"}, {"id": "IP-653", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.d", "stem": "The phenomenon that occurs when an object is exposed to an oscillating perturbation at a frequency matching its own natural frequency is called:", "options": ["Amplification", "Pulsation", "Resonance", "Excitation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Resonance occurs when energy is applied at the exact natural (precessional) frequency of a system, resulting in maximum energy transfer. In MRI, this means the RF pulse must match the Larmor frequency of the hydrogen nuclei to cause excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-654", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.h", "stem": "The development of phase coherence combined with which process results in coherent magnetization that precesses in the transverse plane?", "options": ["The excitation pulse alone", "Angular displacement (radian shift)", "Return to thermal equilibrium", "Nutation"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Nutation is the process by which the net magnetization vector tips away from the longitudinal axis into the transverse plane under the influence of an RF pulse. Combined with phase coherence among the spins, nutation produces coherent transverse magnetization that can be detected by the receiver coil.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-655", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "According to Faraday's law, the voltage signal detected by the receiver coil in MRI is induced by the precession of magnetization in the:", "options": ["Transverse plane", "Longitudinal plane", "Sagittal plane", "Coronal plane"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "According to Faraday's law, a changing magnetic flux through a coil induces a voltage. The precessing transverse magnetization creates this changing flux in the receiver coil, generating the MR signal. Only the transverse component of magnetization produces a detectable signal because it rotates perpendicular to the coil.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 18; Ch. 9, p. 311"}, {"id": "IP-656", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "After excitation, the process by which hydrogen nuclei release absorbed RF energy and return toward thermal equilibrium is called:", "options": ["Relaxation", "Saturation", "Precession", "Excitation"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Relaxation is the process by which excited hydrogen nuclei release the energy absorbed from the RF pulse and return toward their thermal equilibrium state. This involves both T1 recovery (longitudinal) and T2 decay (transverse), which occur simultaneously but at different rates.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-657", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "The factors that affect MRI image contrast are typically divided into which two categories?", "options": ["Intrinsic and diagnostic contrast", "Diagnostic and extrinsic contrast", "Intrinsic and extrinsic contrast", "Intrinsic, diagnostic, and extrinsic contrast"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI contrast factors are divided into intrinsic (tissue-dependent) and extrinsic (operator-controlled) categories. Intrinsic factors include T1, T2, proton density, flow, and diffusion. Extrinsic factors include TR, TE, flip angle, TI, and b-value.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-658", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "All of the following are extrinsic (operator-controlled) contrast parameters EXCEPT:", "options": ["Repetition time (TR)", "Flip angle", "b-value", "Flow"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Flow is an intrinsic tissue characteristic determined by blood velocity and direction within vessels—it cannot be directly set by the operator. TR, flip angle, and b-value are all extrinsic parameters that the technologist selects on the scan console.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-659", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "At 1.0 Tesla, the approximate T1 recovery time of fat is:", "options": ["200 ms", "500 ms", "1,500 ms", "2,000 ms"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat has a short T1 (~200 ms at 1.0T) because the carbon lattice structure of fat molecules closely matches the Larmor frequency, facilitating efficient energy exchange between hydrogen nuclei and the molecular lattice (spin-lattice relaxation). Water has a much longer T1 (~2,500 ms at 1.0T).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-660", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.b", "stem": "The time constant that describes the duration for 63% of transverse magnetization to dephase in a tissue is called:", "options": ["T1 recovery time", "Relaxation rate", "Flip angle", "T2 decay time"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2 decay time is the time constant for transverse magnetization to decay to 37% of its initial value, meaning 63% has dephased. T2 decay results from spin-spin interactions where neighboring nuclei exchange energy, causing progressive loss of phase coherence. T1 recovery describes longitudinal magnetization return.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 27"}, {"id": "IP-661", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Fat molecules contain hydrogen atoms bound primarily to which two other elements?", "options": ["Carbon and nitrogen", "Carbon and oxygen", "Oxygen and nitrogen", "Silicon and oxygen"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In fat molecules (triglycerides), hydrogen atoms are primarily bound to carbon and oxygen atoms within the fatty acid chains and glycerol backbone. The efficient tumbling rate of these large molecules at the Larmor frequency explains fat's short T1 and relatively short T2.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-662", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Compared to fat, water has:", "options": ["A long T1 recovery time and a short T2 decay time", "Short T1 and T2 times", "A short T1 recovery time and a long T2 decay time", "Long T1 and T2 times"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Water has both a long T1 recovery time (inefficient spin-lattice relaxation due to small molecular size and rapid tumbling) and a long T2 decay time (high molecular mobility reduces spin-spin interactions). Fat has short T1 and relatively short T2 values by comparison.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 32"}, {"id": "IP-663", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.e", "stem": "In MRI, the net magnetization vector (NMV) is considered fully saturated when the flip angle reaches:", "options": ["90 degrees", "45 degrees", "180 degrees", "360 degrees"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "At a 90-degree flip angle, all longitudinal magnetization is tipped into the transverse plane, leaving zero longitudinal magnetization. This state is called full saturation because no further longitudinal magnetization is available for excitation. A 180-degree pulse inverts the magnetization rather than saturating it.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 13"}, {"id": "IP-664", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "The intrinsic contrast properties that determine the signal intensity of a tissue include:", "options": ["T1 recovery time and proton density only", "Proton density and T2 decay time only", "T1 recovery time and T2 decay time only", "T1 recovery time, proton density, and T2 decay time"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The three intrinsic tissue properties that determine MR signal intensity are T1 recovery time, T2 decay time, and proton (hydrogen) density. These properties vary between tissues and pathology, creating the inherent contrast differences exploited by different pulse sequence parameter selections.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 25"}, {"id": "IP-665", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which extrinsic parameter primarily controls the amount of T1 weighting in a spin-echo image?", "options": ["T2 decay time", "Magnetic field strength", "Repetition time (TR)", "Echo time (TE)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "TR controls T1 weighting by determining the recovery interval between excitation pulses. A short TR (~400-700 ms) allows tissues with short T1 (like fat) to recover more signal than tissues with long T1 (like CSF), creating T1 contrast. TE controls the degree of T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-666", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "When a long repetition time (TR) is selected, both fat and water fully recover their longitudinal magnetization, which results in:", "options": ["Diminished T1 contrast between tissues", "Enhanced T1 contrast between tissues", "Increased T2 weighting", "Signal void in fat"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When a long TR is selected, all tissues—regardless of their T1 values—have sufficient time to fully recover their longitudinal magnetization before the next excitation pulse. Because all tissues recover equally, T1-based contrast differences between them are minimized.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-667", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.5", "stem": "Images whose contrast is primarily determined by the apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) of tissues are called:", "options": ["Contrast-enhanced images", "Diffusion-weighted images (DWI)", "Susceptibility-weighted images (SWI)", "Magnetization transfer contrast (MTC) images"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Diffusion-weighted images derive their contrast from the apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC), which measures the random Brownian motion of water molecules. Tissues with restricted diffusion (e.g., acute stroke) appear bright on DWI, while freely mobile water appears dark at high b-values.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-668", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Pathological tissue often contains a high proportion of free water, which makes it most conspicuous on:", "options": ["Proton density-weighted images", "T1-weighted images", "T2-weighted images", "Diffusion-weighted images"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Pathological tissue (tumors, infection, inflammation) often contains excess free water from edema, which has a long T2 decay time. T2-weighted images are designed to maximize contrast based on T2 differences, making these water-rich lesions appear bright and highly conspicuous.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-669", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "In a spin-echo pulse sequence, the repetition time (TR) is defined as the time interval between successive 90-degree excitation pulses applied to:", "options": ["The same slice location", "Different slice locations within the same acquisition", "The entire imaging volume simultaneously", "Only the center slice in a multi-slice acquisition"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "TR is defined as the time interval between successive 90-degree excitation pulses applied to the same slice location. During each TR period, multiple slices at different locations are excited in an interleaved fashion, but TR specifically refers to the repetition cycle for one particular slice.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36; Ch. 5, p. 152"}, {"id": "IP-670", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "Which pulse sequence family is considered the gold standard for most clinical MRI applications?", "options": ["Gradient echo", "Echo planar imaging", "Spin echo", "Steady-state free precession"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Spin echo is considered the gold standard for clinical MRI due to its excellent image quality, versatility across tissue types, true T2 weighting capability (from the 180-degree refocusing pulse), and relative insensitivity to magnetic susceptibility artifacts compared to gradient echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-671", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "All of the following are advantages of spin-echo pulse sequences EXCEPT:", "options": ["Good overall image quality", "Relatively long scan times", "High versatility across clinical applications", "Ability to produce true T2-weighted images"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Relatively long scan times are a disadvantage—not an advantage—of conventional spin-echo sequences. The long TR required for T2 weighting combined with single-line-per-TR k-space filling makes SE inherently slow. Good image quality, high versatility, and true T2 weighting are genuine advantages.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-672", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In MRI spatial encoding, applying very steep phase-encoding gradient slopes reduces the:", "options": ["Image weighting", "Amplitude of the resultant echo", "Total number of phase-encoding steps", "Slice thickness"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Very steep phase-encoding gradient slopes produce large phase shifts across the voxel, causing more intravoxel dephasing and reducing the net signal amplitude of the echo. These steep gradients encode the highest spatial frequencies in k-space, contributing fine detail but lower signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-673", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "In turbo spin-echo (TSE/FSE) imaging, blurring at the boundaries between tissues with different T2 decay times is caused by:", "options": ["Excessive signal enhancement from the refocusing pulses", "Complete signal loss at tissue interfaces", "T2 filtering across the echo train, which smooths edge detail", "Reflection artifacts from the multiple 180-degree pulses"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In FSE/TSE, each successive echo in the echo train experiences additional T2 decay, so later echoes have lower signal than earlier ones. This progressive T2 filtering smooths the transition between tissues with different T2 values, producing edge blurring. Longer echo train lengths worsen this effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-674", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "A spin-echo-based pulse sequence that uses an initial 180-degree inverting pulse to selectively suppress signal from specific tissues is called:", "options": ["Gradient echo", "T1-weighted imaging", "Turbo spin echo", "Inversion recovery"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Inversion recovery adds an initial 180-degree inverting pulse before the standard spin-echo readout. By selecting an appropriate inversion time (TI), specific tissues can be nulled when their recovering longitudinal magnetization passes through zero. This enables selective tissue suppression (fat via STIR, CSF via FLAIR).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-675", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.5", "stem": "Which inversion recovery sequence produces images that are predominantly T1-weighted but display pathology as bright signal due to fat suppression?", "options": ["FLAIR", "Conventional spin echo", "Proton density-weighted imaging", "STIR"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "STIR uses a short TI (~150 ms at 1.5T) timed to the null point of fat's longitudinal recovery curve, suppressing fat signal. The resulting images are predominantly T1-weighted with additive T1 and T2 contrast, making pathology (which typically has long T1 and T2) appear bright against the suppressed fat background.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-676", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "STIR (short tau inversion recovery) is most commonly used and clinically important in which area of MRI imaging?", "options": ["Musculoskeletal", "Contrast-enhanced angiography", "Bone marrow transplant evaluation", "Cardiac perfusion"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "STIR is the workhorse fat-suppression sequence in musculoskeletal MRI because it reliably nulls fat signal regardless of field homogeneity (unlike frequency-selective fat sat). This makes bone marrow edema, fractures, tendon/ligament injuries, and soft tissue pathology conspicuous against the suppressed fatty marrow and subcutaneous fat.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-677", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "The primary purpose of the FLAIR (fluid attenuated inversion recovery) sequence is to:", "options": ["Enhance the signal from cerebrospinal fluid", "Suppress the signal from cerebrospinal fluid", "Suppress the signal from fat tissue", "Enhance the signal from blood vessels"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "FLAIR uses a long TI (~2,000 ms at 1.5T) matched to the T1 of CSF to suppress its signal. By removing the bright CSF, periventricular white matter lesions (such as those seen in multiple sclerosis) and cortical pathology become much more conspicuous than on standard T2-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-678", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "To enhance the visibility of pathology on FLAIR images, which contrast agent may be administered?", "options": ["Iodinated contrast", "Gadolinium-based contrast", "Manganese-based contrast", "Barium sulfate"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium-based contrast can be used with FLAIR sequences to improve detection of leptomeningeal disease, subtle enhancing lesions, and post-surgical changes. The CSF suppression of FLAIR makes even faint enhancement along the meninges or cortical surface more visible than on standard T1-weighted post-contrast images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-679", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "In an inversion recovery pulse sequence, which parameter must be long enough to ensure full longitudinal recovery of all tissue magnetization vectors between successive inversion pulses?", "options": ["Inversion time (TI)", "Echo time (TE)", "Echo train length (ETL)", "Repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In inversion recovery, the TR must be long enough for complete longitudinal recovery of all tissue magnetization vectors before the next 180-degree inversion pulse. If TR is too short, tissues with long T1 values will not fully recover, leading to progressive saturation and loss of contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-680", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "In an inversion recovery sequence, which timing parameter ensures adequate T1 recovery of all tissue vectors and therefore controls the overall T1 contrast?", "options": ["Inversion time (TI)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Echo time (TE)", "Echo train length (ETL)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "TR in an inversion recovery sequence sets the overall time allowed for T1 recovery between inversion pulses. While TI determines which specific tissue is nulled, TR must be sufficiently long to ensure all tissues recover fully, maintaining consistent T1 contrast throughout the acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-681", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "A balanced gradient-echo pulse sequence maintains both residual transverse and recovering longitudinal magnetization in a steady state. This sequence type is also known as:", "options": ["Spoiled gradient echo", "Coherent gradient echo", "Steady-state free precession (SSFP)", "Echo planar imaging"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Steady-state free precession (SSFP) is a balanced gradient-echo sequence that preserves both residual transverse and recovering longitudinal magnetization in a dynamic equilibrium. This produces images with T2/T1-weighted contrast, making fluid appear very bright. Vendor names include TrueFISP, FIESTA, and balanced FFE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-682", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.b", "stem": "In gradient-echo imaging, gradient pulses that are applied specifically to destroy residual transverse magnetization are called:", "options": ["Rewinder gradients", "Spoiler gradients", "Crusher gradients", "Encoding gradients"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spoiler gradients are applied at the end of each TR period to intentionally dephase and destroy residual transverse magnetization. This ensures that only freshly recovered longitudinal magnetization contributes to the next excitation, producing T1-weighted contrast. The opposite approach (rewinding) preserves transverse magnetization for T2/T1 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 109"}, {"id": "IP-683", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "To maximize T1 contrast differences in a gradient-echo sequence, the flip angle should be ________ and the TR should be short:", "options": ["Small (less than 20 degrees)", "Reversed", "Large (70 degrees or more)", "Equal to the Ernst angle"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A large flip angle (70 degrees or more) combined with a short TR maximizes T1 contrast in gradient-echo imaging. The large flip creates significant differences in longitudinal recovery between tissues with different T1 values. Small flip angles produce proton density or T2* weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-684", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a typical TR or TE value used in spin-echo imaging?", "options": ["Long TR: 2,000 ms", "Short TE: 10-25 ms", "Long TR: 6,000 ms", "Long TE: 60 ms or greater"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Standard spin-echo TR values range from ~400-700 ms for T1 weighting to ~2,000-4,000 ms for T2 weighting. A TR of 6,000 ms is atypically long for conventional SE and is more commonly associated with FLAIR or heavily T2-weighted inversion recovery sequences. Standard long TR values are approximately 2,000 ms.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 42"}, {"id": "IP-685", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "The number of TR periods required to reach the steady state in a gradient-echo sequence depends on:", "options": ["The flip angle and relaxation times of tissues only", "The relaxation times of tissues and the TR only", "The flip angle and the TR only", "The flip angle, relaxation times of tissues, and the TR"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The number of TR periods needed to establish the steady state depends on the flip angle (which determines how much magnetization is tipped each TR), the T1 and T2 relaxation times of the tissues (which determine recovery and decay rates), and the TR duration (which sets the repetition interval).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-686", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "In the steady state of a gradient-echo sequence, there is a coexistence of both longitudinal and transverse:", "options": ["Decay", "Resolution", "Magnetization", "Pulse sequences"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In the steady state, both longitudinal and transverse magnetization coexist because the TR is too short for either to fully recover or fully decay. This creates a dynamic equilibrium where each TR maintains consistent amounts of both magnetization components.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-687", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "The steady state in gradient-echo imaging is established when the TR is:", "options": ["Shorter than the T1 and T2 relaxation times of tissues", "Longer than the T1 and T2 relaxation times of tissues", "Equal to the T1 relaxation time of the tissue of interest", "Variable depending on the number of slices acquired"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The steady state is established when the TR is shorter than the T1 and T2 relaxation times of the tissues being imaged. Under these conditions, transverse magnetization from the previous excitation has not fully decayed before the next pulse, creating a persistent blend of longitudinal and transverse components.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-688", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "To maintain a steady state in balanced gradient-echo imaging, the TR should typically be in the range of:", "options": ["5 to 15 ms", "20 to 50 ms", "50 to 100 ms", "100 to 200 ms"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "To maintain a stable steady state in balanced gradient-echo imaging, the TR typically falls in the range of 20 to 50 ms. This range is short enough to prevent substantial T2 decay between excitations while allowing the balanced gradient scheme to refocus all magnetization components within each TR period.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-689", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.b", "stem": "In gradient-echo imaging, spoiling (destroying residual transverse magnetization) is the opposite process of:", "options": ["Coherent gradient echo", "Spin-echo refocusing", "Rewinding (rephasing residual transverse magnetization)", "Flip angle manipulation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Spoiling and rewinding are opposite approaches to managing residual transverse magnetization between TR periods. Spoiling uses gradient or RF methods to destroy it (producing T1-weighted contrast), while rewinding uses a rephasing gradient to preserve it (enabling T2/T1-weighted steady-state contrast).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 109"}, {"id": "IP-690", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "Gradient-echo sequences cannot produce true T2 weighting because the TE is too short to fully measure T2 decay. A minimum TE of approximately how many milliseconds is required for true T2 contrast?", "options": ["60 ms", "70 ms", "80 ms", "90 ms"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "True T2 weighting requires a minimum TE of approximately 60 ms to allow sufficient time for T2 decay differences between tissues to manifest. Gradient-echo sequences typically use much shorter TEs and lack the 180-degree refocusing pulse, so they produce T2*-weighted rather than true T2-weighted contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-691", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "Advantages of balanced gradient-echo (SSFP) sequences include:", "options": ["Good image contrast and loud gradient noise only", "Loud gradient noise and fast scan times only", "Good image contrast and fast scan times", "Good image contrast, loud gradient noise, and fast scan times"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Balanced SSFP sequences provide excellent image contrast (bright fluid, good tissue differentiation) and very fast scan times due to their short TR. Loud gradient noise is an inherent byproduct of rapid gradient switching—a disadvantage, not an advantage, of these sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-692", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.7", "stem": "The phase-directional (Dixon-type) chemical shift artifact does not appear in conventional spin-echo or which other type of acquisition?", "options": ["Gradient echo", "Inversion recovery", "Fast spin echo", "Echo planar imaging"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The phase-directional (Dixon-type) chemical shift artifact, which produces the India ink effect at fat-water interfaces, does not appear in conventional spin-echo sequences because the 180-degree refocusing pulse ensures fat and water spins are rephased at the echo time. In gradient-echo imaging, this effect is TE-dependent, appearing when fat and water are out of phase.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 265"}, {"id": "IP-693", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.9", "stem": "The three-dimensional volume of tissue from which MR signal is acquired and used to calculate pixel signal intensity is called a:", "options": ["Pixel", "Voxel", "Matrix element", "Field of view"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A voxel (volume element) is the three-dimensional volume of tissue from which MR signal is sampled and used to calculate pixel signal intensity. Voxel size is determined by pixel dimensions (FOV/matrix) in the frequency and phase directions multiplied by the slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 209"}, {"id": "IP-694", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "At 1.5 Tesla, the approximate frequency difference between water and fat protons due to chemical shift is:", "options": ["50 Hz", "220 Hz", "440 Hz", "1,000 Hz"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "At 1.5T, the chemical shift between fat and water protons is approximately 220 Hz, calculated from the 3.5 ppm frequency difference multiplied by the Larmor frequency at 1.5T (~63.87 MHz). This frequency difference causes spatial misregistration along the frequency-encoding axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-695", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "In a superconducting MRI system, the Y-axis gradient alters the magnetic field strength along the vertical (anterior-to-posterior) axis of the magnet bore. Which gradient axis and anatomical direction does this correspond to?", "options": ["Y-axis, vertical (anterior-to-posterior)", "Y-axis, horizontal (right-to-left)", "Z-axis, longitudinal (head-to-foot)", "X-axis, horizontal (right-to-left)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a superconducting MRI system, the Y-axis gradient alters the magnetic field along the vertical (anterior-to-posterior) direction. The X-axis is horizontal (right-to-left) and the Z-axis is along the bore (head-to-foot). These physical gradients are combined for oblique imaging planes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-696", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "Gradient coils perform all of the following spatial encoding tasks EXCEPT:", "options": ["Slice selection", "Frequency encoding", "Sequence encoding", "Phase encoding"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gradient coils perform three spatial encoding tasks: slice selection, frequency encoding, and phase encoding. 'Sequence encoding' is not a recognized gradient function. The pulse sequence timing (order of RF pulses and gradients) is controlled by the pulse generator module, not the gradient coils themselves.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-697", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.9", "stem": "Including a gap between adjacent slices in a multi-slice acquisition is important for reducing:", "options": ["Cross-talk artifact", "Chemical shift artifact", "Susceptibility artifact", "Motion artifact"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Including a gap between adjacent slices prevents the overlap of imperfect RF excitation profiles, reducing cross-talk artifact. Without a gap, the edges of one slice's excitation profile can excite tissue in the neighboring slice, causing signal loss and reduced contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-698", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "After a slice is selected in MRI, the signal from within that slice must be spatially localized (encoded) along:", "options": ["Only the frequency-encoding axis", "Both the frequency-encoding and phase-encoding axes", "Only the phase-encoding axis", "All three gradient axes simultaneously"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "After slice selection isolates a specific plane, the MR signal within that plane must be localized in two remaining dimensions using frequency encoding (along one in-plane axis) and phase encoding (along the perpendicular in-plane axis). Both are required for complete spatial localization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 128"}, {"id": "IP-699", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "To achieve a large field of view (FOV) in the frequency-encoding direction, the technologist should apply a frequency-encoding gradient with:", "options": ["A steep slope (high amplitude)", "A long duration", "Maximum slew rate", "A shallow slope (low amplitude)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A shallow (low amplitude) frequency-encoding gradient produces a gentle slope across the imaging volume, mapping a wider range of spatial positions to the available bandwidth. This results in a larger FOV. A steep gradient compresses the spatial mapping, producing a smaller FOV.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-700", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "Spatial localization of the MR signal along the shorter axis of the anatomy within a selected slice is achieved by:", "options": ["Phase encoding", "Frequency decoding", "Triangulation", "Frequency encoding"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Phase encoding is typically assigned to the shorter anatomical axis because the number of phase-encoding steps directly determines scan time. Using fewer steps along the short axis reduces acquisition time while the frequency axis (which does not affect scan time) covers the longer dimension.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145; Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-701", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "In axial images acquired on a superconducting MRI system, the short axis of the anatomy (anterior-to-posterior) typically lies along which gradient axis?", "options": ["X-axis (horizontal/right-to-left)", "Z-axis (longitudinal/head-to-foot)", "Oblique axis", "Y-axis (vertical/anterior-to-posterior)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In axial images on a superconducting system, the short axis of the anatomy (anterior-to-posterior) lies along the Y-axis gradient (vertical direction). The X-axis is right-to-left and the Z-axis runs along the bore in the head-to-foot direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 134"}, {"id": "IP-702", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "The steepest phase-encoding gradient slope (either positive or negative) determines the:", "options": ["Voxel size in the phase direction", "Gradient slope angle", "Pixel size in the phase direction", "Slice thickness"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The steepest phase-encoding gradient slope determines the smallest phase difference that can be resolved, which directly sets the pixel size in the phase direction. Steeper maximum gradients produce smaller pixels and higher spatial resolution along the phase axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145; Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-703", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "Slice thickness in MRI is determined by the combination of the slice-select gradient amplitude and the:", "options": ["Spatial location of the slice", "Transmit bandwidth of the RF pulse", "Phase matrix size", "Slice gap"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slice thickness is determined by the combination of the slice-select gradient amplitude and the transmit bandwidth of the RF pulse. A steeper gradient or narrower transmit bandwidth produces thinner slices, while a shallower gradient or wider bandwidth produces thicker slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-704", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The mathematical process that converts raw frequency data from the MR echo into a spatial image is called:", "options": ["Fast Fourier transform (FFT)", "Repetition time calculation", "Echo time measurement", "Field of view selection"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) is the mathematical algorithm that converts the raw frequency-domain data collected in k-space into a spatial-domain image. Without FFT, the digitized echo data cannot be displayed as a recognizable anatomical image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-705", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "The data collected in k-space contains information about the ________ of each signal and its spatial origin.", "options": ["dead time", "rephasing characteristics", "gradient slope", "frequency"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "k-Space data contains information about the frequency of each signal component and its spatial origin within the imaging volume. The frequency information encodes both the location and signal amplitude of each voxel, which the FFT then converts into a spatial image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 158"}, {"id": "IP-706", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "Which of the following accurately describes the geometry of k-space?", "options": ["Circular with parallel axes", "Triangular with parallel axes", "Rectangular with perpendicular axes", "Circular with perpendicular axes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "k-Space has a rectangular geometry with two perpendicular axes: the frequency axis (horizontal, kx) and the phase axis (vertical, ky). Each point in this rectangular grid stores frequency and phase information that contributes to the final image after Fourier transformation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 159"}, {"id": "IP-707", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.h", "stem": "Data lines located in the upper portion of k-space are referred to as:", "options": ["equal lines", "negative lines", "positive lines", "zero-filled lines"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Data lines in the upper portion of k-space are referred to as positive lines, corresponding to positive phase-encoding gradient amplitudes. The lower portion contains negative lines, and the center line (zero) corresponds to no phase-encoding gradient application.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-708", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.g", "stem": "The time interval during which the frequency-encoding (readout) gradient is active and signal is being digitized is known as the:", "options": ["amplitude modulation period", "sampling window", "data acquisition interval", "radian time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The sampling window is the time interval during which the frequency-encoding (readout) gradient is active and the MR signal is being digitally sampled (analog-to-digital conversion). Its duration is determined by the receive bandwidth and the number of frequency-encoding data points.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142; Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-709", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.3", "stem": "According to the Nyquist theorem, the minimum sampling rate must be at least ________ the highest frequency present in the MR signal.", "options": ["equal to", "twice", "three times", "five times"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Nyquist theorem states that the minimum sampling rate must be at least twice the highest frequency present in the signal to accurately reproduce it digitally. Sampling below this rate causes aliasing, where higher frequencies are misrepresented as lower frequencies.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-710", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.g", "stem": "In MRI, which principle dictates the minimum rate at which the signal must be digitally sampled?", "options": ["The anti-aliasing filter", "The Nyquist theorem", "The frequency matrix size", "The receive bandwidth setting"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Nyquist theorem dictates the minimum rate at which the MR signal must be digitally sampled during the readout period. If the sampling rate is insufficient, frequency aliasing occurs. The anti-aliasing filter is a consequence of applying Nyquist principles, not the principle itself.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-711", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When the MR signal is sampled at a rate below the minimum required by the Nyquist criterion, the resulting misrepresentation of frequencies produces an artifact known as:", "options": ["ghosting", "phase wrap", "aliasing", "chemical shift"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When the signal is sampled below the Nyquist rate, frequencies beyond the sampling capacity are misrepresented as lower frequencies, producing aliasing artifact. This manifests as anatomy from outside the field of view being folded or wrapped into the image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-712", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.g", "stem": "Which of the following statements about the sampling window is correct?", "options": ["It is directly selected by the operator on the scan protocol", "It is automatically determined by the receive bandwidth and frequency matrix", "It remains constant regardless of other parameter changes", "It is identical to the repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The sampling window duration is automatically determined by the receive bandwidth and the frequency matrix size—it is not directly selected by the operator. Wider bandwidth or larger frequency matrix shortens or lengthens the window respectively.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-713", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following does NOT directly affect scan time in a standard two-dimensional acquisition?", "options": ["Frequency matrix", "Repetition time (TR)", "Phase matrix", "Number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The frequency matrix does not directly affect scan time in a standard 2D acquisition. Scan time is calculated as TR × phase matrix × NSA. Changing the frequency matrix alters spatial resolution in the frequency direction and the sampling window duration but not the total scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-714", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A pulse sequence is defined as a coordinated series of RF pulses, gradient applications, and:", "options": ["intervening time periods", "phase modulation steps", "data collection events", "Fourier transform operations"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A pulse sequence is a precisely coordinated series of RF pulses, gradient applications, and intervening time periods that together define how the MR signal is generated, spatially encoded, and collected. The timing intervals (TR, TE, TI) are critical components of this coordination.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 152"}, {"id": "IP-715", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Partial echo, spiral, and single-shot acquisition are all examples of:", "options": ["image reconstruction algorithms", "artifact reduction techniques", "k-space filling strategies", "parallel imaging methods"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Partial echo, spiral, and single-shot acquisition are all k-space filling strategies that determine how and in what order the lines of k-space are sampled. These strategies affect scan time, SNR, and susceptibility to artifacts. They are distinct from image reconstruction algorithms or parallel imaging methods.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-716", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "Which acquisition method collects data from an entire volume of tissue rather than from individual discrete slices?", "options": ["Sequential two-dimensional", "Interleaved two-dimensional", "Three-dimensional volumetric", "Radial"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Three-dimensional (3D) volumetric acquisition excites and encodes an entire slab of tissue using phase encoding in two directions (in-plane and through-plane). This produces isotropic or near-isotropic voxels that can be reformatted in any plane without stair-step artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-717", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Magnetic field strength, voxel volume, and receive bandwidth each independently influence:", "options": ["spatial resolution", "contrast resolution", "signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "scan time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) is independently influenced by magnetic field strength (higher B0 = more signal), voxel volume (larger voxels = more signal), and receive bandwidth (narrower bandwidth = less noise sampled). Each factor can be changed independently to affect SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-718", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.d", "stem": "The amplitude of the MR signal received from a given tissue is primarily determined by the number of:", "options": ["neutrons per voxel", "mobile hydrogen protons per voxel", "electrons per voxel", "pixels in the matrix"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The MR signal amplitude from a given tissue depends primarily on the number of mobile hydrogen protons per voxel (proton density). Tissues with high proton density (water, soft tissue) produce stronger signals than tissues with low proton density (cortical bone, air).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-719", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "The range of frequencies sampled during application of the frequency-encoding gradient is defined as the:", "options": ["phase encoding range", "receive bandwidth", "number of excitations (NEX)", "scan matrix"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The receive bandwidth defines the range of frequencies sampled during application of the frequency-encoding gradient. It determines how many frequencies per pixel are included in the readout, directly affecting SNR, chemical shift artifact, and minimum achievable TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-720", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.8", "stem": "The smallest individual element of a two-dimensional digital MR image is the:", "options": ["pixel", "voxel", "echo time (TE)", "signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A pixel (picture element) is the smallest individual element of a two-dimensional digital image displayed on screen. Each pixel represents the signal intensity of the corresponding voxel. The voxel is the three-dimensional volume element, while TE and SNR are imaging parameters.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-721", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "Contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR) is calculated as the difference in ________ between two adjacent tissues.", "options": ["signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "number of excitations (NEX)", "number of signal averages (NSA)", "repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR) is calculated as the difference in signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) between two adjacent tissues. Higher CNR means better ability to distinguish one tissue from another. CNR depends on both the intrinsic contrast between tissues and the overall noise level.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 226"}, {"id": "IP-722", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "In magnetization transfer imaging, energy is exchanged between restricted macromolecular-bound and mobile ________, resulting in altered T1 recovery times of the mobile pool.", "options": ["ions", "hydrogen protons", "carbon nuclei", "electrons"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In magnetization transfer imaging, off-resonance RF pulses saturate hydrogen protons bound to macromolecules (restricted pool). Energy is then exchanged between these restricted protons and mobile free water protons, altering the T1 recovery times and signal intensity of the mobile pool.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-723", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.5", "stem": "Following gadolinium administration, which fat suppression technique uses a frequency-selective inversion pulse to null the fat signal without affecting contrast-enhanced tissues?", "options": ["SPIR (Spectral Presaturation with Inversion Recovery)", "STIR (Short Tau Inversion Recovery)", "Chemical fat saturation", "Dixon method"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SPIR (Spectral Presaturation with Inversion Recovery) uses a frequency-selective inversion pulse tuned to the fat resonance frequency. Unlike STIR, which nulls fat based on T1, SPIR selectively inverts only fat spins without affecting gadolinium-enhanced tissues that also have short T1 values. STIR suppresses all short-T1 signals including enhanced lesions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-724", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "The ability to distinguish two closely spaced structures as separate and distinct on an MR image, which is primarily governed by voxel size, is known as:", "options": ["partial volume averaging", "spatial resolution", "contrast resolution", "phase variation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spatial resolution is the ability to distinguish two closely spaced structures as separate and distinct entities on an MR image. It is primarily determined by voxel size—smaller voxels yield higher spatial resolution. Contrast resolution measures the ability to differentiate tissues by signal intensity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-725", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Decreasing voxel size in an MR acquisition will:", "options": ["improve SNR but degrade spatial resolution", "improve contrast while decreasing scan time", "improve spatial resolution but reduce SNR", "reduce scan time but degrade spatial resolution"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Decreasing voxel size improves spatial resolution by reducing partial volume averaging, but it reduces SNR because fewer hydrogen protons contribute signal from the smaller volume. This fundamental trade-off between resolution and SNR is central to MRI protocol optimization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-726", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "If the field of view (FOV) remains unchanged and the acquisition matrix is increased, the voxel size will:", "options": ["increase", "decrease", "remain the same", "vary unpredictably"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When FOV remains unchanged and the matrix is increased, each pixel covers a smaller area (FOV/matrix = pixel size). Since voxel size equals pixel area multiplied by slice thickness, the voxel volume decreases. This improves spatial resolution at the cost of reduced SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-727", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "What is the primary effect on image quality when the number of signal averages (NSA) is increased?", "options": ["Decreased signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "Increased signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "Decreased scan time", "Reduced spatial resolution"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing NSA improves SNR by averaging multiple acquisitions of the same data. Coherent signal adds constructively while random noise partially cancels. The trade-off is a proportional increase in scan time (doubling NSA doubles scan time).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-728", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "By approximately what factor does the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) increase when the number of signal averages (NSA) is doubled?", "options": ["2", "√2 (approximately 1.4)", "4", "No measurable change occurs"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When NSA is doubled, SNR increases by the square root of 2 (approximately 1.4), not by a factor of 2. This is because noise is random and only partially cancels with averaging, following a square-root relationship. Quadrupling NSA would be needed to double the SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-729", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "What effect does widening the receive bandwidth have on signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)?", "options": ["SNR increases", "SNR decreases", "Voxel size increases", "Scan time increases"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Widening the receive bandwidth increases the range of noise frequencies sampled, which decreases SNR. However, wider bandwidth offers benefits including reduced chemical shift artifact and shorter minimum TE. The trade-off between bandwidth and SNR is a fundamental protocol consideration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-730", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "Reducing slice thickness while keeping all other parameters constant will result in:", "options": ["increased signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "decreased signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "increased scan time", "improved contrast resolution"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Reducing slice thickness decreases voxel volume, meaning fewer hydrogen protons contribute to the signal from each voxel. This directly reduces SNR. The benefit is improved spatial resolution in the through-plane direction and reduced partial volume averaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-731", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Moving from a lower to a higher static magnetic field strength primarily results in:", "options": ["decreased signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "increased signal-to-noise ratio (SNR)", "decreased spatial resolution", "increased scan time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Higher static magnetic field strength increases the number of hydrogen nuclei in the low-energy (parallel) state, increasing net magnetization and the available signal. SNR increases approximately linearly with field strength (e.g., 3.0T provides roughly double the SNR of 1.5T).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210; Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-732", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.8", "stem": "Partial volume averaging is most likely to occur when:", "options": ["voxel dimensions are large relative to the structures being imaged", "voxel dimensions are small", "receive bandwidth is high", "the acquisition matrix is large"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Partial volume averaging occurs when voxel dimensions are large relative to the structures being imaged, causing multiple tissue types within a single voxel to be averaged together. The resulting signal intensity represents a mixture rather than any individual tissue. Smaller voxels reduce this effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-733", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Aliasing (wraparound) artifact in MRI is a direct result of:", "options": ["oversampling in the frequency direction", "undersampling of anatomy that extends beyond the field of view", "high signal-to-noise ratio", "use of a long repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Aliasing occurs when anatomy extends beyond the defined field of view and is undersampled—the signal from outside the FOV is mapped incorrectly into the image, appearing to wrap around. Oversampling in the frequency direction and increasing FOV are countermeasures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-734", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "Motion-related ghosting artifacts propagate primarily along which encoding direction?", "options": ["Frequency encoding", "Phase encoding", "Slice selection", "Through-plane"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Motion-related ghosting propagates along the phase-encoding direction because phase encoding occurs over multiple TR periods, making it sensitive to periodic motion. Frequency encoding is completed in a single readout and is less affected. Ghost images of moving anatomy appear displaced along the phase axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-735", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Chemical shift artifact occurs primarily because fat and water protons:", "options": ["recover longitudinal magnetization at different rates", "precess at slightly different resonant frequencies", "have significantly different tissue densities", "require different gradient amplitudes for excitation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Chemical shift artifact occurs because fat and water protons precess at slightly different resonant frequencies (3.5 ppm difference). The frequency-encoding gradient cannot distinguish this chemical frequency difference from a spatial frequency difference, causing fat signal to be spatially displaced relative to water.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-736", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.e", "stem": "Which of the following is a direct consequence of increasing the receive bandwidth?", "options": ["Chemical shift artifact is reduced", "Chemical shift artifact is increased", "Scan time is lengthened", "Signal-to-noise ratio is increased"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the receive bandwidth spreads a wider range of frequencies across the same number of pixels, reducing the number of hertz per pixel. Since chemical shift displacement is measured in pixels per hertz difference, wider bandwidth reduces the spatial displacement of chemical shift artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-737", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.a", "stem": "Magnetic susceptibility artifacts are most prominent on which type of pulse sequence?", "options": ["Spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Inversion recovery", "Fast spin echo"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magnetic susceptibility artifacts are most prominent on gradient-echo sequences because they lack the 180-degree refocusing pulse that compensates for static field inhomogeneities. Spin-echo and fast spin-echo sequences use refocusing pulses to correct much of the susceptibility-induced dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-738", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact is characterized by:", "options": ["alternating bright and dark lines paralleling high-contrast interfaces", "a discrete line of signal crossing the image in the frequency direction", "repeating ghost images displaced in the phase direction", "a focal region of signal void near metallic hardware"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact appears as alternating bright and dark lines running parallel to high-contrast interfaces (e.g., the skull/brain or spinal cord/CSF boundary). It results from the finite number of phase-encoding steps used to approximate sharp signal transitions. Increasing the matrix reduces this artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-739", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.6", "stem": "A zipper artifact appearing as a discrete line of signal across the image is most commonly caused by:", "options": ["patient motion during acquisition", "extraneous radiofrequency interference entering the scan room", "a malfunctioning gradient amplifier", "anatomy extending beyond the field of view"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A zipper artifact is a discrete line of extraneous signal crossing the image, most commonly caused by radiofrequency interference leaking into the scan room through a compromised Faraday cage (open door, damaged RF shielding, or nearby electronic equipment). It appears at a fixed frequency position.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 275"}, {"id": "IP-740", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "A technologist notices pulsatile flow artifact from a vessel within the imaging field of view. Which technique specifically compensates for the phase shifts caused by constant-velocity flow?", "options": ["Gradient moment nulling (flow compensation)", "Spatial presaturation pulses", "Shorter echo time (TE)", "Increased number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient moment nulling (flow compensation) uses additional gradient lobes to rephase spins that have accumulated phase shifts due to constant-velocity flow. By zeroing the first moment of the gradient waveform, it compensates for velocity-related dephasing and reduces flow artifact. Sat pulses suppress incoming flow signal instead.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-741", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Increasing the echo time (TE) in a spin echo sequence primarily enhances:", "options": ["T1 weighting", "T2 weighting", "proton density weighting", "diffusion weighting"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing TE allows more time for T2 decay differences between tissues to develop, enhancing T2 weighting. Tissues with short T2 lose signal faster than those with long T2, creating greater contrast. T1 weighting is controlled primarily by TR, not TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-742", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "A spin echo sequence prescribed with a short TR and a short TE will produce images that are primarily:", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "proton density-weighted", "diffusion-weighted"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Short TR limits T1 recovery time, accentuating T1 differences between tissues. Short TE minimizes T2 decay effects. Together, short TR and short TE produce T1-weighted contrast where tissues with short T1 (fat) appear bright and those with long T1 (CSF) appear dark.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-743", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Images acquired using a spin echo sequence with a long TR and a long TE are predominantly:", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "proton density-weighted", "susceptibility-weighted"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Long TR allows full T1 recovery (minimizing T1 contrast) while long TE allows differential T2 decay (maximizing T2 contrast). This combination is the standard T2-weighted protocol where fluid and pathology with long T2 appear bright.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-744", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "When a spin echo sequence is programmed with a long TR and a short TE, the resulting image contrast is primarily:", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "proton density-weighted", "diffusion-weighted"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Long TR minimizes T1 contrast by allowing full recovery, and short TE minimizes T2 contrast by not allowing significant decay. The remaining contrast is determined primarily by proton density differences between tissues, producing proton density-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-745", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.j", "stem": "The magnetic behavior of paramagnetic substances is attributed to the presence of unpaired:", "options": ["atoms", "electrons", "nuclei", "ions"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Paramagnetic substances contain unpaired electrons whose magnetic moments partially align with the external field, producing a small positive magnetic susceptibility. Gadolinium has seven unpaired electrons, making it strongly paramagnetic and an effective MRI contrast agent.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4; Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-746", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.1.j", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT one of the three naturally occurring ferromagnetic elements?", "options": ["Iron", "Nickel", "Aluminum", "Cobalt"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The three naturally occurring ferromagnetic elements are iron, nickel, and cobalt. Aluminum is not ferromagnetic—it is weakly paramagnetic. Ferromagnetic materials have strong positive susceptibility and retain magnetization after removal from the external field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 313"}, {"id": "IP-747", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Clinical MRI scanner configurations currently in use include open systems, dedicated extremity systems, and:", "options": ["permanent magnet systems only", "resistive magnet systems only", "hybrid PET-MR systems", "open-bore (wide-bore) systems"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Current clinical MRI scanner configurations include open systems (C-shaped or double-pillar permanent magnets), dedicated extremity systems, and open-bore (wide-bore) systems that use short, wide superconducting magnets to reduce claustrophobia while maintaining high field strength.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 315"}, {"id": "IP-748", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which of the following are advantages of permanent magnet MRI systems compared to superconducting systems?", "options": ["Higher achievable field strengths and faster imaging speeds", "No external power supply required and no cryogenic cooling needed", "Smaller fringe field and higher signal-to-noise ratio", "Greater field homogeneity and wider bore diameter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Permanent magnet MRI systems require no external power supply and no cryogenic cooling because the static field is generated by permanently magnetized materials. Their disadvantages include limited field strength (typically ≤0.3T) and heavy weight. Superconducting systems achieve higher field strength but require expensive cryogen maintenance.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-749", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In a superconducting MRI magnet, the wire coils are cooled to extremely low temperatures using a substance known as a:", "options": ["halogen", "cryogen", "refrigerant", "coolant"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In superconducting MRI magnets, the wire coils are cooled to near absolute zero using a cryogen—a substance that produces extremely low temperatures. This eliminates electrical resistance in the coils, allowing current to flow indefinitely without an external power source.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "IP-750", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "Which cryogen is used in modern superconducting MRI magnets to maintain the coils at near absolute zero?", "options": ["Water", "Liquid helium", "Freon", "Liquid nitrogen"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Modern superconducting MRI magnets use liquid helium as the sole cryogen to maintain the coils at approximately 4 Kelvin (near absolute zero). Older systems used both liquid nitrogen and liquid helium, but current sealed-system designs use helium only with a cold head recondenser to minimize boil-off.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318; Ch. 10, p. 365"}, {"id": "IP-751", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.4.a", "stem": "Modern gradient coils are manufactured by etching conductive pathways onto the surface of a copper-plated cylinder. This manufacturing approach is known as the:", "options": ["elbow design", "skin design", "fingerprint design", "joint design"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The fingerprint design refers to the manufacturing technique where conductive pathways are etched onto a copper-plated cylinder in a pattern resembling fingerprints. This precise etching allows for optimized gradient linearity and efficiency in modern gradient coil systems.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 330"}, {"id": "IP-752", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.2.a", "stem": "In addition to the host computer, which hardware module is primarily responsible for coordinating the timing of all RF pulses and gradient applications during a scan?", "options": ["Graphical user interface (GUI)", "Pulse generator module (PGM)", "Color display monitor", "Central processing unit (CPU)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The pulse generator module (PGM) is the hardware component responsible for coordinating the precise timing of all RF pulses and gradient applications during a scan sequence. It translates the scan protocol into the exact timing signals needed to execute the pulse sequence.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-753", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.f", "stem": "Which intrinsic tissue characteristic primarily determines image contrast on a diffusion-weighted image (DWI)?", "options": ["The random thermal motion of water molecules", "The concentration of hydrogen protons in the tissue", "The rate at which longitudinal magnetization recovers", "The velocity of blood flow through capillary beds"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Diffusion-weighted imaging contrast depends on the random thermal (Brownian) motion of water molecules within tissue. Tissues where water movement is restricted (e.g., acute stroke, dense tumor) retain signal and appear bright, while tissues with freely moving water lose signal at high b-values.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-754", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.f", "stem": "In tissue affected by cytotoxic edema, how is the diffusion of extracellular water molecules affected?", "options": ["Diffusion becomes completely isotropic", "Diffusion is restricted due to decreased extracellular space", "Diffusion increases due to breakdown of cell membranes", "Diffusion velocity increases proportionally to the swelling"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In cytotoxic edema (e.g., acute stroke), cells swell and compress the extracellular space, restricting the movement of water molecules outside the cells. This restricted diffusion causes the tissue to retain signal on DWI and appear bright, with correspondingly low ADC values.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-755", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.f", "stem": "How does a densely cellular tumor affect molecular diffusion compared to a simple fluid-filled cyst?", "options": ["It allows longer mean free paths for water molecules", "It eliminates the effects of magnetic susceptibility", "It restricts water molecule movement, resulting in less signal attenuation on DWI", "It accelerates proton dephasing, causing complete signal loss"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Densely cellular tumors restrict water molecule movement due to tightly packed cells reducing the extracellular space. On DWI, this restriction causes less signal attenuation (tissue remains bright) compared to a simple cyst where water molecules move freely and signal is attenuated.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-756", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.g", "stem": "Which physiological process is specifically evaluated by MR perfusion imaging?", "options": ["Macroscopic blood velocity in major arteries", "Random thermal motion of extracellular water", "Microscopic capillary blood flow delivery to tissue parenchyma", "Bulk flow of cerebrospinal fluid through the ventricles"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MR perfusion imaging specifically evaluates microscopic capillary blood flow delivery to tissue parenchyma (tissue-level perfusion). This is distinct from macroscopic arterial flow velocity (measured by MRA), random molecular diffusion (measured by DWI), or bulk CSF flow dynamics.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-757", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.g", "stem": "During dynamic susceptibility contrast (DSC) perfusion imaging, what happens to the T2*-weighted signal as the gadolinium bolus first passes through normal brain tissue?", "options": ["Signal intensity increases significantly", "Signal intensity drops transiently", "Signal remains steady while background is suppressed", "Longitudinal recovery rate increases directly"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "During the first pass of a gadolinium bolus through tissue, the concentrated paramagnetic contrast causes local magnetic field inhomogeneities that accelerate T2* dephasing, producing a transient signal drop on T2*-weighted images. This signal-time curve is used to calculate perfusion parameters.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-758", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.2.g", "stem": "Which perfusion parameter represents the average time required for blood to transit through a tissue's capillary network?", "options": ["Fractional anisotropy (FA)", "Cerebral blood volume (CBV)", "Mean transit time (MTT)", "Apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Mean transit time (MTT) represents the average time blood takes to traverse a tissue's capillary network from arterial input to venous output. Prolonged MTT suggests impaired blood flow and may indicate ischemia. Cerebral blood volume (CBV) measures total blood within a tissue region.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-759", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.11", "stem": "The Moire pattern (zebra-stripe) artifact is primarily caused by the combination of:", "options": ["Patient motion and incorrect phase encoding direction", "Main magnetic field inhomogeneity and gradient non-linearity", "Radiofrequency interference and low receiver bandwidth", "Slice cross-talk and insufficient TR"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Moire pattern (zebra-stripe) artifact results from the combination of main magnetic field inhomogeneity and gradient non-linearity, typically at the periphery of the imaging volume. The interference between the actual and expected magnetic field profiles creates alternating bright and dark bands.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 277"}, {"id": "IP-760", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.11", "stem": "Under which imaging scenario is a Moire artifact most likely to be observed?", "options": ["Small FOV scan of the internal auditory canals", "High-resolution fast spin echo of the lumbar spine", "Large FOV gradient echo sequence of the abdomen", "Multi-voxel spectroscopy acquisition of the brain"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Moire artifact is most likely with large FOV gradient-echo sequences, especially of the abdomen or pelvis, where the imaging volume extends to the periphery of the magnet where field inhomogeneity and gradient non-linearity are most pronounced. Small FOV and spin-echo sequences are less susceptible.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 277"}, {"id": "IP-761", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.11", "stem": "Which action is most effective for minimizing a Moire pattern artifact?", "options": ["Switch to a spin echo sequence and center the patient at isocenter", "Decrease slice thickness and increase the echo time", "Increase the field of view to cover more anatomy", "Activate the chemical fat suppression pulse"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Switching to a spin-echo sequence reduces Moire artifact because the 180-degree refocusing pulse compensates for static field inhomogeneities. Centering the patient at isocenter places them in the most homogeneous region of the magnet where gradient linearity is best.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 277"}, {"id": "IP-762", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.10", "stem": "In a conventional 2D spin echo sequence, which parameter primarily dictates the maximum number of slices that can be acquired in a single acquisition?", "options": ["Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Number of signal averages (NSA)", "Receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a conventional 2D spin-echo sequence, the maximum number of slices is primarily limited by TR. During each TR period, slices are excited sequentially. A longer TR provides more time within each repetition to excite additional slices, while a shorter TR limits the number that can be accommodated.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-763", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.10", "stem": "A technologist needs to add five additional slices to a T1-weighted sequence but the scanner indicates the maximum number has been reached. Without changing the TE or using concatenations, which adjustment will allow the additional slices?", "options": ["Increase the TR slightly", "Decrease the receiver bandwidth", "Increase the field of view", "Decrease the phase matrix"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the TR slightly provides additional time within each repetition period to accommodate more slice excitations. This is the most direct way to add slices without changing TE or using concatenations. The trade-off is a modest increase in scan time and potentially altered T1 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-764", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.10", "stem": "If a technologist reduces the number of slices in a standard 2D multi-slice acquisition from 25 to 15 while keeping TR, phase matrix, and NSA unchanged, what happens to the total scan time?", "options": ["Scan time decreases by approximately 40%", "Scan time remains unchanged", "Scan time doubles due to reduced spatial coverage", "Scan time decreases only if TE is also reduced"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In standard 2D multi-slice imaging, scan time is determined by TR × phase matrix × NSA. The number of slices does not appear in this formula because all slices are acquired within each TR period through interleaved excitation. Reducing slices only decreases spatial coverage, not scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-765", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.12", "stem": "When planning an axial acquisition of the abdomen, the phase encoding direction is typically assigned anterior-to-posterior (A/P). What is the primary reason for this convention?", "options": ["To minimize scan time by utilizing the shortest anatomical dimension", "To prevent respiratory motion artifacts from propagating across the liver and pancreas", "To increase the signal-to-noise ratio in the center of the image", "To ensure the chemical shift artifact occurs along the edges of the patient"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Phase encoding is assigned to the shortest anatomical dimension to minimize the number of phase-encoding steps needed and reduce scan time. In the abdomen, A/P is typically the shortest dimension. Additionally, motion artifacts propagate along the phase direction, so the shortest axis minimizes their extent.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-766", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.12", "stem": "A technologist is performing a sagittal sequence of the cervical spine. To prevent swallowing and pulsatile motion artifacts from obscuring the spinal cord, how should the phase and frequency directions be assigned?", "options": ["Phase A/P, Frequency S/I", "Phase S/I, Frequency A/P", "Phase R/L, Frequency S/I", "Phase S/I, Frequency R/L"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Assigning phase encoding S/I (superior-inferior) and frequency encoding A/P (anterior-posterior) ensures that swallowing and pulsatile artifacts from anterior neck structures propagate in the S/I direction rather than across the spinal cord. This prevents these artifacts from obscuring the cord.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-767", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.12", "stem": "If a technologist encounters severe aliasing (wraparound) artifact on a coronal shoulder image, along which directional axis is the anatomy wrapping into the image?", "options": ["The frequency encoding axis", "The slice selection axis", "The phase encoding axis", "The Z-axis gradient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Aliasing (wraparound) artifact occurs along the phase-encoding axis when anatomy extends beyond the FOV in that direction. The phase-encoded signal wraps around because phase values repeat cyclically. Anti-aliasing oversampling in the phase direction can prevent this artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-768", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.16", "stem": "When a protocol requires a very short TR and a high number of slices, the scanner may automatically divide the slices into separate groups acquired in different TR periods. This process is known as:", "options": ["Parallel imaging", "Fractional averaging", "Concatenations", "Interleaved acquisition"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Concatenations (also called acquisitions or packages) divide slices into separate groups acquired in successive TR periods. This is necessary when the number of required slices exceeds what can be accommodated within a single TR, typically with short-TR T1-weighted protocols.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-769", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.16", "stem": "If a technologist changes a sequence from 1 concatenation to 2 concatenations without altering the TR, phase matrix, or NSA, what is the direct effect on total scan time?", "options": ["The scan time is reduced by half", "The scan time remains exactly the same", "The scan time doubles", "The scan time increases by a factor of the square root of 2"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Doubling the concatenations doubles scan time because the total number of TR periods must be repeated for each concatenation group. All slices still require the same number of phase-encoding steps and NSA, but they are split across twice as many acquisition cycles.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-770", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.16", "stem": "Which clinical scenario most frequently requires the use of multiple concatenations?", "options": ["A heavily T2-weighted fast spin echo of the pelvis requiring a TR of 6000 ms", "A 3D gradient echo volume of the internal auditory canals", "A T1-weighted spin echo of the entire thoracic spine requiring 35 slices with a TR of 400 ms", "A dynamic contrast-enhanced breast MRI with a temporal resolution of 60 seconds"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A T1-weighted spin-echo sequence requiring many slices (35) with a short TR (400 ms) is the classic scenario requiring multiple concatenations. The short TR provides insufficient time to excite all 35 slices within each repetition, so the scanner splits them into groups.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-771", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.17", "stem": "In diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI), what does the b-value directly control?", "options": ["The degree of T1 weighting in the background tissue", "The spatial resolution of the apparent diffusion coefficient map", "The sequence's sensitivity to the diffusion of water molecules", "The velocity at which the scanner table moves during a whole-body scan"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The b-value directly controls the sequence's sensitivity to the diffusion of water molecules. Higher b-values apply stronger diffusion-sensitizing gradients, causing greater signal loss in tissues with freely moving water while retaining signal in tissues with restricted diffusion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-772", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.17", "stem": "If a technologist increases the b-value from 0 to 1000 s/mm² for a brain DWI, what is the anticipated effect?", "options": ["Increased SNR and decreased diffusion weighting", "Decreased SNR and increased diffusion weighting", "Increased T2 shine-through effect and improved spatial resolution", "Complete elimination of all susceptibility artifacts"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the b-value from 0 to 1000 s/mm² strengthens the diffusion-sensitizing gradients, which increases diffusion weighting (greater sensitivity to restricted diffusion) but decreases SNR due to signal loss from dephasing of freely moving water molecules.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-773", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.17", "stem": "Which three gradient factors combine to determine the magnitude of the b-value?", "options": ["Gradient amplitude, duration of the gradient pulses, and the time interval between the gradient pulses", "Gradient slew rate, receiver bandwidth, and the phase encoding matrix", "Main magnetic field strength, gradient amplitude, and echo time (TE)", "Radiofrequency flip angle, gradient duration, and repetition time (TR)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The b-value magnitude is determined by three gradient factors: the amplitude (strength) of the diffusion-sensitizing gradient pulses, their duration, and the time interval between the two gradient lobes (which determines how far water molecules must move to experience dephasing).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-774", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.18", "stem": "In Phase Contrast MRA, what happens if the VENC is set significantly lower than the actual peak blood flow velocity?", "options": ["The blood vessels will appear dark and indistinguishable from stationary tissue", "Signal aliasing will occur, making the center of the vessel appear dark or display flow in the wrong direction", "The spatial resolution will drop drastically, causing severe image blurring", "The scan time will increase proportionately to the velocity mismatch"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When VENC is set below the actual peak flow velocity in phase-contrast MRA, the phase shifts exceed ±180 degrees, causing aliasing. The vessel center (where velocity is highest) appears dark or displays reversed flow direction because the phase values wrap around beyond the measurable range.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-775", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.18", "stem": "A technologist is setting up a PC-MRA to evaluate the superior sagittal sinus. Which VENC setting is most appropriate for this venous structure?", "options": ["150 cm/s", "80 cm/s", "20 cm/s", "5 cm/s"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Venous structures like the superior sagittal sinus have relatively slow flow velocities (~15-20 cm/s). A VENC of 20 cm/s is appropriate to maximize sensitivity to these slow velocities. Higher VENC settings (80-150 cm/s) are used for arterial structures and would produce poor venous contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-776", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.18", "stem": "What is the primary trade-off when using Phase Contrast MRA compared to Time of Flight MRA?", "options": ["PC-MRA is highly susceptible to saturation of in-plane flow", "PC-MRA completely lacks the ability to determine the direction of blood flow", "PC-MRA relies heavily on the administration of a gadolinium contrast agent", "PC-MRA typically requires longer scan times due to the acquisition of multiple flow-encoded data sets"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Phase-contrast MRA requires acquiring multiple flow-encoded datasets (typically 4: one reference plus three directional), resulting in longer scan times than TOF-MRA. However, PC-MRA provides quantitative flow velocity data and directional information that TOF cannot offer.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-777", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "How does parallel imaging (e.g., SENSE, GRAPPA) fundamentally reduce scan time?", "options": ["By reducing the repetition time (TR) to the absolute minimum allowed by the gradients", "By utilizing the spatial sensitivity profiles of phased array coils to fill in missing phase encoding steps", "By acquiring half of the k-space data and using conjugate symmetry to calculate the rest", "By combining multiple slice acquisitions into a single thick slab"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Parallel imaging reduces scan time by acquiring fewer phase-encoding lines than the full matrix requires, then using the spatial sensitivity profiles of individual phased-array coil elements to mathematically reconstruct the missing data. This is fundamentally different from partial Fourier or 3D slab acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-778", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "A protocol utilizes a parallel imaging acceleration factor (R) of 4. What is the expected SNR penalty?", "options": ["SNR will be reduced to 25% of the original value", "SNR will be reduced by a factor of the square root of 4 (i.e., cut in half)", "SNR will decrease by exactly 4%", "SNR will improve slightly due to the reduction in scan time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The SNR penalty from parallel imaging follows a square-root relationship with the acceleration factor (R). At R=4, SNR is reduced by √4 = 2, meaning SNR is cut in half. An additional geometry factor (g-factor) may further reduce SNR depending on coil geometry.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-779", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "Which artifact is exclusively associated with parallel imaging when the FOV is too small or the acceleration factor is too high?", "options": ["Truncation / Gibbs artifact", "Chemical shift type II (In and Out of phase)", "Central point artifact", "SENSE/unfolding artifact appearing in the center of the image"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "SENSE/unfolding artifacts are unique to parallel imaging and appear when the acceleration factor is too high or the FOV is too small, causing the reconstruction algorithm to improperly separate overlapping signal. These residual aliasing artifacts typically appear centrally in the image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-780", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.11", "stem": "Applying a low-pass filter to raw k-space data produces an image that appears:", "options": ["Sharper, with enhanced edge detail", "Smoother, with reduced image noise", "Completely devoid of T1 contrast", "With severe chemical shift artifacts"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A low-pass filter attenuates high spatial frequencies (fine detail and noise) while preserving low frequencies (overall signal and contrast). This produces a smoother image with reduced noise at the cost of some edge sharpness. It is commonly used to improve SNR in noisy acquisitions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-781", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.11", "stem": "To enhance the boundaries between gray and white matter, which type of k-space filter would be applied?", "options": ["High-pass filter", "Low-pass filter", "Fermi filter", "Baseline subtraction filter"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A high-pass filter attenuates low spatial frequencies while enhancing high frequencies, which emphasize edges and boundaries between tissues. This improves the visibility of interfaces such as gray-white matter boundaries but can increase image noise.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-782", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.11", "stem": "Which filter is commonly applied to reduce the appearance of Gibbs (truncation) artifacts?", "options": ["Maximum Intensity Projection (MIP)", "2D spatial smoothing filter (e.g., Hanning or Fermi filter)", "High-pass filter", "Radiofrequency presaturation filter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact is reduced by applying a 2D spatial smoothing filter such as a Hanning or Fermi filter, which tapers the k-space data at the periphery. This reduces the ringing caused by the abrupt truncation of k-space data at high spatial frequencies.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-783", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.c", "stem": "What is the defining characteristic of a coherent (steady-state) gradient echo sequence?", "options": ["It relies on a 180-degree RF pulse to refocus the transverse magnetization", "It uses spoiler gradients to completely destroy residual transverse magnetization", "It uses a rewinder gradient to preserve and maintain residual transverse magnetization", "It requires an inversion recovery prep pulse to null the transverse magnetization"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A coherent (steady-state) gradient-echo sequence uses rewinder gradients to preserve and maintain residual transverse magnetization from one TR to the next. This preserved magnetization contributes to the signal in subsequent excitations, producing T2/T1-weighted contrast. Spoiled GRE destroys this magnetization instead.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-784", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.c", "stem": "Because coherent GRE sequences maintain residual transverse magnetization, the resulting image contrast is highly dependent on which tissue property?", "options": ["The absolute T1 relaxation time", "The ratio of T2 to T1 (T2/T1 ratio)", "The velocity of molecular diffusion", "The tissue's magnetic susceptibility coefficient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Because coherent GRE sequences maintain residual transverse magnetization, image contrast depends heavily on the T2/T1 ratio of tissues. Tissues with a high T2/T1 ratio (like fluid) appear bright, while tissues with a low ratio appear darker. This is distinct from pure T1 or T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-785", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.c", "stem": "Which clinical application is most suited for a balanced coherent GRE sequence (e.g., TrueFISP, FIESTA, balanced SSFP)?", "options": ["Identifying microhemorrhages in the brain parenchyma", "Performing a pre- and post-gadolinium evaluation of a liver mass", "Evaluating cardiac wall motion and ventricular volumes (CINE imaging)", "Quantifying the degree of steatosis (fat) in the liver"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Balanced SSFP sequences (TrueFISP, FIESTA) produce excellent fluid-tissue contrast and fast scan times, making them ideal for cardiac CINE imaging where ventricular wall motion and volumes must be assessed dynamically across the cardiac cycle. The bright blood contrast delineates the endocardial border clearly.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-786", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.e", "stem": "Fast gradient echo sequences use ultra-short TR and TE. To generate meaningful contrast, what is typically applied before the rapid readout begins?", "options": ["A robust fat-saturation pulse", "A magnetization preparation pulse (e.g., 180-degree inversion or 90-degree driven equilibrium pulse)", "A series of flow compensation gradients", "A high b-value diffusion gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Fast gradient-echo sequences use ultra-short TR and TE that provide minimal inherent contrast. To generate clinically useful contrast, a magnetization preparation pulse (such as a 180-degree inversion for T1 weighting or a driven equilibrium pulse) is applied before the rapid readout train begins.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-787", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.e", "stem": "Which clinical scenario represents the most common use of a T1-weighted 3D fast spoiled GRE (e.g., LAVA, VIBE)?", "options": ["Dynamic contrast-enhanced (DCE) imaging of the abdomen during breath-hold", "High-resolution evaluation of the internal auditory canal cranial nerves", "Routine T2-weighted evaluation of the intervertebral discs", "Non-contrast time-of-flight evaluation of the peripheral vasculature"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Dynamic contrast-enhanced (DCE) imaging of the abdomen is the most common clinical application of T1-weighted 3D fast spoiled GRE sequences (LAVA, VIBE, THRIVE). These sequences provide rapid volumetric coverage during breath-hold, capturing multiple arterial and venous contrast phases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-788", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.e", "stem": "In an ultra-fast gradient echo sequence, the flip angle is typically:", "options": ["Fixed at exactly 90 degrees", "Set dynamically above 180 degrees to force rapid recovery", "Variable, but generally small (e.g., 5 to 20 degrees)", "Replaced entirely by a series of 180-degree refocusing pulses"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Ultra-fast gradient-echo sequences typically use small flip angles (5-20 degrees) to minimize longitudinal magnetization saturation during the rapid repetitions. Small flip angles allow faster T1 recovery between excitations, maintaining adequate signal even with very short TRs.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-789", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "A standard clinical DWI sequence for brain imaging is typically built upon which pulse sequence architecture?", "options": ["Fast Spin Echo (FSE)", "Echo Planar Imaging (EPI)", "3D Spoiled Gradient Echo (SPGR)", "Steady State Free Precession (SSFP)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Clinical brain DWI is built on an echo planar imaging (EPI) readout, which acquires all k-space lines after a single excitation. EPI's ultrafast acquisition minimizes motion sensitivity but introduces susceptibility-related geometric distortion, particularly at air-tissue interfaces.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-790", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "During a DWI sequence, why are two large gradient lobes applied symmetrically on either side of the 180-degree refocusing pulse?", "options": ["To saturate the signal from subcutaneous fat", "To dephase and then rephase stationary spins, leaving moving spins dephased", "To increase the signal-to-noise ratio in the center of the anatomy", "To accelerate the spatial encoding process in the frequency direction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The two large gradient lobes (Stejskal-Tanner gradients) dephase and then rephase stationary spins symmetrically around the 180-degree pulse, so stationary tissue retains full signal. Water molecules that move between the two gradient applications experience incomplete rephasing and lose signal proportional to their diffusion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-791", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "Which artifact is a well-known limitation of the EPI readout used in standard DWI, particularly at tissue-air interfaces?", "options": ["Magic angle artifact", "Cross-talk artifact", "Susceptibility-induced geometric distortion", "Zipper artifact"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The EPI readout used in standard DWI is highly sensitive to magnetic susceptibility differences at tissue-air interfaces (e.g., skull base, sinuses). These susceptibility gradients cause geometric distortion—spatial warping of the image—which is a well-known limitation of EPI-based sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-792", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.6", "stem": "SWI exploits tissue magnetic properties by utilizing which components of the MRI signal data?", "options": ["Only the magnitude data", "Only the T1 relaxation data", "Both the magnitude and the phase data", "Both the T2 and T2* recovery data"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "SWI exploits the magnetic susceptibility differences between tissues by utilizing both magnitude data (signal intensity) and phase data (phase shifts from susceptibility). The phase information is filtered and multiplied with the magnitude to create images exquisitely sensitive to paramagnetic substances.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-793", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.6", "stem": "Which of the following substances causes signal loss (blooming) that is highly conspicuous on SWI?", "options": ["Deoxyhemoglobin in a venous anomaly", "Simple fluid in an arachnoid cyst", "Myelin in normal white matter tracts", "Cerebrospinal fluid in the lateral ventricles"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Deoxyhemoglobin is paramagnetic and creates local field inhomogeneities that cause T2* signal loss (blooming) on SWI. This makes venous structures, microhemorrhages, and hemosiderin deposits highly conspicuous as dark foci. Simple fluid (cysts) and normal white matter lack this paramagnetic effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-794", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.6", "stem": "To visualize small venous structures or microhemorrhages over a thicker volume, SWI post-processing utilizes which reconstruction algorithm?", "options": ["Maximum Intensity Projection (MIP)", "Minimum Intensity Projection (MinIP)", "Multiplanar Reformation (MPR)", "Apparent Diffusion Coefficient (ADC) mapping"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SWI uses minimum intensity projection (MinIP) to display the darkest voxels across a thicker slab, making small dark structures like veins and microhemorrhages conspicuous. Maximum intensity projection (MIP) would suppress these dark structures and is used instead for angiographic data.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-795", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.7", "stem": "Arterial Spin Labeling (ASL) is a unique perfusion technique because it:", "options": ["Requires a double dose of gadolinium contrast", "Can only be performed on 3.0 Tesla or higher systems", "Uses an RF inversion pulse to tag the patient's own arterial blood as an endogenous contrast agent", "Relies exclusively on T1-weighted fast spin echo techniques"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Arterial Spin Labeling (ASL) uses an RF inversion pulse to magnetically tag (invert) the patient's own arterial blood upstream of the imaging slice, using it as an endogenous contrast agent. No exogenous contrast injection is required, making ASL ideal for patients with renal impairment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-796", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.7", "stem": "In Dynamic Susceptibility Contrast (DSC) perfusion imaging, what creates the contrast mechanism used to calculate perfusion maps?", "options": ["The T1 shortening effect of gadolinium increasing signal in extracellular space", "The paramagnetic susceptibility effect of a concentrated gadolinium bolus causing rapid T2* signal loss", "The restricted diffusion of water molecules secondary to cytotoxic edema", "The shift in resonance frequency between oxygenated and deoxygenated hemoglobin"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In DSC perfusion, a concentrated gadolinium bolus passing through capillaries creates strong local susceptibility effects that accelerate T2* dephasing, causing rapid signal loss on T2*-weighted EPI images. This transient signal drop is measured over time to calculate CBV, CBF, and MTT maps.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-797", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.7", "stem": "An area of brain tissue demonstrating normal Cerebral Blood Volume (CBV) but significantly prolonged Mean Transit Time (MTT) most likely represents:", "options": ["The necrotic infarct core", "Healthy, unaffected brain tissue", "The ischemic penumbra (tissue at risk)", "An area of active hemorrhage"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ischemic penumbra is tissue at risk that shows normal CBV (autoregulatory vasodilation maintains blood volume) but prolonged MTT (blood takes longer to transit the capillary bed due to reduced perfusion pressure). This mismatch pattern identifies salvageable tissue that may benefit from intervention.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-798", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.8", "stem": "The x-axis of an MR spectroscopy (MRS) spectrum is measured in which unit?", "options": ["Milliseconds (ms)", "Hertz (Hz)", "Parts per million (ppm)", "Millimeters squared per second (mm²/s)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The x-axis of an MRS spectrum is measured in parts per million (ppm), a dimensionless unit that normalizes chemical shift frequency differences relative to the operating frequency of the scanner. This allows spectra from different field strengths to be directly compared.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-799", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.8", "stem": "In a normal brain MRS spectrum, which metabolite produces the tallest peak at approximately 2.0 ppm and serves as a marker of neuronal health?", "options": ["Choline (Cho)", "N-acetylaspartate (NAA)", "Creatine (Cr)", "Lactate (Lac)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "N-acetylaspartate (NAA) produces the tallest peak in normal brain MRS at approximately 2.0 ppm and is a marker of neuronal integrity and viability. Decreased NAA indicates neuronal loss or damage. Choline (Cho) at 3.2 ppm reflects membrane turnover, and creatine (Cr) at 3.0 ppm serves as an internal reference.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-800", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.8", "stem": "A distinct double peak (doublet) at 1.3 ppm that inverts at TE 144 ms indicates the presence of:", "options": ["Normal white matter metabolism", "Active cell membrane proliferation", "Anaerobic glycolysis and tissue necrosis", "Healthy cellular energy storage"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A lactate doublet at 1.3 ppm that inverts at TE 144 ms indicates anaerobic glycolysis and tissue necrosis. Lactate is normally absent in healthy brain tissue and its presence suggests ischemia, abscess, or high-grade tumor with necrotic core. The J-coupling of lactate causes the characteristic inversion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-801", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.b", "stem": "What is the most critical data requirement for producing high-quality multiplanar reformations (MPR) without stair-step artifacts?", "options": ["Acquisition of data in multiple separate phase encoding directions", "Use of a heavily T2-weighted contrast mechanism", "Acquisition of an isotropic or near-isotropic 3D volume", "Application of maximum intensity projection filters"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "High-quality multiplanar reformations require isotropic or near-isotropic 3D volume data where voxel dimensions are equal in all three directions. Non-isotropic data produces stair-step artifacts when reformatted because the through-plane resolution is coarser than the in-plane resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-802", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.b", "stem": "A technologist acquires a high-resolution 3D FIESTA of the internal auditory canals and uses MPR to create images perpendicular to the seventh cranial nerve. This post-processing technique:", "options": ["Increases the signal-to-noise ratio compared to the original acquisition", "Generates images based on new spatial encoding gradients", "Does not require the patient to remain in the scanner for additional imaging", "Can only generate orthogonal planes (sagittal or coronal)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MPR images are generated by computationally reslicing the existing 3D dataset in any arbitrary plane without requiring additional scan time or keeping the patient in the scanner. This post-processing technique cannot create new data but can display existing data in clinically useful orientations.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-803", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.b", "stem": "Compared to directly acquiring an image in an oblique plane, an MPR image generated from a truly isotropic 3D dataset yields:", "options": ["Higher spatial resolution", "Identical spatial resolution", "Lower spatial resolution", "Heavily distorted anatomical contrast"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When the source 3D dataset is truly isotropic (equal voxel dimensions in all directions), MPR images in any reformatted plane have identical spatial resolution to directly acquired images. The information content per voxel is the same regardless of the viewing orientation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-804", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.c", "stem": "In dynamic contrast-enhanced breast MRI, what is the primary purpose of applying image subtraction?", "options": ["To eliminate signal from the heart and lungs", "To remove bright pre-contrast fat and glandular tissue signal, isolating areas of contrast enhancement", "To mathematically combine the T1 and T2 relaxation times", "To suppress blooming artifact caused by biopsy clips"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Image subtraction in breast MRI removes the bright pre-contrast signal from fat and dense glandular tissue, isolating only the areas that enhance after gadolinium administration. This dramatically improves the conspicuity of enhancing lesions against the otherwise complex breast tissue background.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-805", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.c", "stem": "Which factor will most severely degrade the quality of a subtracted image?", "options": ["The use of a short TR during the acquisition", "Patient motion occurring between the pre-contrast and post-contrast acquisitions", "Utilizing an isotropic 3D sequence", "The administration of a macrocyclic contrast agent"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patient motion between pre- and post-contrast acquisitions is the most severe degrading factor for subtracted images. Even slight misregistration causes incomplete cancellation, producing bright or dark rims around structures that obscure or mimic enhancement patterns.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-806", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.c", "stem": "A technologist subtracts an unenhanced mask from a contrast-enhanced MR angiogram of the lower extremities. This post-processing technique is known as:", "options": ["MR subtraction angiography", "Phase contrast velocity mapping", "Apparent diffusion coefficient calculation", "Maximum Intensity Projection (MIP)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "MR subtraction angiography involves acquiring a pre-contrast mask and a contrast-enhanced dataset, then subtracting the mask from the enhanced images. This removes background signal (bone, fat, soft tissue) and isolates enhancing vessels, similar to digital subtraction angiography in conventional catheter studies.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-807", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.d", "stem": "How is an Apparent Diffusion Coefficient (ADC) map generated?", "options": ["By applying a mathematical algorithm solely to the b=1000 image", "By calculating the signal change between images acquired at different b-values (e.g., b=0 and b=1000)", "By directly measuring the T2* decay of the tissue", "By subtracting the pre-contrast T1 from the post-contrast T1 image"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An ADC map is generated by calculating the rate of signal change between images acquired at two or more different b-values (e.g., b=0 and b=1000). The mathematical algorithm fits the signal decay curve on a voxel-by-voxel basis to derive the apparent diffusion coefficient, which quantifies water molecule mobility.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-808", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.d", "stem": "The primary clinical reason for generating an ADC map alongside the DWI trace image is to:", "options": ["Increase the spatial resolution of the final image", "Differentiate true restricted diffusion from the T2 shine-through effect", "Correct for magnetic susceptibility artifacts at the skull base", "Quantify the exact volume of a cerebral infarction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ADC map differentiates true restricted diffusion from T2 shine-through. On DWI trace images, both restricted diffusion and long T2 tissues appear bright. The ADC map shows restricted diffusion as dark (low ADC) and T2 shine-through as bright (high ADC), enabling accurate diagnosis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-809", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.d", "stem": "On an ADC map, an area of acute cerebral infarction with severe cytotoxic edema will display:", "options": ["High signal intensity (bright) representing a high ADC value", "Low signal intensity (dark) representing a low ADC value", "Isointense signal relative to normal white matter", "A signal void surrounded by a bright rim"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Acute cerebral infarction causes cytotoxic edema with severely restricted water diffusion. On the ADC map, this restricted diffusion appears as low signal intensity (dark) because the ADC value is low. This is the opposite of DWI, where restricted diffusion appears bright.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-810", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "CINE MRI imaging is most fundamentally reliant on which process?", "options": ["Retrospective or prospective cardiac/respiratory gating", "Heavy T1 weighting and gadolinium contrast", "Maximum intensity projection (MIP) reconstruction", "Apparent diffusion coefficient calculations"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "CINE MRI relies fundamentally on cardiac (or respiratory) gating—either prospective triggering or retrospective gating—to synchronize data acquisition with the cardiac cycle. Multiple images are reconstructed at different cardiac phases to display wall motion as a continuous loop.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-811", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "When evaluating cardiac ventricular function using CINE imaging, the temporal resolution is primarily determined by:", "options": ["The spatial matrix size", "The number of cardiac phases reconstructed across the R-R interval", "The administration rate of the contrast bolus", "The total slice thickness of the volume"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Temporal resolution in cardiac CINE imaging is determined by the number of cardiac phases reconstructed across the R-R interval. More phases provide finer temporal sampling of wall motion but require more data per heartbeat. Typically 20-30 phases are reconstructed for adequate motion assessment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-812", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "A physician requests a CINE phase contrast sequence of the aqueduct of Sylvius. What is the clinical purpose of this examination?", "options": ["To measure the ejection fraction of the left ventricle", "To evaluate the pulsatile flow dynamics of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)", "To identify areas of restricted diffusion in the midbrain", "To track the bolus of contrast through the Circle of Willis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "CINE phase-contrast imaging of the aqueduct of Sylvius evaluates pulsatile CSF flow dynamics through this narrow channel connecting the third and fourth ventricles. This helps assess normal-pressure hydrocephalus, aqueductal stenosis, and CSF circulation abnormalities.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-813", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.1", "stem": "What does the acronym DICOM stand for?", "options": ["Digital Image Capture and Object Matrix", "Direct Interface for Computerized Online Modalities", "Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine", "Data Integration Code for Medical Outcomes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "DICOM stands for Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine. It is the universal standard that defines how medical images and associated metadata are formatted, stored, and transmitted between imaging devices, PACS, and workstations.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-814", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.1", "stem": "Which component of a DICOM file contains the patient's name, MRN, scan date, TR, TE, and slice thickness?", "options": ["The pixel data payload", "The DICOM header", "The HL7 wrapper", "The presentation state descriptor"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The DICOM header is the metadata section of a DICOM file that contains patient information (name, MRN), study details (date, time), and acquisition parameters (TR, TE, slice thickness). The pixel data payload contains the actual image data. Both are essential components of a complete DICOM file.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-815", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.1", "stem": "To ensure a new MRI scanner will communicate properly with an existing PACS, which document must IT administrators compare?", "options": ["The DICOM Conformance Statement", "The HIPAA Business Associate Agreement", "The FDA 510(k) Clearance", "The Joint Commission safety protocols"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The DICOM Conformance Statement is a technical document provided by each equipment manufacturer that specifies which DICOM services and data formats the device supports. Comparing conformance statements between the scanner and PACS ensures communication compatibility before installation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-816", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.2", "stem": "PACS archives commonly use RAID storage. What does RAID stand for?", "options": ["Rapid Access Information Database", "Redundant Array of Independent Disks", "Radiology Archive and Integration Device", "Remote Access Image Directory"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RAID stands for Redundant Array of Independent Disks. PACS archives use RAID configurations to provide data redundancy (protection against disk failure) and improved read/write performance by distributing data across multiple physical drives.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-817", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.2", "stem": "How does a short-term archive differ from a long-term archive in a PACS?", "options": ["Short-term uses compressed JPEG while long-term uses raw DICOM", "Short-term holds only text reports while long-term holds images", "Short-term uses fast solid-state or high-speed disk arrays for rapid retrieval while long-term uses slower high-capacity storage", "Short-term archives are only accessible by radiologists while long-term are public"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Short-term archives use fast solid-state drives or high-speed disk arrays for rapid image retrieval of recent studies (typically accessed frequently). Long-term archives use slower, higher-capacity storage (tape, optical, or cloud) for studies that are accessed infrequently but must be retained for legal compliance.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-818", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.2", "stem": "What primary factor dictates how long a facility must retain MRI examination records?", "options": ["The physical storage limit of the RAID servers", "State and federal legal retention requirements", "The manufacturer's warranty on the MRI scanner", "The patient's insurance provider guidelines"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "State and federal legal retention requirements dictate the minimum period a facility must retain imaging records. These requirements vary by jurisdiction and patient age (pediatric records may require longer retention). Storage capacity and manufacturer warranties are secondary to legal obligations.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-819", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.3", "stem": "What is the primary function of the Radiology Information System (RIS)?", "options": ["To physically store the raw k-space data", "To reconstruct 3D models from DICOM images", "To manage patient scheduling, order entry, workflow, and billing within the radiology department", "To encrypt image data before sending it over the hospital network"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Radiology Information System (RIS) manages departmental workflow including patient scheduling, order entry, examination tracking, report generation, and billing. It interfaces with PACS (for images) and the EMR (for clinical data) to coordinate the complete radiology workflow.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-820", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.3", "stem": "Which standard is primarily used for transmitting text-based medical data between the RIS, EMR, and PACS?", "options": ["HL7 (Health Level Seven)", "HIPAA", "TCP/IP", "JPEG 2000"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "HL7 (Health Level Seven) is the standard protocol for transmitting text-based medical data between healthcare information systems. It handles ADT (admission, discharge, transfer) messages, orders, and results between the RIS, EMR, and PACS. DICOM handles image data transmission.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-821", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.3", "stem": "Which best describes an Electronic Medical Record (EMR)?", "options": ["A standalone database solely for storing radiology images", "A comprehensive digital version of a patient's paper chart with integration to departmental systems like PACS", "The hardware interface connecting the MRI console to the internet", "The protocol used to de-identify patient information for research"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An Electronic Medical Record (EMR) is a comprehensive digital version of a patient's paper chart that integrates data from multiple departmental systems including PACS (images), RIS (radiology reports), and laboratory results. It provides a unified patient record accessible across the healthcare enterprise.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-822", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.4", "stem": "Before sending an MRI study to an outside researcher, de-identification involves:", "options": ["Converting images from DICOM to JPEG format", "Removing all Protected Health Information (PHI) from the DICOM header and ensuring no burned-in text remains on the images", "Deleting the study from the PACS after transmission", "Applying a high-pass filter to blur facial features on sagittal brain images"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "De-identification removes all Protected Health Information (PHI) from DICOM headers—including patient name, MRN, date of birth, and study dates—and ensures no burned-in text on images contains identifiable information. This is required by HIPAA before sharing studies for research or external consultation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-823", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.4", "stem": "The security feature that records which user logged in, when they accessed the system, and which files they viewed is called:", "options": ["An encryption key", "An audit trail", "A firewall", "A virtual private network (VPN)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An audit trail is the security feature that automatically logs user access to the system, recording who logged in, when they accessed the system, and which files or images they viewed. This creates a verifiable chain of accountability required for HIPAA compliance and security monitoring.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-824", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.4", "stem": "When transmitting MRI images to an off-site radiologist for interpretation, which technology scrambles the data during transit to prevent unauthorized access?", "options": ["Data compression", "Encryption", "De-identification", "RAID mirroring"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Encryption scrambles image data during transmission so that intercepted data cannot be read without the correct decryption key. This protects patient information during transfer over networks, especially when images are sent to off-site radiologists for remote interpretation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-825", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.5", "stem": "What three pieces of information must be configured for the MRI scanner to send images to a PACS server?", "options": ["The MAC address, the HL7 code, and the gateway router", "The IP address, the port number, and the AE Title (Application Entity Title)", "The subnet mask, the DICOM header, and the encryption key", "The EMR ID, the RAID configuration, and the bandwidth limit"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "To send images from the MRI scanner to a PACS server, three pieces of network information must be configured: the IP address (network location), the port number (communication channel), and the AE Title (Application Entity Title, which uniquely identifies the DICOM node). All three are required for successful DICOM communication.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-826", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.5", "stem": "When the MRI scanner requests a list of scheduled patients from the RIS, which DICOM service is being utilized?", "options": ["DICOM Print", "Modality Worklist (MWL)", "DICOM C-STORE", "DICOM C-MOVE"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Modality Worklist (MWL) is the DICOM service that allows imaging equipment to query the RIS for a list of scheduled patients and their associated order information. This eliminates manual data entry at the scanner console, reducing transcription errors and improving workflow efficiency.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-827", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.C.5", "stem": "Which networking infrastructure is essential for a radiologist to securely connect to hospital PACS from a remote location?", "options": ["A Virtual Private Network (VPN)", "A Local Area Network (LAN)", "A Modality Worklist (MWL)", "A redundant array of independent disks (RAID)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A Virtual Private Network (VPN) creates an encrypted tunnel over the public internet, allowing a radiologist to securely connect to the hospital PACS from a remote location. A LAN is local-only, MWL handles scheduling, and RAID is a storage configuration—none provide secure remote access.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-828", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.12", "stem": "When using parallel imaging techniques such as SENSE or GRAPPA, what is the most common artifact if the acceleration factor is too high for the coil geometry?", "options": ["Zipper artifact from RF leakage", "Residual aliasing or fold-over appearing within the center of the image", "Chemical shift misregistration at fat-water interfaces", "Moire pattern at the edges of the field of view"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When the parallel imaging acceleration factor is too high relative to the coil geometry, the reconstruction algorithm cannot adequately separate overlapping signals, producing residual aliasing or fold-over artifacts typically appearing in the center of the image. This is distinct from standard aliasing, which wraps from the edges.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 253"}, {"id": "IP-829", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.12", "stem": "The geometry factor (g-factor) in parallel imaging describes spatially dependent noise amplification. In which region of the image is the g-factor penalty typically worst?", "options": ["At the periphery, closest to the coil elements", "At the center, farthest from the coil elements", "Uniformly distributed across the entire image", "Only along the frequency encoding axis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The g-factor penalty in parallel imaging is worst at the center of the image, farthest from the coil elements. Coil elements provide the best spatial encoding sensitivity near their surface, so the center—equidistant from all elements—has the least unique spatial information, resulting in the highest noise amplification.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-830", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.12", "stem": "A technologist notices bands of residual aliasing artifact in the center of a parallel imaging acquisition. Which adjustment would most effectively reduce this artifact?", "options": ["Increase the echo time (TE) to improve T2 contrast", "Decrease the acceleration factor or increase the field of view", "Switch from a phased array coil to the built-in body coil", "Apply a stronger frequency-encoding gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Decreasing the acceleration factor reduces the number of missing k-space lines that must be estimated, directly reducing residual aliasing. Increasing the FOV ensures anatomy fits within the encoded region. Switching to a body coil would worsen the problem since parallel imaging requires phased-array coils.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-831", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "During routine quality control testing, slice thickness accuracy is typically verified by scanning an ACR phantom containing:", "options": ["Parallel line pairs of decreasing spacing", "Crossed wedge ramps oriented at a known angle", "Uniform water-filled spheres of varying diameters", "Alternating bands of paramagnetic and diamagnetic materials"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slice thickness accuracy is verified using crossed wedge ramps in the ACR phantom. The measured width of the signal from these ramps, oriented at a known angle, allows calculation of the actual slice thickness. Deviations indicate gradient calibration issues.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 209"}, {"id": "IP-832", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "If a QC slice thickness measurement reveals the actual slice is significantly thicker than prescribed, which of the following is the most likely cause?", "options": ["The receiver bandwidth is set too narrow", "The slice selection gradient amplitude is lower than expected", "The phase encoding matrix is too large", "The number of signal averages (NSA) is too high"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "If the actual slice is thicker than prescribed, the most likely cause is a slice-selection gradient amplitude that is lower than expected. A weaker gradient produces a shallower slope, exciting a broader band of frequencies and thus a thicker slice. Receiver bandwidth and matrix affect in-plane parameters, not slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-833", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "According to the ACR MRI accreditation program, the measured slice thickness during quality control should be within what tolerance of the prescribed 5 mm slice?", "options": ["Exactly equal with zero tolerance", "Within plus or minus 0.7 mm", "Within plus or minus 5 mm regardless of prescribed thickness", "Within plus or minus 50 percent of the prescribed value"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR MRI accreditation program specifies that measured slice thickness should be within ±0.7 mm of the prescribed 5 mm slice. This tolerance ensures clinically acceptable spatial accuracy while accounting for normal gradient calibration variation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 209"}, {"id": "IP-834", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "The initial RF pulse in an inversion recovery (IR) sequence is a:", "options": ["90-degree excitation pulse", "180-degree inversion pulse", "45-degree preparatory pulse", "Variable flip angle pulse"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The inversion recovery sequence begins with a 180-degree inversion pulse that flips the net magnetization vector from the positive longitudinal axis to the negative axis. After a delay (TI), a standard 90-degree excitation and 180-degree refocusing pulse follow to form the echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-835", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "Which combination of RF pulses is used in a conventional spin echo (SE) sequence?", "options": ["Two successive 90-degree pulses", "A 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse", "Two successive 180-degree pulses", "A 180-degree pulse followed by a 90-degree pulse"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A conventional spin echo uses a 90-degree excitation pulse to tip magnetization into the transverse plane, followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse that rephases dephased spins to form the echo. This combination compensates for static field inhomogeneities and produces true T2 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-836", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "Which RF pulse train correctly describes a conventional inversion recovery (IR) sequence?", "options": ["90-degree, 180-degree, 180-degree", "180-degree, 90-degree, 180-degree", "90-degree, 90-degree, 180-degree", "180-degree, 180-degree, 90-degree"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The inversion recovery RF pulse train is 180°–90°–180°: the initial 180° inverts longitudinal magnetization, the 90° excites it into the transverse plane after the TI delay, and the final 180° refocuses the echo. This distinguishes IR from standard SE (90°–180°).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-837", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "T2-weighted FLAIR (fluid-attenuated inversion recovery) sequences are most commonly used to evaluate:", "options": ["Musculoskeletal contusions", "Subcutaneous fat distribution", "Retro-orbital fat", "Periventricular white matter disease"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "T2-weighted FLAIR is primarily used to evaluate periventricular white matter disease (such as MS plaques) because the suppressed CSF signal eliminates the bright fluid that would otherwise obscure lesions adjacent to the ventricles. Lesions appear bright against the dark CSF and gray/white matter.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-838", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "The excitation pulse in a gradient echo (GRE) sequence is typically:", "options": ["A fixed 90-degree RF pulse", "A fixed 180-degree RF pulse", "A variable flip angle pulse selected to achieve the desired contrast", "A flip angle restricted to values below 10 degrees"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In gradient-echo sequences, the excitation pulse uses a variable flip angle selected by the operator to achieve desired contrast. Unlike spin echo (fixed 90°), GRE flip angles range from very small (5°) to near 90°, giving control over T1 weighting, proton density, and saturation effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-839", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "Short tau inversion recovery (STIR) sequences are clinically useful for evaluating all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Bone marrow and musculoskeletal contusions", "Fat suppression in the presence of metal hardware", "Lesions within retro-orbital fat", "Cerebrospinal fluid"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "STIR is clinically useful for musculoskeletal contusions, fat suppression near metal hardware (where frequency-selective methods fail), and retro-orbital fat evaluation. CSF has a long T1 similar to the STIR null point and may be partially suppressed, making STIR suboptimal for CSF evaluation—FLAIR is preferred.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-840", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "STIR sequences effectively suppress signal from all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Fat within bone marrow", "Gadolinium-enhanced lesions", "Retro-orbital fat", "Cerebrospinal fluid"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "STIR suppresses signal from all tissues with T1 values matching the null point, including fat and gadolinium-enhanced tissue (which also has short T1). CSF has a very long T1 and is not suppressed by STIR—it appears bright. This is why STIR should not be used post-gadolinium.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-841", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "In a gradient echo pulse sequence, the echo is formed primarily by:", "options": ["Reversing the polarity of the readout gradient to rephase transverse magnetization", "Applying a 180-degree RF refocusing pulse", "Applying a second 90-degree excitation pulse", "Activating the phase-encoding gradient at maximum amplitude"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In gradient-echo sequences, the echo is formed by reversing the polarity of the readout (frequency-encoding) gradient. The initial negative lobe dephases spins, and the subsequent positive lobe rephases them to form the gradient echo. No 180° RF refocusing pulse is used, which is the key difference from spin echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 91"}, {"id": "IP-842", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "The 180-degree refocusing pulse in a spin echo sequence rephases signal dephasing caused by:", "options": ["Static magnetic field (B0) inhomogeneities only", "Magnetic susceptibility differences only", "Chemical shift-related frequency differences only", "Static field inhomogeneities, magnetic susceptibility differences, and chemical shift-related dephasing"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The 180-degree refocusing pulse in spin echo rephases all sources of static dephasing: B0 field inhomogeneities, magnetic susceptibility differences between tissues, and chemical shift frequency offsets. This comprehensive rephasing produces true T2 contrast rather than T2* contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-843", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The gradient that remains active during echo signal acquisition is the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Slice-select gradient", "Frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Flow-encoding gradient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding (readout) gradient remains active during echo signal acquisition. It creates a linear frequency variation across the slice so that each spatial position along the readout axis produces signal at a unique frequency, enabling spatial localization after Fourier transformation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-844", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "In a gradient echo sequence, when the TR is substantially shorter than the T2 relaxation time of the tissue, the magnetization enters a condition known as:", "options": ["Steady state", "Complete spin dephasing", "Spin rephasing", "Signal saturation"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When TR is substantially shorter than tissue T2 relaxation times, residual transverse magnetization persists before the next excitation. This creates a steady state where both longitudinal and transverse magnetization reach a dynamic equilibrium, which is the basis for SSFP and other steady-state GRE sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-845", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.e", "stem": "In a standard MRI pulse sequence, the phase-encoding gradient is applied:", "options": ["After the frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Before the frequency-encoding (readout) gradient", "Instead of the frequency-encoding gradient", "Simultaneously with the frequency-encoding gradient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The phase-encoding gradient is applied between the excitation and readout events—after the slice-select gradient but before the frequency-encoding gradient. Its amplitude is stepped through different values for each TR period, encoding spatial information along the phase axis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 145"}, {"id": "IP-846", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "During echo signal readout, the active gradient is the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Slice-selection gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Oblique gradient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "During echo signal readout, the frequency-encoding gradient is the active gradient. It spatially encodes signal along one in-plane axis by assigning unique frequencies to different positions. The phase-encoding gradient is applied before readout, and slice selection occurs during excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-847", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.f", "stem": "The gradient commonly referred to as the 'readout' gradient is the:", "options": ["Phase-encoding gradient", "Slice-selection gradient", "Frequency-encoding gradient", "Oblique gradient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The frequency-encoding gradient is commonly called the readout gradient because it is active during the period when the echo signal is being read out (sampled) by the receiver coil and analog-to-digital converter.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-848", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1", "stem": "To achieve a phase-encoding matrix of 256 with a single signal average (1 NSA), the pulse sequence must complete how many TR repetitions?", "options": ["192", "256", "512", "2"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Each TR period fills one line of k-space in conventional sequences. A phase-encoding matrix of 256 with 1 NSA requires 256 TR repetitions, one for each unique phase-encoding gradient amplitude needed to fill all 256 lines.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-849", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A conventional dual-echo spin echo sequence is prescribed with 20 slice locations. How many short-TE images will be produced?", "options": ["2", "4", "20", "40"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A dual-echo SE sequence produces two echoes at each slice location (one at short TE, one at long TE). With 20 slice locations, 20 short-TE images are produced—one per slice. The total output is 40 images (20 short-TE + 20 long-TE).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-850", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A conventional dual-echo spin echo sequence is prescribed with 20 slice locations. How many long-TE images will be produced?", "options": ["2", "4", "20", "40"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Similarly, the dual-echo SE produces 20 long-TE images—one at each of the 20 slice locations. The long-TE images provide T2-weighted contrast while the short-TE images provide PD or T1-weighted contrast from the same acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-851", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "In a dual-echo spin echo sequence, how many images are created at each slice location?", "options": ["2", "4", "20", "40"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "At each slice location in a dual-echo spin echo sequence, exactly 2 images are created: one at the short TE and one at the long TE. This provides two different contrast weightings from a single acquisition without additional scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-852", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "A dual-echo spin echo sequence is prescribed with 20 slice locations. What is the total number of images produced?", "options": ["2", "4", "20", "40"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A dual-echo SE with 20 slices produces 2 images per slice × 20 slices = 40 total images. Half (20) are short-TE images and half (20) are long-TE images, providing comprehensive T1/PD and T2 information simultaneously.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-853", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "In a dual-echo spin echo sequence, the two sets of images are acquired with different amounts of:", "options": ["T1 contrast information", "T2 contrast information", "T2* contrast information", "Proton density information"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The two sets of images in a dual-echo SE are acquired at different echo times, so they contain different amounts of T2 contrast information. The short-TE set has minimal T2 weighting (PD or T1), while the long-TE set has maximal T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-854", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "If a dual-echo spin echo sequence were converted to a fast spin echo (FSE) sequence with the same number of echoes, how many lines of k-space would be filled during each TR period?", "options": ["4", "1", "8", "2"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A dual-echo FSE fills 2 lines of k-space per TR period (ETL = 2), matching the number of echoes. In conventional dual-echo SE, only 1 line per echo per TR is filled but two echoes are read out. The FSE version fills one k-space line from each echo.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-855", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "A conventional spin echo sequence requires 12 minutes to acquire. If the same acquisition is performed using fast spin echo with an echo train length (ETL) of 6 and all other scan time factors remain unchanged, the new acquisition time will be approximately:", "options": ["2 minutes", "1 minute", "6 minutes", "4 minutes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "FSE scan time equals conventional SE time divided by the ETL. With ETL = 6: 12 min / 6 = 2 minutes. Each TR fills 6 k-space lines instead of 1, reducing the number of required TR periods by a factor of 6.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-856", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "In a fast spin echo (FSE) sequence, the effective TE corresponds to the echo collected with:", "options": ["The steepest (outermost) phase-encoding gradient amplitudes", "High-amplitude phase-encoding gradients", "Low-amplitude (shallow) phase-encoding gradients", "The first phase-encoding step applied"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The effective TE in FSE corresponds to the echo collected with low-amplitude (shallow) phase-encoding gradients, which fill the central lines of k-space. These central lines determine overall image contrast, so the TE at which they are collected defines the effective TE and contrast weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68; Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-857", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "In a fast spin echo (FSE) sequence, the data lines that contribute most to spatial resolution are acquired with:", "options": ["The central (low-frequency) lines of k-space", "High-amplitude (steep) phase-encoding gradients", "Low-amplitude (shallow) phase-encoding gradients", "The first phase-encoding steps"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spatial resolution in FSE is determined by the high-frequency data at the periphery of k-space, which is acquired with high-amplitude (steep) phase-encoding gradients. These outer lines encode fine detail and edge information, while central lines determine contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-858", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "When acquiring T1- or PD-weighted images with a fast spin echo (FSE) sequence, blurring artifact can be minimized by selecting:", "options": ["A shorter echo train length (ETL)", "A longer echo train length (ETL)", "A larger field of view (FOV)", "A wider receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Blurring in FSE results from T2 filtering across the echo train. A shorter ETL reduces the range of T2 decay across the echoes, minimizing blurring. This is particularly important for T1 and PD weighting where a long echo train would degrade sharpness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-859", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "When acquiring T2-weighted images with a fast spin echo (FSE) sequence, scan time can be reduced by selecting:", "options": ["A shorter echo train length (ETL)", "A longer echo train length (ETL)", "A narrower receiver bandwidth", "A larger acquisition matrix"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A longer ETL reduces T2-weighted FSE scan time by filling more k-space lines per TR period. Since T2-weighted images tolerate some blurring (the contrast is inherently soft), longer ETLs are acceptable for T2 acquisitions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-860", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.b", "stem": "A gradient echo sequence that uses gradient or RF spoiling to destroy residual transverse magnetization before each excitation pulse is classified as:", "options": ["A rewound gradient echo sequence", "A spoiled (incoherent) gradient echo sequence", "A balanced gradient echo sequence", "A magnetization-prepared sequence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A spoiled (incoherent) gradient echo sequence uses gradient or RF spoiling to destroy residual transverse magnetization before each new excitation. This ensures only longitudinal magnetization contributes to signal, producing T1-weighted contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 109"}, {"id": "IP-861", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.b", "stem": "Dynamic contrast-enhanced imaging of the liver typically employs a gradient echo sequence with:", "options": ["An additional 180-degree refocusing pulse", "An initial 180-degree inversion pulse", "Gradient or RF spoiling", "Steady-state free precession (SSFP)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Dynamic contrast-enhanced liver imaging uses spoiled gradient echo sequences because spoiling produces clean T1-weighted contrast ideal for detecting gadolinium enhancement. The short TR enables rapid volumetric acquisition during breath-hold for arterial and venous phase timing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 109"}, {"id": "IP-862", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.c", "stem": "Gradient echo sequences designed to produce high signal intensity from fluid include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Coherent gradient echo sequences", "Spoiled (incoherent) gradient echo sequences", "Steady-state gradient echo sequences", "T2*-weighted gradient echo sequences"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spoiled (incoherent) GRE sequences destroy residual transverse magnetization, eliminating the T2 contribution that makes fluid bright. Coherent, steady-state, and T2*-weighted GRE sequences all preserve some transverse magnetization, producing high signal from fluid.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 106"}, {"id": "IP-863", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Contrast-enhanced MR angiography of the renal arteries is typically performed using which type of gradient echo sequence?", "options": ["Spoiled (incoherent) gradient echo", "Coherent (rewound) gradient echo", "Balanced steady-state free precession (SSFP)", "T2*-weighted gradient echo"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Contrast-enhanced MRA of renal arteries uses spoiled GRE because spoiling produces strong T1 weighting that maximizes the signal enhancement from gadolinium in the arterial phase. The short TR and small flip angle enable fast 3D volumetric acquisition during breath-hold.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 109; Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-864", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "Which statement about gradient echo (GRE) sequences is correct?", "options": ["GRE sequences can produce either T1-weighted or T2*-weighted contrast depending on parameter selection", "GRE sequences are limited to producing only T2*-weighted contrast", "GRE sequences always produce proton density-weighted contrast", "GRE sequences require a 180-degree refocusing pulse to achieve T1 weighting"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "GRE sequences can produce T1-weighted contrast (using large flip angles, short TR, and spoiling) or T2*-weighted contrast (using small flip angles and longer TE without spoiling). This versatility distinguishes GRE from SE, which cannot produce T2* weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-865", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "Gradient echo image contrast is influenced by all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Magnetic susceptibility differences", "Local magnetic field inhomogeneity", "Chemical shift effects", "Aliasing artifact"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "GRE image contrast is influenced by magnetic susceptibility differences, local field inhomogeneity, and chemical shift effects—all of which affect T2* dephasing. Aliasing artifact is a spatial encoding issue unrelated to GRE-specific contrast mechanisms.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "IP-866", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "Gradient echo sequences used to evaluate hemorrhagic lesions rely primarily on which imaging mechanism?", "options": ["Magnetic susceptibility effects", "Magnetic field inhomogeneity correction", "Chemical shift differences", "Spatial aliasing"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "GRE sequences are exquisitely sensitive to magnetic susceptibility effects because they lack the 180° refocusing pulse. Hemorrhagic blood products (hemosiderin, deoxyhemoglobin) are paramagnetic and cause local field distortions that produce conspicuous signal loss (blooming) on GRE images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89; Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-867", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "A FLAIR (fluid-attenuated inversion recovery) sequence is primarily designed to suppress signal from:", "options": ["Multiple sclerosis plaques", "Gadolinium-enhanced tissue", "Fat", "Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "FLAIR is designed to suppress CSF signal using a long inversion time matched to CSF's T1 recovery (~2,000 ms at 1.5T). This makes periventricular and cortical pathology visible against the suppressed CSF background. MS plaques and gadolinium-enhanced tissue are not suppressed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-868", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "At which of the following field strengths would the shortest inversion time (TI) be required to null fat signal on a STIR sequence?", "options": ["0.35 T", "1.0 T", "1.5 T", "3.0 T"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fat T1 varies with field strength—shorter at lower fields (e.g., ~80 ms at 0.35T) and longer at higher fields (~260 ms at 3.0T). Since STIR TI is set to approximately 69% of fat's T1, the lowest field strength (0.35T) requires the shortest TI to reach the fat null point.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-869", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "To null the signal from a specific tissue using an inversion recovery sequence, the inversion time (TI) should be set to approximately what percentage of that tissue's T1 relaxation time?", "options": ["43%", "69%", "80%", "37%"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "To null a tissue using IR, the TI is set to approximately 69% of that tissue's T1 relaxation time (specifically TI = T1 × ln2 ≈ 0.693 × T1). At this TI, the recovering longitudinal magnetization of the target tissue passes through zero, producing no signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-870", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.4", "stem": "Which of the following best describes an echo planar imaging (EPI) pulse sequence?", "options": ["A single 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a single 180-degree refocusing pulse", "A 180-degree inversion pulse followed by a 90-degree/180-degree combination", "A rapid series (train) of gradient echoes acquired after a single excitation", "A rapid series (train) of spin echoes generated by multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "EPI acquires a rapid train of gradient echoes after a single excitation by rapidly alternating the readout gradient polarity. This allows an entire image to be acquired in a fraction of a second. FSE uses multiple RF refocusing pulses instead, which is fundamentally different.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-871", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "Which of the following best describes a fast spin echo (FSE) pulse sequence?", "options": ["A single 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a single 180-degree refocusing pulse", "A 180-degree inversion pulse followed by a 90-degree/180-degree combination", "A rapid series (train) of gradient echoes acquired after a single excitation", "A rapid series (train) of spin echoes generated by multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "FSE uses multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses after a single 90-degree excitation, generating a train of spin echoes. Each echo fills a different line of k-space, dramatically reducing scan time compared to conventional SE while maintaining true T2 contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-872", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "Which of the following best describes an inversion recovery (IR) pulse sequence?", "options": ["A single 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a single 180-degree refocusing pulse", "A 180-degree inversion pulse followed by a 90-degree excitation and 180-degree refocusing pulse", "A rapid series (train) of gradient echoes acquired after a single excitation", "A rapid series (train) of spin echoes generated by multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Inversion recovery begins with a 180-degree inversion pulse, followed after the TI delay by a 90-degree excitation pulse and 180-degree refocusing pulse (standard SE readout). The initial inversion provides tissue-selective suppression capability.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-873", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "Which of the following best describes a conventional spin echo (SE) pulse sequence?", "options": ["A 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse", "A 180-degree inversion pulse followed by a 90-degree/180-degree combination", "A rapid series (train) of gradient echoes acquired after a single excitation", "A rapid series (train) of spin echoes generated by multiple refocusing pulses"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Conventional spin echo consists of a 90-degree excitation pulse followed by a 180-degree refocusing pulse, producing a single echo per TR period. This is the simplest SE configuration and the foundation from which FSE, IR, and other variants are derived.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 59"}, {"id": "IP-874", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.4", "stem": "Which of the following EPI acquisition strategies would produce the least susceptibility-related distortion?", "options": ["Single-shot SE-EPI with a 256 x 256 matrix", "Single-shot GRE-EPI with a 512 x 192 matrix", "Multi-shot (4-shot) SE-EPI with a 256 x 256 matrix", "Single-shot SE-EPI with a 192 x 192 matrix"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Multi-shot SE-EPI distributes k-space acquisition across multiple excitations (shots), reducing the echo train length per shot. This shortens the readout window, reducing susceptibility-induced distortion compared to single-shot approaches. SE-EPI also benefits from the 180° refocusing pulse.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-875", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.7", "stem": "When performing functional MRI (fMRI) to map the visual cortex, which pulse sequence maximizes sensitivity to the BOLD (blood oxygen level-dependent) effect?", "options": ["Spin echo EPI", "Gradient echo EPI", "Fast spin echo with driven equilibrium", "3D spoiled gradient echo with magnetization transfer"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient echo EPI maximizes BOLD sensitivity because it preserves T2* contrast, which is the basis of the BOLD effect. The T2* shortening caused by deoxyhemoglobin in active brain regions is best detected without a 180° refocusing pulse (which would rephase susceptibility effects).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-876", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "On which of the following sequences will multiple sclerosis (MS) plaques appear hyperintense relative to both cerebrospinal fluid and normal white matter?", "options": ["T2-weighted FLAIR", "T1-weighted FLAIR", "T2-weighted fast spin echo", "T2-weighted FSE with RF fat suppression"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T2-weighted FLAIR suppresses CSF signal while maintaining T2 sensitivity, making MS plaques appear bright against both the dark CSF and the relatively lower-signal normal white matter. Standard T2 FSE shows plaques bright but CSF is also bright, obscuring periventricular lesions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-877", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "In a balanced gradient echo (SSFP) acquisition, the predominant contrast weighting is determined by:", "options": ["T1 relaxation time alone", "T2 relaxation time alone", "T2* decay rate", "The ratio of T2 to T1 relaxation times"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In balanced SSFP, the contrast weighting is determined by the T2/T1 ratio of tissues. Fluids with high T2/T1 ratios (like CSF and blood) appear very bright, while tissues with lower ratios (like muscle) appear darker. This is distinct from pure T1, T2, or T2* weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-878", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.d", "stem": "In a balanced gradient echo (SSFP) cardiac image, all of the following structures demonstrate high signal intensity EXCEPT:", "options": ["Blood within the left ventricle", "Cerebrospinal fluid", "Blood within the inferior vena cava", "Normal myocardium"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In balanced SSFP cardiac images, fluids with high T2/T1 ratios (blood, CSF) appear bright. Normal myocardium has a relatively low T2/T1 ratio and appears dark compared to the blood pool, which is essential for delineating ventricular walls during CINE evaluation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-879", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "Parallel imaging techniques include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["SENSE (Sensitivity Encoding)", "SMASH (Simultaneous Acquisition of Spatial Harmonics)", "GRAPPA (Generalized Autocalibrating Partially Parallel Acquisition)", "SAT (spatial saturation)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "SENSE, SMASH, and GRAPPA are all parallel imaging techniques that use phased-array coil sensitivity profiles to reconstruct undersampled k-space data. SAT (spatial saturation) is a presaturation technique used to suppress signal from specific regions—it is not a parallel imaging method.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-880", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "Before a parallel imaging acquisition can be performed, the scanner must first acquire a low-resolution:", "options": ["Test bolus scan", "Frequency filtering scan", "Calibration (reference) scan", "Presaturation scan"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Before parallel imaging can be performed, a low-resolution calibration (reference) scan must be acquired to map the individual sensitivity profiles of each phased-array coil element. This calibration data is used by the reconstruction algorithm to separate overlapping signals.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-881", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "When performing 2D time-of-flight MR venography of the inferior vena cava (IVC) using axial slices, the presaturation band should be placed:", "options": ["Anterior to the imaging slices", "Posterior to the imaging slices", "Superior to the imaging slices", "Inferior to the imaging slices"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "For 2D TOF MR venography of the IVC using axial slices, the presaturation band is placed superior to the imaging slices to suppress incoming arterial blood (flowing inferiorly from the heart). This allows visualization of venous blood flowing superiorly from the lower extremities.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-882", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "When performing 2D time-of-flight MR angiography of the carotid arteries using axial slices, the presaturation band should be placed:", "options": ["Anterior to the imaging slices", "Posterior to the imaging slices", "Superior to the imaging slices", "Inferior to the imaging slices"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "For 2D TOF carotid MRA using axial slices, the presaturation band is placed superior to suppress venous return (jugular veins flowing inferiorly). This allows visualization of arterial blood flowing superiorly in the carotids without venous contamination.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-883", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "When performing 2D time-of-flight MR angiography of the circle of Willis using axial slices, the presaturation band is typically placed:", "options": ["Anterior to the imaging slices", "Posterior to the imaging slices", "Superior to the imaging slices", "Inferior to the imaging slices"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "For 2D TOF MRA of the circle of Willis using axial slices, the presaturation band is placed superior to suppress superior sagittal sinus venous return. This isolates the arterial signal from the carotid and vertebrobasilar systems flowing into the circle of Willis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-884", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "When performing 2D time-of-flight MR venography of the superior sagittal sinus using axial slices, the presaturation band should be placed:", "options": ["Anterior to the imaging slices", "Posterior to the imaging slices", "Superior to the imaging slices", "Inferior to the imaging slices"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "For 2D TOF venography of the superior sagittal sinus, the presaturation band is placed inferior to suppress incoming arterial blood from the carotids. Venous blood in the sagittal sinus flows posteriorly/inferiorly, so inferior saturation blocks arterial contamination.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-885", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "The scan time for a 2D conventional spin echo (SE) sequence is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x number of slices", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA / ETL", "TR x number of shots x NSA"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "2D conventional SE scan time = TR × number of phase-encoding steps × NSA. The number of slices does not appear because all slices are acquired within each TR period through interleaved multi-slice excitation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-886", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "The scan time for a 2D inversion recovery (IR) sequence is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x number of slices", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA / ETL", "TR x number of shots x NSA"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "2D IR scan time uses the same formula as SE: TR × phase-encoding steps × NSA. Despite the additional inversion pulse, the interleaved multi-slice approach still acquires all slices within each TR period, so slice count does not affect scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78; Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-887", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "The scan time for a 2D gradient echo (GRE) sequence is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x number of slices", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA / ETL", "TR x number of shots x NSA"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "2D GRE scan time = TR × phase-encoding steps × NSA. The formula is identical to SE because each TR fills one line of k-space per slice. GRE's time advantage comes from its much shorter TR (not a different formula).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-888", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.4", "stem": "The scan time for an echo planar imaging (EPI) sequence is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x number of slices", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x ETL", "TR x number of shots x NSA"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "EPI scan time = TR × number of shots × NSA. In single-shot EPI, shots = 1, so scan time per slice ≈ one TR period. In multi-shot EPI, the total k-space is divided across multiple excitations (shots), increasing time proportionally.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122; Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-889", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "The scan time for a 2D fast spin echo (FSE) sequence is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x number of slices", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA / ETL", "TR x number of shots x NSA"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "FSE scan time = TR × phase-encoding steps × NSA / ETL. Dividing by the echo train length accounts for the multiple k-space lines filled per TR period. Longer ETL = shorter scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68; Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-890", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "The scan time for a 3D (volume) acquisition is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA x number of slice-encoding steps", "TR x number of phase-encoding steps x NSA / ETL", "TR x number of shots x NSA"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "3D scan time = TR × phase-encoding steps × NSA × number of slice-encoding steps. The additional factor accounts for the second phase-encoding direction used to partition the slab into individual slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-891", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "In a fast spin echo sequence, if the echo train length (ETL) is increased by a factor of four while all other parameters remain unchanged, the scan time will be reduced to approximately:", "options": ["The same duration (no change)", "One-half the original time", "One-third the original time", "One-quarter the original time"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "FSE scan time is inversely proportional to ETL. Quadrupling the ETL (×4) reduces scan time to one-quarter of the original. If the original scan was any duration, dividing by 4 gives the new time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-892", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "For a 3D volume acquisition, the total scan time is determined by:", "options": ["TR x NSA x receiver bandwidth x slice thickness", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps x slab thickness", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps x ETL", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps x number of slice-encoding partitions"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "3D volume scan time = TR × NSA × phase-encoding steps × number of slice-encoding partitions. The slice-encoding partitions replace the slice count from 2D imaging, and each partition requires a separate phase-encoding step in the through-slab direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-893", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "In a multi-shot fast imaging acquisition, the number of shots (excitations) is calculated by:", "options": ["TR x number of phase-encoding steps", "Number of phase-encoding steps / ETL", "ETL / number of phase-encoding steps", "Number of phase-encoding steps x NSA"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In multi-shot FSE, shots = number of phase-encoding steps / ETL. Each shot (excitation) fills ETL lines of k-space, so the total phase-encoding matrix divided by the ETL gives the number of shots required.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-894", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "A single-shot fast spin echo (FSE) acquisition occurs when:", "options": ["The number of phase-encoding steps equals the ETL (e.g., 256 PEs with ETL of 256)", "The ETL is double the number of phase-encoding steps", "The ETL is half the number of phase-encoding steps", "The ETL is one-quarter the number of phase-encoding steps"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Single-shot FSE occurs when ETL equals the total number of phase-encoding steps (e.g., ETL = 256 with 256 PEs). All k-space lines are acquired after a single excitation, producing the fastest possible FSE acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-895", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "A 4-shot fast spin echo (FSE) acquisition requires a phase-encoding matrix of 256 and an ETL of:", "options": ["256", "128", "32", "64"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A 4-shot FSE requires 4 excitations to fill 256 PE lines. Shots = PE / ETL, so 4 = 256 / ETL, meaning ETL = 64. Each shot fills 64 k-space lines, and 4 shots × 64 lines = 256 total.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-896", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "To minimize scan time and motion sensitivity, clinical diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI) is typically acquired using:", "options": ["Single-shot echo planar imaging (EPI)", "Single-shot fast spin echo", "Multi-shot (two-shot) EPI", "Multi-shot (four-shot) EPI"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Single-shot EPI acquires the entire k-space dataset after one excitation, minimizing scan time and motion sensitivity. This is ideal for DWI because diffusion-sensitizing gradients amplify any motion between shots. Multi-shot approaches reduce distortion but increase motion sensitivity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-897", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "The technique in which a portion of k-space lines are acquired and the remainder are estimated using conjugate symmetry is known by all of the following terms EXCEPT:", "options": ["Half Fourier", "Partial Fourier", "Fractional Fourier", "Interleaved acquisition"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Half Fourier, partial Fourier, and fractional Fourier are all synonymous terms for acquiring slightly more than half of k-space and using conjugate symmetry to estimate the missing data. Interleaved acquisition refers to the order in which slices are excited, not a k-space filling strategy.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-898", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "In a 3D (volume) acquisition, individual slices within the slab are produced by:", "options": ["Applying a second phase-encoding gradient in the slice-selection direction", "Multiple 180-degree refocusing pulses along the slice-selection direction", "Sampling multiple lines of k-space per TR period", "Precise slice-selective RF excitation pulses"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In 3D acquisitions, individual slices within the excited slab are produced by applying a second phase-encoding gradient in the slice-selection direction (slice-encoding or partition-encoding). This encodes spatial information through the slab thickness, which the FFT then separates into discrete slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-899", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "The total scan time for a 3D (volume) acquisition is determined by:", "options": ["TR x NSA x receiver bandwidth x slice thickness", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps x number of slabs", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps x ETL", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps x number of slice partitions"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "3D scan time = TR × NSA × phase-encoding steps × number of slice partitions. This formula accounts for the additional encoding direction needed to resolve individual slices from the volumetric slab.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-900", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "In the standard k-space diagram, one axis represents the phase-encoding direction and the other represents the:", "options": ["Spatial position", "Signal intensity", "Image contrast", "Frequency-encoding direction"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In a standard k-space diagram, one axis represents phase encoding (ky, vertical) and the other represents the frequency-encoding direction (kx, horizontal). These two axes correspond to the spatial frequency domains of the final image.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 159"}, {"id": "IP-901", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "In a conventional spin echo sequence, one line of k-space is filled during each:", "options": ["Frequency-encoding period", "Echo time (TE) interval", "Repetition time (TR) period", "Excitation pulse"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In conventional SE, one line of k-space is filled during each TR period. The phase-encoding gradient amplitude determines which specific line is filled, and the frequency-encoding gradient is active during the echo readout to sample that line.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-902", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Due to conjugate symmetry, the data in the upper portion of k-space is a mirror image of the data in the:", "options": ["Right portion", "Left portion", "Upper portion", "Lower portion"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Due to conjugate (Hermitian) symmetry, k-space data in the upper half is a complex conjugate mirror image of the lower half. This mathematical property allows reconstruction of a complete dataset from slightly more than half the data, reducing scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-903", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "The technique of acquiring slightly more than half of the phase-encoding views in k-space and using conjugate symmetry to estimate the missing data is known as:", "options": ["Zero fill interpolation", "Fast spin echo", "Half (partial) Fourier imaging", "Power scanning"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Half (partial) Fourier imaging exploits conjugate symmetry by acquiring slightly more than half the phase-encoding views and mathematically estimating the remainder. This reduces scan time at the cost of some SNR loss.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-904", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.b", "stem": "In a fast spin echo sequence with an echo train length (ETL) of 8, how many lines of k-space are filled during each TR period?", "options": ["4", "2", "12", "8"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In FSE with ETL = 8, exactly 8 lines of k-space are filled during each TR period—one line per echo in the echo train. Each of the 8 refocusing pulses generates a separate echo that fills a different k-space line.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-905", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.a", "stem": "To create a projection image from a 3D MRA dataset, the most commonly used post-processing technique is:", "options": ["Multiplanar reformation (MPR)", "Region of interest calculation", "Maximum intensity projection (MIP)", "Summation pixel projection"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Maximum Intensity Projection (MIP) is the standard post-processing technique for 3D MRA. It projects the brightest voxel along each ray path through the volume, creating an angiographic image that displays the high-signal vessels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-906", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.a", "stem": "A 3D time-of-flight MRA of the circle of Willis is post-processed to display all intracranial vasculature in a single axial view. This type of image is known as a:", "options": ["Multiplanar reformation", "Segmented image", "Minimum intensity projection", "Collapsed (projection) image"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A collapsed (projection) image displays all vasculature from a 3D TOF dataset in a single view by projecting the maximum intensity along each viewing angle. This produces an overview of the entire vascular tree similar to a conventional angiogram.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-907", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.a", "stem": "When post-processing a 3D TOF MRA of the circle of Willis, selectively removing background tissue to improve visualization of the intracranial vasculature is a step known as:", "options": ["Multiplanar reformation", "Segmentation", "Maximum intensity projection", "Collapsed imaging"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Segmentation is the process of selectively removing background tissue (brain parenchyma, bone, fat) from a 3D MRA dataset before applying MIP, improving visualization of the target vasculature without overlap from bright non-vascular structures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-908", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.b", "stem": "Generating additional images in arbitrary planes from a 3D volumetric dataset is accomplished using a technique known as:", "options": ["Multiplanar reformation (MPR)", "Region of interest calculation", "Maximum intensity projection (MIP)", "Summation pixel projection"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Multiplanar reformation (MPR) generates images in arbitrary planes by computationally reslicing a 3D volumetric dataset. This allows visualization of anatomy in orientations not directly acquired, without additional scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-909", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.b", "stem": "To produce high-quality multiplanar reformatted (MPR) images, the original acquisition voxel should be:", "options": ["As rectangular (anisotropic) as possible", "Acquired during a single breath-hold", "As close to isotropic (equal dimensions) as possible", "Elongated in the slice-select direction"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "High-quality MPR images require isotropic voxels (equal dimensions in all three directions) to avoid stair-step artifact and resolution loss when reformatting in oblique or non-acquired planes. Anisotropic voxels produce directionally dependent resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-910", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Acquiring the low-frequency (high-signal) central lines of k-space first in a rectilinear (linear) fashion is known as:", "options": ["Linear ordering", "Centric ordering", "Elliptic centric ordering", "Reverse centric ordering"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Centric ordering acquires the central (low-frequency, high-contrast) lines of k-space first in a linear (rectilinear) fashion from the center outward. This ensures peak contrast information is captured at the beginning of the acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-911", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "Acquiring the low-frequency (high-signal) central lines of k-space first in a spiral pattern is known as:", "options": ["Linear ordering", "Centric ordering", "Elliptic centric ordering", "Reverse centric ordering"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Elliptic centric ordering acquires central k-space lines first in a spiral pattern, covering the two-dimensional center of k-space more efficiently than linear centric ordering. This is particularly useful for contrast-enhanced 3D acquisitions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-912", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "During dynamic contrast-enhanced imaging, k-space is typically filled using which ordering scheme to ensure optimal capture of peak contrast enhancement?", "options": ["Linear ordering", "Centric ordering", "Reverse centric ordering", "Reverse linear ordering"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Centric k-space ordering is preferred for dynamic contrast-enhanced imaging because it captures the central lines (which determine image contrast) at the beginning of the acquisition when contrast enhancement is at its peak.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 199"}, {"id": "IP-913", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.1", "stem": "The high-frequency (low-amplitude) data points located in the periphery of k-space primarily contribute to:", "options": ["Overall image contrast", "Overall signal intensity", "Noise reduction", "Edge detail and spatial resolution"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The peripheral (outer) lines of k-space contain high spatial frequency data that encodes fine edge detail and spatial resolution. These low-amplitude data points contribute the sharpest features of the image but have minimal effect on overall contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-914", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.c", "stem": "During contrast-enhanced imaging of the abdominal organs, pre- and post-gadolinium images are acquired. To isolate areas of contrast enhancement, the post-processing technique performed is:", "options": ["Multiplanar reformation", "Image subtraction", "Region of interest calculation", "Maximum intensity projection"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Image subtraction removes pre-contrast background signal from post-contrast images, isolating areas that demonstrate gadolinium enhancement. This is the standard technique for evaluating liver lesion enhancement patterns during dynamic contrast-enhanced imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-915", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.b", "stem": "A 3D dataset reconstructed to display a three-dimensional representation of the anatomy using opacity and shading is known as:", "options": ["Multiplanar reformation (MPR)", "Region of interest calculation (ROI)", "Image subtraction", "Volume rendering (VR)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Volume rendering (VR) uses opacity and shading algorithms to create a three-dimensional representation of anatomy from a 3D dataset. Unlike MIP (which shows only the brightest voxels), VR displays tissue relationships with depth perception.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-916", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "Evaluation of cardiac function can be performed using all of the following techniques EXCEPT:", "options": ["Cardiac CINE imaging", "Multiphase imaging", "Myocardial perfusion imaging", "Single-slice, single-phase static imaging"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Cardiac function evaluation requires dynamic assessment over the cardiac cycle using CINE, multiphase, or perfusion imaging. Single-slice, single-phase static imaging captures only one moment and cannot assess wall motion, ejection fraction, or valvular function.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-917", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The mathematical process that converts MR signal data from a plot of signal intensity over time to a plot of signal intensity over frequency is known as:", "options": ["Fourier transformation", "Chemical shift analysis", "Parts per million calibration", "Volume rendering"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fourier transformation converts MR signal data from a time-domain representation (signal intensity vs. time) to a frequency-domain representation (signal intensity vs. frequency). This mathematical operation is essential for extracting spatial and spectral information from raw MR data.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-918", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The mathematical operation that converts MR signal data from the time domain to the frequency domain is called:", "options": ["Fourier transformation", "Chemical shift encoding", "Parts per million scaling", "Volume rendering"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fourier transformation converts time-domain signals to frequency-domain data. In MRI, this is performed twice (2D FT) to convert k-space raw data into a spatial image. The process is reversible—inverse FT converts frequency data back to time domain.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-919", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "Which statement about Fourier transformation in MRI is correct?", "options": ["Fourier transformation converts time-domain signal data (such as the FID) into a frequency spectrum", "Fourier transformation converts frequency data into raw k-space data", "Fourier transformation is only performed in the phase-encoding direction", "Fourier transformation increases the signal-to-noise ratio of the image"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fourier transformation converts time-domain data (such as the FID or echo) into a frequency spectrum showing the amplitude of each frequency component. In MRI, this is applied in both the frequency and phase directions to reconstruct the spatial image from k-space.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-920", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.2", "stem": "The Fourier transformation calculations in an MRI system are performed by the:", "options": ["Gradient amplifier", "Array processor", "RF amplifier", "Analog-to-digital converter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The array processor is the specialized hardware component that performs the computationally intensive Fourier transformation calculations. It converts raw k-space data into viewable images rapidly enough for clinical workflow. The gradient amplifier powers gradients, and the ADC digitizes the signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 344"}, {"id": "IP-921", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "A cardiac imaging technique that applies spatial presaturation bands across the myocardium to create a visible grid pattern for assessing wall motion is known as:", "options": ["Myocardial tagging", "Four-chamber CINE imaging", "Short-axis imaging", "Cardiac gating"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Myocardial tagging applies spatial presaturation bands in a grid pattern across the myocardium at end-diastole. As the heart contracts, the tag lines deform with the myocardium, providing a visible measure of regional wall motion and strain.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-922", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Normal physiological blood flow, characterized by a parabolic velocity profile where central flow is fastest and flow near the vessel wall is slowest, is known as:", "options": ["Laminar flow", "Accelerated flow", "Vortex flow", "Turbulent flow"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Laminar flow is the normal physiological blood flow pattern characterized by a parabolic velocity profile where central flow is fastest and flow near the vessel wall is slowest due to friction. This orderly flow pattern produces predictable MR signal behavior.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-923", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Blood flow velocity at a site of vascular stenosis (narrowing) is described as:", "options": ["Laminar flow", "Accelerated flow", "Vortex flow", "Turbulent flow"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "At a stenosis, the narrowed lumen forces blood through a smaller cross-section, accelerating the flow velocity according to the continuity equation (A₁V₁ = A₂V₂). This accelerated flow can cause signal loss on MRA due to intravoxel dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-924", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "The swirling blood flow pattern that occurs immediately distal to a vascular stenosis is known as:", "options": ["Laminar flow", "Accelerated flow", "Vortex flow", "Turbulent flow"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Vortex flow is the swirling, circular flow pattern that develops immediately distal to a stenosis as the accelerated jet expands into the wider vessel lumen. This complex flow pattern causes signal loss on MRA and may overestimate the degree of stenosis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-925", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Under normal physiological conditions, the predominant blood flow pattern in most vessels is:", "options": ["Laminar flow", "Accelerated flow", "Vortex flow", "Turbulent flow"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Under normal physiological conditions, blood flow in most vessels follows a laminar pattern with a parabolic velocity profile. Turbulent flow occurs in pathological conditions (severe stenosis, aneurysms) or at vessel bifurcations.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-926", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "A major advantage of MR angiography over conventional catheter angiography is that:", "options": ["Both heavily T1- and T2-weighted images can be produced", "Multiple projection views can be generated from a single acquisition", "Much smaller catheters are required", "Less ionizing radiation is used"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRA generates 3D volumetric data that can be post-processed into multiple projection views from any angle, all from a single acquisition. Conventional catheter angiography requires separate injections for each projection angle. MRA also uses no ionizing radiation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-927", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Which MRA technique is least sensitive to slow-flowing blood?", "options": ["3D phase contrast MRA", "3D time-of-flight MRA", "2D phase contrast MRA", "2D time-of-flight MRA"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "3D TOF MRA is least sensitive to slow flow because the thick slab excitation saturates slow-flowing spins that remain within the slab for many TR periods. 2D TOF uses thin sequential slices that minimize saturation of slow flow, making it more sensitive.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-928", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Which MRA technique provides the highest sensitivity for visualizing small vessels?", "options": ["3D phase contrast MRA", "3D time-of-flight MRA", "2D phase contrast MRA", "2D time-of-flight MRA"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "3D TOF provides the highest spatial resolution for small vessel visualization because it uses thin slice partitions, high matrix, and small voxels. The volumetric acquisition also provides isotropic data ideal for MIP post-processing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-929", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Which MRA technique is inherently sensitive to blood flow direction?", "options": ["3D phase contrast MRA", "3D time-of-flight MRA", "2D time-of-flight MRA", "Contrast-enhanced MRA"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Phase contrast MRA is inherently sensitive to flow direction because it uses bipolar gradient pairs that encode velocity as phase shifts. The sign of the phase shift indicates direction—positive for one direction and negative for the opposite.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-930", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Which MRA technique can be tuned to detect a specific range of flow velocities by adjusting the velocity encoding (VENC) parameter?", "options": ["3D phase contrast MRA", "3D time-of-flight MRA", "2D time-of-flight MRA", "Contrast-enhanced MRA"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Phase contrast MRA uses the VENC parameter to tune sensitivity to a specific velocity range. The VENC sets the maximum velocity that can be measured without aliasing, allowing optimization for arterial (high VENC) or venous (low VENC) flow.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-931", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "The signal intensity of blood on a time-of-flight (TOF) MRA sequence is primarily determined by:", "options": ["Gadolinium concentration", "Flow-related enhancement", "Velocity-induced phase shift", "Restricted diffusion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "TOF MRA relies on flow-related enhancement: unsaturated blood flowing into a saturated imaging slice produces bright signal relative to the suppressed stationary tissue. Signal intensity depends on flow velocity, slice thickness, TR, and flip angle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-932", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "The signal intensity of blood on a phase contrast (PC) MRA sequence is primarily determined by:", "options": ["Gadolinium concentration", "Flow-related enhancement", "Velocity-induced phase shift", "Restricted diffusion"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Phase contrast MRA signal intensity depends on velocity-induced phase shifts created by bipolar gradient pairs. Moving spins accumulate a net phase proportional to their velocity, while stationary spins experience zero net phase. The phase difference creates the vascular contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-933", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "The signal intensity on a diffusion-weighted image is primarily determined by:", "options": ["Gadolinium concentration", "Flow-related enhancement", "Velocity-induced phase shift", "The degree of water molecule diffusion"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "DWI signal intensity is determined by the degree of water molecule diffusion within tissue. Areas of restricted diffusion retain signal (appear bright) while areas of free diffusion lose signal. This is controlled by the b-value and the tissue's ADC.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-934", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In an MRA acquisition, suppression of signal from unwanted vessels is most commonly achieved by applying:", "options": ["Gradient moment nulling", "Spatial presaturation bands", "Spectral presaturation", "Increased receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spatial presaturation bands are placed upstream of the imaging volume to suppress signal from unwanted vessels. The sat band saturates the magnetization of incoming blood so it produces no signal when it enters the imaging slice, selectively eliminating arterial or venous contamination.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-935", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "To minimize signal loss from intravoxel dephasing in MRA sequences, which combination of parameter adjustments is most effective?", "options": ["Long TR and large voxels", "Short TE and small voxels", "Long TE and large field of view", "Long TR and wide receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Short TE minimizes time for intravoxel dephasing, and small voxels reduce the range of velocities within each voxel. Together, these reduce signal loss from velocity dispersion in MRA. Long TE and large voxels worsen intravoxel dephasing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-936", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In laminar flow, blood velocity is greatest:", "options": ["Farthest from the heart", "At the vessel wall", "At the center of the vessel", "Only during systole"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In laminar flow, the parabolic velocity profile means blood at the center of the vessel travels fastest because it experiences the least friction from the vessel wall. Velocity decreases progressively toward the wall where friction is greatest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-937", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Single-order (first-order) gradient moment nulling effectively compensates for:", "options": ["Constant-velocity flow only", "Both constant-velocity and accelerating flow", "Accelerating, decelerating, and pulsatile flow", "All types of flow including turbulent flow"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "First-order gradient moment nulling compensates only for constant-velocity (first-order) flow by adding gradient lobes that zero the first moment. Higher-order corrections are needed for accelerating or pulsatile flow but add complexity and increase TE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-938", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In a spin echo sequence, flowing blood commonly appears as a signal void because:", "options": ["Both the excitation and refocusing pulses are slice-selective, and the relatively long TE allows excited spins to flow out of the slice before signal collection", "The RF flip angle is too small to excite moving protons", "Gradient echo rephasing cancels the flow signal before the spin echo forms", "The receiver bandwidth is insufficient to sample the Doppler-shifted frequencies of moving blood"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In spin echo, both the 90° and 180° pulses are slice-selective, so blood excited by the 90° may flow out of the slice before the 180° refocusing pulse. Without refocusing, these spins produce no echo signal, creating a flow void. The relatively long TE exacerbates this effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-939", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "At the point of maximum stenosis within a diseased vessel, the velocity of blood flow is:", "options": ["Increased", "Decreased", "Reversed", "Unaffected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "At the point of maximum stenosis, the reduced cross-sectional area forces the same volume of blood through a narrower opening, increasing velocity according to the continuity principle. This acceleration is a key feature used to grade stenosis severity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-940", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In a time-of-flight (TOF) MRA sequence, stationary tissue appears hypointense relative to flowing blood because of:", "options": ["T2 relaxation effects", "T2* decay effects", "Saturation effects from repeated RF pulses", "Magnetic field inhomogeneities"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In TOF MRA, stationary tissue is repeatedly excited by RF pulses at short TR, progressively saturating its longitudinal magnetization and reducing its signal. This saturation effect makes background tissue appear dark relative to fresh unsaturated inflowing blood.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-941", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In a time-of-flight (TOF) MRA sequence, flowing blood appears hyperintense relative to stationary tissue because of:", "options": ["T2 relaxation effects", "The type of RF coil used", "The presaturation pulse applied", "Flow-related enhancement (inflow of unsaturated spins)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Flow-related enhancement occurs in TOF MRA when unsaturated blood from outside the imaging volume enters the saturated slice. These fresh spins have full longitudinal magnetization and produce much brighter signal than the partially saturated stationary tissue.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-942", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "In phase contrast MRA, the signal intensity within a vessel is dependent on the:", "options": ["Velocity of the flowing blood", "T1 relaxation time of the surrounding tissue", "Field of view selected", "Number of phase-encoding steps"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In phase contrast MRA, signal intensity within vessels depends on blood velocity. The bipolar flow-encoding gradients create phase shifts proportional to velocity, which are then displayed as signal intensity differences. Faster flow produces brighter signal (up to the VENC limit).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-943", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "A unique capability of phase contrast MRA compared to time-of-flight MRA is the ability to determine the:", "options": ["Exact diameter of the vessel lumen", "Direction of blood flow", "Temporal displacement of the vessel", "Percentage stenosis of a lesion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Phase contrast MRA uniquely determines flow direction because the sign (positive or negative) of the velocity-induced phase shift encodes whether blood is flowing toward or away from the gradient. TOF MRA shows flow presence but cannot determine direction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 304"}, {"id": "IP-944", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "A major advantage of 3D time-of-flight MRA over 2D time-of-flight MRA is the ability to:", "options": ["Determine blood flow velocities", "Shorten imaging time", "Visualize smaller vessels with higher spatial resolution", "Reduce the signal intensity from stationary tissue"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "3D TOF provides higher spatial resolution than 2D TOF because it uses thin slice partitions within a volume, achieving smaller voxels and smoother vessel depiction. This makes 3D TOF superior for visualizing small intracranial vessels like the circle of Willis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-945", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "A major advantage of 2D time-of-flight MRA over 3D time-of-flight MRA is the ability to:", "options": ["Image a larger vascular territory without saturation of slow-flowing blood", "Determine the percentage stenosis of a lesion", "Better image reverse flow", "Image a thrombus without depicting the slower flow surrounding it"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "2D TOF images each slice independently with fresh unsaturated blood entering each thin slice, maintaining sensitivity to slow-flowing blood over a large vascular territory. 3D TOF's thick slab saturates slow flow, making it less suitable for extensive vascular surveys.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-946", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "Cardiac CINE acquisitions typically utilize which type of pulse sequence?", "options": ["Inversion recovery", "Spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Fast spin echo"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Cardiac CINE acquisitions typically use gradient echo (specifically balanced SSFP) sequences because of their fast scan times, high temporal resolution, and excellent blood-myocardium contrast. Spin echo is too slow for dynamic cardiac imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-947", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "Each frame of a cardiac CINE sequence displays the heart:", "options": ["In a different imaging plane", "With varying degrees of spatial resolution", "From a slightly different viewing angle", "At a different phase of the cardiac cycle"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Each frame of a cardiac CINE sequence displays the heart at a different phase of the cardiac cycle (e.g., end-diastole, mid-systole, end-systole). When played as a loop, these frames show wall motion, valve function, and ventricular contraction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-948", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.4.e", "stem": "CINE (kinematic) studies of joints are performed primarily to:", "options": ["Visualize motion and function", "Visualize blood flow", "Measure muscle strength", "Evaluate bone density"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "CINE (kinematic) studies of joints are performed to visualize motion and function—for example, tracking patellar tracking during knee flexion/extension or TMJ disc displacement during mouth opening. This dynamic assessment cannot be achieved with static imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-949", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "Which of the following b-values would produce an image with the greatest amount of diffusion weighting?", "options": ["750 s/mm2", "450 s/mm2", "825 s/mm2", "1100 s/mm2"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Higher b-values produce greater diffusion weighting by applying stronger or longer diffusion-sensitizing gradients. At b = 1100 s/mm², the greatest signal attenuation from freely diffusing water occurs, maximizing contrast between restricted and unrestricted diffusion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-950", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "The primary purpose of calculating an apparent diffusion coefficient (ADC) map is to:", "options": ["Reduce the contribution from diffusion effects", "Eliminate T2 shine-through from the diffusion-weighted image", "Increase the signal-to-noise ratio", "Reduce T1 weighting in the image"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ADC map eliminates T2 shine-through, which is a confounding factor on DWI where tissues with long T2 appear bright regardless of diffusion restriction. The ADC map shows truly restricted diffusion as dark (low ADC) and T2 shine-through as bright (high ADC).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-951", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.5", "stem": "Changing the b-value in a diffusion-weighted sequence alters the:", "options": ["Amplitude, timing, and/or duration of the diffusion-sensitizing gradients", "Amplitude of the phase-encoding gradient", "Duration of the readout gradient", "Spatial resolution of the image"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The b-value is determined by the amplitude, timing, and/or duration of the diffusion-sensitizing gradients. Changing any of these three parameters alters the b-value, which controls the sequence's sensitivity to water molecule motion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-952", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.7", "stem": "During a dynamic susceptibility contrast (DSC) perfusion study of the brain using a gadolinium-based contrast agent, the T2* shortening effect causes:", "options": ["Increased MR signal intensity", "Reduced MR signal intensity", "Increased acquisition time", "Increased chemical shift artifact"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "During DSC perfusion, the concentrated gadolinium bolus passing through brain capillaries creates strong local susceptibility effects that shorten T2*, causing rapid signal loss on T2*-weighted EPI images. This signal drop is measured over time to calculate perfusion maps.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-953", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.8", "stem": "The fundamental MR principle underlying MR spectroscopy (MRS) is:", "options": ["Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction", "Chemical shift", "Flow-related enhancement", "The BOLD (blood oxygen level-dependent) effect"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MR spectroscopy is fundamentally based on chemical shift—the small differences in resonant frequency between hydrogen nuclei in different molecular environments (e.g., NAA, choline, creatine, lactate). These frequency differences are displayed on a parts-per-million scale.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-954", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "When producing an MRA projection image from a 3D TOF dataset using the MIP technique, which tissue type can appear bright and mimic vascular flow?", "options": ["Tissues with long T2 relaxation times", "Tissues or substances with extremely short T1 relaxation times (e.g., fat, methemoglobin)", "Polycystic brain lesions", "Any substance with an extremely short T2 relaxation time"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "On MIP images from TOF MRA, any tissue with extremely short T1 (such as fat or methemoglobin) appears bright because it recovers longitudinal magnetization quickly between TR periods, mimicking the flow-related enhancement of blood vessels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-955", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.7", "stem": "The intrinsic contrast mechanism used in functional MRI (fMRI) is:", "options": ["Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction", "Chemical shift", "Flow-related enhancement", "The BOLD (blood oxygen level-dependent) effect"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Functional MRI uses the BOLD effect, which relies on the paramagnetic properties of deoxyhemoglobin. During neuronal activation, increased blood flow delivers excess oxyhemoglobin, reducing deoxyhemoglobin concentration and causing a local increase in T2*-weighted signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-956", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "All of the following techniques can be used to optimally time the start of a contrast-enhanced MRA acquisition EXCEPT:", "options": ["Automated bolus detection", "Test bolus injection", "Centric k-space filling", "Real-time fluoroscopic triggering"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Centric k-space filling is a k-space ordering strategy, not a timing technique. Automated bolus detection, test bolus injection, and real-time fluoroscopic triggering are all methods used to time the start of a contrast-enhanced MRA acquisition with peak arterial enhancement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-957", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "To reconstruct an image acquired using parallel imaging, which of the following is required?", "options": ["A test bolus scan", "A reference or calibration scan", "A back-projection algorithm", "A half-Fourier acquisition"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Parallel imaging reconstruction requires a reference (calibration) scan that maps the spatial sensitivity profiles of individual phased-array coil elements. Without this calibration data, the algorithm cannot separate overlapping signals from the undersampled acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-958", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.10", "stem": "When parallel imaging is used to reduce acquisition time, which of the following is always true?", "options": ["Scan time is reduced and spatial resolution is increased", "Spatial resolution is reduced as the acceleration factor increases", "SNR is unaffected unless the acceleration factor exceeds 2", "SNR is reduced while spatial resolution remains unaffected"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "When parallel imaging reduces scan time, SNR always decreases while spatial resolution is maintained. The SNR penalty comes from acquiring fewer phase-encoding lines (reduced signal averaging) and the geometry factor (g-factor noise amplification).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-959", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "The time interval between successive excitation pulses in a pulse sequence is known as the:", "options": ["Inversion time (TI)", "Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Preparation time (PR)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The repetition time (TR) is defined as the time interval between successive excitation pulses in a pulse sequence. TR is a fundamental timing parameter that controls T1 weighting, scan time, and the maximum number of slices in multi-slice acquisitions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-960", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "In a spin echo sequence, the time interval between the 90-degree excitation pulse and the center of the spin echo is the:", "options": ["TE (echo time)", "TR (repetition time)", "TI (inversion time)", "One-half TE"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The echo time (TE) is defined as the time interval between the 90-degree excitation pulse and the center of the spin echo. TE controls the amount of T2 decay that occurs before signal collection, determining the degree of T2 weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-961", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.3", "stem": "Presaturation pulses are most commonly used to:", "options": ["Improve spatial resolution", "Reduce flow-related artifacts", "Reduce scan time", "Increase the signal from flowing blood"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Presaturation pulses suppress signal from specific regions by saturating the magnetization of tissue before the excitation pulse. This is most commonly used to reduce flow-related artifacts by suppressing incoming blood signal from vessels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-962", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.3", "stem": "In a standard pulse sequence, presaturation pulses are applied:", "options": ["Before the excitation pulse", "After the 180-degree refocusing pulse", "Between the 90-degree and 180-degree pulses", "After the echo is collected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Presaturation pulses are applied before the excitation pulse so that the targeted tissue (flowing blood, fat) has its magnetization destroyed before the imaging sequence begins. The subsequent excitation pulse cannot produce signal from already-saturated tissue.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-963", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "In gradient echo sequences, the flip angle is primarily adjusted to:", "options": ["Achieve angles less than 90 degrees only", "Vary the angle between successive pulse repetitions", "Control saturation effects and image contrast", "Reduce SAR exclusively in larger patients"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In GRE sequences, the flip angle is primarily adjusted to control saturation effects and image contrast. Smaller flip angles reduce saturation (allowing PD or T2* weighting with shorter TR), while larger flip angles increase T1 contrast. This versatility is unique to GRE.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-964", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Complete saturation of a tissue occurs when:", "options": ["Insufficient time is allowed for T2 decay to complete", "The image signal becomes uniformly bright", "Longitudinal magnetization is not allowed to recover between successive excitations", "Proton density effects dominate the image contrast"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Complete saturation occurs when longitudinal magnetization is not allowed to recover between successive excitations—typically when TR is very short relative to T1 and the flip angle is large. In this state, there is no longitudinal magnetization available to produce signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-965", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Increasing the echo time (TE) primarily:", "options": ["Increases T2 contrast between tissues", "Reduces T2 contrast between tissues", "Increases T1 contrast between tissues", "Has no effect on image contrast"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing TE allows more time for differential T2 decay between tissues with different T2 values, increasing T2 contrast. Tissues with short T2 lose signal faster than those with long T2, making the contrast between them more apparent.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-966", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Reducing the TR to a value at or below the T1 relaxation time of the tissue:", "options": ["Increases the signal-to-noise ratio and reduces saturation", "Has no effect on signal or saturation", "Increases both the SNR and saturation effects", "Decreases the signal-to-noise ratio and increases saturation effects"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Reducing TR to a value at or below the tissue T1 prevents full longitudinal recovery, decreasing the available signal (lower SNR) and increasing saturation effects. The incomplete recovery also accentuates T1 differences between tissues, creating T1-weighted contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-967", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Reducing the echo time (TE) primarily:", "options": ["Increases T1 contrast weighting", "Increases proton density contrast weighting", "Reduces saturation effects", "Reduces T2 contrast between tissues"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Reducing TE minimizes the time available for T2 decay between different tissues, reducing T2 contrast. At very short TE, all tissues retain similar amounts of transverse magnetization regardless of their T2 values, eliminating T2-based contrast differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-968", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "As the repetition time (TR) increases, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR):", "options": ["Increases up to a point (as more longitudinal recovery occurs)", "Decreases", "Is not affected by TR", "Causes the TE to increase"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "As TR increases, more longitudinal magnetization recovers before the next excitation, increasing the available signal and therefore SNR. However, beyond a certain TR, all tissues fully recover and the SNR gain plateaus while scan time continues to increase.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-969", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "As the echo time (TE) increases, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR):", "options": ["Increases", "Decreases (due to increased T2/T2* decay)", "Is not affected by TE", "Causes the TR to increase"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "As TE increases, more T2/T2* decay occurs before signal collection, resulting in lower overall signal amplitude and decreased SNR. The trade-off is that longer TE provides greater T2 contrast between tissues.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-970", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "In a gradient echo sequence, reducing the flip angle while holding the TR constant reduces:", "options": ["T2* contrast weighting", "Proton density contrast weighting", "Saturation of the tissue magnetization", "Total scan time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Reducing the flip angle in GRE decreases the amount of longitudinal magnetization tipped into the transverse plane, reducing saturation of tissue magnetization. This allows the magnetization to recover more fully between excitations, which is useful with short TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-971", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "In a 2D conventional spin echo multislice sequence, scan time is calculated by:", "options": ["TE x number of phase-encoding steps x TR", "TR x FOV x NSA", "TR x number of slices x NSA", "TR x NSA x number of phase-encoding steps"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "2D conventional SE multislice scan time = TR × NSA × number of phase-encoding steps. This formula applies because multiple slices are interleaved within each TR and the number of slices does not independently affect scan time (provided they fit within the TR).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-972", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "In an inversion recovery pulse sequence, image contrast is controlled by:", "options": ["TR and TE only", "TI only", "TI and TE only", "TR, TE, and TI"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In IR, image contrast is controlled by all three timing parameters: TI determines which tissue is nulled, TR controls overall T1 recovery (and must be long enough for complete recovery), and TE determines the degree of T2 weighting in the readout.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-973", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "In an inversion recovery pulse sequence, the time between the initial 180-degree inversion pulse and the subsequent 90-degree excitation pulse is known as the:", "options": ["Echo time (TE)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Inversion time (TI)", "T1 relaxation time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The inversion time (TI) is the interval between the 180-degree inversion pulse and the 90-degree excitation pulse. It determines the point at which longitudinal magnetization is sampled, controlling which tissue (if any) is at the null point.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-974", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "The inversion time (TI) is also referred to by the Greek letter:", "options": ["Alpha", "Theta", "Sigma", "Tau"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The inversion time (TI) is also referred to by the Greek letter tau (τ). The term 'short tau inversion recovery' (STIR) derives its name from this convention—STIR uses a short tau (TI) to null fat.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-975", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "A STIR sequence can suppress signal from any tissue whose T1 relaxation time matches the inversion null point, including:", "options": ["Fat only", "Water and cerebrospinal fluid", "Fat and gadolinium-enhanced tissue (both have T1 values near the STIR null point)", "Only tissues with very long T1 values"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "STIR suppresses any tissue whose T1 matches the null point at the selected TI. Both fat and gadolinium-enhanced tissue can have similar short T1 values at certain field strengths, so STIR can inadvertently suppress enhancing lesions—a key reason not to use STIR post-contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-976", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth (narrowing the BW) causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Become inverted", "Increase", "Remain unaffected"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Narrowing the receive bandwidth reduces the range of noise frequencies sampled, which increases SNR. Fewer noise frequencies are included in each pixel's measurement, improving the signal-to-noise ratio at the cost of increased chemical shift artifact and longer readout time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-977", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth (narrowing the BW) causes chemical shift artifact to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Decrease", "Remain unaffected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Narrowing the bandwidth increases chemical shift artifact because the reduced hertz-per-pixel mapping means the fixed frequency difference between fat and water (e.g., 220 Hz at 1.5T) displaces fat signal across more pixels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-978", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth (narrowing the BW) causes the readout (sampling) time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Decrease", "Remain unaffected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Narrowing the bandwidth increases the readout (sampling) time because the same number of frequency data points must be sampled over a narrower frequency range, requiring a longer sampling window to maintain the same frequency resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-979", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth (narrowing the BW) causes magnetic susceptibility artifact to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Become inverted", "Increase", "Remain unaffected"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Narrowing the bandwidth increases magnetic susceptibility artifact because the longer readout time and reduced hertz-per-pixel allow more time for susceptibility-induced dephasing to accumulate, creating greater signal distortion near tissue interfaces.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 269"}, {"id": "IP-980", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Decreasing the receiver bandwidth (narrowing the BW) causes the maximum number of available slices to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Become inverted", "Increase", "Remain unaffected"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Narrowing the bandwidth increases the minimum TE (due to the longer readout window), which reduces the maximum number of slices that can fit within each TR period. Fewer slices can be interleaved when each slice requires a longer readout.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-981", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "Increasing the receiver bandwidth (widening the BW) causes the available echo train length (ETL) to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Become inverted", "Increase", "Remain unaffected"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Increasing the bandwidth does not affect the available echo train length (ETL). ETL is determined by the number of refocusing pulses and echo spacing in FSE, which are independent of the receiver bandwidth setting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-982", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.15", "stem": "The time during which the frequency-encoding gradient is active (readout time) increases when the:", "options": ["Receiver bandwidth is narrowed", "Receiver bandwidth is widened", "Number of phase-encoding steps is increased", "Flip angle is increased"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The readout time increases when the receiver bandwidth is narrowed because the ADC must sample the same number of data points over a smaller frequency range, requiring a proportionally longer sampling window.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 142"}, {"id": "IP-983", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "In a conventional spin echo multi-echo sequence, the multiple images produced differ primarily in the amount of:", "options": ["T1 weighting", "Phase-encoding resolution", "T2 weighting", "Spatial resolution"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a dual-echo (multi-echo) SE sequence, the multiple images differ in T2 weighting because each echo is collected at a progressively longer TE. The first echo has less T2 decay (PD/T1 weighted) while the second has more T2 decay (T2 weighted).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65"}, {"id": "IP-984", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "In a 3D acquisition, the SNR increases with an increase in:", "options": ["Field of view only", "Number of slice-encoding partitions only", "Echo time", "Both field of view and number of slice-encoding partitions"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In 3D acquisitions, SNR increases with both FOV (larger FOV = larger voxels = more signal per voxel) and number of slice-encoding partitions (more partitions = more signal averaging in the through-slab direction). Both factors independently contribute to the SNR equation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-985", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "In 2D multislice acquisitions, gaps are generally required between adjacent slices to prevent:", "options": ["Aliasing artifacts", "Gradient reversal errors", "Cross-excitation (cross-talk) between slices", "Inversion pulse interference"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gaps between slices in 2D multislice acquisitions prevent cross-excitation (cross-talk), where the imperfect RF pulse profile of one slice partially excites tissue in an adjacent slice. This reduces contrast and signal in the affected slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-986", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "Doubling the number of signal averages (NSA) will:", "options": ["Decrease the SNR", "Increase the SNR by a factor of approximately 1.41 (the square root of 2)", "Double the SNR", "Not affect the SNR"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Doubling NSA increases SNR by √2 (approximately 1.41), not by a factor of 2. This square-root relationship exists because noise is random and only partially cancels with averaging, while coherent signal adds linearly. Scan time doubles proportionally.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-987", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Increasing the number of phase-encoding steps will produce an image with:", "options": ["Increased voxel volume", "Decreased voxel volume (improved spatial resolution)", "An unchanged voxel volume", "Higher signal-to-noise ratio"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing phase-encoding steps with a fixed FOV reduces pixel size in the phase direction, decreasing voxel volume and improving spatial resolution. The trade-off is longer scan time (more TR periods needed) and reduced SNR (smaller voxels).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-988", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "Reducing the number of signal averages (NSA) will reduce the scan time and:", "options": ["Decrease the SNR", "Increase the SNR by a factor of 1.41", "Not affect the SNR", "Double the SNR"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Reducing NSA decreases scan time proportionally but also decreases SNR because fewer signal averages are available to suppress random noise. The SNR reduction follows the square-root relationship (halving NSA reduces SNR by ~29%).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-989", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "Doubling the NSA will increase the SNR by a factor of:", "options": ["2", "4", "1.6", "1.41 (the square root of 2)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Doubling NSA increases SNR by a factor of √2, which equals approximately 1.41. To double the SNR, NSA would need to be quadrupled (√4 = 2). This square-root relationship is fundamental to understanding the SNR-time trade-off.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-990", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "Reducing the field of view (FOV) by a factor of 2 will reduce the voxel volume by a factor of:", "options": ["Square root of 2", "2", "8", "4"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Reducing FOV by half reduces pixel dimensions by half in both the frequency and phase directions. Voxel volume = pixel area × slice thickness, so halving both pixel dimensions reduces pixel area by 4, and thus voxel volume by a factor of 4.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-991", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "A STIR sequence using TR 3000 ms, TE 20 ms, and TI 140 ms produces an image with dark fat and bright water. The contrast in this image is primarily based on:", "options": ["Flow effects", "T1 differences", "T2 differences", "Dephasing effects"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "STIR with TR 3000/TE 20/TI 140 nulls fat at the TI null point. The short TE minimizes T2 effects, so the dominant contrast mechanism is T1 differences between remaining tissues. Water appears bright because its long T1 places its recovery curve well above the null point at TI 140.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "IP-992", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.12", "stem": "When selecting the phase-encoding direction, the technologist typically chooses the axis along which:", "options": ["The most signal is needed", "Scan time will not be affected", "Motion artifacts will traverse the least critical anatomy", "Resolution will not be distorted"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The phase-encoding direction is chosen so that motion artifacts (which propagate along the phase axis) traverse the least critical anatomy. For example, in chest imaging, phase is set L/R so respiratory motion ghosts don't obscure the mediastinum.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-993", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.5", "stem": "A chemical (spectral) fat suppression pulse suppresses fat signal based on the:", "options": ["Precessional frequency difference between fat and water", "Total amount of fat in the imaging slice", "T2 relaxation time of fat", "T1 relaxation time of fat"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Chemical (spectral) fat suppression uses a frequency-selective RF pulse tuned to the precessional frequency of fat protons (which differ from water by 3.5 ppm). This pulse saturates fat magnetization based on frequency alone, independent of T1 or T2 values.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-994", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "Increasing the slice thickness from 5 mm to 10 mm (doubling it) causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Increase by a factor of 2", "Increase by a factor of 4", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease by a factor of 2"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Doubling slice thickness from 5 mm to 10 mm doubles the voxel volume, which doubles the number of hydrogen protons contributing signal per voxel. SNR increases linearly with slice thickness (factor of 2), at the cost of increased partial volume averaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-995", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Increasing the number of phase-encoding steps (matrix) from 128 to 256 causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Increasing phase-encoding steps from 128 to 256 reduces pixel size in the phase direction by half, decreasing voxel volume. Smaller voxels contain fewer protons, reducing SNR. Scan time also doubles because twice as many TR periods are needed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-996", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.4", "stem": "Gradient moment nulling is most effective when compensating for signal loss caused by:", "options": ["Pulsatile flow", "Stationary tissue", "Slow constant-velocity flow", "Magnetic field inhomogeneities"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gradient moment nulling (flow compensation) is most effective for slow, constant-velocity flow because first-order nulling zeroes the first gradient moment, correcting for linear velocity-related phase shifts. Pulsatile and accelerating flow require higher-order corrections.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-997", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.4", "stem": "Gradient moment nulling techniques rephase the signal from moving spins by using additional:", "options": ["RF pulses", "Gradient lobes", "Series of short rapid RF pulses", "Flow-encoding bipolar gradients"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient moment nulling rephases moving spins by adding extra gradient lobes to the pulse sequence. These additional lobes are designed so that the net phase accumulation from constant-velocity motion equals zero, eliminating flow-related signal loss.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 280"}, {"id": "IP-998", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.10", "stem": "In a conventional 2D spin echo multislice sequence, the maximum number of slices increases when the:", "options": ["TE is increased", "NSA is increased", "TR is increased", "Matrix size is doubled"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The maximum number of slices in a 2D SE multislice sequence increases when TR is increased because each TR period provides more time for interleaved slice excitations. More slices can be sequentially excited and read out within a longer TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-999", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.10", "stem": "In a conventional 2D spin echo multislice sequence, increasing the TE from 20 ms to 40 ms causes the maximum number of available slices to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Remain unaffected", "Increase proportionally to TR x TE", "Double"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing TE from 20 to 40 ms means each slice requires a longer time window for echo formation and readout. This leaves less time within each TR for exciting additional slices, decreasing the maximum number of available slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1000", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "In a 3D acquisition, increasing the TR causes the number of available slice partitions to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Remain unaffected", "Increase proportionally", "Double"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In 3D acquisitions, the number of slice-encoding partitions is independent of TR because the slice-encoding steps are performed as an additional phase-encoding direction applied within each TR period. Changing TR affects scan time but not the number of available partitions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1001", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "In a 3D acquisition, increasing the number of slice-encoding partitions from 64 to 128 causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Remain unaffected", "Increase by a factor of 1.41", "Double"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In 3D acquisitions, scan time = TR × phase-encoding steps × NSA × slice-encoding partitions. Doubling the partitions from 64 to 128 directly doubles the scan time because twice as many encoding steps must be completed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1002", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Increasing the frequency matrix from 256 to 512 causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Decrease", "Remain unaffected", "Increase proportionally", "Double"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The frequency matrix does not affect scan time in standard 2D acquisitions because frequency encoding is completed during each echo readout and does not require additional TR periods. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1003", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.14", "stem": "The effective TE in a fast spin echo pulse sequence determines the:", "options": ["Image contrast", "Scan time", "Spatial resolution", "Number of frequency samples"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The effective TE in FSE determines image contrast because it corresponds to the echo time at which the central (contrast-determining) lines of k-space are collected. Adjusting the effective TE changes the contrast weighting from PD to T2.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-1004", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.14", "stem": "In a fast spin echo sequence, the central lines of k-space are associated with the:", "options": ["Spatial resolution of the image", "Repetition time", "Effective TE (image contrast)", "Total scan time"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The central lines of k-space contain the low spatial frequency data that determines overall image contrast. In FSE, the effective TE is defined by when these central lines are collected in the echo train, directly controlling the contrast weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68; Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-1005", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.6", "stem": "When triggering an MRI scan from the patient's ECG signal, the effective TR of the sequence is determined by the:", "options": ["Number of phase-encoding steps selected", "Number of cardiac phases being imaged", "Number of frequency-encoding steps selected", "Patient's heart rate"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "When cardiac gating (triggering) is used, the effective TR is determined by the patient's heart rate because each R-R interval serves as the repetition period. Faster heart rates produce shorter effective TR, and slower rates produce longer effective TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-1006", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Increasing the repetition time (TR) causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing TR directly increases scan time because scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA. Each TR period takes longer, and the total number of TR periods remains the same, resulting in a proportionally longer acquisition.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1007", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Increasing the echo time (TE) causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing TE does not affect scan time because TE is measured within each TR period and does not change the number of TR repetitions required. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA, and TE is not in this formula.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1008", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.10", "stem": "Increasing the number of slices in a 2D multislice acquisition causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected (slices acquired within existing TR)", "Decrease"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In 2D multislice imaging, all slices are acquired within each TR period through interleaved excitation. Adding or removing slices (within the TR capacity) does not change the total scan time because the number of TR periods remains the same.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1009", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "For a given tissue T1 and TR, the flip angle that produces maximum signal from that tissue is known as the:", "options": ["90-degree angle", "180-degree angle", "45-degree angle", "Ernst angle"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The Ernst angle is the flip angle that produces maximum signal for a given tissue T1 and TR combination. It is calculated as cos(α) = e^(-TR/T1). Using the Ernst angle optimizes SNR but may not produce the desired contrast weighting.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-1010", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.6", "stem": "Increasing the field of view (FOV) causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing FOV does not affect scan time because FOV changes pixel size but not the number of phase-encoding steps, TR periods, or NSA. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA, and FOV is not in this formula.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1011", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Increasing the phase-encoding matrix causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the phase-encoding matrix increases scan time because more phase-encoding steps require more TR periods. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA, so doubling the phase matrix doubles scan time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1012", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "Increasing the slice thickness causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing slice thickness does not affect scan time because slice thickness is determined by gradient amplitude and RF bandwidth during each excitation, not by the number of TR periods. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1013", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "Increasing the number of signal averages (NSA) causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing NSA directly increases scan time proportionally because each additional signal average requires repeating the entire phase-encoding sequence. Doubling NSA doubles scan time. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1014", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.11", "stem": "Increasing the slice thickness causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing slice thickness increases voxel volume, which increases the number of hydrogen protons contributing signal per voxel. More protons produce stronger signal, directly increasing SNR linearly with slice thickness.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-1015", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Increasing the acquisition matrix causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Increasing the acquisition matrix reduces pixel and voxel size, decreasing the number of protons per voxel and thus reducing the signal amplitude. This decrease in signal directly reduces SNR despite improved spatial resolution.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-1016", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.5", "stem": "Increasing the flip angle causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Increase up to the Ernst angle, then decrease", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Always decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "SNR increases with flip angle up to the Ernst angle, where signal is maximized for the given TR and T1. Beyond the Ernst angle, excessive saturation of longitudinal magnetization reduces the available signal, decreasing SNR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 90"}, {"id": "IP-1017", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.13", "stem": "Reducing the echo train length (ETL) causes the scan time to:", "options": ["Increase", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Reducing ETL increases scan time because fewer k-space lines are filled per TR period, requiring more TR repetitions to complete the full phase-encoding matrix. Scan time = TR × phase matrix × NSA / ETL.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 68"}, {"id": "IP-1018", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Reducing the echo time (TE) causes the SNR to:", "options": ["Increase (less T2/T2* decay before signal collection)", "Become inverted", "Remain unaffected", "Decrease"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Reducing TE increases SNR because less T2/T2* decay occurs before signal collection, preserving more of the initial transverse magnetization amplitude. The echo is collected while signal is still strong.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 210"}, {"id": "IP-1019", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Reducing the echo time (TE) yields images with:", "options": ["More T1 contrast information", "Less T1 contrast information", "More T2 contrast information", "Less T2 contrast information"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Reducing TE minimizes the time available for differential T2 decay between tissues, yielding images with less T2 contrast information. At very short TE, T2 differences between tissues are not yet expressed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-1020", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Increasing the repetition time (TR) yields images with:", "options": ["More T1 contrast information", "Less T1 contrast information", "More T2 contrast information", "Less T2 contrast information"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing TR allows more complete longitudinal recovery for all tissues, which minimizes T1 contrast differences between them. Long TR yields less T1 contrast information because all tissues converge toward full recovery.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-1021", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Increasing the echo time (TE) yields images with:", "options": ["More T1 contrast information", "Less T1 contrast information", "More T2 contrast information", "Less T2 contrast information"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing TE allows more time for differential T2 decay, yielding images with more T2 contrast information. Tissues with different T2 values show progressively greater signal differences at longer echo times.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-1022", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Reducing the repetition time (TR) yields images with:", "options": ["More T1 contrast information", "Less T1 contrast information", "More T2 contrast information", "Less T2 contrast information"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Reducing TR limits longitudinal recovery time, accentuating T1 differences between tissues. Short TR yields more T1 contrast information because tissues with different T1 values recover to significantly different degrees.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "IP-1023", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Reducing the flip angle in a gradient echo sequence yields images with:", "options": ["More T1 contrast information", "Less T1 contrast information (more PD or T2* weighting)", "More T2 contrast information", "Less T2 contrast information"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Reducing the flip angle in GRE reduces longitudinal magnetization saturation, which diminishes T1 contrast and shifts the weighting toward proton density or T2*. Less T1 contrast information is obtained because tissues are less differentially saturated.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-1024", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Increasing the flip angle in a gradient echo sequence yields images with:", "options": ["More T1 contrast information", "Less T1 contrast information", "More T2 contrast information", "Less T2 contrast information"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Increasing the flip angle in GRE increases longitudinal magnetization saturation, accentuating T1 differences between tissues with different T1 recovery rates. This produces more T1 contrast information, similar to using a shorter TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "IP-1025", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "A coil designed to be placed inside a patient's body (e.g., endorectal or endovaginal) is classified as a:", "options": ["local (endocavitary) coil", "body coil", "volume coil", "phased-array coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "An endocavitary coil (such as an endorectal or endovaginal coil) is classified as a local coil because it is placed directly within or adjacent to the anatomy of interest to maximize signal-to-noise ratio from that specific region. Its proximity to the target tissue provides dramatically improved SNR compared to external surface coils. The body coil (option b) is a large, built-in coil used for transmitting RF and whole-body imaging, not for intracavitary applications.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-1026", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.A.3.a", "stem": "Which of the following statements about quadrature coils is true?", "options": ["They use four separate pairs of coils to transmit and receive signals", "A quadrature design compromises signal-to-noise ratio", "Most volume coils utilize a quadrature configuration", "Quadrature coils are used exclusively for large field-of-view imaging"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Most volume coils (such as the body coil and head coils) utilize a quadrature configuration, which uses two coil elements oriented 90 degrees apart to detect signal from perpendicular planes simultaneously. This design provides up to a 41% improvement in SNR compared to a linear coil. Option b is incorrect because quadrature design improves (not compromises) the signal-to-noise ratio.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-1027", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.1.a", "stem": "In a conventional spin echo pulse sequence, how many lines of k-space are filled during each repetition time (TR)?", "options": ["1", "2", "10", "12"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In a conventional spin echo pulse sequence, only one line of k-space is filled during each repetition time (TR). This is because each TR interval produces one echo from one phase-encoding step. This one-line-per-TR limitation is the primary reason conventional spin echo sequences have relatively long scan times. Fast spin echo sequences overcome this by filling multiple k-space lines per TR using an echo train.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 65 | MIP Ch. 6, p. 165"}, {"id": "IP-1028", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "The two primary clinical applications of inversion recovery sequences are:", "options": ["STIR and FLAIR", "STIR and EPI", "FLAIR and EPI", "STIR, FLAIR, and EPI"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The two primary clinical applications of inversion recovery sequences are STIR (Short Tau Inversion Recovery), which suppresses fat signal for musculoskeletal and body imaging, and FLAIR (Fluid Attenuated Inversion Recovery), which suppresses CSF signal for brain imaging. EPI (echo planar imaging) is a data acquisition strategy, not an inversion recovery sequence, making options b through d incorrect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "IP-1029", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "When the primary region of interest is pathology such as edema or tumor, which type of image weighting is generally preferred?", "options": ["T1 weighting to maximize anatomical detail", "T2 weighting to maximize contrast between pathology and normal tissue", "Proton density weighting to eliminate all contrast", "Diffusion weighting to assess tissue cellularity"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "T2-weighted images are generally preferred for evaluating pathology such as edema and tumors because these conditions increase tissue water content, which prolongs T2 relaxation and produces bright signal on T2-weighted images. This creates excellent contrast between abnormal and normal tissue. T1 weighting (option a) provides superior anatomic detail but generally less sensitivity for detecting pathologic water accumulation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-1030", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.2", "stem": "FLAIR (Fluid Attenuated Inversion Recovery) sequences are designed to nullify the signal from:", "options": ["fat", "water", "muscle", "cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "FLAIR (Fluid Attenuated Inversion Recovery) sequences use an inversion time specifically chosen to nullify the signal from cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), which has the longest T1 in the brain. By suppressing CSF signal, FLAIR improves detection of periventricular and cortical lesions that would otherwise be obscured by bright CSF on standard T2-weighted images. Water suppression (option b) refers to a different technique used in MR spectroscopy, not FLAIR imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 84"}, {"id": "IP-1031", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "Which statement about steady-state free precession (SSFP) sequences is correct?", "options": ["With a sufficiently short TR, residual transverse magnetization is maintained before it can fully decay", "The TR must be longer than both the T1 and T2 relaxation times", "A specific flip angle and TE combination is required to sustain the steady state", "The steady state causes fluid with long T2 values to appear dark"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In steady-state free precession (SSFP) sequences, the TR is kept sufficiently short (shorter than the T2 of tissues) so that residual transverse magnetization is maintained before it can fully decay. This creates a steady state where both longitudinal and transverse magnetization reach equilibrium, producing images with T2/T1-weighted contrast. Option b is incorrect because the TR must be shorter than T2 to maintain the steady state, not longer than both T1 and T2.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 119"}, {"id": "IP-1032", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "In which technique is residual transverse magnetization intentionally destroyed before the next RF excitation pulse?", "options": ["Incoherent gradient echo sequencing", "Coherent gradient echo sequencing", "RF spoiling", "Fast spin echo imaging"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "RF spoiling is a technique that intentionally destroys residual transverse magnetization before the next RF excitation pulse by varying the phase of successive RF pulses. This prevents the buildup of steady-state transverse magnetization and produces predominantly T1-weighted contrast in gradient echo sequences. Incoherent gradient echo (option a) uses gradient spoiling rather than RF spoiling — although related, RF spoiling is more effective at eliminating residual transverse magnetization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 109"}, {"id": "IP-1033", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3", "stem": "Which pulse sequence technique is capable of acquiring an entire MR image in a fraction of a second?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Fast spin echo", "Echo planar imaging (EPI)", "Steady-state free precession"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Echo planar imaging (EPI) can acquire an entire MR image in a fraction of a second by filling all lines of k-space after a single RF excitation using rapidly oscillating frequency-encoding gradients. This ultrafast acquisition makes EPI essential for diffusion-weighted imaging, perfusion imaging, and functional MRI. Conventional spin echo (option a) requires a separate TR for each k-space line, making it orders of magnitude slower.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-1034", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.A.3.f", "stem": "Advantages of time-of-flight (TOF) MR angiography include the ability to image without intravenous contrast, sensitivity to flowing blood, and the option to acquire data in:", "options": ["only 2D", "only 3D", "2D but not 3D", "either 2D or 3D"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Time-of-flight (TOF) MR angiography can be acquired in either 2D or 3D modes. 2D TOF uses sequential thin slices and is more sensitive to slow flow (e.g., venous imaging), while 3D TOF acquires a volume slab and provides higher spatial resolution for arterial imaging. Both modes image flowing blood without intravenous contrast by exploiting inflow enhancement. Option a is incorrect because 3D TOF is widely used for intracranial arterial imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "IP-1035", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which timing parameter controls the amount of longitudinal relaxation that occurs before protons are excited by the next RF pulse?", "options": ["Echo time (TE)", "Inversion time (TI)", "Repetition time (TR)", "Inversion recovery (IR)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The repetition time (TR) controls the amount of longitudinal (T1) relaxation that occurs between successive RF excitation pulses. A longer TR allows more complete T1 recovery, while a shorter TR limits recovery and creates T1-weighted contrast. Echo time (option a) controls the amount of T2 decay that occurs before signal readout, not longitudinal relaxation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 24"}, {"id": "IP-1036", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.7", "stem": "If the phase encoding direction is not set appropriately for the anatomy being imaged, the resulting images may demonstrate:", "options": ["wraparound and chemical shift artifacts", "wraparound and motion artifacts", "motion and susceptibility artifacts", "chemical shift and susceptibility artifacts"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "If the phase encoding direction is not optimally assigned for the anatomy being imaged, wraparound artifact (aliasing) can occur if the anatomy extends beyond the FOV in that direction, and motion artifacts from physiologic motion (breathing, cardiac pulsation, peristalsis) will propagate across the anatomy of interest. Susceptibility artifacts (options c, d) are not affected by the phase encoding direction assignment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-1037", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.7", "stem": "Changes to the acquisition matrix directly affect both spatial resolution and:", "options": ["the phase encoding direction", "scan time", "the echo time (TE)", "the number of signal averages (NSA)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Changes to the acquisition matrix directly affect spatial resolution (more pixels = finer resolution) and scan time (more phase-encoding steps = longer acquisition). Increasing the phase matrix increases the number of k-space lines that must be filled, proportionally lengthening scan time. The phase encoding direction (option a) is a separate parameter assignment, not directly determined by matrix size.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-1038", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "On T1-weighted images, tissues that have taken up gadolinium-based contrast appear:", "options": ["radiolucent", "hyperintense (bright)", "heterogeneous", "completely signal-void"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents shorten the T1 relaxation time of tissues that take up the contrast, causing them to appear hyperintense (bright) on T1-weighted images. This T1 shortening effect is the basis for contrast-enhanced MRI and allows identification of vascular structures, tumors, and areas of blood-brain barrier breakdown. 'Radiolucent' (option a) is a radiographic term not applicable to MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-1039", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.3", "stem": "A technologist can reduce motion-related mismapping artifacts by reminding the patient to remain still, adjusting the phase encoding direction, and applying:", "options": ["wider receive bandwidth", "increased number of signal averages only", "thinner slices only", "spatial presaturation pulses"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Spatial presaturation pulses (sat bands) can be placed over areas of motion (such as the anterior abdominal wall or vessels) to suppress signal from those regions before it contributes to ghosting artifacts. Combined with patient cooperation and appropriate phase encoding direction, presaturation pulses are an effective strategy for reducing motion-related phase mismapping. Wider receive bandwidth (option a) affects chemical shift artifact, not motion artifacts.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "IP-1040", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.7", "stem": "When fat and water protons are out of phase with each other, their signals:", "options": ["cross over", "become enhanced", "double in intensity", "cancel each other"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "When fat and water protons are out of phase (180 degrees apart in their precessional cycles), their signals cancel each other, resulting in signal loss at fat-water interfaces. This produces the characteristic dark outline (India ink artifact) seen on out-of-phase gradient echo images around organs bordered by fat. Signal enhancement or doubling (options b, c) would occur when fat and water signals are in phase and add constructively.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 265"}, {"id": "IP-1041", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact is primarily caused by:", "options": ["patient motion", "undersampling of high spatial frequencies", "metallic objects in the field of view", "out-of-phase fat and water"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gibbs (truncation) artifact results from undersampling of high spatial frequencies in k-space, which occurs when insufficient phase-encoding steps are used to accurately represent sharp transitions in signal intensity (such as the skull-brain interface). The artifact appears as alternating bright and dark lines parallel to high-contrast boundaries. Patient motion (option a) causes ghosting artifacts, not the ringing pattern characteristic of Gibbs artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 272"}, {"id": "IP-1042", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.6", "stem": "A zipper artifact appearing as a discrete line across the image is most commonly caused by:", "options": ["radiofrequency (RF) leakage into the scan room", "patient motion during the acquisition", "an excessively high flip angle", "incorrect placement of the surface coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A zipper artifact appears as a discrete bright or dark line across the image and is most commonly caused by radiofrequency (RF) leakage into the scan room from external sources. This occurs when the Faraday cage (RF shielding) is compromised, such as when the scan room door is left open or the RF seal is damaged. Patient motion (option b) causes ghosting, not a discrete zipper line.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 275"}, {"id": "IP-1043", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.11", "stem": "A technologist can help prevent Moire artifact by using spin echo sequences and ensuring the patient does not:", "options": ["move during the scan", "breathe during the acquisition", "create a conductive loop with their body", "wear a hospital gown"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Moire artifact can be caused when the patient's body creates a conductive loop (such as crossed arms or legs, or skin-to-skin contact), which can interact with the gradient and RF fields to produce interference patterns. Using spin echo sequences (which are less susceptible to field inhomogeneity effects) and ensuring no conductive loops helps prevent this artifact. Patient motion (option a) causes ghosting, not Moire patterns.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 277"}, {"id": "IP-1044", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "On T2-weighted images, normal skeletal muscle appears:", "options": ["hyperintense (white)", "intermediate to bright", "gray", "hypointense (dark)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Normal skeletal muscle appears hypointense (dark) on T2-weighted images because muscle tissue has a relatively short T2 relaxation time due to its organized fiber structure and low free water content. When muscle appears bright on T2, it suggests pathology such as edema, inflammation, or denervation. Hyperintense muscle (option a) would indicate abnormality rather than normal tissue.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "IP-1045", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.3", "stem": "On proton density-weighted images, fat appears:", "options": ["hyperintense (bright)", "gray", "intermediate", "hypointense (dark)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "On proton density-weighted images (long TR, short TE), fat appears hyperintense (bright) because fat has a high proton density and the long TR allows nearly complete T1 recovery. The short TE minimizes T2 contrast, so tissues with high hydrogen concentration (like fat) appear bright. Hypointense fat (option d) would be characteristic of fat-suppressed sequences, not standard PD-weighted images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 41"}, {"id": "IP-1046", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.5", "stem": "On a standard diffusion-weighted image acquired with a high b-value (e.g., b=1000), acute cytotoxic edema appears:", "options": ["Hypointense due to increased water mobility", "Hyperintense due to restricted diffusion", "Isointense regardless of diffusion status", "Hypointense due to T1 shortening"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Acute cytotoxic edema (such as in acute stroke) restricts the random motion of water molecules within cells, causing signal to remain hyperintense on high b-value DWI. Restricted diffusion retains phase coherence among water protons, preserving signal. Option a is incorrect because increased water mobility (as in vasogenic edema) would cause signal loss on high b-value images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-1047", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.5", "stem": "Increasing the b-value on a diffusion-weighted sequence primarily increases:", "options": ["T1-weighted contrast contribution", "Sensitivity to slow-moving water molecules", "Signal-to-noise ratio throughout the image", "Spatial resolution in the phase-encoding direction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the b-value strengthens the diffusion-sensitizing gradients, making the sequence more sensitive to slow-moving (restricted) water molecules while further attenuating signal from freely mobile water. Higher b-values improve diffusion contrast but reduce overall SNR because more signal is lost from all tissues. Option c is incorrect because SNR decreases as b-value increases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-1048", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.5", "stem": "A lesion that appears bright on DWI and dark on the corresponding ADC map most likely represents:", "options": ["T2 shine-through artifact", "True restricted diffusion", "Freely mobile water (e.g., CSF)", "Susceptibility artifact from hemorrhage"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "True restricted diffusion appears bright on DWI (high b-value) AND dark on the ADC map, confirming that water motion is genuinely reduced. T2 shine-through (option a) appears bright on DWI but remains bright (not dark) on the ADC map because the signal is caused by long T2 rather than restricted diffusion. The ADC map eliminates T2 contamination, making it essential for confirming true restriction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "IP-1049", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.6", "stem": "Susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI) is most sensitive to which of the following?", "options": ["Differences in T1 relaxation times between tissues", "Variations in magnetic susceptibility between tissues", "Differences in proton density between tissues", "Variations in T2 relaxation times only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SWI exploits small differences in magnetic susceptibility between tissues by combining magnitude and phase information from a high-resolution, long-TE gradient echo acquisition. This makes SWI exquisitely sensitive to paramagnetic substances such as deoxyhemoglobin, hemosiderin, and iron deposits. Option a is incorrect because T1 contrast is minimized in SWI by using a long TR or low flip angle.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-1050", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.6", "stem": "On SWI images, small cortical veins typically appear:", "options": ["Bright due to their high proton density", "Dark due to the paramagnetic effect of deoxyhemoglobin", "Isointense with surrounding brain parenchyma", "Bright due to time-of-flight inflow enhancement"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cortical veins contain deoxyhemoglobin, which is paramagnetic and causes local magnetic field inhomogeneity. This produces phase differences that SWI processing converts into signal loss, making veins appear dark. Option d is incorrect because TOF inflow enhancement brightens vessels in MRA techniques, not in SWI where the goal is to visualize susceptibility differences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-1051", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.B.6", "stem": "Which clinical application is SWI particularly useful for compared to conventional sequences?", "options": ["Evaluation of ligament tears in the knee", "Detection of small hemorrhagic foci (microbleeds) in the brain", "Assessment of lumbar disc herniations", "Visualization of the biliary tree"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SWI is particularly useful for detecting small hemorrhagic foci (cerebral microbleeds) that may be invisible on conventional T1 or T2-weighted sequences. The technique's sensitivity to hemosiderin and other blood breakdown products makes it superior for identifying microbleeds associated with conditions such as cerebral amyloid angiopathy and hypertensive vasculopathy. Option a is incorrect because ligament evaluation relies on standard T2/PD-weighted sequences, not SWI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "IP-1052", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.2", "stem": "In interleaved slice acquisition, odd-numbered slices are typically excited first, followed by even-numbered slices. The primary purpose of this approach is to:", "options": ["Increase the spatial resolution of each slice", "Reduce cross-talk between adjacent slices", "Decrease the total scan time", "Improve the signal-to-noise ratio per slice"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Interleaved slice acquisition reduces cross-talk (cross-excitation) by ensuring that adjacent slices are not excited consecutively. Because RF pulses have imperfect slice profiles, exciting neighboring slices back-to-back can partially saturate adjacent tissue, reducing signal. By exciting alternating slices first, each slice has time to recover before its neighbor is excited. Option c is incorrect because interleaving does not change the total number of excitations or TR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-1053", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.2", "stem": "A technologist notices signal loss in slices at the edges of a multislice acquisition obtained with sequential slice ordering and no interslice gap. The most likely cause is:", "options": ["Chemical shift artifact", "Aliasing from an undersized field of view", "Cross-excitation from imperfect RF pulse profiles", "Gibbs artifact from insufficient matrix size"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Sequential slice ordering without an interslice gap makes the acquisition vulnerable to cross-excitation, where the imperfect profile of each RF pulse partially excites tissue in the adjacent slice. This repeated partial excitation saturates the magnetization in neighboring slices, causing signal loss. Option a is incorrect because chemical shift artifact displaces fat signal along the frequency-encoding direction, not between slices.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-1054", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.2", "stem": "Which of the following is a disadvantage of interleaved multislice acquisition in diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI)?", "options": ["It increases susceptibility artifact severity", "It may cause slice-to-slice signal intensity variations if the patient moves between odd and even slice groups", "It eliminates the ability to use parallel imaging", "It requires a longer echo time for each slice"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In interleaved DWI, odd and even slice groups are acquired at different times within the TR. If the patient moves between these two acquisition windows, the odd and even slices may have slightly different positions or signal characteristics, producing a characteristic alternating-slice intensity pattern. Option a is incorrect because susceptibility artifact severity depends on TE and field strength, not slice ordering.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5, p. 135"}, {"id": "IP-1055", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.3", "stem": "According to the Nyquist theorem, the sampling rate must be at least:", "options": ["Equal to the highest frequency present in the signal", "Twice the highest frequency present in the signal", "Three times the highest frequency present in the signal", "Four times the lowest frequency present in the signal"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Nyquist theorem states that to accurately digitize an analog signal without aliasing, the sampling rate must be at least twice the highest frequency component in the signal. This minimum rate is called the Nyquist rate. If the sampling rate falls below this threshold, frequencies above the Nyquist frequency are misrepresented as lower frequencies, producing aliasing artifacts. Option a is incorrect because sampling at exactly the signal frequency would miss half of the frequency information.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-1056", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Data Acquisition, Processing, & Storage", "spec": "3.B.3", "stem": "If the Nyquist criterion is violated during MRI data acquisition, the resulting artifact is:", "options": ["Chemical shift misregistration", "Gibbs ringing", "Aliasing (wraparound)", "Zipper artifact"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Violating the Nyquist criterion means the signal is undersampled, and frequencies above the Nyquist frequency fold back into the acquired bandwidth. In MRI, this manifests as aliasing (wraparound), where anatomy outside the field of view is superimposed onto the opposite side of the image. Gibbs ringing (option b) is caused by truncation of k-space data, not by sampling rate violations.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 6, p. 184"}, {"id": "IP-1057", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.4", "stem": "Chemical misregistration artifact occurs because fat and water protons:", "options": ["Have different T1 relaxation times", "Precess at slightly different frequencies due to their different chemical environments", "Have different proton densities", "Respond differently to 180-degree refocusing pulses"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Chemical misregistration results from the frequency difference between fat and water protons (~3.5 ppm), which causes fat signal to be spatially displaced relative to water along the frequency-encoding direction. The gradient system assigns spatial position based on frequency, so the inherent frequency offset of fat protons causes them to be mapped to an incorrect location. Option a describes a tissue property that affects image contrast but does not directly cause spatial misregistration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-1058", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.4", "stem": "Which parameter change would REDUCE the spatial displacement caused by chemical misregistration?", "options": ["Decreasing the receiver bandwidth", "Increasing the receiver bandwidth", "Increasing the echo time", "Decreasing the matrix size"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Increasing the receiver bandwidth increases the range of frequencies assigned per pixel, which reduces the number of pixels over which the fat-water frequency difference is displaced. A wider bandwidth means the ~220 Hz fat-water offset (at 1.5T) spans fewer pixels, minimizing spatial misregistration. Decreasing bandwidth (option a) would worsen the artifact by assigning fewer Hz per pixel, spreading the displacement over more pixels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 261"}, {"id": "IP-1059", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.8", "stem": "The primary advantage of using a rectangular field of view is:", "options": ["Increased signal-to-noise ratio", "Reduced scan time while maintaining spatial resolution", "Elimination of chemical shift artifact", "Improved fat suppression uniformity"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rectangular FOV reduces the number of phase-encoding steps in proportion to the FOV reduction in the phase direction, directly reducing scan time while maintaining the same pixel size (spatial resolution) as the full FOV. This is useful for imaging elongated anatomy such as the spine. Option a is incorrect because reducing the phase FOV actually decreases SNR proportional to the reduction in phase-encoding steps.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1060", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.8", "stem": "Rectangular FOV is most appropriate for imaging anatomy that is:", "options": ["Circular in cross-section, such as the brain", "Elongated in one dimension, such as the spine", "Very deep in the anterior-posterior direction", "Surrounded by significant amounts of moving tissue"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rectangular FOV is most effective for imaging anatomy that is significantly longer in one dimension than the other (such as the spine or extremities), because the FOV can be reduced in the shorter dimension without introducing aliasing. For circular anatomy like the brain (option a), rectangular FOV offers less benefit and risks aliasing if the anatomy extends beyond the reduced dimension.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 237"}, {"id": "IP-1061", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.a", "stem": "A vector quantity in MRI is defined as having both:", "options": ["Frequency and amplitude", "Magnitude and direction", "Phase and frequency", "Wavelength and period"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A vector is a mathematical quantity characterized by both magnitude (size or strength) and direction. In MRI, the net magnetization vector (NMV) is described by its magnitude (proportional to the number of excess spin-up protons) and its direction (along the longitudinal axis at equilibrium, tipping into the transverse plane after RF excitation). Option a describes aspects of a signal waveform, not a vector.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-1062", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.B.3.a", "stem": "Which of the following best describes the net magnetization vector (NMV) at thermal equilibrium?", "options": ["It points in a random direction that changes with each measurement", "It lies entirely in the transverse (XY) plane", "It is aligned parallel to the main magnetic field (B0)", "It oscillates between the longitudinal and transverse planes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "At thermal equilibrium, the slight excess of protons aligned parallel to B0 creates a net magnetization vector that points along the longitudinal (Z) axis, parallel to the main magnetic field. There is no transverse component because individual proton phases are random and cancel out. Option b would describe the NMV immediately after a 90-degree RF pulse, not at equilibrium.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 8"}, {"id": "IP-1063", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.6", "stem": "The transmit gain (TG) calibration performed before each MRI scan determines the:", "options": ["Optimal receiver bandwidth for the selected sequence", "RF power needed to achieve the prescribed flip angle", "Correct gradient amplitude for spatial encoding", "Number of signal averages required for adequate SNR"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Transmit gain calibration measures how much RF power must be delivered by the transmit coil to achieve the prescribed flip angle in the patient being scanned. This varies with patient size, body composition, and coil loading. Option a is incorrect because receiver bandwidth is a user-selected parameter, not determined by the prescan calibration.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-1064", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.6", "stem": "If the transmit gain calibration is inaccurate, the most likely consequence is:", "options": ["Incorrect image contrast due to inaccurate flip angles", "Increased geometric distortion", "Aliasing in the phase-encoding direction", "Loss of fat suppression in STIR sequences only"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "An inaccurate transmit gain produces flip angles that differ from the prescribed values, directly affecting image contrast. For example, if the actual flip angle is less than 90 degrees in a spin echo sequence, T1 contrast and overall signal intensity will be altered. Geometric distortion (option b) results from gradient nonlinearity, not transmit gain errors.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-1065", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.9", "stem": "Which of the following techniques is most effective at reducing cross-talk in a multislice acquisition?", "options": ["Increasing the echo time", "Applying an interslice gap of 10-30%", "Using a wider receiver bandwidth", "Decreasing the number of signal averages"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Applying an interslice gap (typically 10-30% of the slice thickness) physically separates adjacent slices, preventing the overlapping tails of imperfect RF slice profiles from exciting neighboring tissue. This is the most straightforward and widely used method for reducing cross-talk. Increasing the echo time (option a) affects T2 contrast and has no effect on cross-talk.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 273"}, {"id": "IP-1066", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.C.14", "stem": "The dielectric effect (standing wave artifact) is most commonly observed at:", "options": ["Low field strengths (0.2-0.5 T) in small patients", "High field strengths (3 T and above) in large body parts", "Any field strength when metallic implants are present", "Low field strengths when fat suppression is applied"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The dielectric effect occurs when the RF wavelength within tissue approaches the dimensions of the body part being imaged, creating constructive and destructive interference patterns (standing waves). At 3 T, the RF wavelength in tissue is approximately 26 cm, comparable to abdominal dimensions, producing characteristic central brightening or shading. This artifact is negligible at lower field strengths where the RF wavelength is much longer relative to body size. Option c describes susceptibility artifact, not dielectric effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 276"}, {"id": "IP-1067", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.7", "stem": "Geometric accuracy in MRI is primarily assessed during quality control by:", "options": ["Measuring the SNR in a uniform phantom", "Comparing measured phantom dimensions to known physical dimensions", "Evaluating the uniformity of fat suppression", "Counting the number of ghosting artifacts"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Geometric accuracy is assessed by scanning a phantom with precisely known dimensions and comparing the measured distances on the image to the actual physical dimensions. Deviations indicate gradient nonlinearity or miscalibration that could cause spatial distortion in clinical images. SNR measurement (option a) assesses signal quality, not geometric fidelity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 232"}, {"id": "IP-1068", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Physical Principles of Image Formation", "spec": "1.D.8", "stem": "During routine equipment inspection, a technologist should check RF coils for:", "options": ["Correct Larmor frequency tuning only", "Visible damage to cables, connectors, and coil housing", "Proper gradient calibration settings", "Correct transmit bandwidth programming"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Routine equipment inspection of RF coils includes checking for visible damage such as cracked housing, frayed or kinked cables, bent or corroded connectors, and loose elements. Damaged coils can produce image artifacts, uneven signal, or even pose safety risks from exposed conductors. Larmor frequency tuning (option a) is handled automatically by the prescan, not by visual inspection.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "IP-1069", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.A.9", "stem": "A voxel in MRI represents a three-dimensional volume element whose dimensions are determined by the:", "options": ["Pixel size in the frequency direction, pixel size in the phase direction, and slice thickness", "Field of view, receiver bandwidth, and echo time", "TR, TE, and flip angle", "Number of signal averages, matrix size, and coil type"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A voxel is the three-dimensional tissue volume represented by each pixel in the image. Its dimensions are determined by the pixel size in both the frequency-encoding and phase-encoding directions (which depend on FOV and matrix) multiplied by the slice thickness. Larger voxels contain more protons and produce higher SNR but lower spatial resolution. Option c lists contrast parameters that affect signal intensity but not voxel geometry.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7, p. 209"}, {"id": "IP-1070", "domain": "Image Production", "subcategory": "Sequence Parameters & Options", "spec": "2.C.7", "stem": "At 1.5 T, fat and water protons are in phase at approximately:", "options": ["2.3 ms and 6.9 ms", "4.6 ms and 9.2 ms", "1.1 ms and 3.3 ms", "6.9 ms and 11.5 ms"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "At 1.5 T, fat and water protons cycle between in-phase and out-of-phase states based on their ~220 Hz frequency difference. They are out of phase at ~2.3 ms and in phase at ~4.6 ms, then the cycle repeats (out-of-phase at ~6.9 ms, in-phase at ~9.2 ms). Selecting the appropriate TE allows deliberate imaging at either state. Option a lists the out-of-phase echo times, not the in-phase times.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 265"}, {"id": "PR-003", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.F", "stem": "Which of the following best describes the anatomic course of the ulnar nerve?", "options": ["It passes between the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the olecranon process", "It courses medial to the biceps brachii muscle", "It bifurcates at the cubital fossa", "It is the least commonly injured peripheral nerve"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The ulnar nerve passes posteriorly through the cubital tunnel between the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the olecranon process, making it vulnerable to compression at this location. This superficial course is why striking the area causes the familiar 'funny bone' sensation. The ulnar nerve does not bifurcate at the cubital fossa (option c) — that description better fits the brachial artery.", "reference": "SA Ch. 9"}, {"id": "PR-004", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.L", "stem": "A classic MRI appearance of avascular necrosis (AVN) of the femoral head includes:", "options": ["A rim of decreased signal intensity on both T1 and T2 images", "An inner band of increased signal seen only on T2 images", "Both a peripheral low-signal rim and a central high-signal band on T2 images", "Uniform high signal throughout the femoral head on all sequences"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The classic 'double line sign' of avascular necrosis (AVN) consists of a peripheral band of low signal on T1 and T2 (representing sclerotic bone) with an inner band of high signal on T2 (representing granulation tissue or fluid). This combination is highly specific for AVN of the femoral head. A uniform high signal throughout the femoral head (option d) would not be consistent with AVN and might suggest a different pathology such as transient osteoporosis.", "reference": "SA Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-005", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.G", "stem": "An increased volume within the carpal tunnel may be associated with:", "options": ["Masses such as neuromas, lipomas, or ganglion cysts only", "Masses and increased fat/muscle content only", "Masses and congenital variants such as a persistent median artery only", "Masses, increased fat/muscle content, and congenital variants such as a persistent median artery"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Carpal tunnel syndrome results from increased pressure within the tunnel, which can be caused by masses (neuromas, lipomas, ganglion cysts), increased fat or muscle content within the tunnel, or congenital variants such as a persistent median artery. MRI is valuable for identifying the specific cause of compression. Option a is incorrect because it limits the causes to masses only, ignoring other well-documented etiologies.", "reference": "SA Ch. 9"}, {"id": "PR-009", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.N", "stem": "Baker's cysts (popliteal cysts) are characterized by which of the following?", "options": ["They are also called popliteal cysts and are well visualized on MRI", "They are difficult to detect on MRI", "They appear as uniform low signal on both T1 and T2", "They require contrast administration for identification"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Baker's cysts (popliteal cysts) are fluid-filled structures that arise from the gastrocnemius-semimembranosus bursa in the popliteal fossa. They are well visualized on MRI, appearing as well-defined fluid collections with low T1 and high T2 signal intensity. Option b is incorrect because MRI is actually the modality of choice for evaluating popliteal cysts due to its excellent soft tissue contrast and multiplanar capability.", "reference": "SA Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-010", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "The pancreas is most commonly evaluated in which imaging plane?", "options": ["Axial", "Coronal", "Sagittal", "Oblique coronal"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The pancreas is most commonly evaluated in the axial plane because this orientation displays the full extent of the gland from head to tail in a single or few slices, along with its relationship to surrounding vascular structures. The axial plane also allows assessment of the pancreatic duct, common bile duct, and adjacent vessels. Coronal imaging (option b) is useful as a supplement but does not optimally display the transverse orientation of the pancreas.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-011", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "The lobe of the liver that is most anterior and extends across the midline is the:", "options": ["Caudate lobe", "Left lobe", "Quadrate lobe", "Right lobe"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The left lobe of the liver is the most anterior lobe and extends across the midline to the left, overlying the stomach and portions of the pancreas. It is separated from the right lobe by the falciform ligament. The caudate lobe (option a) is located posteriorly against the inferior vena cava and does not extend across the midline anteriorly.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-012", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Which techniques can improve the quality of abdominal and pelvic MRI examinations?", "options": ["Careful selection of phase and frequency encoding directions", "Use of fast scanning techniques", "Scanning the patient in a fasting state", "All of these techniques improve abdominal/pelvic exam quality"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All listed techniques improve abdominal and pelvic MRI quality: careful phase/frequency direction selection minimizes motion artifacts from bowel and respiratory movement, fast scanning techniques reduce motion-related signal loss, and fasting reduces bowel peristalsis and gastric content. These strategies work synergistically to improve image quality in body imaging. Selecting only one or two techniques (options a-c) understates the comprehensive approach needed for high-quality abdominal MRI.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-013", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "On T1-weighted sequences, abdominal fluid collections can be classified as benign or pathologic by comparing their signal to urine in the bladder because:", "options": ["Pathologic fluids will appear hyperintense compared to urine", "Pathologic fluids will appear hypointense compared to urine", "Pathologic fluids will appear isointense compared to urine", "Pathologic fluids alter the T1 of surrounding urine"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "On T1-weighted images, simple fluid (such as urine or transudate) appears hypointense due to its long T1 relaxation time. Pathologic fluids containing protein, blood products, or cellular debris have shortened T1 values and appear hyperintense relative to simple urine. This signal difference allows classification of fluid collections as benign or pathologic. Option b is incorrect because pathologic fluids with their shortened T1 appear brighter, not darker, than simple urine.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "PR-014", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following body regions has an inherently good SNR for MRI?", "options": ["Chest and abdomen only", "Chest and pelvis only", "Abdomen and pelvis only", "Chest, abdomen, and pelvis"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The abdomen and pelvis have inherently good SNR because they contain organs with high proton density surrounded by fat, which provides natural contrast. The chest, however, has inherently poor SNR due to low proton density in air-filled lung parenchyma and minimal surrounding fat. Options including the chest (a, b, d) are incorrect because the chest's air-filled alveoli severely limit available MR signal.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-015", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "The thickest myocardium in the heart is found in the:", "options": ["Right atrium", "Left atrium", "Right ventricle", "Left ventricle"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The left ventricle has the thickest myocardium (approximately 10-16 mm) because it generates the highest pressures to pump blood through the systemic circulation. This increased wall thickness is proportional to the workload of the chamber. The right ventricle (option c) has much thinner walls (approximately 3-5 mm) because it only needs to generate sufficient pressure for pulmonary circulation.", "reference": "SA Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PR-016", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "The SNR of the chest is inherently low because:", "options": ["Proton density is low and little fat exists for contrast", "Proton density is low but signal is trapped in air-filled alveoli", "Little fat exists and signal is trapped in alveoli", "Proton density is low, little fat exists, and signal is trapped in alveoli"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The chest has inherently low SNR for MRI because lung tissue has very low proton density (lungs are mostly air) and there is minimal surrounding fat to provide signal and contrast. These two factors combine to produce poor signal from the thorax. Option d incorrectly adds 'signal trapped in alveoli' as a contributing factor — this is not a recognized MRI physics concept; the issue is simply low hydrogen concentration in air-filled tissue.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-017", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.4", "stem": "The brachial plexus is a collection of:", "options": ["Lymphatic ducts", "Blood vessels", "Nerves", "Both lymphatic ducts and blood vessels"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The brachial plexus is a network of nerves (C5-T1 nerve roots) that originate from the cervical and upper thoracic spinal cord and innervate the upper extremity. On MRI, the nerve roots and trunks appear as intermediate signal structures in the supraclavicular and axillary regions. Lymphatic ducts (option a) and blood vessels (option b) are separate anatomic structures that course through the same region but are not components of the brachial plexus.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-018", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "On a T1-weighted sagittal image of the spine, if the vertebral bodies are uniformly hypointense compared to the intervertebral discs, this finding may indicate:", "options": ["Diffuse metastatic disease", "Osteoporosis", "Osteomalacia", "Discitis"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "On T1-weighted images, normal vertebral body marrow contains fat and appears hyperintense relative to intervertebral discs. When vertebral bodies appear uniformly hypointense compared to discs, this reversal of the normal signal pattern suggests diffuse marrow replacement, most commonly from metastatic disease. Osteoporosis (option b) typically shows patchy signal changes rather than uniform hypointensity and would not cause a complete reversal of the marrow-to-disc signal relationship.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36 | SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-019", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which pulse sequence provides improved contrast of vertebral discs, bone, and adjacent ligaments?", "options": ["Spin echo T1-weighted", "Gradient echo T2*-weighted", "Spin echo T2-weighted", "Gradient echo T1-weighted"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient echo T2*-weighted sequences provide improved contrast between vertebral discs, bone, and adjacent ligaments because T2* weighting exaggerates susceptibility differences between these structures while maintaining adequate signal. The bright disc and dark bone/ligament contrast is particularly useful for evaluating disc herniations and foraminal stenosis. Spin echo T1-weighted images (option a) provide excellent anatomic detail but less contrast differentiation between disc and ligamentous structures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 94"}, {"id": "PR-023", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Regarding MRI of the spine, which statements are true?\nI. Normal aging causes loss of disc signal\nII. Disc degeneration is best evaluated on T1 images\nIII. On T1 axial images, disc herniations appear to encroach on dark nerve roots surrounded by brighter epidural fat", "options": ["I and II only", "I and III only", "II and III only", "I, II, and III"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Statements I and III are correct: normal aging causes progressive loss of disc hydration and signal, and on T1 axial images, disc herniations appear as intermediate-signal material encroaching on low-signal nerve roots surrounded by bright epidural fat. Statement II is incorrect because disc degeneration is best evaluated on T2-weighted images (not T1), where the loss of water content in the nucleus pulposus is most conspicuous as decreased signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40 | SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-024", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Regarding MRI of the spine, which statements are true?\nI. Fractures and marrow replacement appear dark on T1\nII. Contrast should always be administered before obtaining any spinal images\nIII. Vertebral hemangiomas appear bright on T1-weighted images", "options": ["I and II only", "I and III only", "II and III only", "I, II, and III"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Statements I and III are correct: fractures and marrow-replacing processes (such as metastases) cause loss of normal fatty marrow signal and appear dark on T1-weighted images, and vertebral hemangiomas appear bright on T1 due to their high fat content. Statement II is incorrect because pre-contrast images should always be obtained before administering gadolinium to establish a baseline for comparison — contrast is never given before initial imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36 | SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-025", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The 'myelographic effect' on MRI is most evident on images that are:", "options": ["Heavily T1-weighted", "Heavily T2-weighted", "Proton density-weighted", "Post-gadolinium enhanced"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The myelographic effect occurs on heavily T2-weighted images (such as T2 FSE with long TE) where CSF appears very bright against dark surrounding structures, mimicking the appearance of a conventional myelogram. This technique is useful for evaluating the thecal sac, nerve root compression, and spinal canal stenosis without contrast injection. Heavily T1-weighted images (option a) would show CSF as dark, producing the opposite effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "PR-026", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which of the following are advantages of MRI spinal imaging over other imaging modalities?\nI. Extent of tumor blockage above and below can be visualized\nII. No beam-hardening artifacts\nIII. Large areas can be surveyed on sagittal images", "options": ["I and II only", "I and III only", "II and III only", "I, II, and III"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All three statements are advantages of MRI for spinal imaging: MRI can visualize the full extent of tumor blockage above and below the lesion on sagittal images without repositioning, there are no beam-hardening artifacts from bone (a CT limitation), and large anatomic areas can be surveyed efficiently on sagittal sequences. Options excluding any statement underestimate MRI's comprehensive advantages over CT and myelography for spinal evaluation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 311"}, {"id": "PR-028", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which type of coil would provide the best image quality for thoracic spine imaging?", "options": ["Body coil", "Posterior surface coil", "Phased array spine coil", "Helmholtz coil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A phased array spine coil provides the best image quality for thoracic spine imaging because it combines the high SNR of multiple surface coil elements with the extended coverage needed for the thoracic spine's length. The individual elements provide excellent signal near the surface while the array configuration maintains uniform coverage. The body coil (option a) provides uniform coverage but significantly lower SNR compared to a phased array due to its greater distance from the anatomy of interest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 337"}, {"id": "PR-029", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.13", "stem": "The vocal cords are optimally imaged during _____ breathing in the _____ plane.", "options": ["Quiet; coronal", "Quiet; axial", "Fast, rhythmic; coronal", "Fast, rhythmic; axial"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The vocal cords are optimally imaged during quiet breathing in the axial plane. Quiet breathing keeps the vocal cords in a relaxed, adducted position providing consistent anatomy, while the axial plane displays both cords symmetrically and allows assessment of cord mobility and surrounding structures. Coronal imaging (options a, c) does not optimally display the bilateral symmetry of the vocal cords within the larynx.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PR-037", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The optic nerves, optic chiasm, and the Circle of Willis are contained within which intracranial cistern?", "options": ["Ambient cistern", "Pontine cistern", "Quadrigeminal cistern", "Suprasellar cistern"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The suprasellar cistern is located above the sella turcica and contains the optic nerves, optic chiasm, and the circle of Willis (including the anterior communicating artery, proximal anterior cerebral arteries, and internal carotid artery bifurcations). This cistern is clinically important because masses here can compress the optic chiasm causing visual field deficits. The ambient cistern (option a) wraps around the midbrain and does not contain the optic structures.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-039", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following are true regarding MRI appearance of stroke?", "options": ["Edema appears bright on T2-weighted images", "The affected area is often wedge-shaped", "The area involved typically lies within a single vascular territory", "All of these findings are characteristic of stroke on MRI"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "All listed findings are characteristic of stroke on MRI: cytotoxic edema from ischemia appears bright on T2-weighted and FLAIR images, the affected area is often wedge-shaped corresponding to the vascular territory, and the involved region typically follows the distribution of a single arterial supply. These combined features help distinguish stroke from other causes of signal abnormality. Options a through c each describe only one characteristic.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-040", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "How does multiple sclerosis typically appear on brain MRI?", "options": ["T2-weighted images demonstrate bright lesions of varying sizes", "T1-weighted images are the optimal sequence for detecting lesions", "T1-weighted images show lesions most prominently in the centrum semiovale", "Lesions are best detected on proton density images"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Multiple sclerosis (MS) plaques characteristically appear as bright (hyperintense) lesions on T2-weighted and FLAIR images due to demyelination and associated edema. These lesions are classically found in the periventricular white matter, corpus callosum, and infratentorial regions. T1-weighted images (option b) are less sensitive for detecting MS plaques, though chronic 'black holes' may be seen on T1.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-041", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "On spin echo T1 or T2-weighted images of the brain, which structures will appear dark (signal void)?", "options": ["Fat and cortical bone only", "Fat and fast-moving blood only", "Cortical bone and fast-moving blood", "Fat, cortical bone, and fast-moving blood"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "On spin echo T1 and T2-weighted images, cortical bone appears dark due to its very low proton density (minimal mobile hydrogen), and fast-moving blood appears as a signal void due to flow-related dephasing and outflow effects. Fat (excluded from the correct answer) actually appears bright on T1-weighted images due to its short T1 relaxation time. Option d incorrectly includes fat as a dark structure.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "PR-045", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Which pulse sequence should be included in an infant brain protocol to best distinguish between gray and white matter?", "options": ["Proton density", "Inversion recovery", "3D phase contrast", "2D time of flight"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Inversion recovery sequences provide superior gray-white matter contrast in infant brains because the TI can be selected to maximize signal differences based on the unique T1 relaxation properties of myelinating and unmyelinated brain tissue. This is especially important because the normal myelination pattern in infants differs significantly from adults. Proton density imaging (option a) provides poor gray-white matter differentiation in the infant brain where water content is high throughout.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 78"}, {"id": "PR-046", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following is a typical finding on MR images of a geriatric patient's brain?", "options": ["Undersized ventricles with compressed cortical sulci", "Enlarged spaces between brain tissue and the skull due to cerebral atrophy", "Increased white matter signal on T1-weighted images", "Thickened cortical gray matter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cerebral atrophy is a normal age-related finding characterized by widened sulci and enlarged ventricles as brain parenchyma volume decreases. On MRI, this appears as increased CSF spaces between the brain surface and the skull. Undersized ventricles with compressed sulci (option a) describes the opposite of age-related atrophy and could suggest conditions such as pseudotumor cerebri or diffuse cerebral edema.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-047", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "A syrinx is best defined as:", "options": ["an abnormally narrow portion of the skull", "inflammation of the brain parenchyma", "a fluid-filled cavity within the central canal of the spinal cord", "agenesis of the corpus callosum"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A syrinx (syringomyelia) is a longitudinal, fluid-filled cavity within the central canal or parenchyma of the spinal cord. On MRI, it follows CSF signal intensity (dark on T1, bright on T2) and can extend over multiple vertebral levels. An abnormally narrow portion of the skull (option a) describes craniosynostosis, which is a completely different pathology unrelated to the spinal cord.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-048", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "When multiple sclerosis plaques are identified on MRI, they are frequently found:", "options": ["only on T1-weighted sequences", "within the cervical spinal cord", "exclusively within the lateral ventricles", "as hypointense artifacts on T2-weighted images"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Multiple sclerosis plaques are commonly found within the cervical spinal cord, in addition to the brain's periventricular white matter and corpus callosum. Cervical cord lesions are characteristically short-segment and peripherally located. Option a is incorrect because T2-weighted sequences (not T1) are the primary detection sequence for MS plaques due to the bright appearance of demyelinated lesions on T2/FLAIR.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-049", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following statements about gliomas is NOT true?", "options": ["They are primary malignant tumors of the central nervous system", "Glioblastoma multiforme is the most aggressive type", "They originate within the brain or spinal cord parenchyma", "They arise exclusively from the meninges"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gliomas are primary CNS tumors that originate from glial cells (astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, ependymal cells) within the brain or spinal cord parenchyma — they are intra-axial tumors. They do NOT arise from the meninges; tumors originating from the meninges are called meningiomas, which are extra-axial. Glioblastoma multiforme (option b) is indeed the most aggressive type of glioma, making that statement true.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-050", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Both meningiomas and acoustic neuromas (vestibular schwannomas) share which characteristic?", "options": ["They are isointense on all post-contrast sequences", "They are extra-axial lesions arising outside the brain parenchyma", "They are metastatic in origin", "They are classified as high-grade malignancies"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Both meningiomas and acoustic neuromas (vestibular schwannomas) are extra-axial lesions, meaning they arise outside the brain parenchyma itself. Meningiomas arise from the meninges, and acoustic neuromas arise from the Schwann cells of the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII). Neither is metastatic (option c) — both are primary tumors arising from non-parenchymal structures adjacent to the brain.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-051", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A family member reports that approximately one hour earlier, the patient experienced sudden slurred speech and confusion that resolved completely. The emergency physician most likely suspects a:", "options": ["cerebral aneurysm", "transient ischemic attack (TIA)", "desmoteplase reaction", "cervical subluxation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is characterized by a sudden onset of focal neurological deficits (such as slurred speech and confusion) that completely resolve within minutes to hours, typically within 24 hours. TIAs are caused by temporary interruption of blood flow to a region of the brain. A cerebral aneurysm (option a) would more likely present with a severe headache ('thunderclap headache') if ruptured, rather than transient neurological symptoms that fully resolve.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-052", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "A butterfly (batwing) vertebra is a congenital anomaly characterized by:", "options": ["a normal finding spanning both cerebral hemispheres", "a finding that appears following tPA administration", "a sagittal cleft in the vertebral body producing wing-like projections", "protrusion of the spinal cord outside the spinal canal"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A butterfly vertebra is a congenital anomaly resulting from failure of fusion of the lateral chondrification centers during embryonic development, producing a sagittal cleft in the vertebral body that gives the appearance of wing-like projections on frontal radiographs or coronal MRI. It is typically an incidental finding with no clinical significance. Option a incorrectly describes it as a finding spanning cerebral hemispheres, which confuses it with a butterfly glioma of the brain.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-053", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Schmorl's nodes are defined as:", "options": ["benign osseous tumors", "vertebral compression fractures", "herniations of the nucleus pulposus through the vertebral endplate into the vertebral body", "positive signs of degenerative disc disease"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Schmorl's nodes are herniations of the nucleus pulposus through the cartilaginous vertebral endplate into the vertebral body. They appear as focal depressions in the endplate, often with surrounding reactive marrow changes visible on MRI. They are generally considered incidental findings related to chronic disc disease. Vertebral compression fractures (option b) involve collapse of the vertebral body height, which is a distinctly different pathology.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-056", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.7", "stem": "Which of the following statements about MR spectroscopy (MRS) is true?", "options": ["It is an outdated form of MR imaging no longer used clinically", "It is used only for industrial material analysis", "It evaluates the chemical composition of tissue in vivo", "It produces images that can be reconstructed in multiple planes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MR spectroscopy (MRS) evaluates the chemical composition of tissue in vivo by measuring the concentrations of metabolites such as N-acetylaspartate (NAA), choline, creatine, and lactate. It is a valuable clinical tool for characterizing brain tumors, metabolic disorders, and other pathologies. Option a is incorrect because MRS remains an active clinical tool with expanding applications, particularly in neuro-oncology and metabolic disease evaluation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "PR-057", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When positioning a patient for a routine brain MRI, the laser alignment light should be centered at the:", "options": ["manubrial notch", "mentum (chin)", "glabella", "iliac crest"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "For routine brain MRI, the laser alignment light is centered at the glabella (the smooth area between the eyebrows above the nose). This landmark ensures proper centering of the head coil and positions the brain at isocenter for optimal image quality. The mentum (option b, the chin) is located too inferiorly and would result in inadequate coverage of the vertex of the brain.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PR-058", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "On a routine axial brain MRI, the frequency encoding direction is typically assigned along which anatomical axis?", "options": ["The slice selection direction", "The anterior-to-posterior (A/P) axis", "The axis that divides the brain into left and right hemispheres", "The direction of the laser light"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "On routine axial brain MRI, the frequency encoding direction is typically assigned along the anterior-to-posterior (A/P) axis. This assignment places the phase encoding direction left-to-right, which minimizes propagation of motion artifacts from pulsatile blood flow in the carotid and basilar arteries across the brain parenchyma. Option c describes the left-right axis, which is the phase encoding direction in standard axial brain imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "PR-059", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a characteristic appearance on T1-weighted brain images?", "options": ["Hypointense blood vessels due to flow void", "Hypointense air and cortical bone", "Hyperintense calcifications", "Hyperintense fatty tissue and subcutaneous fat"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Calcifications typically appear hypointense (dark) on T1-weighted images due to their low proton density and short T2, not hyperintense. All other options are correct T1 characteristics: blood vessels appear as flow voids, air and cortical bone are hypointense, and fatty tissue is hyperintense due to its short T1. Calcifications are better detected on CT or susceptibility-weighted MRI sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "PR-060", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "T1-weighted brain images are best suited for demonstrating:", "options": ["Normal anatomy and congenital structural anomalies", "Vascularity and edema", "Acute hemorrhagic products exclusively", "Calcified lesions"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1-weighted images provide excellent anatomic detail with clear differentiation between gray matter, white matter, CSF, and fat, making them ideal for demonstrating normal anatomy and identifying structural or congenital anomalies. The contrast between tissue types on T1 provides a reliable anatomic roadmap. Option b (vascularity and edema) is better evaluated on T2-weighted or post-contrast T1 images rather than pre-contrast T1 alone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 36"}, {"id": "PR-061", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which pulse sequence best demonstrates bone marrow edema, fractures, and bone bruises in the spine?", "options": ["Gradient echo", "Fast spin echo", "Fluid attenuated inversion recovery (FLAIR)", "Short tau inversion recovery (STIR)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "STIR (Short Tau Inversion Recovery) is the preferred sequence for detecting bone marrow edema, occult fractures, and bone bruises because it suppresses the normal bright fat signal from marrow, making edema (water signal) conspicuous as bright areas against the now-dark marrow background. FLAIR (option c) is designed to suppress CSF signal in the brain, not fat signal in the marrow, making it less sensitive for bone marrow pathology.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "PR-062", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A STIR sequence should be performed before gadolinium administration because STIR:", "options": ["suppresses the signal from enhancing lesions, potentially masking pathology", "counteracts the T1-shortening effect of gadolinium", "is always acquired after contrast", "is never performed in conjunction with contrast media"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "STIR must be performed before gadolinium administration because STIR suppresses signal based on T1 relaxation time, not chemical selectivity. Gadolinium shortens the T1 of enhancing tissues to values similar to fat, so the STIR inversion pulse would inadvertently suppress the signal from enhancing lesions, potentially masking the very pathology being evaluated. Option b incorrectly describes the mechanism — STIR does not counteract gadolinium but rather cannot distinguish enhanced tissue from fat.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, p. 82"}, {"id": "PR-063", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which pulse sequence typically begins with a small flip angle (e.g., 45 degrees), uses a short TE, a short TR, and offers fast scan times?", "options": ["Inversion recovery", "Spin echo", "Fast spin echo", "Gradient echo"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences characteristically use small flip angles (less than 90 degrees), short TR, and short TE, allowing very fast scan times. The use of gradient reversal instead of 180-degree refocusing pulses enables these shorter timing parameters. Inversion recovery (option a) requires an additional 180-degree inversion pulse and longer TI, making it inherently slower than gradient echo imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 89"}, {"id": "PR-064", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Advantages of gradient echo sequences in brain imaging include faster scan times, the ability to perform 3D volumetric acquisitions, and compatibility with:", "options": ["inversion recovery preparation pulses only", "spin echo refocusing pulses only", "fat saturation techniques only", "echo planar imaging (EPI) readouts"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gradient echo sequences are compatible with echo planar imaging (EPI) readouts, enabling ultrafast acquisitions used in diffusion-weighted imaging, perfusion imaging, and functional MRI. The combination of gradient echo excitation with EPI readout allows entire images to be acquired in milliseconds. Options a through c each describe only one capability rather than the unique advantage of EPI compatibility that enables advanced neuroimaging applications.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "PR-065", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When imaging the brain after gadolinium administration, which of the following structures does NOT normally enhance?", "options": ["Mucous membranes of the nasal sinuses", "Pineal and pituitary glands", "Simple cysts", "Choroid plexus"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Simple cysts do not enhance after gadolinium administration because they are avascular fluid collections without a blood supply or capillary network to deliver contrast agent. Normal enhancing structures include mucous membranes (which have a rich blood supply), the pineal and pituitary glands (which lack a complete blood-brain barrier), and the choroid plexus (which has fenestrated capillaries). Option a is incorrect because nasal sinus mucosa normally enhances due to its vascularity.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-066", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "Perfusion and diffusion imaging of the brain primarily provide:", "options": ["physiological and functional detail about tissue viability", "information for tumor staging only", "guidance for biopsy planning only", "data used exclusively for cardiac evaluations"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Perfusion and diffusion imaging provide physiological and functional information about tissue viability, including blood flow at the capillary level (perfusion) and the random motion of water molecules within tissue (diffusion). These techniques are critical for evaluating acute stroke, differentiating tumor recurrence from radiation necrosis, and assessing tissue cellularity. Option b is incorrect because these techniques have broad applications beyond tumor staging alone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, p. 122"}, {"id": "PR-091", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.S", "stem": "An infection of skeletal muscle that typically occurs in young adults is known as:", "options": ["plantar fasciitis", "soft-tissue abscess", "myositis", "cellulitis"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Myositis is an infection or inflammation of skeletal muscle that can occur in young adults, often presenting with pain, swelling, and elevated inflammatory markers. On MRI, myositis appears as muscle edema (bright on T2/STIR) with possible enhancement after contrast. Cellulitis (option d) affects the skin and subcutaneous tissue, not the skeletal muscle itself.", "reference": "SA Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-092", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "On a T2-weighted MR image, normal skeletal muscle appears:", "options": ["hypointense (dark)", "hyperintense (bright)", "intermediate signal", "variable depending on hydration"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Normal skeletal muscle appears hypointense (dark) on T2-weighted images due to its short T2 relaxation time resulting from organized protein structure and limited free water content. Increased T2 signal in muscle indicates pathology such as edema, inflammation, or denervation changes. Hyperintense muscle (option b) would represent an abnormal finding requiring further evaluation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "PR-093", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The diencephalon is the region of the brain that consists of the:", "options": ["brainstem and medulla", "cerebral cortex and corpus callosum", "thalamus and hypothalamus", "cerebellum and pons"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The diencephalon is the central region of the brain located between the cerebral hemispheres and the midbrain, consisting primarily of the thalamus and hypothalamus. The thalamus serves as a relay center for sensory information, while the hypothalamus regulates autonomic functions and endocrine activity. The brainstem and medulla (option a) are part of the posterior fossa structures, not the diencephalon.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-094", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Cavernous malformations (cavernomas) are clusters of abnormal, dilated vessels that are classically described as resembling a:", "options": ["blackberry or mulberry", "bird's nest", "ball of yarn", "bunch of grapes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Cavernous malformations (cavernomas) are classically described as having a mulberry or blackberry appearance on MRI, with a characteristic 'popcorn' pattern of mixed signal intensities from blood products in various stages of evolution, surrounded by a dark hemosiderin rim on T2-weighted images. A 'ball of yarn' (option c) is not a recognized radiologic descriptor for any vascular malformation.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-096", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Approximately 90% of meningiomas are located supratentorially. Given this distribution, which of the following is an important technical consideration?", "options": ["The most superior slices of a brain scan should include coverage through the meninges and vertex", "Only posterior fossa imaging is required to evaluate meningiomas", "A dedicated spine protocol is needed to detect most meningiomas", "Meningiomas are best evaluated without contrast enhancement"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Since approximately 90% of meningiomas are located supratentorially (above the tentorium cerebelli), brain MRI protocols must ensure complete coverage through the meninges and vertex to avoid missing convexity meningiomas at the top of the skull. Inadequate superior coverage could result in a meningioma being excluded from the imaging volume. Option b is incorrect because limiting imaging to the posterior fossa would miss the vast majority of meningiomas.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-098", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "In addition to being categorized by the tissue affected, encephalomalacia can be further classified according to its:", "options": ["shape", "size", "color (white or red)", "associated loss of function"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Encephalomalacia (softening of brain tissue due to injury or disease) can be classified as white or red based on its pathologic appearance. White encephalomalacia involves liquefactive necrosis with cystic change, while red encephalomalacia contains hemorrhagic components. This color classification correlates with the underlying etiology and timing of the insult. Size (option b) is not the primary classification system for encephalomalacia.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-100", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "What is often the first clinical manifestation of small vessel occlusive disease?", "options": ["Sudden blindness", "Stroke or transient ischemic attack", "Facial tics", "Nausea and vomiting"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Small vessel occlusive disease commonly presents first as a stroke or transient ischemic attack (TIA), as progressive narrowing and occlusion of penetrating arterioles leads to lacunar infarcts in deep brain structures such as the basal ganglia, thalamus, and pons. Sudden blindness (option a) is more characteristic of large vessel disease affecting the ophthalmic or retinal arteries, not small vessel disease.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-101", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "An Arnold-Chiari malformation affects the brain primarily by:", "options": ["disrupting the blood supply to the cerebral hemispheres", "obstructing the normal flow of cerebrospinal fluid", "increasing intracranial pressure through mass effect", "causing softening of the cortical gray matter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Arnold-Chiari malformation involves herniation of cerebellar tonsils through the foramen magnum, which obstructs the normal flow of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) at the craniocervical junction. This obstruction can lead to hydrocephalus, syringomyelia, and increased intracranial pressure. Disrupting blood supply (option a) is not the primary mechanism — the pathology relates to structural herniation and CSF flow obstruction.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-102", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following is a clinical feature associated with Dandy-Walker syndrome?", "options": ["Impaired respiratory function", "Progressive paralysis", "Syndactyly (fused fingers and toes)", "Slurred speech"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Dandy-Walker syndrome is a congenital posterior fossa malformation characterized by agenesis or hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis, cystic dilation of the fourth ventricle, and enlargement of the posterior fossa. It is associated with various congenital anomalies including syndactyly (fused fingers/toes), cardiac defects, and facial abnormalities. Impaired respiratory function (option a) is not a characteristic clinical feature of this syndrome.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-104", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.8", "stem": "Which symptom is most commonly associated with an acoustic neuroma (vestibular schwannoma)?", "options": ["Facial tics", "Impaired breathing", "Double vision", "Vertigo and hearing loss"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Acoustic neuromas (vestibular schwannomas) arise from the Schwann cells of the vestibular portion of cranial nerve VIII in the internal auditory canal. The most common presenting symptoms are sensorineural hearing loss, tinnitus, and vertigo/imbalance due to compression of the vestibulocochlear nerve. Facial tics (option a) would suggest involvement of the facial nerve (CN VII), which is less commonly affected early in the disease course.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-106", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which combination of symptoms is most commonly associated with a subarachnoid hemorrhage?", "options": ["Loss of bladder control, visual changes, and headaches", "No symptoms in most cases", "Facial tics, numbness in the hands", "Severe headache, visual changes, motor deficits, and loss of consciousness"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) classically presents with sudden severe headache (often described as 'the worst headache of my life'), visual changes, motor deficits, and potentially loss of consciousness. These symptoms result from blood irritating the meninges and increasing intracranial pressure. Option a describes symptoms more typical of other neurological conditions; SAH has a dramatic acute presentation.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3"}, {"id": "PR-107", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.12", "stem": "Acute sinusitis is defined as lasting up to a maximum of:", "options": ["4 days", "4 weeks", "4 months", "12 weeks"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Acute sinusitis is defined as lasting up to a maximum of 4 weeks, with symptoms including nasal congestion, purulent discharge, facial pain/pressure, and decreased sense of smell. Sinusitis lasting beyond 12 weeks is classified as chronic. Option a (4 days) is too short to define even an acute episode of sinusitis.", "reference": "SA Ch. 2"}, {"id": "PR-111", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "After the brain, which anatomical region is the second most commonly imaged in MRI?", "options": ["Brain", "Vertebral column (spine)", "Cerebral vessels", "Peripheral arteries"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "After the brain, the vertebral column (spine) is the second most commonly imaged anatomical region in MRI. Spine MRI is widely performed for evaluating disc disease, spinal cord pathology, stenosis, and tumors. Cerebral vessels (option c) are typically evaluated as part of brain MRI or dedicated MRA, not as a separate primary imaging region.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-112", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The vertebral column comprises approximately what fraction of an individual's total height?", "options": ["One-quarter", "One-half", "One-fifth", "Two-fifths"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The vertebral column comprises approximately two-fifths (40%) of an individual's total height. This proportion is important for understanding body habitus and planning imaging coverage for total spine studies. One-quarter (option a) significantly underestimates the contribution of the spinal column to total height.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-115", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "In normal anatomy, the conus medullaris terminates at the level of:", "options": ["T11-T12", "L1-L2", "L4-L5", "L5-S1"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In normal adult anatomy, the conus medullaris (the tapered terminal end of the spinal cord) terminates at the L1-L2 vertebral level. A conus located below L2-L3 may indicate a tethered cord or other developmental abnormality. L4-L5 (option c) would represent a significantly low-lying conus, which is pathologic in adults.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-117", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "In MRI, a structure should be evaluated in a minimum of how many imaging planes to help distinguish normal from abnormal anatomy?", "options": ["1", "2", "3", "4"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In MRI, a structure should be evaluated in a minimum of two imaging planes to help distinguish normal from abnormal anatomy. Orthogonal planes provide complementary information about the three-dimensional shape and extent of structures and pathology. A single plane (option a) provides insufficient spatial information and may miss pathology that is oriented in the plane of imaging.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-118", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "In an adult, a primary function of the spleen is the production of:", "options": ["antibodies (immunoglobulins)", "white blood cells", "hormones", "red blood cells"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "In adults, the spleen functions primarily as an immune organ, producing antibodies (immunoglobulins) and filtering blood to remove old or damaged red blood cells and pathogens. While the spleen produces red blood cells during fetal development, this hematopoietic function is transferred to the bone marrow after birth. Red blood cell production (option d) is not a primary function of the adult spleen.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-119", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Under normal circumstances, the spleen:", "options": ["is easily palpable on routine physical examination", "is not palpable on routine physical examination", "can only be visualized using ultrasound", "is located in the right upper quadrant"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Under normal circumstances, the spleen is not palpable on routine physical examination because it is protected beneath the left lower rib cage. A palpable spleen on physical examination suggests splenomegaly (enlargement), which can be caused by infection, portal hypertension, hematologic disorders, or other pathology. Option a is incorrect because a palpable spleen is an abnormal finding.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-122", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "Why is it standard practice to acquire multiple post-contrast phases of the liver at timed intervals following gadolinium injection?", "options": ["To suppress the signal from blood vessels", "To facilitate post-processing subtraction", "To allow hemangiomas to progressively fill with contrast over time", "To enhance the appearance of the hepatocytes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Multiple timed post-contrast phases of the liver are acquired because different lesions have characteristic enhancement patterns at different time points. Hemangiomas specifically show peripheral nodular enhancement in the arterial phase with progressive centripetal fill-in on delayed images — a pattern that requires multiple phases to demonstrate. Suppressing blood vessel signal (option a) is not the purpose of multiphase imaging; that is achieved with subtraction techniques.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-124", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.7", "stem": "Gallstones formed primarily from excess bilirubin in bile are classified as:", "options": ["cystic stones", "biliary stones", "cholesterol stones", "pigment stones"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Gallstones formed primarily from excess bilirubin in bile are classified as pigment stones. These are further subdivided into black pigment stones (associated with hemolytic disorders) and brown pigment stones (associated with infection). Cholesterol stones (option c) are formed from excess cholesterol in bile and represent a different stone composition, though they are the most common type of gallstone overall.", "reference": "SA Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-128", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.C.2", "stem": "Which symptoms are most commonly associated with endometriosis?", "options": ["Pelvic pain and infertility", "Pelvic pain and amenorrhea", "Infertility and irregular menstruation", "Amenorrhea and dysuria"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Endometriosis is characterized by the presence of endometrial tissue outside the uterine cavity, most commonly presenting with chronic pelvic pain and infertility. On MRI, endometriomas (chocolate cysts) demonstrate high T1 signal from hemorrhagic content with T2 shading. Amenorrhea (option b) is not typically associated with endometriosis; patients usually have regular but painful menstrual cycles.", "reference": "SA Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-129", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.C.1", "stem": "Simple cysts typically demonstrate signal intensity similar to that of:", "options": ["fat", "bone", "water", "muscle"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Simple cysts contain serous fluid and therefore demonstrate signal intensity similar to water: hypointense on T1-weighted images and markedly hyperintense on T2-weighted images. They show no internal enhancement after contrast administration. Fat (option a) has the opposite signal pattern, appearing bright on T1 due to its short T1 relaxation time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 40"}, {"id": "PR-132", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.D", "stem": "In patients with a rotator cuff tear, pain typically worsens when attempting activities:", "options": ["at or below waist level", "at or above shoulder level", "that involve pronating the elbow", "that involve flexing the wrist"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In patients with rotator cuff tears, pain typically worsens with overhead activities (at or above shoulder level) because these positions require the torn rotator cuff muscles to generate force for abduction and external rotation against gravity. The supraspinatus tendon is most commonly involved. Activities at or below waist level (option a) place less demand on the rotator cuff and are generally less painful.", "reference": "SA Ch. 9"}, {"id": "PR-134", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.S", "stem": "The vessel walls of a venous hemangioma are characteristically:", "options": ["thick and fibrous", "thin and constricted", "smooth and pliable", "rough and scarred"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Venous hemangiomas are characterized by thick, fibrous vessel walls that distinguish them from capillary hemangiomas, which have thinner walls. On MRI, venous hemangiomas appear as well-defined lobulated masses with high T2 signal due to slow-flowing blood within dilated vascular channels. Thin and constricted walls (option b) would be more characteristic of normal veins under compression, not hemangiomas.", "reference": "SA Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-137", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.K", "stem": "When a fracture of the superior pubic ramus is identified, the technologist should also evaluate the inferior pubic ramus because:", "options": ["fractures of both rami typically occur together due to the ring structure of the pelvis", "the inferior ramus is always fractured first", "isolated superior ramus fractures do not occur", "the inferior ramus is more susceptible to avascular necrosis"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "When a fracture of the superior pubic ramus is identified, the inferior ramus should also be evaluated because fractures of both rami typically occur together due to the ring structure of the pelvis. The pelvic ring cannot break in only one location without disrupting another point in the ring (similar to breaking a pretzel). Option c is incorrect because isolated superior ramus fractures can occur but are less common than combined bilateral ramus fractures.", "reference": "SA Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-139", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.O", "stem": "Which tarsal bone is the largest and most posterior bone of the ankle joint?", "options": ["cuboid", "navicular", "talus", "calcaneus"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The calcaneus (heel bone) is the largest and most posterior bone of the foot and ankle, forming the prominence of the heel and serving as the attachment point for the Achilles tendon. It articulates with the talus superiorly and the cuboid anteriorly. The talus (option c) sits on top of the calcaneus and is the second largest tarsal bone, but it is positioned more superiorly and anteriorly.", "reference": "SA Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-140", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Regarding the use of gadolinium-based contrast agents in pregnant patients, which statement is correct?", "options": ["Gadolinium is considered completely safe throughout pregnancy", "Gadolinium crosses the placenta and should be avoided unless the benefit clearly outweighs the risk", "Gadolinium is contraindicated only during the first trimester", "Gadolinium has no effect on fetal tissue regardless of gestational age"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents cross the placenta and enter the fetal circulation, where the long-term effects on the developing fetus are not fully understood. Therefore, gadolinium should be avoided during pregnancy unless the clinical benefit clearly outweighs the potential risk to the fetus. Option a is incorrect because gadolinium is not considered completely safe in pregnancy — it is a risk-benefit decision made in consultation with the referring physician.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PR-142", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "When performing time-of-flight MR angiography, which technique will most effectively improve suppression of stationary background tissue?", "options": ["Increasing the TR to allow full longitudinal recovery", "Applying presaturation pulses to the imaging volume", "Increasing the receiver bandwidth", "Using a larger field of view"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Presaturation pulses, decreased TR, and increased flip angle all improve stationary tissue suppression in TOF-MRA by keeping background tissue saturated. Presaturation pulses are the most direct method, selectively saturating signal from stationary spins. Increasing TR allows more longitudinal recovery, which is the opposite of the desired effect. MIP Ch. 8 p. 298.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8 p. 298"}, {"id": "PR-143", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "Which parameter adjustment most effectively reduces intravoxel dephasing in MR angiography?", "options": ["Reduced slice thickness", "Increased echo time", "Increased field of view", "Increased number of signal averages"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Reducing slice thickness decreases the range of velocities within each voxel, thereby reducing intravoxel dephasing and improving vessel conspicuity. Reducing FOV also helps by decreasing voxel size. Increasing TE would worsen dephasing, not reduce it. MIP Ch. 8 p. 298.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8 p. 298"}, {"id": "PR-146", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "The ulnar nerve is located between which two anatomic landmarks at the elbow?", "options": ["Medial epicondyle of the humerus and the olecranon process", "Lateral epicondyle and the radial head", "Bicipital groove and the lesser tuberosity", "Coracoid process and the acromion"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The ulnar nerve passes through the cubital tunnel between the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the olecranon process, making it the most commonly injured nerve in the body due to its superficial location. This area is colloquially known as the 'funny bone.' SA Ch. 4.", "reference": "SA Ch. 9"}, {"id": "PR-147", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "On MRI of the hip, which finding is characteristic of avascular necrosis (AVN)?", "options": ["Diffuse homogeneous high signal on T1-weighted images throughout the femoral head", "A rim of decreased signal on T1 and T2 images with an inner band of increased signal on T2", "Complete absence of signal in the femoral head on all sequences", "Uniform low signal on T2-weighted images with no T1 abnormality"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The classic MRI appearance of AVN includes a low-signal-intensity rim (representing reactive interface) visible on both T1 and T2 images, with an inner band of high signal on T2 (representing granulation tissue or fluid). This 'double-line sign' on T2 is considered pathognomonic for AVN. MIP Ch. 2 p. 51 / SA Ch. 6.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2 p. 51 / SA Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-148", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "Carpal tunnel syndrome on MRI may show increased canal volume due to which finding?", "options": ["Mass lesion such as neuroma, lipoma, or ganglion cyst", "Decreased synovial fluid production", "Atrophy of the flexor tendons", "Calcification of the transverse carpal ligament"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "An increase in carpal tunnel volume may be associated with mass lesions (neuromas, lipomas, hemangiomas, ganglion cysts), increased fat/muscle content, congenital variants such as a persistent median artery, or synovial hypertrophy from rheumatoid arthritis. Tendon atrophy would decrease, not increase, tunnel volume. SA Ch. 4.", "reference": "SA Ch. 9"}, {"id": "PR-152", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "2.A.3", "stem": "Baker's cysts (popliteal cysts) on MRI typically demonstrate:", "options": ["Low signal on T1 and high signal on T2, best seen in the sagittal plane", "High signal on both T1 and T2 due to hemorrhagic content", "Signal void on all sequences due to calcification", "Heterogeneous signal that enhances intensely after contrast administration"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Baker's cysts (popliteal cysts) contain synovial fluid and therefore appear as uniform low signal on T1 and high signal on T2-weighted images. They are located in the popliteal fossa and are best visualized on sagittal images. They are easily identified on MRI and do not typically require contrast for diagnosis. SA Ch. 6.", "reference": "SA Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PR-153", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "On spin echo T1 and T2-weighted brain images, which structures normally appear dark (hypointense)?", "options": ["Subcutaneous fat and bone marrow", "Cortical bone and rapidly flowing blood", "Gray matter and cerebrospinal fluid", "White matter and orbital fat"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cortical bone has very low proton density and short T2, producing signal void on all standard SE sequences. Rapidly flowing blood also appears dark on SE images due to flow void (time-of-flight signal loss). Fat appears bright on T1 due to its short T1. CSF appears dark on T1 but bright on T2. MIP Ch. 2 p. 32.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2 p. 32"}, {"id": "PR-154", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "2.A.1", "stem": "On MRI of an acute stroke, which imaging characteristics are typically observed?", "options": ["The affected area is often wedge-shaped, lying within a single vascular territory", "The affected area appears bright on T1-weighted images in the hyperacute phase", "Edema appears dark on both T1 and T2-weighted images", "The affected territory spans multiple vascular distributions symmetrically"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Stroke on MRI typically appears as a wedge-shaped region of edema within a single vascular territory. The edema produces high signal on T2-weighted images (not dark). On T1, the area may appear isointense or mildly hypointense in the acute phase. DWI is the most sensitive sequence for detecting acute ischemic stroke. MIP Ch. 2 p. 51.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2 p. 51"}, {"id": "PR-162", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "The vocal cords are best imaged in which plane and during which type of breathing?", "options": ["Coronal plane during phonation", "Axial plane during quiet breathing", "Sagittal plane during breath-hold", "Coronal plane during deep inspiration"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The vocal cords are in a relaxed, abducted position during quiet breathing, with the glottis open between them, and are best evaluated in the axial plane. The axial plane provides optimal cross-sectional visualization of the laryngeal structures, airway patency, and cord symmetry. HMT Ch. 10.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 10"}, {"id": "PR-163", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which coil type is most appropriate for imaging the thoracic spine in adult patients?", "options": ["Body coil", "Posterior surface coil", "Phased array spine coil", "Helmholtz coil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Phased array spine coils provide the best combination of signal-to-noise ratio and coverage for thoracic spine imaging in adults. The posterior surface coil alone suffers from signal fall-off anteriorly in larger patients. Phased array coils use multiple receiver elements to maintain high SNR across a large field of view. MIP Ch. 9 p. 337 / HMT Ch. 14.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 337 / HMT Ch. 14"}, {"id": "PR-164", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which advantage does MRI spinal imaging offer over other modalities such as myelography?", "options": ["MRI provides superior visualization of cortical bone detail", "MRI can survey large areas on sagittal images without intrathecal contrast", "MRI is faster than CT for emergency spine trauma evaluation", "MRI eliminates all motion artifact in spinal imaging"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRI spine imaging advantages include the ability to image above and below a tumor simultaneously, a lack of beam-hardening artifacts, no need for intrathecal contrast, and excellent soft tissue contrast on sagittal images that allow large-area surveys. CT provides better cortical bone detail. MIP Ch. 2 / HMT Ch. 14.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 14"}, {"id": "PR-165", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Regarding MRI of the spine, which statement is correct?", "options": ["Paramagnetic contrast should always be injected before acquiring any spinal images", "Vertebral body fractures and marrow replacement appear bright on T1-weighted images", "Bone hemangiomas typically appear hyperintense on T1-weighted images due to their fat content", "Normal intervertebral discs appear dark on T2-weighted images"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Vertebral hemangiomas contain fat and appear bright on T1-weighted images. T1 images should be obtained BEFORE gadolinium injection because contrast enhancement can mask changes in vertebral body signal (fractures and marrow replacement appear dark on T1, and contrast could obscure this finding). HMT Ch. 14 / MIP Ch. 2.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 14 / MIP Ch. 2"}, {"id": "PR-166", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Regarding degenerative disc disease on MRI, which statement is accurate?", "options": ["Normal aging causes increased T2 signal in intervertebral discs", "Disc degeneration is best evaluated on T1-weighted images", "Disc herniations on T1 axial images appear as soft tissue encroaching on the dark nerve roots surrounded by bright epidural fat", "All disc herniations enhance intensely after gadolinium administration"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "On T1 axial images, disc herniations appear as intermediate-signal soft tissue displacing the normally dark nerve roots from the surrounding bright epidural fat. Normal aging causes loss of disc hydration, resulting in decreased (not increased) T2 signal. Disc degeneration is best seen on T2-weighted images where the loss of water content is most conspicuous. HMT Ch. 14 / MIP Ch. 2.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 14 / MIP Ch. 2"}, {"id": "PR-170", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which pulse sequence provides the best contrast between vertebral discs, bone, and adjacent ligaments in spine imaging?", "options": ["Spin echo T1-weighted", "Gradient echo T2*-weighted", "Spin echo T2-weighted", "STIR"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient echo T2*-weighted sequences display discs and CSF as relatively high signal while bone and ligaments remain dark, providing excellent contrast between these structures. This is particularly useful for evaluating disc-osteophyte complexes and foraminal stenosis. T1 SE shows good anatomic detail but less contrast between disc and CSF. HMT Ch. 14 / MIP Ch. 4.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 14 / MIP Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PR-171", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which body region has an inherently high signal-to-noise ratio for MRI?", "options": ["Chest", "Wrist", "Abdomen and pelvis", "Extremities"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The abdomen and pelvis have inherently high SNR due to their large tissue volume, which provides abundant hydrogen protons for signal generation. The chest has low SNR due to air-filled lungs, cardiac motion, and respiratory motion. Extremities have lower tissue volume and therefore lower inherent SNR. MIP Ch. 7 p. 210.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 7 p. 210"}, {"id": "PR-172", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which strategy improves the quality of abdominal and pelvic MRI examinations?", "options": ["Careful selection of phase and frequency encoding directions to minimize motion artifacts", "Scanning the patient immediately after a large meal for optimal bowel distension", "Using the slowest available pulse sequence for maximum SNR", "Positioning the phase-encoding direction along the longest body axis"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Selecting the phase-encoding direction to minimize propagation of respiratory and bowel motion artifacts, using fast scanning techniques to reduce acquisition time, and scanning fasting patients (to reduce bowel motion) all improve abdominal/pelvic image quality. Scanning after a large meal increases bowel motion. HMT Ch. 16 / MIP Ch. 8.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 16 / MIP Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PR-173", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "The lobe of the liver that is most anterior and extends across the midline is the:", "options": ["Caudate lobe", "Left lobe", "Quadrate lobe", "Right lobe"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The left lobe of the liver is the most anterior and extends across the midline to the left. The caudate lobe is the smallest lobe, located posteriorly adjacent to the IVC. The quadrate lobe lies between the gallbladder fossa and the ligamentum teres. The right lobe is the largest but does not extend across the midline. SA Ch. 5.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-174", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "The pancreas is typically best displayed in which imaging plane?", "options": ["Axial (transverse)", "Coronal", "Sagittal", "Oblique coronal"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The pancreas lies transversely in the retroperitoneum, extending from the duodenal C-loop (head) to the splenic hilum (tail). The axial plane best displays its full length in a single slice or a few contiguous slices. Coronal images can show the relationship to surrounding structures but typically do not capture the entire pancreas in one slice. SA Ch. 5 / HMT Ch. 16.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7 / HMT Ch. 16"}, {"id": "PR-175", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A.2", "stem": "Which technique can improve visualization of the pancreas on MRI?", "options": ["Administering oral water or contrast to distend the stomach and duodenum", "Using the longest available TE for maximum T2 weighting", "Imaging exclusively in the sagittal plane", "Avoiding breath-hold techniques to allow signal averaging"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Oral water or contrast agents distend the stomach and duodenum, creating a dark or bright interface that separates these structures from the pancreas and improves visualization. Fast scanning techniques reduce respiratory motion, and prone positioning can also reduce bowel-related artifacts. Long TE alone does not specifically improve pancreatic visualization. HMT Ch. 16 / SA Ch. 5.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 16 / SA Ch. 7"}, {"id": "PR-176", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following structures are components of the basal ganglia?", "options": ["Hypothalamus, epithalamus, and bilateral thalami", "Caudate nucleus, lentiform nucleus, and bilateral thalami", "Pons, medulla, and midbrain", "Bilateral anterior cerebral arteries, posterior cerebral arteries, and communicating arteries"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The basal ganglia are a group of subcortical nuclei that include the caudate nucleus, lentiform nucleus (putamen + globus pallidus), and the thalami. These structures play a key role in motor control, learning, and executive function. Option D describes the circle of Willis, which is the arterial anastomosis at the base of the brain, not the basal ganglia.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3, pp. 100-120"}, {"id": "PR-177", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.14", "stem": "Which of the following correctly identifies the components of the circle of Willis?", "options": ["Hypothalamus, epithalamus, and bilateral thalami", "Caudate nucleus, lentiform nucleus, and bilateral thalami", "Pons, medulla, and midbrain", "Bilateral anterior and posterior cerebral arteries, anterior communicating artery, and bilateral posterior communicating arteries"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The circle of Willis is an arterial anastomosis at the base of the brain formed by the anterior cerebral arteries, posterior cerebral arteries, anterior communicating artery, and posterior communicating arteries (plus contributions from the internal carotid arteries). This structure provides collateral circulation to the brain. Option C describes the brainstem components, not the vascular ring.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3, pp. 140-160"}, {"id": "PR-178", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following structures are components of the diencephalon?", "options": ["Hypothalamus, epithalamus, and bilateral thalami", "Caudate nucleus, lentiform nucleus, and bilateral thalami", "Pons, medulla, and midbrain", "Bilateral anterior and posterior cerebral arteries and communicating arteries"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The diencephalon is a division of the forebrain composed of the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus, and subthalamus. It sits between the cerebral hemispheres and the midbrain. Option C describes the brainstem, which lies inferior to the diencephalon.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3, pp. 100-115"}, {"id": "PR-179", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.13", "stem": "Which imaging plane best demonstrates the base of the tongue and the epiglottis?", "options": ["Coronal", "Oblique", "Sagittal", "Axial"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The sagittal plane provides the best visualization of midline structures in the neck, including the base of the tongue, epiglottis, and their relationship to the oropharynx and larynx. These structures are oriented in the anterior-posterior direction and are best seen in profile on sagittal images. The axial plane would show these structures in cross-section but without the superior-inferior relationships.", "reference": "SA Ch. 5, pp. 260-275"}, {"id": "PR-180", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When evaluating a patient for metastatic brain disease, which contrast administration protocol is recommended to optimize lesion detection?", "options": ["Single standard dose with immediate imaging only", "Single standard dose with immediate imaging followed by an additional dose and delayed imaging", "Double dose with rapid imaging", "No contrast is needed for metastatic disease evaluation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "For metastatic brain disease, administering a standard dose of gadolinium-based contrast agent with initial imaging, followed by an additional dose and delayed imaging (approximately 20-30 minutes), can improve detection of small enhancing lesions. The delayed component allows contrast to accumulate in lesions with a disrupted blood-brain barrier. Single-dose rapid imaging alone may miss small metastases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 370-375"}, {"id": "PR-181", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "What is the primary reason for using cardiac gating when imaging the brain of a patient with a history of seizures?", "options": ["To minimize pulsatile flow motion artifact in the temporal lobes", "To monitor the patient for potential seizure activity", "To eliminate the need for patient communication during the exam", "To produce black-blood vascular contrast"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Cardiac gating is used in seizure protocol brain imaging to reduce pulsatile CSF and vascular flow artifacts, particularly in the temporal lobes and posterior fossa. These regions are critical for seizure evaluation and are prone to motion artifact from nearby vascular structures. Cardiac gating synchronizes data acquisition to the cardiac cycle, reducing ghost artifacts. Gating is not used for patient monitoring purposes.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, pp. 260-265"}, {"id": "PR-182", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which imaging plane is considered most important when evaluating a patient with a seizure disorder?", "options": ["Sagittal", "Axial", "Coronal", "Sagittal oblique"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Coronal images are essential in seizure protocol MRI because they provide the best visualization of the hippocampi and mesial temporal structures, which are the most common source of temporal lobe epilepsy. Coronal slices oriented perpendicular to the long axis of the hippocampus allow direct side-to-side comparison for asymmetry in size and signal. Axial images are also obtained but are less sensitive to subtle hippocampal pathology.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 365-370"}, {"id": "PR-183", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When a patient arrives for a brain MRI with a visible cranial surgical scar, what is the most appropriate initial action?", "options": ["Proceed immediately with the MRI to determine the type of surgery", "Screen the patient and contact their physician or family to determine the type of surgery performed", "Disregard the scar and proceed with standard protocol", "Cover the scar with a sterile drape before scanning"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A visible cranial scar indicates prior surgery, which may have involved placement of ferromagnetic implants, aneurysm clips, or other devices that could be hazardous in the MRI environment. The technologist must screen the patient thoroughly and obtain surgical history from the patient, physician, or family before proceeding. Scanning without this information could result in serious injury. Covering the scar has no safety benefit.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 12, pp. 310-315; ACR MRI Safety Manual"}, {"id": "PR-184", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "After administration of a gadolinium-based contrast agent to evaluate the extent of a brain tumor, which pulse sequence weighting is most appropriate?", "options": ["T1-weighted", "T2-weighted", "Proton density-weighted", "T2*-weighted (gradient echo)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "T1-weighted images are the standard for post-contrast brain tumor evaluation because gadolinium shortens the T1 relaxation time of enhancing tissues, causing them to appear hyperintense (bright). This allows clear delineation of tumor margins, enhancement patterns, and surrounding edema. T2-weighted images are useful for identifying edema but do not demonstrate contrast enhancement effectively.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 370-375"}, {"id": "PR-185", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "During a brain MRI of a patient with decreased consciousness, an area of high signal intensity is seen on both T1-weighted and T2-weighted images. Which type of lesion is most likely?", "options": ["Metastatic tumor", "Abscess", "Hemorrhage containing methemoglobin", "Neurofibroma"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A lesion that appears hyperintense on both T1- and T2-weighted images is characteristic of subacute hemorrhage containing methemoglobin. Methemoglobin has paramagnetic properties that shorten T1, producing high signal on T1-weighted images, while the intact red blood cells in the subacute phase also produce high signal on T2-weighted images. Metastatic lesions, abscesses, and neurofibromas typically do not show this dual-hyperintense pattern.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 375-380"}, {"id": "PR-186", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.9", "stem": "Which imaging planes are optimal for high-resolution T1-weighted evaluation of the pituitary gland?", "options": ["Sagittal and coronal", "Coronal and axial", "Axial and sagittal", "Coronal only"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Sagittal and coronal planes are the standard imaging planes for pituitary MRI. The coronal plane is perpendicular to the sella turcica and provides the best visualization of the pituitary gland, stalk, and cavernous sinuses for side-to-side comparison. The sagittal plane shows the gland's relationship to the optic chiasm and sphenoid sinus. Axial images add little value for pituitary evaluation.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3, pp. 130-140"}, {"id": "PR-187", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.9", "stem": "When evaluating a patient for a suspected pituitary microadenoma, why is rapid imaging performed immediately after contrast injection?", "options": ["Microadenomas enhance faster than normal pituitary tissue", "Microadenomas appear hypointense against the rapidly enhancing normal pituitary gland", "Delayed imaging is preferred because microadenomas enhance slowly", "The timing of contrast injection has no clinical significance"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Dynamic post-contrast imaging for pituitary microadenomas relies on the differential enhancement between the normal pituitary gland and the adenoma. The normal pituitary gland lacks a blood-brain barrier and enhances rapidly and intensely after contrast injection. Microadenomas enhance more slowly, so on early post-contrast images they appear relatively hypointense (dark) against the brightly enhancing normal gland. Delayed imaging allows the adenoma to catch up, reducing conspicuity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 372-375"}, {"id": "PR-188", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "When imaging the brain of an infant under 1 year of age whose brain is not yet fully myelinated, which sequence best demonstrates gray-white matter differentiation?", "options": ["T1-weighted spin echo", "T2-weighted spin echo", "Spoiled gradient echo", "Inversion recovery"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Inversion recovery sequences (particularly STIR or IR-prepared sequences) provide superior gray-white matter contrast in the unmyelinated or incompletely myelinated infant brain. Standard T1-weighted sequences show reduced contrast between gray and white matter in infants because the T1 values of unmyelinated white matter are much longer than in adults. Inversion recovery exploits T1 differences more effectively, producing hyperintense white matter relative to gray matter.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 3, pp. 78-85"}, {"id": "PR-189", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "On T1-weighted (short TR/short TE) spin echo images of the brain, how does normal white matter appear relative to gray matter?", "options": ["Hyperintense (brighter than gray matter)", "Hypointense (darker than gray matter)", "Isointense (same signal as gray matter)", "Signal void (no signal)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "On T1-weighted images, white matter appears hyperintense (bright) relative to gray matter because myelinated white matter has a shorter T1 relaxation time. The lipid content of myelin sheaths causes white matter to recover longitudinal magnetization more quickly, producing higher signal on T1-weighted sequences. Gray matter, with its longer T1, appears darker by comparison.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, pp. 30-35"}, {"id": "PR-190", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.8", "stem": "Which two cranial nerves traverse the internal auditory canals (IACs)?", "options": ["Cranial nerves IV and V (trochlear and trigeminal)", "Cranial nerves V and VI (trigeminal and abducens)", "Cranial nerves VI and VII (abducens and facial)", "Cranial nerves VII and VIII (facial and vestibulocochlear)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Cranial nerve VII (facial nerve) and cranial nerve VIII (vestibulocochlear nerve) travel together through the internal auditory canal from the brainstem to the inner ear. This is clinically significant because acoustic neuromas (vestibular schwannomas) commonly arise from CN VIII within the IAC. The trigeminal nerve (CN V) exits through the Meckel cave, not the IAC.", "reference": "SA Ch. 3, pp. 145-155"}, {"id": "PR-191", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "For most standard brain MRI examinations, what is the recommended patient position and anatomic centering landmark?", "options": ["Prone with centering at the acanthomeatal line", "Supine with centering at the nasion", "Supine with centering at the external auditory meatus", "Prone with centering at the vertex"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Standard brain MRI is performed with the patient supine and head-first in the head coil. The nasion (bridge of the nose) is used as the centering landmark because it corresponds approximately to the center of the brain in the superior-inferior direction and provides consistent positioning for the laser light localizer. The external auditory meatus is used as a landmark for some skull base protocols but not routine brain imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 360-365"}, {"id": "PR-192", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.13", "stem": "What is the optimal patient positioning and coil selection for thyroid gland imaging?", "options": ["Supine with the head coil extended inferiorly over the neck", "Supine with a small surface coil placed on the anterior neck", "Supine using the body coil to ensure a large field of view", "Prone with a surface coil on the posterior neck"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Thyroid MRI is performed with the patient supine and a small flexible surface coil (or anterior neck array) placed directly over the anterior neck. This provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for the superficial thyroid gland. The body coil would provide inadequate spatial resolution due to its large coverage area. The head coil is designed for the cranium and does not optimally cover the thyroid region.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 5, pp. 110-115"}, {"id": "PR-193", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "On T1-weighted images, how do tissues with short T1 relaxation times—such as fat and gadolinium-enhanced structures—appear compared to surrounding normal tissues?", "options": ["Hyperintense (brighter)", "Hypointense (darker)", "Isointense (same signal intensity)", "Signal void"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Tissues with short T1 relaxation times recover longitudinal magnetization quickly and therefore produce high signal on T1-weighted images. Fat inherently has a short T1, while gadolinium-based contrast agents shorten the T1 of tissues they accumulate in. Both appear hyperintense relative to surrounding structures on T1-weighted sequences. This principle is fundamental to understanding post-contrast enhancement patterns in clinical MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, pp. 30-40"}, {"id": "PR-194", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "In dynamic susceptibility contrast (DSC) perfusion imaging for stroke evaluation, how does normal brain tissue appear relative to ischemic tissue on T2*-weighted images during contrast passage?", "options": ["Hyperintense to ischemic tissue", "Hypointense to ischemic tissue", "Isointense to ischemic tissue", "No signal difference is observed"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "During DSC perfusion imaging, the first pass of gadolinium causes signal loss on T2*-weighted images due to susceptibility effects. Normal brain tissue with intact perfusion shows significant signal drop as the contrast bolus passes through its capillary bed. Ischemic tissue with reduced blood flow shows less signal loss (remains relatively bright) because less contrast reaches the affected region. Therefore, normal brain appears hypointense relative to ischemic brain during the bolus passage.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 16, pp. 400-405"}, {"id": "PR-195", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.14", "stem": "Which MRA technique best demonstrates flow within small intracranial vessels with high-velocity blood flow?", "options": ["2D time-of-flight MRA", "3D time-of-flight MRA", "3D phase contrast MRA", "Contrast-enhanced MRA"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "3D time-of-flight (TOF) MRA is the preferred technique for intracranial arterial imaging because its thin-partition acquisition and high spatial resolution excel at depicting small vessels. The 3D volume excitation maintains consistent inflow enhancement for high-velocity arterial flow within the intracranial circulation. 2D TOF is better suited for slower flow in larger vessels (such as the carotid arteries in the neck) because each thin slice receives fresh unsaturated spins.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 13, pp. 335-340"}, {"id": "PR-196", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.15", "stem": "Which MRA technique is recommended for evaluating extracranial vascular flow, such as the carotid arteries in the neck?", "options": ["2D time-of-flight MRA", "3D time-of-flight MRA", "3D phase contrast MRA", "Contrast-enhanced MRA only"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "2D time-of-flight MRA is well-suited for evaluating extracranial carotid arteries because each thin slice receives fresh, unsaturated inflowing blood. This technique is less susceptible to signal loss from in-plane saturation that can occur with 3D TOF in longer vascular segments. The sequential slice acquisition allows consistent inflow enhancement over the length of the neck vessels. 3D TOF is preferred for the intracranial circulation where vessels are smaller and flow velocities are higher.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 13, pp. 335-340"}, {"id": "PR-197", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "What is the standard dose of gadolinium-based contrast media for imaging of the central nervous system?", "options": ["1.0 mL/kg", "10 mL/kg", "1 mmol/kg", "0.1 mmol/kg"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The standard dose for gadolinium-based contrast agents in CNS imaging is 0.1 mmol/kg body weight. This is the FDA-approved dose for most GBCA products. At a typical concentration of 0.5 mmol/mL, this translates to 0.2 mL/kg. Higher doses (double or triple) were historically used for certain indications but are less common with modern high-relaxivity agents. Option A (1.0 mL/kg) and option C (1 mmol/kg) represent overdoses.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 370-372"}, {"id": "PR-198", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.15", "stem": "On coronal MRA images of the neck vasculature, where are the vertebral arteries located relative to the carotid arteries?", "options": ["Medial to the carotid arteries", "Superior to the carotid arteries", "Lateral to the carotid arteries", "Inferior to the carotid arteries"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The vertebral arteries course through the transverse foramina of the cervical vertebrae and are located medial (and posterior) to the common and internal carotid arteries when viewed on coronal images. The carotid arteries travel anterolaterally in the carotid sheath, while the vertebral arteries run along the vertebral column closer to midline. Understanding this spatial relationship is important for MRA interpretation and planning saturation bands.", "reference": "SA Ch. 5, pp. 280-300"}, {"id": "PR-199", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents are used in CNS imaging primarily because they improve detection of which of the following?", "options": ["Infection, infarction, and inflammation only", "Neoplasm only", "Any pathology that disrupts the blood-brain barrier", "Normal anatomic variants"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents enhance tissues where the blood-brain barrier (BBB) is disrupted, allowing the contrast to leak into the extracellular space. This includes infections (abscesses), infarctions (acute stage), inflammatory conditions (such as multiple sclerosis plaques), and neoplasms. The common denominator is BBB breakdown, not a single disease category. Normal brain parenchyma with an intact BBB does not enhance.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 370-375"}, {"id": "PR-200", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "What type of coil is most commonly used for MRI of the spine?", "options": ["Surface/local coil (phased array spine coil)", "Body coil", "Head coil", "Extremity coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Spine MRI is performed using a dedicated phased-array surface coil that is built into the table or placed beneath the patient. This coil provides high signal-to-noise ratio for the superficial spine structures while covering the necessary field of view. The body coil would provide inadequate SNR for the detailed evaluation required in spine imaging. Modern MRI systems use multi-element phased-array spine coils for optimal coverage and parallel imaging capability.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 380-385"}, {"id": "PR-201", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "In a patient who has undergone lumbar disk surgery, how does gadolinium-enhanced MRI help distinguish recurrent disk herniation from postoperative scar tissue?", "options": ["Scar tissue never enhances while recurrent disk always enhances", "Scar tissue enhances while recurrent disk does not enhance", "Recurrent disk enhances more slowly than scar tissue", "Neither scar tissue nor recurrent disk enhances"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "On gadolinium-enhanced MRI, postoperative scar tissue (epidural fibrosis) enhances rapidly and homogeneously because it is vascularized granulation tissue. Recurrent or residual disk material enhances only at its periphery and more slowly because the disk itself is relatively avascular. This differential enhancement pattern on early post-contrast imaging is the key to distinguishing these two entities. On delayed images, both may eventually enhance, reducing diagnostic accuracy.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 385-390"}, {"id": "PR-202", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "What is the optimal patient positioning and coil placement for cervical spine MRI?", "options": ["Supine with a surface coil positioned under the neck, covering C1 through C7", "Supine with a surface coil placed on top of the neck, covering C1 through C7", "Supine with a surface coil positioned beside the neck", "Prone with a surface coil placed on top of the neck"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Cervical spine MRI is performed with the patient supine using the phased-array spine coil elements built into the table beneath the neck, or with a dedicated cervical spine coil positioned under/around the neck. The coil must cover from the craniocervical junction (C1) through the cervicothoracic junction (C7-T1). Supine positioning provides patient comfort and reduces motion artifact. The coil is placed underneath (posterior to) the spine to be closest to the structures of interest.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 380-385"}, {"id": "PR-203", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When a sagittal thoracic spine image with a small field of view demonstrates cord compression, what is the best method for determining the exact vertebral level?", "options": ["Use the xiphoid process as a landmark and count superiorly from T12", "Use the sternal notch as a landmark and count inferiorly from T1", "Obtain a large field-of-view sagittal localizer and count vertebral levels inferiorly from C2", "Place radiopaque markers at T1 and T12 before scanning"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A large field-of-view sagittal localizer image that includes easily identifiable landmarks (such as C2, which is recognized by its odontoid process) is the most reliable method for determining thoracic vertebral levels. Counting down from C2 eliminates ambiguity from transitional vertebrae or anatomic variants. Surface landmarks like the xiphoid or sternal notch are unreliable for precise vertebral level identification due to body habitus variation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 382-385"}, {"id": "PR-204", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "On T1-weighted images of the spine, how does cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) appear relative to the spinal cord?", "options": ["Hyperintense (brighter than the cord)", "Hypointense (darker than the cord)", "Isointense (same signal as the cord)", "Variable depending on flow rate"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "CSF has a long T1 relaxation time and therefore appears hypointense (dark) on T1-weighted images. The spinal cord has an intermediate T1 value and appears relatively brighter than the surrounding CSF. This contrast relationship reverses on T2-weighted images, where CSF becomes hyperintense (bright) due to its long T2 relaxation time, creating the myelographic effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, pp. 30-35"}, {"id": "PR-205", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The conus medullaris and cauda equina can be visualized on all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Sagittal images of the cervical spine", "Sagittal images of the thoracic spine", "Sagittal images of the lumbar spine", "Coronal images of the thoracic spine"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The conus medullaris (terminal end of the spinal cord) typically lies at the L1-L2 level in adults, and the cauda equina extends below it. Sagittal images of the thoracic or lumbar spine and coronal images of the thoracolumbar region can all demonstrate these structures. Cervical spine sagittal images, however, do not extend inferiorly enough to include the conus, which is located in the thoracolumbar transition.", "reference": "SA Ch. 4, pp. 200-220"}, {"id": "PR-206", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Which of the following is an advantage of using 3D gradient echo axial imaging for the cervical spine?", "options": ["It provides thin contiguous sections that can be reformatted into other imaging planes", "It eliminates the need for any sagittal imaging", "It produces only T2-weighted contrast", "It requires longer scan times than 2D acquisitions with equivalent coverage"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "3D gradient echo sequences acquire a volume of thin, contiguous (or overlapping) slices that can be retrospectively reformatted into any imaging plane without loss of spatial resolution. This is particularly useful in cervical spine imaging for evaluating neural foramina and disk-osteophyte complexes. By adjusting TR, TE, and flip angle, the operator can produce T1-weighted, proton density-weighted, or T2*-weighted contrast.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 4, pp. 89-95; Ch. 15, pp. 380-385"}, {"id": "PR-207", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Neurological", "spec": "1.B.6", "stem": "When performing a complete spine MRI to evaluate for intramedullary spinal cord metastases, why is gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted imaging useful?", "options": ["Normal spinal cord enhances while metastatic lesions do not", "Metastatic lesions within the cord enhance while normal cord does not", "Scar tissue enhances while disk material does not", "CSF signal is suppressed after contrast administration"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Intramedullary spinal cord metastases enhance after gadolinium administration because the tumor disrupts the blood-spinal cord barrier, allowing contrast to leak into the lesion. Normal spinal cord maintains an intact blood-cord barrier and does not enhance. This differential enhancement makes gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted images essential for detecting intramedullary lesions that might be subtle on unenhanced sequences.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 385-390"}, {"id": "PR-208", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.A", "stem": "What technique is used to minimize pulsatile flow motion artifacts when performing cardiac MRI?", "options": ["Calculating the heart rate manually and entering it into the scanner", "Applying ECG leads and synchronizing data acquisition to the cardiac cycle", "Administering a sedative to reduce heart rate", "Using respiratory compensation only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cardiac gating (also called cardiac triggering) uses ECG leads to monitor the cardiac cycle in real time. The MRI system synchronizes data acquisition with the R-wave of the ECG, ensuring that data is collected during the same phase of the cardiac cycle for each repetition. This eliminates motion artifacts caused by cardiac pulsation. Simply knowing the heart rate is insufficient; the scan must be actively triggered from the cardiac signal.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, pp. 260-270"}, {"id": "PR-209", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B", "stem": "Iron oxide-based oral contrast agents used in abdominal MRI produce what signal characteristics on T1- and T2-weighted images?", "options": ["Hyperintense on both T1- and T2-weighted images", "Hypointense on both T1- and T2-weighted images", "Hyperintense on T1-weighted and hypointense on T2-weighted images", "Hypointense on T1-weighted and hyperintense on T2-weighted images"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Iron oxide particles are superparamagnetic and cause significant T2 and T2* shortening, producing signal loss (dark signal) on T2-weighted images. They also cause T1 shortening but the T2 effect dominates, so the bowel appears dark on both T1- and T2-weighted images, acting as a negative oral contrast agent. This helps distinguish bowel loops from enhancing pathology in the abdomen and pelvis.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 395-400"}, {"id": "PR-210", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.2", "stem": "Due to the oblique orientation and size of the pancreas, which imaging approach can potentially visualize the entire organ on a single slice?", "options": ["Coronal acquisition with thin slices", "Sagittal acquisition with thin slices", "Axial acquisition with thin slices", "Oblique acquisition with thick slices"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The pancreas lies obliquely across the retroperitoneum, with the head in the right upper quadrant and the tail extending toward the splenic hilum in the left upper quadrant. Because of this orientation, standard orthogonal planes cannot capture the entire organ in a single slice. An oblique axial or oblique coronal plane prescribed along the long axis of the pancreas, combined with slightly thicker slices, can capture the entire gland. Thin coronal or axial slices would only show portions of the pancreas per slice.", "reference": "SA Ch. 7, pp. 430-445"}, {"id": "PR-211", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B.1", "stem": "On T2-weighted MR images, how do hepatic hemangiomas typically appear relative to normal liver parenchyma?", "options": ["Hyperintense", "Hypointense", "Isointense", "Signal void"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Hepatic hemangiomas are benign vascular tumors composed of blood-filled sinusoidal spaces. Their high water content produces markedly prolonged T2 relaxation times, causing them to appear very bright (hyperintense) on T2-weighted images, often described as having a light bulb sign. This characteristic T2 hyperintensity helps differentiate hemangiomas from malignant lesions, which typically have less dramatic T2 prolongation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 395-400"}, {"id": "PR-212", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.B", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT an appropriate patient position for abdominal MRI?", "options": ["Supine, head-first within the head coil", "Supine, head-first with a torso phased-array coil", "Supine, feet-first with a torso phased-array coil", "Prone, feet-first with a torso phased-array coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Abdominal MRI requires a torso phased-array coil to provide adequate coverage and signal-to-noise ratio for the abdominal region. The head coil is designed for cranial imaging and is far too small to accommodate the abdomen. Patients can be positioned supine or prone, head-first or feet-first, depending on the clinical indication and scanner configuration. The torso array coil is placed over the anterior abdomen in supine or posterior abdomen in prone.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 390-395"}, {"id": "PR-213", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.C.2", "stem": "Which imaging plane is considered best for initial evaluation of the uterus on pelvic MRI?", "options": ["Sagittal", "Axial", "Coronal", "Oblique"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The sagittal plane is the primary imaging plane for uterine evaluation because it displays the uterus in its natural orientation along the long axis, showing the endometrial canal, myometrium, and cervix in continuity. This plane also demonstrates the relationship of the uterus to the bladder anteriorly and rectum posteriorly. Additional oblique planes perpendicular to the long axis of the uterus are often prescribed from the sagittal images.", "reference": "SA Ch. 8, pp. 510-530"}, {"id": "PR-214", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Body", "spec": "2.C.2", "stem": "Which imaging plane is considered best for evaluation of the ovaries on pelvic MRI?", "options": ["Sagittal", "Axial", "Coronal", "Oblique"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Coronal images provide excellent visualization of the ovaries because the ovaries lie in the ovarian fossae along the lateral pelvic sidewalls. The coronal plane displays both ovaries simultaneously, allowing side-to-side comparison of size and morphology. Axial images also contribute to ovarian evaluation, but the coronal plane is generally preferred for initial assessment. Sagittal images are more useful for midline structures like the uterus.", "reference": "SA Ch. 8, pp. 510-530"}, {"id": "PR-215", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.R", "stem": "When performing peripheral MRA to evaluate arterial flow in the lower extremities, where should saturation pulses be placed relative to the acquired slices?", "options": ["Superior to the acquired slices", "Within the acquired slices", "Inferior to the acquired slices", "Saturation pulses are not necessary for peripheral MRA"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In lower extremity arterial MRA using time-of-flight technique, a saturation band is placed inferior to (downstream from) the imaging slices to suppress venous return flow from the feet traveling superiorly. Since arterial flow in the legs travels from superior to inferior, it enters the slices as fresh unsaturated spins and produces bright signal. The inferior saturation pulse eliminates the signal from ascending venous blood, providing clean arterial-only images.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 13, pp. 335-345"}, {"id": "PR-216", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3", "stem": "Because most joints in the body are oriented obliquely, MR imaging of joints is typically performed in which plane?", "options": ["Sagittal", "Axial", "Coronal", "Oblique"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Joints such as the shoulder, knee, wrist, and ankle are not perfectly aligned with the standard orthogonal planes of the body. To accurately demonstrate joint anatomy including ligaments, tendons, and cartilage, imaging planes must be prescribed obliquely, aligned to the specific anatomic axes of each joint. For example, shoulder imaging uses oblique coronal and oblique sagittal planes aligned to the supraspinatus tendon, and knee imaging uses oblique sagittal planes aligned to the ACL.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 15, pp. 400-410"}, {"id": "PR-217", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.L", "stem": "What is the recommended foot position when imaging the hip joints on MRI?", "options": ["Externally rotated", "Internally rotated", "Neutral position", "Rotated toward the hip of interest"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Internal rotation of the feet (approximately 15-20 degrees) is the standard positioning for hip MRI because it places the femoral neck parallel to the coronal imaging plane. This corrects for the natural anteversion of the femoral neck and allows true coronal images to display the femoral neck in its full length without foreshortening. External rotation would exaggerate the anteversion and foreshorten the femoral neck on coronal images.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 12, pp. 220-225"}, {"id": "PR-218", "domain": "Procedures", "subcategory": "Musculoskeletal", "spec": "3.N", "stem": "When evaluating the anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) of the knee, what is the recommended foot positioning?", "options": ["Externally rotated approximately 15-20 degrees", "Internally rotated approximately 15-20 degrees", "Neutral position", "Plantarflexed"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "External rotation of the foot (approximately 15-20 degrees) aligns the ACL with the sagittal imaging plane, allowing visualization of the ligament in its full length on a single sagittal image. The ACL courses from the posterior lateral femoral condyle to the anterior tibial plateau in an oblique orientation; slight external rotation brings the ligament into the sagittal plane. Without this positioning, the ACL may appear truncated across multiple slices.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 14, pp. 250-255"}, {"id": "SA-001", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.b", "stem": "A substance classified as diamagnetic:", "options": ["is highly susceptible to the external magnetic field", "contains some materials that interact with the magnetic field", "contains no unpaired electrons and weakly opposes the external magnetic field", "strongly repels the magnetic field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Diamagnetic substances contain no unpaired electrons and weakly oppose the external magnetic field, producing a very small negative susceptibility. Most biological tissues are diamagnetic. Option a describes ferromagnetic materials, which are highly susceptible and strongly attracted to the field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4"}, {"id": "SA-002", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.b", "stem": "Which statement about paramagnetic materials is correct?", "options": ["They include gadolinium-based contrast agents", "The entire magnetic moment of the substance aligns with the external field", "They display no measurable magnetic attraction", "They exhibit the strongest magnetic attraction of all material types"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Paramagnetic materials contain unpaired electrons that weakly align with the external magnetic field, producing a small positive susceptibility. Gadolinium-based contrast agents are paramagnetic, which is the basis of their T1-shortening effect in MRI. Option d is incorrect because ferromagnetic materials, not paramagnetic, exhibit the strongest magnetic attraction.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4"}, {"id": "SA-003", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.b", "stem": "Ferromagnetic substances, when exposed to a magnetic field, are strongly attracted and:", "options": ["lose all magnetization immediately upon removal from the field", "remain permanently magnetized after removal from the field", "become mildly attracted but quickly return to a neutral state", "are repelled once the field exceeds a critical threshold"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Ferromagnetic substances are strongly attracted to an external magnetic field and retain their magnetization after removal from the field. This permanent magnetization is due to the alignment of magnetic domains within the material. Option a is incorrect because ferromagnetic materials do not lose their magnetization immediately — they retain residual magnetism.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4 | MIP Ch. 10, p. 347"}, {"id": "SA-004", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "The perimeter around the MRI scanner that defines where the static magnetic field strength may pose a hazard to individuals with ferromagnetic implants is known as the:", "options": ["1.5 T circle", "3.0 T line", "3-gauss circle", "5-gauss line"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The 5-gauss line defines the perimeter around the MRI scanner where the static magnetic field strength may pose a hazard to individuals with ferromagnetic implants such as pacemakers. This boundary is used for safety zoning and access restriction. The 3-gauss circle (option c) is not the standard safety perimeter designation used in current MR safety guidelines.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351 | ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-005", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1.f", "stem": "According to current FDA guidelines, adults may be scanned in a static magnetic field strength of up to:", "options": ["1.5 T", "3.0 T", "8.0 T", "11 T"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "According to current FDA guidelines, adults may be scanned in a static magnetic field strength of up to 8.0 T for clinical imaging under the non-significant risk category. Fields above this level require specific safety protocols and institutional review. Option b (3.0 T) represents the most commonly used high-field clinical strength but is not the FDA upper limit.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 346 | ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-006", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "The magnetic fringe field surrounding an MRI scanner extends:", "options": ["only horizontally, parallel to the bore axis", "in three dimensions including above, below, and to the sides of the magnet", "only within the scan room due to RF shielding", "exclusively in the direction of the patient bore opening"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The magnetic fringe field surrounding an MRI scanner extends in three dimensions — above, below, and to all sides of the magnet — not just along the bore axis. This is why safety zones must account for areas above and below the scanner room. Option a is incorrect because the field extends omnidirectionally, not just horizontally.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-007", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "In a well-documented 2001 MRI accident, which ferromagnetic object became a projectile that struck and killed a child in the scanner room?", "options": ["A set of surgical forceps", "An oxygen tank", "A wheelchair", "An emergency crash cart"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In a well-documented 2001 MRI accident, a ferromagnetic oxygen tank became a projectile when brought into the scanner room, striking and killing a child. This tragic event highlighted the extreme danger of ferromagnetic objects near the MRI magnet and led to significant improvements in MR safety protocols. Surgical forceps (option a) are too small to generate the projectile force involved in this incident.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 346 | ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-008", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "As a ferromagnetic object is moved closer to the bore of a superconducting MRI magnet, the translational force acting on the object:", "options": ["increases slightly in a linear fashion", "increases exponentially", "decreases slightly", "stops suddenly at a fixed distance"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "As a ferromagnetic object moves closer to the bore of a superconducting MRI magnet, the translational force increases exponentially due to the steep spatial gradient of the magnetic field near the bore entrance. This exponential increase makes the last few feet before the bore opening the most dangerous zone. A linear increase (option a) significantly underestimates the danger.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-009", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Compared to imaging modalities that use ionizing radiation, MRI is considered safer because it employs:", "options": ["lower-energy X-rays", "targeted gamma radiation", "non-ionizing radiofrequency energy and magnetic fields", "filtered CT radiation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI is considered safer than ionizing radiation modalities because it employs non-ionizing radiofrequency energy and magnetic fields rather than X-rays or gamma radiation. Non-ionizing radiation does not have sufficient energy to remove electrons from atoms or break chemical bonds in DNA. Option a is incorrect because MRI does not use X-rays of any energy level.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-010", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "The specific absorption rate (SAR) averaged over the entire body or over a small sample volume is known as:", "options": ["specific absorption rate", "global SAR or local SAR respectively", "RF absorption rate", "total RF absorption rate"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SAR (specific absorption rate) averaged over the entire body is termed global SAR, while SAR averaged over a small sample volume (typically 10 grams of tissue) is termed local SAR. Both metrics are used to ensure RF energy deposition remains within safe limits during MRI scanning. Option a simply restates the term without distinguishing the two measurement types.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-011", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "Patients with high blood pressure, certain cardiac conditions, and diabetes are at increased risk from sudden body temperature elevation caused by RF energy because these conditions impair:", "options": ["the body's ability to thermoregulate", "the gradient coil cooling system", "the patient's ability to remain still during scanning", "the accuracy of the SAR calculation by the scanner"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Patients with high blood pressure, cardiac conditions, and diabetes are at increased risk from RF-induced heating because these conditions impair the body's ability to thermoregulate (dissipate heat through vasodilation and sweating). Compromised thermoregulation means RF energy deposition can cause dangerous core temperature elevation. Option b is incorrect because these conditions affect the patient's physiology, not the scanner's cooling system.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-012", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "MR-approved ECG leads are typically constructed from which material to help prevent thermal burns?", "options": ["Carbon fiber or non-ferromagnetic conductive materials", "Nickel", "Titanium", "Aluminum"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "MR-approved ECG leads are constructed from carbon fiber or other non-ferromagnetic conductive materials to minimize RF-induced heating and prevent thermal burns. Traditional metallic leads can act as antennas in the RF field, concentrating energy at the lead tips. Nickel (option b) is ferromagnetic and would pose both projectile and heating risks in the MR environment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357 | ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-013", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "Stainless steel body piercing jewelry in the MRI environment:", "options": ["is strongly attracted to the magnetic field and can cause burns", "is generally not attracted to the field but can cause RF-induced heating", "is easily rotated by the field but cannot heat up", "is both strongly attracted and prone to heating"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Most stainless steel body piercing jewelry is not strongly attracted to the magnetic field (as austenitic stainless steel is non-ferromagnetic), but it can cause RF-induced heating because any conductive material in the RF field can act as an antenna and concentrate energy locally. Option a is incorrect because standard body piercing jewelry is typically made from non-ferromagnetic stainless steel grades.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357 | ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-014", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "The time-varying gradient magnetic fields have the potential to stimulate a patient's:", "options": ["visual cortex", "auditory acuity", "peripheral nerves", "oral reflexes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The rapidly switching time-varying gradient magnetic fields can induce electrical currents in the patient's body sufficient to stimulate peripheral nerves, causing tingling, twitching, or in extreme cases, painful stimulation. This is known as peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS). The visual cortex (option a) can experience magnetophosphenes from the static field, but direct stimulation from gradients primarily affects peripheral nerves.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-015", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1.c", "stem": "If a patient experiences the magnetohemodynamic effect while inside the MRI scanner, what happens to the cardiac cycle once the patient is removed from the static field?", "options": ["The heart suddenly stops", "Blood pressure drops precipitously", "Blood velocity continues to rise", "The cardiac cycle returns to normal"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The magnetohemodynamic effect occurs when the static magnetic field interacts with flowing blood (a conductive fluid), inducing a voltage across blood vessels that can cause T-wave elevation on ECG. This effect is reversible — once the patient is removed from the static field, the cardiac cycle returns to normal because the induced voltage ceases. Option a is incorrect because the heart does not stop; the effect is merely an electrical artifact.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-016", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "According to the ACR safety framework, which zone contains the actual MRI scanner?", "options": ["Zone I", "Zone II", "Zone III", "Zone IV"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "According to the ACR safety framework, Zone IV is defined as the physical confines of the room in which the MR scanner is located (the scan room itself). Access to Zone IV is the most restricted and requires the highest level of safety screening. Zone I (option a) encompasses all areas freely accessible to the general public outside the MR facility.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-017", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.6", "stem": "According to ACR safety guidelines, Level 1 MR personnel have:", "options": ["no formal safety training", "completed basic MR safety education sufficient to ensure their own safety in the MR environment", "been thoroughly trained and can independently manage all safety zones", "extensive training with full supervisory authority over Zone IV"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Level 1 MR personnel have completed basic MR safety education sufficient to ensure their own safety when working within the MR environment. They can safely enter Zone III but are not independently authorized to manage all safety zones. Level 2 personnel (not described in option c) have more comprehensive training and can supervise non-MR personnel entering restricted zones.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-018", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.a", "stem": "Ideally, MR patients should undergo safety screening how many times before entering the scanner?", "options": ["Once", "Twice", "Three times", "Five times"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Ideally, MR patients should undergo safety screening three times before entering the scanner: during scheduling or ordering, upon arrival at the MR facility, and immediately before entering the scan room (Zone IV). This redundant screening process helps catch any safety concerns that may have been missed in earlier screenings. Screening only once (option a) provides insufficient safety verification.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-019", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "If a patient experiences claustrophobia, pre-examination anxiolytic medication should be discussed with the:", "options": ["MR scheduler", "MR technologist", "radiologist", "referring physician"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "If a patient experiences claustrophobia and may benefit from pre-examination anxiolytic medication, this should be discussed with the referring physician who has the authority to prescribe medication and knowledge of the patient's medical history. The MR technologist (option b) does not have prescribing authority and should not independently determine medication needs.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-020", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.6", "stem": "The final safety screening of a patient before entering the MR scanner should be performed by:", "options": ["any available MR staff member", "Level 2 MR personnel who have been trained in MR safety", "MR managers only", "radiologists only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The final safety screening of a patient before entering the MR scanner should be performed by Level 2 MR personnel who have been thoroughly trained in MR safety and can make informed decisions about patient screening, implant compatibility, and emergency procedures. Option a is incorrect because not all MR staff members have the required Level 2 training for final screening authority.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-021", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.a", "stem": "Regarding parents or guardians who accompany pediatric patients into the MR scan room:", "options": ["They are exempt from safety screening since they are not being scanned", "They must undergo the same complete safety screening process as any person entering Zone IV", "They only need to remove jewelry and watches", "They are screened only if the scanner is actively operating"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Parents or guardians who accompany pediatric patients into the MR scan room must undergo the same complete safety screening process as any person entering Zone IV. They are exposed to the same magnetic field hazards as the patient, and any ferromagnetic objects they carry could become projectiles. Option a is incorrect — being a non-patient does not exempt anyone from safety screening.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-022", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.b", "stem": "Ferromagnetic aneurysm clips within the MRI environment are subject to:", "options": ["both torque and RF-induced thermal heating", "torque only, with no thermal effects", "thermal heating only, with no translational force", "no significant interaction with the magnetic field"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Ferromagnetic aneurysm clips in the MRI environment are subject to both torque (rotational force from the magnetic field attempting to align the clip with B0) and RF-induced thermal heating (the metallic clip can act as an antenna concentrating RF energy). Both effects pose serious risks including clip migration and tissue damage. Option b is incorrect because thermal heating is a significant concern in addition to torque.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 347"}, {"id": "SA-023", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which statement about gadolinium-based contrast agents and pregnant patients is NOT true?", "options": ["The decision to administer contrast should be handled on a case-by-case basis", "Studies have confirmed that gadolinium cannot cross the placenta into fetal circulation", "Any contrast reaching the fetus is excreted into the amniotic fluid", "Written informed consent should be obtained from any pregnant patient undergoing contrast-enhanced MRI"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The statement that gadolinium cannot cross the placenta is NOT true — studies have demonstrated that gadolinium-based contrast agents do cross the placenta into fetal circulation. Once in the fetus, the contrast is excreted into the amniotic fluid where it can remain for extended periods. Options a, c, and d are all true statements regarding gadolinium use in pregnancy.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "SA-024", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "If a patient experiences a medical emergency while inside the MRI scanner, the technologist should:", "options": ["Leave the patient on the table to avoid further harm", "Remove the patient from the bore but keep them in the scan room and begin CPR", "Remove the patient from the scan room on an MR-conditional stretcher to a designated safe area before beginning lifesaving procedures", "Immediately transfer the patient to the emergency department without intervention"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "If a patient experiences a medical emergency while inside the MRI scanner, the technologist should remove the patient from the scan room on an MR-conditional stretcher to a designated safe area before beginning lifesaving procedures. This ensures that emergency responders and equipment (crash cart, defibrillator) are not exposed to the magnetic field. Option b is incorrect because performing CPR inside the scan room prevents use of standard emergency equipment and puts responders at risk.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-025", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "During an uncontrolled quench, a patient remaining inside the scanner is at risk for frostbite from escaping cryogen, tympanic membrane rupture from rapid pressure changes, and:", "options": ["peripheral nerve stimulation", "asphyxiation from oxygen displacement by helium gas", "RF-induced thermal burns", "projectile injury from loose equipment"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "During an uncontrolled quench, the rapidly boiling liquid helium expands to approximately 760 times its liquid volume as gas, which can displace oxygen in the scan room and cause asphyxiation. Combined with the risk of frostbite from escaping cryogen and tympanic membrane rupture from pressure changes, these constitute the primary quench hazards. Peripheral nerve stimulation (option a) is related to gradient fields, not cryogen release.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 365"}, {"id": "SA-031", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "According to the ACR safety framework, Zone IV is defined as:", "options": ["all areas freely accessible to the general public", "the region where free access by unscreened personnel can result in serious injury or death", "the interface between publicly accessible and strictly controlled zones", "the physical confines of the room in which the MR scanner is located"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Zone IV is defined as the physical confines of the room in which the MR scanner is located. It requires the highest level of access restriction and safety screening. All persons entering Zone IV must be screened by Level 2 MR personnel. Option b describes Zone III, where unscreened personnel could potentially experience injury.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-032", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Items classified as MR Safe are those that:", "options": ["are entirely non-metallic and non-conductive, posing no known hazards in any MR environment", "include standard surgical clips", "include ferromagnetic scissors designed for the OR", "include routing leads used for neurostimulation systems"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Items classified as MR Safe are entirely non-metallic, non-conductive, and non-magnetic, posing no known hazards in any MR environment regardless of field strength. This is the most restrictive safety classification under the ASTM labeling system. Standard surgical clips (option b) are typically classified as MR Conditional or MR Unsafe, not MR Safe.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-033", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1.a", "stem": "Some patients may experience vertigo when positioned at the isocenter of the magnet. Normal vestibular function typically returns within approximately how many minutes after removal from the field?", "options": ["5", "7", "15", "20"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Some patients experience vertigo when positioned at the isocenter of the magnet due to the interaction of the static magnetic field with the vestibular apparatus (particularly the semicircular canals). Normal vestibular function typically returns within approximately 15 minutes after removal from the field. Option a (5 minutes) may be insufficient for complete resolution in some patients.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-034", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.b", "stem": "Implanted devices such as cardiac pacemakers, implantable defibrillators, and aneurysm clips may all contain ferromagnetic components that interact with the external magnetic field. Which screening step is essential before scanning any patient with an implant?", "options": ["Verifying the device manufacturer, model, and MR labeling status", "Obtaining a chest X-ray to confirm device location", "Performing a test scan at low field strength first", "Consulting the FDA MAUDE database for adverse event reports"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The essential screening step before scanning any patient with an implanted device is verifying the specific manufacturer, model number, and MR labeling status (MR Safe, MR Conditional, or MR Unsafe) of the device. Different models from the same manufacturer may have different MR compatibility, making specific identification critical. A chest X-ray (option b) can confirm device location but does not determine MR compatibility.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-026", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "In the first-level controlled operating mode, the maximum allowable core body temperature rise should not exceed:", "options": ["25 degrees C", "1 degree C above 37 degrees C (total 38 degrees C)", "49 degrees C", "52 degrees C"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "In the first-level controlled operating mode, the maximum allowable core body temperature rise should not exceed 1 degree Celsius above the normal 37 degrees C, for a total of 38 degrees C. This limit protects patients from potentially dangerous hyperthermia caused by RF energy absorption. Option a (25 degrees C) is not a body temperature metric but an ambient temperature value.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-027", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2.a", "stem": "To reduce RF energy deposition (SAR) in a patient, a technologist can use a different receive coil, and also:", "options": ["decrease the number of slices and decrease the TR", "increase the number of slices", "increase the TR", "increase the flip angle and decrease the TR"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing the TR reduces SAR because it allows more time between RF excitation pulses, decreasing the average rate of RF energy deposition per unit time. Using a different receive coil can also reduce SAR if it requires less transmitted RF power. Decreasing the TR (options a, d) would increase the pulse repetition rate and therefore increase SAR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-035", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1.b", "stem": "Modern MR Conditional pacemaker designs have addressed MRI compatibility concerns by replacing the reed switch with a digital transducer, reducing ferromagnetic components, and:", "options": ["eliminating all metallic components entirely", "using only titanium housings", "modifying lead designs to reduce RF-induced heating", "limiting use to 0.5 T systems only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Modern MR Conditional pacemaker designs have addressed MRI compatibility by replacing the reed switch with a digital transducer (less susceptible to magnetic field effects), reducing ferromagnetic components, and modifying lead designs to reduce RF-induced heating at the electrode tips. Lead modifications include shorter lead lengths, altered lead geometries, and improved insulation. Eliminating all metallic components (option a) is not feasible for a functioning pacemaker.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-036", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3.c", "stem": "The parameter that defines the minimum current amplitude required to stimulate biological tissue at very long pulse durations is known as the:", "options": ["chronaxie value", "rheobase", "relative permittivity", "quench threshold"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The rheobase is defined as the minimum current amplitude required to stimulate biological tissue at very long (essentially infinite) pulse durations. It represents the threshold below which no amount of time will cause stimulation. The chronaxie value (option b) is the pulse duration at which the threshold current is twice the rheobase — a related but distinct parameter.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-028", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3.b", "stem": "The acoustic noise level within the bore of a 1.5 T MRI scanner during operation is approximately:", "options": ["20 dB", "100 dB", "125 dB", "170 dB"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The acoustic noise level within the bore of a 1.5 T MRI scanner during operation is approximately 100 dB, which is comparable to a jackhammer or chainsaw. This noise is generated by the rapid switching of gradient coils against the static magnetic field (Lorentz forces). At this level, hearing protection is mandatory for all patients. Option a (20 dB) represents a whisper, far below actual scanner noise levels.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-037", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Safety concerns associated with the use of cryogens in MRI include asphyxiation from oxygen displacement, potential for explosion due to rapid gas expansion, and:", "options": ["radiofrequency interference", "peripheral nerve stimulation", "cryogenic burns (frostbite) from contact with escaping liquid helium", "projectile hazard from gradient coil failure"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In addition to asphyxiation from oxygen displacement and the potential for explosion from rapid gas expansion, cryogenic burns (frostbite) from contact with escaping liquid helium are a significant safety concern. Liquid helium at approximately 4 Kelvin (-269 degrees C) causes immediate tissue damage on contact. Peripheral nerve stimulation (option b) is caused by gradient fields, not cryogen exposure.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 365"}, {"id": "SA-029", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "The highly pressurized double container that stores liquid helium in a superconducting MRI system, consisting of an inner chamber separated from an outer shell by an evacuated space, is called a:", "options": ["cryostat", "cold head", "dewar", "cryogenic agent"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A dewar is the highly pressurized double-walled container that stores liquid helium in a superconducting MRI system. It consists of an inner chamber separated from an outer shell by an evacuated (vacuum) space that provides thermal insulation. The cryostat (option a) is the broader term for the entire cooling system assembly, while the dewar is specifically the storage vessel.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "SA-030", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "A fully filled MRI cryostat may contain over how many liters of liquid helium?", "options": ["1,200", "1,600", "1,800", "2,000"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A fully filled MRI cryostat may contain over 1,600 liters of liquid helium, which maintains the superconducting magnet coils at approximately 4 Kelvin (-269 degrees C). During a quench, this volume of liquid helium can expand to over 1.2 million liters of gas, creating significant asphyxiation and pressure hazards. Option a (1,200 liters) underestimates the typical volume.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9, p. 318"}, {"id": "SA-038", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "According to the ACR White Paper on MR Safety, which zone is designated as the \"control area\" requiring completed screening verification before entry?", "options": ["Zone I (public access)", "Zone II (interface between public and controlled areas)", "Zone III (restricted access, screening required)", "Zone IV (scanner room)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Zone III is the restricted interface between public areas and the magnet room (Zone IV). All individuals must complete MRI safety screening before entering Zone III, which serves as the final checkpoint to prevent ferromagnetic objects and unscreened individuals from reaching the scanner.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-039", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When screening a patient with a passive implant, the technologist must identify:", "options": ["Only the name of the device", "The manufacturer, model number, and year of implantation", "The surgeon's name and hospital where it was placed", "Only the hospital where the device was implanted"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Precise device identification (manufacturer, model, and implant date) is required to determine the device's MR safety status (MR Safe, MR Conditional, or MR Unsafe) by cross-referencing with the manufacturer's documentation or databases such as MRIsafety.com.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-040", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "An implant labeled with a green square according to ASTM International standards is classified as:", "options": ["Untested for MRI safety", "MR Safe — non-conducting, non-metallic, and non-magnetic", "MR Safe only at 1.5T field strength", "MR Conditional"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The green square indicates MR Safe status under the ASTM International labeling system. MR Safe items pose no known hazards in any MRI environment because they contain no metallic, conducting, or magnetic components. Examples include plastic surgical clips and certain ceramic implants.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-041", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "An implant labeled with a yellow triangle according to ASTM International standards is classified as:", "options": ["MR Safe for all patients and field strengths", "MR Conditional — safe only under specific documented conditions", "MR Unsafe under all circumstances", "Made entirely of non-metallic materials"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The yellow triangle indicates MR Conditional status. These devices have been tested and found safe only under specific conditions such as field strength, SAR limits, gradient slew rate, and spatial gradient. All stated conditions must be met exactly to prevent patient injury.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-042", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "An object labeled with a red circle and diagonal slash according to ASTM International standards must:", "options": ["Be stored in Zone III only", "Never enter the scanner room (Zone IV)", "Be scanned with caution at reduced SAR", "Be covered with non-conductive material before scanning"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The red circle with diagonal slash indicates MR Unsafe status. These objects pose a definite hazard in all MRI environments and must never be brought into Zone IV. Examples include standard ferromagnetic oxygen tanks, scissors, and most conventional pacemakers.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-043", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The \"projectile effect\" (missile effect) is caused by which magnetic field?", "options": ["The gradient (time-varying) field", "The radiofrequency (RF) field", "The static magnetic field (B0)", "The shim field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The static magnetic field (B0) exerts a constant attractive force on ferromagnetic objects, pulling them toward the bore with potentially lethal velocity. The force is proportional to the product of the field strength and the spatial field gradient (B × dB/dx). This translational force is strongest at the bore entrance where the spatial gradient is greatest.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-044", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The FDA limit for static magnetic field (B0) exposure in clinical MRI for adults and children older than one month is:", "options": ["1.5 T", "3.0 T", "8.0 T", "4.0 T"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FDA has established 8.0 T as the upper limit for clinical MRI in adults and children older than one month of age. For neonates (under one month), the limit is 4.0 T. Systems operating above these thresholds require an investigational device exemption (IDE).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-045", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The primary biological effect of radiofrequency (RF) energy deposition in MRI is:", "options": ["Hearing loss", "Tissue heating (thermal effects)", "Visual flashing (phosphenes)", "Peripheral nerve stimulation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF energy is absorbed by tissue and converted to heat. The Specific Absorption Rate (SAR) quantifies this energy deposition in watts per kilogram (W/kg). Tissues with poor perfusion (such as the eyes and testes) are most vulnerable because they cannot efficiently dissipate heat. Hearing loss and PNS are effects of the gradient field.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-046", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "To prevent RF-induced thermal burns during MRI, the technologist must ensure:", "options": ["The patient holds their breath during all sequences", "No skin-to-bore contact and no conductive loops are formed by cables or limbs", "The scan room temperature is below 60°F", "The ventilation fan is turned off during scanning"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF burns occur when conductive loops are formed — either by patient limbs touching each other, skin contacting the bore wall, or cables crossing. These loops allow induced currents to concentrate and generate focal heating. Padding should be placed between the patient and the bore, and cables should be routed without forming loops.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-047", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The IEC/FDA limit for whole-body Specific Absorption Rate (SAR) in Normal Operating Mode is:", "options": ["4.0 W/kg", "2.0 W/kg", "3.2 W/kg", "0.4 W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Normal Operating Mode SAR limit of 2.0 W/kg restricts the core body temperature rise to approximately 0.5°C. The First Level Controlled Mode allows up to 4.0 W/kg but requires medical supervision and positive operator acknowledgment due to the increased risk of thermal injury.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-048", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The primary biological effect of time-varying magnetic fields (gradient fields) is:", "options": ["Tissue heating", "Peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS)", "Oxygen displacement", "Cataract formation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rapidly switching gradient fields induce electrical voltages in conductive tissues (nerves and muscles), which can cause peripheral nerve stimulation manifesting as tingling, twitching, or muscle contractions. The threshold depends on the rate of field change (dB/dt) and is monitored by the scanner to stay within FDA limits.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-049", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Magnetophosphenes (perceived flashing lights) during MRI are caused by stimulation of the:", "options": ["Auditory nerve", "Retina", "Skin", "Cardiac muscle"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magnetophosphenes are visual sensations (\"seeing stars\" or flashes) caused by gradient-induced electrical stimulation of the retina. They are harmless and reversible but serve as an indicator that the patient is approaching the PNS threshold. They can also occur with rapid head movement through the static field.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-050", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The loud knocking or banging noise produced during MRI scanning is caused by:", "options": ["The cryogen pump cycling", "Lorentz forces vibrating the gradient coils", "The RF transmitter firing", "The patient table motor engaging"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When current flows through the gradient coils in the presence of the strong static magnetic field, Lorentz forces cause the coils to vibrate rapidly, producing the characteristic loud acoustic noise. Sound levels can exceed 100 dB, making hearing protection mandatory for all patients and anyone in Zone IV during scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-051", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The FDA limit for acoustic noise exposure in MRI without hearing protection is:", "options": ["140 dB", "99 dB", "85 dB", "60 dB"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The FDA limits MRI acoustic noise to 99 dB(A) without hearing protection. Since most clinical sequences exceed this level (especially at 3T), hearing protection — earplugs, headphones, or both — is standard for all patients. Repeated unprotected exposure can cause permanent sensorineural hearing loss.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-052", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which implanted device is generally considered an absolute contraindication to MRI unless specifically verified as MR Conditional?", "options": ["Titanium hip replacement", "Legacy (non-MR Conditional) cardiac pacemaker or ICD", "Coronary artery stent", "Dental amalgam filling"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Legacy cardiac pacemakers and implantable cardioverter-defibrillators (ICDs) that have not been tested or labeled as MR Conditional pose potentially lethal risks including lead heating, device malfunction, and inappropriate shock delivery. Specific MR Conditional pacemaker systems exist but require strict protocol adherence.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-053", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A patient with a cochlear implant is generally:", "options": ["Safe for MRI at any field strength", "Contraindicated unless the specific model has been verified as MR Conditional", "Safe only at 3T", "Safe if earplugs are worn"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cochlear implants contain internal magnets and electronic components that can experience torque, demagnetization, and heating in the MRI environment. Some newer models are MR Conditional with specific restrictions (field strength, head positioning, magnet removal). The device must be positively identified before scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-054", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The most reliable method for screening a patient with a history of metalworking for intraocular ferrous foreign bodies is:", "options": ["Asking the patient directly", "Orbital X-ray or CT scan", "Using a handheld magnet near the eyes", "Screening with a metal-detection wand"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Orbital radiographs (or CT) are the gold standard for detecting intraocular metallic foreign bodies in patients with occupational exposure to metal grinding, welding, or machining. Even small ferrous fragments in the eye can move in the magnetic field, causing retinal damage or blindness. Patient history alone is insufficient.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-055", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "Transdermal medication patches with metallic foil backings can cause which hazard during MRI?", "options": ["Image artifacts only", "Thermal burns at the patch site", "Magnet quench", "Motion blur"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Metallic foil backings on transdermal patches (such as certain nicotine and fentanyl patches) can act as conductors, concentrating RF energy and causing focal thermal burns. These patches must be identified during screening and removed or replaced with non-metallic alternatives before scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-056", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "Iron oxide pigments in tattoos or permanent cosmetics can cause which effect during MRI?", "options": ["Localized heating and swelling at the tattoo site", "The tattoo becoming a projectile hazard", "Complete signal loss throughout the image", "No effect on the patient or image"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Iron oxide pigments in tattoos and permanent cosmetics can interact with the RF field, causing localized heating, swelling, and skin irritation. The risk is generally low but increases with large tattoos, high-SAR sequences, and proximity to the RF coil. Cold compresses should be applied if the patient reports warmth or discomfort at the tattoo site.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-057", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.6", "stem": "\"Level 2 MR Personnel\" are defined as individuals who:", "options": ["Work in the front office and schedule appointments", "Have received extensive training in MR safety and are authorized to supervise others in Zone IV", "Are patients who have been screened for MRI", "Perform cleaning and maintenance in the MRI suite"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Level 2 MR Personnel (such as MRI technologists and radiologists) have undergone comprehensive MR safety training and are authorized to independently access Zones III and IV. They are also qualified to screen and supervise non-MR personnel and Level 1 personnel who need access to restricted zones.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-058", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "During a magnet quench, which gas is rapidly released from the cryostat?", "options": ["Nitrogen", "Helium", "Oxygen", "Hydrogen"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Modern superconducting MRI magnets use liquid helium to maintain the superconducting coils near absolute zero (−4.2 K / −269°C). During a quench, the coils lose superconductivity and the liquid helium rapidly boils off into a large volume of gas. One liter of liquid helium expands to approximately 760 liters of gas.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-059", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "The immediate life-threatening risk to occupants during a magnet quench is:", "options": ["Fire from electrical discharge", "Asphyxiation due to oxygen displacement by helium gas", "Electrical shock", "Ionizing radiation exposure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Released helium gas displaces oxygen in the scan room, creating an oxygen-deficient atmosphere. Normal air contains approximately 21% oxygen; levels below 19.5% are considered dangerous, and levels below 16% can cause loss of consciousness. Room oxygen monitors should trigger an alarm when levels drop below 19.5%.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-060", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "If the MRI scan room humidity drops below approximately 30%, it increases the risk of:", "options": ["Electrostatic discharge (ESD) and image artifacts", "Condensation on the magnet bore", "RF shielding leaks", "Spontaneous quench"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Low humidity increases static electricity buildup, which can damage sensitive electronic components and cause image artifacts. Conversely, excessively high humidity can cause condensation on cold surfaces. The recommended scan room humidity is typically maintained between 40–60% relative humidity.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-061", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "The recommended ambient temperature for the MRI scan room is typically:", "options": ["50–60°F (10–16°C)", "65–75°F (18–24°C)", "80–90°F (27–32°C)", "Below freezing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The scan room temperature must balance equipment cooling requirements with patient comfort. Temperatures between 65–75°F (18–24°C) keep the magnet and gradient systems operating efficiently while maintaining a comfortable environment. Excessive heat increases the risk of gradient system shutdown and patient discomfort.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-062", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Fire extinguishers designated for use in Zone IV (the scanner room) must be:", "options": ["Standard CO2 extinguishers", "Non-ferrous and non-magnetic", "Standard Class A extinguishers", "Any commercially available extinguisher"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Standard fire extinguishers contain ferromagnetic components (steel tanks, valves) that would become projectiles in the MRI environment. Only non-ferrous, non-magnetic fire extinguishers specifically designed for MRI use may be stored in Zone IV.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-063", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "If a patient experiences cardiac arrest (Code Blue) while in the MRI scanner, the first action should be to:", "options": ["Begin CPR immediately inside the scanner", "Undock the table and rapidly move the patient to Zone III before initiating resuscitation", "Initiate an emergency quench of the magnet", "Call the radiologist before taking any action"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The code cart, defibrillator, and other emergency equipment are ferromagnetic and must never enter Zone IV. The fastest and safest response is to undock the table and move the patient to Zone III, where CPR and defibrillation can be performed safely. Emergency quenching is slow, dangerous, and unnecessary for a cardiac arrest.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-064", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Before bringing any ancillary equipment (such as an IV pole or wheelchair) into Zone IV, the technologist must:", "options": ["Verify that it is heavy enough to resist the magnetic pull", "Confirm the equipment bears an MR Safe or MR Conditional label", "Simply wipe it down with disinfectant", "Assume it is safe if it appears non-metallic"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "All equipment must be verified as MR Safe or MR Conditional before entering Zone IV. Many hospital items that appear non-magnetic (such as stainless steel IV poles or oxygen regulators) contain ferromagnetic components. Never assume any equipment is MRI-compatible without checking the label or documentation.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-065", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "Passive magnetic shielding (steel walls surrounding the magnet room) primarily serves to contain the:", "options": ["Fringe field (5-gauss line) within the room boundaries", "Radiofrequency field", "Gradient field noise", "Cryogen gas during a quench"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Passive shielding uses ferromagnetic steel plates in the walls, floor, and ceiling to redirect and contain the fringe field. This reduces the extent of the 5-gauss line, allowing the MRI suite to be located in smaller spaces and protecting nearby areas with sensitive equipment (such as pacemaker clinics) from magnetic field effects.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-066", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "RF shielding (Faraday cage) surrounding the MRI scanner room primarily prevents:", "options": ["Ferromagnetic objects from entering the room", "External radiofrequency interference from causing image artifacts", "Ionizing radiation from escaping the room", "Helium gas from entering the ventilation system"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Faraday cage is a continuous copper or aluminum enclosure surrounding the scan room that blocks external RF signals (from radio stations, cell phones, and electronic equipment) from entering and contaminating the MR signal. Any breach in the RF shielding (such as an open door or damaged seal) can produce zipper artifacts in the images.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-067", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "The \"5-gauss line\" marks the boundary where:", "options": ["The magnetic field is at its maximum strength", "The fringe field reaches a level potentially hazardous to unscreened implanted devices", "Zone III begins", "RF heating effects become significant"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line represents the boundary beyond which the magnetic field may interfere with cardiac pacemakers and other magnetically sensitive implanted devices. This boundary must be clearly marked with signage, and access must be restricted to screened individuals only.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-068", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "If a ferromagnetic object becomes pinned to the magnet bore, the technologist should:", "options": ["Attempt to pull the object free by hand", "Leave the object in place, remove the patient safely, and call service engineering", "Initiate an emergency quench immediately", "Power off the scanner using the emergency stop button"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Attempting to pull a pinned ferromagnetic object creates a crushing or laceration risk if it suddenly releases. The correct response is to ensure patient safety first, leave the object in place, and contact qualified service personnel. Emergency quenching is not indicated unless there is an immediate life-threatening situation.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-069", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Regarding pregnant MRI technologists, the current safety recommendation is:", "options": ["They may not work in the MRI department at all during pregnancy", "They may continue working but should generally avoid remaining in the scan room during active scanning", "They must wear a lead apron at all times", "They are limited to five minutes of exposure per day"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "While no harmful biological effects of MRI on the fetus have been proven, a precautionary approach is recommended. Pregnant technologists may continue performing MRI duties (screening, positioning, protocol setup) but should avoid remaining in the scan room (Zone IV) during active scanning to minimize RF and gradient field exposure.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-070", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Spatial encoding of the MRI signal is accomplished by the:", "options": ["Static magnet (B0)", "Gradient coil system", "Radiofrequency coils", "Shim coils"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The gradient coils create controlled linear variations in the magnetic field to perform spatial encoding: slice selection, phase encoding, and frequency encoding. These three gradient functions allow the MRI system to localize signal origin in three-dimensional space.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-071", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Slew rate is defined as:", "options": ["The speed of the patient table", "Maximum gradient amplitude divided by rise time", "The duration of the repetition time", "The field of view divided by matrix size"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slew rate (measured in T/m/s) represents how quickly the gradient coils can reach their maximum amplitude. Higher slew rates enable faster imaging but increase the risk of peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS). Slew rate = maximum gradient amplitude (mT/m) ÷ rise time (ms).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-072", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which tissues are at highest risk for RF-induced thermal injury due to poor heat dissipation (low perfusion)?", "options": ["Liver and kidney", "Eyes and testes", "Skeletal muscle", "Brain"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The eyes and testes have limited blood supply and poor thermoregulatory capacity, making them particularly vulnerable to RF-induced heating. The lens of the eye is avascular and cannot dissipate heat effectively, and the testes have temperature-sensitive spermatogenesis. Well-perfused organs (liver, muscle, brain) can dissipate heat more efficiently.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-073", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which pulse sequence type produces the highest Specific Absorption Rate (SAR)?", "options": ["Gradient echo (GRE)", "Fast spin echo (FSE/TSE)", "Echo planar imaging (EPI)", "Localizer (scout)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Fast spin echo sequences generate the highest SAR due to their train of 180° refocusing RF pulses applied during each TR interval. Each 180° pulse deposits four times more RF energy than a 90° pulse. Gradient echo sequences use smaller flip angles and no refocusing pulses, resulting in significantly lower SAR.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-074", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The magnetohydrodynamic effect observed on ECG tracings during MRI manifests as:", "options": ["P-wave amplitude spikes", "Elevated T-wave amplitude", "QRS complex disappearance", "Cardiac arrest"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The magnetohydrodynamic effect occurs when flowing blood (a conducting fluid) moves through the strong static magnetic field, inducing a voltage that superimposes on the ECG signal. This primarily manifests as T-wave elevation, which can mimic hyperkalemia or ischemia and complicate cardiac gating.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-075", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The spatial field gradient of the static magnet is strongest at:", "options": ["Isocenter (center of the bore)", "The bore entrance", "The control room", "The corners of the scan room"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The spatial field gradient — the rate of change in field strength over distance — is greatest at the bore entrance where the field transitions rapidly from high strength inside the bore to lower strength outside. This is where the translational (missile) force is strongest, making the bore entrance the most dangerous location for ferromagnetic objects.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-076", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "A \"zipper\" artifact running across the MRI image in the frequency-encoding direction most likely indicates:", "options": ["Patient motion", "An RF shielding breach (such as an open door or failed light bulb)", "A metallic implant", "Respiratory artifact"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A zipper artifact is a discrete line of signal that appears when external RF interference leaks into the scan room through a break in the Faraday cage. Common causes include an open scan room door, a failed RF-filtered light bulb, or a damaged waveguide seal. The artifact appears at the frequency of the interfering RF signal.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-077", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "\"Blooming\" artifact (exaggerated signal void surrounding a metallic object) is caused by:", "options": ["Fat signal contamination", "Magnetic susceptibility differences from metal or iron", "Water signal interference", "Patient motion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Blooming (susceptibility) artifact occurs when ferromagnetic or strongly paramagnetic materials create local magnetic field inhomogeneities that distort the surrounding signal. The artifact appears as a signal void (black region) that is typically larger than the actual implant. It is most pronounced on gradient echo and T2*-weighted sequences.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-078", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The magnetic force responsible for twisting or aligning an elongated ferromagnetic object (such as a hemostat) with the magnetic field lines is:", "options": ["Translational force", "Rotational force (torque)", "Lorentz force", "Electromotive force"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Torque (rotational force) acts to align elongated ferromagnetic objects with the direction of the magnetic field lines, similar to a compass needle. Torque is greatest at isocenter where the field is most uniform and strongest. Translational force pulls objects toward the bore; torque twists them into alignment.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-079", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "To prevent thermal injury from RF-induced heating, the ACR recommends using insulation padding of what minimum thickness between the patient and the bore or coils?", "options": ["1 mm", "Approximately 1 cm (0.4 inches)", "5 cm", "Padding is unnecessary if the ventilation fan is running"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR recommends a minimum of 1 cm of insulation padding between the patient's skin and the bore wall or RF coils to prevent thermal burns from induced currents. For high-SAR sequences, 2 cm of padding may be advisable. Padding must be non-conductive and positioned to eliminate all skin-to-bore contact.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-080", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Most modern coronary artery stents are considered MR Conditional or MR Safe and can be scanned:", "options": ["Immediately after placement with no required waiting period", "Only after six weeks of tissue incorporation", "Only after six months", "Never under any circumstances"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Current ACR guidelines indicate that most modern coronary stents are composed of non-ferromagnetic alloys and can be safely scanned immediately after placement. The earlier recommendation of a 6–8 week waiting period has been revised based on evidence that tissue embedment is not required to prevent stent migration. The specific stent model should always be verified.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-081", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Vertigo, nausea, or a metallic taste experienced by patients when moving quickly through the fringe field is caused by:", "options": ["The RF field heating the inner ear", "The static magnetic field (B0) affecting fluid in the semicircular canals", "Gradient coil stimulation of the retina", "Claustrophobia"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The static magnetic field exerts magnetohydrodynamic forces on the endolymph fluid in the semicircular canals of the inner ear, creating a false sensation of motion (vertigo). This effect is more pronounced with rapid head movements and at higher field strengths. Instructing patients to move slowly through the bore entrance helps minimize symptoms.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-082", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "If the cryogen vent fails during a quench and expanding helium gas pressurizes the scan room, the result may be:", "options": ["The scan room door being pulled inward", "The door being pinned shut (if inward-opening) or blasting open (if outward-opening)", "The magnet increasing in field strength", "A fire in the scan room"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rapid helium expansion during a quench can create significant positive pressure inside the scan room. If the door opens inward, this pressure can pin it shut with thousands of pounds of force, trapping occupants. If the door opens outward, the pressure can blow it open violently. Emergency protocols may include breaking the RF window to equalize pressure.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-083", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Scanning in \"First Level Controlled Mode\" allows whole-body SAR to reach 4.0 W/kg. This mode requires:", "options": ["No special action by the operator", "Medical supervision and positive operator acknowledgment of the increased risk", "The patient to be sedated", "A field strength of 1.5T only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "First Level Controlled Mode permits higher SAR limits but carries an increased risk of tissue heating (>1°C core temperature rise). The operator must actively acknowledge this elevated risk, and medical supervision must be available. The system will not enter this mode without positive confirmation.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-084", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Neurostimulators (such as deep brain stimulators) are particularly hazardous in MRI primarily because:", "options": ["They are too heavy for the MRI table", "The long implanted leads can act as RF antennas, causing severe heating at the electrode tip", "They always power off in the magnetic field", "They cause blooming artifact only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The primary risk with neurostimulators in MRI is not movement or artifact but RF-induced heating at the electrode tip. Long implanted leads can act as antennas, concentrating RF energy at the electrode-tissue interface and potentially causing thermal injury to brain or spinal cord tissue. Specific MR Conditional neurostimulator models exist with strict scanning protocols.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-085", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "When screening a patient with retained shrapnel or bullet fragments, the most critical safety factor to determine is:", "options": ["The caliber of the bullet", "The anatomic location of the fragment relative to vital structures", "How long ago the injury occurred", "Whether the patient is currently in pain"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Even weakly ferromagnetic fragments may experience slight movement in the magnetic field. If the fragment is located near a vital structure (blood vessel, nerve, eye, spinal cord), even minimal displacement could cause catastrophic injury. The composition and proximity to critical anatomy are the primary safety determinants.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-086", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Standard ECG electrodes with metal snaps should be replaced in MRI with electrodes made of:", "options": ["Copper", "Silver/silver chloride or carbon fiber (non-ferrous materials)", "Aluminum", "Stainless steel"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Standard metal-snap ECG electrodes can cause RF-induced burns and produce significant artifact. MRI-compatible electrodes use non-ferrous conductive materials such as silver/silver chloride or carbon fiber that minimize both heating risk and image artifact while maintaining adequate signal quality for cardiac gating.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-087", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The spatial field gradient map provided in the scanner manual helps the technologist determine:", "options": ["Where RF heating is highest in the bore", "Where the attractive translational (pulling) force is strongest", "Where image quality is optimal", "Where acoustic noise is loudest"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The spatial gradient map (typically shown as colored contour lines) indicates the rate of change of the static field at various locations around the magnet. This information is critical for determining whether MR Conditional devices can safely tolerate the translational force at their specific implant location relative to the bore.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-088", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.6", "stem": "Can non-MR personnel (such as a family member or maintenance worker) enter Zone III without supervision?", "options": ["No, they may never enter Zone III under any circumstances", "Yes, they may move freely throughout the MRI suite", "Yes, but only under strict supervision by Level 2 MR Personnel", "Only if they sign a liability waiver"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Non-MR personnel have not completed MR safety training and must be screened and continuously supervised by Level 2 MR Personnel when in Zone III or Zone IV. They should never be left unattended in restricted areas due to the risk of introducing ferromagnetic objects or entering the scan room without proper screening.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-089", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "If liquid helium escapes into the scan room during a quench, in addition to asphyxiation risk, another physical hazard to occupants is:", "options": ["Thermal burns from heat", "Frostbite (cold burns)", "Ionizing radiation burns", "Chemical corrosion of the skin"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Liquid helium exists at approximately −269°C (−4.2 K). Contact with the escaping cryogenic gas or liquid causes immediate severe frostbite. Even the cold gas cloud that forms during a quench can cause cold burns to exposed skin. Personnel must evacuate immediately and avoid contact with the visible vapor cloud.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-090", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Passive orthopedic implants (such as titanium screws and plates) primarily cause which issue during MRI?", "options": ["They fly out of the body due to the projectile effect", "Susceptibility artifact (image distortion) and potential minor heating", "Complete MRI system failure", "Peripheral nerve stimulation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Most passive titanium orthopedic implants are non-ferromagnetic and do not experience significant translational or rotational forces in the MRI environment. However, they create local magnetic field inhomogeneities that produce susceptibility artifact (signal void and geometric distortion) and may experience minor RF-induced heating, particularly if the implant is large.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-091", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "An oxygen monitor in the MRI scan room is required to trigger an alarm if oxygen concentration falls below:", "options": ["25%", "19.5%", "15%", "10%"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Normal atmospheric oxygen is approximately 21%. OSHA defines an oxygen-deficient atmosphere as one containing less than 19.5% oxygen. The scan room oxygen monitor must alarm at this threshold to warn of potential helium displacement from a slow cryogen leak or quench event, allowing immediate evacuation.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-092", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "\"Temporary threshold shift\" caused by MRI acoustic noise exposure is defined as:", "options": ["Permanent deafness", "A temporary reduction in hearing sensitivity following noise exposure", "Tinnitus (ringing in the ears)", "Vertigo"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Temporary threshold shift is a reversible decrease in hearing sensitivity that occurs after exposure to loud noise. While it resolves after the noise exposure ends, repeated episodes can lead to permanent sensorineural hearing loss. This is why hearing protection is mandatory for all patients and personnel during MRI scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-093", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Modern MR Conditional implants often specify a limit for B1+rms rather than SAR alone. The primary safety advantage of using B1+rms is that it:", "options": ["Accounts for patient thermoregulation capacity", "Is a precise machine output measurement independent of patient weight or input errors", "Measures the spatial field gradient around the implant", "Is only applicable to 3T scanners"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SAR is an estimated value that depends on patient weight input (which can be erroneous) and varies with patient geometry. B1+rms is a direct measurement of the actual RF power emitted by the coil, making it a more reliable and reproducible safety metric for implant heating assessments. Many newer MR Conditional implants specify B1+rms limits.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-094", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The \"antenna effect\" that can cause severe thermal injury in patients with abandoned pacemaker leads occurs when the lead length:", "options": ["Is oriented perpendicular to the static magnetic field", "Corresponds to a resonant fraction (such as half-wavelength) of the RF frequency", "Is fully insulated along its entire length", "Is less than 5 cm"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When the length of an implanted lead corresponds to a resonant fraction of the RF wavelength (particularly the half-wavelength), it acts as an antenna that efficiently absorbs RF energy. This creates a standing wave that concentrates energy at the electrode tip, generating extreme focal heating that can cause severe tissue burns.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-095", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The spatial field gradient (SFG) of the static magnet is responsible for which physical force on ferromagnetic objects?", "options": ["Peripheral nerve stimulation", "Translational (missile) force", "RF heating", "Vertigo"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The translational force that pulls ferromagnetic objects toward the bore is proportional to the product of the field strength and its spatial gradient (B × dB/dx). The spatial field gradient represents the rate of change of the static magnetic field over distance, and it is greatest at the bore entrance.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-096", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "To avoid confusion with time-varying (encoding) gradients, the spatial field gradient of the static magnet is typically measured in:", "options": ["Tesla per second (T/s)", "Watts per kilogram (W/kg)", "Tesla per meter (T/m) or gauss per centimeter (G/cm)", "Decibels (dB)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The spatial field gradient is measured in units of field strength per unit distance (T/m or G/cm) because it describes how the static field changes across space. Time-varying gradient slew rates are measured in T/m/s (change over time). SAR is measured in W/kg. This distinction is important for understanding implant safety specifications.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-097", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "During a magnet quench, if the cryogen vent fails and the scan room becomes pressurized, making the inward-opening door impossible to open, the emergency action is to:", "options": ["Push harder on the door", "Break the control room (RF) window to equalize pressure", "Wait for the pressure to subside naturally", "Turn off the ventilation system"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Positive pressure from expanding helium gas can seal an inward-opening door with thousands of pounds of force. Breaking the RF (control room) window equalizes the pressure between the scan room and the control room, allowing the door to be opened and occupants to evacuate. This is a last-resort emergency action.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-098", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "If a patient experiences cardiac arrest in the MRI scanner, why is initiating a magnet quench the wrong first response?", "options": ["Quenching takes too long and introduces additional hazards (asphyxiation from helium gas)", "Quenching instantly stops the patient's heart", "Quenching damages the defibrillator", "Quenching the magnet is illegal"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A quench takes several minutes to reduce the field, during which the patient receives no resuscitation. The released helium gas creates asphyxiation and frostbite hazards. The fastest and safest approach is to undock the table, move the patient to Zone III, and begin CPR with standard emergency equipment outside the magnetic field.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-099", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "According to the ACR Manual on MR Safety, any unlabeled or unidentified object must be treated as:", "options": ["MR Conditional", "MR Safe if it does not appear magnetic", "MR Unsafe", "Acceptable after testing with a handheld magnet"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ACR mandates that any object without clear MR safety labeling or documentation must be assumed MR Unsafe and excluded from Zones III and IV. Handheld magnet testing is insufficient because it cannot assess torque at isocenter, RF heating potential, or the effects of higher field strengths.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-100", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Group II gadolinium-based contrast agents with a macrocyclic molecular structure provide:", "options": ["Higher relaxivity but lower chemical stability", "High chemical stability and minimal risk of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF)", "Zero risk of any allergic reaction", "Faster renal excretion than all other agents"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Macrocyclic (Group II) GBCAs have a cage-like structure that tightly binds the gadolinium ion, greatly reducing the risk of free gadolinium release (dissociation). This structural stability is associated with a significantly lower incidence of NSF compared to linear (Group I) agents. Many facilities have adopted macrocyclic agents as their standard.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-101", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Per the ACR Manual on Contrast Media, the recommendation for breastfeeding after gadolinium administration is:", "options": ["Mandatory pump-and-discard for 24 hours", "Permanent discontinuation of breastfeeding", "Breastfeeding may continue without interruption", "The infant must be monitored in a hospital for 24 hours"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ACR states that less than 0.04% of the administered gadolinium dose enters breast milk, and the infant absorbs less than 1% of that orally. The resulting systemic infant dose is negligible. Breastfeeding may continue without interruption following gadolinium administration.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-102", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "The \"Full Stop / Final Check\" protocol recommended by MR safety experts involves:", "options": ["Pausing the scan sequence to verify image quality", "A momentary pause at the Zone IV threshold to visually confirm the patient and stretcher are clear of ferromagnetic hazards", "Stopping the magnet for routine maintenance", "Checking the patient's insurance authorization"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Full Stop / Final Check is a brief, deliberate pause at the Zone IV doorway before entering the scan room. It is designed to disrupt \"inattentional blindness\" — the phenomenon where a screened patient or staff member unknowingly re-enters with a forgotten hazard (phone, scissors, oxygen tank). This protocol has prevented multiple projectile incidents.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-103", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The primary biological effect of radiofrequency (RF) energy in MRI is:", "options": ["Peripheral nerve stimulation", "Tissue heating (thermal effects)", "Acoustic damage to hearing", "Displacement of implanted devices"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF energy is absorbed by tissue and converted to heat, measured by the Specific Absorption Rate (SAR). Additional RF-related risks include antenna effects on implanted leads and thermal injuries from conductive loops. PNS and acoustic noise are effects of the gradient field, not the RF field.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-104", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The FDA limits for RF exposure in MRI are calculated to prevent the core body temperature from rising by more than:", "options": ["0.1°C", "1°C", "3°C", "5°C"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The FDA establishes SAR limits to prevent a core body temperature increase exceeding 1°C. In Normal Operating Mode (2.0 W/kg whole body), the expected rise is approximately 0.5°C. First Level Controlled Mode (4.0 W/kg) approaches the 1°C limit and requires medical supervision.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-105", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The FDA limit for whole-body SAR in First Level Controlled Mode is:", "options": ["2.0 W/kg for 6 minutes", "4.0 W/kg for 15 minutes", "8.0 W/kg for 5 minutes", "10.0 W/kg for 10 minutes"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The First Level Controlled Mode permits a whole-body SAR of 4.0 W/kg averaged over 15 minutes. This mode carries increased thermal risk and requires positive operator acknowledgment and medical supervision. Normal Operating Mode is limited to 2.0 W/kg.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-106", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS) in MRI is a biological effect of:", "options": ["The static magnetic field (B0)", "The radiofrequency (RF) field", "Time-varying magnetic fields (gradient coils)", "The shim coil system"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "PNS is caused by rapidly switching gradient fields that induce electrical currents in peripheral nerves, causing tingling, twitching, or involuntary muscle contractions. The static field causes translational and rotational forces on ferromagnetic objects. The RF field causes tissue heating.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-107", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Magnetophosphenes (visual flashes or \"seeing stars\") during MRI are caused by:", "options": ["RF heating of the optic nerve", "Static field effects on the lens", "Gradient magnetic fields stimulating the retina", "Contrast agent entering the vitreous humor"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Magnetophosphenes are harmless, reversible visual sensations caused by gradient-induced electrical stimulation of the retina. They are a recognized biological effect of time-varying magnetic fields and may also occur when a person moves rapidly through the fringe field of the static magnet.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-108", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The loud knocking or banging noise during MRI scanning is produced by:", "options": ["The radiofrequency (RF) coils", "The cryogen cooling pump", "Time-varying magnetic fields (gradient coils vibrating via Lorentz forces)", "The patient table motor"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Acoustic noise in MRI is produced when current-carrying gradient coils experience Lorentz forces in the strong static magnetic field, causing rapid mechanical vibration. Sound levels can exceed 100 dB(A), particularly at 3T, making hearing protection mandatory for all occupants during scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-109", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The \"missile effect\" in which ferromagnetic objects accelerate toward the MRI bore is caused by:", "options": ["Torsion (rotational force)", "Translational force", "Lorentz force from gradient switching", "RF-induced repulsion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The translational force is the attractive pulling force that accelerates ferromagnetic objects toward the bore, creating the dangerous \"missile effect.\" Torsion (torque) is a separate rotational force that twists objects to align with the magnetic field lines. Both forces act simultaneously on ferromagnetic objects in the MRI environment.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-110", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The \"fringe field\" in MRI refers to:", "options": ["The gradient field used for spatial encoding", "The portion of the static magnetic field that extends beyond the bore into the surrounding environment", "The RF field generated during excitation", "The field produced by shim coils"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The fringe field is the static magnetic field that extends outside the magnet bore into the surrounding space. Its extent is defined by the 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line and determines the required size of the controlled access area. Active and passive shielding are used to minimize the fringe field footprint.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-111", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Regarding cardiac pacemakers and MRI, which statement is most accurate?", "options": ["All cardiac pacemakers are absolutely contraindicated regardless of model", "All cardiac pacemakers are safe for MRI scanning", "Legacy (non-conditional) pacemakers are contraindicated, but specific MR Conditional models may be scanned under strict protocols", "Pacemakers only cause artifact and pose no safety risk"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "While legacy pacemakers remain a contraindication to MRI, several manufacturers now offer MR Conditional pacemaker systems that have been tested and labeled for safe use under specific conditions (field strength, SAR limits, lead configuration, programmed mode). Strict adherence to the manufacturer's conditions and institutional protocols is required.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-112", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Intracranial aneurysm clips made of titanium are generally considered:", "options": ["An absolute contraindication regardless of material", "Safe for MRI because titanium is non-ferromagnetic", "Safe only at field strengths below 0.5T", "MR Unsafe due to the clip's proximity to the brain"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Titanium aneurysm clips are non-ferromagnetic and are generally considered safe for MRI. However, ferrous (ferromagnetic) aneurysm clips remain an absolute contraindication due to the risk of clip displacement and fatal hemorrhage. Positive identification of the clip material and model is essential before scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-113", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Under the ASTM International MR safety labeling system, the green square symbol indicates:", "options": ["MR Unsafe", "MR Conditional", "MR Safe", "Not yet tested for MRI"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The three ASTM International MR safety labels are: green square = MR Safe (no known hazards in any MRI environment), yellow triangle = MR Conditional (safe only under specific conditions), and red circle with diagonal slash = MR Unsafe (poses definite hazards in all MRI environments).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-114", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "An implant classified as \"MR Conditional\" can be safely scanned only when:", "options": ["The patient signs a special consent form", "All manufacturer-specified safety parameters (field strength, SAR, gradient conditions) are strictly followed", "The technologist determines it appears non-magnetic", "The implant has been in place for more than 6 weeks"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MR Conditional devices have demonstrated safety only within precisely defined conditions documented by the manufacturer. These typically include maximum field strength, SAR limits, gradient slew rate, spatial gradient limits, and specific coil requirements. Deviating from any stated condition can result in patient injury.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-115", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Regarding the biological effects of MRI on the developing fetus, current evidence indicates:", "options": ["MRI has been proven to cause birth defects", "No harmful biological effects have been demonstrated, though caution is advised", "MRI is absolutely contraindicated during all trimesters", "Only gradient noise affects the fetus"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "No harmful biological effects of MRI on the developing fetus have been proven to date. However, because fetal cells are rapidly dividing and potentially more susceptible to environmental influences, a precautionary approach is recommended. MRI should be performed during pregnancy when the clinical benefit outweighs the theoretical risk, particularly avoiding the first trimester when possible.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-116", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Regarding gadolinium contrast and pregnancy, which statement is correct?", "options": ["Gadolinium cannot cross the placental barrier", "Gadolinium crosses the placenta and enters fetal circulation", "Gadolinium is routinely recommended during pregnancy", "Gadolinium has no effect on the fetus regardless of dose"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium does cross the placenta and enters the fetal circulation, where it is excreted by fetal kidneys into the amniotic fluid. The fetus then swallows and re-absorbs the gadolinium, potentially prolonging exposure. For this reason, gadolinium should be avoided during pregnancy unless the clinical benefit clearly outweighs the risk.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-117", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "In the event of cardiac arrest during an MRI examination, CPR should be initiated:", "options": ["Immediately inside the scan room while the patient remains in the bore", "Only after the patient has been evacuated from the scan room (Zone IV) to Zone III", "After an emergency quench has been completed", "Only by the radiologist, not the technologist"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The patient must be removed from Zone IV before starting CPR because emergency resuscitation equipment (defibrillator, code cart, monitors) is ferromagnetic and cannot safely enter the magnetic field. The fastest response is to undock the table and move the patient out of the scan room to Zone III where standard ACLS protocols can be followed.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-118", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "During a magnet quench, the cryogen that is rapidly released from the cryostat is:", "options": ["Liquid nitrogen", "Liquid helium", "Liquid oxygen", "Liquid hydrogen"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Modern superconducting MRI magnets use liquid helium (not nitrogen) to cool the superconducting coils to near absolute zero. During a quench, the liquid helium rapidly boils off into an enormous volume of gas. While older magnet designs used both nitrogen and helium, current sealed-helium systems contain only helium as the cryogen.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-119", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "The two primary physical hazards to patients and staff during a magnet quench are:", "options": ["Electrical shock and fire", "Frostbite from cryogenic gas and asphyxiation from oxygen displacement", "Ionizing radiation exposure and chemical burns", "Magnetic field increase and RF heating"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "During a quench, the released helium gas poses two immediate dangers: frostbite (the gas is extremely cold, originating from liquid at −269°C) and asphyxiation (the expanding helium displaces oxygen in the room). Personnel must evacuate immediately and avoid breathing the visible vapor cloud.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-120", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "RF \"antenna effects\" in MRI can induce currents in implanted leads or external cables, resulting in:", "options": ["Gradient noise amplification", "Thermal injuries (burns) at the lead or cable tip", "Static field enhancement", "Image resolution improvement"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When implanted leads or external cables act as RF antennas, they absorb and concentrate RF energy, generating high current density at the tip. This can produce severe focal thermal burns at the electrode-tissue interface. This mechanism is the primary safety concern for patients with pacemaker leads, neurostimulator leads, and abandoned or retained leads.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-121", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Potential biological effects of prolonged exposure to high static magnetic fields include:", "options": ["Peripheral nerve stimulation and muscle twitching", "Fatigue, headaches, and hypotension", "Hearing loss and tinnitus", "Skin erythema and edema"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Bioeffects specifically associated with the static magnetic field include fatigue, headaches, hypotension, dizziness, and a metallic taste. These symptoms are more commonly reported at higher field strengths (3T and above) and are generally transient. PNS is caused by gradient fields, and hearing effects are caused by acoustic noise.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-122", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The magnetic force that causes the \"missile effect\" — where ferromagnetic objects accelerate toward the MRI bore — is:", "options": ["Torsion (rotational force)", "Translational force", "Electromagnetic induction", "Diamagnetic repulsion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The translational force pulls ferromagnetic objects along the spatial field gradient toward the bore, creating the potentially lethal missile effect. Torsion (torque) is a separate rotational force that twists objects to align with the field lines. Both forces are generated by the static magnetic field but act through different mechanisms.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "SA-123", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "According to FDA guidance, what is the maximum recommended static magnetic field strength for clinical MRI of the head and trunk in adults?", "options": ["4 T", "8 T", "3 T", "10 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current FDA guidance permits static magnetic field strengths up to 8 T for adults and children aged 1 month and older. The previous limit of 2 T for head and neck was superseded by updated guidelines. Neonates younger than 1 month are limited to 4 T.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.346"}, {"id": "SA-124", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which parameter is used to quantify the rate of change of gradient magnetic fields that may cause peripheral nerve stimulation?", "options": ["SAR (W/kg)", "dB/dt (T/s)", "Gauss/cm", "RF power (watts)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The rate of change of magnetic field over time (dB/dt), measured in T/s, is the parameter used to assess the risk of peripheral nerve stimulation from rapidly switching gradient fields. SAR measures RF energy deposition, not gradient-induced effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-125", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Gradient field strength in MRI systems is typically expressed in which unit(s)?", "options": ["Tesla/minute", "Gauss/cm or milliTesla/meter", "Watts/kilogram", "Amperes per meter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient strength is expressed in gauss/cm (G/cm) or milliTesla/meter (mT/m). These units describe the change in magnetic field per unit distance along the gradient axis. Watts/kilogram measures SAR, not gradient amplitude.", "reference": "MIP Ch.9 p.330"}, {"id": "SA-126", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which anatomical structures are considered most sensitive to temperature elevations from RF energy deposition during MRI?", "options": ["Bone and cartilage", "Testes and eyes", "Skin and subcutaneous fat", "Smooth muscle and tendons"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The testes and eyes lack efficient blood flow for heat dissipation, making them the most thermally sensitive structures during MRI. Bone, skin, and muscle have better mechanisms for distributing and dissipating heat.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-127", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "A patient presents for an MRI with temporary cardiac pacing wires in place. What is the most appropriate course of action?", "options": ["Proceed with the exam using low-SAR sequences", "Proceed only if the wires are not connected to a pulse generator", "Do not perform the examination", "Contact the referring physician for clearance before scanning"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Temporary pacing wires are an absolute contraindication for MRI regardless of whether they are connected to a pulse generator. The wires can act as antennas, concentrating RF energy and potentially inducing cardiac arrhythmias.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-128", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which of the following factors does NOT directly contribute to increased acoustic noise levels during MRI?", "options": ["Higher gradient duty cycles", "Stronger gradient magnetic fields", "Stronger static magnetic field", "Faster gradient switching rates"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Acoustic noise in MRI is produced by Lorentz forces on the gradient coils when current changes rapidly in the presence of the static field. Higher gradient duty cycles, stronger gradient amplitudes, and faster switching all increase noise. The static field strength itself is constant and does not directly generate acoustic vibrations.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-129", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following implanted devices is classified as an absolute contraindication for MRI under current ASTM safety labeling guidelines?", "options": ["Titanium orthopedic rod", "Dental root canal post", "Non-conditional cochlear implant", "Stainless steel surgical hemostasis clip"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Non-conditional cochlear implants contain ferromagnetic components and active electronics that can be damaged or displaced by the magnetic field, making them an absolute contraindication. Titanium orthopedic hardware, dental posts, and most hemostasis clips are generally MR Conditional or MR Safe.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-130", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Prior to entering the MRI scanner room (Zone IV), who must be screened for ferromagnetic objects and implants?", "options": ["Only the patient", "Only the patient and accompanying family members", "All persons entering the scanner room, including staff and visitors", "Only persons who have not been screened within the past year"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "All individuals entering Zone IV must be screened for ferromagnetic objects and implants, not just patients. This includes MRI technologists, nurses, physicians, family members, maintenance personnel, and any other visitors. A ferromagnetic object carried by anyone poses a projectile hazard.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-131", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Why must RF coil cables be prevented from contacting the patient's skin during MRI?", "options": ["Cable contact causes motion artifacts", "Cables may induce claustrophobic reactions", "Cables can concentrate RF energy and cause thermal burns", "Cable vibration increases acoustic noise to unsafe levels"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When RF coil cables form loops or contact the patient's skin, they can act as antennas that concentrate RF energy, leading to localized heating and thermal burns. This is one of the most common preventable injuries in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-132", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "When evaluating the potential biological effects of MRI, which electromagnetic field component is associated with tissue heating through energy absorption?", "options": ["The static magnetic field", "The radiofrequency (RF) field", "The gradient magnetic field", "The earth's magnetic field"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The RF field deposits energy in tissue as heat, quantified by the specific absorption rate (SAR). The static field produces translational and torque forces but not significant heating. The gradient field primarily causes peripheral nerve stimulation rather than thermal effects.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-133", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "What is the FDA normal operating mode SAR limit for whole-body exposure during clinical MRI?", "options": ["0.4 W/kg", "2.0 W/kg", "4.0 W/kg", "8.0 W/kg"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The normal operating mode SAR limit is 4 W/kg averaged over the whole body. The value 0.4 W/kg was previously classified as the insignificant risk level. The 8 W/kg limit applies to SAR per gram of tissue in extremities.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-134", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "What is the primary reason for maintaining controlled temperature, humidity, and airflow within the MRI scanner room?", "options": ["To prevent gradient coil overheating", "To reduce the rate of cryogen boil-off", "To help patients tolerate RF-induced heating effects", "To reduce the risk of cable-related burns"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Maintaining a cool, controlled environment in the scanner room helps patients dissipate heat generated by RF energy absorption. This is especially important when scanning at higher SAR levels. While climate control also benefits equipment, the primary safety rationale is patient thermoregulation.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-135", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "According to current professional guidelines, which statement best describes the policy for pregnant MRI technologists?", "options": ["Pregnant technologists must be restricted from all MRI environments", "Pregnant technologists may perform duties but should avoid remaining in the scan room during image acquisition", "Pregnant technologists must transfer to a different department immediately", "No specific restrictions are recommended at any stage of pregnancy"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current guidelines state that pregnant technologists may continue working in the MRI environment but may choose to avoid remaining in the scan room during active scanning. There is no requirement for complete restriction from the MRI suite, as the static field alone has not been shown to cause harm.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.368"}, {"id": "SA-136", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "A patient with permanent tattooed eyeliner containing ferrous pigment should be advised of which potential complication before undergoing MRI?", "options": ["Permanent discoloration of the tattooed area", "Permanent skin irritation and swelling around the eyes", "Transient skin irritation or localized swelling in the tattooed area", "Complete loss of the tattoo pigmentation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Ferrous-based tattoo pigments can interact with the RF field, causing localized heating that may produce transient skin irritation or swelling. These effects are typically self-limiting. Permanent damage is rare with current clinical field strengths.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-137", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Orbital screening for suspected intraocular metallic foreign bodies should be performed before entering an MRI system operating at what minimum field strength?", "options": ["0.5 T", "0.01 T", "1.0 T", "1.5 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Even very low magnetic field strengths can exert sufficient force on a small intraocular metallic fragment to cause tissue damage. Screening is recommended at field strengths as low as 0.01 T because the eye is highly vulnerable to mechanical injury from even small ferromagnetic particles.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-138", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "What is the standard screening method for detecting suspected intraocular metallic foreign bodies prior to MRI?", "options": ["Slit-lamp ophthalmic examination", "Handheld ferromagnetic detector", "Plain film radiographs of the orbits", "Signed patient self-report questionnaire"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Plain film radiographs of the orbits are the accepted standard screening method for detecting intraocular metallic foreign bodies. They can identify metallic fragments as small as 0.1 mm. While CT offers higher sensitivity, orbital X-rays are the standard first-line screen.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-139", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which electromagnetic field component in MRI has been associated with involuntary muscle contractions, cardiac arrhythmias, and the perception of light flashes (magnetophosphenes)?", "options": ["The static magnetic field", "The radiofrequency field", "The time-varying gradient magnetic field", "The shim coil magnetic field"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Time-varying gradient fields induce electrical currents in conductive tissues. These induced currents can stimulate peripheral nerves causing muscle twitching, potentially affect cardiac conduction, and stimulate the retina to produce perceived light flashes called magnetophosphenes.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-140", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Before each MRI examination, the technologist should verify that monitoring cables and RF coil connections meet which safety requirement?", "options": ["Cables are coiled neatly on top of the patient for organization", "All cable insulation is intact and cables are routed without forming loops or contacting the patient", "Cables are grounded to the scanner chassis", "Cable connections are tightened with maximum force"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cable insulation must be inspected for damage before each exam, and cables should be routed in a straight line without forming loops. Loops can act as antennas for RF energy, and direct cable contact with skin can cause thermal burns.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-141", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "At what magnetic field strength contour line should warning signs be posted to restrict access by individuals with cardiac pacemakers and other implanted devices?", "options": ["1 gauss line", "5 gauss line", "50 gauss line", "100 gauss line"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line is the standard perimeter at which restricted access must be enforced and warning signs posted. This boundary defines the area where the fringe field may interfere with implanted cardiac devices and other sensitive electronics.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-142", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which property of helium gas is most important for technologists to understand when planning emergency quench procedures?", "options": ["Helium is heavier than air and pools at floor level", "Helium is lighter than air and rises to the ceiling, displacing oxygen", "Helium is flammable and poses an ignition risk", "Helium produces a visible green-tinted vapor when released"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Helium is lighter than air and rapidly rises to the ceiling during a quench event, displacing oxygen and creating an asphyxiation hazard. It is odorless, tasteless, and not flammable. The cold helium vapor appears as a white cloud but is not colored.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.365"}, {"id": "SA-143", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which cryogen is used in modern superconducting MRI magnets to maintain the coils at superconducting temperatures?", "options": ["Liquid nitrogen", "Liquid helium", "Liquid argon", "Liquid oxygen"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Modern superconducting MRI magnets use liquid helium exclusively to cool the superconducting wire to approximately 4 K. Older systems used both liquid nitrogen and liquid helium, but current sealed-system designs use only helium with a cold-head recondensing system.", "reference": "MIP Ch.9 p.318"}, {"id": "SA-144", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Plain film orbital radiographs can detect intraocular metallic foreign bodies as small as:", "options": ["0.1 x 0.1 x 0.1 mm", "0.5 x 0.5 x 0.5 mm", "1.0 x 1.0 x 1.0 mm", "2.0 x 2.0 x 2.0 mm"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Orbital radiographs are sensitive enough to detect metallic fragments as small as 0.1 mm in each dimension. This high sensitivity makes them the standard first-line screening tool for patients with suspected intraocular metallic foreign bodies before MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-145", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "When evaluating whether a metallic foreign body is safe for MRI, which factor is most critical to determine?", "options": ["The date the foreign body was acquired", "The ferromagnetic properties of the object", "The patient's body mass index", "The duration of the planned examination"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ferromagnetic properties of a metallic foreign body are the most critical factor in determining MRI safety. Ferromagnetic materials experience translational force and torque in the magnetic field. The object's geometry, location, and field strength are also important but secondary.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.347"}, {"id": "SA-146", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Which component of the ECG waveform is most commonly augmented or distorted when a patient is positioned within the MRI static magnetic field?", "options": ["P wave", "QRS complex", "T wave", "PR interval"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The T wave of the ECG is most commonly augmented within the static magnetic field due to the magnetohydrodynamic effect: blood flowing through the aorta generates an electrical potential that superimposes on the T wave. This artifact can mimic hyperkalemia and complicates cardiac monitoring.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.352"}, {"id": "SA-147", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The FDA-recommended specific absorption rate (SAR) limit for whole-body RF exposure during clinical MRI in normal operating mode is:", "options": ["0.4 W/kg", "1.5 W/kg", "4.0 W/kg", "8.0 W/kg"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The normal operating mode whole-body SAR limit is 4.0 W/kg. The head SAR limit is 3.2 W/kg, and the extremity limit is 8.0 W/kg per gram of tissue. The older 0.4 W/kg value represents a historical insignificant risk threshold.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-148", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "A patient scheduled for MRI reports having a ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clip. Which action is most appropriate?", "options": ["Proceed if the clip was placed more than 6 weeks ago", "Proceed using only low-field-strength sequences", "Do not perform the MRI examination", "Scan only if the patient signs an additional consent form"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clips are an absolute contraindication for MRI. The magnetic field can exert torque and translational force on the clip, potentially causing vessel rupture and fatal hemorrhage. Unlike some abdominal clips, intracranial aneurysm clips require specific MR Conditional labeling verification.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-149", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When scanning pregnant women, infants, or patients with cardiovascular impairment, core body temperature increases from RF exposure should be limited to no more than:", "options": ["0.5°C", "1.0°C", "2.0°C", "3.0°C"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "For vulnerable populations including pregnant women, infants, and patients with compromised thermoregulation, the recommended maximum core temperature increase is 0.5°C. For healthy adults the limit is 1.0°C. This more conservative threshold reflects their reduced ability to dissipate excess heat.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-150", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "For whole-body MRI exposure in normal healthy adults, no adverse health effects are expected if core body temperature does not increase by more than:", "options": ["0.5°C", "1.0°C", "2.0°C", "3.0°C"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The accepted safety threshold for healthy adults is a core temperature increase of no more than 1.0°C during MRI. This limit ensures that RF energy deposition remains within a range that the body can safely dissipate. Vulnerable populations are held to the stricter 0.5°C limit.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-151", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Radiofrequency energy deposited into the body during an MRI examination is primarily converted into which form and distributed by which mechanism?", "options": ["Sound energy; distributed through bone conduction", "Heat; distributed through blood flow", "Electrical current; distributed through the nervous system", "Kinetic energy; distributed through muscle contraction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF energy absorbed by tissue during MRI is converted into heat through resistive (ohmic) losses. This thermal energy is then distributed throughout the body primarily via blood flow. Patients with impaired circulation are at higher risk for RF-related thermal injury.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-152", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The dB/dt thresholds established for time-varying gradient magnetic fields have been conclusively proven to cause no biological effects at any level used in clinical MRI.", "options": ["This statement is accurate for all clinical field strengths", "This statement is inaccurate; biological effects such as peripheral nerve stimulation can occur at clinical dB/dt levels", "This applies only to gradient echo sequences", "This applies only at field strengths below 1.5 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Biological effects from time-varying gradient fields, including peripheral nerve stimulation and magnetophosphenes, can and do occur at dB/dt levels used in clinical MRI. FDA guidelines establish thresholds to minimize these effects, but they have not been proven absent.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-153", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which pulse sequence type typically produces the highest gradient dB/dt values during clinical MRI?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Fast spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Echo planar imaging"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Echo planar imaging (EPI) requires extremely rapid gradient switching to acquire all k-space lines in a single TR, producing the highest dB/dt values of any standard clinical sequence. This is why EPI is most likely to approach peripheral nerve stimulation thresholds.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-154", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "What is the FDA-specified upper limit for the total magnetic field strength (static plus gradient contribution) during clinical MRI scanning?", "options": ["2 T", "4 T", "6 T", "10 T"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FDA specifies that the total magnetic field including gradient contributions should not exceed certain limits. When gradients are active, the combined field must remain within safe bounds. Historically this was cited as a 6 T limit, though modern systems operate under updated operating mode frameworks.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-155", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Why does the FDA restrict the rate of change (dB/dt) of gradient magnetic fields during MRI?", "options": ["To prevent peripheral nerve stimulation", "To reduce ohmic tissue heating", "To prevent carcinogenesis", "To eliminate magnetophosphenes completely"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The primary reason for dB/dt restrictions is to prevent peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS). Rapidly changing gradient fields induce electrical currents in tissue that can stimulate peripheral nerves, causing involuntary muscle contractions. While magnetophosphenes may also occur, PNS is the dose-limiting biological effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-156", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "At which location within the MRI system is the rate of change of the magnetic field (dB/dt) greatest?", "options": ["At the center of the gradient field (isocenter)", "At the center of the main magnetic field", "At the periphery (ends) of the gradient fields", "At the entrance to the bore"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The dB/dt is greatest at the ends (periphery) of the gradient fields, not at isocenter. This is because the spatial variation in field strength is steepest at the edges of the gradient coil coverage. Patients positioned off-center or with extremities at the bore edges experience higher dB/dt exposure.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-157", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The notation used to express the rate of change of a magnetic field over time is:", "options": ["SAR", "dB/dt", "mT/m", "W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "dB/dt represents the change in magnetic field strength (dB) over change in time (dt), measured in Tesla per second (T/s). SAR and W/kg both refer to specific absorption rate for RF energy. mT/m is a unit of gradient amplitude, not rate of change.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-158", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Under which condition do gradient coil switching during MRI induce voltages or currents in the patient or electrical conductors within the bore?", "options": ["When gradient amplitude is increasing or decreasing", "When gradients are at a constant magnetic field level", "When gradients are at peak amplitude but not changing", "Only when the frequency encoding gradient is active"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Induced voltages and currents occur when the gradient amplitude is changing (increasing or decreasing), not when it is held constant. According to Faraday's law, it is the rate of change of the magnetic field that induces an electromotive force in conductors.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-159", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The primary biological risk from exposure to rapidly switching gradient magnetic fields without proper safety limits is:", "options": ["Significant ohmic heating of patient tissues", "Induction of electrical currents in patient tissues", "Direct damage to gradient coils", "Production of patient skin burns from RF energy"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rapid gradient switching induces electrical currents in the patient's conductive tissues via electromagnetic induction. Without safety limits on dB/dt, these induced currents could reach levels sufficient to cause peripheral nerve stimulation, involuntary muscle contractions, or cardiac stimulation.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-160", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "What is the primary source of acoustic noise generated during an MRI procedure?", "options": ["The cryogenic cooling pump", "The gradient magnetic field coils", "The static main magnetic field", "The radiofrequency transmitter coil"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Acoustic noise in MRI is primarily produced by the gradient coils. When current pulses through the gradient coils in the presence of the static magnetic field, Lorentz forces cause the coils to vibrate rapidly, producing loud knocking or banging sounds that can exceed 100 dB.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-161", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "If electronic decoupling is not available, improper positioning of a receive coil relative to the transmit coil could result in:", "options": ["Increased gradient acoustic noise", "Inadvertent patient movement", "Radiofrequency burns to the patient", "Gradient coil malfunction"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When electronic decoupling is unavailable, the receive coil must be positioned orthogonally to the transmit coil. Improper alignment allows the transmit RF field to induce excessive currents in the receive coil, which can cause localized RF burns to the patient.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-162", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "If electronic decoupling is unavailable on an MRI system, failure to properly orient the receive coil orthogonally to the body transmit coil may result in:", "options": ["Inadvertent coil movement during imaging", "Gradient coil malfunction", "Possible damage to the receive coil", "Radiofrequency interference artifacts only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Without electronic decoupling, a receive coil that is not properly oriented relative to the transmit coil can absorb excessive RF energy during transmission. This energy overload can damage the coil's electronics, preamplifiers, or tuning circuits.", "reference": "MIP Ch.9 p.337"}, {"id": "SA-163", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "SAR limitation issues during MRI are most likely encountered when using which transmit coil?", "options": ["Body coil", "Extremity coil", "Head coil", "Knee coil"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The body transmit coil covers the largest tissue volume and therefore deposits the most total RF energy, making SAR limitations most commonly encountered with whole-body coil transmission. Smaller transmit coils (head, extremity) expose less tissue volume and are less likely to exceed whole-body SAR limits.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-164", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which parameter adjustment is most effective for reducing RF power deposition (SAR) when sequence parameters exceed FDA limits?", "options": ["Decrease the TE", "Decrease the TR", "Increase the TR", "Increase the flip angle"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Increasing the TR allows more time between RF excitation pulses, reducing the average rate of RF energy deposition and lowering SAR. Decreasing TR would increase the pulse rate and worsen SAR. Reducing flip angle is another effective approach but was not among the listed options.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-165", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Why should patients with Swan-Ganz (pulmonary artery) catheters generally not undergo MRI?", "options": ["Cardiac arrhythmias from magnetic torque on the catheter tip", "Eddy current inductive heating may damage or melt the catheter", "Susceptibility artifacts obscure all diagnostic information", "Vital sign monitoring is completely impossible during MRI"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Swan-Ganz catheters contain conductive elements that can experience eddy current inductive heating from the rapidly switching gradient and RF fields, potentially causing the catheter to heat and damage surrounding tissue or melt. The catheter wire can also act as an antenna for RF energy concentration.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-166", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "The fringe field exclusion zone for individuals with cardiac pacemakers and defibrillators should be enforced at the:", "options": ["0.5 gauss perimeter", "5 gauss perimeter", "50 gauss perimeter", "500 gauss perimeter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 5 gauss (0.5 mT) perimeter is the established boundary for restricting access by individuals with active cardiac implants. At field strengths above 5 gauss, the fringe field may interfere with pacemaker reed switches or pulse generator programming.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-167", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "At what level of core body temperature increase does the FDA consider SAR exposure to be at the level of concern during MRI?", "options": ["0.1°C", "0.5°C", "1.0°C", "2.0°C"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FDA defines SAR as reaching the level of concern when RF exposure produces a core temperature increase of 1.0°C in healthy adults. This threshold represents the boundary between normal operating mode and first-level controlled operating mode.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-168", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "FDA SAR level restrictions during MRI are primarily imposed to control the risk of:", "options": ["Gradient-induced acoustic noise injury", "Inducing current in coil cables", "Claustrophobic panic disorders", "Systemic and/or local thermal injury"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "SAR restrictions exist to prevent thermal injury from RF energy absorption. RF energy is converted to heat in tissue, and without limits, excessive heating could cause systemic temperature elevation or localized burns. Acoustic noise and cable currents are gradient-related concerns, not SAR-related.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-169", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "If selected imaging parameters will produce SAR levels exceeding the FDA normal operating mode limit, which patient population is at greatest risk?", "options": ["Extremely thin patients", "Febrile (fever) patients", "Hypotensive patients", "Pediatric patients under age 10"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Febrile patients already have an elevated core body temperature and reduced capacity for further heat dissipation. Additional RF-induced heating from high-SAR sequences could push their temperature to dangerous levels. This makes febrile patients the highest-risk group when SAR limits are exceeded.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-170", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "How should ECG leads and monitoring cables be positioned within the MRI scanner bore?", "options": ["Coiled on top of the patient for easy access", "Coiled under the patient to prevent tangling", "Electrically grounded to the bore wall", "Insulated and routed in a straight line along the long axis of the magnet"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "ECG leads and cables must be insulated and placed in a straight line parallel to the bore axis (z-axis). This minimizes the cross-sectional loop area exposed to the RF field. Coiling cables creates loops that can act as antennas, concentrating RF energy and causing burns.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-171", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Ferromagnetic objects must be prohibited from the MRI environment primarily because they pose a:", "options": ["Electrical arcing hazard with the scanner", "Interference problem with the RF system", "Projectile hazard from translational force", "Direct violation of FDA inspection regulations"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The static magnetic field exerts a strong translational (attractive) force on ferromagnetic objects, accelerating them toward the bore as a projectile. This is the most dangerous and common MRI safety hazard, capable of causing serious injury or death.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-172", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Can the ECG gating system used for cardiac pulse triggering in MRI also serve as a reliable diagnostic cardiac monitoring device during the procedure?", "options": ["Yes, the MRI ECG system provides diagnostic-quality cardiac monitoring", "No, the MRI-compatible ECG shows artifacts that prevent reliable diagnostic monitoring", "Yes, but only at field strengths below 1.0 T", "Yes, if specialized cardiac leads are used"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRI-compatible ECG systems are designed for triggering purposes and cannot provide diagnostic-quality cardiac monitoring. The magnetohydrodynamic effect augments the T wave, gradient switching creates electrical noise, and lead positioning is optimized for gating rather than diagnosis. A separate MR-compatible physiologic monitor is needed for clinical cardiac assessment.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.352"}, {"id": "SA-173", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "In the event of a cryogenic helium leak or catastrophic magnet quench, what is the first action the MRI technologist should take?", "options": ["Call the fire department", "Evacuate all persons from the scan room", "Open the scan room door to ventilate cryogenic gases", "Shut down the MR system power"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The immediate priority during a quench or cryogenic leak is to evacuate all personnel and patients from the scan room. Helium gas rapidly displaces oxygen and can cause asphyxiation. Opening the door before evacuation could allow helium to spread into adjacent areas. Emergency services are contacted after everyone is safe.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.365"}, {"id": "SA-174", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "With all other imaging parameters held constant, which change would INCREASE acoustic noise during an MRI procedure?", "options": ["Increasing the RF pulse bandwidth", "Decreasing the RF pulse bandwidth", "Increasing the echo time", "Decreasing the number of signal averages"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Decreasing the RF pulse bandwidth requires a longer RF pulse to maintain selectivity, which in turn requires stronger or faster gradient switching to achieve the same slice profile. This increased gradient activity produces more acoustic noise. Increasing bandwidth has the opposite effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-175", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "With all other imaging parameters held constant, which change would INCREASE acoustic noise production during MRI?", "options": ["Increasing slice thickness", "Decreasing slice thickness", "Increasing the number of signal averages", "Decreasing the matrix size"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Thinner slices require steeper slice-select gradients, which means greater gradient amplitude and faster switching. This increased gradient demand directly translates to louder acoustic noise. Increasing slice thickness reduces gradient demands and noise.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-176", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "With all other imaging parameters held constant, which change would INCREASE acoustic noise during MRI?", "options": ["Increasing the field of view", "Decreasing the field of view", "Increasing the receiver coil size", "Switching from a head coil to a body coil"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A smaller FOV requires steeper frequency and phase encoding gradients to achieve the same spatial resolution over a smaller area. Steeper gradients mean greater amplitude and faster switching, which increases acoustic noise. Larger FOV reduces gradient demands.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-177", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which statement is TRUE regarding RF-induced ohmic heating of tissues during MRI?", "options": ["Ohmic tissue heating is greatest at the center of the body", "Environmental cooling has no effect on heat dissipation", "Patient body habitus (size) is a factor in RF tissue heating", "RF tissue heating is never clinically significant"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Patient body size directly affects RF energy absorption. Larger patients absorb more total RF energy due to increased tissue volume and cross-sectional area exposed to the RF field. Ohmic heating is greatest at the body surface, not the center, and environmental cooling does help with heat dissipation.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-178", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "What is the current FDA upper limit for static magnetic field strength in clinical MRI systems for adult patients?", "options": ["2 T", "4 T", "8 T", "No upper limit has been established"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Current FDA guidance establishes 8 T as the upper limit for clinical MRI in adults and children aged 1 month and older. The previous 2 T limit was updated as clinical experience demonstrated safety at higher field strengths. Systems operating above 8 T require an investigational device exemption.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.346"}, {"id": "SA-179", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Based on current evidence, exposure to static magnetic field strengths used in clinical MRI:", "options": ["Causes confirmed harmful biological effects requiring strict exposure limits", "Has not been shown to produce verified harmful biological effects in humans", "Is safe only at field strengths below 0.5 T", "Produces cumulative genetic damage over repeated exposures"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "No verified harmful biological effects from static magnetic fields at clinical MRI strengths have been demonstrated. Transient effects such as vertigo, metallic taste, and T-wave augmentation on ECG occur but resolve upon removal from the field. These are not considered harmful.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-180", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Research studies have concluded that static magnetic fields up to what strength produce no substantial harmful biological effects?", "options": ["1.0 T", "1.5 T", "2.0 T", "3.0 T"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Studies have consistently demonstrated that static magnetic fields up to 2.0 T produce no substantial harmful biological effects. While transient sensory effects (vertigo, nausea, metallic taste) may occur at higher field strengths, no permanent tissue damage has been documented at clinical levels.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-181", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The primary biological effect of radiofrequency energy exposure during MRI is:", "options": ["Ionization of intracellular components", "Molecular chemistry aberrations", "Tissue heating from ohmic losses", "No biological effects occur at clinical levels"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "RF energy in MRI operates in the non-ionizing frequency range and cannot cause ionization. The primary biological effect is tissue heating through resistive (ohmic) energy absorption. While thermal effects at clinical SAR levels are generally well-tolerated, they must be monitored in vulnerable patients.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-182", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "A patient has retained pacemaker leads but no attached pulse generator. Is it safe to proceed with MRI?", "options": ["Yes, leads without a generator pose no MRI risk", "No, retained leads are contraindicated even without an attached generator", "Yes, if the leads have been in place for more than 6 weeks", "Yes, but only at field strengths of 1.5 T or below"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Retained pacemaker leads are contraindicated for MRI even when no pulse generator is attached. The leads can act as antennas that concentrate RF energy, causing localized tissue heating at the lead tips. This risk is independent of whether a generator is connected.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-183", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The FDA normal operating mode SAR limit for the head during clinical MRI is:", "options": ["0.4 W/kg", "3.2 W/kg", "4.0 W/kg", "8.0 W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The SAR limit for the head in normal operating mode is 3.2 W/kg. The whole-body limit is 4.0 W/kg, and the extremity limit is 8.0 W/kg per gram of tissue. The 0.4 W/kg value is a historical insignificant risk level, not a current operating limit.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.357"}, {"id": "SA-184", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Time-varying gradient magnetic fields may induce electrical currents in which of the following structures?", "options": ["Peripheral nerves only", "Blood vessels only", "Both peripheral nerves and blood vessels, and may produce retinal phosphenes", "Neither nerves nor blood vessels at clinical field strengths"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Time-varying gradient fields can induce electrical currents in any conductive tissue, including peripheral nerves and blood vessels. They may also stimulate the retina, producing the perception of light flashes known as retinal phosphenes or magnetophosphenes.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.363"}, {"id": "SA-185", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following devices is generally considered safe for MRI after the surgical site has healed (approximately 6 weeks post-implantation)?", "options": ["Non-conditional cochlear implant", "Abdominal surgical clips", "Active bone growth stimulator", "Cardiac pacemaker with abandoned leads"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Abdominal surgical clips and pins are generally considered safe for MRI after approximately six weeks, once fibrous tissue has anchored them in place. Cochlear implants and active bone growth stimulators contain electronic components or ferromagnetic materials that make them contraindicated regardless of healing time.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-186", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "According to current guidelines, which statement accurately reflects recommendations for pregnant individuals in the MRI environment?", "options": ["Pregnant patients should never undergo MRI under any circumstances", "Pregnant technologists may choose to leave the scan room during image acquisition", "Pregnant patients require written authorization from an obstetrician before scanning", "All pregnant individuals must remain outside the 50 gauss line"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current guidelines allow pregnant technologists to continue MRI duties while recommending they may voluntarily leave the scan room during active scanning. Pregnant patients may be scanned when MRI provides essential diagnostic information. There is no blanket prohibition against MRI during pregnancy.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.368"}, {"id": "SA-187", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Which observation has been documented regarding the effects of clinical static magnetic fields on the cardiovascular system?", "options": ["Significant cardiac arrhythmias occur routinely during 1.5 T scanning", "Small electric potentials develop in blood vessels flowing perpendicular to the field", "Permanent changes in blood viscosity have been confirmed", "Red blood cell morphology is permanently altered above 1.0 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The magnetohydrodynamic effect generates small electric potentials when blood flows perpendicular to the static magnetic field. This produces the T-wave augmentation seen on ECG during MRI. These effects are transient and resolve when the patient exits the field. No permanent cardiovascular changes have been documented.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.352"}, {"id": "SA-188", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which of the following is a critical safety verification that must be performed before every MRI examination?", "options": ["Confirm the patient's insurance authorization", "Verify that all coil cables are intact, unlooped, and not contacting the patient", "Ensure the scanner has been calibrated within the past 24 hours", "Check that the bore temperature is below 20°C"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cable inspection is a mandatory pre-scan safety check. Damaged insulation can expose conductive elements, looped cables can concentrate RF energy, and skin contact can cause burns. These simple checks prevent the most common preventable MRI injuries.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.358"}, {"id": "SA-189", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "In passive magnetic shielding of an MRI suite, what is the effect of placing iron in the walls surrounding the magnet?", "options": ["The fringe field is extended further from the magnet", "The fringe field is drawn closer to the magnet, reducing its extent", "The fringe field is eliminated completely", "The fringe field direction is reversed"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Passive shielding uses ferromagnetic iron in the walls to provide a preferential path for magnetic flux lines. This draws the fringe field inward, reducing the distance at which the 5-gauss line extends. Approximately 10 mm of unsaturated iron can reduce the fringe field by about 50%.", "reference": "MIP Ch.9 p.326"}, {"id": "SA-190", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "Which of the following is a valid reason for initiating a manual (emergency) magnet quench?", "options": ["To reduce acoustic noise during a pediatric examination", "To remove a large ferromagnetic object trapping a patient against the bore", "To vent excess helium that has accumulated above normal levels", "To reset the magnet after a power fluctuation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A manual quench should only be initiated in true emergencies, such as when a ferromagnetic projectile is trapping a patient and cannot be physically removed, or when emergency personnel need access to the magnet room. A quench is never performed for routine helium management or noise control.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.365"}, {"id": "SA-191", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "Individuals with non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemakers must remain outside which fringe field boundary?", "options": ["5 gauss line", "10 gauss line", "50 gauss line", "100 gauss line"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The 5 gauss (0.5 mT) line is the critical boundary for individuals with non-conditional cardiac pacemakers. The fringe field above this level can interfere with pacemaker function by activating reed switches, reprogramming the device, or inducing currents in the leads.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-192", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "Analog watches and magnetic stripe cards (credit cards) should be kept outside which fringe field contour?", "options": ["5 gauss line", "10 gauss line", "50 gauss line", "100 gauss line"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Analog watches with mechanical movements and magnetic stripe cards are sensitive to magnetic fields above approximately 100 gauss. At this field strength, watch mechanisms can be magnetized and card data can be erased. This boundary is further from the magnet than the 5-gauss pacemaker restriction zone.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-193", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.D", "stem": "The RF shielding (Faraday cage) of an MRI scanner room must encompass which structural elements?", "options": ["Only the walls of the scan room", "Only the walls and ceiling", "Walls, windows, and all wiring or cables entering the room", "Only the area immediately surrounding the bore"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A complete Faraday cage must shield all potential RF entry points: walls, ceiling, floor, windows (using conductive mesh or glass), door seals, and every cable or conduit that penetrates the room. Any gap in the shield allows external RF interference to enter and produce zipper artifacts on images.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-194", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following is classified as an absolute contraindication for MRI?", "options": ["Pregnancy in the first trimester", "Fever above 38°C", "Non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemaker", "Ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clips that have been verified as MR Conditional"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemaker is an absolute contraindication for MRI. The magnetic field can interfere with pacing function, induce currents in the leads, and cause cardiac arrhythmias. Pregnancy and fever are relative considerations. MR Conditional clips that have been verified are permitted.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-195", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which of the following items is generally considered safe to bring into the MRI scanner room?", "options": ["MR Conditional aluminum oxygen cylinder", "Standard hospital ventilator", "Standard hospital fire extinguisher", "Steel IV pole"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "An MR Conditional aluminum oxygen cylinder is constructed from non-ferromagnetic material and is considered safe for the MRI environment when used according to labeling conditions. Standard hospital ventilators, fire extinguishers, and steel IV poles typically contain ferromagnetic components and pose projectile risks.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "SA-196", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "The standard screening method for detecting intraocular metallic foreign bodies as small as 0.1 mm prior to MRI is:", "options": ["Orbital radiographs (plain film X-rays)", "CT of the orbits", "MRI of the orbits at low field strength", "Ocular ultrasound"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Orbital radiographs are the standard first-line screening tool and can detect metallic fragments as small as 0.1 mm in each dimension. While CT is more sensitive, plain films remain the practical standard for routine pre-MRI screening due to availability and cost. MRI should not be used to screen for metallic foreign bodies.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.351"}, {"id": "SA-197", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Family members or ancillary personnel who accompany a patient into the MRI scan room must:", "options": ["Only be screened if they will remain in the room during scanning", "Wear a lead apron for radiation protection during the procedure", "Be screened for MRI contraindications as thoroughly as the patient", "Sign a liability waiver but do not require screening"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Anyone entering the MRI scan room (Zone IV) must undergo the same thorough screening as the patient, regardless of whether they are being scanned. The static magnetic field, gradient fields, and RF energy affect all individuals in the room equally. Lead aprons are used for ionizing radiation protection and serve no purpose in MRI.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-198", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "In preparation for an MRI examination, patients should be instructed to:", "options": ["Wear their own clothing to increase comfort during the exam", "Keep their wristwatch on to monitor exam duration", "Leave hearing aids in place to hear technologist instructions", "Change into facility-provided clothing verified to be free of metallic components"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Patients must change into MR-safe facility-provided gowns or scrubs that contain no metallic components such as snaps, zippers, underwires, or metallic threads. Personal clothing may contain hidden metallic elements that pose burn or projectile risks. Watches, hearing aids, and other electronic devices must be removed before entering the scan room.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-199", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "An emergency room patient with a C3 fracture and suspected spinal cord compression is sent for MRI. What is the most appropriate first step before proceeding?", "options": ["Rush the patient into the scanner on the ER stretcher to avoid aggravating the fracture", "Screen the patient and family for the possibility of implants or metallic foreign bodies", "Cancel the exam upon learning the patient has a total hip replacement", "Allow the patient to keep their jewelry on to avoid unnecessary movement"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Regardless of clinical urgency, thorough MRI safety screening must be completed before any patient enters the scan room. The ER stretcher may contain ferromagnetic components and must never enter Zone IV without verification. A total hip replacement is generally MR Conditional and would not automatically require exam cancellation. All jewelry and metallic objects must be removed.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-200", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which personnel groups should receive education about the hazards of the static magnetic field in a superconducting MRI facility?", "options": ["Only the MRI technologists and radiologists", "MRI staff and the anesthesia/respiratory therapy teams", "All clinical staff who may respond to emergencies in the MRI suite", "All personnel who may enter or work near the MRI environment, including nursing, housekeeping, code teams, and fire department"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Every person who may enter or work near the MRI environment must understand the hazards of the static magnetic field, including support staff such as housekeeping, facilities maintenance, fire department personnel, and code teams. Untrained personnel responding to emergencies are at particular risk of introducing ferromagnetic objects into the scan room.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 346 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-201", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "According to the ACR Guidance Document on MR Safe Practices, Level 2 MR personnel are defined as individuals who have:", "options": ["No formal MRI safety training", "Basic MRI safety orientation only", "Extensive training in MRI safety including the static field, gradient fields, and RF energy hazards", "Completed a nationally recognized MRI safety certification examination"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ACR defines Level 2 MR personnel as individuals who have been extensively trained and educated in MRI safety, including the broader aspects of MRI physics and the hazards of static, gradient, and RF fields. Level 2 personnel are authorized to enter Zone IV (the scan room) independently and are responsible for ensuring the safety of all individuals in the MR environment.", "reference": "ACR Guidance Document / MIP Ch. 10 p. 346"}, {"id": "SA-202", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "According to the ACR four-zone model for MRI facility design, which zone description is NOT part of the standard framework?", "options": ["Zone I: freely accessible to the general public", "Zone II: the interface between the public area and the MR-controlled areas", "Zone III: the restricted area near the scan room, accessible only to screened personnel", "Zone V: a designated outdoor perimeter security zone around the facility"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The ACR four-zone model includes Zone I (general public access), Zone II (interface/screening area), Zone III (restricted ‘warm zone’ typically including the control room), and Zone IV (the scan room or ‘hot zone’). There is no Zone V in the ACR framework. Zone III is the critical boundary where ferromagnetic screening must occur before entering Zone IV.", "reference": "ACR Guidance Document / MIP Ch. 10 p. 346"}, {"id": "SA-203", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which element is LEAST essential to include on an MRI screening questionnaire?", "options": ["History of prior surgical procedures and implanted devices", "Current pregnancy status", "Patient's preferred pharmacy for prescriptions", "History of prior injuries involving metallic foreign bodies"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "An MRI screening questionnaire must include questions about prior surgeries, implants, metallic foreign bodies, and pregnancy status to identify potential contraindications to MRI. The patient's preferred pharmacy has no relevance to MRI safety screening. Thorough screening is the primary defense against MRI-related injuries.", "reference": "ACR Guidance Document / MIP Ch. 10 p. 347"}, {"id": "SA-204", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Under the current ASTM International labeling standard for MRI device safety, which term is NOT part of the official classification system?", "options": ["MR Safe", "MR Conditional", "MR Reliable", "MR Unsafe"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ASTM International standard defines three official safety classifications: MR Safe (poses no known hazards in any MR environment), MR Conditional (safe under specific conditions), and MR Unsafe (poses hazards in all MR environments). 'MR Reliable' is not a recognized ASTM classification. The older term 'MR Compatible' has been retired and replaced by this system.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-205", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following is considered an absolute contraindication to MRI?", "options": ["Pregnancy in any trimester", "Metallic orthopedic hardware in the extremities", "Non-MR Conditional ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clip", "Dental braces or orthodontic appliances"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A non-MR Conditional ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clip is an absolute contraindication because the magnetic field can torque or displace the clip, potentially causing fatal hemorrhage. Pregnancy is not an absolute contraindication — MRI may be performed when the clinical benefit outweighs the theoretical risk. Orthopedic hardware and dental appliances are generally MR Conditional.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-206", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "The accepted standard-of-care method for initial screening of suspected intraocular ferrous foreign bodies prior to MRI is:", "options": ["Computed tomography (CT)", "MRI of the orbits", "Plain film radiography of the orbits", "Visual examination by ophthalmology"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Plain film radiography (typically AP and lateral views of the orbits) is the accepted standard of care for screening patients with a history of metallic foreign body exposure. It is fast, inexpensive, and effective at detecting ferromagnetic fragments. CT provides greater sensitivity for small fragments but is not the initial screening standard.", "reference": "ACR MR Safety / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-207", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which imaging modality provides the greatest sensitivity for detecting small intraocular ferrous foreign bodies when plain films are inconclusive?", "options": ["Computed tomography (CT)", "Ultrasound of the orbits", "Repeat plain film radiography with different projections", "MRI with gradient echo sequences"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "CT provides superior sensitivity for detecting very small metallic foreign bodies compared to plain films due to its cross-sectional imaging capability and high spatial resolution. MRI should never be used to screen for suspected ferromagnetic foreign bodies, as the magnetic field could mobilize the fragment and cause ocular injury.", "reference": "ACR MR Safety / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-208", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which screening element is LEAST relevant to MRI safety and would not typically appear on a standard MRI screening questionnaire?", "options": ["History of prior surgeries and implanted devices", "History of prior injuries involving metallic fragments", "Patient's current dietary restrictions", "Current or suspected pregnancy"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MRI screening questionnaires must address surgical implants, metallic foreign body exposure, and pregnancy status to identify potential contraindications. Dietary restrictions, while relevant to general patient care, have no bearing on MRI safety screening and would not appear on a standard MRI screening form.", "reference": "ACR MR Safety / MIP Ch. 10 p. 347"}, {"id": "SA-209", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which implanted device is generally considered safe for MRI scanning at all currently used clinical field strengths?", "options": ["Non-MR Conditional ferromagnetic aneurysm clip", "Non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemaker", "Prosthetic heart valve", "Non-MR Conditional cochlear implant"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Most prosthetic heart valves are composed of non-ferromagnetic or weakly ferromagnetic materials and are considered safe for MRI at all clinical field strengths. The minimal ferromagnetic attraction is far less than the mechanical forces the valve already withstands from cardiac motion. Non-MR Conditional pacemakers, aneurysm clips, and cochlear implants remain absolute or relative contraindications depending on their specific labeling.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-210", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Before using patient monitoring equipment in the MRI environment, compatibility must be verified through:", "options": ["Visual inspection of the device for ferromagnetic components only", "Confirmation that the device has a current FDA 510(k) clearance for any medical use", "Prior testing and/or manufacturer documentation confirming MR compatibility at the specific field strength", "Approval from the referring physician"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "All monitoring equipment used in the MRI environment must have documented MR compatibility for the specific field strength in use, verified through manufacturer testing data or independent prior testing. FDA 510(k) clearance for general medical use does not guarantee MR safety. Visual inspection alone cannot detect all ferromagnetic components or electronic susceptibility issues.", "reference": "ACR MR Safety / MIP Ch. 10 p. 346"}, {"id": "SA-211", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which of the following items is generally safe to bring into the scan room of a high-field superconducting MRI system?", "options": ["Stainless steel surgical hemostats", "Standard stainless steel scissors", "Non-ferromagnetic copper tools", "Standard laryngoscope"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Copper is a non-ferromagnetic metal and will not experience translational or rotational force in a magnetic field, making copper tools generally safe in the MRI scan room. Surgical stainless steel instruments may contain ferromagnetic alloys that can become projectiles. Standard laryngoscopes contain ferromagnetic components and batteries that are MR Unsafe.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-212", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "To minimize the risk of RF-induced thermal injury, cables from RF coils and ECG leads within the MRI bore should be:", "options": ["Routed straight without forming loops and positioned away from the patient's skin", "Coiled neatly and placed on the patient's chest", "Formed into large loops to reduce electrical resistance", "Draped loosely across the patient's body for comfort"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "RF coil and ECG cables must be routed straight without forming loops to prevent the cables from acting as antennas that concentrate RF energy, which can cause thermal burns at skin contact points. Loops create areas of concentrated induced current, and direct skin contact with cables increases burn risk. Padding should be placed between all cables and the patient's skin.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-213", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which condition creates the greatest risk of RF-induced thermal injury from surface coil cables during MRI?", "options": ["Cables routed straight with insulation padding between cables and skin", "Cables forming loops while in direct contact with the patient's skin", "Cables securely fastened to the coil housing with no patient contact", "Cables positioned along the bore wall away from the patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The greatest risk for RF thermal injury occurs when cables form loops (which concentrate induced RF energy) while simultaneously making direct contact with the patient's skin. This combination creates a focused pathway for current flow through the skin at the contact point. Proper cable management requires straight routing with insulating padding between all cables and the patient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-214", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "An emergency magnet quench is performed in order to:", "options": ["Improve magnetic field homogeneity during scanning", "Rapidly eliminate the magnetic field by boiling off the cryogen", "Reset the gradient amplifiers after a system fault", "Reduce acoustic noise levels during a scan"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A quench rapidly destroys the superconductivity of the magnet coils by boiling off the liquid helium cryogen, causing the magnetic field to collapse. This emergency procedure is reserved for life-threatening situations where the magnetic field itself is trapping a person or a ferromagnetic object is pinning a patient. Quenching is irreversible and extremely costly.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 365 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-215", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "During an emergency magnet quench, patients and personnel must be evacuated from the scan room primarily to avoid:", "options": ["Asphyxiation from oxygen displacement by helium gas", "Exposure to increased RF energy during the quench process", "Electrical shock from the demagnetizing coils", "Contamination from cryogenic fluid residue"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "During a quench, a massive volume of helium gas is released rapidly into the scan room, displacing oxygen and creating an asphyxiation hazard. The helium can also cause frostbite on contact with skin, and the rapid pressure change and noise can potentially cause hearing damage. The primary and most life-threatening risk is oxygen displacement leading to asphyxiation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 365 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-216", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which MRI-related parameter is regulated by the FDA to protect patients from potential hearing damage?", "options": ["Bore diameter", "Scan duration per sequence", "Acoustic noise levels", "Static magnetic field strength"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FDA regulates acoustic noise levels generated during MRI scanning, as the rapid switching of gradient coils produces sound pressure levels that can exceed 99 dB(A) and cause temporary or permanent hearing damage. Hearing protection (earplugs and/or headphones) must be provided to all patients. Bore dimensions and scan times are not directly regulated by the FDA.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-217", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "For optimal operation of an MRI system, the recommended ambient temperature and relative humidity ranges for the equipment room are approximately:", "options": ["30–50°F / 30–50% humidity", "65–75°F / 45–60% humidity", "80–90°F / 70–100% humidity", "No specific temperature or humidity range is required"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRI systems require a controlled environment with ambient temperature approximately 65–75°F (18–24°C) and moderate relative humidity (typically 45–60%) to ensure proper operation of the superconducting magnet, gradient amplifiers, and electronics. Excessive heat or humidity can cause system faults, increased helium boil-off, and degraded image quality.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 344 / Vendor specifications"}, {"id": "SA-218", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The traditional threshold fringe field level at which patients with non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemakers must be excluded is:", "options": ["50 gauss (5 mT)", "15 gauss (1.5 mT)", "5 gauss (0.5 mT)", "1 gauss (0.1 mT)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line has traditionally been the threshold beyond which patients with non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemakers and other electronically active implants must not be exposed. This fringe field level marks the controlled access boundary around the MRI scanner. Modern MR Conditional pacemakers may be approved for scanning at higher field strengths under specific conditions.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-219", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Passive magnetic field shielding of the MRI suite is achieved by lining the room with:", "options": ["Copper sheets", "Steel plates", "Lead sheets", "Aluminum foil"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Passive magnetic shielding uses ferromagnetic material (steel) to contain the fringe magnetic field by providing a low-reluctance return path for magnetic flux lines. Copper is used for RF shielding (Faraday cage), not magnetic shielding. Lead is used for ionizing radiation shielding and has no magnetic shielding properties.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326 / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-220", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Radiofrequency (RF) shielding of the MRI scan room is achieved by lining the room with:", "options": ["Copper (Faraday cage)", "Steel plates", "Lead sheets", "Concrete reinforcement"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "RF shielding uses a Faraday cage constructed of highly conductive material — typically copper or aluminum — to prevent external RF interference from entering the scan room and to contain the RF energy generated during imaging. Steel is used for magnetic shielding, and lead is used for ionizing radiation shielding.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 337 / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-221", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The 5-gauss line around an MRI scanner represents the boundary beyond which:", "options": ["Image quality begins to degrade due to field inhomogeneity", "The general public should not have uncontrolled access due to potential implant and device interactions", "Gradient coil noise can no longer be heard", "The RF field can no longer induce tissue heating"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line defines the controlled access boundary around the MRI scanner. Beyond this level, the fringe magnetic field can potentially affect cardiac pacemakers, neurostimulators, and other electronically active implants. The general public must not have uncontrolled access to areas exceeding this threshold. Facility design must ensure the 5-gauss line does not extend into unrestricted public areas.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-222", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The unit of measurement used to quantify RF energy absorption by the body during MRI is:", "options": ["Tesla per second", "Decibels (dB)", "Watts per kilogram (W/kg)", "Millitesla per meter (mT/m)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The Specific Absorption Rate (SAR) is measured in watts per kilogram (W/kg) and represents the rate at which RF energy is absorbed by body tissue during MRI. Higher SAR values indicate greater RF energy deposition and increased tissue heating potential. Tesla measures magnetic field strength, and decibels measure sound intensity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-223", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The primary purpose of magnetic field shielding (either active or passive) in MRI facility design is to:", "options": ["Allow ferromagnetic objects to safely enter the scan room", "Confine the fringe field to within the scan room rather than extending into adjacent areas", "Eliminate the fringe field entirely so it does not exist", "Reduce acoustic noise transmitted through the walls"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magnetic shielding — whether active (self-shielded superconducting coils) or passive (steel room lining) — is designed to contain the fringe magnetic field within the scan room or its immediate surroundings. This prevents the 5-gauss line from extending into uncontrolled public areas. The fringe field cannot be completely eliminated while maintaining the imaging field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326 / MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-224", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Fringe field management is least problematic for which MRI system type?", "options": ["High-field superconducting systems without self-shielding", "Mid-field superconducting systems", "Low-field vertical permanent magnet systems", "Ultra-high-field research systems (7T+)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Low-field permanent magnet systems (typically 0.2–0.7T with vertical field orientation) generate minimal fringe fields that are naturally contained close to the magnet, making siting and fringe field management straightforward. Higher field superconducting systems produce more extensive fringe fields requiring active or passive shielding. Ultra-high-field systems present the greatest fringe field challenges.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 315 / MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-225", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "According to IEC guidelines, the SAR limit for the head in normal operating mode is:", "options": ["2.0 W/kg", "3.2 W/kg", "4.0 W/kg", "12.0 W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The IEC (International Electrotechnical Commission) sets the SAR limit for the head at 3.2 W/kg in normal operating mode. The whole-body SAR limit is 4.0 W/kg in normal mode, while 10 W/kg applies to any gram of tissue in the head/torso and 12 W/kg applies to any gram in the extremities. These limits are designed to prevent excessive tissue heating.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / IEC 60601-2-33"}, {"id": "SA-226", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The whole-body SAR limit in normal operating mode, as established by IEC guidelines, is:", "options": ["0.4 W/kg", "2.0 W/kg", "4.0 W/kg", "8.0 W/kg"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The IEC sets the whole-body SAR limit at 4.0 W/kg for normal operating mode. In first-level controlled mode (requiring medical supervision), the limit increases to 4.0 W/kg averaged over any 10-gram tissue mass. The 0.4 W/kg value is not a current IEC SAR limit. These limits are designed to prevent core body temperature increases exceeding 1°C.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / IEC 60601-2-33"}, {"id": "SA-227", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The term used to describe the rate at which radiofrequency energy is absorbed by body tissue during MRI is:", "options": ["Signal acquisition ratio (SAR)", "Specific absorption rate (SAR)", "Spatial attenuation response (SAR)", "Spectral amplitude range (SAR)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Specific Absorption Rate (SAR) is the standard metric for quantifying RF energy absorption in tissue during MRI, measured in watts per kilogram (W/kg). SAR is influenced by RF frequency, flip angle, number of RF pulses, patient body habitus, and coil configuration. Higher SAR values correlate with greater tissue heating potential.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-228", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The predominant biological effect of radiofrequency (RF) fields during MRI is:", "options": ["Peripheral nerve stimulation", "Tissue heating", "Hypothermia", "Acoustic trauma"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The primary biological effect of RF energy absorption during MRI is tissue heating. RF energy is deposited in tissue and converted to thermal energy, which the body must dissipate. Excessive RF deposition can raise core body temperature. Peripheral nerve stimulation is the primary biological effect of time-varying gradient fields, not RF fields.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-229", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The RF antenna effect from improperly managed cables or conductive materials in the MRI bore can result in:", "options": ["Improved signal-to-noise ratio", "RF interference artifacts only", "Thermal injury to the patient, including potential burns", "Reduced acoustic noise during scanning"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The antenna effect occurs when conductive materials (cables, wires, or conductive implants) concentrate RF energy at focal points, potentially generating sufficient heat to cause thermal burns or even ignite flammable materials. While RF interference artifacts can also occur, the primary safety concern is thermal injury. Proper cable routing and insulating padding are essential preventive measures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-230", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "IEC guidelines limit the RF-induced increase in core body temperature to no more than:", "options": ["0.1°C", "0.5°C", "1°C", "2°C"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The IEC limits RF-induced core body temperature rise to 1°C in normal operating mode. This threshold is based on research showing that temperature elevations beyond 1°C can impair thermoregulatory function, particularly in vulnerable populations such as patients with impaired thermoregulation, fever, or cardiovascular compromise. SAR limits are calibrated to maintain temperature increases below this threshold.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / IEC 60601-2-33"}, {"id": "SA-231", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The distribution pattern of RF-induced tissue heating within the body during MRI is:", "options": ["Uniform throughout all tissue layers", "Greatest at the body surface, decreasing toward the center", "Greatest at the body center, decreasing toward the surface", "Concentrated exclusively in bone tissue"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF energy deposition follows a surface-to-center gradient, with the highest energy absorption occurring at the body surface (skin and subcutaneous tissue) and decreasing toward the core. This is due to the skin effect, where high-frequency electromagnetic waves penetrate tissue with exponentially decreasing intensity. This pattern means superficial tissues and the skin surface are at greatest risk for thermal injury.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-232", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Radiofrequency (RF) energy used in MRI is classified as:", "options": ["High-energy ionizing radiation", "High-energy non-ionizing radiation", "Low-energy non-ionizing radiation", "Low-energy ionizing radiation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "RF energy used in MRI falls within the non-ionizing portion of the electromagnetic spectrum at relatively low energy levels (typically 1–300 MHz). Unlike X-rays or gamma rays, RF waves do not have sufficient energy to ionize atoms or break chemical bonds. The primary biological effect of RF in MRI is tissue heating, not cellular damage from ionization.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-233", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "When the flip angle is doubled during an MRI sequence, RF energy deposition (SAR) increases by a factor of:", "options": ["2", "4", "8", "16"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "SAR is proportional to the square of the flip angle. Therefore, doubling the flip angle increases SAR by a factor of 2² = 4. This quadratic relationship means that small increases in flip angle can produce significant increases in RF energy deposition and tissue heating. This is why gradient echo sequences with small flip angles deposit far less RF energy than spin echo sequences using 90°/180° pulses.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-234", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which pulse sequence type deposits the most RF energy (highest SAR) for a given imaging protocol?", "options": ["Gradient echo", "Echo planar imaging", "Conventional spin echo", "Fast spin echo (FSE/TSE)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Fast spin echo sequences deposit the highest SAR because they use multiple 180° refocusing pulses per TR interval (the echo train). Each 180° pulse deposits four times the RF energy of a 90° pulse. Long echo trains with short echo spacing significantly increase cumulative RF deposition compared to conventional spin echo (one 180° per TR) or gradient echo (no refocusing pulses).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / MIP Ch. 3 p. 68"}, {"id": "SA-235", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which anatomic structures are most sensitive to temperature increases from RF energy deposition during MRI?", "options": ["Brain and spinal cord", "Vertebral bodies", "Eyes (globes) and testes", "Liver and pancreas"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The eyes and testes are the most thermally sensitive structures because they have limited blood flow for heat dissipation. The lens of the eye is avascular and particularly vulnerable to thermal damage, which can lead to cataract formation. The testes are temperature-sensitive organs where even modest heating can impair spermatogenesis. Other well-perfused organs dissipate RF-generated heat more efficiently.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-236", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The FDA considers clinical MRI systems operating at which maximum static field strength to be non-significant risk for adult patients?", "options": ["1.5 T", "3.0 T", "4.0 T", "8.0 T"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "In 2003, the FDA raised the non-significant risk threshold for clinical MRI to 8 T for adult patients and children over 1 month of age. Systems operating at or below 8 T do not require an investigational device exemption (IDE) for clinical use. For neonates under 1 month of age, the non-significant risk level is 4 T.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / FDA Guidance 2003"}, {"id": "SA-237", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "A magnetic field strength of 1 Tesla is equivalent to how many gauss?", "options": ["1,000 gauss", "10,000 gauss", "100,000 gauss", "100 gauss"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "One Tesla equals 10,000 gauss. This conversion is essential for understanding fringe field measurements, as fringe fields are typically expressed in gauss (e.g., the 5-gauss line). A 1.5 T scanner therefore has a main field of 15,000 gauss, and a 3.0 T scanner operates at 30,000 gauss.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1 p. 1 / MIP Ch. 9 p. 313"}, {"id": "SA-238", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT directly regulated by the FDA for clinical MRI systems?", "options": ["Maximum static magnetic field strength", "RF absorption limits (SAR)", "Gradient coil physical length", "Acoustic noise levels"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FDA regulates static field strength (non-significant risk thresholds), SAR limits for RF energy deposition, dB/dt limits for time-varying gradient fields, and acoustic noise levels. The physical length of gradient coils is a hardware design parameter determined by the manufacturer and is not directly regulated by the FDA as a patient safety metric.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / FDA Guidance"}, {"id": "SA-239", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "At which static magnetic field level have no confirmed adverse biological effects been reported in humans?", "options": ["Fields above 4 T", "Fields above 8 T", "Fields below approximately 2–3 T", "Any field strength currently used clinically"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Extensive research has shown no confirmed harmful biological effects from exposure to static magnetic fields at levels up to approximately 2–3 T, which encompasses the vast majority of clinical MRI systems. At higher field strengths (7T+), transient sensory effects such as vertigo, metallic taste, and magnetophosphenes have been reported, though no permanent injury has been documented.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-240", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The static magnetic field strength at the isocenter of an MRI scanner is measured in units of:", "options": ["Gauss", "Tesla", "Watts per kilogram", "Decibels"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The main magnetic field strength (B0) at isocenter is expressed in Tesla (T). Clinical systems typically operate at 1.5 T or 3.0 T. While gauss is also a unit of magnetic field strength (1 T = 10,000 G), Tesla is the standard SI unit used to describe the main field of MRI systems. Gauss is more commonly used for fringe field measurements.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1 p. 1 / MIP Ch. 9 p. 313"}, {"id": "SA-241", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The magnetic fringe field surrounding an MRI scanner is typically measured in units of:", "options": ["Gauss", "Tesla", "Watts per kilogram", "Decibels"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Fringe field measurements are conventionally expressed in gauss (G) because the values involved are much smaller than the main field. The 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line is the standard controlled access boundary. While Tesla could technically be used, gauss is the standard unit for fringe field mapping and safety signage in MRI facilities.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / MIP Ch. 9 p. 313"}, {"id": "SA-242", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The translational force experienced by a ferromagnetic object near an MRI scanner depends primarily on:", "options": ["The object's ferromagnetic properties and the spatial field gradient", "The object's color and surface texture", "The ambient room temperature", "The RF frequency of the scanner"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The translational (projectile) force on a ferromagnetic object depends on its ferromagnetic susceptibility, mass, geometry, and the spatial gradient of the magnetic field (how rapidly the field strength changes with distance from isocenter). The spatial field gradient is strongest at the bore entrance, which is why the projectile risk is greatest at that location. The main field strength and object properties together determine the magnitude of the force.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-243", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The magnetohydrodynamic effect observed on ECG monitoring during MRI manifests as:", "options": ["ST segment depression", "Widened QRS complex", "Elevated T-wave amplitude", "Prolonged PR interval"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When blood (a conductive fluid) flows through the static magnetic field, the magnetohydrodynamic effect induces a voltage that superimposes on the ECG signal, most prominently augmenting the T-wave. This artifact increases with field strength and can mimic hyperkalemia on ECG. It is not a true cardiac abnormality and resolves when the patient exits the magnetic field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-244", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Hearing protection for patients undergoing MRI is:", "options": ["Optional and provided only upon patient request", "Required for all patients and should consist of earplugs, headphones, or both", "Required only for pediatric patients", "Unnecessary if the scanner operates below 1.5 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hearing protection is required for all patients undergoing MRI, as gradient coil switching generates acoustic noise levels that can exceed 99 dB(A) and potentially cause temporary or permanent hearing damage. Both earplugs and MR-compatible headphones are acceptable, and using both together provides optimal protection. This requirement applies at all clinical field strengths.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-245", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which statement best describes the safety concerns associated with gradient magnetic fields during MRI?", "options": ["Gradients generate RF energy that heats tissue", "Rapid gradient switching produces acoustic noise and can induce peripheral nerve stimulation", "Gradients create a static projectile risk for ferromagnetic objects", "Gradients have no known safety concerns at clinical levels"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient coils produce two primary safety concerns: acoustic noise from rapid mechanical vibration of the gradient coils (Lorentz forces), and peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS) from rapidly changing magnetic fields inducing electrical currents in tissue. The heat generated in the gradient coils is managed by the cooling system and does not directly heat the patient. RF energy deposition is a separate concern from gradient fields.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / MIP Ch. 9 p. 330"}, {"id": "SA-246", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The T-wave elevation observed on ECG during MRI is caused by which phenomenon?", "options": ["Magnetohydrodynamic (hemodynamic) effect", "Magnetophosphenes", "Peripheral nerve stimulation", "RF-induced tissue heating"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The magnetohydrodynamic (also called magneto-hemodynamic) effect produces a voltage as blood flows through the static magnetic field, which appears as T-wave elevation on ECG tracings. This is a field-induced artifact, not a true cardiac abnormality. Magnetophosphenes are a separate phenomenon involving visual light flashes caused by time-varying magnetic fields stimulating the retina.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-247", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The visual phenomenon of perceiving flashing lights or 'stars' during exposure to rapidly changing magnetic fields is known as:", "options": ["Magnetohydrodynamic effect", "Peripheral nerve stimulation", "RF interference artifact", "Magnetophosphenes"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Magnetophosphenes are the perception of flickering lights caused by time-varying (gradient) magnetic fields inducing small electrical currents in the retina. This is a transient, harmless sensory effect that resolves immediately when the gradient fields are turned off. The magnetohydrodynamic effect involves blood flow through the static field and produces ECG changes, not visual phenomena.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-248", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Current regulatory limits on time-varying (gradient) magnetic fields (dB/dt) are based on:", "options": ["A fixed numerical value of 6 T/s for all systems", "The threshold for peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS)", "A fixed gradient amplitude of 10 G/cm", "The maximum SAR value for the sequence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Modern IEC/FDA guidelines for time-varying magnetic fields are based on PNS thresholds rather than a single fixed dB/dt value. The normal operating mode limits dB/dt to 80% of the mean PNS threshold, while the first-level controlled mode allows operation up to 100% of the PNS threshold with medical supervision. This approach accounts for the complex relationship between gradient waveform, pulse duration, and nerve stimulation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / IEC 60601-2-33"}, {"id": "SA-249", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a biological effect of time-varying (gradient) magnetic fields?", "options": ["Tissue heating and increased core body temperature", "Acoustic noise and potential hearing damage", "Peripheral nerve stimulation and tingling sensations", "Magnetophosphenes (flashing lights)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Tissue heating is a biological effect of RF (radiofrequency) fields, not time-varying gradient fields. Gradient fields produce acoustic noise (from coil vibration), peripheral nerve stimulation (from induced currents in tissue), and magnetophosphenes (from retinal stimulation). Distinguishing between RF effects and gradient field effects is important for understanding MRI safety.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357, 363"}, {"id": "SA-250", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which pulse sequence type produces the greatest concern for time-varying magnetic field (dB/dt) effects?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Echo planar imaging (EPI)", "Fast spin echo"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Echo planar imaging (EPI) uses the most rapidly switching gradient waveforms of any standard pulse sequence, producing the highest dB/dt values and the greatest risk of peripheral nerve stimulation. EPI acquires all k-space data after a single excitation by rapidly oscillating the readout gradient, requiring extremely fast gradient switching that approaches or reaches PNS thresholds.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / MIP Ch. 4 p. 122"}, {"id": "SA-251", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Gradient magnetic field strength is measured in which unit(s)?", "options": ["Watts per kilogram (W/kg)", "Millitesla per meter (mT/m)", "Decibels (dB)", "Tesla per second (T/s)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gradient field strength (amplitude) is expressed in millitesla per meter (mT/m) or equivalently in gauss per centimeter (G/cm), both describing how much the magnetic field changes per unit distance. Modern clinical systems achieve gradient amplitudes of 30–80 mT/m. T/s (Tesla per second) measures the rate of change of the field (slew rate related), and W/kg measures SAR.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 330 / MIP Ch. 5 p. 129"}, {"id": "SA-252", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The primary safety concern with gradient magnetic fields is their ability to:", "options": ["Generate large amounts of ionizing radiation", "Induce electrical currents in conductive materials and tissue", "Permanently magnetize body tissues", "Cause long-term cognitive impairment"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rapidly changing gradient fields induce electrical currents in any conductive medium, including body tissue, implanted wires, and cables. In tissue, these induced currents can stimulate peripheral nerves (causing tingling or muscle twitching). In conductive implants or monitoring leads, induced currents can cause localized heating. Gradient fields do not produce ionizing radiation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / MIP Ch. 9 p. 330"}, {"id": "SA-253", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Reported biological effects of time-varying magnetic fields in MRI include:", "options": ["Cutaneous sensations, magnetophosphenes, and involuntary muscle contractions", "Permanent hearing loss and chronic headaches", "Increased cancer risk after repeated exposures", "Irreversible peripheral neuropathy"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Documented effects of time-varying gradient fields include mild cutaneous (skin) tingling, magnetophosphenes (visual light flashes from retinal stimulation), and at higher dB/dt levels, involuntary muscle contractions. At extreme levels, cardiac stimulation is theoretically possible but has not been reported with clinical MRI systems. All reported effects are transient and resolve when gradient activity ceases.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / IEC 60601-2-33"}, {"id": "SA-254", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The FDA non-significant risk level for static magnetic field exposure in clinical MRI for patients over 1 month of age is:", "options": ["1.5 T", "3.0 T", "4.0 T", "8.0 T"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The FDA classifies clinical MRI systems operating at up to 8 T as non-significant risk for patients over 1 month of age. For neonates (under 1 month), the threshold is 4 T. These thresholds determine whether an investigational device exemption (IDE) is required for clinical use of the MRI system.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / FDA Guidance 2003"}, {"id": "SA-255", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The FDA non-significant risk level for the static magnetic field that applies to ALL patient populations, including neonates, is:", "options": ["1.5 T", "3.0 T", "4.0 T", "8.0 T"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "While the FDA allows up to 8 T for patients over 1 month of age, the most restrictive threshold that applies to all patient populations including neonates (under 1 month) is 4 T. Systems operating above 4 T require additional safety considerations and may need an IDE when scanning neonates. This distinction is important for facilities that image very young infants.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / FDA Guidance 2003"}, {"id": "SA-256", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which pulse sequence generates the most rapid gradient switching and therefore poses the greatest risk for peripheral nerve stimulation?", "options": ["Conventional spin echo", "Gradient echo", "Fast spin echo", "Echo planar imaging (EPI)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Echo planar imaging (EPI) requires the fastest gradient switching rates of any standard clinical sequence, as it must traverse all of k-space in a single shot or very few excitations. This produces the highest dB/dt values and brings the system closest to PNS thresholds. Diffusion-weighted imaging, which uses EPI readouts combined with strong diffusion gradients, represents one of the highest dB/dt applications in clinical practice.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / MIP Ch. 4 p. 122"}, {"id": "SA-257", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Gradient rise time refers to:", "options": ["The time required for a gradient to reach its maximum amplitude", "The duration of one complete TR interval", "The total scan time for a single acquisition", "The time between successive phase-encoding steps"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Gradient rise time is the time required for a gradient coil to ramp from zero to its maximum amplitude. Shorter rise times enable faster gradient switching (higher slew rates), which reduces minimum TE and improves temporal resolution but also increases the risk of peripheral nerve stimulation and acoustic noise. Slew rate equals maximum gradient amplitude divided by rise time.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 330"}, {"id": "SA-258", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The gradient duty cycle describes:", "options": ["The time required for a gradient to reach maximum amplitude", "The total duration of one TR interval", "The fraction of the TR period during which the gradients are actively switched on", "The change in magnetic field strength per unit distance"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gradient duty cycle is the proportion of time during each TR that the gradient coils are actively energized. Higher duty cycles mean the gradients are on for a greater percentage of each repetition, producing more heat in the gradient coils and requiring more robust cooling. Sequences like EPI have very high duty cycles. Rise time describes how quickly a gradient reaches peak amplitude, and gradient strength (mT/m) describes the spatial field variation.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 330"}, {"id": "SA-259", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "To prevent auditory damage during MRI, patients should be provided with:", "options": ["Earplugs only", "MR-compatible headphones only", "Both earplugs and headphones for maximum protection", "No hearing protection if the scan is shorter than 10 minutes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "For optimal hearing protection during MRI, both earplugs (which provide passive noise reduction) and MR-compatible headphones (which add further attenuation) should be offered to patients. Combined use provides the highest noise reduction ratio. All patients must receive hearing protection regardless of scan duration, as even brief sequences can produce harmful noise levels exceeding 99 dB(A).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-260", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "The standard initial screening method for detecting metallic foreign bodies in the orbits prior to MRI is:", "options": ["Plain film radiography of the orbits", "Computed tomography of the orbits", "MRI of the orbits with gradient echo", "Ophthalmic ultrasound"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Plain film orbital radiographs are the accepted standard of care for initial screening of suspected intraocular metallic foreign bodies. They can detect fragments as small as 0.1 mm. CT provides greater sensitivity for very small fragments but is used when plain films are negative but clinical suspicion remains high. MRI must never be used to screen for ferromagnetic foreign bodies.", "reference": "ACR MR Safety / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-261", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which of the following items can generally be considered safe for entry into the MRI scan room without additional testing?", "options": ["Aluminum oxygen cylinder", "Standard hospital respirator", "Standard hospital fire extinguisher", "Standard metal IV pole"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Aluminum is non-ferromagnetic and will not experience translational force in the magnetic field, making aluminum oxygen cylinders generally safe for the MRI environment. Standard hospital respirators, fire extinguishers, and IV poles may contain ferromagnetic components and cannot be assumed safe without specific MR safety verification from the manufacturer.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-262", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following is an absolute contraindication for MRI?", "options": ["Pregnancy in the first trimester", "Elevated body temperature (fever)", "Non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemaker", "Non-MR Conditional ferromagnetic aneurysm clip"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemaker remains one of the most critical absolute contraindications for MRI due to risks of lead heating, device malfunction, and cardiac arrhythmia. While non-MR Conditional ferromagnetic aneurysm clips are also contraindicated, many modern clips are MR Conditional. Pregnancy and fever are not absolute contraindications.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-263", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "The most commonly reported adverse effect following gadolinium-based contrast agent administration is:", "options": ["Anaphylaxis", "Headache", "Nausea", "Injection site pain"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Headache is the most frequently reported adverse effect of gadolinium-based contrast agents. Other common mild effects include nausea, dizziness, and injection site coldness or pain. Severe reactions including anaphylaxis are extremely rare, occurring in fewer than 0.01% of administrations.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "SA-264", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "What is the standard clinical dosage of gadolinium-based contrast agents for MRI?", "options": ["1.0 mmol/kg body weight", "0.5 mmol/kg body weight", "0.1 mmol/kg body weight", "0.01 mmol/kg body weight"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The standard clinical dose for most gadolinium-based contrast agents is 0.1 mmol/kg body weight (equivalent to 0.2 mL/kg of a 0.5 M solution). A dose of 1.0 mmol/kg would be ten times the standard dose and is not used in routine clinical practice. Dosing must be weight-based and adjusted for renal function.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "SA-265", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "In an MRI Faraday cage, which structural element requires RF shielding in addition to the walls and ceiling?", "options": ["The patient table rails", "The gradient coil housing", "Windows, doors, and all wiring/cables entering the room", "The helium vent piping"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A complete Faraday cage must shield all penetrations into the scan room, including windows (with conductive mesh or glass), doors (with RF gaskets), and all wiring and cables (with RF filters or waveguides). Any gap in the shielding allows external RF interference to enter and degrade image quality, or allows scanner RF to leak out.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 337 / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-266", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Analog watches and magnetic-stripe credit cards should be excluded from fringe fields exceeding:", "options": ["5 gauss", "10 gauss", "50 gauss", "100 gauss"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Analog watches and credit cards with magnetic stripes can be damaged by fringe fields as low as 100 gauss (10 mT). Electronic equipment, computers, and magnetic media are typically restricted at 50 gauss, while the 5-gauss line serves as the controlled access boundary for individuals with pacemakers. These thresholds guide facility design and signage placement.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-267", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The fringe field level at which non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemakers must be excluded from the MRI environment is:", "options": ["5 gauss (0.5 mT)", "10 gauss (1.0 mT)", "50 gauss (5.0 mT)", "100 gauss (10 mT)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The 5-gauss (0.5 mT) line is the established threshold for excluding patients with non-MR Conditional cardiac pacemakers and other electronically active implants. Warning signs and restricted access controls must be posted at the 5-gauss boundary. This is the most restrictive fringe field threshold in MRI safety.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-268", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which of the following is a valid reason for initiating an emergency magnet quench?", "options": ["To allow firefighters to safely enter the scan room during a fire", "To improve magnetic field homogeneity after a shimming failure", "To reduce acoustic noise during a long scan sequence", "To vent excess helium during routine cryogen maintenance"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "An emergency quench may be initiated to allow first responders (firefighters, code team) to safely enter the scan room, or to release a patient trapped by a ferromagnetic object. Quenching is an irreversible, costly emergency measure and is never performed for routine maintenance, shimming, or noise reduction. The magnet must be re-ramped to field after a quench.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 365 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-269", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Regarding passive magnetic shielding with ferromagnetic material (iron/steel), which statement is correct?", "options": ["Placing iron in the walls pulls the fringe field closer to the magnet, containing it", "The further the iron is placed from the magnet, the less material is needed", "Only a millimeter of iron is needed to reduce the fringe field by half", "Passive shielding eliminates the fringe field entirely"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Passive shielding works by providing a low-reluctance return path for magnetic flux lines through ferromagnetic material (iron or steel) in the walls. This pulls the fringe field inward, closer to the magnet, effectively containing it within the scan room. The closer the iron is to the magnet, the less material is needed — not the opposite.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326 / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-270", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which safety practice regarding cables and implants in the MRI environment is most critical?", "options": ["Cables may be loosely looped if they are not touching the patient", "Cable insulation only needs inspection during annual QC testing", "Ensure cables are not looped, do not touch the patient's skin, and verify implant MR safety before scanning", "Only cables longer than 2 meters require inspection before use"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Before every MRI examination, cables must be routed straight without loops, insulation must be inspected for damage, and pads must separate all cables from the patient's skin to prevent RF burns. Additionally, the MR safety status of any implant (including aneurysm clips) must be verified using manufacturer documentation before proceeding with scanning.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-271", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which statement about biological effects of the static magnetic field in MRI is accurate?", "options": ["Significant effects on cell growth have been documented below 2 T", "No verified studies demonstrate cancer induction from the static field at clinical strengths", "The static field causes permanent changes to blood chemistry", "Prolonged exposure to 1.5 T causes cumulative genetic damage"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Extensive research has found no verified evidence of cancer induction or significant harmful biological effects from static magnetic fields at clinical MRI strengths. Small electrical potentials are induced in blood vessels flowing perpendicular to the field (magnetohydrodynamic effect), but these are transient and produce no lasting harm. No effects on cell growth or morphology have been demonstrated below 2 T.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-272", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which guideline regarding pregnancy and MRI is considered current best practice?", "options": ["Pregnant patients must never undergo MRI under any circumstances", "Pregnant technologists may choose to avoid the scan room during the first trimester and during image acquisition", "MRI is contraindicated throughout all three trimesters of pregnancy", "Pregnant patients require gadolinium contrast for enhanced fetal imaging"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current ACR guidelines state that MRI may be performed on pregnant patients when the clinical benefit outweighs the theoretical risk. Pregnant technologists may reasonably choose to remain outside the scan room during the first trimester and during active scanning as a precautionary measure. Pregnancy is not an absolute contraindication to MRI, and gadolinium is generally avoided during pregnancy unless absolutely necessary.", "reference": "ACR MR Safety / MIP Ch. 10"}, {"id": "SA-273", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following implanted devices is generally considered safe for MRI scanning?", "options": ["Non-MR Conditional cochlear implant", "Abdominal surgical clips anchored by fibrous tissue", "Electrically active bone growth stimulator", "Non-MR Conditional neurostimulator"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Abdominal surgical clips and pins become anchored by fibrous tissue over time and are generally considered safe for MRI. Cochlear implants and electrically active bone growth stimulators are typically contraindicated unless specifically labeled as MR Conditional, as they contain electronic components and/or ferromagnetic materials that can malfunction or heat in the magnetic field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-274", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Time-varying gradient magnetic fields can induce which biological effects?", "options": ["Tissue heating identical to RF energy deposition", "Electrical currents in nerves, blood vessels, and retinal phosphenes (flashing lights)", "Permanent magnetization of hemoglobin in red blood cells", "Ionization of tissue water molecules"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rapidly switching gradient fields induce small electrical currents in conductive tissues, including peripheral nerves (causing tingling or PNS), blood vessels, and the retina (producing magnetophosphenes or visual flashing lights). Tissue heating is primarily an RF effect, not a gradient field effect. Gradient fields do not ionize tissue or permanently magnetize blood components.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-275", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "According to IEC guidelines, which SAR limit applies to the whole head in normal operating mode?", "options": ["0.4 W/kg", "3.2 W/kg", "4.0 W/kg", "8.0 W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The IEC establishes the head SAR limit at 3.2 W/kg in normal operating mode. The whole-body limit is 4.0 W/kg, and localized SAR limits are 10 W/kg per gram of tissue in the head/torso and 12 W/kg in the extremities. The 0.4 W/kg value cited in some older references is not a current IEC threshold.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357 / IEC 60601-2-33"}, {"id": "SA-276", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "According to the ACR White Paper on MR Safety, the restricted control area where all patients and personnel must have their MRI screening verified before proceeding is designated as:", "options": ["Zone I — the general public access area", "Zone II — the interface between public and controlled areas", "Zone III — the restricted access control area", "Zone IV — the magnet room itself"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "ACR Zone III is the last checkpoint before the magnet room where final screening verification occurs. Access to Zone III is physically restricted (locked door or badge access) and supervised by Level 2 MR personnel. Zone IV is the actual scanner room containing the magnet. Patients must not proceed to Zone IV until all screening is complete in Zone III. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 347)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 347"}, {"id": "SA-277", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The projectile (missile) effect in the MRI environment—where ferromagnetic objects are forcefully accelerated toward the scanner—is caused by the attractive force of:", "options": ["The time-varying gradient magnetic fields", "The radiofrequency (RF) electromagnetic field", "The static magnetic field (B₀)", "The shim coil correction fields"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The static magnetic field (B₀) is always on in superconducting systems and exerts a powerful attractive force on ferromagnetic objects. This force increases exponentially as the object approaches the bore opening due to the steep spatial field gradient. The projectile effect is the most dangerous and most commonly reported MRI safety incident. Neither RF energy nor gradient fields produce significant translational force on objects. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 351; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-278", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The primary biological effect associated with the time-varying gradient magnetic fields during MRI is:", "options": ["Tissue heating from RF energy absorption", "Peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS) from induced electrical currents", "Oxygen desaturation of arterial blood", "Cataract formation in the crystalline lens"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Rapidly switching gradient fields induce small electrical currents in conductive tissues (primarily peripheral nerves), which can cause involuntary muscle twitching, tingling sensations, or in extreme cases, cardiac stimulation. The rate of change of the gradient field (dB/dt) determines the severity of nerve stimulation. PNS is the dose-limiting bioeffect for gradient performance. Tissue heating (choice A) is associated with RF energy, not gradients. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 363)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-279", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The primary biological risk associated with absorption of radiofrequency (RF) energy during MRI scanning is:", "options": ["Sensorineural hearing loss", "Tissue heating (thermal injury)", "Magnetophosphenes (perception of flashing lights)", "Vertigo and spatial disorientation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF energy deposited in tissue during excitation pulses is absorbed and converted to heat through molecular friction. The specific absorption rate (SAR), measured in watts per kilogram, quantifies this energy deposition. Excessive SAR can raise core body temperature to dangerous levels, particularly in patients with impaired thermoregulation. Acoustic noise (choice A) causes hearing risk, but that is a gradient effect, not RF. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 357)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 357"}, {"id": "SA-280", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The FDA’s current upper limit for static magnetic field strength in clinical MRI of adults and children older than one month is:", "options": ["3.0 Tesla", "4.0 Tesla", "8.0 Tesla", "1.5 Tesla"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The FDA classifies MRI systems operating at static field strengths up to 8 T for adults and children over one month as non-significant risk devices. For neonates (under one month old), the limit is 4 T. The previous 4 T limit for adults was revised upward as safety data accumulated at higher field strengths. This is a frequently tested factual recall item on the ARRT exam. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; FDA Guidance Document)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-281", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "An implant or device labeled with the ASTM green square symbol (“MR Safe”) is defined as an item that:", "options": ["Has not been tested in the MRI environment", "Is entirely non-conducting, non-metallic, and non-magnetic, posing no known hazards in all MRI environments", "Is safe to scan only at field strengths of 1.5 T or below", "Contains weakly ferromagnetic components that can be safely scanned with monitoring"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ASTM MR Safe label (green square) indicates the device poses no known hazards in any MRI environment because it contains no metallic, conducting, or magnetic components—typically constructed of plastic, silicone, or glass. This is the most permissive safety designation. MR Conditional (yellow triangle) items require specific scanning conditions, while MR Unsafe (red circle) items must never enter the MRI environment. (ASTM F2503; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-282", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "An implant labeled with the ASTM yellow triangle symbol (“MR Conditional”) may be safely scanned:", "options": ["In any MRI system regardless of field strength or sequence parameters", "Under no circumstances whatsoever", "ONLY when the specific conditions listed on the device labeling are met (field strength, SAR limits, gradient slew rate, etc.)", "Only if the patient is sedated during the examination"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "MR Conditional devices have been tested and demonstrated safe under specific, clearly defined conditions. These conditions typically include maximum static field strength, maximum spatial gradient, maximum SAR, and specific coil requirements. Exceeding any stated condition converts the scan from “conditional” to potentially unsafe. The technologist must verify all conditions against the scanner’s specifications before proceeding. (ASTM F2503; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-283", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "According to IEC/FDA standards, the whole-body specific absorption rate (SAR) limit for the Normal Operating Mode is:", "options": ["4.0 W/kg", "2.0 W/kg", "3.2 W/kg", "8.0 W/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Normal Operating Mode whole-body SAR limit is 2.0 W/kg, which corresponds to an anticipated core temperature rise of approximately 0.5°C. The First Level Controlled Operating Mode allows up to 4.0 W/kg (approximately 1°C rise) with medical supervision. The 3.2 W/kg limit (choice C) applies to head SAR in Normal Mode. Understanding these thresholds is essential for managing scan parameters in temperature-sensitive patients. (IEC 60601-2-33; MIP Ch. 10 p. 358)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 358"}, {"id": "SA-284", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "An emergency magnet quench—the rapid boil-off and venting of cryogens—should be initiated ONLY when:", "options": ["Image quality has deteriorated and the magnet needs to be reset", "A person is trapped against the magnet by a ferromagnetic object or there is a life-threatening fire in Zone IV", "A power outage has interrupted the scan in progress", "The department is closing for the day and the magnet must be shut down"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A quench is an emergency-only procedure reserved for immediately life-threatening situations such as a person pinned to the magnet by a ferromagnetic projectile or an uncontrollable fire in the scan room. Quenching is dangerous (risk of asphyxiation, frostbite, and equipment damage), extremely costly (loss of helium and potential magnet damage), and requires days to weeks for magnet recovery. It should never be used for routine shutdowns or non-emergencies. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 365; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 365"}, {"id": "SA-285", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "During a magnet quench, the most immediate life-threatening risk to patients and staff who remain in the scan room is:", "options": ["Thermal burns from ignited cryogen gas", "Asphyxiation due to rapid oxygen displacement by expanding helium gas", "Electrocution from exposed wiring", "Ionizing radiation exposure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When liquid helium rapidly boils off during a quench, it expands approximately 760 times its liquid volume into gas. If the quench vent pipe fails or is obstructed, this massive volume of helium can displace breathable oxygen in the scan room within seconds, creating an immediately life-threatening asphyxiation hazard. All personnel and patients must evacuate the scan room immediately during a quench event. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 365; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 365"}, {"id": "SA-286", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "If a fire erupts inside the MRI scan room (Zone IV), the fire extinguisher used must be:", "options": ["A standard CO₂ extinguisher from the hallway supply", "A non-ferromagnetic (MR Safe or MR Conditional) fire extinguisher", "Any standard hospital Code Red fire extinguisher", "No extinguisher should be used—the magnet must be quenched first"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Standard fire extinguishers contain ferromagnetic steel components that will become dangerous projectiles in the presence of the static magnetic field. Only non-ferromagnetic fire extinguishers specifically designed and labeled for use in the MRI environment may be brought into Zone IV. These extinguishers should be clearly marked and stored within Zone III for immediate access. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 367)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 367"}, {"id": "SA-287", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "To minimize the risk of RF-induced thermal burns during MRI scanning, the technologist must ensure that:", "options": ["The patient holds their breath throughout each sequence", "No skin-to-skin contact or skin-to-bore contact occurs, and no conductive cables form loops on or near the patient", "The scan room temperature is maintained below 60°F (15°C)", "The bore ventilation fan is turned off during scanning"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "RF burns occur when induced currents concentrate in conductive pathways—including looped cables, crossed limbs (skin-to-skin contact), or points where the patient’s skin contacts the bore wall. Padding must be placed to prevent direct skin-to-bore contact, and all cables must be positioned without forming loops. Crossed legs, clasped hands, and ECG lead configurations are common risk scenarios. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 359; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 359"}, {"id": "SA-288", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Which of the following devices is generally considered an ABSOLUTE contraindication to MRI unless specifically verified as MR Conditional with documented scanning conditions?", "options": ["Titanium total hip arthroplasty", "A legacy (non-MR Conditional) cardiac pacemaker or implantable cardioverter-defibrillator", "Dental amalgam restorations", "A coronary artery stent placed more than six weeks prior"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Legacy cardiac pacemakers and ICDs that have not been specifically designed and tested for the MRI environment pose potentially lethal risks including lead heating, inappropriate device activation, and cardiac arrest. While many modern pacemakers are MR Conditional, any unidentified or legacy device is treated as an absolute contraindication until its specific make, model, and safety status are verified. Titanium implants (choice A) and dental fillings (choice C) are generally MRI compatible. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 347)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-289", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "A patient reports a history of grinding or welding metal. The MOST appropriate screening method to rule out intraocular metallic foreign bodies before MRI is:", "options": ["Asking the patient whether they experience any ocular pain", "Obtaining orbital radiographs or CT of the orbits", "Testing the area with a handheld magnet near the patient’s eye", "Passing a ferromagnetic detection wand over the patient’s face"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patient history alone is unreliable for detecting retained intraocular metallic foreign bodies—many patients are unaware of their presence. Orbital radiographs (or CT when available) are the standard of care for definitive screening because they can identify small ferromagnetic fragments that could move and damage the retina or vitreous in the magnetic field, potentially causing permanent vision loss. A handheld magnet (choice C) is dangerous and contraindicated. (ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-290", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The loud acoustic noise (knocking, banging) produced during MRI scanning is generated by:", "options": ["The cryogen recirculation pump vibrating", "Lorentz forces causing rapid mechanical vibration of the gradient coils", "The RF transmitter coil oscillating at the Larmor frequency", "The motorized patient table advancing into the bore"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When electrical current pulses through the gradient coils in the presence of the strong static magnetic field, Lorentz forces cause the coils to vibrate rapidly against their mounting structures, producing the characteristic loud knocking and banging sounds. Acoustic noise levels in MRI can exceed 100 dB, making hearing protection mandatory for all patients and personnel in Zone IV. Faster gradient switching and higher field strengths increase noise levels. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 363; MIP Ch. 9 p. 330)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-291", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "According to current ACR guidelines, the administration of gadolinium-based contrast agents to pregnant patients is managed by:", "options": ["Administering contrast routinely as in non-pregnant patients", "Avoiding gadolinium unless the clinical benefit clearly outweighs the potential risk to the fetus", "Prohibiting gadolinium under all circumstances during pregnancy", "Permitting gadolinium only during the first trimester"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium crosses the placental barrier and enters the fetal circulation, where its effects on fetal development are not fully characterized. The ACR recommends avoiding gadolinium in pregnant patients unless the potential diagnostic benefit to the mother justifies the theoretical risk to the fetus, and only after careful discussion between the ordering physician and the radiologist. This risk-benefit analysis should be documented. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "SA-292", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The visual phenomenon of flashing or flickering lights (magnetophosphenes) reported by some patients during MRI is caused by:", "options": ["RF-induced heating of the crystalline lens", "Stimulation of retinal photoreceptors by rapidly changing gradient magnetic fields", "Anxiety-related visual hallucinations from claustrophobia", "Reflection of the laser alignment lights off the bore interior"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Magnetophosphenes are benign visual sensations caused by electrical currents induced in the retina by the time-varying gradient magnetic fields. They can also occur when a patient moves their head rapidly through the static field gradient near the bore opening. This is a well-documented bioeffect that is harmless and reversible, though it may startle patients if they are not warned beforehand. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 363)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-293", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The MRI system component responsible for spatial encoding—including slice selection, phase encoding, and frequency encoding—is the:", "options": ["Static main magnet (B₀)", "Gradient coil system", "Radiofrequency coil system", "Shim coil system"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The three orthogonal gradient coils (X, Y, and Z) create controlled linear variations in the magnetic field that enable spatial localization of the MR signal. The slice-select gradient determines slice position, the phase-encoding gradient provides spatial information in one in-plane direction, and the frequency-encoding (readout) gradient provides information in the other. The RF coils (choice C) excite and receive signal but do not perform spatial encoding. (MIP Ch. 5 p. 128; MIP Ch. 9 p. 330)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 5 p. 128"}, {"id": "SA-294", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "A patient presents with a documented MR Conditional intracranial aneurysm clip. Under which circumstances may this patient undergo MRI?", "options": ["Immediately—all modern aneurysm clips are MRI compatible", "Only when the specific manufacturer, model number, and material composition are positively identified and all stated safety conditions are met", "Never—all intracranial aneurysm clips are absolute MRI contraindications", "Only if the patient signs a liability waiver releasing the facility from responsibility"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Intracranial aneurysm clips require the most rigorous identification process of any implant because a ferromagnetic clip subjected to the MRI magnetic field can torque, displacing the clip and causing fatal intracranial hemorrhage. The specific make, model, material, and MR safety classification must be confirmed through operative reports, implant cards, or direct manufacturer verification. A patient waiver (choice D) does not mitigate physical risk. (ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-295", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "If a patient experiences cardiac arrest while positioned inside the MRI bore, the technologist’s FIRST action must be to:", "options": ["Begin chest compressions immediately inside the bore", "Rapidly remove the patient from the scan room (Zone IV) to the adjacent Zone III area", "Initiate an emergency magnet quench", "Contact the radiologist for authorization to proceed"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Effective CPR cannot be performed inside the confined bore, and emergency resuscitation equipment (including defibrillators) cannot be safely operated in Zone IV due to the static magnetic field. The patient must be rapidly moved out of Zone IV into Zone III where the code team can perform full resuscitation with standard equipment. A quench (choice C) is not indicated for cardiac arrest—it would delay life-saving treatment and create additional hazards. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 367)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-296", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The term “isocenter” in MRI refers to:", "options": ["The entrance of the scanner bore", "The geometric center of the magnetic field where all three gradients intersect at zero (X=0, Y=0, Z=0) and field homogeneity is greatest", "The location of the operator console in Zone III", "The distal end of the patient table"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Isocenter is the point at the geometric center of the magnet bore where the static field is most homogeneous and the gradient fields are most linear. The anatomy of interest should be positioned at isocenter for optimal image quality. This is also the location where SAR deposition is typically modeled and where the greatest field homogeneity exists. (MIP Ch. 9 p. 315; MIP Ch. 5 p. 128)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 315"}, {"id": "SA-297", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Passive magnetic shielding of an MRI suite is typically accomplished by lining the walls, floor, and ceiling with:", "options": ["Copper sheeting", "Iron or steel plates", "Lead sheeting", "Aluminum panels"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Passive shielding uses ferromagnetic materials (iron or steel) to provide a low-reluctance return path for the magnetic flux lines, containing the fringe field within the shielded room and reducing its extent outside the suite. This helps keep the 5 Gauss line within the controlled area. Copper and aluminum (choices A and D) are used for RF shielding (Faraday cage), not magnetic shielding. Lead (choice C) is used for ionizing radiation shielding. (MIP Ch. 9 p. 326; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326"}, {"id": "SA-298", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The Faraday cage (RF shield) surrounding the MRI scan room is designed to prevent external radiofrequency interference from degrading image quality. It is typically constructed of:", "options": ["Copper or aluminum sheeting", "Steel plates", "Lead panels", "Reinforced concrete"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The Faraday cage is an electrically conductive enclosure (typically copper or aluminum) that blocks external RF signals from entering the scan room and prevents the scanner’s RF emissions from escaping. If the RF shield is compromised (e.g., the scan room door is left open), external RF interference can produce zipper artifacts on images. The Faraday cage serves a completely different function from the magnetic shielding (steel). (MIP Ch. 9 p. 337; MIP Ch. 8 p. 275)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 337"}, {"id": "SA-299", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "According to FDA/IEC standards, hearing protection is mandatory for MRI patients when acoustic noise levels exceed approximately:", "options": ["140 dB sustained", "99 dB average (with a 140 dB peak limit)", "60 dB average", "85 dB average"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The IEC standard limits MRI acoustic noise to 99 dB(A) time-weighted average with a peak limit of 140 dB. In practice, virtually all clinical MRI sequences exceed these thresholds, making hearing protection (earplugs, headphones, or both) standard practice for every patient. Higher field strengths and faster gradient switching produce louder acoustic noise. (IEC 60601-2-33; MIP Ch. 10 p. 363)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-300", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which MRI pulse sequence type typically deposits the HIGHEST specific absorption rate (SAR) and therefore produces the greatest tissue heating?", "options": ["Gradient echo (GRE)", "Fast spin echo (FSE/TSE)", "Echo planar imaging (EPI)", "Three-plane localizer"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Fast spin echo sequences use multiple high-energy 180° refocusing RF pulses within each TR interval (the echo train), depositing substantially more RF energy than gradient echo sequences, which use only low-flip-angle excitation pulses without 180° refocusing. Longer echo trains and shorter TR values further increase SAR in FSE. The technologist may need to increase TR, reduce the echo train length, or decrease the number of slices to bring SAR within limits. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 358; MIP Ch. 3 p. 68)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 358"}, {"id": "SA-301", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "An object such as a steel oxygen cylinder or wrench that contains iron and is strongly attracted to the MRI magnetic field is classified as:", "options": ["Diamagnetic", "Ferromagnetic", "Paramagnetic", "Non-magnetic"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Ferromagnetic materials (iron, nickel, cobalt, and certain alloys) exhibit strong magnetic properties and are forcefully attracted to the static magnetic field. In the MRI environment, ferromagnetic objects pose the greatest projectile and torque hazards. Paramagnetic materials (choice C) are weakly attracted and pose minimal risk, while diamagnetic materials (choice A) are weakly repelled by magnetic fields. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 347; MIP Ch. 1 p. 4)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 347"}, {"id": "SA-302", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Transdermal medication patches with metallic foil backings must be evaluated or removed prior to MRI because the foil component can:", "options": ["Cause the medication to become inactive during the scan", "Act as a conductive loop that concentrates RF-induced currents, causing localized skin burns", "Become a projectile and fly off the patient toward the magnet", "Produce aliasing artifacts that render the images non-diagnostic"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Metallic foil components in transdermal patches can act as antennas or conductive loops that concentrate RF-induced electrical currents at the skin surface, causing localized thermal burns. Several cases of second-degree burns have been reported from scanning patients with foil-backed patches. The technologist should identify and evaluate all patches during screening. Non-metallic patches may remain in place. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 359)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-303", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The 5 Gauss (0.5 mT) line surrounding an MRI system is significant in safety planning because it represents:", "options": ["The geometric center of the magnet bore", "The boundary beyond which the magnetic fringe field may interfere with implanted cardiac devices and other sensitive equipment", "The entrance to the patient waiting room", "The maximum extent of the RF electromagnetic field"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 5 Gauss line marks the boundary where the static magnetic fringe field drops to 5 Gauss (0.5 mT)—the level above which cardiac pacemakers and other magnetically sensitive devices may malfunction. This boundary typically defines the physical extent of Zone IV restricted access. Active shielding in modern magnets significantly reduces the 5 Gauss line footprint compared to unshielded systems. (MIP Ch. 9 p. 326; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326"}, {"id": "SA-304", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "A whole-body SAR of approximately 4.0 W/kg is expected to produce a core body temperature increase of approximately:", "options": ["0.25°C", "1.0°C", "3.0°C", "0.1°C"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A whole-body SAR of 4.0 W/kg corresponds to the First Level Controlled Operating Mode and is predicted to elevate core body temperature by approximately 1°C in a patient with normal thermoregulation. This threshold requires medical supervision because a 1°C rise may be clinically significant in vulnerable populations (febrile patients, neonates, patients with impaired thermoregulation). The Normal Operating Mode limit of 2.0 W/kg corresponds to approximately 0.5°C rise. (IEC 60601-2-33; MIP Ch. 10 p. 358)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 358"}, {"id": "SA-305", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) effect typically causes which artifactual change on a patient’s ECG trace during MRI?", "options": ["Elevated P-wave amplitude", "Augmented T-wave amplitude that may mimic ST-segment changes", "Complete absence of the QRS complex", "Inversion of the U-wave"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When electrically conductive blood flows through the strong static magnetic field, the MHD effect generates a voltage that superimposes on the ECG signal, most prominently augmenting the T-wave. This artifact can mimic ST-segment elevation and interfere with accurate R-wave detection for cardiac gating. Using vectorcardiographic (VCG) gating algorithms rather than standard ECG helps compensate for MHD-related T-wave distortion. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 351)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-306", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which patient condition poses the GREATEST risk for RF-related thermal injury during MRI due to impaired ability to dissipate heat?", "options": ["Claustrophobia", "Impaired thermoregulation (e.g., fever, multiple sclerosis, diabetes with autonomic neuropathy)", "Sensorineural hearing loss", "Generalized anxiety disorder"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patients with impaired thermoregulation cannot effectively dissipate the heat generated by RF energy absorption during scanning. Conditions that impair sweating, peripheral vasodilation, or autonomic nervous system function—such as fever, MS, diabetes with neuropathy, and certain medications—place patients at significantly increased risk for thermal injury. These patients may require reduced SAR protocols and enhanced monitoring. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 358; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 358"}, {"id": "SA-307", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The fringe field of a superconducting MRI magnet extends:", "options": ["Only within the interior of the scanner bore", "In all three spatial dimensions beyond the bore, including through walls, floors, and ceilings", "Only in the vertical direction above the magnet", "Only within the boundaries of Zone IV"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The fringe field extends outward from the magnet in all directions and can affect areas beyond the scan room walls, including adjacent rooms and floors above and below. Active shielding in modern magnets significantly reduces the fringe field footprint but does not eliminate it entirely. This is why the 5 Gauss line must be mapped and controlled during site planning. (MIP Ch. 9 p. 326; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326"}, {"id": "SA-308", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Among the following items, which represents the HIGHEST projectile risk in the MRI environment?", "options": ["A wooden patient positioning board", "A plastic IV pole", "A standard steel-body oxygen cylinder", "A wax crayon"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Steel oxygen cylinders are among the most dangerous and most commonly reported projectile hazards in MRI. Their large mass and strong ferromagnetic properties create enormous translational force in the magnetic field. Multiple fatalities and serious injuries have been attributed to oxygen tank projectile incidents. Only MR Safe (aluminum or composite) cylinders may be brought into Zone IV. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 347)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-309", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A ferromagnetic detection system installed at the entrance to Zone IV serves as:", "options": ["A replacement for the verbal and written MRI screening process", "A supplemental last line of defense to detect hidden or forgotten ferromagnetic objects before they enter the magnet room", "A calibration device for the MRI gradient system", "An automated patient tracking and counting system"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Ferromagnetic detectors are passive screening devices that alert staff when ferromagnetic material passes through the detection zone. They serve as a critical final safety layer but do NOT replace the comprehensive verbal and written screening process. Objects may be detected that were missed during screening, including items in pockets, hair accessories, or ferromagnetic components within medical devices. (ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-310", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "According to ACR guidelines, which healthcare professional must be immediately available whenever patients are being scanned in the MRI suite?", "options": ["The hospital chief executive officer", "An MRI safety–trained physician (MRMD) or their designated physician representative", "A hospital security officer", "A family member of the patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR requires that a physician with MRI safety training (the MR Medical Director or MRMD) be immediately available during all patient scanning for clinical decision-making and emergency management. “Immediately available” typically means the physician can respond within minutes, not necessarily present in the control room at all times. This requirement ensures appropriate medical oversight for contrast decisions, adverse events, and incidental findings. (ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-311", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "A patient’s implant identification card indicates the device is MR Conditional at 1.5 T only. The ordered examination is on a 3 T scanner. The technologist should:", "options": ["Proceed with the scan at 3 T since higher field strength simply improves image resolution", "NOT scan the patient at 3 T because the MR Conditional designation is field-strength specific and the stated conditions are not met", "Contact the device manufacturer to request a field-strength override", "Apply additional padding around the implant and proceed at 3 T"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MR Conditional labeling specifies exact conditions under which scanning is safe—including maximum static field strength. Scanning a 1.5 T–only conditional device at 3 T violates the stated conditions and may result in device malfunction, tissue heating, or displacement. There is no “override” process—the conditions are determined by testing and cannot be waived. The patient should be scanned on a 1.5 T system or alternative imaging should be arranged. (ASTM F2503; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-312", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The MRI scanner operator console (technologist workstation) is typically located in which ACR safety zone?", "options": ["Zone I — general public access", "Zone II — public/controlled interface", "Zone III — the restricted control area", "Zone IV — the magnet room"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Zone III houses the operator console and is the restricted area where the technologist controls the scanner, monitors the patient, and manages access to Zone IV. Zone III is physically separated from Zone IV by the RF-shielded scan room wall and door. Access to Zone III is restricted to screened personnel and patients who have completed the screening process. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 347)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-313", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The MRI suite is maintained at a controlled temperature and humidity primarily to:", "options": ["Maximize patient comfort during long examinations", "Prevent electronic equipment malfunction and help manage patient thermal load during high-SAR sequences", "Maintain the liquid helium at the correct operating temperature", "Reduce the acoustic noise level produced by gradient coils"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Controlled room temperature (typically 68–72°F) serves dual purposes: it protects sensitive electronic components from overheating and provides a cooler ambient environment that helps dissipate the heat generated in the patient’s body by RF energy absorption. During high-SAR sequences, a cooler room temperature provides an additional thermal safety margin. The helium cooling system (choice C) is independent of room temperature. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 358; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 358"}, {"id": "SA-314", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The correct sequential order of ACR safety zones from the public entrance to the magnet room is:", "options": ["Zone IV → Zone III → Zone II → Zone I", "Zone I → Zone II → Zone III → Zone IV", "Zone II → Zone I → Zone IV → Zone III", "Zone I → Zone III → Zone II → Zone IV"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR zone system progresses from least restricted to most restricted: Zone I (freely accessible public areas), Zone II (interface between public and controlled environments where initial screening occurs), Zone III (restricted control area with limited access), and Zone IV (the magnet room itself, the highest-risk environment). Each zone transition increases the level of screening and access control. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 347)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-315", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Cochlear implants are generally considered an absolute MRI contraindication (unless specifically verified as MR Conditional) primarily because they contain:", "options": ["A large lithium battery that may overheat", "An internal magnet component that can be torqued, displaced, or demagnetized by the static field", "Components too large to fit within the scanner bore", "Wiring that interferes with gradient coil function"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Most cochlear implants contain a small internal magnet used for external processor attachment. In the MRI static magnetic field, this magnet can experience significant torque (potentially causing it to flip or migrate within the tissue) or become demagnetized (rendering the implant nonfunctional). Some newer cochlear implants are MR Conditional with specific requirements, such as surgical magnet removal or field-strength restrictions. (ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-316", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "To reduce the risk of peripheral nerve stimulation (PNS) during an MRI examination, the technologist can adjust scan parameters by:", "options": ["Increasing the RF flip angle", "Reducing the gradient slew rate (rate of gradient switching)", "Increasing the RF transmit power", "Widening the receiver bandwidth"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "PNS is directly related to the rate of change of the magnetic field (dB/dt), which is determined by the gradient amplitude and slew rate. Reducing the slew rate decreases dB/dt and lowers the risk of nerve stimulation. This may require accepting longer minimum TE values or slightly longer scan times. RF parameters (choices A and C) affect SAR and tissue heating, not PNS. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 363; MIP Ch. 9 p. 330)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 363"}, {"id": "SA-317", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "The international standards organization responsible for establishing the MR Safe, MR Conditional, and MR Unsafe labeling system for medical devices is:", "options": ["The American College of Radiology (ACR)", "The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA)", "ASTM International (formerly the American Society for Testing and Materials)", "The Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "ASTM International developed and maintains the F2503 standard, which defines the three-tier MRI safety labeling system using standardized symbols: green square (MR Safe), yellow triangle (MR Conditional), and red circle with diagonal line (MR Unsafe). While the FDA enforces device labeling regulations and the ACR provides clinical safety guidance, ASTM sets the testing standards and labeling terminology. (ASTM F2503; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ASTM F2503"}, {"id": "SA-318", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a recognized bioeffect of the static magnetic field?", "options": ["Vertigo or dizziness when the patient moves their head rapidly", "A metallic taste sensation in the mouth", "Tissue heating from energy absorption", "Magnetophosphenes at very high field strengths"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Tissue heating is caused by radiofrequency (RF) energy absorption and is measured by the specific absorption rate (SAR)—it is NOT a bioeffect of the static field. Known static field bioeffects include vertigo and nystagmus (from vestibular stimulation during head movement), metallic taste (from induced currents on the tongue), and magnetophosphenes (retinal stimulation at high field strengths). These effects are generally transient and benign. (MIP Ch. 10 p. 351)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 351"}, {"id": "SA-319", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "A patient presents for MRI wearing an external fixation device (such as a halo vest for cervical spine stabilization). Before scanning, the technologist MUST:", "options": ["Remove the device immediately to prevent projectile risk", "Identify the exact manufacturer, model, and material composition of the device and verify its MR safety classification before proceeding", "Proceed with scanning at a reduced field strength only", "Apply extra foam padding around the device and scan at standard parameters"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "External fixation devices vary widely in material composition—some are constructed of titanium or carbon fiber (potentially MR Conditional), while others contain stainless steel or other ferromagnetic alloys (MR Unsafe). The technologist must identify the specific device through operative records, implant documentation, or manufacturer databases and verify all stated conditions before scanning. Removing a halo vest (choice A) is clinically contraindicated as it immobilizes the cervical spine. (ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-320", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "In a modern sealed-helium superconducting MRI system, the coldhead (cryocooler) functions to:", "options": ["Heat the magnet coils to operating temperature during system startup", "Recondense evaporated helium gas back into liquid to maintain superconducting temperatures", "Pump supplemental oxygen into the scan room for patient comfort", "Regulate the gradient coil switching speed"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The coldhead continuously recondenses helium gas that evaporates from the cryostat back into liquid helium, maintaining the superconducting coils at approximately 4 K (–269°C). This closed-loop recondensation system dramatically reduces helium consumption and the need for manual helium refills. If the coldhead fails, helium will gradually boil off and eventually cause a quench if not repaired. [UPDATED CONCEPT: Modern sealed helium systems have minimal or zero boil-off designs] (MIP Ch. 9 p. 318)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 318"}, {"id": "SA-321", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.5", "stem": "Which of the following events could potentially trigger an unplanned quench in a superconducting MRI system?", "options": ["A brief facility power outage", "Physical damage to the cryostat compromising its vacuum insulation", "Scanning a patient who has a large decorative tattoo", "Operating a surface receiver coil at maximum gain"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The cryostat maintains a vacuum insulation layer that prevents heat transfer to the liquid helium. If this vacuum is breached (from physical impact, manufacturing defect, or seal failure), ambient heat enters the cryostat and rapidly boils the helium, causing an uncontrolled quench. Power outages (choice A) affect the coldhead but do not cause immediate quench because the thermal mass of the helium provides hours of margin. (MIP Ch. 9 p. 318; MIP Ch. 10 p. 365)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 318"}, {"id": "SA-322", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The 5 Gauss (0.5 mT) fringe field boundary must be contained within:", "options": ["Any area regardless of public access", "Zone IV (the magnet room) or a clearly marked and controlled restricted area that excludes unscreened public access", "Within one foot of the magnet bore opening", "Outside the building perimeter"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The 5 Gauss line must not extend into areas accessible to the unscreened general public because magnetic fields above this level can interfere with cardiac pacemakers and other implanted electronic devices. Site planning must ensure the 5 Gauss line is contained within physically controlled restricted areas through a combination of room design, active shielding, and/or passive (ferromagnetic) shielding. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 9 p. 326)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 9 p. 326"}, {"id": "SA-323", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.4", "stem": "Among gadolinium-based contrast agents, which chemical structure is associated with the LOWEST risk for nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF)?", "options": ["Linear ionic agents", "Linear non-ionic agents", "Macrocyclic agents (ACR Group II)", "All agent types carry identical NSF risk"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Macrocyclic gadolinium agents have a cage-like molecular structure that holds the gadolinium ion more tightly than linear agents, resulting in greater thermodynamic and kinetic stability. This reduces the release of free Gd³⁺ ions, which are believed to trigger the fibrotic process in NSF. The ACR classifies macrocyclic agents as Group II (lower risk), while certain linear agents (particularly non-ionic linear) are classified as Group I (higher risk). (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "SA-324", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "During an MRI scan, a patient uses the communication system to report a localized sensation of warmth on their arm. The technologist’s appropriate response is to:", "options": ["Reassure the patient that mild warming is always normal and continue scanning", "Immediately stop the scan, remove the patient from the bore, and inspect the area for signs of thermal injury, cable contact, or skin-to-skin loops", "Increase the bore ventilation fan speed and resume the scan", "Instruct the patient to remain still and complete the current sequence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "While mild generalized warming can be a normal consequence of RF energy deposition, a localized sensation of heat is a warning sign for potential RF burns caused by conductive cable contact, skin-to-skin loops, or skin-to-bore contact. The scan must be stopped immediately to assess for erythema or burns. Continuing to scan (choices A, C, D) risks escalating a mild thermal event into a clinically significant burn. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; MIP Ch. 10 p. 359)", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 359"}, {"id": "SA-325", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The safety metric B₁⁺ᵣᵐˢ is increasingly used alongside SAR for MR Conditional implant safety screening. B₁⁺ᵣᵐˢ quantifies:", "options": ["The strength of the static magnetic field at isocenter", "The root-mean-square value of the RF magnetic field (B₁⁺) delivered to the patient over the pulse sequence, reflecting average RF power exposure", "The maximum gradient slew rate during echo planar imaging", "The peak acoustic noise level in decibels during scanning"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "B₁⁺ᵣᵐˢ measures the time-averaged RF magnetic field intensity experienced by the patient and provides a more direct assessment of implant heating risk than whole-body SAR alone. Many newer MR Conditional device labeling conditions specify maximum B₁⁺ᵣᵐˢ values because local implant heating depends on the RF field distribution near the device, which B₁⁺ᵣᵐˢ characterizes more accurately than global SAR. This is an emerging metric on the 2025 ARRT content specifications. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; IEC 60601-2-33)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-326", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The MR screening checklist used before every examination relates primarily to:", "options": ["imaging parameter optimization", "daily quality assurance testing", "patient and personnel safety", "facility accreditation requirements"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The MR screening checklist completed before every examination is primarily related to patient and personnel safety. It screens for contraindicated implants, ferromagnetic objects, pregnancy, and other safety concerns that could pose a risk in the MR environment. Imaging parameter optimization (option a) is performed during protocol selection, not during the safety screening process.", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "SA-327", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT an absolute contraindication to entering the MRI scan room?", "options": ["Certain cardiac pacemakers", "Certain ferromagnetic aneurysm clips", "Non-MR Safe infusion pumps", "Claustrophobia"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Claustrophobia is a patient management challenge addressable through sedation, open-bore systems, or coaching techniques -- it is not an absolute contraindication to entering the scan room. Certain cardiac pacemakers, ferromagnetic aneurysm clips, and non-MR Safe infusion pumps can pose serious safety hazards in the magnetic field environment.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 346"}, {"id": "SA-328", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Preventing injury from the strong magnetic field in MRI requires:", "options": ["A knowledgeable MR technologist and controlled access to the magnetic field only", "A knowledgeable MR technologist and a detailed medical history of anyone entering the room only", "Controlled access and a detailed medical history only", "A knowledgeable MR technologist, controlled access to the magnetic field, and a detailed screening history for all individuals entering the scan room"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "MRI safety requires trained personnel who understand the hazards, restricted access through the ACR Zone system, and thorough screening of every individual before entering the magnetic field environment. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete, listing only two of the three essential safety measures.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 346"}, {"id": "SA-329", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "In the event of a magnet quench, who should be evacuated from the MRI scan room?", "options": ["Only the patient currently being scanned", "The patient and any accompanying family members", "The patient, family members, and nonessential staff", "All individuals in the immediate area"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "During a magnet quench, rapidly boiling cryogens expand to approximately 760 times their liquid volume, displacing oxygen in the scan room and potentially causing asphyxiation. All individuals in the immediate area must be evacuated to prevent oxygen deprivation injury. Option a is incorrect because everyone in the area is at risk, not just the patient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 365"}, {"id": "SA-330", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The fringe magnetic field extending beyond an MRI system can interact with:", "options": ["CT scanners and cardiac pacemakers only", "CT scanners and nuclear medicine scanners only", "Cardiac pacemakers and nuclear medicine scanners only", "CT scanners, cardiac pacemakers, and nuclear medicine scanners"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The fringe magnetic field can interfere with CT scanner operation and image quality, disrupt cardiac pacemaker function (potentially life-threatening), and affect nuclear medicine gamma camera detectors. All sensitive electronic equipment must be located beyond the critical fringe field boundary. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351; Ch. 9, p. 326"}, {"id": "SA-331", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The general public must be warned and access restricted at the point where the MRI system's fringe field reaches:", "options": ["0.1 Gauss", "0.5 Gauss", "1 Gauss", "5 Gauss"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The 5-gauss line is the internationally recognized boundary at which the general public must be warned and access restricted due to potential interference with cardiac pacemakers and other implanted devices. This boundary must be marked and controlled. Option a (0.1 gauss) is far below the standard restriction level.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 351; Ch. 9, p. 326"}, {"id": "SA-332", "domain": "Safety", "subcategory": "MRI Screening & Safety", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The physiological effects of time-varying gradient fields on the body are influenced by:", "options": ["Only the duration and repetition pattern of gradient pulses", "Only the repetition pattern and distribution of induced current through the body", "Only the duration of gradient pulses and distribution of induced current", "The duration of gradient pulses, their repetition pattern, and the distribution of induced current through the body"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The physiological effects of time-varying gradient fields (such as peripheral nerve stimulation) depend on the duration of gradient pulses, their repetition pattern, and how the induced currents are distributed through the body. All three factors together determine whether stimulation thresholds are exceeded. Options a, b, and c are each incomplete.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10, p. 363"}, {"id": "PC-001", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Paramagnetic substances demonstrate what type of magnetic susceptibility when exposed to an external magnetic field?", "options": ["High positive", "Small positive", "Mostly negative", "Completely negative (repelled)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Paramagnetic substances have unpaired electrons that weakly align with the external magnetic field, producing a small positive magnetic susceptibility. This is the basis for gadolinium-based contrast agents' ability to shorten T1 relaxation times. High positive susceptibility (option a) describes ferromagnetic materials, which have a much stronger interaction with the field.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 1, p. 4"}, {"id": "PC-002", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Which statement about MR contrast agents is NOT true?", "options": ["They can contain paramagnetic metal ions", "They can contain superparamagnetic metal ions", "They affect both T1 relaxation and T2 decay times", "They are very similar in mechanism to iodinated X-ray contrast agents"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "MR contrast agents work by a fundamentally different mechanism than iodinated X-ray contrast agents. MR agents alter tissue relaxation times (T1 and T2) to affect signal intensity indirectly, while iodinated agents directly attenuate X-ray beams based on their atomic number. Options a through c are all true statements about MR contrast agents.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-003", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The primary clinical effect of paramagnetic contrast agents is to:", "options": ["lengthen T1 relaxation times", "shorten T1 relaxation times", "lengthen T2 decay times", "eliminate proton density weighting"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The primary clinical effect of paramagnetic contrast agents (such as gadolinium chelates) is to shorten T1 relaxation times of nearby tissues, causing them to appear hyperintense on T1-weighted images. This T1-shortening effect occurs because the unpaired electrons in gadolinium create fluctuating local magnetic fields that enhance spin-lattice relaxation. Lengthening T1 (option a) would decrease signal on T1-weighted images, the opposite of the desired effect.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-004", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The most commonly used type of contrast agent in clinical MRI is:", "options": ["paramagnetic", "superparamagnetic", "ferromagnetic", "diamagnetic"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Paramagnetic gadolinium-based contrast agents are the most commonly used type of contrast agent in clinical MRI, employed in approximately 30-40% of all MRI examinations. They are used for a wide range of applications including tumor characterization, vascular imaging, and inflammatory disease evaluation. Superparamagnetic agents (option b) have more limited clinical applications, primarily for liver imaging.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-005", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The purpose of chelating the gadolinium metal ion in MR contrast agents is to:", "options": ["allow for lower doses", "accelerate the agent's transit through the body", "reduce the free ion's toxicity and facilitate renal excretion", "increase the relaxivity of the compound"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Free gadolinium ions (Gd3+) are highly toxic to biological systems. Chelating the gadolinium ion within an organic ligand (such as DTPA or DOTA) dramatically reduces its toxicity by preventing the free ion from interacting with biological molecules, while also facilitating renal excretion of the complex. Increasing relaxivity (option d) is not the primary purpose of chelation, though the chelate structure does influence relaxivity.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51 | ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-006", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Which statement about gadolinium-based contrast agents is true?", "options": ["They cause T1-weighted tissues to appear darker", "At high local concentrations, they produce T2 shortening that can cause signal loss", "They readily cross the intact blood-brain barrier", "They positively enhance signal on T2-weighted sequences only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "At high local concentrations (such as in the bladder or immediately after bolus injection), gadolinium produces T2 shortening effects that can cause signal loss on T2-weighted images. This is because the T2 shortening effect becomes dominant over the T1 shortening effect at very high concentrations. Option a is incorrect because gadolinium causes T1-weighted tissues to appear brighter, not darker.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-007", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "After intravenous administration, water-soluble gadolinium chelates distribute primarily into which body compartment?", "options": ["The extracellular space", "The intracellular space only", "The cerebrospinal fluid exclusively", "The lipid bilayer of cell membranes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "After intravenous administration, standard water-soluble gadolinium chelates distribute primarily into the extracellular space (both intravascular and interstitial compartments). They do not cross intact cell membranes or the blood-brain barrier. The intracellular space (option b) is not accessible to these agents because their molecular size and hydrophilic properties prevent membrane crossing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-008", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Which statement about blood pool contrast agents is NOT true?", "options": ["They remain in the vascular space for a shorter time than standard extracellular gadolinium agents", "They have a prolonged intravascular half-life", "They are macromolecular in nature", "They can be used to assess myocardial viability"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Blood pool agents remain in the vascular space for a LONGER time than standard extracellular gadolinium agents, not a shorter time — that is what makes them 'blood pool' agents. Their macromolecular nature or protein-binding properties prevent rapid extravasation into the interstitial space. Options b through d are all true characteristics of blood pool agents.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-009", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Ferucarbotran is a superparamagnetic iron oxide (SPIO) contrast agent that is currently available primarily in:", "options": ["the United States", "Europe and Japan", "South America", "Australia only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Ferucarbotran (Resovist) is a superparamagnetic iron oxide (SPIO) contrast agent that has been primarily available in Europe and Japan for liver imaging. It is taken up by Kupffer cells in the liver, causing normal liver tissue to lose signal on T2*-weighted images while lesions without Kupffer cells remain bright. It was not approved for use in the United States (option a).", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-010", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Ferumoxide, a superparamagnetic iron oxide agent, is primarily taken up and processed by the:", "options": ["liver (reticuloendothelial system)", "kidneys", "pancreas", "stomach"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Ferumoxide (Feridex) is a superparamagnetic iron oxide agent that is primarily taken up by the reticuloendothelial system (Kupffer cells) of the liver. This selective uptake causes normal liver parenchyma to darken on T2-weighted images, improving contrast between normal tissue and hepatic lesions. The kidneys (option b) are the primary route of excretion for gadolinium agents, not SPIO particles.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 2, p. 51"}, {"id": "PC-011", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The use of which agent administered orally has helped promote the clinical utility of magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)?", "options": ["Ferucarbotran", "Secretin", "Manganese", "Water-soluble gadolinium"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Secretin, administered intravenously, stimulates pancreatic exocrine secretion and increases fluid volume in the pancreatic and biliary ducts, improving their visualization on MRCP. This physiologic stimulation enhances the hydrographic effect of heavily T2-weighted sequences used in MRCP. Ferucarbotran (option a) is a liver-specific SPIO agent, not used for MRCP enhancement.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PC-012", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4.c", "stem": "Which statement about glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is true?", "options": ["GFR can be estimated using serum creatinine level and body weight alone", "In most healthy adults, the normal GFR is 100 mL/min/1.73 m2 or higher", "GFR is generally accepted as the best overall index of kidney function", "GFR can indicate the presence of kidney disease but cannot assess its severity"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "GFR is generally accepted as the best overall index of kidney function because it directly measures the volume of plasma filtered by the glomeruli per unit time. It can be estimated using equations that incorporate serum creatinine, age, sex, and race (not just creatinine and body weight as stated in option a). GFR can both detect kidney disease AND assess its severity (contradicting option d).", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-013", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4.a", "stem": "When prescreening a patient for gadolinium-based contrast administration, MR providers should:", "options": ["rely solely on the patient's self-reported medical history", "obtain laboratory values (e.g., eGFR) in addition to reviewing the medical history", "administer contrast without screening if the patient has no known allergies", "defer all screening decisions to the referring physician"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "When prescreening patients for gadolinium-based contrast administration, MR providers should obtain laboratory values (particularly eGFR) in addition to reviewing the medical history to assess renal function and identify risk factors for adverse reactions. Relying solely on self-reported history (option a) is insufficient because patients may not know their renal function status.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-014", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4.c", "stem": "According to ACR guidelines, patients with which stages of chronic kidney disease should generally not receive gadolinium-based contrast agents?", "options": ["Stage 1 only", "Stages 2 and 3", "Stages 4 and 5 (eGFR <30 mL/min/1.73 m2)", "Stage 5 only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "According to ACR guidelines, patients with stages 4 and 5 chronic kidney disease (eGFR <30 mL/min/1.73 m2) should generally not receive gadolinium-based contrast agents due to the elevated risk of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF). If contrast is deemed essential, Group II agents (macrocyclic) should be used with the lowest effective dose. Stage 5 only (option d) is too restrictive — stage 4 patients are also at significant risk.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-015", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2.a", "stem": "Some MR facilities instruct patients to follow which preparation before a contrast-enhanced examination?", "options": ["Take a mild sedative before and after the exam", "Have nothing by mouth (NPO) for at least 2 to 3 hours before the exam", "Avoid operating heavy equipment for 24 hours after the exam", "Drink plenty of fluids and take a mild laxative afterward"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Some MR facilities instruct patients to have nothing by mouth (NPO) for at least 2 to 3 hours before a contrast-enhanced examination to reduce the risk of aspiration in the event of nausea or vomiting following contrast administration. This is especially important for patients receiving sedation. Taking a sedative (option a) is not standard pre-contrast preparation for all patients.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-016", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5.d", "stem": "When administering IV contrast, the technologist should document the lot number, amount administered, and expiration date because these details are essential for:", "options": ["billing and insurance reimbursement only", "quality assurance tracking and adverse event investigation", "determining the patient's next appointment time", "adjusting the scan parameters for optimal image contrast"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Documenting the contrast agent's lot number, amount administered, and expiration date is essential for quality assurance tracking and adverse event investigation. If a patient experiences a delayed reaction, this information allows identification of the specific contrast lot and enables correlation with any manufacturer recalls or safety alerts. Billing (option a) is a secondary consideration, not the primary purpose.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-017", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2.c", "stem": "The most commonly used intravenous injection sites for MR contrast administration are the:", "options": ["axillary, brachial, and radial arteries", "radial, ulnar, and cephalic veins", "basilic, cephalic, and median cubital veins of the antecubital fossa", "saphenous, plantar, and dorsal veins of the lower extremity"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The basilic, cephalic, and median cubital veins of the antecubital fossa are the most commonly used intravenous injection sites for MR contrast administration. These veins are superficial, readily accessible, and large enough to accommodate the injection rates needed for contrast-enhanced studies. Arteries (option a) are never used for routine contrast injection due to the risk of arterial damage and distal embolization.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-018", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2.c", "stem": "Why should a technologist flush the IV catheter line before injecting contrast?", "options": ["To add air to the line for better flow", "To prevent clotting at the injection site", "To confirm successful catheter insertion", "To remove air from the line and verify catheter patency"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Flushing the IV catheter line before injecting contrast serves to remove air from the line (preventing air embolism) and verify that the catheter is patent and properly positioned within the vein. If the catheter has infiltrated, the flush will cause swelling at the injection site, alerting the technologist before contrast is administered. Adding air (option a) is dangerous and the opposite of correct technique.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-019", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5.b", "stem": "Which of the following is classified as a mild reaction to gadolinium-based contrast?", "options": ["Hypertension", "Nausea and vomiting", "Dyspnea", "Periorbital and facial edema"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Nausea and vomiting are classified as mild reactions to gadolinium-based contrast agents, along with other symptoms such as urticaria (hives), headache, and warmth at the injection site. These typically resolve without treatment or with simple observation. Dyspnea (option c) is classified as a moderate reaction requiring more immediate medical attention.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-020", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5.b", "stem": "Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF) affects which body systems?", "options": ["Renal tissue only", "Skin tissue only", "Skin and internal organs (including lungs, heart, and liver)", "Spinal cord and brain only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF) affects the skin (causing thickening and hardening) AND internal organs including the lungs, heart, liver, and skeletal muscle. The 'systemic' in NSF reflects involvement beyond just the skin. Option b (skin only) underestimates the extent of disease, and option a (renal tissue only) incorrectly identifies the target — NSF affects many tissues but ironically spares the kidneys that triggered it.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-021", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5.b", "stem": "Which statement about trends in gadolinium-based contrast safety is true?", "options": ["The incidence of NSF continues to rise despite provider efforts", "Ensuring adequate time between contrast-enhanced examinations is not clinically important", "Definitive treatments have been developed for established NSF", "Newer macrocyclic agents have a significantly better safety profile than older linear agents"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Newer macrocyclic gadolinium agents have a significantly better safety profile than older linear agents because macrocyclic chelates bind gadolinium more tightly, reducing the release of free toxic gadolinium ions (transmetallation). This has led to a dramatic decrease in NSF cases since the preferential use of macrocyclic agents began. Option a is incorrect because NSF incidence has declined significantly, not risen.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-022", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5.b", "stem": "Approximately what proportion of patients receiving blood pool contrast agents report adverse side effects?", "options": ["One-tenth", "One-fourth", "One-half", "Two-thirds"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Approximately one-fourth (25%) of patients receiving blood pool contrast agents report adverse side effects, which are generally mild and self-limiting. This rate is higher than standard extracellular gadolinium agents, which have a much lower overall adverse event rate. One-half (option c) overestimates the typical side effect frequency.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-023", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2.e", "stem": "To prevent mistiming a contrast-enhanced MR angiogram, the technologist should:", "options": ["have the patient maintain a single continuous breath-hold throughout the entire acquisition", "synchronize the start of data acquisition with the arrival of the contrast bolus in the target vessels", "flush the injection site with a large bolus of saline after the scan is complete", "shorten the acquisition time to the minimum possible"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "To prevent mistiming a contrast-enhanced MR angiogram, the technologist should synchronize the start of k-space center acquisition with the arrival of the contrast bolus in the target vessels. This can be accomplished using a test bolus or automated bolus detection (MR fluoroscopic triggering). A single continuous breath-hold (option a) is not practical for the entire acquisition and does not address timing.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "PC-024", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "What is an advantage of using blood pool agents during MR angiography compared to conventional catheter angiography?", "options": ["The agents quickly disperse to the interstitial tissues for broader coverage", "Blood pool agents target specific organs such as the pancreas", "They eliminate the need for patient breath-holds entirely", "They allow detection of smaller vessels without the use of iodinated contrast or arterial catheterization"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Blood pool agents allow detection of smaller vessels during MR angiography without the need for iodinated contrast or arterial catheterization, providing a less invasive alternative to conventional angiography. Their prolonged intravascular half-life enables extended imaging windows for high-resolution vascular assessment. Option a is incorrect because blood pool agents are designed to stay intravascular, not disperse to interstitial tissues.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 298"}, {"id": "PC-025", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2.e", "stem": "For pulmonary MR imaging, newer alternatives to traditional breath-hold techniques include breath-pacing and:", "options": ["increasing the flip angle to maximum", "respiratory triggering (navigator or bellows)", "cardiac gating only", "switching to a spin echo sequence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "For pulmonary MR imaging, newer alternatives to traditional breath-hold techniques include breath-pacing and respiratory triggering using navigator echoes or bellows. These methods allow data acquisition synchronized to the respiratory cycle, enabling imaging of patients who cannot perform adequate breath-holds. Cardiac gating only (option c) addresses cardiac motion but not respiratory motion.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 8, p. 243"}, {"id": "PC-026", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2.c", "stem": "A magnetic resonance arthrogram is typically performed by injecting dilute gadolinium directly into the joint space under fluoroscopic guidance, followed by MRI scanning within:", "options": ["5 minutes of injection", "20 minutes of injection to prevent contrast resorption", "60 minutes of injection", "24 hours of injection"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "After injecting dilute gadolinium directly into a joint space under fluoroscopic guidance, MRI scanning should be performed within approximately 20 minutes to prevent contrast resorption from the joint. As the gadolinium is absorbed into surrounding tissues, the arthrographic effect diminishes, reducing diagnostic quality. Waiting 60 minutes (option c) allows excessive contrast resorption and degraded image quality.", "reference": "HMT Ch. 8"}, {"id": "PC-027", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Upon receiving a new imaging order, an MRI technologist's first responsibility is to:", "options": ["Verify the room humidity level", "Position the appropriate coil on the table", "Confirm the patient's identity and the accuracy of the order", "Enter the protocol parameters into the scanner"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Patient safety begins with verifying the correct patient and procedure before any other steps. Misidentification errors can lead to wrong-site or wrong-patient examinations. The remaining options describe preparatory steps that occur after identity verification is complete.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-028", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "A \"time-out\" or \"pause\" procedure performed immediately before starting the scan is designed to:", "options": ["Allow the superconducting magnet to stabilize", "Verify the correct patient, correct anatomical site, and correct procedure", "Calibrate the radiofrequency coils for the selected protocol", "Confirm the contrast agent's expiration date"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The time-out is a standardized safety verification mandated by The Joint Commission (TJC) to prevent wrong-patient, wrong-site, and wrong-procedure errors. It must occur immediately before the procedure begins and involves the entire care team. The other options describe routine preparatory tasks that are not part of the formal time-out process.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-029", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "In a medical malpractice lawsuit, which party generally bears the burden of proof?", "options": ["The technologist named in the suit", "The facility's risk management department", "The plaintiff (the patient bringing the claim)", "The presiding judge"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In malpractice cases, the plaintiff must demonstrate four elements: duty, breach, causation, and damages. The burden of proving negligence rests with the person bringing the lawsuit, not with the defendant or the court.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-030", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which ethical principle is best described by the phrase \"first, do no harm\"?", "options": ["Beneficence", "Nonmaleficence", "Veracity", "Autonomy"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Nonmaleficence is the obligation to avoid causing harm to patients. Beneficence refers to the duty to actively promote the patient's well-being. Veracity is the obligation to tell the truth, and autonomy is the patient's right to make their own informed decisions.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-031", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "A technologist leaves a confused, elderly patient unattended on the MRI table, and the patient falls to the floor. The technologist is most likely to face a claim of:", "options": ["Assault", "Battery", "Negligence", "Libel"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Negligence occurs when a healthcare professional fails to exercise the standard of care expected of a reasonably prudent practitioner. Leaving a vulnerable patient unattended breaches the duty of care. Assault involves threatening harm, battery involves unauthorized physical contact, and libel is a written defamatory statement.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-032", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "If a competent adult patient demands to stop the examination during an active scan sequence, the technologist must:", "options": ["Apply positioning aids to keep the patient still", "Contact security for assistance", "Immediately stop the scan and safely remove the patient from the bore", "Administer sedation to calm the patient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A competent patient has the legal and ethical right to withdraw consent at any time, even during a procedure. The technologist must respect this decision immediately. Restraining, sedating, or ignoring the patient's wishes constitutes a violation of patient rights and may result in charges of battery or false imprisonment.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-033", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "What is the legal distinction between physical restraints and positioning aids in medical imaging?", "options": ["Restraints provide comfort, while positioning aids ensure safety", "Restraints limit a patient's movement against their will and require a physician's order; positioning aids help maintain position for image quality", "Technologists may independently order the use of restraints", "Positioning aids require a physician's order before use"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Restraints restrict movement against the patient's will and require a physician's order due to their potential to cause harm and legal implications (false imprisonment). Positioning aids such as sponges, straps, and sandbags are used with patient cooperation to maintain optimal positioning for image quality and do not require a physician's order.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-034", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "A retained surgical sponge is discovered incidentally during an MRI examination. A malpractice case in this scenario would most likely proceed under which legal doctrine?", "options": ["Respondeat superior", "Stare decisis", "Res ipsa loquitur", "Habeas corpus"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Res ipsa loquitur (\"the thing speaks for itself\") applies when negligence is self-evident from the outcome alone — a retained surgical instrument would not occur absent negligence. Respondeat superior holds employers liable for employees' actions. Stare decisis refers to precedent in court rulings. Habeas corpus protects against unlawful detention.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-035", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Medical record documentation for an MRI procedure must always include:", "options": ["The technologist's initials only", "The date, time, and full signature with credentials", "The date only", "The interpreting radiologist's name only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Complete documentation is a legal requirement and must include the date, time, and full signature with professional credentials. Initials or partial information do not meet the standard for medical-legal documentation and may be challenged in court proceedings.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-036", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Which of the following is classified as an unintentional tort?", "options": ["Battery", "Negligence", "False imprisonment", "Assault"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Negligence is an unintentional tort because the harm occurs without deliberate intent — it results from a failure to meet the standard of care. Battery (unauthorized touching), false imprisonment (unlawful restriction of movement), and assault (threat of harm) are all intentional torts requiring deliberate action.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-037", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Threatening a patient by saying \"If you don't hold still, we will restrain you\" constitutes which legal offense?", "options": ["Battery", "Assault", "Libel", "Negligence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Assault is the threat of harmful or unwanted contact that causes reasonable apprehension in the patient. Battery is the actual unauthorized physical contact. Libel is written defamation, and negligence is an unintentional failure to meet the standard of care.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-038", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The ethical \"Principle of Double Effect\" states that:", "options": ["Harmful actions are acceptable if both parties agree", "A morally good action may be permissible even if it produces an unintended negative side effect", "Two technologists must agree before proceeding with a questionable action", "Negative effects of treatment are always intentional"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Principle of Double Effect recognizes that a well-intentioned medical action (such as administering pain medication) may have an unintended harmful consequence (such as respiratory depression). The key ethical requirement is that the harmful effect is not the intended goal of the action.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-039", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When an outpatient voluntarily lies down on the MRI table after receiving an explanation of the procedure, this behavior represents which type of consent?", "options": ["Informed consent", "Implied consent", "Written consent", "Express consent"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Implied consent is inferred from a patient's cooperative actions, such as voluntarily positioning themselves for an examination. Informed consent involves a detailed explanation of risks and benefits with formal acknowledgment. Express consent is a direct verbal or written statement of agreement.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-040", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Performing an MRI examination on the wrong body part — effectively touching the patient without valid consent for that specific procedure — is an example of:", "options": ["Assault", "Battery", "Slander", "Fraud"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Battery is the intentional, unauthorized touching of another person. Performing an examination on a body part not covered by the patient's consent constitutes battery. Assault is the threat of harm, slander is spoken defamation, and fraud involves intentional deception.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-041", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal doctrine \"respondeat superior\" translates to:", "options": ["\"The thing speaks for itself\"", "\"Let the master answer\"", "\"Stand by things decided\"", "\"Do no harm\""], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Respondeat superior holds an employer vicariously liable for the negligent actions of employees performed within the scope of their employment. \"The thing speaks for itself\" is res ipsa loquitur. \"Stand by things decided\" is stare decisis.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-042", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following conditions would invalidate a patient's informed consent?", "options": ["The patient is 18 years of age", "All risks of the procedure were explained", "The patient was coerced into signing the consent form", "The patient asked clarifying questions before signing"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Valid informed consent requires that the patient be competent, adequately informed, and acting voluntarily. Coercion — any form of pressure, threat, or undue influence — renders the consent involuntary and therefore legally invalid.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-043", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The unauthorized destruction or alteration of medical records is legally termed:", "options": ["Negligence", "Spoliation", "Battery", "Libel"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spoliation refers to the intentional destruction, alteration, or concealment of evidence — including medical records. This can result in severe legal penalties, including adverse inference (the court may assume the destroyed records contained damaging evidence).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-044", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Discussing a patient's medical history in a public elevator constitutes a breach of:", "options": ["Patient confidentiality under HIPAA", "Res ipsa loquitur", "Assault statutes", "Battery statutes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) protects patient health information (PHI). Discussing identifiable patient information in any public space — including elevators, cafeterias, and hallways — violates HIPAA privacy regulations and can result in civil and criminal penalties.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-045", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Spreading false spoken statements about a patient that damage their reputation is legally classified as:", "options": ["Libel", "Slander", "Battery", "Negligence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slander is spoken defamation — making false oral statements that harm another person's reputation. Libel is written or published defamation. Both are forms of defamation but differ in their medium of communication.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-046", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The \"reasonably prudent person\" standard used in malpractice cases asks:", "options": ["What an untrained layperson would do in the same situation", "How a professional with similar education and training would act under the same circumstances", "What the attending physician would have done", "What the patient would have preferred"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The reasonably prudent person standard compares the defendant's actions to those of a similarly trained professional in the same or similar circumstances. This peer-based standard forms the foundation of negligence law in healthcare.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-047", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The ARRT Code of Ethics requires that radiologic technologists provide all services with:", "options": ["Full respect for human dignity", "Priority given to patients with commercial insurance", "Personal opinions regarding the clinical diagnosis", "Maximum emphasis on examination speed"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Respect for human dignity is a foundational principle of the ARRT Code of Ethics. Technologists must treat all patients equitably regardless of insurance status, refrain from offering diagnoses (which is outside their scope of practice), and prioritize quality over speed.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-048", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which action by an MRI technologist would violate the ARRT Code of Ethics?", "options": ["Refusing to perform a scan without a valid physician's order", "Informing a patient that their images show a fracture", "Reporting a safety hazard in the scan room", "Following infection control protocols when treating a contagious patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Interpreting or diagnosing imaging findings is outside the technologist's scope of practice and violates the ARRT Code of Ethics. Technologists acquire and optimize images but must defer all diagnostic interpretation to the radiologist or referring physician.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-049", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Aphasia is defined as difficulty with:", "options": ["Walking", "Speaking or understanding language", "Swallowing", "Breathing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Aphasia is the loss or impairment of the ability to produce or comprehend language, most commonly resulting from stroke or brain injury. Difficulty swallowing is dysphagia, difficulty walking is related to motor impairment, and difficulty breathing is dyspnea.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-050", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Dysphagia is defined as difficulty with:", "options": ["Breathing", "Speaking", "Swallowing", "Hearing"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Dysphagia refers specifically to difficulty swallowing, often caused by neurological conditions, structural abnormalities, or post-surgical changes. The \"G\" in dysphaGia can serve as a mnemonic for the GI tract.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-051", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "According to the Kübler-Ross model, the first stage of grief is typically:", "options": ["Anger", "Denial", "Depression", "Bargaining"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Kübler-Ross model describes five stages of grief: Denial, Anger, Bargaining, Depression, and Acceptance (remembered by the mnemonic DABDA). Denial (\"This isn't happening\") is the initial protective response that helps patients process difficult information gradually.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-052", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "According to Maslow's hierarchy of needs, which category of needs must be met first?", "options": ["Safety needs", "Self-actualization", "Physiologic needs (food, water, air)", "Love and belonging"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Maslow's hierarchy places physiologic needs — food, water, air, shelter, and sleep — at the base as the most fundamental requirements. These must be satisfied before higher-level needs such as safety, belonging, esteem, and self-actualization can be addressed.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-053", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The most effective approach for communicating with a hearing-impaired patient is to:", "options": ["Speak loudly and rapidly", "Face the patient directly and speak clearly at a normal pace", "Use complex medical terminology", "Avoid eye contact to reduce pressure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Facing the patient enables lip reading and allows them to observe nonverbal cues such as facial expressions and gestures. Speaking clearly at a normal pace — rather than shouting — improves comprehension. Medical jargon should be avoided, and maintaining eye contact demonstrates engagement and respect.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-054", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When communicating with pediatric patients, the technologist should:", "options": ["Speak only to the parent or guardian", "Get down to the child's eye level and use age-appropriate language", "Maintain a strict and authoritative tone", "Withhold information about what will happen during the scan"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Getting down to the child's eye level reduces intimidation and builds trust. Using age-appropriate language and honest, simple explanations helps the child feel safe and increases cooperation during the examination.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-055", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The \"teach-back\" method is used in patient education to:", "options": ["Train new MRI students on protocols", "Validate that the patient understood the instructions by having them repeat them in their own words", "Correct errors made by the referring physician", "Calibrate the radiofrequency coils"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The teach-back method is an evidence-based communication strategy that confirms patient comprehension by asking them to explain the information in their own words. This technique is particularly valuable for post-procedure instructions and contrast precautions.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-056", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When using a slide board (transfer board), the primary purpose is to:", "options": ["Weigh the patient before the examination", "Bridge the gap between surfaces and reduce friction during patient transfer", "Restrain the patient during the scan", "Provide warmth to the patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slide boards are safe patient handling devices designed to bridge the gap between the stretcher and the MRI table while minimizing friction. This reduces the physical strain on the technologist's back and decreases the risk of patient injury during lateral transfers.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-057", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "Proper body mechanics for lifting or transferring a heavy patient include:", "options": ["Bending at the waist to reach the patient", "Keeping the back straight and lifting with the legs", "Holding the patient as far from the body as possible", "Twisting at the torso while carrying the load"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Proper body mechanics require a straight back, bent knees, and use of the large leg muscles to generate lifting force. Bending at the waist, twisting, or holding loads away from the body significantly increases the risk of lumbar spine injury.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-058", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "The \"log rolling\" technique is used to transfer patients with a suspected:", "options": ["Upper extremity fracture", "Spinal injury", "Isolated head injury", "Lower extremity cramp"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Log rolling maintains the entire spinal column in neutral alignment during transfer by moving the patient as a single unit. This technique requires a minimum of three personnel and is essential for any patient with a known or suspected spinal injury.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-059", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "When managing a patient with a urinary catheter during an MRI examination, the drainage bag must be positioned:", "options": ["Above the level of the bladder", "Below the level of the bladder", "On the patient's lap", "Clamped and disconnected"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The drainage bag must remain below bladder level at all times to maintain gravity-dependent urine flow and prevent retrograde reflux into the bladder, which can cause urinary tract infection (UTI).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-060", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Syncope (fainting) is most commonly caused by:", "options": ["Hyperglycemia", "Hypotension", "Systemic infection", "A full stomach"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Syncope results from a transient reduction in cerebral blood flow, most often caused by hypotension (low blood pressure). Common triggers include vasovagal responses, orthostatic changes, and dehydration. The technologist should lower the patient's head and elevate the legs to restore cerebral perfusion.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-061", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Orthostatic hypotension occurs when a patient:", "options": ["Consumes excessive sugar", "Experiences dizziness or lightheadedness upon standing", "Has chronically elevated blood pressure", "Develops an allergic reaction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Orthostatic hypotension is a sudden drop in blood pressure that occurs when a patient moves from a lying or sitting position to standing. Symptoms include dizziness, lightheadedness, and potential syncope. MRI technologists should assist patients in sitting up slowly before standing, particularly elderly patients and those on antihypertensive medications.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-062", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "The normal resting heart rate for an adult is:", "options": ["40–50 beats per minute", "60–100 beats per minute", "100–120 beats per minute", "Greater than 120 beats per minute"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The normal adult resting heart rate ranges from 60 to 100 beats per minute. A rate below 60 bpm is classified as bradycardia, while a rate above 100 bpm is tachycardia. Both extremes may require clinical evaluation before proceeding with the MRI examination.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-063", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Tachycardia is defined as a resting heart rate:", "options": ["Below 50 beats per minute", "Greater than 100 beats per minute", "Associated with elevated blood pressure", "Accompanied by low respiratory rate"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Tachycardia is a resting heart rate exceeding 100 beats per minute. It may be caused by fever, anxiety, pain, dehydration, or cardiac pathology. Bradycardia is defined as a rate below 60 bpm. Tachycardia is a heart rate measurement and should not be confused with blood pressure or respiratory rate abnormalities.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-064", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "When assessing a patient who is receiving supplemental oxygen via a face mask, which method provides the most accurate body temperature measurement?", "options": ["Oral temperature", "Rectal or tympanic temperature", "Axillary temperature", "Forehead strip temperature"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Oral temperature readings are unreliable when the patient is breathing through an open mouth or receiving supplemental oxygen via mask, as airflow across the thermometer affects the reading. Rectal and tympanic (ear) measurements are not affected by respiratory devices and provide more accurate core body temperature readings.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-065", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Hypoxia is defined as:", "options": ["Low blood glucose", "Inadequate oxygen delivery at the tissue level", "Low blood pressure", "Elevated carbon dioxide in the blood"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hypoxia is a condition in which tissues receive insufficient oxygen to maintain normal cellular function. It is indicated by a pulse oximetry (SpO2) reading below 90%. Signs include cyanosis, confusion, and tachycardia. Elevated CO2 is hypercapnia, low glucose is hypoglycemia, and low blood pressure is hypotension.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-066", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "According to current American Heart Association (AHA) guidelines, the correct sequence for adult Basic Life Support (BLS) is:", "options": ["Airway – Breathing – Compressions (A-B-C)", "Compressions – Airway – Breathing (C-A-B)", "Breathing – Airway – Compressions (B-A-C)", "Wait for the physician to arrive before initiating resuscitation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current AHA guidelines recommend initiating chest compressions first (C-A-B) because early compressions maintain coronary and cerebral perfusion. The previous A-B-C sequence delayed compressions while the rescuer assessed the airway and provided breaths. Immediate bystander CPR significantly improves survival rates.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-067", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "The AHA-recommended chest compression rate for adult CPR is:", "options": ["60–80 compressions per minute", "80–100 compressions per minute", "100–120 compressions per minute", "Greater than 140 compressions per minute"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The AHA recommends a compression rate of 100–120 per minute for adult CPR, often compared to the tempo of the song \"Stayin’ Alive.\" Compressions should be at least 2 inches deep with full chest recoil between compressions.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-068", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "The AHA-recommended compression-to-ventilation ratio for single-rescuer adult CPR is:", "options": ["15:2", "5:1", "30:2", "50:2"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The current AHA standard for single-rescuer adult CPR is 30 compressions followed by 2 rescue breaths. This ratio maximizes the time spent delivering chest compressions, which is the most critical intervention for maintaining circulation during cardiac arrest.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-069", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Hypovolemic shock is caused by:", "options": ["Severe systemic infection", "Significant loss of blood or fluid volume", "An acute allergic reaction", "Pump failure of the heart"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hypovolemic shock results from a critical reduction in circulating blood or fluid volume, commonly caused by hemorrhage, severe dehydration, or major burns. Septic shock is caused by infection, anaphylactic shock by allergic reaction, and cardiogenic shock by cardiac pump failure.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-070", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "A severe bloodstream infection that causes systemic inflammatory response and hemodynamic collapse is classified as:", "options": ["Cardiogenic shock", "Septic shock", "Neurogenic shock", "Hypovolemic shock"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Septic shock results from an overwhelming systemic infection that triggers a massive inflammatory response, leading to vasodilation, hypotension, and organ dysfunction. Cardiogenic shock involves cardiac pump failure, neurogenic shock results from spinal cord injury, and hypovolemic shock is caused by volume loss.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-071", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.1", "stem": "The drug of choice for treating severe anaphylaxis with respiratory distress is:", "options": ["Diphenhydramine (Benadryl)", "Epinephrine (adrenaline)", "Aspirin", "Atropine"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Epinephrine is the first-line treatment for severe anaphylaxis because it reverses bronchospasm, reduces mucosal edema, and supports blood pressure through vasoconstriction. Diphenhydramine is an adjunctive antihistamine but acts too slowly for life-threatening reactions. Aspirin and atropine are not indicated for anaphylaxis.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-072", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.F.2", "stem": "Where can a technologist find detailed information on the safe handling of a chemical spill?", "options": ["The patient chart", "The Safety Data Sheet (SDS)", "The MRI technique chart", "The informed consent form"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Safety Data Sheet (SDS), formerly known as the Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS), is a standardized document required by OSHA for all hazardous materials. It contains information on chemical properties, health hazards, first aid measures, spill cleanup procedures, and required personal protective equipment.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-073", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.1", "stem": "An inanimate object that can transmit infectious organisms from one person to another (such as a doorknob or MRI coil surface) is called a:", "options": ["Vector", "Fomite", "Vehicle", "Reservoir"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A fomite is any non-living object or surface that can harbor and transmit pathogens through contact. Common fomites in MRI include coil surfaces, positioning sponges, headphones, and table pads. A vector is a living organism (such as a mosquito) that transmits disease. A vehicle refers to a contaminated medium such as food or water.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-074", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.1", "stem": "Disease transmitted through the bite of a living organism, such as a mosquito or tick, is classified as:", "options": ["Fomite transmission", "Vector-borne transmission", "Droplet transmission", "Vehicle-borne transmission"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Vector-borne transmission involves a living organism (vector) that carries and transmits the pathogen to a new host. Examples include malaria (mosquito), Lyme disease (tick), and Zika virus (mosquito). Fomites are inanimate objects, and vehicles are non-living media such as contaminated food or water.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-075", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.4", "stem": "Airborne precautions — including a negative-pressure isolation room and an N95 respirator — are required for patients with:", "options": ["Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA)", "Seasonal influenza", "Tuberculosis (TB)", "Clostridioides difficile (C. diff)"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Tuberculosis is transmitted via tiny airborne droplet nuclei that remain suspended in the air for extended periods and can travel long distances. This requires airborne precautions with a negative-pressure room and N95 respirator. MRSA requires contact precautions, influenza requires droplet precautions, and C. diff requires contact precautions with soap-and-water hand hygiene.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-076", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "Medical asepsis differs from surgical asepsis (sterilization) in that medical asepsis:", "options": ["Destroys all microorganisms including spores", "Reduces the number of pathogens but does not eliminate all organisms", "Is used exclusively in operating rooms", "Requires an autoclave"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Medical asepsis (\"clean technique\") reduces the number and spread of microorganisms but does not eliminate them entirely. Surgical asepsis (\"sterile technique\") involves the complete destruction of all microorganisms and their spores. Most MRI procedures require medical asepsis; surgical asepsis is reserved for invasive procedures.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-077", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "The non-sterile border surrounding a sterile field extends:", "options": ["One-half inch from the edge", "One inch from the edge", "Four inches from the edge", "The entire outer edge is sterile"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The standard non-sterile border of a sterile field is one inch from the edge of the drape. Any item that touches or falls within this border is considered contaminated. The technologist must avoid reaching over the sterile field and ensure all sterile items remain within the safe zone.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-078", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "If a sterile package appears damp or shows evidence of moisture penetration (\"strike-through\"), the technologist should:", "options": ["Dry the package and use it", "Discard the package as contaminated", "Proceed with caution", "Use it last to minimize risk"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Moisture acts as a bridge for bacterial migration (\"wicking\") from non-sterile surfaces through the packaging material, compromising the sterile barrier. Any package with visible moisture, tears, or broken seals must be considered contaminated and discarded.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-079", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "The most effective method of sterilization for reusable metal instruments is:", "options": ["Chemical disinfectant soaking", "Autoclaving (steam under pressure)", "Ultraviolet light exposure", "Freezing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Autoclaving uses pressurized steam at high temperature (typically 121°C / 250°F at 15 psi) to destroy all microorganisms and their spores. It is the gold standard for sterilizing heat-resistant metal instruments. Chemical soaking achieves high-level disinfection but not true sterilization.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-080", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "According to CDC guidelines, the recommended minimum duration for effective hand washing is:", "options": ["5 seconds", "10 seconds", "20 seconds", "1 minute"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The CDC recommends washing hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds — approximately the time it takes to hum \"Happy Birthday\" twice. Effective hand hygiene is the single most important measure for preventing the transmission of healthcare-associated infections.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-081", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.5", "stem": "A patient undergoing chemotherapy who has a severely compromised immune system requires which type of isolation?", "options": ["Protective (reverse) isolation", "Contact isolation", "Airborne isolation", "Droplet isolation"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Protective (reverse) isolation protects the immunocompromised patient from environmental pathogens brought in by healthcare workers and visitors. Unlike standard isolation that protects staff from the patient, reverse isolation protects the patient from the staff and surroundings.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-082", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.5", "stem": "Nosocomial (healthcare-associated) infections are commonly caused by which pathogens?", "options": ["Ebola and Marburg viruses", "MRSA and Clostridioides difficile (C. diff)", "Malaria parasites", "Rabies virus"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Healthcare-associated infections (HAIs) — formerly called nosocomial infections — are most commonly caused by organisms that thrive in hospital environments, including MRSA and C. diff. These organisms are frequently transmitted via contaminated surfaces and inadequate hand hygiene. Ebola, malaria, and rabies are not typical HAI pathogens.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-083", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.3", "stem": "\"Standard Precautions\" in infection control means:", "options": ["Wearing gloves only when caring for HIV-positive patients", "Treating all blood and body fluids as potentially infectious regardless of diagnosis", "Wearing a mask at all times", "Taking precautions only when a patient has a known communicable disease"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Standard Precautions (formerly Universal Precautions) assume that all blood, body fluids, secretions, excretions, non-intact skin, and mucous membranes may contain transmissible infectious agents. This approach applies to every patient encounter, regardless of known or suspected infection status.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-084", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "When using a power injector, the \"Keep Vein Open\" (KVO) rate serves to:", "options": ["Deliver contrast at the maximum flow rate", "Maintain IV patency by providing a slow saline drip between injections", "Measure the patient's estimated glomerular filtration rate", "Warm the contrast agent to body temperature"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The KVO rate delivers a slow continuous saline drip (typically 1–2 mL/s) to prevent the IV line from clotting between contrast injections. This maintains catheter patency without delivering a significant fluid volume. The KVO rate is distinct from the contrast injection rate and the saline flush rate.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-085", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "\"Bolus tracking\" or \"fluoro-triggering\" allows the MRI scan to begin:", "options": ["Immediately after contrast injection without delay", "Automatically when contrast reaches a predetermined signal intensity threshold in the target vessel", "After a fixed five-minute delay", "Before contrast is administered"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Bolus tracking monitors a region of interest (ROI) placed over the target vessel in real time. When the contrast bolus arrives and signal intensity crosses the preset threshold, the diagnostic sequence is triggered automatically. This technique ensures optimal arterial-phase timing for contrast-enhanced MRA and dynamic studies.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-086", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Warming gadolinium-based contrast agents before injection primarily reduces:", "options": ["The magnetic susceptibility of the agent", "The viscosity of the agent, making injection easier", "The total volume required for the study", "The sterility of the contrast vial"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Warming gadolinium contrast to body temperature reduces its viscosity, which lowers injection resistance and allows smoother delivery through small-gauge catheters. This is particularly important for power-injected studies where high viscosity could trigger pressure-limit alarms or cause catheter failure.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-087", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "Which laboratory value is critical to evaluate before administering gadolinium-based contrast agents?", "options": ["Liver enzyme levels", "Estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR)", "White blood cell count", "Serum cholesterol level"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The eGFR measures renal function and is the key screening value before gadolinium administration. Patients with severely impaired renal function (eGFR <30 mL/min/1.73m²) are at increased risk for nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF), particularly with Group I (linear) agents. Liver enzymes, WBC, and cholesterol are not directly relevant to contrast safety.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-088", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "According to ACR guidelines, gadolinium-based contrast agents are generally considered safe when the patient's eGFR is:", "options": ["Greater than 10 mL/min/1.73m²", "Greater than 30 mL/min/1.73m²", "Less than 15 mL/min/1.73m²", "Exactly 100 mL/min/1.73m²"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR Manual on Contrast Media establishes an eGFR threshold of 30 mL/min/1.73m² as the general safety cutoff for gadolinium administration. Below this level, the risk of NSF increases significantly, especially with Group I (linear) agents. Group II (macrocyclic) agents carry a much lower risk but screening is still recommended.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-089", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "The primary risk factor for developing Nephrogenic Systemic Fibrosis (NSF) is:", "options": ["Hypertension", "Severe renal insufficiency (eGFR <30)", "Asthma", "Prior contrast allergy"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "NSF is a debilitating fibrotic condition affecting the skin and internal organs, linked almost exclusively to gadolinium exposure in patients with severe renal impairment. The risk is highest with Group I (linear) agents in patients with eGFR <30. Hypertension, asthma, and prior contrast allergy are not independent risk factors for NSF.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-090", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "According to ACR guidelines, the recommendation for breastfeeding mothers after receiving gadolinium contrast is:", "options": ["Pump and discard breast milk for 24 hours", "Continue breastfeeding without interruption", "Permanently discontinue breastfeeding", "Gadolinium is absolutely contraindicated during lactation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR states that less than 0.04% of the administered gadolinium dose enters breast milk, and the infant absorbs less than 1% of that amount orally. The systemic dose to the infant is considered negligible, and breastfeeding may continue without interruption. Pump-and-dump is no longer recommended.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-091", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "A \"bolus\" injection refers to:", "options": ["A slow continuous drip over several hours", "A rapid injection of a specific volume at one time", "An intramuscular injection", "Oral administration of contrast"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A bolus injection delivers the entire contrast dose rapidly as a single push, which is the standard method for gadolinium administration in MRI. This produces a concentrated contrast bolus that enables optimal vascular and tissue enhancement. A slow infusion over time is called a drip.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-092", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Which of the following IV catheter gauges has the largest diameter?", "options": ["22 gauge", "20 gauge", "18 gauge", "24 gauge"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In the gauge system for needles and catheters, a smaller gauge number indicates a larger diameter. An 18-gauge catheter has the largest lumen of the options listed, allowing higher flow rates for power injection. A 24-gauge catheter is the smallest and is typically used for pediatric patients.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-093", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Applying a tourniquet before venipuncture causes the veins to:", "options": ["Collapse and become less visible", "Distend with blood and become more prominent", "Disappear beneath the skin", "Become sterilized"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A tourniquet occludes venous return while allowing continued arterial flow, causing blood to pool and veins to distend. This makes veins more visible and palpable, facilitating catheter placement. The tourniquet should not be left in place for more than one minute to avoid tissue ischemia.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-094", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "If contrast extravasation occurs during injection, the technologist should:", "options": ["Increase the injection rate to push the contrast through", "Apply heat to the injection site immediately", "Stop the injection, remove the catheter, and apply pressure followed by ice", "Apply a tourniquet proximal to the site"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "When extravasation is detected, the injection must be stopped immediately to prevent further tissue infiltration. The catheter should be removed, and direct pressure applied. Ice (cold compress) should be applied to cause vasoconstriction and reduce swelling. The extremity should be elevated, and the event documented. Warm compresses may be used after 24 hours.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-095", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Flushing the IV tubing with saline before contrast injection primarily prevents:", "options": ["Cooling of the contrast agent", "Air embolism", "Extravasation", "Mixing of incompatible medications"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Flushing IV tubing with saline before connecting to the power injector removes air from the line, preventing potentially fatal air embolism. Even small volumes of air injected intravenously can cause cardiovascular compromise. This is a critical patient safety step that must never be skipped.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-096", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "Mild adverse reactions to gadolinium contrast typically present as:", "options": ["Peripheral edema", "Nausea and urticaria (hives)", "Cardiac arrest", "Seizure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Mild contrast reactions include nausea, urticaria (hives), pruritis (itching), and mild headache. These reactions are generally self-limiting and may be treated with observation or antihistamines. Cardiac arrest and seizures represent severe, life-threatening reactions requiring emergency intervention.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-097", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "A vasovagal reaction is characterized by:", "options": ["Hypertension and tachycardia", "Pallor, hypotension, and bradycardia", "Urticaria and pruritis", "Fever and chills"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A vasovagal reaction is a parasympathetic-mediated response that produces pallor (pale skin), hypotension (low blood pressure), and bradycardia (slow heart rate). It may progress to syncope (fainting). Treatment includes placing the patient supine with legs elevated. This is distinct from an allergic reaction, which presents with hives and potential anaphylaxis.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-098", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The approximate half-life of gadolinium contrast in a patient with normal renal function is:", "options": ["5 minutes", "2 hours", "24 hours", "1 week"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents are eliminated primarily through glomerular filtration with a half-life of approximately 1.5–2 hours in patients with normal renal function. Nearly all of the administered dose is excreted within 24 hours. In patients with renal impairment, the half-life is significantly prolonged, increasing the risk of NSF.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-099", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "A legal document that designates a specific person to make medical decisions for a patient if they become incapacitated is called a:", "options": ["Living will", "Healthcare proxy (durable power of attorney)", "Do-not-resuscitate (DNR) order", "Informed consent form"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A healthcare proxy (also called durable power of attorney for healthcare) designates a specific individual to make medical decisions on the patient's behalf if they become unable to do so. A living will outlines the patient's wishes for end-of-life care but does not designate a decision-maker. A DNR order addresses only resuscitation preferences.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-100", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which ethical principle refers to the duty to act in the patient's best interest and actively promote their well-being?", "options": ["Beneficence", "Nonmaleficence", "Autonomy", "Veracity"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Beneficence is the active promotion of the patient's welfare — doing good. This is distinct from nonmaleficence (avoiding harm), autonomy (respecting the patient's right to self-determination), and veracity (the duty of truthfulness).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-101", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Using physical restraints on a patient without a physician's order or documented medical necessity may result in a legal charge of:", "options": ["Battery", "Negligence", "False imprisonment", "Assault"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "False imprisonment is the unlawful restriction of a person's freedom of movement. Applying physical restraints without proper authorization (physician's order plus documented medical necessity) constitutes false imprisonment. Battery is unauthorized touching, assault is the threat of harm, and negligence is failure to meet the standard of care.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-102", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "According to The Joint Commission (TJC) standards, the minimum required patient identifiers before performing any imaging examination are:", "options": ["Patient name and room number", "Patient name and date of birth (or medical record number)", "Patient name and physician name", "Date of birth and examination type"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "TJC requires a minimum of two unique patient identifiers to verify identity before any procedure. Acceptable identifiers include the patient's full name combined with date of birth or medical record number. Room number is not an acceptable identifier because patients can be moved between rooms.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-103", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When communicating with a patient who does not speak English, the standard of care requires the use of:", "options": ["A family member as interpreter", "A qualified medical interpreter", "Gestures and sign language", "Speaking slowly and loudly"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Healthcare facilities are required to provide qualified medical interpreters for patients with limited English proficiency. Family members may misinterpret medical terminology or omit critical information, and their use raises patient confidentiality concerns. Speaking louder does not overcome a language barrier.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-104", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The most important discharge instruction for a patient who has received gadolinium contrast is:", "options": ["\"Do not eat for four hours\"", "\"Drink plenty of fluids to help flush the contrast\"", "\"Avoid sunlight for 24 hours\"", "\"Stay in bed for the rest of the day\""], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Adequate hydration after gadolinium administration supports renal excretion of the contrast agent. Patients should be encouraged to drink water or clear fluids to promote kidney function and accelerate contrast clearance. There are no restrictions on food, sunlight, or activity following gadolinium administration.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-105", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "If a patient's IV infusion pump begins to alarm during the MRI scan, the technologist should:", "options": ["Turn the pump off immediately", "Contact the nurse to troubleshoot the alarm", "Clamp the IV line and continue scanning", "Unplug the pump from the outlet"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRI technologists should not independently alter infusion pump settings or rates without proper training and physician orders. The appropriate response is to pause the scan if necessary and notify the patient's nurse, who has the authority and training to troubleshoot the alarm and adjust the pump.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-106", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "When caring for a patient with a nasogastric (NG) tube, the technologist must ensure that:", "options": ["The tube is clamped tightly at all times", "The tube is secured to the patient's nose and gown to prevent accidental dislodgment", "The patient is positioned completely flat", "The tube is removed before scanning"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Nasogastric tubes must be properly secured during patient transfer and scanning to prevent accidental dislodgment, which is painful and requires reinsertion. Suction should only be disconnected with a physician's order. The head of the bed should typically remain slightly elevated (30 degrees) to reduce aspiration risk.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-107", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "When administering supplemental oxygen to a patient with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), a lower flow rate (such as 2 L/min) is typically used because:", "options": ["Higher flow rates waste oxygen", "High-flow oxygen can suppress the hypoxic respiratory drive in COPD patients", "COPD patients are allergic to high concentrations of oxygen", "High-flow oxygen causes excessive coughing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Many COPD patients rely on a \"hypoxic drive\" to stimulate breathing — their chemoreceptors respond primarily to low oxygen levels rather than elevated CO2. Administering high-flow oxygen can eliminate this stimulus, potentially causing respiratory depression or arrest. Low-flow (1–2 L/min) nasal cannula is the standard approach.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-108", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.1", "stem": "In the chain of infection, a person with a compromised immune system (such as a cancer or diabetes patient) is classified as the:", "options": ["Reservoir", "Susceptible host", "Portal of exit", "Mode of transmission"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The susceptible host is the final link in the chain of infection — a person whose weakened immune defenses allow the pathogen to establish infection. Immunocompromised patients (chemotherapy, diabetes, HIV) are highly susceptible hosts. Breaking any link in the chain (reservoir, portal of exit, mode of transmission, portal of entry, susceptible host) prevents infection transmission.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-109", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.1", "stem": "Transmission of disease through contaminated food, water, drugs, or blood products is classified as:", "options": ["Vector-borne transmission", "Vehicle-borne transmission", "Airborne transmission", "Droplet transmission"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Vehicle-borne transmission occurs through a non-living contaminated medium that carries the pathogen to the host. Common vehicles include food, water, blood products, and medications. This is distinct from vector-borne transmission (living organisms), airborne transmission (suspended droplet nuclei), and droplet transmission (large respiratory particles).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-110", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "To prevent needlestick injuries, contaminated needles must always be:", "options": ["Recapped using two hands before disposal", "Bent or broken before placement in waste", "Placed directly into a sharps container without recapping", "Discarded in the regular trash"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "OSHA regulations prohibit recapping contaminated needles using two hands due to the high risk of needlestick injury. Used needles must be placed directly into a puncture-resistant sharps container without recapping, bending, or breaking. If recapping is absolutely necessary, the one-handed \"scoop\" technique must be used.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-111", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.4", "stem": "Clostridioides difficile (C. diff) requires enteric precautions, which specifically mandate:", "options": ["Using alcohol-based hand sanitizer", "Washing hands thoroughly with soap and water", "Wearing an N95 respirator", "Leaving the patient's door open for ventilation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "C. diff spores are resistant to alcohol-based hand sanitizers. Thorough hand washing with soap and water is the only effective method for removing C. diff spores from the hands. Contact precautions (gown and gloves) are also required, and the patient's room should be cleaned with sporicidal agents.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-112", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "\"Medication reconciliation\" is the process of:", "options": ["Prescribing new medications for the patient", "Comparing the patient's current medication list against new orders to identify discrepancies", "Disposing of expired medications", "Calculating the correct dosage for contrast agents"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Medication reconciliation is a patient safety process that compares medications the patient is currently taking against newly ordered medications to identify and resolve discrepancies such as duplications, omissions, drug interactions, and dosing errors. It is required at every transition of care.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-113", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "A patient with a known allergy to contrast media may be prescribed a premedication protocol consisting of:", "options": ["Antibiotics and aspirin", "Corticosteroids and antihistamines", "Beta-blockers and diuretics", "Insulin and glucose"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The standard premedication protocol for patients with prior contrast reactions includes corticosteroids (such as prednisone or methylprednisolone) to suppress the immune response and antihistamines (such as diphenhydramine) to block histamine-mediated symptoms. This protocol is typically administered 12–13 hours and again 1–2 hours before the contrast study.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-114", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "Inflammation of a vein, often presenting with pain, redness, and swelling at the IV site, is called:", "options": ["Extravasation", "Phlebitis", "Cyanosis", "Embolism"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Phlebitis is inflammation of a vein, commonly caused by mechanical irritation from the catheter, chemical irritation from medications, or infection. Signs include pain, erythema (redness), warmth, and swelling along the vein. If untreated, phlebitis can progress to thrombophlebitis (clot formation) or infection.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-115", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Glucagon is sometimes administered before abdominal MRI to:", "options": ["Increase the patient's heart rate", "Reduce bowel peristalsis (motion)", "Enhance renal function", "Sedate the patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Glucagon is an antispasmodic agent that temporarily inhibits smooth muscle contraction, reducing bowel peristalsis and associated motion artifact. It is commonly used in abdominal MRI studies including enterography, MRCP, and dynamic liver imaging where bowel motion can degrade image quality.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-116", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.5", "stem": "If a diabetic patient becomes hypoglycemic (presenting with shakiness, confusion, and diaphoresis), the immediate treatment is to administer:", "options": ["Insulin", "A rapid-acting form of glucose (such as orange juice or glucose tablets)", "A beta-blocker", "Water only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hypoglycemia (blood sugar <70 mg/dL) requires immediate glucose replacement. Oral sources such as orange juice, glucose tablets, or candy provide rapid blood sugar elevation. Administering insulin would further lower blood sugar and worsen the emergency. If the patient is unconscious, IV dextrose or intramuscular glucagon should be administered by trained personnel.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-117", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "The period of drowsiness and confusion that immediately follows a seizure is called the:", "options": ["Tonic phase", "Post-ictal state", "Aura", "Clonic phase"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The post-ictal state is the recovery period following a seizure, characterized by drowsiness, confusion, headache, and sometimes temporary weakness. Patients require close monitoring and a safe environment during this phase. The tonic phase involves sustained muscle contraction, and the clonic phase involves rhythmic jerking.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-118", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Which of the following factors increases a patient's risk of falling during an MRI visit?", "options": ["Being younger than 50 years old", "Polypharmacy (taking multiple sedating medications)", "Having eaten a full meal", "Chronic hypertension"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Polypharmacy — particularly the use of multiple sedating medications such as opioids, benzodiazepines, and antihistamines — is a significant risk factor for falls. Other fall risk factors include advanced age, altered mental status, recent anesthesia, mobility impairment, and orthostatic hypotension.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-119", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents are classified into two structural groups: linear and macrocyclic. Which category is considered more chemically stable and less likely to deposit in tissues?", "options": ["Linear ionic agents", "Linear non-ionic agents", "Macrocyclic agents", "Both categories are equally stable"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Macrocyclic agents have a cage-like molecular structure that binds the gadolinium ion more tightly, significantly reducing the risk of dissociation (release of free toxic gadolinium) and tissue deposition. Linear agents have an open-chain structure that allows greater dissociation, which has been associated with NSF and gadolinium brain deposition.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-120", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "When caring for a patient with a chest tube and water-seal drainage system, the drainage unit must be kept:", "options": ["On the patient's lap during transfer", "Upright and below the level of the patient's chest", "Clamped during the entire scan", "Above the patient's head"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The water-seal drainage unit must remain upright and below chest level to maintain gravity-dependent drainage and prevent fluid from flowing back into the pleural space. Tipping the unit can break the water seal, potentially causing a pneumothorax. The tube should not be routinely clamped unless specifically ordered by the physician.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-121", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.4", "stem": "Droplet precautions — requiring a standard surgical mask within three feet of the patient — are indicated for which of the following diseases?", "options": ["Tuberculosis", "Influenza or bacterial meningitis", "MRSA", "Hepatitis B"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Droplet precautions apply to pathogens transmitted via large respiratory droplets that travel short distances (approximately 3–6 feet). Influenza and bacterial meningitis spread through droplets. Tuberculosis requires airborne precautions (N95 respirator), MRSA requires contact precautions, and hepatitis B is transmitted through blood and body fluids (standard precautions).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-122", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "The term \"parenteral\" administration refers to:", "options": ["Oral administration", "Rectal administration", "Any route other than the gastrointestinal tract (such as IV, IM, or subcutaneous)", "Topical administration"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Parenteral literally means \"beside the intestine\" — any route that bypasses the GI tract. In MRI, gadolinium contrast is almost always administered parenterally via intravenous injection. Other parenteral routes include intramuscular (IM), subcutaneous (SC), and intradermal (ID).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-123", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "When monitoring a patient under moderate (conscious) sedation, which monitoring device provides the earliest warning of respiratory depression?", "options": ["Pulse oximeter", "Capnograph (end-tidal CO2 monitor)", "ECG monitor", "Blood pressure cuff"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Capnography measures breath-by-breath ventilation by detecting exhaled CO2 and identifies apnea or hypoventilation within seconds. Pulse oximetry lags behind respiratory depression because oxygen saturation does not drop until after ventilation has already been compromised. ECG and blood pressure monitoring detect cardiovascular changes, not respiratory depression.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-124", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "When setting up a power injector, the pressure limit (PSI) is configured to prevent:", "options": ["The contrast from cooling during injection", "Catheter or vein rupture due to excessive injection force", "Air embolism", "The scan from triggering prematurely"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The pressure limit is a safety mechanism that automatically stops the injection if resistance in the IV line or vein exceeds the preset threshold. This prevents catheter failure, vein rupture, or severe extravasation. The PSI limit is set based on the catheter gauge and location — smaller catheters and hand veins require lower pressure limits.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-125", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "Which type of adverse reaction to gadolinium contrast can occur 3 hours to 7 days after injection?", "options": ["Acute anaphylaxis", "Vasovagal reaction", "Delayed cutaneous reaction", "Air embolism"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Delayed contrast reactions typically manifest as skin reactions — rash, erythema, urticaria, or pruritis — appearing hours to days after gadolinium administration. They are generally self-limiting and treated with antihistamines or topical steroids. Patients should be informed about the possibility of delayed reactions at discharge.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-126", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "If a technologist makes an error in a paper medical record, the correct method to fix it is to:", "options": ["Apply correction fluid (white-out)", "Erase the entry completely", "Draw a single line through the error, write \"error,\" and initial and date the correction", "Scribble over the entry so it cannot be read"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Medical record corrections must maintain the legibility of the original entry for legal transparency. The correct method is to draw a single line through the error (keeping the original readable), label it \"error,\" and add initials and the date. Using white-out, erasing, or obscuring entries may constitute spoliation and raises legal concerns.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-127", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "When cleaning MRI surface coils and positioning devices, the technologist should use:", "options": ["Full-strength hospital bleach", "A disinfectant approved by the equipment manufacturer", "Water only", "Sterile saline"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRI coils contain sensitive electronic components and specialized housings that can be damaged by harsh chemicals. The technologist should use only manufacturer-approved disinfectants to ensure effective cleaning without degrading the coil housing, insulation, or electronic connections, which could create safety hazards or image artifacts.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-128", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Before placing ECG electrodes for cardiac gating, the patient's skin should be prepared (shaved and lightly abraded) primarily to:", "options": ["Remove surface bacteria", "Reduce skin impedance and improve signal quality", "Cool the skin surface", "Prevent hair pulling during electrode removal"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Poor electrode-to-skin contact caused by high impedance (resistance) degrades the ECG signal quality, produces gating artifacts, and increases the risk of RF-induced heating and burns at the electrode site. Skin preparation removes oils, dead skin cells, and hair to maximize conductivity and ensure reliable cardiac gating.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-129", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "The acronym FAST is used to rapidly assess a patient for signs of:", "options": ["Heart attack (myocardial infarction)", "Stroke (cerebrovascular accident)", "Seizure", "Diabetic coma"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "FAST stands for Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, and Time to call 911. It is a validated rapid screening tool for stroke recognition. Early identification and treatment of stroke (within the therapeutic window) significantly improves patient outcomes.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-130", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When using a mechanical or hydraulic patient lift for transfer, the most important safety step is to:", "options": ["Move as quickly as possible", "Verify the weight limit and ensure the sling is properly seated under the patient", "Have the patient hold their breath during the lift", "Use the smallest available sling"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Improper sling sizing, incorrect sling placement, and exceeding the lift's weight capacity are the leading causes of patient falls during mechanical transfers. The technologist must verify the lift's weight limit against the patient's weight and ensure the sling is properly positioned under the patient's thighs and back before initiating the lift.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-131", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "For a patient taking metformin (Glucophage) who has acute kidney injury or severe chronic kidney disease, the protocol for gadolinium contrast administration typically requires:", "options": ["Continuing metformin without modification", "Withholding metformin for 48 hours after injection and re-evaluating renal function", "Substituting insulin for metformin", "Performing immediate dialysis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "While routine metformin discontinuation is no longer required for patients with normal renal function, patients with acute kidney injury or severe CKD are at risk of contrast-induced renal decline. If renal function worsens, metformin can accumulate and cause life-threatening lactic acidosis. The 48-hour hold allows renal function to be reassessed.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-132", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "An incident report regarding a patient injury in the MRI department:", "options": ["Is placed directly in the patient's medical chart", "Is an internal administrative document and is not part of the medical record", "Is mailed to the patient's home address", "Is optional and only filed at the technologist's discretion"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Incident reports are internal risk management and quality improvement documents. They are not part of the medical record and should not be referenced in the patient's chart, as this could compromise the legal privilege that protects them from discovery in litigation. The clinical facts of the event should be documented objectively in the medical record.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-133", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When transferring a patient with a suspected spinal injury from a stretcher to the MRI table, the safest method is:", "options": ["The draw-sheet transfer", "The slide board with log-rolling technique", "The two-person cradle lift", "Having the patient scoot independently"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The slide board combined with log-rolling maintains spinal alignment throughout the transfer by moving the patient as a single unit. This method bridges the gap between surfaces while minimizing flexion, extension, and rotation of the spine. It requires a coordinated team effort with one person controlling the head and neck.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-134", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal doctrine that may hold a supervising physician liable for a technologist's negligence when the technologist was acting under the physician's direct supervision is:", "options": ["Res ipsa loquitur", "Borrowed servant", "Corporate liability", "Stare decisis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The borrowed servant doctrine applies when a physician exercises direct control over a technologist during a specific task — essentially \"borrowing\" the employee from the hospital. The supervising physician becomes liable for the technologist's actions performed under their direction. This is distinct from respondeat superior, which holds the employer liable.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-135", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which ethical principle refers to the duty to tell the truth and avoid deception?", "options": ["Beneficence", "Nonmaleficence", "Veracity", "Fidelity"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Veracity is the ethical obligation to be truthful and transparent in all interactions with patients. This includes providing honest information about procedures, risks, and outcomes. Fidelity is faithfulness and keeping promises, beneficence is promoting good, and nonmaleficence is avoiding harm.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-136", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The ethical principle of fidelity refers to:", "options": ["Telling the truth", "Faithfulness and keeping promises", "Doing good for the patient", "The patient's right to self-determination"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Fidelity is the ethical duty to be loyal and to fulfill commitments made to patients. This includes following through on promised care, maintaining professional boundaries, and honoring the trust placed in the healthcare provider by the patient.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-137", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Which category of medication is used to treat nausea and vomiting?", "options": ["Analgesic", "Antiemetic", "Antihistamine", "Anticoagulant"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Antiemetics (anti- = against, emesis = vomiting) are drugs that prevent or treat nausea and vomiting. A common example is ondansetron (Zofran), frequently used as premedication for patients prone to contrast-related nausea. Analgesics relieve pain, antihistamines treat allergic reactions, and anticoagulants prevent blood clotting.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-138", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Medications such as heparin and warfarin (Coumadin) are classified as:", "options": ["Thrombolytics", "Anticoagulants", "Diuretics", "Analgesics"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Anticoagulants (\"blood thinners\") prevent new clots from forming by inhibiting clotting factors. Heparin acts rapidly and is used in acute settings, while warfarin has a delayed onset and is used for long-term anticoagulation. These drugs do not dissolve existing clots — that is the function of thrombolytics.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-139", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Thrombolytic agents (such as tPA) differ from anticoagulants because they:", "options": ["Prevent new clots from forming", "Actively dissolve or break down existing blood clots", "Increase systemic blood pressure", "Promote clot formation at the injury site"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Thrombolytics (\"clot busters\") actively dissolve existing clots by converting plasminogen to plasmin, which breaks down fibrin. They are used in acute stroke, pulmonary embolism, and myocardial infarction. Anticoagulants prevent new clot formation but cannot dissolve clots that have already formed.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-140", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Which drug is the specific reversal agent for opioid overdose (such as morphine or fentanyl)?", "options": ["Flumazenil (Romazicon)", "Naloxone (Narcan)", "Epinephrine", "Atropine"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Naloxone (Narcan) is a competitive opioid antagonist that rapidly reverses respiratory depression, sedation, and hypotension caused by opioid overdose. It can be administered IV, IM, SC, or intranasally. Flumazenil reverses benzodiazepines, not opioids. Epinephrine treats anaphylaxis, and atropine treats bradycardia.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-141", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Which drug is the specific reversal agent for benzodiazepine overdose (such as diazepam or midazolam)?", "options": ["Flumazenil (Romazicon)", "Naloxone (Narcan)", "Glucagon", "Diphenhydramine (Benadryl)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Flumazenil (Romazicon) is a competitive benzodiazepine antagonist that reverses the sedative and respiratory depressant effects of benzodiazepines such as midazolam (Versed) and diazepam (Valium). It is essential for managing over-sedation during conscious sedation procedures in MRI.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-142", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Medications such as furosemide (Lasix) that increase urine output to treat edema or hypertension are called:", "options": ["Diuretics", "Antiemetics", "Cathartics", "Sedatives"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Diuretics promote the excretion of water and sodium by the kidneys, reducing fluid volume and lowering blood pressure. Patients on diuretics may need more frequent bathroom breaks during long MRI examinations and may be at increased risk for dehydration and orthostatic hypotension.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-143", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "While the normal adult resting pulse is 60–100 bpm, the normal resting heart rate for a preschool-age child (ages 3–5) is approximately:", "options": ["40–60 bpm", "60–80 bpm", "80–120 bpm", "120–160 bpm"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Pediatric heart rates are naturally faster than adult rates due to smaller cardiac stroke volume. Typical resting heart rates for preschool children (3–5 years) range from 80–120 bpm. Neonates have the fastest rates (120–160 bpm), which gradually decrease toward adult norms through adolescence.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-144", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "The leakage of a non-vesicant fluid (such as normal saline) into surrounding tissue at the IV site is clinically termed:", "options": ["Extravasation", "Infiltration", "Phlebitis", "Embolism"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Infiltration refers to the leakage of non-irritating (non-vesicant) fluids into surrounding tissue, while extravasation specifically refers to leakage of vesicant or irritating fluids (such as gadolinium contrast) that can cause tissue necrosis. This distinction is clinically important because extravasation requires more aggressive intervention.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-145", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "Semi-critical items that contact mucous membranes (such as endocavitary coils) require:", "options": ["Low-level disinfection", "High-level disinfection", "Sterilization only", "Cleaning with water alone"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Spaulding classification categorizes medical devices by infection risk. Semi-critical items contact mucous membranes or non-intact skin and require high-level disinfection, which eliminates all vegetative microorganisms, mycobacteria, and viruses but not necessarily all bacterial spores. Critical items (entering sterile tissue) require sterilization.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-146", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Analgesic medications are prescribed specifically to:", "options": ["Induce sleep", "Relieve pain", "Prevent infection", "Reduce fever"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Analgesics are drugs specifically designed to relieve pain. They range from non-opioid options (NSAIDs, acetaminophen) to opioid agents (morphine, fentanyl). Sleep-inducing drugs are sedatives/hypnotics, infection-preventing drugs are antibiotics/antiseptics, and fever-reducing drugs are antipyretics.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-147", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal theory of corporate liability holds that:", "options": ["The technologist is solely responsible for all errors", "The hospital or facility has a duty to ensure safe equipment and employ qualified staff", "The physician is always the responsible party", "The patient assumes all risk upon entering the facility"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Corporate liability holds the healthcare institution itself responsible for maintaining a safe environment, properly credentialing staff, and ensuring functional equipment. Unlike respondeat superior (which is vicarious liability through employees), corporate liability is a direct duty owed by the organization to its patients.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-148", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "A PICC line (peripherally inserted central catheter) differs from a standard peripheral IV because its tip terminates in the:", "options": ["Axillary vein", "Superior vena cava (SVC)", "Radial artery", "Subclavian vein"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A PICC line is inserted into a peripheral vein (typically in the upper arm) but is advanced until the tip rests in the superior vena cava near the right atrium. This central placement allows for long-term IV therapy, administration of irritating medications, and high-flow-rate contrast injection. MRI technologists should verify PICC line compatibility before scanning.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-149", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal term for the unlawful touching of a person without their consent is:", "options": ["Assault", "Battery", "Negligence", "Defamation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Battery is the unauthorized physical contact with another person. Assault is the threat of harmful contact that creates reasonable apprehension — no actual touching is required. Students commonly confuse these two terms on the ARRT exam.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-150", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A patient who has already signed a consent form and is mid-procedure:", "options": ["Cannot withdraw consent once the procedure has begun", "May withdraw consent only if a complication occurs", "Retains the right to revoke consent at any time", "Must obtain the radiologist's permission to withdraw consent"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Consent is voluntary and continuous — a competent patient may withdraw it at any moment, even after the procedure has begun. The technologist must immediately stop the examination and safely remove the patient if consent is revoked.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-151", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal doctrine \"res ipsa loquitur\" translates to:", "options": ["\"Let the master answer\"", "\"The thing speaks for itself\"", "\"Stand by things decided\"", "\"First, do no harm\""], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Res ipsa loquitur (\"the thing speaks for itself\") applies when the negligence is self-evident from the injury — such as a retained surgical instrument. \"Let the master answer\" is respondeat superior (employer liability). \"Stand by things decided\" is stare decisis (legal precedent).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-152", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which component of the ARRT Standards of Ethics is mandatory, enforceable, and can result in revocation of certification if violated?", "options": ["The Code of Ethics", "The Rules of Ethics", "The Preamble", "The Mission Statement"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ARRT Standards of Ethics consists of two parts: the Code of Ethics (aspirational ideals for professional conduct) and the Rules of Ethics (mandatory, enforceable standards). Violations of the Rules can result in disciplinary action including revocation of certification.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-153", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The medical term for difficulty breathing is:", "options": ["Aphasia", "Dysphagia", "Dyspnea", "Dysphonia"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Dyspnea is difficulty breathing (dysp- = difficult, -pnea = breathing). Aphasia is difficulty with language/speech (often from stroke). Dysphagia is difficulty swallowing. Dysphonia is difficulty with voice production. These terms are frequently tested and commonly confused.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-154", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.1", "stem": "A living organism such as a mosquito or tick that transmits disease from one host to another is classified as a:", "options": ["Fomite", "Vector", "Vehicle", "Reservoir"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A vector is a living organism that transmits pathogens between hosts (examples: mosquitoes for malaria, ticks for Lyme disease). A fomite is an inanimate object that harbors pathogens (doorknobs, coil surfaces). A vehicle is a non-living medium like contaminated food or water. A reservoir is where the pathogen normally lives and multiplies.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-155", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.2", "stem": "Surgical asepsis (sterilization) differs from medical asepsis in that surgical asepsis:", "options": ["Only reduces the number of pathogens present", "Destroys all microorganisms and their spores", "Is achieved through routine hand washing", "Applies only to non-critical medical devices"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Surgical asepsis (sterile technique) achieves complete destruction of all microorganisms including resistant bacterial spores. Medical asepsis (clean technique) reduces the pathogen count but does not eliminate all organisms. Sterilization is required for critical items that enter sterile body tissue.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-156", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.4", "stem": "The most effective method for removing Clostridioides difficile (C. diff) spores from the hands is:", "options": ["Alcohol-based hand sanitizer", "Thorough hand washing with soap and water", "Antiseptic wipes", "Hydrogen peroxide rinse"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "C. diff spores are highly resistant to alcohol-based hand sanitizers and most antiseptic agents. Only thorough mechanical hand washing with soap and water can effectively remove these spores from the skin. This is why soap-and-water hand hygiene is specifically mandated for C. diff contact precautions.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-157", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.E.4", "stem": "Tuberculosis (TB) requires which level of transmission-based precautions?", "options": ["Contact precautions with gown and gloves", "Droplet precautions with a standard surgical mask", "Airborne precautions with a negative-pressure room and N95 respirator", "Standard precautions only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Tuberculosis is transmitted via tiny airborne droplet nuclei (<5 microns) that remain suspended in the air for extended periods. This requires airborne precautions including a negative-pressure isolation room and an N95 or higher respirator for all personnel entering the room.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-158", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "A resting heart rate below 60 beats per minute is classified as:", "options": ["Tachycardia", "Bradycardia", "Arrhythmia", "Fibrillation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Bradycardia is defined as a resting heart rate below 60 bpm (brady- = slow, -cardia = heart). Tachycardia is a rate above 100 bpm (tachy- = fast). Arrhythmia is any irregular heart rhythm, and fibrillation is rapid, uncoordinated cardiac contractions.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-159", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "The diastolic blood pressure reading (bottom number) represents the pressure in the arteries during:", "options": ["Ventricular contraction (systole)", "Ventricular relaxation (diastole)", "Maximum cardiac output", "Atrial contraction"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Diastolic pressure is the minimum arterial pressure during the relaxation phase of the cardiac cycle when the ventricles are filling. Systolic pressure (top number) represents the maximum pressure during ventricular contraction. A normal adult blood pressure is approximately 120/80 mmHg.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-160", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "Shock caused by a severe systemic allergic reaction is classified as:", "options": ["Hypovolemic shock", "Cardiogenic shock", "Anaphylactic shock", "Neurogenic shock"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Anaphylactic shock results from a severe systemic allergic reaction causing massive vasodilation, bronchospasm, and cardiovascular collapse. Hypovolemic shock is caused by blood/fluid loss, cardiogenic shock by cardiac pump failure, and neurogenic shock by spinal cord injury disrupting sympathetic tone.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-161", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.3", "stem": "The universal distress signal for a choking victim is:", "options": ["Waving both hands overhead", "Clutching the throat with both hands", "Pounding on the chest", "Pointing to the mouth repeatedly"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Clutching the throat with one or both hands is the recognized universal sign for foreign body airway obstruction (choking). Healthcare providers must recognize this sign immediately and initiate the Heimlich maneuver (abdominal thrusts) for conscious choking victims.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-162", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "The leakage of a vesicant (tissue-damaging) fluid such as gadolinium contrast into the surrounding soft tissue is termed:", "options": ["Infiltration", "Extravasation", "Phlebitis", "Thrombosis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Extravasation specifically refers to the leakage of a vesicant or irritating fluid (such as contrast media) into surrounding tissue, where it can cause tissue necrosis. Infiltration refers to leakage of non-irritating fluids (such as normal saline). This clinical distinction is important because extravasation requires more aggressive intervention.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-163", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Nitroglycerin for the treatment of angina (chest pain) is most commonly administered via which route?", "options": ["Intravenous injection", "Intramuscular injection", "Sublingual (under the tongue)", "Transdermal patch only"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Sublingual administration allows nitroglycerin to be absorbed rapidly into the bloodstream through the highly vascular oral mucosa, bypassing first-pass hepatic metabolism. This produces rapid coronary artery vasodilation and relief of angina symptoms within 1–3 minutes.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-164", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "In contrast administration, the difference between a \"bolus\" injection and an \"infusion\" is that a bolus:", "options": ["Is administered slowly over several hours", "Delivers the entire dose rapidly as a single push", "Can only be given intramuscularly", "Does not require IV access"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A bolus injection delivers the entire contrast dose rapidly at one time, producing a concentrated vascular bolus for optimal enhancement. An infusion (drip) delivers medication slowly over a prolonged period at a controlled rate. Most gadolinium MRI studies use bolus injection technique.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-165", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.1", "stem": "When lifting a heavy object using proper body mechanics, the load should be held:", "options": ["As far from the body as possible for leverage", "At shoulder height for maximum control", "As close to the body's center of gravity as possible", "At arm's length to maintain balance"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Keeping the load close to the body's center of gravity minimizes the torque placed on the lumbar spine. Holding objects at arm's length dramatically increases the effective load on the back muscles and intervertebral discs, increasing the risk of musculoskeletal injury.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-166", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "To prevent urinary tract infection, a urinary catheter drainage bag must always be positioned:", "options": ["Higher than the level of the bladder", "At the same level as the bladder", "Below the level of the bladder", "Position does not affect infection risk"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The drainage bag must remain below bladder level to maintain gravity-dependent urine flow. Positioning the bag above the bladder allows urine to flow retrograde (backward) into the bladder, introducing bacteria and significantly increasing the risk of catheter-associated urinary tract infection (CAUTI).", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-167", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Supplemental oxygen is classified as:", "options": ["A comfort measure that any staff member may administer freely", "A drug that requires a physician's order (except in emergencies)", "A non-regulated substance with no dosage requirements", "A device that only respiratory therapists may operate"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Oxygen is classified as a drug with specific dosage, flow rate, and delivery method orders. Like any medication, it must be prescribed by a physician, except in life-threatening emergencies where standing protocols may authorize immediate administration. Excessive oxygen can be harmful, particularly in COPD patients.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-168", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "The most commonly used vein for venipuncture in the upper extremity is the:", "options": ["Cephalic vein", "Basilic vein", "Median cubital vein", "Dorsal metacarpal vein"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The median cubital vein in the antecubital fossa is the preferred site for venipuncture because it is typically large, well-anchored, superficial, and easily palpable. The cephalic and basilic veins are acceptable alternatives. Dorsal hand veins are smaller and used primarily when antecubital access is unavailable.", "reference": ""}, {"id": "PC-169", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.2", "stem": "Which MR-compatible monitoring device is used to assess a patient's blood oxygen saturation level during an MRI procedure?", "options": ["Manual sphygmomanometer", "Peripheral pulse oximeter", "Portable ventilator", "Tympanic thermometer"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A pulse oximeter measures peripheral oxygen saturation (SpO2) by detecting the ratio of oxygenated to deoxygenated hemoglobin using light absorption. MR-compatible versions use fiber-optic cables to avoid RF interference. A sphygmomanometer measures blood pressure, not oxygenation.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-170", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "Which pre-existing condition places a patient at higher risk for an adverse reaction to gadolinium-based MRI contrast agents?", "options": ["Asthma or history of allergic reactions", "Type 2 diabetes mellitus", "Essential hypertension", "Obesity (BMI > 30)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Patients with asthma or a history of allergic reactions are at increased risk for adverse reactions to gadolinium-based contrast agents. These patients have a heightened immune reactivity that may predispose them to anaphylactoid reactions. Diabetes, hypertension, and obesity are not independent risk factors for contrast reactions.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-171", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "A patient experiencing a panic episode during MRI may develop physiological complications such as hyperventilation or vasovagal syncope. This means panic disorders in MRI:", "options": ["Are only a scheduling inconvenience with no health risk", "Can pose genuine health threats beyond simple anxiety", "Require immediate administration of anxiolytic medication", "Always necessitate termination of the examination"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Panic disorders during MRI can escalate beyond psychological discomfort to produce physiological effects including hyperventilation, tachycardia, vasovagal syncope, and exacerbation of underlying cardiac conditions. These responses represent genuine health threats that require appropriate monitoring and intervention.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.350"}, {"id": "PC-172", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "What is the most effective first-line intervention for managing patient anxiety and claustrophobia during MRI?", "options": ["Providing detailed information about the equipment and procedure before scanning", "Administering intravenous sedation before the exam", "Administering oral sedation 30 minutes before the exam", "Minimizing discussion about the scanner to avoid increasing anxiety"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Patient education and clear communication are the safest and most effective first-line interventions for MRI-related anxiety. Explaining the procedure, expected noises, duration, and communication options empowers the patient and reduces fear of the unknown. Sedation carries additional risks and should be reserved for patients who cannot tolerate the exam despite verbal support.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.350"}, {"id": "PC-173", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "According to current ACR guidelines, breastfeeding after intravenous gadolinium contrast administration:", "options": ["Should be suspended for at least 24 hours", "Does not need to be interrupted, as minimal gadolinium enters breast milk", "Should be suspended for at least 48 hours", "Must be permanently discontinued"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current ACR guidelines state that the amount of gadolinium excreted in breast milk is extremely small and poorly absorbed by the infant's GI tract. Breastfeeding does not need to be interrupted after gadolinium administration. However, a lactating mother who remains concerned may voluntarily pump and discard milk for 12-24 hours.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-174", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "What is the most commonly reported adverse reaction following intravenous administration of gadolinium-based contrast agents?", "options": ["Hives (urticaria)", "Nausea", "Headache", "Shortness of breath"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Headache is the most frequently reported side effect of gadolinium-based contrast agents, followed by nausea and injection site reactions. Severe adverse reactions such as anaphylaxis are extremely rare, occurring in fewer than 1 in 10,000 administrations.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-175", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "During recovery from general anesthesia following an MRI-guided procedure, which complication requires the technologist to maintain a quiet environment and position the patient on their side?", "options": ["Emergence delirium from hypoxia", "Post-procedural headache", "Contrast-related nausea", "Vomiting, which poses an aspiration risk"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Vomiting during recovery from general anesthesia is a serious hazard because it creates an aspiration risk. Positioning the patient on their side (recovery position) helps prevent aspiration. A quiet environment also aids recovery, as noise can aggravate emergence delirium, which may itself indicate hypoxia.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-176", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The standard clinical dose of gadolinium-based MRI contrast agents is approximately:", "options": ["0.01 mmol/kg", "0.1 mmol/kg", "1.0 mmol/kg", "10 mmol/kg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The standard clinical dose of gadolinium-based contrast agents is 0.1 mmol/kg body weight, typically administered as a single intravenous injection. The maximum volume is generally limited to approximately 20 mL for standard single-dose vials. A dose of 1.0 mmol/kg would be ten times the standard dose.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-177", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "The most frequently reported side effect following intravenous gadolinium contrast administration is:", "options": ["Anaphylaxis", "Headache", "Nausea", "Vomiting"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Headache is the most commonly reported adverse effect of gadolinium-based contrast agents, occurring in a small percentage of patients. Nausea and injection site reactions also occur but less frequently. Severe reactions such as anaphylaxis are extremely rare.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-178", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "What is the first action an MRI technologist should perform when beginning a patient's examination?", "options": ["Review the physician's orders in the chart", "Verify the patient's identity", "Position the patient on the scanner table", "Obtain a complete medical history from the patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patient identification is always the first priority before any imaging procedure. Verifying identity prevents wrong-patient errors, which can lead to unnecessary exposure and legal liability. The order review and history follow after identity is confirmed.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-179", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "In a medical malpractice lawsuit, the burden of proving that malpractice occurred rests with the:", "options": ["Physician named in the suit", "Hospital risk management department", "Patient (plaintiff)", "Technologist who performed the procedure"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In medical malpractice cases, the burden of proof lies with the patient plaintiff. The patient must demonstrate four elements: duty of care existed, that duty was breached, the breach caused injury, and measurable damages resulted.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-180", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The ethical principle of nonmaleficence is best described as the obligation to:", "options": ["Act in the patient's best interest", "Maintain patient confidentiality at all times", "Do no harm to the patient", "Treat all patients equally regardless of background"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Nonmaleficence means 'do no harm' and is one of the foundational principles of medical ethics. It requires healthcare workers to avoid actions that could injure the patient. Beneficence, by contrast, refers to acting in the patient's best interest.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-181", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "An MRI technologist leaves a patient unattended on the scanner table and the patient falls, sustaining a head injury. The technologist is most likely liable for:", "options": ["Slander", "Negligence", "Battery", "False imprisonment"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Negligence occurs when a healthcare professional fails to provide the expected standard of care, resulting in patient injury. Leaving a patient unattended on the scanner table breaches the duty of continuous patient monitoring. Battery requires intentional unauthorized contact, and slander involves spoken defamation.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-182", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A competent patient becomes claustrophobic during an MRI and requests to stop the exam. The technologist's most appropriate first response is to:", "options": ["Call security to help restrain the patient", "Immediately stop the scan and inform the supervisor", "Encourage the patient to overcome the fear and continue", "Reassure the patient and attempt to talk them through the procedure"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A competent patient has the right to refuse any medical procedure. However, the technologist's first response should be to reassure and attempt supportive communication. If the patient still refuses after reassurance, the exam must be stopped. Forcing or coercing the patient could constitute battery or false imprisonment.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-183", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal doctrine of res ipsa loquitur applies when:", "options": ["The employer is liable for the employee's actions", "The negligent act is self-evident from the circumstances alone", "Previous court decisions must be followed", "The patient has breached the confidentiality agreement"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Res ipsa loquitur ('the thing speaks for itself') applies when the negligent act is so obvious that no expert testimony is needed to prove it. An example would be imaging evidence of a surgical instrument left inside a patient. Respondeat superior deals with employer liability.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-184", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "When documenting information in a patient's medical record, the MRI technologist must:", "options": ["Sign and date the entry only", "Date the entry, record the time, and sign with name and credentials", "Date the entry, record the time, and list the department", "Date the entry and sign with name and credentials only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Proper medical record documentation requires the date, time, the technologist's signature, and professional credentials. This creates a complete legal record that identifies who made the entry and when. Incomplete documentation may not hold up in legal proceedings.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-185", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "In legal terminology, unintentional misconduct that falls below the standard of care is called:", "options": ["Libel", "Battery", "False imprisonment", "Negligence"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Negligence is defined as unintentional misconduct where a healthcare professional fails to meet the accepted standard of care, resulting in patient harm. Battery is intentional unauthorized touching, libel is written defamation, and false imprisonment is unlawful patient restraint.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-186", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Which action constitutes legal assault against a patient?", "options": ["Striking the patient", "Physically restraining the patient without justification", "Causing the patient to feel threatened or apprehensive of harm", "Performing an imaging study without the patient's consent"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Assault is the act of causing a patient to feel threatened or apprehensive of imminent harmful contact. It does not require physical touch — that would be battery. Performing a study without consent constitutes battery, not assault.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-187", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Regarding the ethical principle of double effect, which statement is INCORRECT?", "options": ["The action itself must be morally neutral or good", "The good effect need not be the sole intention of the action", "The good effect must be equal to or greater in importance than the bad effect", "The bad effect must not be the means by which the good effect is achieved"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The principle of double effect requires that the good effect must be the only intention — the agent must not intend the harmful effect. Stating that 'the good effect need not be the sole intention' is incorrect because it implies the harmful outcome can be intentionally sought.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-188", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When an ambulatory outpatient lies down on the MRI table as instructed by the technologist, the patient has provided:", "options": ["Implied consent", "Informed consent", "Emergency consent", "Vicarious liability"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Implied consent is demonstrated through the patient's cooperative actions, such as voluntarily lying on the scanner table when instructed. Informed consent requires a formal explanation of risks, benefits, and alternatives. Emergency consent applies when a patient is unable to provide consent due to a life-threatening situation.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-189", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "An MRI technologist performs a scan on the wrong body part. This action is legally classified as:", "options": ["Assault", "Breach of confidentiality", "Battery", "Negligence with implied consent"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Performing an imaging exam on the wrong body part constitutes battery because the patient only consented to the correct examination. Any medical procedure performed without proper consent — including scanning an unauthorized body region — is classified as battery regardless of intent.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-190", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Unintentional acts by a technologist that fall below the standard of care and result in patient injury are most likely prosecuted under which type of law?", "options": ["Criminal law", "Tort law", "Administrative law", "Constitutional law"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Tort law governs civil wrongs including medical negligence and malpractice. When a technologist unintentionally causes patient injury by failing to meet the standard of care, the case falls under tort law. Criminal law applies to intentional harmful acts, and administrative law governs regulatory matters.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-191", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal doctrine of respondeat superior holds that:", "options": ["The evidence speaks for itself", "A reasonable professional should make the decision", "Technologists do not need their own liability insurance", "The employer (master) is responsible for the employee's actions"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Respondeat superior ('let the master answer') holds that employers are vicariously liable for negligent acts committed by employees within the scope of their employment. However, this does not absolve the individual technologist of personal responsibility.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-192", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which statement regarding informed consent is NOT accurate?", "options": ["Consent must be given voluntarily without duress", "The patient must understand every aspect of the procedure in complete detail", "The patient must be of legal age or have an authorized representative", "Risks and benefits must be explained in terms the patient can understand"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Informed consent does not require the patient to understand every aspect in complete detail — rather, the explanation must be sufficient for a reasonable person to make an informed decision. The key elements are: voluntary consent, legal competence, adequate disclosure of risks and benefits, and patient comprehension at an appropriate level.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-193", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The deliberate destruction or alteration of medical records without proper authorization is legally known as:", "options": ["Medical negligence", "Failure to follow the standard of care", "Spoliation", "Vicarious liability"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Spoliation refers to the intentional destruction, alteration, or concealment of evidence, including medical records. Courts may impose severe sanctions for spoliation, including adverse inference instructions that allow juries to assume the destroyed records contained unfavorable information.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-194", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal doctrine of stare decisis requires courts to:", "options": ["Apply ethical consequentialism to medical cases", "Determine fault based on the self-evident nature of the negligence", "Assign liability to the supervising physician", "Follow precedents established by previous court decisions"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Stare decisis ('to stand by things decided') is the principle that courts should follow established precedent when ruling on similar cases. This provides consistency and predictability in legal outcomes. Res ipsa loquitur, not stare decisis, deals with self-evident negligence.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-195", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "A technologist who physically touches a patient without permission, outside of an emergency situation, may be found guilty of:", "options": ["Negligence", "Breach of confidentiality", "Battery", "Assault"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Battery is the unauthorized touching of another person without consent. In healthcare, this includes performing any procedure without the patient's knowledge or agreement. Emergency consent is the only exception, where life-threatening situations allow treatment without explicit permission.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-196", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Sharing a patient's confidential medical information with someone who has no legitimate need to know constitutes:", "options": ["Vicarious liability", "Invasion of privacy", "Libel", "Stare decisis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Discussing patient information with unauthorized individuals is an invasion of privacy and violates HIPAA regulations. This differs from libel (written defamation) and slander (spoken defamation). Vicarious liability relates to employer responsibility for employee actions.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-197", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "If a supervising radiologist directs a technologist to scan a patient with a known cardiac pacemaker and the patient suffers cardiac arrest, the technologist may be partially protected under:", "options": ["Respondeat superior — the employer bears responsibility for supervised actions", "Res ipsa loquitur — the negligence is self-evident", "Stare decisis — previous court rulings apply", "The standard of care doctrine — the technologist followed instructions"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Respondeat superior ('let the master answer') may provide partial protection because the technologist was acting under the direction of a supervising physician. However, technologists have an independent professional duty to refuse unsafe practices, and this doctrine does not guarantee complete protection.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-198", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT considered a fundamental patient right?", "options": ["Right to privacy during the examination", "Right to receive a diagnosis from the MRI technologist", "Right to refuse the MRI examination", "Right to be informed of potential risks of the procedure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Diagnosis is exclusively within the scope of practice of physicians, not technologists. Providing a diagnosis as a technologist exceeds the scope of practice and could expose the technologist to legal liability. Patients do have rights to privacy, refusal of treatment, and disclosure of risks.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-199", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The legal term for the written, malicious spreading of false information about a person is:", "options": ["Breach of confidentiality", "Libel", "Slander", "Qualified privilege"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Libel refers to written or published defamatory statements. Slander, by contrast, refers to spoken defamation. Both are forms of defamation, but the distinction between written (libel) and oral (slander) communication is legally significant.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-200", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "In a medical negligence case, the burden of proof lies with the:", "options": ["Attending physician", "Patient (plaintiff)", "Imaging technologist", "Hospital risk management team"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The patient plaintiff bears the burden of proving medical negligence. They must demonstrate that a duty of care existed, the duty was breached, the breach caused the injury, and measurable damages resulted. The defendant does not need to prove innocence.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-201", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "All of the following may constitute battery EXCEPT:", "options": ["Touching a patient without obtaining consent", "Sharing patient information with an unauthorized person", "Performing an MRI on the wrong anatomical region", "Administering contrast without the patient's knowledge"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Sharing patient information is an invasion of privacy or breach of confidentiality, not battery. Battery specifically involves unauthorized physical contact or medical procedures performed without consent. Scanning the wrong body part and giving contrast without consent are both forms of battery.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-202", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Threatening a patient with physical harm or creating a reasonable apprehension of unwanted contact is legally classified as:", "options": ["Battery", "Unauthorized touching", "Assault", "Negligent misconduct"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Assault is the act of creating a reasonable apprehension or fear of harmful or unwanted contact. Unlike battery, assault does not require actual physical touching — the threat alone constitutes the offense. Both are intentional torts in healthcare law.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-203", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The 'reasonable prudent person' standard in malpractice law is interpreted as:", "options": ["How a reasonable jury member would have acted", "How a similarly trained professional would have acted under the same circumstances", "How the most experienced specialist in the field would have acted", "How the hospital administrator would expect the employee to act"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The reasonable prudent person (or reasonable professional) standard asks what a similarly trained healthcare professional would have done in the same situation. It does not hold the technologist to the standard of a specialist but rather to the standard of a competent peer.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-204", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "According to the ARRT Standards of Ethics, the principal objective that radiologic technologists must advance through their professional practice is:", "options": ["Maximizing department revenue", "Providing quality patient care", "Increasing imaging throughput efficiency", "Maintaining equipment in optimal condition"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ARRT Standards of Ethics establish that the primary professional obligation of radiologic technologists is to provide quality patient care. All other professional activities — efficiency, equipment maintenance, continuing education — support this central objective.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-205", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Under the ARRT Code of Ethics, radiologic technologists are specifically required to:", "options": ["Diagnose conditions found during imaging studies", "Respond to patient needs with empathy and deliver care with respect and dignity", "Prescribe imaging protocols without physician input", "Determine which patients should receive contrast agents"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ARRT Code of Ethics requires technologists to respond to patient needs with empathy while delivering care with respect and dignity. Diagnosis and prescribing are outside the technologist's scope of practice. Protocol selection requires collaboration with the supervising physician.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-206", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which scenario would NOT constitute a violation of the ARRT Standards of Ethics?", "options": ["Contacting a referring physician about a potentially dangerous order", "Sharing patient images on personal social media", "Falsifying continuing education documentation", "Performing procedures outside the technologist's scope of practice"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Contacting a referring physician about a potentially unsafe order is an ethical obligation, not a violation. The ARRT Code of Ethics requires technologists to act as patient advocates. Sharing images, falsifying records, and practicing outside one's scope are all ethical violations.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-207", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Which combination of factors may predispose a patient to a syncopal (fainting) episode?", "options": ["Hypertension and obesity", "Bradycardia and hyperglycemia", "Anxiety and hunger", "Fever and tachycardia"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Anxiety and hunger (hypoglycemia) are common triggers for vasovagal syncope. Anxiety activates the sympathetic nervous system, and hunger reduces blood glucose, both contributing to a drop in blood pressure and loss of consciousness. Hypertension alone does not typically cause syncope.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-208", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "What is the most appropriate first-line approach for managing a claustrophobic patient scheduled for MRI?", "options": ["Administer oral sedation before the exam", "Cancel the examination and suggest an alternative modality", "Force the patient to comply with the procedure", "Provide thorough education about the procedure and use supportive communication techniques"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Patient education and supportive communication are the safest and most effective first-line interventions for claustrophobia in MRI. Sedation carries risks and should be reserved for patients who cannot tolerate the exam despite verbal support. Forcing compliance would violate patient rights.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-209", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "Which patient populations require continuous pulse oximetry monitoring during MRI procedures?", "options": ["Only pediatric patients under age 5", "Sedated, unresponsive, or uncommunicative patients and those with impaired hearing", "Only patients receiving intravenous contrast", "All patients regardless of clinical status"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patients who cannot communicate distress — including sedated, unresponsive, psychiatric, pediatric, and hearing-impaired patients — require continuous pulse oximetry monitoring during MRI. Alert, communicative adult patients may be monitored visually and verbally.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-210", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "A patient sedated with diazepam (Valium) for an MRI procedure should be monitored with:", "options": ["Pulse oximetry", "ECG gating only", "Peripheral pulse gating only", "Verbal communication alone"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Patients sedated with benzodiazepines such as diazepam require pulse oximetry monitoring to detect respiratory depression, the most serious potential complication of sedation. ECG gating monitors cardiac rhythm for imaging purposes but is insufficient for monitoring sedation depth.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-211", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C.3", "stem": "What is the minimum recommended monitoring for all patients undergoing MRI, regardless of sedation status?", "options": ["Visual and/or verbal monitoring throughout the procedure", "Continuous ECG monitoring", "Continuous respiratory rate monitoring", "Automated blood pressure measurement every 5 minutes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "At minimum, all MRI patients should be monitored visually and/or verbally throughout the procedure. This includes maintaining communication via the intercom system and visual observation through the window. Additional physiologic monitoring is required for sedated or high-risk patients.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-212", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "Prior to the ACR 2010 Contrast Media Update, gadolinium-based contrast agents were considered to have:", "options": ["No known contraindications", "Contraindications limited to pregnancy and breastfeeding only", "Contraindications including renal insufficiency and low GFR", "Contraindications including sickle cell disease and hypertension"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Before the ACR published the 2010 Contrast Media Update identifying nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF) risk, gadolinium agents were widely considered to have no significant contraindications. The 2010 update established renal insufficiency and low GFR as contraindications due to NSF risk.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-213", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "Following the ACR Contrast Media Update, which patient condition is now recognized as a contraindication for gadolinium-based contrast agents?", "options": ["Sickle cell disease", "Controlled hypertension", "Severe renal insufficiency with low GFR", "History of mild headache after previous contrast"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "After identifying the association between gadolinium and nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF), the ACR established severe renal insufficiency and low estimated GFR as contraindications. Patients with GFR below 30 are at highest risk. Sickle cell disease and hypertension are not specific contraindications.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-214", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "Current precautions for gadolinium-based contrast agent administration include screening patients for:", "options": ["Sickle cell disease and hypertension only", "Pregnancy only", "Low GFR and renal insufficiency", "All of the above including sickle cell, pregnancy, low GFR, and renal disease"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The primary precaution for gadolinium administration is screening for renal impairment by assessing GFR. Patients with low GFR are at risk for nephrogenic systemic fibrosis. While pregnancy and other conditions are considered, renal function screening is the critical precaution per current ACR guidelines.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-215", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "FDA-approved gadolinium-based MRI contrast agents are currently indicated for:", "options": ["Oral administration only", "Intravenous injection for adult patients only", "Intravenous injection for both adult and pediatric patients including neonates", "Intrathecal injection for myelography"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "FDA-approved gadolinium-based contrast agents are indicated for intravenous injection in patients of all ages, including pediatric patients and neonates. Specific agents have pediatric indications at adjusted doses. Intrathecal administration is an off-label use that carries significant neurotoxicity risk.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-216", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "A diabetic patient who has excessive insulin relative to blood glucose is experiencing:", "options": ["Diabetic ketoacidosis", "Hyperglycemia", "Hypoglycemia (insulin shock)", "Metabolic alkalosis"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Excessive insulin causes hypoglycemia (insulin shock) by driving glucose out of the bloodstream and into cells faster than it can be replenished. Symptoms include diaphoresis, tremors, confusion, and loss of consciousness. Hyperglycemia results from insufficient insulin, the opposite condition.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-217", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.2", "stem": "What is the correct sequence for administering basic life support (BLS)?", "options": ["Check responsiveness, activate emergency response, begin chest compressions, open airway, deliver breaths", "Open airway first, then check pulse, then begin compressions", "Deliver rescue breaths first, then check pulse, then begin compressions", "Check pulse, begin compressions, then call for help"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Current BLS guidelines follow the C-A-B sequence: check responsiveness, call for help/activate emergency response, begin Chest compressions, open the Airway, and deliver Breaths. The emphasis on early compressions reflects evidence that maintaining circulation is the most critical intervention.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-218", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.D.4", "stem": "A patient lying on the MRI table reports feeling faint. What should the technologist do FIRST?", "options": ["Immediately begin CPR", "Call the supervising physician", "Remove the patient from the scanner and call a code", "Elevate the patient's legs above heart level and monitor vital signs"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "For a patient experiencing pre-syncopal symptoms, the immediate intervention is to elevate the legs to improve venous return to the brain. The patient should be removed from the bore if inside, positioned with legs elevated, and monitored. CPR is only indicated if the patient becomes pulseless.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-219", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.5", "stem": "The appropriate initial treatment for contrast media extravasation at an IV injection site is:", "options": ["Apply a tourniquet proximal to the site", "Immediately restart the IV in the same vein", "Apply warm or cold compresses and elevate the affected extremity", "Administer epinephrine subcutaneously"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Contrast extravasation is treated conservatively with elevation of the affected limb and application of warm or cold compresses to promote absorption and reduce swelling. Severe cases involving large volumes or skin compromise require surgical consultation. A new IV should be started at a different site if the exam must continue.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-220", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Which of the following is most likely to cause loss of patency (flow) in an intravenous line?", "options": ["Excessive IV fluid flow rate", "A blood clot or kink in the tubing", "Using a large-gauge catheter", "Placing the IV bag above the patient"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A blood clot forming at the catheter tip or a kink in the IV tubing are the most common causes of lost IV patency. Clots form when blood backs up into the catheter due to insufficient flow or when the catheter position shifts. Kinked tubing mechanically obstructs flow.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-221", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Why are deep veins generally avoided for routine venipuncture?", "options": ["Deep veins have thicker walls that are harder to puncture", "Deep veins carry deoxygenated blood only", "Deep veins are located near arteries and nerves, increasing the risk of complications", "Deep veins do not provide adequate blood flow for IV infusion"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Deep veins run alongside major arteries and nerves. Accessing them risks arterial puncture, nerve damage, and hematoma formation. Superficial veins of the antecubital fossa and forearm are preferred for routine venipuncture because they are easily palpable and carry lower complication risk.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-222", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "A multi-dose vial differs from a single-dose vial in that it:", "options": ["Contains a preservative allowing withdrawal of multiple doses", "Is designed to be used by multiple patients simultaneously", "Must be refrigerated after first use and discarded within 24 hours", "Contains a higher concentration of the medication"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Multi-dose vials contain preservatives (such as benzyl alcohol) that inhibit bacterial growth after the vial is punctured, allowing multiple doses to be withdrawn over time. Single-dose vials lack preservatives and must be used immediately. Multi-dose vials should never be shared between patients per infection control guidelines.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-223", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.3", "stem": "The viscosity of gadolinium-based contrast media can be reduced by:", "options": ["Warming the contrast to body temperature before injection", "Refrigerating the contrast before injection", "Adding saline to dilute the contrast in the syringe", "Using a smaller gauge needle for injection"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Warming contrast media to body temperature (37°C) reduces its viscosity, making it easier to inject through small-gauge catheters and reducing injection pressure. Refrigeration increases viscosity. Dilution alters the concentration and is not a standard practice.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-224", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "The gauge number of an IV needle or catheter refers to its:", "options": ["Length in centimeters", "Flow rate capacity in mL/min", "Internal diameter — larger numbers indicate smaller lumens", "External coating thickness"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "IV gauge refers to the internal diameter of the needle or catheter, with an inverse relationship: higher gauge numbers indicate smaller lumens. For example, an 18-gauge catheter has a larger lumen than a 22-gauge catheter. Larger lumens (lower gauge) allow faster flow rates for contrast injection.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-225", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Which blood test is used in the calculation of estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) to assess renal function before gadolinium contrast administration?", "options": ["Blood urea nitrogen (BUN)", "Prothrombin time (PT)", "Complete blood count (CBC)", "Serum creatinine"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Serum creatinine is the primary laboratory value used to calculate eGFR, which estimates kidney filtration capacity. The eGFR calculation also incorporates age, sex, and race. BUN is another renal marker but is not directly used in the eGFR formula.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-226", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "Which laboratory test would NOT be used to evaluate a patient's risk of hemorrhage during an invasive MRI-guided procedure?", "options": ["Prothrombin time (PT)", "Serum creatinine", "Partial thromboplastin time (PTT)", "International normalized ratio (INR)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Serum creatinine assesses kidney function, not coagulation status. Prothrombin time (PT), partial thromboplastin time (PTT), and INR are all coagulation tests used to evaluate bleeding risk before invasive procedures.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-227", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Which blood vessel has the thickest tunica media (muscular middle layer)?", "options": ["Arteries", "Veins", "Capillaries", "Venules"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Arteries have the thickest tunica media because they must withstand and regulate high-pressure blood flow from the heart. The thick smooth muscle layer allows arteries to constrict and dilate to regulate blood pressure. Veins have thinner walls with valves, and capillaries have only a single endothelial layer.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-228", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "A normal serum creatinine range for adults is approximately:", "options": ["0.01 to 0.1 mg/dL", "0.6 to 1.2 mg/dL", "5.0 to 10.0 mg/dL", "15 to 30 mg/dL"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Normal serum creatinine ranges from approximately 0.6 to 1.2 mg/dL in adults, though values may vary slightly by laboratory and patient demographics. Elevated creatinine indicates impaired renal function and requires eGFR calculation before administering gadolinium-based contrast agents.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-229", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "An estimated GFR (eGFR) below 15 mL/min/1.73m² is indicative of:", "options": ["Normal renal function", "Mild renal impairment", "Moderate renal impairment", "Kidney failure (Stage 5 chronic kidney disease)"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "An eGFR below 15 indicates Stage 5 chronic kidney disease (kidney failure), the most severe classification. These patients are at the highest risk for nephrogenic systemic fibrosis and gadolinium-based contrast agents are generally contraindicated without compelling clinical necessity.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-230", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.4", "stem": "According to ACR guidelines, gadolinium-based contrast agents should be used with extreme caution in patients with an eGFR below:", "options": ["90 mL/min", "60 mL/min", "30 mL/min", "15 mL/min"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ACR recommends caution with gadolinium in patients with eGFR below 30 mL/min due to the risk of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF). Group II agents (macrocyclic chelates) are preferred in these patients when contrast is clinically necessary. All patients should be evaluated on a case-by-case basis.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-231", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "Which type of circulation is responsible for the reoxygenation of blood?", "options": ["Pulmonary circulation", "Systemic circulation", "Portal circulation", "Coronary circulation"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Pulmonary circulation carries deoxygenated blood from the right ventricle to the lungs, where gas exchange occurs and blood is reoxygenated. The oxygenated blood then returns to the left atrium via the pulmonary veins. Systemic circulation distributes oxygenated blood to body tissues.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-232", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.2", "stem": "The outermost layer of a blood vessel, composed of fibrous connective tissue, is the:", "options": ["Tunica adventitia (externa)", "Tunica media", "Tunica intima", "Endothelium"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The tunica adventitia (also called tunica externa) is the outermost layer of blood vessels, composed of fibrous connective tissue that provides structural support and anchors the vessel to surrounding tissues. The tunica media is the muscular middle layer, and the tunica intima is the smooth inner lining.", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-233", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.G.1", "stem": "A normal blood urea nitrogen (BUN) range for adults is approximately:", "options": ["0.6 to 1.2 mg/dL", "3 to 5 mg/dL", "7 to 20 mg/dL", "50 to 100 mg/dL"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Normal BUN ranges from approximately 7 to 20 mg/dL. BUN reflects the amount of nitrogen in the blood from the waste product urea, which is cleared by the kidneys. Elevated BUN may indicate renal impairment, dehydration, or high-protein diet. The 0.6 to 1.2 range corresponds to serum creatinine.", "reference": "MIP Ch.10 p.367"}, {"id": "PC-234", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which type of blood cell is primarily responsible for transporting oxygen bound to hemoglobin?", "options": ["Leukocyte", "Thrombocyte", "Erythrocyte", "Basophil"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Erythrocytes (red blood cells) contain hemoglobin, the iron-rich protein that binds oxygen in the lungs and delivers it to tissues throughout the body. Thrombocytes (platelets) function in clot formation, not gas exchange.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-235", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which laboratory value is most commonly used as an indicator of patient dehydration?", "options": ["Blood urea nitrogen (BUN)", "Partial thromboplastin time (PTT)", "Serum potassium", "Hematocrit"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "An elevated hematocrit indicates hemoconcentration, which occurs when plasma volume decreases relative to red blood cell mass — a hallmark of dehydration. BUN can also rise with dehydration but is less specific, as it is affected by renal function and protein intake.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-236", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which device is most appropriate for administering long-term parenteral nutrition or chemotherapy?", "options": ["Peripherally inserted central catheter (PICC line)", "Chest tube", "Nasogastric tube", "Foley catheter"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A PICC line or other central venous catheter provides reliable long-term venous access for administering parenteral nutrition, chemotherapy, and other infusions that would irritate peripheral veins. A chest tube drains air or fluid from the pleural space and is unrelated to medication administration.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-237", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "For which clinical application is intravenous gadolinium-based contrast most commonly indicated in MRI?", "options": ["Musculoskeletal joint evaluation without suspected pathology", "Routine screening brain MRI in asymptomatic patients", "Evaluation of suspected neoplasm, infection, or inflammatory disease", "All non-contrast MRI sequences as a standard protocol additive"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents are indicated when enhanced tissue characterization is needed, most commonly for evaluating suspected tumors, infections, or inflammatory conditions across brain, spine, and body imaging. Contrast is not routinely added to all MRI protocols — its use is guided by clinical indication.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "PC-238", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Approximately what percentage of patients experience adverse reactions to gadolinium-based contrast agents during MRI?", "options": ["Less than 1–2%", "5–10%", "15–20%", "Greater than 25%"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The overall incidence of adverse reactions to gadolinium-based contrast agents is low, generally reported at less than 2% of all administrations. Most reactions are mild and self-limiting. Severe anaphylactoid reactions are extremely rare, occurring in fewer than 0.01% of cases.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "PC-239", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which patient history finding places an individual at increased risk for an adverse reaction to gadolinium-based contrast agents?", "options": ["History of asthma or significant allergies", "Prior surgical procedure under general anesthesia", "Family history of cardiovascular disease", "Current use of oral anticoagulant medications"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Patients with a history of asthma, significant allergies, or prior contrast reactions are at increased risk for adverse reactions to gadolinium-based agents. These patients may require premedication with corticosteroids and antihistamines per department protocol. Prior surgery under anesthesia alone does not constitute a specific risk factor for contrast reactions.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "PC-240", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which factor has been reported to increase the likelihood of an adverse reaction following gadolinium administration?", "options": ["Patient age over 65 years", "Prior adverse reaction to a gadolinium-based contrast agent", "Body mass index greater than 30", "History of claustrophobia"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A prior adverse reaction to a gadolinium-based agent is one of the strongest predictors of a subsequent reaction and should always be documented during MRI screening. While advanced age and obesity may affect contrast dosing and renal clearance, they are not primary risk factors for acute allergic-like reactions.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "PC-241", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Mild contrast reactions such as flushing, urticaria, and nausea are classified as which type of adverse event?", "options": ["Anaphylactic", "Vasovagal", "Physiologic (non-allergic-like)", "Cardiovascular"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ACR classifies contrast reactions by severity. Mild reactions include limited urticaria (hives), flushing, nausea, and transient warmth — these are generally self-limiting and often resolve without treatment. Anaphylactic reactions are severe, life-threatening events involving bronchospasm, laryngeal edema, or cardiovascular collapse.", "reference": "ACR Contrast Manual"}, {"id": "PC-242", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "An MRI technologist discovers that an adult patient in the waiting area is unresponsive. What should be the technologist's first action?", "options": ["Begin chest compressions immediately", "Activate the emergency response system (call for help)", "Administer rescue breaths", "Attach an automated external defibrillator (AED)"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Per AHA Basic Life Support guidelines, the first action when finding an unresponsive adult is to activate the emergency response system and call for help. Early activation ensures that advanced care is en route while the rescuer begins CPR. Beginning compressions without first calling for help delays the arrival of advanced life support.", "reference": "AHA BLS / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-243", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When performing single-rescuer CPR on an adult, what is the current recommended ratio of chest compressions to ventilations?", "options": ["15 compressions to 2 ventilations", "30 compressions to 2 ventilations", "15 compressions to 1 ventilation", "5 compressions to 1 ventilation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The AHA recommends a 30:2 compression-to-ventilation ratio for single-rescuer adult CPR. This ratio maximizes coronary and cerebral perfusion by minimizing interruptions in chest compressions. The older 15:2 ratio is no longer used for adult single-rescuer CPR but remains the standard for two-rescuer infant and child CPR.", "reference": "AHA BLS / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-244", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which seizure type is characterized by generalized tonic-clonic activity and loss of consciousness, representing the most severe convulsive presentation?", "options": ["Absence (petit mal)", "Simple partial", "Generalized tonic-clonic (grand mal)", "Myoclonic"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Generalized tonic-clonic (formerly grand mal) seizures are the most severe convulsive seizure type, involving bilateral tonic stiffening followed by rhythmic clonic jerking with complete loss of consciousness. Absence seizures (petit mal) are brief episodes of staring and altered awareness without convulsive motor activity.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-245", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "If cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) is not initiated promptly after cardiac arrest, irreversible brain damage typically begins within approximately:", "options": ["1–3 minutes", "4–6 minutes", "7–10 minutes", "15–20 minutes"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Brain cells are highly sensitive to oxygen deprivation, and irreversible neuronal damage typically begins within 4–6 minutes of cardiac arrest without CPR. This narrow window underscores the critical importance of immediate bystander CPR to maintain cerebral perfusion. The 1–3 minute range is generally too early for permanent damage, while waiting 7+ minutes virtually guarantees significant neurological injury.", "reference": "AHA BLS / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-246", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which type of shock results from the heart's inability to pump sufficient blood to meet the body's metabolic demands?", "options": ["Hypovolemic shock", "Septic shock", "Neurogenic shock", "Cardiogenic shock"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Cardiogenic shock occurs when the heart fails to generate adequate cardiac output, often due to myocardial infarction, severe heart failure, or cardiac tamponade. Hypovolemic shock results from significant blood or fluid loss rather than pump failure.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-247", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which body mechanics principle is most important for MRI technologists to follow when lifting or transferring patients?", "options": ["Keep the back straight and bend at the knees", "Extend the arms fully and lift with the shoulders", "Bend at the waist to reach the patient", "Keep the feet close together for stability"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Proper lifting technique requires keeping the back straight, bending at the knees, and using the large muscles of the legs to generate lifting force. Bending at the waist or lifting with extended arms places excessive strain on the lumbar spine, the most commonly injured body region among healthcare workers during patient transfers.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-248", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Log-rolling technique is specifically indicated when transferring a patient with a suspected injury to the:", "options": ["Upper extremity", "Vertebral column", "Abdominal viscera", "Cranium"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Log-rolling maintains spinal alignment by moving the patient's body as a single unit without twisting or flexing the spine. This technique is essential for patients with suspected vertebral column injuries to prevent secondary spinal cord damage during transfer.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-249", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which body region is most commonly injured among imaging technologists during patient care activities?", "options": ["Cervical spine", "Upper extremities", "Lumbosacral spine", "Lower extremities"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The lumbosacral spine is the most frequently injured body region among imaging technologists, primarily due to improper lifting technique during patient transfers. This highlights the importance of proper body mechanics, use of assistive devices, and team lifting when moving patients.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-250", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "During patient transfer to the MRI scanner, where should a urinary catheter drainage bag be positioned?", "options": ["On the MRI table next to the patient", "Clamped to the IV pole above the patient", "Below the level of the urinary bladder", "At the foot end of the scanner table"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Urinary catheter bags must always be positioned below the level of the bladder to maintain gravity-dependent drainage and prevent urine reflux, which can lead to urinary tract infection. Elevating the bag above bladder level causes retrograde flow of potentially contaminated urine back into the bladder.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-251", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Before performing venipuncture for contrast injection, the technologist should:", "options": ["Cool the contrast agent to reduce viscosity", "Flush the syringe, tubing, and needle with contrast to eliminate air", "Skip flushing to avoid wasting contrast material", "Inject a test bolus of saline only after contrast is loaded into the syringe"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Prior to injection, all air must be expelled from the syringe, connecting tubing, and needle by flushing with contrast agent or saline. Air bubbles introduced intravenously can cause air embolism, a potentially life-threatening complication. Contrast agents should be warmed to body temperature (not cooled), as warming reduces viscosity and improves injection comfort.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-252", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which combination of factors is most likely to cause a syncopal (fainting) episode in a patient?", "options": ["Hypertension and bradycardia", "Anxiety and prolonged fasting (hunger)", "Fever and hyperglycemia", "Obesity and tachycardia"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Syncope is most commonly triggered by vasovagal responses to anxiety, pain, or emotional stress, combined with physiologic stressors such as hunger, dehydration, or prolonged standing. Hypertension is not a direct cause of vasovagal syncope.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-253", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "A diabetic patient who has administered too much insulin relative to their caloric intake is most likely experiencing:", "options": ["Hyperglycemia", "Hypoglycemia", "Diabetic ketoacidosis", "Hyperkalemia"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Excess insulin relative to glucose intake causes hypoglycemia (abnormally low blood sugar), which can present with diaphoresis, confusion, tremor, and in severe cases, loss of consciousness. Hyperglycemia (elevated blood sugar) results from insufficient insulin, the opposite scenario. Fasting MRI patients with diabetes are at particular risk.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-254", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "If a patient experiences cardiac arrest during an MRI examination, the technologist's immediate priority should be to:", "options": ["Activate the emergency quench system", "Call a code and direct the emergency team to the scan room", "Begin CPR while removing the patient from the MRI scan room", "Begin CPR in the scan room while waiting for the emergency team"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In a cardiac arrest during MRI, the patient must be rapidly removed from the scan room (Zone IV) before emergency resuscitation equipment can be safely used. Ferromagnetic emergency equipment must never enter the MR environment. CPR should be initiated during transport out of the scan room. The magnet should not be quenched unless a ferromagnetic object is physically trapping the patient.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 367 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "PC-255", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "During any medical emergency that occurs while a patient is inside the MRI scanner, what is the technologist's first priority?", "options": ["Quench the magnet to eliminate the magnetic field", "Call a code and instruct the team to enter the scan room", "Continue the examination and contact the radiologist", "Remove the patient from the MRI scan room to a safe location"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The first priority in any MRI emergency is to remove the patient from the scan room (Zone IV) to an area where standard emergency equipment can be safely deployed. Emergency response teams unfamiliar with MRI safety could introduce ferromagnetic objects into the scan room, creating a projectile hazard. Magnet quench is reserved for life-threatening situations where the magnetic field itself is the immediate danger.", "reference": "MIP Ch. 10 p. 367 / ACR MR Safety"}, {"id": "PC-256", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "A patient described as having tachycardia will exhibit which vital sign finding?", "options": ["Respiratory rate below 12 breaths per minute", "Heart rate exceeding 100 beats per minute", "Systolic blood pressure above 180 mmHg", "Oxygen saturation below 90%"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Tachycardia is defined as a heart rate exceeding 100 beats per minute at rest in an adult. It may result from anxiety, pain, fever, hemorrhage, or cardiac pathology. Bradycardia (heart rate below 60 bpm) is the opposite finding. A slow respiratory rate is termed bradypnea.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-257", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "What is the expected normal resting heart rate range for an infant?", "options": ["60–80 beats per minute", "80–100 beats per minute", "100–120 beats per minute", "115–130 beats per minute"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Normal infant heart rates range from approximately 110–160 beats per minute depending on age and activity level, with 115–130 bpm representing a typical resting value. Pediatric heart rates are significantly faster than adult rates (60–100 bpm) due to smaller cardiac stroke volume and higher metabolic demands.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-258", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which blood pressure reading represents a normal value for a healthy adult at rest?", "options": ["90/60 mmHg", "120/80 mmHg", "140/100 mmHg", "160/90 mmHg"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A blood pressure of 120/80 mmHg is the benchmark normal value for a resting adult. The first number (systolic) reflects ventricular contraction pressure, and the second (diastolic) represents resting arterial pressure between beats. Readings above 130/80 mmHg are now classified as hypertension per current guidelines.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-259", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which blood pressure finding is most indicative of a patient in shock?", "options": ["Systolic pressure of 130 mmHg", "Diastolic pressure of 90 mmHg", "Systolic pressure of 60 mmHg", "Diastolic pressure of 80 mmHg"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Severe hypotension — particularly a systolic pressure below 90 mmHg — is a hallmark of circulatory shock, indicating inadequate tissue perfusion. A systolic pressure of 60 mmHg represents critical hypotension requiring immediate intervention. A diastolic of 90 mmHg is mildly elevated and not associated with shock.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-260", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "For a patient receiving supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula or face mask, which route should be avoided when measuring body temperature?", "options": ["Tympanic", "Axillary", "Oral", "Temporal artery"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Oral temperature measurement is unreliable in patients receiving supplemental oxygen because the continuous flow of dry gas through the nasal passages and mouth alters the oral cavity temperature. Tympanic, axillary, and temporal artery routes are not affected by supplemental oxygen delivery and remain accurate alternatives.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-261", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "A patient presenting with epistaxis is experiencing which condition?", "options": ["Nosebleed", "Seizure activity", "Cardiac arrhythmia", "Respiratory distress"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Epistaxis is the medical term for nosebleed, which results from rupture of the nasal mucosal blood vessels. It can be caused by trauma, dry air, hypertension, anticoagulant therapy, or nasal pathology. MRI technologists should be aware of basic medical terminology to properly document and communicate patient conditions.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-262", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Shock that results from a significant loss of blood volume or body fluid is classified as:", "options": ["Cardiogenic", "Neurogenic", "Hypovolemic", "Septic"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Hypovolemic shock occurs when circulating blood volume drops significantly due to hemorrhage, severe dehydration, or third-spacing of fluids, resulting in inadequate tissue perfusion. Cardiogenic shock results from pump failure rather than volume loss. Recognizing the mechanism of shock guides appropriate treatment.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-263", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "For an unconscious patient who has sustained a head injury, the primary concern during initial management is:", "options": ["Preventing additional hemorrhage", "Maintaining a patent airway", "Monitoring heart rate continuously", "Obtaining a detailed medical history"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Maintaining a patent airway is the first priority (the 'A' in ABC assessment) for any unconscious patient, as airway compromise is the most immediate life threat. An unconscious head-injury patient may lose protective airway reflexes, making aspiration and obstruction a critical risk. Hemorrhage control is important but secondary to ensuring adequate ventilation.", "reference": "AHA BLS / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-264", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a typical characteristic of geriatric patients that MRI technologists should anticipate?", "options": ["Altered anatomic landmarks due to aging", "Fragile skin prone to tearing", "Diminished cognitive intelligence", "Impaired balance and increased fall risk"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Normal aging does not cause a decline in intelligence. Geriatric patients may process information more slowly but retain their cognitive abilities. Changes in skin fragility, altered anatomic landmarks, and impaired balance are well-documented age-related changes that technologists should accommodate during patient care.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-265", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When administering supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula during a non-critical patient event, the typical initial flow rate is:", "options": ["1–2 L/min", "6–8 L/min", "10–12 L/min", "15 L/min"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Low-flow oxygen via nasal cannula is typically initiated at 1–2 L/min for mild respiratory support, delivering approximately 24–28% FiO2. Higher flow rates (10–15 L/min via non-rebreather mask) are reserved for severe hypoxia or acute emergencies. Technologists should follow department protocols and physician orders for oxygen administration.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-266", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which artery is most commonly used to assess a resting pulse rate in an adult patient?", "options": ["Brachial", "Carotid", "Femoral", "Radial"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The radial artery at the wrist is the standard site for routine pulse assessment in conscious adults due to its accessibility and patient comfort. The carotid artery is used during CPR to check for circulation in an unresponsive patient but is not the preferred site for routine vital signs.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-267", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "During CPR on an adult, which pulse point is checked to assess for the presence of circulation?", "options": ["Radial", "Carotid", "Femoral", "Brachial"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The carotid artery is the preferred pulse check during adult CPR because it is a large central artery that remains palpable even when peripheral pulses (radial, pedal) are absent due to low cardiac output. The brachial artery is used for pulse checks in infant CPR.", "reference": "AHA BLS / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-268", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "Which symptom is commonly associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)?", "options": ["Bradycardia", "Orthopnea", "Dysphagia", "Epistaxis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Orthopnea (difficulty breathing while lying flat) is a hallmark symptom of COPD and other chronic respiratory or cardiac conditions. COPD patients may require an elevated head position during MRI to maintain adequate ventilation. Dysphagia refers to difficulty swallowing, which is unrelated to COPD.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-269", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "To reduce the risk of orthostatic hypotension when helping a patient off the MRI table, the technologist should:", "options": ["Sit the patient up slowly and allow time in the seated position before standing", "Offer the patient a sugary drink to counteract low blood sugar", "Elevate the patient's legs 60 degrees above the heart", "Place the patient in the Trendelenburg position and call for assistance"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Orthostatic (postural) hypotension occurs when blood pools in the lower extremities upon standing, causing a sudden drop in blood pressure. Gradually transitioning from supine to seated to standing allows the cardiovascular system to compensate. Trendelenburg position is used to treat hypotension/shock, not to prevent orthostatic episodes during routine transfers.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-270", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "A central venous catheter is most commonly inserted into which vessel?", "options": ["Median cubital vein", "Subclavian vein", "Brachiocephalic artery", "External jugular vein"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Central venous catheters are most commonly placed in the subclavian vein, internal jugular vein, or femoral vein, with the catheter tip advanced to the superior vena cava. The subclavian approach is a frequent insertion site. The median cubital vein is a peripheral site used for routine venipuncture, not central line placement.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-271", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "A patient diagnosed with apraxia will have the greatest difficulty with which activity?", "options": ["Verbal communication", "Maintaining balance", "Performing purposeful movements such as dressing", "Swallowing food and liquids"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Apraxia is a neurological disorder that impairs the ability to plan and execute purposeful, learned motor movements despite having the physical ability and desire to perform them. Dressing, using utensils, and following multi-step motor commands are commonly affected. Difficulty with speech is aphasia, and difficulty swallowing is dysphagia.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-272", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "A patient with aphasia will have difficulty with all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Speaking", "Reading and writing", "Performing purposeful motor tasks such as dressing", "Understanding spoken language"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Aphasia is a language disorder that affects speaking, reading, writing, and comprehension of spoken language. Performing purposeful motor tasks (such as dressing) is impaired in apraxia, not aphasia. Technologists should use nonverbal communication strategies and allow extra time when caring for patients with aphasia.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-273", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "A pulse oximetry reading that indicates severe hypoxia is:", "options": ["95–100%", "91–94%", "86–90%", "85% or below"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "A pulse oximetry (SpO2) reading of 85% or below indicates severe hypoxia requiring immediate intervention, including supplemental oxygen and assessment for the underlying cause. Normal SpO2 is 95–100%, and readings between 91–94% indicate mild hypoxia warranting clinical attention.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-274", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "An adverse reaction or complication directly caused by a healthcare professional's treatment or procedure is termed:", "options": ["Idiopathic", "Nosocomial", "Iatrogenic", "Anaphylactic"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "An iatrogenic event is any adverse condition caused by medical treatment or a healthcare provider's actions. Nosocomial refers specifically to hospital-acquired infections, not treatment-caused adverse events in general. Idiopathic describes conditions of unknown cause.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-275", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "What is the normal resting pulse rate range for a healthy adult?", "options": ["40–60 bpm", "60–100 bpm", "100–120 bpm", "120–140 bpm"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The normal adult resting heart rate is 60–100 beats per minute. A rate below 60 bpm is classified as bradycardia, while a rate above 100 bpm is tachycardia. Well-conditioned athletes may have resting rates in the 40–60 bpm range without pathology.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-276", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B", "stem": "The medical term used to describe a patient who has a fever is:", "options": ["Hypothermic", "Febrile", "Dyspneic", "Diaphoretic"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Febrile is the medical term describing a patient with an elevated body temperature (fever), generally defined as a core temperature above 38.0°C (100.4°F). Hypothermic describes abnormally low body temperature, and dyspneic refers to difficulty breathing.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-277", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "After a seizure has resolved, the patient should be placed in which position during the postictal recovery period?", "options": ["Recovery position (lateral recumbent)", "Supine with arms at sides", "Seated upright in a wheelchair", "Prone with head turned to the side"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The recovery position (lateral recumbent/Sims' position) helps maintain a patent airway and allows secretions to drain from the mouth, reducing aspiration risk during the postictal period when the patient may be confused or have diminished protective reflexes. Supine positioning increases aspiration risk if the patient vomits.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-278", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "According to the Kübler-Ross model, the first stage of the grieving process is:", "options": ["Anger", "Denial", "Depression", "Bargaining"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Kübler-Ross model identifies five stages of grief: denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance. Denial is the first stage, serving as a defense mechanism that allows the individual to absorb the reality of their situation gradually. MRI technologists may encounter patients at various stages of grief, particularly those receiving imaging for serious diagnoses.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-279", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "According to Maslow's hierarchy of needs, which of the following is NOT classified as a basic physiologic need?", "options": ["Food and water", "Adequate sleep", "Morality and ethical reasoning", "Thermoregulation and shelter"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In Maslow's hierarchy, physiologic needs form the base and include food, water, sleep, thermoregulation, and other biological necessities for survival. Morality and ethical reasoning belong to the self-actualization tier at the top of the hierarchy. Understanding this model helps technologists prioritize patient needs during care.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-280", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "What is the most effective method for a technologist to confirm that a patient has understood pre-procedure instructions?", "options": ["Ask the patient if they understood", "Observe the patient nodding in agreement", "Have the patient restate the information in their own words", "Provide a written handout and assume comprehension"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The teach-back method — having the patient restate information in their own words — is the gold standard for verifying patient comprehension. Simply asking 'do you understand?' often elicits a yes regardless of actual understanding, and nodding does not confirm cognitive processing of the information.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-281", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "When explaining an MRI procedure to a pediatric patient, the technologist should:", "options": ["Stand over the child to project authority and confidence", "Lower to the child's eye level and use age-appropriate language", "Address all explanations to the parent rather than the child", "Use detailed medical terminology to educate the child"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Positioning at the child's eye level creates a less intimidating interaction and improves communication. Standing over a child can feel threatening and reduce cooperation. Age-appropriate language and direct engagement with the child (in addition to the parent) build trust and reduce anxiety.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-282", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "When communicating with a patient who has hearing loss, which approach should the technologist AVOID?", "options": ["Eliminating background noise before speaking", "Speaking loudly in a high-pitched voice", "Facing the patient directly while speaking", "Rephrasing statements when not initially understood"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Speaking loudly in a high-pitched voice is counterproductive for patients with hearing loss, as high-frequency hearing loss is the most common type and loud high-pitched speech distorts sounds further. Effective strategies include facing the patient (enabling lip reading), reducing background noise, and rephrasing rather than simply repeating louder.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-283", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "When providing instructions to a patient with cognitive impairment, the most effective communication strategy is to:", "options": ["Give all instructions at once to minimize repeated interruptions", "Provide clear, simple directions one step at a time", "Speak only to the patient's caregiver or family member", "Use written instructions exclusively since verbal communication is ineffective"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patients with cognitive impairment process information most effectively when it is presented in clear, simple language with one direction given at a time. Overwhelming the patient with multiple simultaneous instructions increases confusion and reduces compliance. The technologist should communicate directly with the patient while involving caregivers as needed.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-284", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which of the following behaviors is least likely to vary based on a patient's cultural background?", "options": ["Preferences regarding direct eye contact", "Primary language spoken", "Physiologic ability to perceive pain", "Comfort level with physical touch from strangers"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The physiologic ability to perceive pain is a neurological function that does not vary by culture. However, the expression and tolerance of pain are significantly influenced by cultural norms. Eye contact preferences, language, and comfort with physical touch are all culturally mediated behaviors that technologists should be sensitive to during patient interactions.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-285", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "Which statement about patients with an altered state of consciousness is NOT accurate?", "options": ["They may be unable to remember verbal instructions given during the altered state", "They will never recall any conversations or events that occurred during the altered state", "The technologist should continue communicating with the patient even if unconscious", "They may provide responses to questions that are inaccurate or unrelated"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "It is inaccurate to state that patients with altered consciousness will never remember anything. Research demonstrates that some patients retain partial awareness and memory even during altered states, including sedation and periods of reduced consciousness. Technologists should always communicate respectfully and maintain professional conduct regardless of the patient's apparent level of awareness.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-286", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "When preparing a pediatric patient for an MRI examination, the technologist should offer choices to the child:", "options": ["As frequently as possible to make the child feel empowered", "Only when a genuine choice actually exists", "Never, since children cannot make informed decisions about medical procedures", "Only when the parent or guardian is not present"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Offering choices to children is an effective strategy for building cooperation, but choices should only be presented when a genuine option exists. Offering a false choice (e.g., 'Do you want to have your MRI now?') and then proceeding regardless of the answer undermines trust and increases anxiety. Real choices (e.g., 'Which arm for the IV?') give children a sense of control.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-287", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A", "stem": "The distance at which a patient typically feels most comfortable during a clinical interaction such as an MRI procedure explanation is:", "options": ["Within 1 foot (intimate space)", "Approximately 3 feet (personal space)", "Approximately 6 feet (social distance)", "Variable depending on the individual patient"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Personal space preferences vary significantly among individuals based on cultural background, personality, and the clinical context. While healthcare interactions typically occur within personal space (1.5–4 feet), technologists should be attentive to nonverbal cues indicating patient discomfort and adjust their proximity accordingly.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-288", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When opening a wrapped sterile package, the first flap should be opened in which direction?", "options": ["Toward the person opening the package", "Away from the person opening the package", "Toward the dominant hand", "To the left side regardless of hand dominance"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The first flap of a sterile package is always opened away from the person to prevent contamination by reaching over the sterile contents. Subsequent flaps are opened to the sides, and the final flap is opened toward the person. This sequence ensures that the sterile field is never compromised by the person's arm or body crossing over the contents.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-289", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When setting up a sterile field, a package that appears damp or wet should be:", "options": ["Considered contaminated and discarded", "Considered sterile since dampness indicates recent autoclaving", "Unwrapped and placed in the center of the sterile field", "Dried with a sterile towel before opening"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "A damp or wet sterile package is always considered contaminated because moisture provides a pathway (wicking) for microorganisms to migrate through the packaging material from the non-sterile exterior to the sterile interior. Such packages must be discarded and replaced with an intact, dry sterile package.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-290", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which device uses high-pressure steam to achieve sterilization of medical instruments and equipment?", "options": ["Ultraviolet light chamber", "Autoclave", "Chemical fog dispenser", "Dry heat oven"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An autoclave uses pressurized steam at temperatures of 121–134°C to destroy all microorganisms including bacterial spores, achieving true sterilization. It is the most common and reliable method of steam sterilization in healthcare settings. Dry heat ovens can also sterilize but require longer exposure times and higher temperatures.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-291", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When the body is invaded by pathogenic organisms, the primary response observed in the bloodstream is:", "options": ["An increase in the red blood cell count", "An increase in the white blood cell count", "An elevation in serum protein levels", "An increase in the platelet count"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Leukocytosis (elevated white blood cell count) is the body's primary hematologic response to infection, as leukocytes are mobilized to identify, attack, and destroy invading pathogens through phagocytosis and immune activation. An elevated red blood cell count (polycythemia) is associated with dehydration or bone marrow disorders, not infection.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-292", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Protective (reverse) isolation is used for patients who have:", "options": ["A highly contagious respiratory infection", "A compromised or suppressed immune system", "An active gastrointestinal infection", "A drug-resistant skin infection"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Protective (reverse) isolation protects immunocompromised patients — such as those undergoing chemotherapy, organ transplant recipients, or those with severe neutropenia — from environmental pathogens. Standard isolation protects healthcare workers and other patients FROM the infected patient, which is the opposite purpose.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-293", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Linen that has been used by a patient with a suspected salmonella infection should be:", "options": ["Placed in a designated biohazard (red) contamination bag", "Placed in the standard dirty linen hamper", "Stored separately for 24 hours before laundering", "Immediately sent to an incinerator for destruction"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Linen contaminated with enteric pathogens such as Salmonella must be handled as biohazardous material and placed in a designated red contamination bag to prevent cross-contamination. Standard dirty linen handling is insufficient for known infectious material. Incineration is not standard protocol for contaminated linen.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-294", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "According to CDC guidelines, what type of precautions should be observed when caring for an HIV-positive patient?", "options": ["Strict isolation with negative-pressure room", "Respiratory isolation with N95 mask", "Enteric precautions with dedicated bathroom", "Standard (universal) precautions"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "HIV is transmitted through blood and body fluids, not through casual contact or airborne routes. Standard (universal) precautions — including hand hygiene, gloves for blood/fluid contact, and sharps safety — are sufficient and appropriate for HIV-positive patients. Strict or respiratory isolation is unnecessary and stigmatizing.", "reference": "CDC / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-295", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Under which condition would a wrapped sterile package still be considered safe to use?", "options": ["The package has a visible tear in the wrapping", "The sterility indicator tape is intact and has changed color appropriately", "The outer surface of the package is damp", "The printed expiration date has been exceeded"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A sterile package is considered safe for use when the sterility indicator tape is intact and shows the appropriate color change confirming exposure to sterilization conditions. Any tear, moisture penetration, or exceeded expiration date compromises the sterile barrier and renders the package contaminated.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-296", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "A sterile tray set up on a table has a border around its edges that must be considered non-sterile. What is the standard width of this non-sterile border?", "options": ["One-half inch", "One inch", "Four inches", "Six inches"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The outer one-inch border of any sterile field or draped surface is considered non-sterile because it is in proximity to unsterile surfaces and is most likely to become contaminated during setup. All sterile items must be placed within this border, and any item touching the border area is considered contaminated.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-297", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "The process of reducing the number of pathogenic microorganisms on surfaces using chemical agents, without achieving complete sterilization, is called:", "options": ["Sterilization", "Surgical asepsis", "Medical asepsis", "Pasteurization"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Medical asepsis (clean technique) involves practices that reduce the number and transmission of pathogenic microorganisms, including hand hygiene, surface disinfection, and standard precautions. Surgical asepsis (sterile technique) aims to create and maintain a completely pathogen-free environment. Sterilization eliminates all microorganisms including spores.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-298", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "An infection acquired by a patient during their stay in a hospital or healthcare facility is termed a:", "options": ["Iatrogenic infection", "Nosocomial (healthcare-associated) infection", "Idiopathic infection", "Community-acquired infection"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Nosocomial infections (now commonly called healthcare-associated infections or HAIs) are acquired during hospitalization and were not present or incubating at the time of admission. An iatrogenic condition is caused directly by medical treatment, while an idiopathic condition has no identifiable cause.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-299", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Diseases such as malaria, in which pathogenic organisms are transmitted to humans through insect bites, are classified as:", "options": ["Nosocomial infections", "Indirect contact infections", "Common vehicle infections", "Vector-borne infections"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "Vector-borne infections are transmitted by living organisms (vectors) such as mosquitoes, ticks, or fleas that carry and transfer pathogens from one host to another. Malaria is the classic example, transmitted by Anopheles mosquitoes. Indirect contact transmission involves contaminated objects (fomites) rather than living vectors.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-300", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which type of white blood cell is primarily responsible for phagocytosis of invading pathogens?", "options": ["Neutrophil (a type of leukocyte)", "Erythrocyte", "Thrombocyte", "Lymphocyte"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Neutrophils are the most abundant type of leukocyte and are the primary cells responsible for phagocytosis — the process of engulfing and destroying bacteria and other pathogens. Lymphocytes participate in adaptive immunity (antibody production and cell-mediated responses) but are not the primary phagocytic cells. Erythrocytes transport oxygen and thrombocytes form clots.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-301", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "In the chain of infection, the location where pathogens live and multiply in sufficient numbers to pose a threat is called the:", "options": ["Carrier", "Portal of entry", "Reservoir", "Fomite"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The reservoir is the habitat where infectious agents survive, grow, and multiply. Reservoirs can be human (carriers), animal, or environmental (soil, water). A fomite is a contaminated inanimate object that can transmit infection, and a carrier is a person who harbors a pathogen without showing symptoms.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-302", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which portion of a sterile surgical gown is considered non-sterile?", "options": ["The front of the arms from elbow to cuff", "The chest area above the waist", "The area at waist level", "The entire back of the gown"], "correct": "d", "rationale": "The back of a sterile surgical gown is always considered non-sterile because the wearer cannot monitor it for contamination. The sterile area includes only the front of the gown from chest to waist level and the sleeves from above the elbow to the cuffs. Any contact with the back of the gown contaminates hands or instruments.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-303", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "In the MRI environment, which of the following would NOT be classified as a fomite (contaminated inanimate object)?", "options": ["The head coil", "The MRI table surface", "A single-use disposable syringe", "The operator console keyboard"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A fomite is a reusable inanimate object that can harbor and transmit pathogens between patients. The head coil, table surface, and keyboard are all reusable surfaces that contact multiple patients or operators and can serve as fomites. A single-use disposable syringe is discarded after one use and does not transfer pathogens between patients.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-304", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which engineering control is most effective for preventing airborne pathogen transmission in healthcare settings?", "options": ["Frequent surface disinfection protocols", "Specialized ventilation systems with HEPA filtration and negative pressure", "Universal masking of all personnel", "Ultraviolet germicidal irradiation of surfaces only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Specialized ventilation systems — including HEPA-filtered negative-pressure isolation rooms — are the primary engineering control for preventing airborne transmission of pathogens such as tuberculosis and measles. While masking provides personal protection, ventilation systems address contamination at the environmental level for all occupants.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-305", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Droplet contamination most commonly occurs through which mechanism?", "options": ["Sneezing or coughing", "Shaking hands with an infected person", "Normal quiet breathing", "Touching shared equipment surfaces"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Droplet transmission occurs when respiratory droplets (>5 micrometers) generated by sneezing, coughing, or talking are propelled a short distance and contact the mucous membranes of a susceptible person. Droplets are too heavy to remain airborne for extended periods, distinguishing droplet from true airborne transmission. Hand contact transmits pathogens through contact, not droplet, mechanisms.", "reference": "CDC / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-306", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which single practice is considered the most effective method for preventing the spread of microorganisms in healthcare settings?", "options": ["Hand hygiene (handwashing)", "Routine surface disinfection of workspaces", "Sterilization of all reusable equipment", "Wearing gloves during all patient interactions"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Hand hygiene is universally recognized as the single most important measure for preventing the transmission of healthcare-associated infections. While gloves, surface disinfection, and sterilization are all important components of infection control, proper hand hygiene before and after patient contact is the foundation of all infection prevention strategies.", "reference": "CDC / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-307", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When removing personal protective equipment (PPE), which item should be removed first?", "options": ["Face mask or respirator", "Isolation gown", "Gloves", "Eye protection or face shield"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gloves are removed first during PPE doffing because they are the most contaminated item and removing them first prevents transferring pathogens to other PPE or skin during subsequent removal steps. The recommended CDC sequence is: gloves first, then gown, then exit the room, then remove mask/respirator and eye protection.", "reference": "CDC / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-308", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "For patients on droplet precautions, what personal protective equipment must healthcare workers and visitors wear when entering the room?", "options": ["Gown only", "Surgical mask", "Gown and surgical mask", "N95 respirator, gown, and gloves"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Droplet precautions require a surgical mask when within approximately 3–6 feet of the patient to prevent inhalation of large respiratory droplets. A gown is not routinely required unless substantial contact with the patient or contaminated surfaces is anticipated. N95 respirators are reserved for airborne precautions (tuberculosis, measles, varicella).", "reference": "CDC / PC general"}, {"id": "PC-309", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "When cleaning environmental surfaces in a healthcare setting, the proper technique is to clean from:", "options": ["Bottom surfaces to top surfaces", "Most contaminated areas to least contaminated areas", "Least contaminated areas to most contaminated areas", "Wet areas to dry areas"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Cleaning should always proceed from the least contaminated (cleanest) areas to the most contaminated (dirtiest) areas to avoid spreading pathogens from heavily soiled areas to cleaner surfaces. Similarly, cleaning from top to bottom prevents dripping contaminated solution onto already-cleaned lower surfaces.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-310", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "The use of chemical disinfectants on surfaces and equipment achieves which level of microbial control?", "options": ["Sterilization (elimination of all microorganisms)", "Surgical asepsis (pathogen-free environment)", "Medical asepsis (reduction of pathogen numbers)", "Complete eradication of all organic matter"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Chemical disinfectants achieve medical asepsis by reducing the number of pathogenic microorganisms on surfaces to a level that is not harmful, but they do not eliminate all organisms (particularly bacterial spores). Sterilization, which destroys all microorganisms including spores, requires methods such as autoclaving, ethylene oxide gas, or prolonged high-level chemical exposure.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-311", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.C", "stem": "Which of the following is true regarding recovery from general anesthesia in the MRI setting?", "options": ["Emergence delirium may indicate hypoxia and requires immediate assessment", "Normal environmental noise levels are acceptable during recovery", "Vomiting is uncommon and typically benign after general anesthesia", "Patients should be positioned supine during the recovery period"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Emergence delirium — an agitated, disoriented state upon awakening from general anesthesia — may indicate hypoxia and requires prompt assessment of airway patency and oxygen saturation. Noise should be minimized as sounds are exaggerated during emergence, and vomiting is a common and serious hazard due to aspiration risk. Patients should be positioned on their side (recovery position) to protect the airway.", "reference": "PC general"}, {"id": "PC-312", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "An MRI technologist receives a new imaging order. Which action should be performed FIRST?", "options": ["Position the appropriate receiver coil on the table", "Enter the scan protocol parameters into the console", "Verify the patient’s identity and confirm the ordered examination", "Check the scan room temperature and humidity"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Patient identification and order verification is the first step in any imaging encounter to prevent wrong-patient or wrong-exam errors. Failing to verify identity before proceeding can result in serious patient safety events and is a Joint Commission National Patient Safety Goal. Coil selection and protocol entry occur after the patient is confirmed. (ACR Practice Parameters; Joint Commission NPSG)", "reference": "ACR Practice Parameters"}, {"id": "PC-313", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "In a medical malpractice claim, which party carries the burden of proving that negligence occurred?", "options": ["The defendant healthcare provider", "The facility’s risk management department", "The plaintiff who filed the lawsuit", "The presiding judge"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "In malpractice litigation, the plaintiff (injured party) bears the burden of proving all four elements of negligence: duty, breach, causation, and damages. The defendant is presumed not liable until the plaintiff meets this burden. The risk management department and the judge do not carry the burden of proof. (Torres' Patient Care in Imaging Technology, Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-314", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The ethical principle expressed by the Latin phrase “primum non nocere” (first, do no harm) is known as:", "options": ["Beneficence", "Nonmaleficence", "Veracity", "Autonomy"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Nonmaleficence is the obligation to avoid causing harm to the patient. Beneficence, in contrast, is the duty to actively promote the patient’s well-being. Students commonly confuse these two principles because both relate to patient welfare, but the key distinction is that nonmaleficence focuses on preventing harm while beneficence focuses on doing good. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-315", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "A technologist leaves a disoriented patient unattended on the MRI table. The patient falls and sustains a hip fracture. This scenario most likely represents which legal claim?", "options": ["Assault", "Battery", "Negligence", "Defamation"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Negligence occurs when a healthcare professional fails to exercise the standard of care that a reasonably prudent professional would provide in the same circumstances. Leaving a disoriented patient unattended breaches the duty of care owed to that patient. Assault and battery are intentional torts requiring deliberate action, which does not apply here. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-316", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1.a", "stem": "A competent adult patient uses the squeeze bulb alarm during an MRI sequence and demands the exam be stopped. What is the technologist’s MOST appropriate response?", "options": ["Continue the sequence to its completion before responding", "Ask the patient to wait until the current series finishes", "Immediately stop the scan and safely remove the patient from the bore", "Contact the referring physician for instructions"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "A competent patient retains the legal right to withdraw consent and discontinue any medical procedure at any time. Continuing the scan against the patient’s wishes could constitute battery or false imprisonment. Contacting the physician first unnecessarily delays response to the patient’s expressed wishes. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1; ACR Practice Parameters)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-317", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "A retained surgical instrument discovered incidentally on an MRI examination would most likely be litigated under which legal doctrine?", "options": ["Respondeat superior", "Stare decisis", "Res ipsa loquitur", "Habeas corpus"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Res ipsa loquitur (“the thing speaks for itself”) applies when the injury would not ordinarily occur without negligence, the instrumentality was under the defendant’s exclusive control, and the plaintiff did not contribute to the event. A retained surgical instrument is a classic example because it self-evidently implies negligence. Respondeat superior addresses employer liability for employee actions, not the evidentiary standard. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-318", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "When charting an event in a patient’s medical record, which elements must the technologist include?", "options": ["Only their initials and employee ID number", "The date, time, description of the event, and full signature with credentials", "Only the date and a brief note", "Only the supervising radiologist’s name and order number"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Complete medical record documentation requires the date, time, a factual description of the event, and the full signature with professional credentials of the person making the entry. Incomplete entries (initials only or date only) do not meet the legal standard for medical charting and may be challenged in litigation. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-319", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "Which of the following is classified as an unintentional tort in healthcare law?", "options": ["Battery", "Negligence", "False imprisonment", "Assault"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An unintentional tort occurs when harm results from carelessness or failure to meet the standard of care, without deliberate intent. Negligence is the only unintentional tort among these options. Assault, battery, and false imprisonment are all intentional torts that require a deliberate act or threat. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-320", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "An MRI technologist tells an anxious patient, “If you do not stop moving, I will strap you to the table.” This statement could be legally classified as:", "options": ["Battery", "Assault", "Libel", "Negligence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Assault is defined as creating a reasonable apprehension or fear of harmful or offensive contact in another person—no physical touching is required. Battery, by contrast, involves actual unauthorized physical contact. The key distinction students should remember is that assault involves the threat and battery involves the act. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-321", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The principle of double effect in healthcare ethics states that a morally good action is permissible even if it produces an unintended harmful side effect, provided the harmful outcome is not the primary goal. Which scenario best illustrates this principle?", "options": ["Performing an exam without informed consent because the schedule is busy", "Administering prescribed sedation that effectively manages anxiety but carries a small risk of respiratory depression", "Two technologists disagreeing on the optimal imaging protocol", "Intentionally prolonging scan time to increase departmental revenue"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The principle of double effect permits an action with a good primary intent (managing anxiety for a necessary exam) even when it carries a foreseeable but unintended negative consequence (respiratory depression risk). The harmful effect must not be the means to achieve the good effect. Choice A violates autonomy, and choice D represents intentional harm. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-322", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1.a", "stem": "An ambulatory outpatient walks into the MRI suite, follows the technologist’s verbal instructions, and voluntarily lies on the scanner table. This patient’s cooperative behavior represents which type of consent?", "options": ["Informed consent", "Implied consent", "Written consent", "Express consent"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Implied consent is inferred from a patient’s voluntary actions and cooperative behavior rather than from a verbal or written declaration. When a patient willingly follows instructions and positions themselves for an exam, their actions demonstrate consent. Informed consent specifically requires a documented explanation of risks, benefits, and alternatives before the procedure. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-323", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "An MRI technologist inadvertently scans the wrong anatomical region on a patient. This unauthorized physical contact could constitute which legal claim?", "options": ["Assault", "Battery", "Slander", "Fraud"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Battery is defined as any unauthorized or unlawful physical contact with another person. Scanning the wrong body part exceeds the scope of the patient’s consent, making it an unauthorized touching. Assault requires a threat or apprehension of contact without actual touching, so it does not apply when physical contact has already occurred. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-324", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The legal doctrine respondeat superior holds that:", "options": ["Negligence is self-evident from the circumstances", "An employer may be held vicariously liable for the negligent acts of an employee performed within the scope of employment", "Courts must follow previously established legal precedent", "A healthcare provider’s first obligation is to prevent harm"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Respondeat superior (“let the master answer”) establishes that employers share legal liability for the actions of their employees committed during the course of employment. Under this doctrine, a hospital can be held liable for a technologist’s negligent conduct during patient care. Res ipsa loquitur (choice A) and stare decisis (choice C) are separate legal principles. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-325", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1.a", "stem": "Which of the following circumstances would INVALIDATE a patient’s informed consent?", "options": ["The patient is a competent 19-year-old adult", "The radiologist thoroughly explained the procedure’s risks and benefits", "The patient was coerced or pressured into signing the consent form", "The patient asked multiple clarifying questions before signing"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Valid informed consent requires three conditions: the patient must be competent, the procedure must be adequately explained (including risks, benefits, and alternatives), and the consent must be given voluntarily without coercion or duress. If any of these conditions is not met, the consent is legally invalid. Students should remember that even if a form is signed, consent obtained under pressure does not meet the legal standard. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-326", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "The intentional destruction, alteration, or concealment of medical records that may be used as evidence is legally termed:", "options": ["Negligence", "Spoliation", "Battery", "Libel"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Spoliation of evidence refers to the deliberate destruction or alteration of records that are relevant to litigation. Courts may impose severe sanctions, including adverse inference instructions against the party responsible for the spoliation. Negligence is unintentional, and libel refers to written defamation—neither applies to record destruction. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-327", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The legal doctrine stare decisis requires courts to:", "options": ["Follow previously established rulings in similar cases to maintain consistency", "Hold employers liable for the actions of their employees", "Infer negligence from circumstances that speak for themselves", "Allow emergency treatment without patient consent"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Stare decisis (“to stand by things decided”) obligates courts to follow precedent—prior judicial decisions in cases with similar facts and legal issues. This doctrine provides predictability and consistency in the legal system. Choice B describes respondeat superior, and choice C describes res ipsa loquitur. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-328", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Two MRI technologists discuss a patient’s diagnosis and medical history while riding a public elevator with other hospital visitors present. This behavior constitutes a violation of:", "options": ["Patient confidentiality and HIPAA regulations", "The doctrine of res ipsa loquitur", "Assault statutes", "Battery statutes"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) prohibits the disclosure of protected health information in any setting where unauthorized individuals may overhear. Discussing patient information in a public area such as an elevator, cafeteria, or hallway is a common but serious HIPAA violation. This is an invasion of patient privacy, not a tort involving physical contact or threat. (HIPAA Privacy Rule; Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-329", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "An MRI technologist makes false spoken statements about a patient that damage the patient’s reputation. This conduct is legally classified as:", "options": ["Libel", "Slander", "Battery", "Negligence"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Slander is the legal term for spoken defamation—false verbal statements that harm another person’s reputation. Libel refers to written or published defamation. The key distinction for exam purposes is the medium: slander is spoken, libel is written. Both are intentional torts. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-330", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT recognized as a standard patient right in healthcare?", "options": ["The right to refuse any examination or procedure", "The right to access and review personal medical records", "The right to receive an immediate diagnosis from the technologist", "The right to privacy during all aspects of care"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Providing a diagnosis is outside the MRI technologist’s scope of practice—image interpretation and diagnosis are the responsibility of the radiologist or referring physician. All other options listed are established patient rights under the Patient’s Bill of Rights and federal regulations. A technologist who offers a diagnosis risks both legal liability and an ARRT ethics violation. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1; ARRT Standards of Ethics)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-331", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.3", "stem": "The standard of care in malpractice cases is determined by how a “reasonably prudent professional” would have acted. This standard is based on:", "options": ["What an average person with no medical training would do in the situation", "How a healthcare professional with comparable education and training would perform under similar circumstances", "What the most experienced specialist in the field would do", "What the patient believes the correct course of action should be"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The reasonable prudent person standard compares the defendant’s actions to those expected of a similarly trained professional under similar circumstances. It does not require perfection or the highest level of expertise—it requires competent, standard-level care. A layperson’s judgment (choice A) and a top specialist’s expertise (choice C) are not the appropriate benchmarks. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-332", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "The ARRT Code of Ethics requires that radiologic technologists deliver services to all patients with:", "options": ["Respect for human dignity regardless of personal characteristics", "Priority given based on insurance status", "Personal opinions about the likely diagnosis shared with the patient", "Emphasis on departmental throughput over individual patient needs"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "The ARRT Standards of Ethics mandate that technologists provide care to all patients with full respect for human dignity, regardless of race, gender, religion, socioeconomic status, or diagnosis. Sharing a diagnosis (choice C) and prioritizing throughput over safety (choice D) both violate the code. (ARRT Standards of Ethics)", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-333", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.2", "stem": "Which action by an MRI technologist would constitute a violation of the ARRT Standards of Ethics?", "options": ["Refusing to perform an examination that lacks a valid physician order", "Interpreting MRI images and communicating a diagnosis to the patient", "Reporting a potential safety hazard to the MRI safety officer", "Providing respectful care to a patient with a communicable disease"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Interpreting images and communicating a diagnosis to a patient is strictly outside the technologist’s scope of practice and violates the ARRT Standards of Ethics. Only a qualified physician (typically a radiologist) may render an official interpretation. Refusing to perform an unordered exam and reporting safety hazards are actually consistent with ethical practice. (ARRT Standards of Ethics)", "reference": "ARRT Standards of Ethics"}, {"id": "PC-334", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "An MRI patient reports feeling lightheaded and then experiences a brief loss of consciousness (syncope). The most common physiological mechanism responsible for this event is:", "options": ["Hyperglycemia", "A sudden decrease in blood pressure reducing cerebral perfusion", "Systemic bacterial infection", "A vagal response triggered by a full stomach"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Syncope (fainting) most commonly results from a transient drop in blood pressure that temporarily reduces blood flow to the brain. This can be triggered by vasovagal responses, orthostatic changes, or anxiety. While hyperglycemia and infection can cause altered consciousness, they are not the most common causes of acute syncope in an MRI setting. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-335", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which of the following approaches is INAPPROPRIATE when managing a claustrophobic patient scheduled for a closed-bore MRI examination?", "options": ["Providing a thorough explanation of the procedure before scanning begins", "Offering MRI-compatible headphones with calming music", "Minimizing the patient’s fears by telling them the scanner is not as enclosed as it looks", "Positioning a prism mirror so the patient can see outside the bore"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Dismissing or minimizing a patient’s anxiety typically worsens the fear response and reduces cooperation. Evidence-based approaches to managing claustrophobia include clear communication, distraction techniques (music, mirrors), feet-first positioning when feasible, and anxiolytic medication when approved. Invalidating the patient’s experience undermines the therapeutic relationship. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-336", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Continuous physiological monitoring with pulse oximetry and/or ECG is REQUIRED for which patient population during MRI?", "options": ["All ambulatory outpatients", "Sedated, anesthetized, or unresponsive patients", "Patients who report wearing hearing aids", "Patients presenting with musculoskeletal complaints"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Patients who are sedated, anesthetized, or otherwise unable to communicate or protect their own airway require continuous physiological monitoring throughout the MRI examination. This typically includes pulse oximetry, ECG, and end-tidal CO2 monitoring as appropriate. Routine ambulatory outpatients who can communicate do not require continuous monitoring. (ACR Manual on MR Safety; Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "ACR Manual on MR Safety"}, {"id": "PC-337", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "According to the ACR Manual on Contrast Media, the PRIMARY risk factor for developing nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF) following gadolinium-based contrast agent administration is:", "options": ["A history of systemic hypertension", "Severe renal insufficiency with an eGFR below 30 mL/min/1.73 m²", "A documented history of asthma", "A reported allergy to shellfish"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "NSF is a rare but potentially devastating fibrosing condition that occurs almost exclusively in patients with severely impaired renal function (eGFR <30). The condition is strongly associated with exposure to certain linear gadolinium-based contrast agents that are less stable and more likely to release free gadolinium. Shellfish allergy and asthma are risk factors for iodinated contrast reactions, not NSF. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-338", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Current ACR guidelines indicate that Group II gadolinium-based contrast agents are generally considered safe for patients whose estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) is above which threshold?", "options": ["10 mL/min/1.73 m²", "30 mL/min/1.73 m²", "15 mL/min/1.73 m²", "100 mL/min/1.73 m²"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An eGFR above 30 mL/min/1.73 m² is the widely accepted threshold above which modern Group II (macrocyclic and stable linear) gadolinium agents carry minimal NSF risk. Below this threshold, additional risk-benefit assessment and possible alternative imaging strategies should be considered. The ACR distinguishes between Group I (higher risk) and Group II (lower risk) agents. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-339", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A diabetic patient presenting for an MRI examination reports excessive thirst, frequent urination, and dry skin. These symptoms are most consistent with:", "options": ["Hypoglycemia", "Hyperglycemia", "Hypertension", "Bradycardia"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hyperglycemia (elevated blood glucose) presents with the classic triad of polydipsia (excessive thirst), polyuria (frequent urination), and dry skin due to dehydration. Hypoglycemia, by contrast, presents with diaphoresis, tremors, confusion, and irritability. Recognizing the difference between hyper- and hypoglycemic presentations is critical for patient care on the MRI registry exam. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-340", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "According to current American Heart Association (AHA) guidelines, the correct sequence for adult basic life support (BLS) is:", "options": ["Airway → Breathing → Compressions (A-B-C)", "Compressions → Airway → Breathing (C-A-B)", "Breathing → Airway → Compressions (B-A-C)", "Check pulse → Call for help → Wait for the code team"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The AHA updated the BLS sequence from A-B-C to C-A-B to prioritize immediate chest compressions, which maintain circulation and coronary perfusion pressure. Early compressions are the single most important intervention for sudden cardiac arrest survival. The older A-B-C sequence delayed compressions while providers assessed the airway. (AHA BLS Guidelines)", "reference": "AHA BLS Guidelines"}, {"id": "PC-341", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient in the MRI waiting area reports feeling faint and dizzy while standing. The technologist’s MOST appropriate immediate action is to:", "options": ["Walk the patient to their vehicle", "Assist the patient to a safe seated or supine position", "Offer the patient a glass of water", "Immediately call 911"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The priority when a patient reports pre-syncopal symptoms is preventing a fall injury by lowering the patient to a safe seated or supine position. This protects the patient from potential head trauma or fractures associated with an uncontrolled fall. Offering water or calling 911 may be appropriate follow-up actions, but preventing the fall is the immediate priority. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-342", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "During a power-injected gadolinium administration, the patient reports sudden pain and swelling at the injection site. The technologist observes localized edema around the IV catheter. What is the MOST appropriate immediate intervention?", "options": ["Increase the injection flow rate to complete the dose quickly", "Apply a warm compress directly to the swelling", "Stop the injection, disconnect the tubing, and apply cold compresses with elevation", "Place a tourniquet proximal to the injection site"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Contrast extravasation requires immediate cessation of the injection to prevent further tissue infiltration. Cold compresses help constrict local blood vessels and limit the spread of extravasated fluid, while elevation promotes drainage. Warm compresses may be used later to promote reabsorption but are not the initial intervention. A tourniquet is contraindicated as it would trap the extravasated fluid. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-343", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The tunica media—the thick muscular layer of a blood vessel wall—is most prominently developed in which type of vessel?", "options": ["Veins", "Arteries", "Capillaries", "Lymphatic vessels"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Arteries have the thickest tunica media because they must withstand the high hydrostatic pressure generated by cardiac contraction. This muscular and elastic layer allows arteries to expand and recoil with each heartbeat. Veins have a thinner tunica media and rely on valves rather than muscle tone to maintain blood flow. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-344", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "A sealed glass medication container designed for single use that requires the neck to be snapped open is called a(n):", "options": ["Vial", "Ampule", "Prefilled syringe", "Bolus cartridge"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "An ampule is a sealed all-glass container that must be broken at the neck to access the medication inside. A vial, in contrast, has a rubber stopper that is accessed with a needle. This distinction is commonly tested because proper technique differs—ampules require a filter needle to prevent glass fragment aspiration into the syringe. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-345", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Before an invasive procedure, which laboratory values are most important to assess the patient’s coagulation status?", "options": ["BUN and serum creatinine", "Estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR)", "Prothrombin time (PT/INR) and platelet count", "Hemoglobin and hematocrit"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "PT/INR measures the extrinsic clotting pathway and platelet count reflects the body’s ability to form a primary hemostatic plug. Together, they indicate whether a patient can achieve adequate hemostasis after an invasive procedure. BUN/creatinine and eGFR assess renal function, while hemoglobin/hematocrit measure oxygen-carrying capacity—important values, but not specific to coagulation. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-346", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "The approximate normal range for adult serum creatinine is:", "options": ["0.1–0.3 mg/dL", "0.6–1.5 mg/dL", "5.0–10.0 mg/dL", "20–40 mg/dL"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Serum creatinine is a byproduct of muscle metabolism that is filtered by the kidneys. Values in the 0.6–1.5 mg/dL range are considered normal for adults (with slight variation by sex and muscle mass). Elevated creatinine suggests impaired renal function and is a key value to check before gadolinium contrast administration. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media; Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-347", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Which blood vessel is responsible for returning oxygenated blood from the lungs to the left atrium of the heart?", "options": ["Pulmonary artery", "Pulmonary vein", "Superior vena cava", "Aorta"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The pulmonary veins are unique because they are the only veins in the body that carry oxygenated blood. They return freshly oxygenated blood from the lungs to the left atrium for systemic distribution. Students often confuse this with the pulmonary arteries, which carry deoxygenated blood from the right ventricle to the lungs. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-348", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "The approximate normal range for blood urea nitrogen (BUN) in adults is:", "options": ["1–2 mg/dL", "8–20 mg/dL", "50–100 mg/dL", "0.1–0.5 mg/dL"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "BUN is a waste product of protein metabolism that is excreted by the kidneys. Normal adult values fall between 8 and 20 mg/dL. Elevated BUN may indicate dehydration, renal dysfunction, or high-protein diet. When paired with an elevated serum creatinine, it strongly suggests impaired kidney function and requires careful evaluation before gadolinium administration. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-349", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Which of the following clinical presentations is most characteristic of an anaphylactoid (allergic-like) reaction to gadolinium-based contrast media?", "options": ["Urticaria (hives) and cutaneous flushing", "Bradycardia with hypotension (vasovagal response)", "Acute renal failure (nephrotoxic reaction)", "Hyperventilation from anxiety (psychogenic reaction)"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Anaphylactoid reactions to gadolinium present with allergic-like symptoms including urticaria, pruritus, flushing, and in severe cases, bronchospasm or laryngeal edema. These reactions are not IgE-mediated but mimic true anaphylaxis. A vasovagal response (choice B) is a physiologic reaction characterized by bradycardia and hypotension, not an allergic mechanism. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-350", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "According to current American Heart Association guidelines, the recommended chest compression rate for adult CPR is:", "options": ["60–80 compressions per minute", "80–100 compressions per minute", "100–120 compressions per minute", "Greater than 140 compressions per minute"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The AHA recommends a compression rate of 100–120 per minute for adult CPR. Rates below 100 produce inadequate cardiac output, while rates exceeding 120 compromise compression depth and myocardial perfusion. The compression depth should be at least 2 inches (5 cm) but no more than 2.4 inches (6 cm). (AHA BLS Guidelines)", "reference": "AHA BLS Guidelines"}, {"id": "PC-351", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The standard compression-to-ventilation ratio for single-rescuer adult CPR is:", "options": ["15:2", "5:1", "30:2", "50:2"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The AHA recommends a 30:2 compression-to-ventilation ratio for single-rescuer adult CPR. This ratio maximizes the time spent on chest compressions, which are the most critical component of resuscitation. The previous 15:2 ratio (choice A) is used for two-rescuer pediatric CPR but not for adult single-rescuer scenarios. (AHA BLS Guidelines)", "reference": "AHA BLS Guidelines"}, {"id": "PC-352", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient presenting with rapid heart rate, cool clammy skin, and low blood pressure after significant hemorrhage is most likely experiencing which type of shock?", "options": ["Septic shock", "Hypovolemic shock", "Anaphylactic shock", "Cardiogenic shock"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hypovolemic shock results from a critical loss of intravascular volume (blood or fluid), leading to inadequate tissue perfusion. The prefix “hypo” (low) and “volemic” (volume) directly describe the mechanism. Septic shock is caused by overwhelming infection, anaphylactic shock by a severe allergic reaction, and cardiogenic shock by pump failure. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-353", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which technique demonstrates proper body mechanics when transferring a patient from a wheelchair to the MRI table?", "options": ["Bending at the waist to reach the patient", "Keeping the back straight while lifting primarily with the legs", "Holding the patient at arm’s length away from the body", "Twisting at the waist while supporting the patient’s weight"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Proper body mechanics require maintaining a straight back, bending at the knees and hips, and using the large muscle groups of the legs to generate lifting force. This technique minimizes stress on the lumbar spine and reduces the risk of musculoskeletal injury. Twisting while lifting (choice D) is one of the most common causes of back injury in healthcare workers. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-354", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The log-roll transfer technique is specifically required when moving a patient with a suspected:", "options": ["Upper extremity fracture", "Spinal or vertebral column injury", "Isolated closed head injury", "Lower extremity muscle cramp"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Log rolling maintains the entire spinal column in neutral alignment during patient transfer, preventing flexion, extension, or rotation that could worsen a vertebral fracture or cause secondary spinal cord injury. This technique requires a coordinated team effort with one person maintaining inline cervical stabilization. Extremity fractures and muscle cramps do not require spinal precautions. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-355", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When transferring a patient with an indwelling urinary catheter to the MRI table, the drainage bag must be positioned:", "options": ["Above the level of the bladder to promote flow", "Below the level of the bladder at all times", "On the patient’s lap for convenience", "Clamped and secured flat on the table surface"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The urinary drainage bag must remain below bladder level to maintain gravity-dependent drainage and prevent retrograde flow of urine back into the bladder, which significantly increases the risk of urinary tract infection. Elevating the bag above the bladder (choice A) reverses the pressure gradient and allows bacterial contamination. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-356", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Before injecting gadolinium-based contrast media, the syringe and IV tubing must be primed (flushed with saline). The primary purpose of this step is to:", "options": ["Cool the contrast media to room temperature", "Eliminate air from the tubing to prevent air embolism", "Prevent contrast extravasation at the injection site", "Ensure proper mixing of the contrast agent"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Priming removes air bubbles from the syringe and tubing to prevent venous air embolism, which can be a potentially fatal complication if a large volume of air enters the circulatory system. Even small air bubbles can cause transient symptoms. Extravasation prevention (choice C) is achieved through proper IV placement and monitoring, not through priming. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6; ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-357", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A critically ill patient develops cardiovascular collapse secondary to an overwhelming systemic infection. This clinical presentation is most consistent with:", "options": ["Cardiogenic shock", "Septic shock", "Neurogenic shock", "Hypovolemic shock"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Septic shock occurs when a systemic infection triggers a dysregulated immune response leading to vasodilation, capillary leak, and ultimately cardiovascular collapse. It is characterized by hypotension refractory to fluid resuscitation and requires vasopressor support. Cardiogenic shock (choice A) results from primary cardiac pump failure, not infection. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-358", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A tracheostomy is a surgically created opening in which anatomical structure?", "options": ["Esophagus", "Trachea", "Stomach", "Larynx"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A tracheostomy creates an artificial airway by making an incision through the anterior neck into the trachea (windpipe). It is performed when a patient requires long-term mechanical ventilation or has an upper airway obstruction. MRI technologists must be aware that tracheostomy tubes may contain ferromagnetic components and must be screened before entering the scan room. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-359", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "An infection that develops as a direct result of a medical intervention or healthcare treatment is classified as:", "options": ["Iatrogenic", "Community-acquired", "Idiopathic", "Airborne"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "An iatrogenic infection is one caused by medical examination, treatment, or intervention (from the Greek “iatros” meaning physician). Common examples include catheter-associated urinary tract infections and surgical site infections. An idiopathic condition (choice C) has no identifiable cause, while community-acquired infections (choice B) originate outside the healthcare setting. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-360", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "A patient’s pulse oximetry monitor displays a heart rate of 112 bpm. This finding is classified as:", "options": ["Bradycardia", "Tachycardia", "Hypertension", "Normal sinus rhythm"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Tachycardia is defined as a resting heart rate exceeding 100 beats per minute. Bradycardia (choice A) is a heart rate below 60 bpm. In the MRI environment, tachycardia may result from anxiety, pain, contrast reaction, or underlying cardiac pathology. Hypertension (choice C) refers to elevated blood pressure, not heart rate. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-361", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "An MRI patient is receiving supplemental oxygen via face mask. Which method provides the most accurate body temperature measurement for this patient?", "options": ["Oral thermometer", "Tympanic (ear) or rectal thermometer", "Axillary (armpit) thermometer", "Forehead palpation"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Oral temperature measurement is unreliable when a patient is breathing through a face mask because the continuous flow of room-temperature or cooled oxygen alters the oral cavity temperature. Tympanic and rectal measurements are not affected by oxygen delivery and provide the most accurate core temperature readings. Axillary measurement (choice C) is the least accurate method overall. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-362", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "An inanimate object such as an MRI scanner surface, door handle, or keyboard that can harbor and transmit pathogenic microorganisms is called a:", "options": ["Vector", "Fomite", "Vehicle", "Reservoir"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A fomite is any nonliving object or surface that can become contaminated with infectious agents and serve as a mechanism for disease transmission between people. In the MRI environment, common fomites include the scanner table, coils, immobilization devices, and positioning pads. A vector (choice A) is a living organism (such as a mosquito or tick) that transmits disease. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-363", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Diseases transmitted through the bite of an infected arthropod, such as malaria (mosquito) or Lyme disease (tick), are examples of:", "options": ["Fomite transmission", "Droplet transmission", "Vector-borne transmission", "Vehicle transmission"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Vector-borne transmission occurs when a living organism (vector)—typically an arthropod such as a mosquito, tick, or flea—transfers an infectious agent from one host to another. This differs from fomite transmission (choice A), which involves nonliving contaminated objects. Droplet transmission (choice B) involves respiratory secretions over short distances. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-364", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient diagnosed with active pulmonary tuberculosis requires which isolation precaution, including a negative-pressure room and N95 respirators for all healthcare workers?", "options": ["Contact precautions", "Droplet precautions", "Airborne precautions", "Enteric precautions"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Airborne precautions are required for pathogens that remain suspended in the air as small-particle aerosols (<5 µm) and can travel long distances. Tuberculosis, measles, and varicella (chickenpox) all require airborne precautions. A negative-pressure room prevents contaminated air from escaping, and N95 respirators filter airborne particles. Droplet precautions (choice B) are for larger respiratory particles that fall within 3–6 feet. (CDC Isolation Precautions; Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-365", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The fundamental difference between medical asepsis and surgical asepsis is:", "options": ["Medical asepsis destroys bacterial spores while surgical asepsis does not", "Medical asepsis reduces the number of pathogens (clean technique), while surgical asepsis eliminates all microorganisms including spores (sterile technique)", "Medical asepsis is used exclusively in operating rooms", "Medical asepsis requires steam sterilization equipment"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Medical asepsis (clean technique) aims to reduce the number and spread of microorganisms through practices like hand hygiene, surface disinfection, and standard precautions. Surgical asepsis (sterile technique) aims to create and maintain a completely microorganism-free environment, including destruction of spores. The most common student error is reversing these definitions. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-366", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "When preparing a sterile field for a procedure, the outer border of the sterile drape that is considered contaminated (non-sterile) extends approximately:", "options": ["One-half inch from the edge", "One inch from the edge", "Four inches from the edge", "The entire perimeter is sterile if the package was sealed"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The standard convention in sterile technique is that the outer one-inch border of a sterile field is considered contaminated because it contacts nonsterile surfaces during setup. Any instruments or supplies that touch this border zone must be considered compromised. This one-inch rule is a foundational concept in surgical asepsis. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-367", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A technologist preparing for a sterile MRI-guided biopsy discovers that the outer wrapper of a sterile instrument tray is damp. The correct action is to:", "options": ["Dry the package and use it if the expiration date is still valid", "Discard the package as contaminated and obtain a new sterile tray", "Use the package only if the inner contents appear dry", "Place the package under a warming lamp before opening"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A wet or damp sterile package must be considered contaminated due to strike-through contamination—moisture wicks bacteria through the packaging material from the nonsterile outer surface to the sterile contents inside. The expiration date and visual appearance of the contents are irrelevant once the moisture barrier has been compromised. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-368", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Which method is considered the gold standard for sterilizing reusable metal surgical instruments?", "options": ["Wiping with chemical disinfectant solution", "Steam sterilization under pressure (autoclaving)", "Ultraviolet light exposure", "Subzero temperature freezing"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Autoclaving uses saturated steam under pressure (typically 121°C at 15 psi for 15–30 minutes) to achieve complete sterilization, destroying all microorganisms including resistant bacterial spores. It is the most reliable and widely used sterilization method for heat-stable instruments. Chemical wipes (choice A) achieve disinfection but not sterilization. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-369", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "According to CDC hand hygiene guidelines, the minimum duration for effective handwashing with soap and water is:", "options": ["5 seconds", "10 seconds", "20 seconds", "60 seconds"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The CDC recommends scrubbing all surfaces of the hands with soap and water for a minimum of 20 seconds to effectively remove transient microorganisms. This is approximately the time required to hum the “Happy Birthday” song twice. Alcohol-based hand rubs are an acceptable alternative when hands are not visibly soiled and require at least 15 seconds of application. (CDC Hand Hygiene Guidelines)", "reference": "CDC Hand Hygiene Guidelines"}, {"id": "PC-370", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient with severe immunosuppression from chemotherapy requires which type of isolation to protect them from environmental pathogens?", "options": ["Protective (reverse) isolation", "Contact isolation", "Airborne isolation", "Droplet isolation"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Protective isolation (also called reverse or neutropenic precautions) is designed to shield the immunocompromised patient from potential sources of infection in the healthcare environment. Unlike standard isolation, which protects healthcare workers from the patient’s infection, protective isolation protects the patient from the environment. Visitors and staff may need to wear masks and gowns, and fresh flowers and uncooked foods may be restricted. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-371", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "When removing personal protective equipment (PPE) after caring for an isolated patient, which item should be removed FIRST to minimize self-contamination?", "options": ["Face mask or respirator", "Isolation gown", "Gloves", "Eye protection or face shield"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Gloves are removed first because they are the most heavily contaminated PPE item after direct patient contact. Removing gloves first prevents transferring pathogens to the face, hair, or clothing during removal of the remaining equipment. The standard CDC doffing sequence is: gloves, gown, eye protection, and mask (removed last, after exiting the room if possible). (CDC PPE Guidelines; Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-372", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "A patient referred for a brain MRI following a recent stroke has been diagnosed with aphasia. The technologist should anticipate that this patient will have difficulty with:", "options": ["Ambulation and balance", "Producing or comprehending spoken language", "Swallowing liquids and solids", "Maintaining adequate respiratory effort"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Aphasia is a language disorder caused by damage to the brain’s language centers (typically Broca’s or Wernicke’s area), most often resulting from stroke. Patients may have difficulty speaking, understanding speech, reading, or writing. Dysphagia (choice C) refers to swallowing difficulty—a different neurological deficit. Technologists should use simple language, visual aids, and allow extra time for communication. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-373", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The medical term dysphagia refers to difficulty with:", "options": ["Breathing", "Speaking", "Swallowing", "Hearing"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Dysphagia (dys = difficulty, phagia = eating/swallowing) describes impaired swallowing function and is commonly seen in stroke patients, patients with esophageal pathology, or those with neuromuscular disorders. Students frequently confuse dysphagia with dysphasia (a language impairment)—the key mnemonic is that the ‘g’ in dysphagia relates to the GI tract (swallowing). (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-374", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "According to the Kübler-Ross model, the FIRST stage of the grieving process is typically:", "options": ["Anger", "Denial", "Depression", "Acceptance"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Kübler-Ross model describes five stages of grief: Denial, Anger, Bargaining, Depression, and Acceptance (mnemonic: DABDA). Denial serves as an initial defense mechanism that buffers the immediate shock. MRI technologists may encounter patients at any stage of grief, particularly those undergoing imaging for serious diagnoses such as cancer staging. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-375", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "According to Maslow’s hierarchy of needs, which category of needs must be satisfied BEFORE a patient can focus on safety instructions or learning about their MRI procedure?", "options": ["Safety and security needs", "Self-actualization needs", "Physiologic needs (air, water, pain relief, temperature regulation)", "Love and belonging needs"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Maslow’s hierarchy places physiologic needs (breathing, pain control, hydration, thermoregulation) at the base. A patient who is in pain, short of breath, or extremely cold cannot effectively attend to safety screening questions or scan instructions. The technologist must address basic comfort before expecting meaningful participation. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-376", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which approach is MOST effective when communicating MRI instructions to a hearing-impaired patient?", "options": ["Speaking in a loud voice to ensure the patient hears", "Facing the patient directly, speaking clearly at a normal pace, and using visual cues", "Using complex medical terminology to demonstrate professionalism", "Directing all communication to accompanying family members instead"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Facing the patient allows lip reading and observation of facial expressions, both of which enhance comprehension for hearing-impaired individuals. Shouting (choice A) distorts speech patterns and makes lip reading more difficult. Communication should always be directed to the patient first, not exclusively to family members, to maintain the patient’s autonomy and dignity. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-377", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When explaining an MRI procedure to a pediatric patient, the technologist should:", "options": ["Direct all explanations exclusively to the parents or guardians", "Position themselves at the child’s eye level and use age-appropriate language", "Use authoritative commands to ensure compliance", "Reassure the child that the procedure will not cause any discomfort, even if sedation is involved"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Getting down to a child’s eye level reduces intimidation and builds trust, which improves cooperation during the examination. Age-appropriate language helps the child understand what to expect. Providing false reassurances (choice D) erodes trust if the child later experiences discomfort, and speaking only to parents (choice A) ignores the child’s need to feel included. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-378", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "Which nonverbal behavior BEST demonstrates active listening and professional engagement when speaking with a patient?", "options": ["Crossing arms across the chest", "Looking at the computer monitor while the patient is speaking", "Maintaining appropriate eye contact with the patient", "Stepping back and increasing physical distance from the patient"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Appropriate eye contact signals attentiveness, empathy, and respect during patient communication. Crossed arms (choice A) and averted gaze (choice B) convey disinterest or defensiveness. Cultural sensitivity should always be considered, as some cultures interpret direct eye contact differently. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-379", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When providing care for a patient who appears unconscious or in an altered mental state, the technologist should:", "options": ["Assume the patient cannot hear and proceed silently", "Continue speaking to the patient and explaining each action before performing it", "Apply physical restraints as a precautionary measure", "Avoid all verbal communication until the patient responds"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hearing is often the last sensory function to diminish in patients with altered consciousness. Patients who appear unresponsive may still be able to hear and comprehend speech. Explaining actions before performing them maintains patient dignity, reduces potential startle responses, and fulfills the standard of care. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-380", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "The teach-back method is a communication technique in which the technologist asks the patient to repeat instructions in their own words. The primary purpose of this technique is to:", "options": ["Evaluate the technologist’s teaching skills", "Confirm that the patient understands the information provided", "Correct errors in the radiologist’s protocol", "Calibrate scanner-specific parameters"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Teach-back validates patient comprehension by having the patient restate key information in their own words. This technique has been shown to reduce miscommunication, improve adherence to pre- and post-procedure instructions, and is particularly valuable for patients with limited health literacy. It is not a test of the patient but a check on the effectiveness of the technologist’s communication. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-381", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When providing a medical explanation to a patient, the appropriate interpersonal distance classified as “personal space” is generally considered to be:", "options": ["Direct physical contact (0–6 inches)", "Approximately 12 feet or greater", "Approximately 1.5 to 4 feet", "Less than 6 inches"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Edward Hall’s proxemics theory defines personal space as approximately 1.5 to 4 feet—the distance appropriate for conversations between acquaintances. The intimate zone (less than 18 inches) is typically reserved for physical examination and may provoke anxiety if entered without warning. The social zone (4–12 feet) and public zone (>12 feet) are too distant for effective one-on-one patient communication. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-382", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Gadolinium-based contrast agents are often warmed to body temperature before injection. The primary purpose of warming the contrast is to:", "options": ["Enhance the agent’s magnetic relaxivity properties", "Reduce the viscosity for smoother injection and improved patient comfort", "Increase the viscosity to slow the injection rate", "Achieve terminal sterilization of the contrast solution"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Warming gadolinium contrast to body temperature (37°C) reduces its viscosity, allowing for a smoother and less painful injection at the flow rates used with power injectors. Lower viscosity also reduces the risk of extravasation by decreasing the injection pressure required. Warming does not meaningfully alter the agent’s relaxivity or sterility. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-383", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "According to the ACR Manual on Contrast Media, a lactating mother who receives a standard dose of gadolinium-based contrast agent should be advised to:", "options": ["Pump and discard breast milk for 24 hours after the injection", "Continue breastfeeding without interruption, as the amount excreted in breast milk is negligible", "Permanently discontinue breastfeeding", "Avoid breastfeeding and switch to formula for one week"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Current ACR guidelines state that the amount of gadolinium excreted into breast milk is extremely small (less than 0.04% of the administered dose), and of that, less than 1% is absorbed from the infant’s GI tract. Therefore, breastfeeding does not need to be interrupted after gadolinium administration. The outdated “pump and dump” recommendation is no longer supported by evidence. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-384", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Among the following intravenous catheter sizes, which gauge has the LARGEST internal diameter?", "options": ["22 gauge", "20 gauge", "18 gauge", "24 gauge"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "IV catheter gauge numbers have an inverse relationship with internal diameter—the smaller the gauge number, the larger the needle bore. An 18-gauge catheter has a larger lumen than 20-, 22-, or 24-gauge catheters and allows higher flow rates, making it preferred for power-injected contrast studies. A 24-gauge catheter (choice D) has the smallest diameter and is typically used for pediatric or difficult-access patients. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-385", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "In contrast media administration, the term “bolus” refers to:", "options": ["A slow intravenous drip infused over several hours", "A rapid injection of a defined volume of contrast at a controlled flow rate", "An intramuscular injection of contrast agent", "An oral contrast preparation taken by mouth"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A bolus injection delivers a concentrated dose of contrast rapidly through an IV line, typically using a power injector at a specified flow rate (e.g., 2–3 mL/sec). This technique is essential for dynamic contrast-enhanced MRI sequences (such as MRA or liver imaging) where precise timing of contrast arrival is critical for diagnostic quality. A slow drip (choice A) would not achieve the necessary arterial-phase enhancement. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-386", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "When cleaning the MRI scan room between patients, the technologist should clean surfaces in which direction?", "options": ["From the most contaminated area to the least contaminated area", "From the least contaminated (cleanest) area toward the most contaminated area", "From the floor upward to the ceiling", "From the bore entrance toward the back of the magnet room"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Cleaning should always proceed from the cleanest areas to the dirtiest areas to prevent cross-contamination. This principle ensures that microorganisms are not dragged from heavily soiled surfaces onto previously clean ones. In the MRI environment, the scanner table and patient contact surfaces should be cleaned systematically following this directional principle. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-387", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The medical term used to describe a patient who currently has a fever is:", "options": ["Afebrile", "Febrile", "Hypothermic", "Diaphoretic"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Febrile indicates the presence of fever (pyrexia), defined as a core body temperature above 100.4°F (38°C). Afebrile (choice A) means without fever. Diaphoretic (choice D) refers to excessive sweating, which may accompany fever but is a separate clinical finding. Hypothermic (choice C) describes an abnormally low body temperature. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-388", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient experiences dizziness and near-syncope immediately upon standing from the MRI table. This presentation is most consistent with:", "options": ["Hyperglycemia", "Orthostatic hypotension", "Essential hypertension", "Anaphylaxis"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Orthostatic (postural) hypotension occurs when blood pressure drops significantly upon moving from a supine or seated position to standing, resulting in transient cerebral hypoperfusion. It is defined as a systolic BP decrease of ≥20 mmHg or diastolic decrease of ≥10 mmHg within three minutes of standing. The technologist should assist the patient back to a seated position and allow gradual position changes. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-389", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "Which of the following is classified as a MILD adverse reaction to gadolinium-based contrast media?", "options": ["Laryngeal edema with stridor", "Cardiac arrest", "Scattered urticaria (hives), nausea, or limited emesis", "Generalized tonic-clonic seizure"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The ACR classifies contrast reactions by severity. Mild reactions include scattered hives, nausea, limited vomiting, and transient flushing—these are typically self-limiting and require observation but rarely need pharmacologic intervention. Laryngeal edema (choice A) and seizures (choice D) are severe reactions requiring immediate emergency treatment. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-390", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "A patient develops severe respiratory distress, facial angioedema, and hypotension within minutes of gadolinium injection. Which medication is the FIRST-LINE treatment for this anaphylactic reaction?", "options": ["Diphenhydramine (Benadryl)", "Epinephrine (adrenaline)", "Aspirin", "Atropine"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Epinephrine is the only first-line treatment for anaphylaxis. It acts as a potent bronchodilator and vasoconstrictor, reversing airway obstruction and restoring blood pressure. Diphenhydramine (choice A) is a second-line adjunct that addresses histamine-mediated symptoms but cannot reverse cardiovascular collapse or severe bronchospasm. Delay in epinephrine administration is the most common cause of fatal anaphylaxis. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-391", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "The medical abbreviation NPO (nil per os) instructs the healthcare team that the patient should receive:", "options": ["No prior operations documented", "Nothing by mouth", "No patient objections to the procedure", "Normal pre-operative orders"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "NPO status means the patient must not eat or drink anything by mouth. This restriction is commonly ordered before procedures requiring sedation (to reduce aspiration risk) and before certain abdominal MRI examinations to reduce bowel motion artifacts or ensure proper gallbladder distension. The technologist should verify NPO compliance before administering sedation. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-392", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "The normal resting heart rate range for a healthy adult is:", "options": ["40–50 beats per minute", "60–100 beats per minute", "100–120 beats per minute", "120–150 beats per minute"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A resting heart rate of 60–100 bpm is considered normal for adults. A rate below 60 bpm is classified as bradycardia (which may be normal in well-conditioned athletes), while a rate above 100 bpm is tachycardia. Monitoring heart rate is important during MRI, particularly for sedated patients and those undergoing cardiac-gated examinations. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-393", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which anatomical site provides the MOST accurate measurement of core body temperature?", "options": ["Oral cavity", "Axillary (armpit) region", "Rectal", "Forehead surface"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Rectal temperature most closely reflects true core body temperature because it measures the temperature of the well-perfused rectal mucosa, which is minimally affected by environmental factors. Oral temperature can be altered by recent food or drink intake and mouth breathing, while axillary measurement (choice B) consistently underestimates core temperature by approximately 1°F. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-394", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "For a patient with a history of chronic kidney disease scheduled for a contrast-enhanced MRI, the ACR recommends that the eGFR laboratory result be obtained within what time frame prior to the examination?", "options": ["Within 24 hours", "Within 30–60 days (or per institutional policy)", "Within 6 months", "No lab work is required before gadolinium administration"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The ACR recommends obtaining an eGFR within a recent time frame (typically 30–60 days, though institutional policies may vary) for patients at risk for renal impairment before gadolinium administration. This ensures the value accurately reflects the patient’s current renal function. Patients with stable chronic kidney disease may have slightly different institutional requirements, but a recent eGFR is always indicated for at-risk populations. (ACR Manual on Contrast Media)", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-395", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.4", "stem": "During venipuncture preparation, a tourniquet is applied proximal to the intended puncture site. The primary purpose of the tourniquet is to:", "options": ["Completely occlude arterial flow to the extremity", "Distend the vein by restricting venous return while maintaining arterial inflow", "Cause the target vein to collapse for easier identification", "Provide a sterile barrier around the puncture site"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A properly applied tourniquet restricts superficial venous return while allowing arterial inflow to continue, causing the target veins to engorge and become more visible and palpable. It should be tight enough to impede venous flow but not so tight that it occludes arterial circulation. The tourniquet should be released within 1–2 minutes to prevent tissue ischemia. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-396", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient becomes pale, diaphoretic, and hypotensive with a heart rate of 48 bpm shortly after IV placement. This clinical presentation is most consistent with a:", "options": ["Severe anaphylactic reaction with tachycardia", "Vasovagal response characterized by bradycardia and hypotension", "Allergic-like urticarial reaction", "Febrile response to the contrast agent"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A vasovagal response is a parasympathetic nervous system–mediated event that causes bradycardia (slow heart rate), hypotension, pallor, and diaphoresis. It is typically triggered by anxiety, pain, or the sight of needles—common in the MRI setting during IV placement. Unlike allergic reactions (which usually cause tachycardia and urticaria), vasovagal events are characterized by a paradoxical decrease in heart rate. Treatment includes positioning the patient supine with legs elevated. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-397", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The medical term epistaxis refers to:", "options": ["An episode of syncope (fainting)", "Projectile vomiting", "A nosebleed", "A persistent headache"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Epistaxis is the medical term for hemorrhage from the nasal cavity (nosebleed). Common causes include dry air, nasal trauma, hypertension, and anticoagulant therapy. In the MRI department, an actively bleeding patient requires stabilization and may need to have the examination rescheduled if hemorrhage cannot be controlled. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-398", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Which pathogen is MOST frequently associated with nosocomial (healthcare-associated) infections in hospital environments?", "options": ["Ebola virus", "Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA)", "Plasmodium species (malaria)", "Rabies virus"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "MRSA is one of the most prevalent healthcare-associated pathogens due to its antibiotic resistance and ability to survive on environmental surfaces for extended periods. Clostridioides difficile (C. diff) is another common nosocomial pathogen. Ebola (choice A), malaria (choice C), and rabies (choice D) are not typically healthcare-associated infections. Standard precautions and thorough equipment cleaning are essential for MRSA prevention. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-399", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The standard precautions policy in healthcare mandates that all personnel must:", "options": ["Wear gloves only when caring for patients known to be HIV-positive", "Exercise caution only with patients who have a confirmed infectious diagnosis", "Treat ALL blood, body fluids, and potentially contaminated materials as if they are infectious", "Wear a surgical mask only when a patient is actively coughing"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Standard precautions (formerly universal precautions) require that all healthcare workers treat every patient’s blood, body fluids, non-intact skin, and mucous membranes as potentially infectious, regardless of the patient’s diagnosis or perceived risk status. This approach eliminates the need to identify specific at-risk patients and provides consistent baseline protection. (CDC Standard Precautions; Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-400", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "Disease transmission that occurs through the bite of an infected arthropod (such as a mosquito or tick) is classified as:", "options": ["Airborne transmission via respiratory droplets", "Vector-borne transmission", "Fomite transmission via contaminated surfaces", "Vehicle transmission via contaminated food or water"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Vector-borne transmission involves a living organism (the vector)—typically an arthropod—that carries and transmits a pathogen between hosts. Mosquitoes transmit malaria and Zika virus, while ticks transmit Lyme disease and Rocky Mountain spotted fever. This mechanism is distinct from airborne, fomite, and vehicle transmission, which do not involve living intermediaries. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-401", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The blood component primarily responsible for oxygen transport throughout the body is the:", "options": ["Leukocyte (white blood cell)", "Erythrocyte (red blood cell)", "Thrombocyte (platelet)", "Phagocyte"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Erythrocytes (red blood cells) contain hemoglobin, the iron-containing protein that binds and transports oxygen from the lungs to peripheral tissues. A decreased red blood cell count or hemoglobin level (anemia) impairs oxygen delivery and may be relevant when evaluating patients with dyspnea or fatigue before MRI. Leukocytes (choice A) fight infection, and thrombocytes (choice C) facilitate clotting. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-402", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The blood component primarily responsible for forming clots to control hemorrhage is the:", "options": ["Leukocyte (white blood cell)", "Erythrocyte (red blood cell)", "Thrombocyte (platelet)", "Plasma albumin"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Thrombocytes (platelets) are cell fragments essential for primary hemostasis—they aggregate at the site of vascular injury to form a platelet plug that initiates the clotting cascade. A low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) significantly increases the risk of bleeding and is a critical lab value to assess before invasive MRI-guided procedures. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-403", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The blood component primarily responsible for immune defense and fighting infection is the:", "options": ["Leukocyte (white blood cell)", "Erythrocyte (red blood cell)", "Thrombocyte (platelet)", "Lipid molecule"], "correct": "a", "rationale": "Leukocytes (white blood cells) are the primary cells of the immune system. An elevated white blood cell count (leukocytosis) typically indicates an active infection or inflammatory process, while a severely depressed count (leukopenia or neutropenia) indicates immunosuppression and may require protective isolation precautions during the MRI visit. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-404", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient’s pulse oximetry reading drops to 85% during an MRI examination. The clinical condition characterized by inadequate oxygen delivery at the tissue level is termed:", "options": ["Hypoglycemia", "Hypoxia", "Hypotension", "Hypercapnia"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "Hypoxia is defined as insufficient oxygen at the tissue level and is indicated by a pulse oximetry (SpO2) reading below 90%. Normal SpO2 is 95–100%. Hypoxia can result from airway obstruction, respiratory depression (especially in sedated patients), or cardiovascular compromise. Hypercapnia (choice D) refers to elevated carbon dioxide levels in the blood, which may coexist with hypoxia. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-405", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.2", "stem": "When transferring a stroke patient with left-sided hemiparesis (weakness) from a wheelchair to the MRI table, the technologist should position themselves on the patient’s:", "options": ["Right (strong) side to encourage independence", "Left (weak/affected) side to provide support and prevent falls", "Behind the patient to push them forward", "Across the room to give verbal instructions only"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The technologist should position on the patient’s weak (affected) side to provide physical support and prevent falls during the transfer. The wheelchair should be positioned so the patient can lead with their strong side. This technique maximizes patient safety while encouraging the patient to use their functional abilities during the transfer. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-406", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A generalized seizure characterized by an initial phase of sustained muscle rigidity (tonic phase) followed by rhythmic jerking movements (clonic phase) is classified as a:", "options": ["Absence (petit mal) seizure", "Tonic-clonic (formerly grand mal) seizure", "Simple focal seizure", "Myoclonic seizure"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A tonic-clonic seizure is the most dramatic form of generalized seizure, involving loss of consciousness, an initial tonic phase (generalized muscle rigidity), and a subsequent clonic phase (rhythmic bilateral jerking). This type of seizure is most commonly tested on registry exams. Absence seizures (choice A) are characterized by brief staring episodes without motor convulsions. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-407", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "A patient develops a generalized tonic-clonic seizure while positioned inside the MRI bore. The technologist’s PRIMARY objective is to:", "options": ["Physically restrain the patient’s extremities to prevent injury", "Insert a bite block or tongue depressor between the patient’s teeth", "Stop the scan, protect the patient from injury by cushioning the head, and remove the patient from the bore when safe", "Continue the scan to document the event on the acquired images"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "The primary goal during any seizure is to protect the patient from injury. In the MRI bore, this means immediately stopping the scan, cushioning the patient’s head against the hard bore surface, and removing the patient when the active seizure subsides. Objects should NEVER be placed in the mouth (choice B), as this can cause tooth fractures, aspiration, or jaw injury. Physical restraint (choice A) increases the risk of musculoskeletal injury. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6; AHA BLS Guidelines)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 6"}, {"id": "PC-408", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "The Trendelenburg position involves placing the patient:", "options": ["With the head elevated above the level of the feet", "With the head lower than the feet", "In a completely flat supine position", "Lying on the left lateral side"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The Trendelenburg position tilts the patient so the head is lower than the feet, using gravity to increase venous return to the heart and improve cerebral perfusion. It is used in the management of shock and severe hypotension. The reverse Trendelenburg (head up, feet down) is used for different clinical indications. MRI technologists should be able to identify and position patients in Trendelenburg when directed. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 5"}, {"id": "PC-409", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "To maintain sterility of a prepared sterile field, the technologist must NEVER:", "options": ["Touch items on the inner surface of the sterile tray with sterile gloves", "Turn their back on the sterile field or allow it to leave their line of sight", "Wear a surgical mask during the sterile setup", "Use sterile transfer forceps to move instruments"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A fundamental rule of surgical asepsis is that a sterile field must be continuously monitored—if you turn your back on it or leave the area, the field is considered potentially compromised because contamination could occur unobserved. All items placed on the sterile field must be added using sterile technique, and the field must remain within direct visual supervision at all times. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 4"}, {"id": "PC-410", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.A.1", "stem": "A patient with a validated Do Not Resuscitate (DNR) order in their medical record experiences cardiac arrest during an MRI examination. The technologist’s appropriate response is to:", "options": ["Initiate CPR immediately regardless of the DNR order", "Honor the DNR directive and refrain from initiating cardiopulmonary resuscitation", "Begin CPR but discontinue after two minutes", "Initiate a magnet quench to facilitate emergency response"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "A valid DNR order is a legally binding advance directive that must be respected. The technologist should not initiate CPR but should ensure the patient is removed from the bore safely, notify the physician and code team, and provide comfort measures. Ignoring a DNR order (choice A) violates the patient’s autonomy and could result in legal consequences. A magnet quench (choice D) is not indicated in a DNR situation. (Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1; ACR Manual on MR Safety)", "reference": "Torres' Patient Care Ch. 1"}, {"id": "PC-411", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.1", "stem": "When assessing for a pulse in an unresponsive adult during a BLS assessment, the rescuer should palpate which artery?", "options": ["Radial artery at the wrist", "Carotid artery in the neck", "Femoral artery in the groin", "Dorsalis pedis artery on the foot"], "correct": "b", "rationale": "The carotid artery is the preferred site for pulse assessment in an unresponsive adult because it is a large central artery that maintains palpable pulsation even when peripheral pulses have become weak or absent due to hypotension. The AHA recommends checking the carotid pulse for no more than 10 seconds before initiating CPR if no pulse is detected. (AHA BLS Guidelines)", "reference": "AHA BLS Guidelines"}, {"id": "PC-412", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Patients with which condition should have renal function assessed (e.g., serum creatinine or eGFR) before receiving a gadolinium-based contrast agent?", "options": ["Cirrhosis", "Heart disease", "Diabetes", "History of stroke"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Patients with diabetes are at increased risk for renal insufficiency (diabetic nephropathy), which impairs clearance of gadolinium-based contrast agents and increases the risk of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF). Therefore, renal function (serum creatinine or eGFR) should be assessed before contrast administration in diabetic patients. While heart disease (option b) may warrant clinical assessment, diabetes is the primary screening indication due to its direct association with renal impairment.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}, {"id": "PC-413", "domain": "Patient Care", "subcategory": "Patient Interactions & Management", "spec": "1.B.3", "stem": "Which of the following is NOT a typical symptom of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF)?", "options": ["Patches of thickened, hardened skin", "Joint contractures and pain", "Shortness of breath", "Yellow plaques on the sclera of the eyes"], "correct": "c", "rationale": "Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis (NSF) is characterized by thickened, hardened skin patches, joint contractures with pain, and yellow plaques on the sclera. It is associated with exposure to certain gadolinium-based contrast agents in patients with severely impaired renal function. Shortness of breath is not a typical symptom of NSF; it is primarily a fibrotic condition affecting the skin and connective tissues, not the respiratory system.", "reference": "ACR Manual on Contrast Media"}];